<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<CENTER><h1>CINCPACFLT Speeches</h1></CENTER>
<hr>
<title>CINCPACFLT at 55th Pearl Harbor Attack Commemoration</title>



<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>

Admiral Archie Clemins, USN<br>

Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>

55th Commemoration of the Attack on Pearl Harbor<BR>

USS ARIZONA Memorial, Pearl Harbor, Hawaii<br>

Pearl Harbor, Hawaii (December 7, 1996)<br>

</h2>

<hr>

<em>Unclassified</em>

<hr>

<P>Senators Inouye and Stevens, Consul General Amae, Consul General Kang, State and City officials, Admiral Prueher, flag and general officers, distinguished guests, veterans and friends...

<P>For the past 55 years, Americans have gathered in Pearl Harbor on December 7th  — not only to honor the bravery and the sacrifice of our veterans . . . but also to rededicate our military’s resolve to never again be complaisant and vulnerable.

<P>We all know the story of the attack.  On that Sunday morning in 1941, Pearl Harbor was at rest.  In a matter of minutes, several hundred U.S. aircraft were damaged or destroyed.   Twenty-one ships were sunk, beached, or severely damaged.  In those few minutes over 2,000 Americans lost their lives,

<P>The real story of Pearl Harbor, however, is not in the statistics, but in the story of the American people . . . ordinary people from all parts of the United States and from all different ethnic groups . . . cast into a conflict where boys quickly became men . . . where average Americans quickly became heroes.

<P>Within this audience there many of those heroes.  One of them is Robert Feller, a native of Verona, Wisconsin, who joined the Navy in October of 1940, and was assigned to the wooden-hulled minesweeper, the USS Ogalala.

<P>Just before 8:00 am on December 7th, 1941, Robert Feller was on duty as the ship’s Messenger of the Watch, when he heard airplanes flying overhead. Looking out of a porthole he saw a Japanese plane drop a torpedo in the water and watched it head directly for his ship.

<P>Robert Feller closed his eyes, thinking he was about to die.  Miraculously the torpedo passed directly underneath his ship . . . and instead hit the USS Helena.  Despite the near miss, Robert Feller’s ship did sink during the ensuing explosions, but he was one of lucky ones, one of the survivors. At the end of the war he returned to Wisconsin, worked as an electrician, and raised three sons.

<P>One of those sons . . .  Major Gene Feller, U.S. Air Force, is here with Jim today.  Major Feller, who flies the KC-135’s, fought in Operation Desert Storm, so like his father, he is a veteran who fought for his country . . .  (Stand and recognize)  We salute this father-son team.

<P>Pearl Harbor is also a story of people like Edward Bourucki (Bo-ru-kee), the son of Polish immigrants, the son who left his 35 cent an hour job in Holyoke, Massachusetts for a $21 a month job in the Navy.

<P>Fifty  years ago Edward Bourucki (Bo-ru-kee) was in the Engineering Logroom of the USS Helena, issuing liberty cards to the crew, when the torpedo that passed under the USS Ogalala impacted his ship in the forward engine room and exploded.

<P>Edward Bourucki and his shipmates, through valiant efforts, were able to save their ship. Then, with a patch over the hole blown open by the torpedo, they sailed the Helena for repairs to the shipyard in Mare Island, California.  Edward Bourucki spent the rest of the war aboard a seaplane tender, then returned to Massachusetts where he finished his education, became a high school business teacher, and raised seven sons.  Five of Edward’s sons are here with him today:
Chester — Robert — Walter — Paul — and Peter.

<P>Pearl Harbor is also story of James Green from the State of Michigan.  Jim was so eager to serve in the Navy that he walked for a mile, through a foot of snow, just to catch the bus that would take him to the processing station.  His first assignment was aboard the USS Arizona as a gunners mate.

<P>On the morning of December 7th, 1941, Jim Green was coming off the magazine watch when the attack started.  He headed for his battle station in the forward gun turret, but he never made it.  The ship exploded, and he went into the water.

<P>Despite a painful shrapnel wound in his leg, Jim Green was volunteering within hours of the attack to work as a diver. He continually dove into oil-saturated water to remove ammunition at risk of exploding.  He dove every day for over a year until the last ship left dry-dock.

<P>Jim Green was justifiably proud of his service.  He was proud of the $5 bill he recovered from his locker on the USS Arizona . . . of his picture that appeared in Life Magazine (in 1942) showing him diving and covered with oil . . . and of the Navy-Marine Corps Medal he was awarded for his heroism.
Jim was proud but he was also humble and modest. It wasn’t until several years after he married Irene, “the girl of his dreams,” that he even told her he was a Pearl Harbor veteran.

<P>Jim and Irene Green were happily married for 48 years. They raised a son, James Jr. (who is a police officer) and a daughter, Kristine (who is a nurse).  Jim Green passed away on February 22nd of this year, but his family is here to honor him one last time.

<P>This afternoon Jim’s remains will be interred with his shipmates in the USS Arizona.  Accompanying Irene for this ceremony are not only James and Kristine, but also Jim and Irene’s grandsons, James III and Jonathan.
(Stand and recognize).

<P>My final story is that of Doris Miller from Waco, Texas . . . an African-American . . . a son of share-croppers who enlisted in the Navy as a Mess Attendant in order to help support his family.  “Dorie” Miller was a heavy-set young man who loved recreational boxing and loved serving in the Navy.  He was assigned to the USS West Virginia.

<P>With his love of the Navy, Doris Miller was not prone to disobeying orders but, on the morning of December 7th, 1941, “Dorie” Miller disobeyed two orders.  He ignored the order to save himself and instead, under enemy strafing, carried his wounded Captain to safety as fire consumed the ship.

<P>Later, although standing orders at the time prohibited non-whites from firing weapons, Dorie Miller manned and operated an anti-aircraft battery gun in an effort to save his ship.

<P>For his extraordinary courage and disregard for his own safety Doris Miller was personally awarded the Navy Cross by Admiral Chester W. Nimitz .   He was the first African-American to receive such an award and his distinguished service continued for two more years until his ship, the USS Liscome Bay, was torpedoed and sunk off the Gilbert Islands. Doris Miller was declared missing and presumed dead.

<P>Although he had no descendants, his legacy lives on in other ways.  Earlier this year in Oahu a Navy Family Housing development was opened in memory of Doris Miller.  Through his name we are reminded that heroism and valor transcend racial and ethnic bounds, and that as Americans, our strength lies in our ability to help one another in time of need.

<P>Our strength in unity must be paralleled by a military which is always ready and always prepared.  Shortly after the end of the war, Fleet Admiral Chester Nimitz addressed a large crowd in front of the New York City Hall, giving this important admonition...

<P>“We must make certain now and for the future, that the peace is secure.  We must remain strong.  Never again should we risk the threat which weakness invites.  We owe this to the men who have fought and to the youngsters who are growing up today.”

<P>This morning, we salute all Pearl Harbor veterans for their service and their sacrifice, and we renew our commitment to ensure there are no more Pearl Harbors.

<P>It is this legacy of vigilance in America which keeps us in peace and prosperity.  It is this legacy of vigilance which allows us to choose our Navy’s missions, lest others choose them for us.

<P>It is fitting that in the not too distant future, the battleship USS Missouri will be brought here to Pearl Harbor, where it will join the Arizona Memorial to form a monument to the beginning and end of the war in the Pacific.

<P>The war started with the attack on Pearl Harbor and the sinking of the USS Arizona . . .  it ended when the surrender documents were signed on the deck of the USS Missouri in Tokyo Bay.  But these two great ships will symbolize more than just the historical bookends of the war . . . more than just the beginning and the end.

<P>The Arizona, with over 900 sons, husbands and fathers still entombed within, symbolizes the tragedy of war, the heavy human toll of being ill-prepared.  As Thomas Jefferson once wrote, “I have seen enough of one war never to wish to see another.”

<P>The Missouri, when she arrives and moors next to the Arizona, will symbolize the triumph of the American fighting spirit;  the spirit which was able to overcome the heavy losses at Pearl Harbor, the spirit which brought victory in the Pacific, and along with that victory, the resolve that our country will always remains prepared.  We have not forgotten the sacrifice of our veterans.

<P>Thank you and God bless you all.
<br>







<br>

<hr>

<center>-USN-</center>

<br>

<br>



