<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<title>CINCPACFLT at Naval Base Pearl Harbor Change of Command</title>

<h2>Remarks as delivered by<br>
Admiral Archie Clemins<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
COMNAVBASE Pearl Harbor Change of Command<br>
</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, Hawaii (November 15, 1996)</strong>
<hr>
Thank you for your participation in this ceremony and for such kind words about the relationships between the Navy and the Hawaiian Community.  I am smart enough to know that when following an accomplished public speaker, the best advice is to be short.  So, though my admiration is long and enduring for Gordon Holder, his wife Pat, and their daughters Ann and Jennifer, my speech in this cere-mony will be an abbreviated one.<p>

Gordon and Pat became our personal and professional friends over seven years ago during one of our tenures in Yokosuka, Japan.  Even then it was obvious that the Holders were a special, close-knit unit.  They viewed the difficult life of an overseas, deployed family with wit and humor, yet served the Navy and its families with great dedication. Even then it was obvious that Gordon Holder was a leader.<p>

Every commanding officer has a unique style and per-sonal perspective on leadership, but the successful ones have qualities with distinct, historical parallels. Often the winning guidelines are quite simple.  Consider the following sugges-tions:

<ul>
<li>“Get out of the Office and Circulate Among the Troops”</li>
<li>“Persuade rather than Coerce”</li>
<li>“Build strong Alliances”</li>
<li>“Encourage Innovation”</li>
</ul>

Those quotes on leadership philosophy were taken from one of my favorite books, a small volume entitled Lincoln on Leadership by Donald Phillips.  All of those traits describe Gordon Holder’s philosophy of leadership.<p>

Last week, during one of our final meetings, I asked Gordon to identify the accomplishment in which he felt the greatest sense of pride.  Without hesitation, he talked about the Ohana Program and the Navy family. As most of you know, the “Ohana Program” is a widely-praised and highly-emulated system to identify and correct quality of life issues.  On Oahu it brought over 100 delegates together from all parts of the Navy family --- the enlisted, the officers, retired members, family members, civilians, teenagers --- all to-gether for an annual conference.  As a result, over 450 sepa-rate issues were prioritized, a coherent strategy for address-ing quality of life concerns was developed, and families now have an effective feedback tool. The “Ohana Program” is a product of good leadership.<p>

Remember those simple guidelines?
<ul>
<li>“Get out of the Office and Circulate Among the Troops”</li>
<li>“Persuade rather than Coerce”</li>
<li>“Build strong Alliances”</li>
<li>“Encourage Innovation”</li>
</ul>

Gordon was there, among the troops, among the fami-lies. He gently persuaded, built alliances, and encouraged innovations. Many people said it couldn’t be done, but “People who say it can not be done should not interrupt those that are doing it." <p>

Gordon Holder also took action to keep his people bet-ter informed . . . he consolidated the different base publica-tions on Oahu into one award-winning newspaper, he cre-ated a Navy cable TV station, and started a housing newslet-ter to disseminate important information to families in gov-ernment quarters.<p>

“People who say it can not be done should not interrupt those that are doing it." <p>

He worked to make Navy housing better . . . establish-ing the key goals of replacement, revitalization and mainte-nance for over 7,000 Navy Family quarters.  He took his case up the chain of command and to Washington, and he fought for funding to improve our housing on Oahu to its highest level ever.<p>

"People who say it can not be done should not interrupt those that are doing it." <p>

Naval Officers have always been trained as ship drivers, pilots, and engineers; yet, we give our officers little or no training in the role of the Navy’s “Mr. Mayor”.  Naval Bases are major shore establishments.  A successful tour requires discipline, goal oriented action, and major diplomacy. Thus, successes and failures are distinguished by the quality of leadership.<p>

Only a leader could have pulled disjointed major com-manders from different claimants into a quality Executive Steering Committee to address environmental issues, com-munity relations, and quality of life.<p>

Only a leader could have worked to integrate our Navy communities . . .  Gordon Holder tore down fences and opened the Navy housing neighborhoods so they no longer feel like restricted bases, but rather like integral parts of the local community.  He regularly sent ships to the Aloha Tower, opening these ships to the public so that taxpayers could see and experience firsthand the professionalism of our Navy.  And he led the way in the construction of Rain-bow Bay Park . . . a park on Navy land which will be oper-ated by the state, and open to the public.<p>

“People who say it can not be done should not interrupt those that are doing it." <p>

These are only a few of Gordon Holder’s accomplish-ments.  In addition to his role as Commander Naval Base, Pearl Harbor, Gordon also had a parallel job as Com-mander, Surface Group, Mid-Pacific.  Handling two difficult jobs simultaneously is a delicate balancing act.  Gordon was successful because he rose to the challenge.  He used new ideas.  He wasn’t afraid of innovation. He could, in the words of Abraham Lincoln, “think anew and act anew”.<p>

No success story is without a supporting cast.   Gordon would be the first to credit his staff and his family.  He is right to do so.  Pat Holder,  in addition to her role as the First Lady of Naval Base, Pearl Harbor, has also worked hard to improve the quality of life for our Sailors and their families in Hawaii.  She personally led the way in opening the Keiki Childcare Center at Makalapa Clinic, and she built close community ties through her work with the American Red Cross and other organizations. <p>

This is the team to whom we are saying a painful “good-bye”.  In the Navy, the price of success is moving on to greater things . . . Gordon and Pat are moving to Norfolk, Virginia to take command of the Naval Doctrine Command.  I can’t think of a better team for the job.   Our Navy needs their leadership abilities and their innovation while it goes about shaping concepts of how our forces will operate in the 21st century, how to integrate technologies and systems, and how to define our expanding our roles.<p>


Although we’re sad to see Gordon and Pat go, we’re  happy to have such a great replacement:  Rear Admiral William G. Sutton and his wife, Claudia.<p>

Woody took command of COMNAVSURFGRU, MID-PAC about two months ago, so he’s not completely changing jobs . . .  rather, he’s expanding his current job --- actually,  he is doubling his work-load and doubling his responsibili-ties.  However, he brings impeccable credentials of past suc-cesses, and I know he is up to the challenges ahead.<p>

Woody and Claudia. Welcome, once again!<p>

Finally,  congratulations to  all the men, women, and families of COMNAVBASE Pearl Harbor for all your great accomplishments over the past two years.  I’d also like to thank our friends and supporters from the community -- especially Mayor Harris  -- who have joined us here for this special occasion.<p>

You are all a part of our Navy’s success story in the Pacific . . .  and you are all a part of our “ohana”.<p>
</p>Gordon, if you will join me... (award presentation)
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
