<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Honolulu Navy League</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral Archie Clemins, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Honolulu, HI. (Wednesday, November 13, 1996)</strong><br><br>
<hr>
Aloha and Good Afternoon — It is certainly a pleasure
to be here today.  I previously have had the opportunity to
meet with Navy Leagues in San Diego, Guam, Singapore and
Japan, but this is my first time to speak to the Honolulu
Navy League.<br>

Therefore, I think it is appropriate that my first speech
since taking Command of the Pacific Fleet would be to this
particular group — and in this setting — to dedicated Navy
supporters who are meeting to honor our most outstanding
military men and women.<br>

As you know, this awards ceremony recognizes a total
of 68 men and women from the Mid-Pacific area . . . men
and women representing the Navy, the Marine Corps and
the Coast Guard. They range from Seaman to First Class,
and from Ensign to Lieutenant Commander.  They are the
very best of each service.<br>

What brings them here? Why do they serve? Why
would a young man or woman, especially one as outstanding
as today’s awardees, join the armed service in today’s
world?<br>

Actually, their answers would be as varied as their ages
and their backgrounds, and I doubt that you would find any
two explanations that match.  In my own case, I am from the
landlocked state of Illinois, but contrary to what you might
think, I joined the NROTC over 30 years ago, not to see the
ocean, but simply because it was a way to pay my college
tuition — all $300 per semester.  I also specialized in the
submarine service not because of the “Hunt for Red October”,
but because the more time I spent underwater, the less
time I was seasick.<br>

Some in this audience may have joined the military for
a sense of adventure and a desire for that “camaraderie of
the campfire” — a phrase that may sound like an odd one to
use in this day and age, but one which, in the 1800’s, accurately reflected the longings of many new recruits.  Some
things don’t change! The sense of camaraderie among military units still produces a very strong draw.<br>

What has changed over time is the caliber of the recruit.  During the early 1800’s when Lewis and Clark were
recruiting for their Corps of Discovery, that courageous
group who would open the lands west of the Missouri River,
the recruiting order was to “find and engage some good
hunters — stout, healthy, unmarried men, accustomed to the
woods, and capable of bearing bodily fatigue . . . ”<br>

Those recruits could never survive in today’s military.
The group before you today, though they are certainly
healthy, no longer need to be good hunters, accustomed to
the woods.  Moreover, they are not all unmarried, and not
just men.  These men and women are well educated and
technically smart. Most importantly, these men and women
are serving by choice, choosing to wear the uniform and to
serve our nation.  This last point is an important one.  We
could not operate the high technology Navy of today with
two year conscripts.<br>

What is it that makes a young person do this for a living?  I doubt that it’s for the money, or because the lifestyle
is easy or accommodating.  People today can expect to spend
well over half of their careers assigned to ships, deploying
with squadrons or marine expeditionary units, or in arduous
overseas assignments.  This means a lot of time away from
home, away from families, and away from loved ones.<br>

So, once again, why do they serve?  Perhaps because
they have a clear sense of purpose in what they are doing,
and they know they are making a difference.  In March of
this past year, CNN interviewed the USS Independence Battle Group Commander during the period of tensions between China and Taiwan.  When asked “Don’t your people
resent being called upon to do this?” the answer was simple.<br>

“My people don’t ask ‘Why us?’ They ask . . . ‘Who
else?’<br>

Who else, indeed?  Who else could exhibit the character
traits needed in a time of crises . . .  the character traits of
Trust, Honesty and Integrity?  Or, phrased in the words of
Chester Nimitz, the “attributes of loyalty, discipline and devotion to duty.”<br>

More importantly, the group in this room has another
character trait, leadership. Leaders trust others, and are
perceived as consistently fair.  They set goals and are result
oriented.  Most importantly for the future, they encourage
innovation.<br>

Many years ago I was given a small gem of a book entitled Lincoln on Leadership.  In describing true leaders,
Phillips also termed them as “self-starting” and most importantly, as “change-orientated”.<br>

Those of you who attended the CINCPACFLT Change
of Command last week heard one of my favorite quotes from
Abraham Lincoln.  You will hear it many times again, but in
its shortened form it starts with this question:<br>

 “Can we do better?”<br>

And it ends with this statement:<br>

“We must think anew, and act anew”.<br>

The leaders in this room do not need to be reminded of
that quote.  They already know that the best leaders never
stop learning and that it doesn’t matter from whom they
learn.  Admiral Nimitz, in a pamphlet entitled Some
Thoughts to Live By, acknowledge that some of the best help
and advice he’d had came from junior officers and enlisted
men.  He said “I have always made it a practice, therefore,
to listen to anyone, no matter what his rank or rate.”<br>

Nimitz’s statements is true today  . . . true for every
leader in this group.  You can never stop listening, never
stop learning, never stop incorporating new ideas.  Maybe
the name of the Lewis and Clark expeditionary team, the
Corps of Discovery, would be an appropriate one for this
group.  You, as the leaders in your services, are entering into
an unknown future.  You are the new Corps of Discovery.<br>

It will be your attitude that will set the tone for the future. I’d like to relay a story about attitude from one of my
favorite books, “A Second Helping of Chicken Soup for the
Soul”.  Actually, the story is a only a cartoon. It shows a
large wall, divided down the middle into two equal sections.<br>

The side on the right is entitled “Learning Experiences”, the side on the left is entitled “Successes”.  On each
section a women, who appears to be a teacher, has made the
traditional “count-to-the-number-five” hash-marks --- four
short lines up and down, a fifth line drawn diagonally
through the other four.<br>

On the side labeled “Learning Experiences” there are
over 20 such groups of five.  This translates into over 100
separate “learning experiences”.  On the “successes” side,
the teacher is drawing only the 14th mark.  This ratio ---100
trials contrasted with 14 success --- is fairly reflective of the
ratio in the real world.<br>

So, with the odds so heavily favored on the “learning
experiences” side, what will keep us from becoming mired in
problems instead of focused on finding solutions?  It will be
our attitude.<br>

Attitude . . . In the words of Grandma Moses . . . “The
world is what we make it, always was, always will be.”  This
will be the challenge . . . how do we view our world with a
positive attitude?  How can we be, not just the instruments
OF change, but also the catalyst FOR change!<br>

To the members of the Navy league the challenge is just
as valid.  Today, you are providing recognition to these leaders.  In the words off Benjamin Disraeli . . . “The greatest
good you can do for another is not just to share your riches,
but to reveal to him his own.”  A recognition ceremony such
as the one today does just that.  You are providing the forum
for the acknowledgment of achievement.  You are also providing  another vital ingredient . . . community support.<br>

With more than 4800 members, this Honolulu Navy
League is the largest Navy League council in the world.  I
can think of no greater testament to the fact that Hawaii has
a community which is supportive of our sea services.<br>

You, the community of Hawaii, provide a forum where
the military can fulfill its mission.  You support the finest,
most dedicated men and women the military can attract. To
paraphrase Admiral Nimitz, whose legacy began here in
Hawaii, “being a part of the military is honorable, soul-satisfying, and sufficiently remunerative to reward any active young person who loves his or her country and is willing
to accept responsibilities.”  He would have been proud of
this group and this community.<br>
Thank You.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
