<title>Remarks by ADM R.J. Zlatoper, outgoing CINCPACFLT, at CINCPACFLT Change of Command</title>
<!--#include file= Insert Chr$(34) / std / header.htm Insert
Chr$(34)-->
<body  background= Insert Chr$(34) / images / graphic /
backgrd.gif Insert Chr$(34)>
<h1>CINCPACFLT<br>
Change of Command</h1>
<h2> Remarks as prepared for<br>
Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Outgoing Commander in Chief,<br>
U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
Pearl Harbor, Hawaii<br>
07 November 1996<br>
</h2>
<hr>
<em><strong>Unclassified</strong></em>
<hr>
<pre><p>
Senator McCain, thank you for your kind words.  Your presence
here bridges my junior officer days to my present chronically
challenged situation magnificently, and sends a strong optimistic
signal to me that there is success to be had after a full Navy
career.  Admiral Johnson, thanks to you especially for joining
us.  Archie and I know how difficult it is to escape Washington
in a position like yours at times like this, but more
importantly, thanks for making time to visit Adak, Korea, Japan
and Guam enroute here.  That WestPac sweep sent a strong,
positive signal to our 215,000 Sailors and Marines in the region,
as well as our Japanese friends whom I visited Tuesday.  Admiral
Prueher, thanks for flying back from your Washington meetings to
be here with us.  This fleet is ready to support your plans.
CNO, I'm pleased to report to you that Pacific Fleet's readiness
is solid today, and we've handled our drawdown well during the
past 27 months, successfully meeting 10 real world contingencies
in the process, and as I speak 192 ships and 50,000 Sailors and
Marines are deployed in the Western Pacific, Indian Ocean, and
Persian Gulf showing America's commitment to peace and security
in the vital Pacific theater.<br>
Captain Baucom, thank you for opening Carl Vinson to all of us
today.  Your ship and your crew look great.  I can't think of a
more dramatic setting for the change of command of the Pacific
Fleet and destiny has once again united Carl Vinson and Zlatoper.
Carl Vinson is really special to me.  This magnificent ship is
the same vessel upon which I took my major command when I was the
first senior air wing commander in the U.S. Navy.  There were
many naysayers when we started that program.  Interestingly
enough, both aviators seated behind me followed my pioneering
course, so I guess it's alright to change with yours truly as the
air wing commander.  We flew carrier aircraft in the arctic for
the first time since World War II.  The weather was slightly
different than here.  And...the air crews of the Carl Vinson air
wing also did the flying in the movie "Top Gun"... You'll hear
more of that later.  I made my 1,000th carrier landing right over
there and then i assumed command 27 months ago as the 27th
commander of the  pacific fleet onboard this magnificent vessel.
Perhaps that explains why we have two chaplains on the dais here.
I really owed god on this one.<br>
I have had 33 years to prepare for this particular speech this
morning and the only i thing i can guarantee you all is that I'm
not ready.  So much to say in so little time.  This is a special
place in a special time.  The good news is that all of you are
special friends, so there is no need to tell you about the
importance of the pacific.  In one way or the other you've all
heard one of the 150 missionary of the pacific speeches I have
delivered throughout the world in the last two years.  Therefore,
you'll be spared a political/military/economic lecture.  Just
remember:  the 21st century will be the century of the Pacific,
and you should care about the Pacific, be concerned, and be
thankful for all that your pacific fleet is doing.  So on to my
speech.  I thought perhaps the best thing would be to deliver 3
short speeches instead of one.  One a speech of thanks.  One a
speech of reminiscence and one a speech on personal philosophy...
A soliloquy from the old guy if you will.<br>
First the speech of thanks.  In the past month I already I have
visited as many of the commands, civilian groups, and staff
personnel to whom i owe everything to thank them in person,
therefore my thanks will be selective and few... Just keep in
mind a quarter million thanks I should be offering.  I am an
energetic rational guy, but today I am emotional beyond belief,
and as I have said continually throughout October, there is an
inverse relationship between my eloquence and emotion... Bear
with me.<br>
My mother and father are the two smartest people I have ever
known.  They are my original and continuing heroes.  As my Dad
always counseled me when he took me on boy scout trips, leave the
boy scout camp cleaner than when you found it.  Dad, we've done
that here.  I think PacFleet is better across the board.  Mom,
you always said be pleased with the situation that you find
yourself in, work hard, get an education.  Well with two Ph.D's
and four masters degrees among your three children, I think
you've been successful beyond belief, and I think your comment
that doing the right thing is often times its own greatest reward
has had a high impact on me throughout.  Barry, you'll hear more
about Barry from this podium momentarily.  She has been my soul
mate for 26 years, has been with me through the successes on this
journey and I wouldn't be here without her, in fact I wouldn't
want to be here without her.  All who know us you know that is a
fact.  In most places we go when I'm not in uniform, I'm known as
barry's husband... Knew it was time to go at last week's Navy
Ohana Conference when two wives said the same thing to me and I
was in uniform...  In front row same gorgeous, talented,
energetic woman that I met at a Sunday volleyball match in
Virginia Beach.  She has made this tour a continuing joy.  She
has also been my tempering agent.  Although when I reminded barry
of another naval aviator she had once dated, who had gotten out
to become a potato chip salesman... And I asked her, "see, aren't
you glad you chose me instead of him?"  She quickly replied, "If
I'd chosen him, he'd be the battle group commander and you'd be
selling potato chips."  How true that is... Because I would not
be where I am today without her unwavering support, her guidance
and thoughtful counsel, and her love.<br>
My daughter, Ashley, recently engaged and in the midst of med
school exams is not here, has been a source of pride for all of
her 23 years and my son, Michael, who did come to be here for
this day has proven once again his wisdom.  Mike, your presence
is really special, thanks buddy.  God truly blesses those who
hang around with the chaplains a lot.  What kind of a man is
Michael?  Talk to him later, you'll be impressed.  One anecdote
I'll never forget was that our family wrote to each other through
each of my twelve deployments.  During Desert Storm my son
Michael, then 14 years old, wrote to me every night.  When I was
14, I didn’t even brush my teeth every night!<br>
I would like to acknowledge and thank our numbered fleet
commanders and the type commanders for their great leadership,
energy, a LGgen Jeff Davis Howell, our Fleet Marine Force
Commander; VADM Bob Natter, ComSeventhFlt; VADM Herb Browne,
ComThirdFlt; VADMs Brent Bennitt, ComNavAirPac, Al Krekich,
ComNavSurfPac and RADM Jerry Ellis, ComSubPac.  Along with RADM
John Sigler, the Deputy CINCPACFLT.  You have been a spectacular
team during my time here and teamwork is my favorite word in the
english language.  I sing the praises of all these leaders today.
America, you'll never know how luck you are to have them, but
there is one special event I must mention.  I have had a strong
interest in naval aviation all of my life generally and the
pacific fleet naval aviation specifically during these last two
years.  Our naval aviators are not always appreciated for their
great contributions.  I have tried not to meddle in VADM Brent
Bennitt's work, but I have had a great deal of interest, and he
knows it.  Today I am pleased to announce we are within ten days
of setting a new record for the longest period in the history of
Pacific Fleet naval aviation that we have operated without a
major aircraft accident.  What a great going away gift to the
senior attack pilot in the Navy from the professional PacFleet
naval aviators as an end to a career.  Keep flying safe, one day
at a time!<br>
Our Pacific Fleet ships and aircraft have the very best
supporting cast I have ever seen.  They are led capably by the
rest of our two dozen plus admirals.  I won't introduce them
individually, but thank them when you see them in today's
audience.  These gentlemen are responsible for all the good work
that has to be accomplished and their work has been
spectacular.<br>
Here in Hawaii the fleet staff deserves the credit and as you
know I lead but one component of the Pacific command.  My
colleagues from the Air Force, General John Lorber; Army, General
John Steele; and Coast Guard, RADM Tom Collins, along with LGen
Beak Howell, are partners in much of what we do and here in our
region joint really works.  Joe, you are fortunate to have a team
that works together so well... A truly joint blessing.<br>
To top it all we have the great fortune to be stationed here in
an island paradise, bathed in the spirit of aloha.  Barry and I
have been enriched by our experiences and we will sorely miss all
of the friends we have made here.  We thank you all for welcoming
us into your homes and hearts and we promise to return as often
as circumstances will permit.  One of my primary goals has been
to make our PacFleet personnel, military and civilian, a more
integral part of the local community, and I believe we have
succeeded.<br>
And now, if you will permit me, part two, reminiscences.  I am
trying to remember the first time I stood on the deck of an
aircraft carrier as a naval aviator and I can't, but I will
always remember this, my last, for today is a memorable occasion.
I don't remember my first A-6 flight in 1964, but I do remember
my last... It was Tuesday with VA-196, the last A-6 squadron in
the Navy.  Thanks main battery.<br>
I don't remember my first visit to Japan - yen 360 to one dollar.
I'll never forget my last when I was awarded the Grand Cordon of
the Rising Sun Tuesday, or Korea’s Tong Il Medal in August.<br>
I don't remember my first combat mission, although my log book
says it was April 6th, 1966 against a Viet Cong staging operation
inside Vietnam, but I will definitely remember my last combat
mission on February 17th, 1991 in a KA-6b during Desert Storm, 33
days into the 43 day war when I flew one mission.  I wanted to
fly in a war we won.  53 times ranger played the William Tell
Overture... Every time we launched a major air strike into
Iraq.<br>
I don't remember the first time I was aboard a navy ship when
there was a fire, but I will always remember my last fire at sea
onboard USS Forrestal on July 29th, 1967.  145 sailors were
killed, the Zuni rockets cooked off, it was then I realized the
ability of Sailors to selflessly come together without regard for
their own lives to save their ship and their shipmates... A
selflessness that I have seen every day in the fleet even
today.<br>
And although our Navy has changed considerably since then, that
one thing still remains, the quality of our sailors.  Foreign
dignitaries still accuse me of dressing up our officers in
enlisted uniforms when I take them aboard our ships and
submarines.  And by the way, some of the music you hear today may
seem non-traditional as far as changes of command are concerned,
but these non-traditional renderings are dedicated to the 212
shipmates men who died while serving on ships or in airwings with
me... Ours is truly an exciting, but sometimes cruel profession.
There are some other more mundane things in my career that I
recall today such as desks at which I've sat.  I don't remember
my first desk as a navy officer, a fold out valet onboard USS
Constellation in 1965 to be shared with two other officers, but I
will always remember my last desk, a solid 30 foot square desk
with 8 drawers, two cabinets and ten times the surface area.
It's not the size that I will remember but the fact that it
belonged to Admiral Chester Nimitz during his tour as CINCPACFLT
in World War II... Come visit the mini-museum we've created in
the entrance way... We're working to preserve our past and
traditions even as we move into the era of computers, e-mail, and
VTC's.<br>
Serving as CPF 50 years after Nimitz has been a special honor...
Because I have been able to follow the course of the war in the
pacific as we commemorated each of the major milestones...
Punctuated by the VJ-Day Commemorations here in Pearl Harbor last
August.<br>
This job, this staff, and this fleet are steeped in proud
tradition and history... And i am honored to have been a part of
it.<br>
I also know that the future of the pacific fleet is bright, under
the leadership of a naval officer who knows this region well,
Admiral Archie Clemins... And with the 250,000 great sailors,
marines and civilians of this fleet I know that the Pacific Fleet
will continue to do great things, and will live up to its proud
reputation.<br>
Today, November 7th, as I reflect on my career, it's appropriate
to note that this is also the 79th anniversary of the Bolshevik
Revolution.  I also don't remember my first encounter with the
Russians on active duty... There were simply so many encounters
during the first 20 years of my career... Although I think the
first was escorting a Bear-Delta bomber in the Mediterranean
while I was flying off the carrier USS Kennedy.<br>
But I will always remember my last encounter with the Russians...
In August as I attended the 300th birthday of the Russian Navy in
Vladivostok... As the Russians' honored guest... With VADM Archie
Clemins,... And ships and Admirals from Japan, Korea, and the
Peoples Republic of China.<br>
With USS Blue Ridge in port, and U.S. sailors walking around the
city... And the spirit of a blossoming friendship between two
nations...  I do remember as a grade school child praying for the
conversion of russia... Guess what, it worked... Indeed, the
world's political and military landscape has changed a great deal
in the last 33 years... For the better by any measure.<br>
But the world remains a dangerous place... And many long standing
tensions continue throughout the region.  We must make certain
that our nation maintains its strength, to prevent future cold
wars, and to deter armed conflict.<br>
Indeed our nation, and our world has changed a great deal in the
last 33 years... And so has our navy.  I can't remember my first
battle group work-ups, heck Lt. j.g.'s only wanted to get safely
back aboard the carrier.  But i'm pretty sure it centered around
open-ocean war-at-sea missions.  But on my last battle group work
ups, we practiced NEO, MIO, strike, humanitarian missions... And,
most importantly, we trained jointly.<br>
Today more than ever our nation relies on us to provide real
presence around the world...and our naval forces give us the
presence and flexibility to do that.  Second, our Navy has become
a better organization socially.  During my career we have led the
way in improving race relations, fighting drug and alcohol abuse,
fully integrating women into our ships and aircraft, and treating
all our members with dignity.  Our Navy has faced these problems
head on, and we are a better organization because of it.<br>
In fact, when you look at any objective statistics, we're doing a
better job than our society as a whole, by a large measure.
Third, our Navy has grown to realize that its people, not
hardware, that counts... Thankfully.  There has been a real
paradigm shift in how we think about taking care of people... As
senior Navy and DoD leadership came to understand that people are
a readiness issue.<br>
Have made real actions in improving QOL, in giving people a
louder voice in making decisions, and in providing them the
support and recognition they deserve and need to do their jobs
successfully.  I'm bragging today because I have been a loud
voice, perhaps sometimes too loud a voice for some on occasion,
but nonetheless...<br>
People are our most important resource, and they are what makes
our Navy great.  So much for reminiscences, that brings me to my
third and final presentation... Some personal philosophy.  The
topics I'll touch are attitude, loyalty, teamwork, ego, and my
leadership philosophy.  My best friend, Barry, and my son,
Michael, age 6, introduced me to the first philosopher that I
have really taken seriously, that is Theodore S. Geisel.  You who
have raised children may know him better by his stage writing
name, Dr. Seuss.  In his book Oh The Places You'll Go he provides
advice and rhymes for proceeding in life, weathering fear,
loneliness and confusion and being in charge of your actions.  As
Michael said from the first page...<br><em>
"Congratulations, today is your day, you are off to great places.
You are off and away.  You are on your own and you know what you
know and you are the guy who will decide where to go and will you
succeed, yes you will, indeed 98 3/4 percent guaranteed."</em><br>
Dr. Seuss' book is basically about attitude and the longer I live
the more I realize the impact of attitude on life.  It is more
important than facts, tasks, education, money, circumstances,
failures, successes, or what other people think, say or do.
Attitude will make or break any organization including the
military and the remarkable thing is we have a choice every day
regarding the attitude that will be in place for that day.  We
can't change the past, that is a fact.  We can't change the
inevitable, but I am convinced as VADM Herb Browne heard me say a
lot that while 80 percent of life is showing up, our satisfaction
with life is only 10 percent of what happens to a person and 90
percent on how we react to it.  We are in charge of our
attitudes.<br>
Second is loyalty.  Those who were on this ship 27 months ago for
my assumption of command might recall my pledge of loyalty... to
juniors, seniors, and peers.  It's still vital.  In a book titled
Without Remorse by a naval oriented author named Tom Clancy, the
author talked about loyalty and its importance.  He says, "Either
you keep the faith with your people or you don't.  If you don't
you fall into that habit then you are not worth serving or
protecting and then other people stop helping you, and then you
are in real trouble."  That's true for any successful team and
absolutely essential for a military organization.<br>
My third topic of my philosophy briefing is very simple.  It
involves teamwork and ego.  Fore two years you have endured
messages and letters from me hat shunned the personal pronouns
"I" and "ME".  It made for some grammatically difficult
formulations, but it was a graphic way to show we were working
together.  People working together, the only resource that
matters in our organization.  I hope to be remembered as someone
who cared about his people and who took care of his people with a
positive attitude and great loyalty.  I stayed in the Navy,
although I never intended to, because I had a commanding officer
who said that I was important to him and the Navy.  It struck me
deeply and for the next 32 years of my Navy service I have known
that good people are what's important.<br>
I've studied management including Maslow's Hierarchy, Magruder's
Theory X, Deming's TQM, Covey's 9 Habits, it seems to me that
being successful requires a four part program:  have a goal, make
a plan, work hard and take care of your people.  Life is hard,
and it's not always fair, but life is also fun.  It is much more
a matter of choice than it is a matter of chance.  In fact our
greatest gift lies in our ability to choose.  We are free to
choose our character, we are free to choose our values, we are
free to choose how to treat other people, we are free to choose
how to handle adversity and we are free to choose what we will
accomplish in life, and finally, we are free to choose our
attitudes.<br>
However, freedom is not free.  And protecting it takes hard work
and sacrifice.  To the men and women of the pacific fleet, you
have had my loyalty for the last 2 1/2 years.  I believe we have
worked successfully as a team.  We have been dedicated to each
other and to the mission of the united states navy and we have
prospered because of it.  Hopefully you have been provided an
environment in which to excel free of any form of discrimination
or harassment, we took good care of each other.  A little over
two years ago when I took command of the Pacific Fleet I didn't
think I could be happier or more proud.  When I look back at what
you have all done I can say without question this has been the
crowning achievement of my career.  I could not possibly have
been happier.  As i said, it's only right that I go back to the
great philosopher, Dr. Seuss, and another of his books called
Marvin K. Mooney which suggests in rhymes other ways the young
man Marvin K. Mooney could travel as long as he gets going now.
It ends with...<br><em>
"You can go by bumper boat or jet, I don't care how you go,
just get.  Marvin K. Mooney, I don't care how, Marvin K. Mooney
will you please go now.  I said go and go I meant, the time had
come so Marvin went."</em><br>
And Barry, it's time for us to go too.  What a great ride, what a
great time, what a great day.  Gracias, Arigato, Kamsah Ha
Mneeda, Thanks Mates, thank you all and may God bless you, God
Bless the United States Navy and God Bless America!  I will now
read my orders.<br>
<hr>
