<title>Remarks by ADM Archie Clemins, Incoming CINCPACFLT, at CINCPACFLT Change of Command</title>
<!--#include file= Insert Chr$(34) / std / header.htm Insert
Chr$(34)-->
<body  background= Insert Chr$(34) / images / graphic /
backgrd.gif Insert Chr$(34)>
<h1>CINCPACFLT<br>
Change of Command</h1>
<h2> Remarks as prepared for<br>
Admiral Archie Clemins, USN<br>
Incoming Commander in Chief,<br>
U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
Pearl Harbor, Hawaii<br>
07 November 1996<br>
</h2>
<hr>
<em><strong>Unclassified</strong></em>
<hr>
<pre><p>
Senator McCain,  ADM Zlatoper,  ADM Prueher,  ADM Johnson, Honored Guests, Men  
and Women of the Pacific Fleet, Ladies and Gentlemen...<br>
Marilyn and I are particularly happy to have our mothers, Marian Paddick and Earline  
Clemins, and our two children, Becky and Travis, here with us today.  We are also  
honored to see many of our relatives and friends, some dating back to high school and  
college days, as well as many friends from the Western Pacific...some people will use any  
occasion to visit Hawaii!<br>  
My remarks will be appropriately short.<br>  
This past month Marilyn and I were granted a rare gift, the gift of time. We had several  
weeks to transition, not only from one assignment to another, but also from one time zone  
to another, while we drove across much of the continental United States.  Somewhere in  
the state of Montana we chanced to hear a National Public Radio interview with Stephen  
Ambrose, a well-known historian, who had just written a new biography entitled  
Undaunted Courage, the story of the Lewis and Clark Expedition.<br>  
This three year expedition, involving roughly two dozen highly skilled and carefully  
selected men, was commissioned by President Jefferson in 1803.  It was tasked to find a  
trans-continental water route, one which would follow the mighty Missouri to its  
headwaters, then to the mouth of the Columbia River, and thus, eventually to the Pacific  
Ocean.  It was perhaps the most significant exploration ever undertaken.  It was also  
unusual in that Lewis and Clark, both Army Captains, shared their command equally.<br>  
The Lewis & Clark expedition was also a dangerous one.  To achieve success it required  
not only a great deal of luck, but also a team which became (in Ambrose's words) "a  
superbly disciplined family" one with unquestioning trust in themselves and the  
knowledge of the strengths and skills of each individual.<br>
The Lewis and Clark expedition became relevant to Marilyn and me because we followed  
its path through several states.  It is relevant to this occasion, because exactly 191 years  
ago today...in 1805...Lewis and Clark first viewed the Pacific Ocean, the same ocean you  
see beyond this Harbor.<br>  
When they reached the Pacific, Lewis and Clark were only half finished with their journey.  
They still had much more territory to explore, and still had to return to Virginia.<br>  
Unlike Lewis and Clark, Admiral Zlatoper and I cannot share this command.  So, at our  
own halfway point at the Pacific Ocean, he has relinquished his command to me, and will  
return to Virginia.  He has left me superbly skilled and carefully selected men and women  
who are equal to the second half of our task, the exploration that lies ahead.<br>  
Our future journey will be challenging.  Meriwether Lewis viewed his journey with great  
optimism.  We must follow his example.  In all of Lewis's journals there are re-occuring  
themes of adequate preparation, of great joy in the adventure, and of continuing  
innovation.  This latter theme does not belong alone to Captain Meriwether Lewis.  You  
will also find it in one of my favorite passages President Lincoln's annual message  
to Congress in 1862:
<em>  
"Still the question recurs "can we do better?"  The dogmas of the quiet past, are  
inadequate to the stormy present. The occasion is piled high with difficulty, and we must  
rise with the occasion.  As our case is new, so we must think anew, and act  
anew."</em><br>
I come to this job with a great sense of gratitude to ADM  Zlatoper and a great awareness  
of the legacy which I am inheriting.  This is the job to which Chester W. Nimitz came  
during World War II.  Marilyn and I will live in his Hawaiian house, the Nimitz House, at  
37 Makalapa.<br>  
Hawaii is in a unique geographical location.  We can look across the Pacific in either  
direction --- either to the East or to the West.  Looking eastward we see continuing  
pressure to "do better" and "think anew" while carrying out the many responsibilities we  
are assigned.  As we look westward, we see the potential explosion of the economic  
growth in Asia.  We see new markets of international trade and the resulting improvement  
in economic prosperity for all.  Asia is on the move, and it is changing -- dramatically,  
quickly...in a way never envisioned by Lewis and Clark. The Pacific Century is at  
hand!<br>  
Our future will be a time of great challenge, just as it was for Lewis and Clark, and it will  
also be a time of bold experimentation, where we must think anew as President Lincoln  
exhorted, while we continue to make the Navy a place where the best and proud serve,  
and we accomplish the mission to the standards of excellence set by ADM Nimitz.<br>  
Thank you very much.<br>  
<hr>
