<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<title>Pacific Fleet Change of Command: Guest Speaker, SEN John McCain</title>
<h2>Remarks as delivered by<br>
Senator John McCain<br>
Guest speaker at the<br>
U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
Change of Command</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, HI. (Thursday, November 7, 1996)</strong>
<hr>
     Thank you.  I am greatly honored to be here today, and to participate in this wonderful ceremony as the men and women of the United States Pacific Fleet officially welcome their new commander, and say farewell and thank you to the man who led you so well for more than two years.<br>

     Admiral Zlatoper and I have known each other for a long time.  We had the honor of serving our country together in difficult circumstances, in trying times.  We flew together in VA-46, and we shared the honor of serving on the USS Forrestal when on a Saturday morning in July in 1967, the men of that magnificent ship were summoned to heroism.<br>

     On that morning, I sat in the cockpit of my A-4 preparing to fly another sortie over North Vietnam.  My parachute rigger, a fine man from Mississippi, wiped off my visor, as he always did, and handed me my helmet.  I started my engine, and a rocket hit the fuel tank under my airplane.  I never saw my friend from Mississippi again.
<br>

     No ship in the United States Navy was better prepared for combat than the Forrestal.  We were all proud to serve on her.  We had just launched 700 sorties against the enemy in four days without a single loss.  We were ready for more.  But we were not ready for the fire that looked to Zap and I and every man serving on the Forrestal to be consuming the entire ship.<br>

     The men of the Forrestal may not have been prepared for that unexpected enemy, but they fought it courageously nonetheless.  They fought it all day, and well into the next.  They fought it with the tenacity usually reserved for hand-to-hand combat.  And they saved the Forrestal.<br>

     Years from now -- hopefully many, many years from now -- when Zap and I are in the Old Sailors Home, we will still remember the lesson of courage and service we learned those many years ago as we watched the crew of the USS Forrestal so bravely answer their summons to heroism.<br>

     Not long after the Forrestal fire, Zap’s and my career paths diverged.  My last mission over Hanoi, regrettably, took a bit longer to complete than scheduled.  Zap kept flying combat missions in an effort to shorten the length of my visit.  As he did so, he exhibited the same professionalism and courage which would distinguish his later service commanding the USS Ranger battle group in the Persian Gulf War.<br>

     Of the many lessons which Vietnam taught me, the one I value most is the realization that although Americans have fought valiantly in many noble causes, we are not assured that the battle will always be necessary or the field well-chosen.  In the end, Americans at war, professional and conscript alike, always find their honor in their answer, if not their summons.  My friend, Admiral Zlatoper found much honor in his answer to his country’s call to arms.<br>

     Years later, in better times, Admiral Zlatoper and I would again work together on behalf of the service we both love.  As a member of Congress, I came to highly value Zap’s frank counsel on issues affecting naval aviation, military budgets, and the drawdown of Naval forces.<br>

     As Chief of Naval Personnel Zap fought to ensure that the Navy’s drawdown wouldn’t force anyone out of a job.  He did it smartly through attrition and selective early retirements, helping America to keep faith with the men and women who served our nation so honorably in the United States Navy.  He also fought for funding for critical quality of life projects like housing, child care and family service centers.<br>

     As Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Pacific Fleet, he made tough decisions about long ship deployments from homeports and loved ones.  And most importantly, in his determination to improve the quality of life for Navy personnel, he gave much louder voice to the sailors in Navy decisions about issues affecting their well-being.<br>

     The men and women he commanded responded to his superb leadership by performing superbly themselves in places like the Taiwan Straits, the Korean peninsula, and the skies over Iraq.<br>

     Outside of the Admiral’s office, in the entrance foyer, the walls are adorned with photos and mementos of Admiral Nimitz.  There is also a case bearing Admiral Nimitz’ medals and sword.  But most impressive is the battle map which Admiral Nimitz used to chart the movement of naval forces during the Battle of Midway.  You can see that extraordinary commander’s battle notes listed day by day, written in red pencil.<br>

     The uncertainties and ambiguities of the age we live in now stand in stark contrast to the moment in which Admiral Nimitz gathered the ships of his fleet which had survived Pearl Harbor and Coral Sea -- three carriers and a small number of cruisers, destroyers and submarines -- and ordered them to battle against Admiral Yamamoto’s Combined Fleet which in its entirety consisted of eight carriers and 230 other combat ships.  Defeat -- a mathematical probability if not certainty -- would have sacrificed virtually all naval defense of Hawaii and the Pacific coast of the United States.<br>

     What possessed Admiral Nimitz to take what seemed such a desperate gamble by committing his small force against the immense strength of the unbeaten Japanese fleet while Washington counseled caution?  What explains his firm faith in the reliability of the intelligence upon which he based the disposition of his ships and his confidence in the men who would command them in battle?  How did he know that the Americans whom he ordered into harm’s way would obey his orders and reward his trust with such courage and resourcefulness that they would bring their country our greatest naval victory, indeed, one of the greatest naval victories in the history of human conflict?<br>

  	He believed in his men.  He believed in their courage and their ability.  He knew that they, like he, were empowered by the justice of their cause, by a love of America expressed in action, in sacrifice, if not in words.  Trust, derived from his appreciation of his countrymen’s virtues, and his wisdom about how such men would discharge their duties in a desperate battle, was the essence of Admiral Nimitz’ extraordinary leadership. <br>

	Small wonder, then, that Admiral Zlatoper has memorialized Admiral Nimitz so.  Nimitz is the model which every commander should emulate.  By memorializing Nimitz we memorialize the very finest virtues of our blessed and beautiful country, and by so doing provide an occasion to remember not just the greatness of American history, but that the greatness of our destiny rests in the hands of every man and woman blessed to call America their home.  That’s why, Admiral Zlatoper, has taken so seriously his responsibilities to the men and women under his command.  He knew that he and they shared equally in the great honor of defending a great nation.<br>

	Zap, you have served your fleet, your Navy and your nation well.  You will be first to direct all praise to the men and women under your command.  But I know that they would direct it back to you - - the man at the helm. <br>

	I want to thank you and Barry for your many years of exemplary service to America, and bid you not good-bye, but fair winds and following seas for I know we will see you again.  I know you will find new ways to serve the Navy and America, and I will continue to rely for many years to come on your wise counsel.  <br>

	Admiral Clemins and Marilyn: congratulations and welcome.  I am confident that you will both distinguish the noble tradition you inherit today.  I look forward to working with you as you lead this great Fleet toward its always magnificent destiny. <br>

	I would like to close by speaking directly to the men and women of the Pacific Fleet.  You serve your country in a place where my family has been privileged to serve for three generations.  My grandfather was an aviator, my father a submariner.  My father was CINCPAC during the Vietnam War, during dark days for our nation and for him personally.  This Fleet sails in waters where their name is still remembered, and their memory revered.  I hold this Fleet closer to my heart than any human institution that I have ever been a part of save my family.  The Pacific Fleet and the Navy was for many years the only world I knew.  It is still the world I know best and love most.  <br>

	I envy you, your service in this Fleet.  I trust in your willingness and ability to uphold the honor of your Fleet and your country.  For I have seen the best of America here in the Pacific for more years than I care to count.  And I know that the best of America still make their living at sea in defense of their country’s cause.  Make the most of these days for you will never forget the honor of your service in this Fleet nor will your country forget the honor you gave her in seas where so many Americans fought for love of country.  And I thank you for the honor of inviting me to return to a place I love so well.  Thank you. 
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
