<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Remarks upon presentation of the Grand Cordon of the Order of the Rising Sun
</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Tokyo, Japan (Monday, November 4, 1996)</strong><br><br>
<hr>
I am deeply grateful and most humbled that you have bestowed this award upon me.  <br>

However the real glory goes not to me, but to the people who made it all happen:  the 
Sailors and Marines of the U.S. Pacific Fleet... their counterparts in the Japan Maritime 
Self Defense Force... and the leadership in the Japan Defense Agency and Maritime 
Staff Office.  <br>

And I am especially appreciative of the efforts of  Admiral Natsukawa, who as Chief of 
Staff has sought to continue building the interoperability of our two services.  <br>

The security relationship between Japan and the United States--and especially 
between the U.S. Navy and the JMSDF--is a relationship that is extremely important... 
and it’s making a positive difference in the region.<br>

As I look back on my career in the Navy, I have especially fond memories of Japan... 
from my time as 7th Fleet Chief of Staff in 87-88, to my present role as CINCPACFLT.  
The Japanese people I’ve worked with over the years have been extremely 
professional and very supportive.  But most of all they’ve been warm and friendly.<br>
So as I depart Japan for the last time as CINCPACFLT, these words come to mind: <br>
“Nihon wa watashi no kokoro no furusato desu”.  <br>
Japan will always occupy a very special place in my heart... and I am forever grateful to all of you for making it so.  <br>

Thank you, and I am looking forward to continuing our friendship.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
