<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<title>Remarks by ADM R.J.Zlatoper, CINCPACFLT, at 3rd Fleet Change of Command</title>
<!--#include file= Insert Chr$(34) / std / header.htm Insert
Chr$(34)-->
<body  background= Insert Chr$(34) / images / graphic /
backgrd.gif Insert Chr$(34)>
<h1>Third Fleet Change of Command</h1>
<h2> Remarks as prepared for<br>
Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
San Diego, California<br>
25 October 1996<br>
</h2>
<hr>
<em><strong>Unclassified</strong></em>
<hr>
<p><pre>
	Thank you, Connie.  It's truly is a pleasure to be here this
morning.  It's a pleasure because it's a beautiful San Diego
morning, and we're looking out over the skyline of one of the
greatest towns in the world.  Although last time I stood here, it
was raining so hard, I couldn't see that skyline!  It's a
pleasure because we're standing on the deck of our nation's most
modern and ready command ship, the USS Coronado.  It's a pleasure
because we're among friends... friends from the community,
friends from other commands, friends from other branches of the
service, friends from other nations, and friends who have served
before us.  But most of all, it's a pleasure to be here today
because we're honoring one of our nation's premiere fighting
forces--the United States 3rd Fleet.

	Change of command ceremonies always stir a mix of emotions
for all parties involved.  We're sad to see an outstanding
officer depart...  But we're also excited for him as he moves on
to undertake even greater challenges and responsibilities.  We're
anxious about what the new guy will be like... although in this
case I can tell you there's no need to worry.  And at the same
time we're proud of all the great things our command has done.
That's certainly the case today with the 3rd Fleet change of
command... especially the part about having pride in this Fleet's
accomplishments!

	You know, as I was thinking about 3rd Fleet and all that
it's done under Vice Admiral Connie Lautenbacher for the past 26
months, the words "conventional wisdom" came to mind.
Conventional wisdom:  the prevailing school of thought... the
established way things are viewed... the widely accepted
standard.  You've probably seen Newsweek magazine's regular "CW
watch" feature which tracks our nation's conventional wisdom...
Assigning up and down arrows to politicians and celebrities based
on how they've lived up to their reputations.  It's a way we can
quantify the difference between what we expect, and what we
actually get.

	So why do I mention all of this today, as we bid farewell to
Vice Admiral Connie Lautenbacher?    I mention it because Vice
Admiral Connie Lautenbacher has defied the conventional wisdom in
all that he's done over the past two years.  And while he's had
some up-arrows, he's also had some down-arrows...

	For example, conventional wisdom says that Admirals are
supposed to look older and more mature ...   And while people
have often said that I am too young looking to be an Admiral,
even I pale in comparison to Connie Lautenbacher.  In fact, were
I a bartender instead of a Fleet commander, I wouldn't serve him
without first checking his I.D.!

	Conventional wisdom also says that Admirals listen to
mainstream music... like country-western or rock 'n roll.  But
not Connie Lautenbacher... He's a Kingston Trio addict, and has
every album they've ever made.  In fact, at a recent dinner he
hosted, his guests were required to arrive early so they could
drive downtown to Coronado's Sunday concert featuring the
Kingston Trio for pre-dinner cocktails!

	And conventional wisdom says that Admirals drive around in
nice, stately automobiles.  But Connie Lautenbacher drives the
"brown bomber"... a perfect pier car, it only looks better when
it gets accidentally oversprayed!  It's sure to be a real crowd-
pleaser in the Pentagon's mall parking lot!

	So Connie, I'm sorry to say, on the areas of mature looks,
musical taste, and choice of a vehicle, you rate a "down arrow"
from Zap Zlatoper's CW-watch!  But there are also some areas
where you deserve an up arrow... a very big up arrow...

	... Like with what you've done to make 3rd Fleet one of our
nation's premiere fighting forces.

	Conventional wisdom used to say that 3rd Fleet wasn't a real
warfighter...
	... That its mission was solely to train deploying forces...
	... That it didn't need a command ship...
	... That it didn't need to train jointly...
	... And that it didn't need to play a role in building
relationships with other nations.

	Conventional wisdom said that battle groups and amphibious
ready group's didn't need to work together...
	... That C4I was just an abstract concept and not a
practical reality...
	... That the "Pacific Rim" didn't include Latin American
nations.
	... And that you could never bring a Navy from Latin America
into a large Pacific exercise like RIMPAC.

	But as Third Fleet commander, Vice Admiral Conrad
Lautenbacher has not only defied conventional wisdom... he has
left it in the dust!  He has shown that Third Fleet can be a
warfighter... and a very good one... through the success of such
exercises as Tempest Express, where 3rd Fleet controlled 20
ships, 200 aircraft, and 20,000 personnel.  He has made jointness
a way of life at Third Fleet... incorporating Army, Air Force,
special ops, Marine and Coast Guard participation in every
exercise he has conducted, and through the addition of liaison
officers on his staff.

	He has integrated carrier battle groups and amphibious ready
groups to create an innovative new concept of the naval
expeditionary task force.  He has taken C4I from abstract concept
to practical reality... creating what has become the model
communications architecture for the joint command ship of the
future.  He has pioneered the Joint Forces Air Component Command
Afloat concept to support afloat operations during low intensity
conflicts.  He has enhanced our relationship with Latin American
nations, coordinating more than 150 port visits... And leading
the way in training with Mexico, Chile, Peru and Ecuador.  And he
has embraced Latin America as a part of the Pacific Rim...
bringing Chile into RIMPAC '96 exercises with Japan, Korea,
Australia and Canada for the first time ever.

	But most importantly, Connie Lautenbacher has taken care of
his people.  He understands that people are 3rd Fleet's most
important resource... and he's fought to put them first in all
that he has done.  He drove a lot of changes in this command
ship, adding over an acre of office space... But before he did
any of that he ensured that berthing and crew habitability were
upgraded first.  In difficult decisions about operating tempo,
Connie Lautenbacher has always been the first to ask, "how will
this affect the Sailors?"  He truly loves his people... And I can
tell you he has been their advocate in every action he has
undertaken.

	Connie, I know you would be the first to look at all the
successes of 3rd Fleet over the past 26 months and give credit to
the men and women in uniform who made it all happen.  But I also
know that your people give you credit... and they join me in
thanking you for your inspirational leadership.

	In the Navy, the price you pay for doing such a great job is
that you get to move on to bigger, better and more challenging
things... and that's certainly the case with Connie.  He's going
to become Chief of the Navy's Office of Program Assessment in
Washington, D.C. ... an extremely important job in our
increasingly technical Navy.  It's great to see another Pacific
Fleet flag officer moving into a very important and influential
Washington position.  We have certainly seen a trend over the
past few months... With Connie to OPA, Norb Ryan to OLA, and Jim
Ellis to OPNAV N3N5.  We're "Pacifying" the Pentagon!  It just
goes to show how Pacific experience is viewed positively by
senior Navy and DOD leadership.

	Susan, I am especially appreciative of your role in Connie's
successful tour here.  You also have defied conventional
wisdom...
... Creating a training program for CO's spouses,
... Helping raise 22-thousand dollars for a scholarship program,
... And co-hosting numerous visiting dignitaries.
You have also provided Connie with support, counsel and
encouragement... He couldn't have done it without you.

	But today just as we're sad to see Connie and Susan go,
we're also excited about our new 3rd Fleet commander, Vice
Admiral Herb Browne.  Herb has been my Deputy Commander in Chief
for the past 15 months, so I can attest to his abilities.  And I
know he was happy about taking these orders... because it meant
he could be reunited with his wife, Lieutenant Commander Jill
Browne.  Herb and Jill, congratulations to you.  You're
inheriting a first-rate team at Third Fleet with great people and
a vitally important mission.  I know you are up to each and every
challenge ahead.

	Let me close by congratulating all the men, women and
families of Third Fleet for all your great accomplishments over
the past two years.  I'd also like to thank our friends and
supporters from the community and other nations who have joined
us here for this special occasion.

	You are all a part of the Third Fleet success story... and
you are all a part of why our Navy and our great nation continue
to defy conventional wisdom.

	Thank you and God bless you all... Connie, if you will join
me...
<hr>
<center><table>
