<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<hr>
<CENTER><h1>CINCPACFLT Speeches</h1>
</CENTER>
<title>Fleet Master Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet Speeches: Oahu Enlisted Navy Birthday Ball</title>
<hr>
<h2>Ohau Enlisted Navy Birthday Ball<br>
Remarks as delivered by<br>
AFCM(AW) George Watson, USN<br>
Fleet Master Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet<br></h2>
<hr>Pearl Harbor, HI, (October 18, 1996)
<hr>
<em><strong>Unclassified</strong></em>
<hr>

<P>Greetings... 

<P>Since the U.S. Navy was established as the Continental Navy on October 13th, 1775, we’ve been on watch... observing  the high points and low moments in our nation’s history... and often helping turn the tide to change a low moment into a high point.

<P>For two-hundred-and-21 years, our Navy has literally helped write history.
Unfortunately, we tend to think of history as a series of days and dates to remember instead of being a series of events involving people, people just like you and me.

<P>When we do remember our history, we usually talk about the leaders, people like Nimitz and Perry, or about battles, like Midway or Manila Bay.

<P>Tonight I want to talk about another group of people who made Navy history.

<P>People like Ruben James, who volunteered to go on a raiding party in Tripoli Harbor during the War with the Barbary Pirates in 1804.  During the raid... to scuttle the captured warship Philadelphia... James was seriously wounded during hand-to-hand combat... wounded severely in both hands, making welding a cutlass next-to impossible.  Despite his wounds, or perhaps because of them, James put himself between an attacking pirate and the commander of that raid, LT Stephen Decatur.   Decatur was uninjured, thanks to James.  Boatswains Mate Ruben James recovered from his wounds and continued to proudly serve  his Navy   for another 32 years.  Ruben James made history...

<P>...just like a Sailor named Dorie Miller.  Miller was a mess steward aboard USS West Virginia on the morning of December 7th, 1941.  When his commanding officer was critically injured during the attack, Miller... who’s battle station had been destroyed in the first minutes of the battle... got his skipper off the bridge and to safety.  Petty Officer Dorie Miller then manned an anti-aircraft gun, even though he’d never been trained to fire an anti-aircraft gun.  Dorie Miller was the first hero of World War Two.
	

<P>In the undeclared war against terrorism, Robert Dean Stetham (STEED-ham) didn’t make a conscious decision to be a hero, or to make history.  Stetham was a Steel Worker Second Class, a SeaBee diver coming back with five other divers from a routine repair job in Greece in the late spring of 1985.  Terrorists took over their flight in Athens, detouring the plane to Beirut.  When authorities didn’t meet the hijackers demands, they killed Petty Officer Stetham... murdered him because he had a U.S. military id-card.  Robert Stetham probably never saw himself a hero, he was just a Sailor.  A Sailor, like Ruben James and Dorie Miller.


<P>We’ve named three ships after Ruben James, one after Robert Stetham.  Dorie Miller’s name graces new housing here in Hawaii.  All three are heroes, all three are part of our history as Sailors, and all three share something with all of us in this room...  <STRONG>Honor, Courage, and Commitment</STRONG>.

<P>Honor has three main characteristics: Honesty, Integrity and Sincerity.

<P>Honesty denotes the presence of character and particularly the absence of deceit or fraud.

<P>Integrity indicates a soundness of moral principle which no power or influence can impair.

<P>Sincerity implies absence of deceit and a strong adherence to truth.

<P>Bravery and Fortitude are the two characteristics that make up courage.

<P>Bravery is characterized by resolute fearlessness and endurance.

<P>Fortitude is strength.  Strength of mind that enables a person to encounter danger or bear pain or adversity.

<P>Commitment, is an agreement or pledge to do something in the present or future.  An action we all experienced when we took our initial enlistment oath, and subsequent re-enlistment oaths .......for us old timers.

<P>I believe the one word that brings the true meaning of this home is  pride .  Pride, is a state or quality of being proud.  You would not be here tonight if you did not possess this quality.  Look around the room and you can see and feel the pride we have for country, service and self.

<P>I don’t think Ruben James ever sat through a Navy Rights and Responsibilities workshop... but I’m sure he understood what our Core Values are all about.  I’m sure he... and Dorie Miller... and Robert Stetham knew that these simple ideas were fundamental to our Navy’s success over its two-hundred-and-21 years of service.  And I think they would be pleased to see us remind ourselves about ideas that are such a part of how we do business, least we take them for granted.

<P><STRONG>Happy Birthday Navy!</STRONG>


<HR>
