<html>
<title>CINCPACFLT Remarks at SEVENTHFLT Change of Command</title>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<hr>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>
Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet<br>
7th Fleet change of command ceremony<br></h2>
<h3>Aboard USS BLUE RIDGE<br>
Yokosuka, Japan<br>
13 September 1996<br>
</h3>
<hr>
Distinguished guests, friends from the Japanese community,
families, and men and women of the United States Seventh Fleet...
Ohayo gozaimasu, good morning, and welcome.  It’s a pleasure to
come together to honor one outstanding officer as he departs from
a glorious tour... to welcome aboard another excellent officer in
his place... and to celebrate the strong relationship between two
great nations.<br>

This morning I want to tell you about an historic event that took
place 145 years ago today... something which has significance to
all of us sitting here this morning.  It was on this day in 1851
that the USS Susquehana--one of our Navy’s first steam-powered
ships--took on coal in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.<br>

You’re probably saying, “Well that’s great Zap, but we’re at the
7th Fleet change of command in Yokosuka, Japan.  What does that
have to do with us?”<br>

Well for starters, the voyage of the Susquehana vividly
demonstrated the tyranny of distance that still complicates naval
planning 150 years later.  You see, the ship was going from
Norfolk to Hong Kong... on a voyage that would take 8 months,
cover 18,500 miles, and require 8 coaling stops -- in Madeira,
Rio, Cape Town, Mauritius, Zanzibar, Ceylon, and Penang.
Susquehanna’s journey showed that sending ships to far away
locations can be expensive, time-consuming, and logistically
difficult.  And while we’ve drastically improved the speed and
range of our ships over the last century and a half -- and we’ve
built canals to bisect major land masses -- distance still
remains a major complicating factor in all that we do.  For
example, today it takes 16 days for ships based on the U.S. West
coast to transit to the western Pacific... and 32 days to the
gulf!  Which is why it is important to keep naval forces forward
deployed close to where they might be needed...<br>

Which brings me to my second point:  the Susquehana, upon arrival
in Hong Kong, became the first flagship of the newly-formed East
Asia Squadron.  It later changed its name to the Asiatic
Squadron... and is considered to be the precursor for today’s
U.S. 7th Fleet.<br>

The squadron’s ships made regular visits to places like Hong
Kong, Shanghai, Manila and Singapore... much like 7th Fleet units
do today.  And the East Asia Squadron played a key role in
protecting commercial interests, building diplomatic relations
with other nations, and keeping the seas open and free.  When you
think about it, this bears a striking resemblance to today’s 7th
Fleet, whose mission is:  To maintain the regional stability that
is essential to economic prosperity... To build positive
relations with other nations through our cooperative engagement
strategy... And to ensure freedom and open access to this
region’s vital ocean highways.<br>

Seventh Fleet units conduct over 100 exercises each year with 15
different countries, demonstrating our goodwill and commitment to
the region... and they respond in time of need to show our
resolve in promoting peace, just like they did earlier this year
in the waters off Taiwan... and just like they did last year when
tensions flared on the Korean Peninsula.<br>

They also serve as diplomats, conducting staff talks and visits
with government and military leaders throughout the 41 nations in
their area of responsibility... building trust and confidence
throughout the region.  Which brings me back to the USS
Susquehana...<br>

The third reason that the ship’s voyage to East Asia is
significant is because it meant the Susquehana would be able to
carry out an important diplomatic mission a few years later.<br>

That mission was in 1854... under the command of a man named
Perry... to a place called Japan.<br>

When Commodore Matthew Perry rode the Susquehana into this bay
and negotiated the Treaty of Kanagawa with the Edo government,
the course of history in Japan and the U.S. was forever changed.
Little did Commodore Perry know the magnitude to which the
relationship between the United States and Japan would grow a
century and a half later.  Today, with $1.3 trillion in trade
annually between Japan and the United States, we share the
largest trade relationship of any two nations on earth!<br>

Our strong partnership for peace -- in the form of our mutual
security treaty -- has become the linchpin of stability in this
region.  And our Navy-to-Navy relationship is the most
comprehensive of any in the world.  Additionally, Japan has
graciously allowed U.S. naval forces to be based here, including
the 17 ships of the Pacific Fleet’s forward deployed naval force.
These ships are 16 steaming days closer to potential trouble
spots... which enables us to overcome the tyranny of distance I
spoke of earlier.<br>

Cooperative efforts between the U.S. And Japan have helped
resolve regional conflicts, guaranteed freedom of the seas, and
reduced the risk of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.
And even more importantly, we have promoted democracy, respect
for human rights, and free markets.  There is little doubt that
ours will continue to be a crucial partnership as we sail into
the unpredictable 21st century.<br>

As I stand here today and look at the United States Seventh
Fleet, and consider all that it has accomplished over the past
two years under Admiral Archie Clemins, I am reminded of
Commodore Perry’s East Asia Squadron.  7th Fleet has enjoyed many
successes... in maintaining stability in this critical part of
the world... in building friendships throughout the region... and
in strengthening our partnership with Japan.  These successes
haven’t just happened... they are the result of hard work and
dedication by all on the 7th Fleet team.<br>

And they are a result of the visionary leadership of Admiral
Archie Clemins.<br>

Through his foresight and untiring commitment to his AOR, Archie
has been the impetus for numerous extraordinary accomplishments.
For the past two years he has reached out to the numerous diverse
nations of this region, and fostered a spirit of friendship
throughout.  He spearheaded the first-ever CARAT series of
exercises with six nations in southeast Asia.  He improved
military-to-military relations with India by reestablishing
Malabar exercises.  He orchestrated the first-ever flagship
visits to such ports as Nagasaki;  Donghae, Korea;  and Port
Klang, Malaysia.  And he planned and executed two highly
successful port visits to the Peoples Republic of China.<br>

Archie has also aggressively worked to bring 7th Fleet into the
information age.  He implemented cutting-edge C4I upgrades for
his staff, flagship and task force commanders.  He developed a
wide area network to build connectivity between 7th Fleet,
CINCPACFLT, USCINCPAC and OPNAV... the first of its kind in the
Navy.  And he was responsible for countless other innovations...
including VTC capabilities on his major afloat units, basic e-
mail capability for all his ships and squadrons, and the Navy’s
first combined tactical and ADP local area network.<br>

But most importantly, Archie has taken care of his people.  He
embarked on an aggressive habitability upgrade to improve quality
of life for the staff and crew on the flagship... and he sought
to ease the strains of high operational tempo on his people by
working to rework deployment rotations.  His people are extremely
important to him... and I can tell you that he has been their
advocate in every decision and recommendation he has made.<br>

Archie, I know that you would be the first to look at all of
these accomplishments, and to give your people the credit.  But I
also know that they give you credit, and they join me in thanking
you for you inspirational leadership.<br>

I’d be remiss if I didn’t mention one particular member of the
7th Fleet team who shares the credit for the accomplishments.
Marilyn, we are all appreciative of your role in Archie’s
successful tour here.  He couldn’t have done it without your
support, counsel and encouragement... and we all thank you for
that.<br>

In the Navy, the reward for success is that you get to move on to
bigger and better things.  And that is certainly the case with
Archie and Marilyn.  Archie will be relieving me in two months as
CINCPACFLT, and I can think of no one better qualified.  In fact,
I recommended that he be the one to relieve me.  I’ve known
Archie for many years... since he was CTF-74 and I was 7th Fleet
chief of staff.  In fact, he relieved me then too!<br>

Though I must admit, this occasion is bittersweet for me.  Bitter
because I know that it means my tenure as CINCPACFLT is drawing
to a close... but sweet because I know that I will be replaced by
such an outstanding officer, a visionary leader, and a true
friend.<br>

This occasion is also sweet because we are getting such an
outstanding replacement as our 7th Fleet commander... Vice
Admiral Robert Natter.  I also met Bob many years ago when he was
Admiral Jeremiah’s executive assistant at CINCPACFLT... and I
have always known he would go places.  He was my head detailer
when I was Chief of Naval Personnel... and I sent him to be Chief
of Legislative Affairs.  At the time he protested because he
wanted a battle group... but I assured him that if he took the
OLA job and did well, he would get a 3rd star and become a Fleet
commander.  Well Bob, this old Admiral was right... and here you
are today!<br>

Bob and Claudia, congratulations and welcome to you both.  You
bring an impeccable record of past successes... and your
leadership and appreciation of this AOR will make you a great 7th
Fleet commander.<br>

This morning, as we stand aboard the modern day equivalent of the
USS Susquehana -- the 7th Fleet command ship, USS Blue Ridge -- I
can’t help but wonder what Commodore Perry would think if we
could somehow bring him here...<br>

He would see how the U.S. Navy’s role in East Asia has
expanded... with the 7th Fleet playing a greater role than ever
in maintaining regional stability.  He would see the strong
relationship that the U.S. enjoys with Japan.  And he would see
all of you... the Sailors, Marines, families and community
members -- both American and Japanese -- who share the credit for
the success of the United States 7th Fleet.<br>

I can’t help but think that he would be proud.<br>

Thank you and God bless you all.  Archie, if you will join me at
the podium...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
