<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000250-B018-296</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/cnfj-d.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108110447 text/html 13922
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:16:55 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>COMNAVFORJAPAN<br>Change of Command</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Yokosuka, Japan (Wednesday, June 26, 1996)</strong><br><br>
It's a pleasure to join all of you on this beautiful day, to honor one outstanding leader before he steams smartly over the horizon... to welcome another excellent officer in his place... and to revere the strong relationship between Japan and the United States.<br>
<br>
But before I talk about that, I want to share with you about the recent renovation of the lobby at CINCPACFLT headquarters.  We made it into a "mini-museum" portraying America's century and a half of involvement in the Pacific.  The centerpiece of this display is a large mural showing Commodore Matthew Perry's expedition to Japan in 1854.  It's a grand portrait by an American artist showing Perry and his men looking dignified and dressed smartly in their uniforms.<br>
<br>
But prudent historical procedures demand that all perspectives be examined... so we have included next to the mural two renditions of Perry's expedition by a Japanese artist.  It shows a gruff and surly image of Perry, with harsh features and facial hair -- which was considered savage and unsightly to Japanese of the Tokugawa era.  In fact, one account of the time described American's "disgusting fondness for beef and milk, and the simplicity of their religious observance" which consisted of "clasping their hands on every seventh day."<br>
<br>
But by the time Perry's visit was over, the two sides had warmed.  The Japanese presented gifts of lacquerware, silk and porcelain... and Perry gave the Japanese a scaled-down locomotive and telegraph set.  Perry and his delegation also serenaded the Japanese officials with a minstrel show... which made everybody laugh and have fun "to general hilarity."  When Perry rose to depart, a jovial Japanese official "threw his arms about the Commodore's neck, crushing, in his tipsy embrace, a pair of new epaulettes, and repeated with maudlin affection, 'Nippon and America, all the same heart!'"<br>
<br>
I'm reminded of those words today as we're gathered together... "Nippon and America, all the same heart."  150 years after Commodore Perry, our two nations still share a fascination with each other.  We're enamored of each other's cultures... We're studying each other's languages more than ever before... We continue to enjoy learning about one another...  And Japanese -- who formerly detested beef -- are going to McDonald's in droves... While Americans are consuming sushi and tofu in record proportions!<br>
<br>
And we're more economically intertwined than ever before.  I spoke with U.S. business leaders at the American Chamber of Commerce in Tokyo yesterday... and they are truly aware of just how interdependent our two economies are.  With $1.3 trillion in trade annually between Japan and the United States, we share the largest trade relationship of any two nations on earth!  As evidence of the impact that this relationship has on our domestic economy, it's worth noting that well over a million American jobs are directly dependent upon trade and investments in Japan.  No doubt this important economic relationship gives us a shared stake in maintaining a peaceful and stabile environment for conducting business.  Which brings me to my next point...<br>
<br>
One of the strongest parts of the overall positive relationship between Japan and the United States is our bilateral security relationship.  Together, we held tyranny in check throughout half a century of Cold War turmoil... and are prudently staying the course in this new era of post-Cold War uncertainty.  Our efforts to maintain peace and stability have been successful.  We have fostered a secure environment in which this region could undergo awesome economic growth.  Former Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs Joseph Nye expressed it another way:<br>
<br><em>
"Security is like oxygen:  you do not tend to notice it until you begin to lose it. The American security presence has helped provide this 'oxygen' for east Asian development."</em><br>
<br>
Indeed, our strong partnership for peace -- in the form of our mutual security treaty -- has been the linchpin of stability in this region for over half a century.  But if there is one part of our security relationship that best defines our friendship and partnership, it is without a doubt our Navy-to-Navy relationship.  If you were to line up a JMSDF officer alongside a U.S. Navy officer, the only difference is that the JMSDF officer would have a sakura blossom where the U.S. Navy officer has a star.  We share so many other things:  our education, our training, our tactics, our system of rank and promotion, our staff organization structures... and our values:  love of country, personal honor, and devotion to duty.  These similarities make it easy for us to be interoperable... and that allows for seamless operations with each other, like we just saw last week during RIMPAC '96 -- the largest naval exercise in the Pacific.  We conduct many other bi-lateral exercises each year -- an average of one per week -- as well as staff talks, personnel exchanges, and ship visits to each other's ports.<br>
<br>
Additionally, Japan has graciously allowed U.S. naval forces to be based here, including the 17 ships of the Pacific Fleet's forward deployed naval force.  Having the USS Independence battle group and the USS Belleau Wood amphibious group forward deployed to Japan is a vital part of maintaining U.S. presence in the western Pacific.  These ships are 16 steaming days closer to the Korean peninsula and other potential trouble spots than units based in the continental U.S.<br>
<br>
In fact, when you account for transit time, maintenance and work-ups, one ship forward deployed to Japan equals 3 to 4 ships based in San Diego in terms of presence and crisis response capability!  And through its generous host-nation support, Japan absorbs 70% of the support costs to maintain these important guardians of stability.  That gives the United States the ability to maintain and modernize our naval forces in this part of the world despite a significant reduction in force.  And as I announced yesterday, our newest ship will join the Independence battle group in September:  the Arleigh Burke-class, Aegis guided missile destroyer USS Curtis Wilbur.<br>
<br>
Cooperative efforts between the U.S. and Japan have helped resolve regional conflicts, guaranteed freedom of the seas, and reduced the risk of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.  And even more importantly, we have promoted democracy, respect for human rights, and free markets.  There is little doubt in my mind that ours will continue to be a crucial partnership as we sail into the unpredictable 21st century.  This morning's terrible bombing of a U.S. Air Force living compound in Saudi Arabia reminds us just how unpredictable, and potentially dangerous, this world can be.  This is precisely the kind of violence against humanity that the U.S. and Japan work so closely together to prevent and deter in east Asia.<br>
<br>
There are many people who share the credit for the successful relationship the U.S. Navy enjoys with Japan.  A good number of those individuals are here today:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... Members of the local community who help to make our Sailors and their families feel welcome...
<li>... JMSDF and defense agency officials who help to facilitate continued interaction between our two sea services...
<li>... Members of the staffs from CNFJ, the U.S. Embassy and COMUSJAPAN who help to build our cooperation and interoperability...
<li>... And the Sailors and their family members who serve as informal ambassadors of the United States to our Japanese hosts...
</ul>
But there is one person in particular, on the American side, who has been the guardian of this important relationship for the past two and a half years:  Rear Admiral Jake Tobin.  He has been the U.S. Navy's pre-eminent leader in fostering our continued successful relationship with our most important Asian ally.  He has led a quantum increase in both the quantity and quality of bilateral exercises with the JMSDF... and significantly enhanced our cross-training agreements.<br>
<br>
Jake has been a strong advocate of U.S. naval presence in the western Pacific... Making a clear, cogent case for forward deployed naval forces in Japan.   And, perhaps most importantly, he has been an advocate for the people... the Sailors, Marines, civilians and their families serving in Japan.  He fought on their behalf to keep cost of living allowances at a fair level.  He brought new housing developments such as Ikego to fruition... while working to modernize existing housing.  And he worked to expand and enhance recreational facilities for personnel serving at bases throughout Japan.<br>
<br>
I have come to value his insight and his in-depth knowledge of the issues... and have never questioned his analysis and advice.  Jake Tobin is a naval officer of unquestionable skill, character, strength and leadership... and he has served the Pacific Fleet, his Navy and his nation well:  a total of 36 years in the naval service... 30 of those years on flying duty; nine in command positions.  He is not someone who has sought the spotlight, but rather has worked quietly, diligently, and effectively to do the finest possible work for the Navy, our nation, and our allies.<br>
<br>
In this final leadership position, by helping to maintain and improve the strong partnership between the U.S. Navy and Japan, he has directly contributed to peace and stability in the Far East.  Rear Admiral Jake Tobin has been good for the U.S. Navy, our forward-deployed naval forces, and Japan-U.S. relations.  He can't say it --he's humble -- but I can!<br>
<br>
Jake, I know that you would be the first to point to the people in the audience -- Japanese community leaders, JMSDF leadership -- and to those from your staff standing in ranks... to give them the credit for all of these wonderful accomplishments.  The operators, planners, engineers, attorneys, ASW experts, environmentalists, comptrollers, and other men and women of U.S. Naval Forces Japan are, indeed, a tremendous group of skilled and dedicated professionals.  But I also know that they thank you... and they join me in giving you credit for helping to keep the relationship between the U.S. Navy and Japan just as strong as ever before.<br>
<br>
And I know they join me in thanking Sally for her own, huge contributions.  Not only for her own family ... but the Navy family -- including more than 4,000 hours as a volunteer for Navy and Marine Corps Relief Society.<br>
<br>
We wish Jake and Sally fair winds and following seas as they sail off on a new journey.  I don't just mean that figuratively... I understand that sailing will be a big part of their future as they transition to civilian life!  Hopefully Jake will have plenty of time to remember where his reading glasses are.  I hear that he tends to lose them.  In fact, the JMSDF once even had his glasses flown in from Atsugi when he forgot them there!  I suppose that's another example of the strong relationship between the U.S. Navy and the JMSDF!<br>
<br>
Jake and Sally, thank you for your service.  You will be missed.  I don't bid you "sayonara," but rather "dewa mata"... because I know we'll meet again soon.<br>
<br>
But fortunately we have the #1 draft choice to replace Jake.  In fact, we have somebody whose career is almost a mirror image of Jake Tobin's.  RADM Mike Haskins is also a P-3 pilot... coming to us from command of the Patrol Wing in the Atlantic -- a job which Jake Tobin also held.  An experienced naval officer with 30 years of service to his nation, he brings impeccable credentials of past successes...  and I have every confidence that he will carry on the great work that Jake Tobin has done.<br>
<br>
Mike and Joanne, congratulations and welcome to you.  You're assuming a position of vital importance to our Navy and our nation... I know you are  fully up to each and every challenge ahead.<br>
<br>
Let me close by congratulating all the people here today who are part of the success story between the United States and Japan.  Agreements, memoranda of understanding and treaties are important to our relationship.  But when you really think about it, what makes the partnership between Japan and America even stronger is the human element... and the fact that we can all come together to celebrate our strong friendship.<br>
<br>
A century and a half after Perry's visit to Japan, those words still ring true...<br><br>
..."Nippon and America... All the same heart!"...<br>
... Nippon to Amerika... Kokoro wa onaji!<br>
<br>
Thank you and God bless you all.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
