<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>American Chamber of Commerce Japan</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Tokyo American Club (Tuesday, June 25, 1996)</strong><br><br>
I appreciate your warm hospitality, and this chance to talk with all of you.<br>
<br>
It's great to be in Tokyo.  Coming from my headquarters in Hawaii, you probably think I'm kidding.  But I'm not, for several reasons:  first, it's great to have this opportunity to meet with such an important group of business leaders in one of the world's economic hubs.  Second, having lived in Yokosuka for two years back in '86- '88, it's great to be back, catch up with old friends, and reminisce on some great times.<br>
<br>
As many of you know, the U.S. Navy's history of involvement in Japan is one that is long and proud.  It goes back to 1854 when Commodore Matthew Perry negotiated the Treaty of Kanagawa, opening relations with the Edo government.<br>
<br>
It's been 22 months since I took command of the Pacific Fleet and since then I have become known in Navy circles as the "Preacher from the West".  That's because I spend much time traveling around the continental U.S. telling Eurocentric Americans why they ought to be thinking more about the Pacific.  It surprises them coming from a guy named "Zlatoper" but I usually convince them that, although their hearts may be in Europe, Africa or Latin America, their wallets are in the Pacific.  I tell them how Asia consumes a third of our nation's exports;  how 3 million American jobs are directly linked to trade and investments in Asia;  how the world's economic and industrial centers of gravity are shifting towards Asia;  and I tell them how U.S. aggregate trade with Asian nations -- 37% -- exceeds that of the European Union and Latin America combined.  In sum, explaining why all Americans should care about the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Expect I'd be preaching to the choir if I were to talk about Pacific Rim economic importance to a group of American business leaders sitting in Tokyo!  But I would like to share three things with you today:  first, some of our current security concerns in the Pacific.  Second, how the U.S. Pacific Fleet, in general, addresses those concerns to promote a secure environment for trade and commerce.  And finally, how our forward deployed naval forces based in Japan specifically fit into the overall equation of maintaining peace and stability in the Pacific.  On that last point, I have some good news to share with you today that affects the force structure of U.S. naval forces here... but I'll get to that later.<br>
<br>
First, consider some of the potential trouble spots in this region... and their potential to impact economic prosperity.  A stunning example occurred earlier this year, when tensions flared up between China and Taiwan.  It was a concern because any sort of instability has the potential to disrupt peace, trade... and the entire region's economic growth and well-being.  Consider this:  even though not a single shot was fired, stock markets in the region plunged, investors scrambled to convert currencies to dollars and gold, and newspaper headlines warned ominously of closed sea lanes, rice hoarding, and instability in a region built on open trade routes and political calm.  It became a concern in the U.S. ... because of our $92 billion in annual trade with China and Taiwan and the fact that 485,000 U.S. jobs are linked to that trade.  One report said that some high tech companies in northern California and elsewhere which rely on Taiwan for manufacturing silicon semiconductors were worried that production could be impeded.  There was talk of a potential silicon crisis -- akin to oil crises caused by past conflicts in the Persian gulf.<br>
<br>
The tension between China and Taiwan is just one of several long-standing animosities in the region.  Other trouble spots include:<br>
<br>
<ul>
<li>... China and India.
<li>... India and Pakistan two historic rivals whose tensions have erupted in armed conflict three times since 1947.
<li>... Russia and Japan technically still at war since agreement was never reached on northern islands after W.W.II.  In recent weeks have seen news reports of Japanese fishing boats being fired upon by Russians in disputed waters.
<li>... In southwest Asia... Iran and Iraq;
<li>... And the Korean peninsula... where the North spends 25% of its GNP on defense despite a stalled economy and famine.
</ul>
There also is civil strife or insurgencies in more than a dozen countries, from the Philippines and Sri Lanka to Cambodia and Indonesia.  And there is anxiety among many smaller Asian nations who harbor concerns about the long-term ambitions of larger powers in the region like China.<br>
<br>
Then there is the alarming militarization of Iran, and continued threats from Iraq... all in a region that supplies oil for most of the world.  The Gulf War in 1991 tripled the price of oil for four months.  It cost the U.S. $200 billion in GNP, and more than $1 trillion in GNP worldwide.  A cut-off of the oil supply from the Arabian Gulf or to oil trade routes would be devastating to the entire world economy... which explains why we take threats from Saddam Hussein so seriously.<br>
<br>
As populations grow and demand for natural resources increases, expect to see greater potential for conflict over resources.  Competing claims over the Spratly Islands has this potential... China, Taiwan, Philippines, Malaysia, Vietnam and Brunei all claim at least a portion of this oil rich area.<br>
<br>
And then there's Russia.  The current dead heat presidential race reminds us that Russia is at a critical juncture in deciding its future course.  We all hope for positive development, politically and economically, in the former Soviet republics.  The U.S. Pacific Fleet conducted bilateral exercises in Hawaii with the Russian Navy last year.  It was a very positive experience.  But Russia still retains significant military capabilities which must be watched... particularly their submarine program, which is still alive and well.<br>
<br>
In summary, there are plenty of reasons to be concerned about our interests and prospects for peace.  And there's no shortage of military potential when you consider that this region is home to 7 of the 9 largest militaries in the world, the world's 2 largest standing armies and 7 of the 10 most numerous submarine forces.<br>
<br>
Given the U.S.'s growing stake in Asia, and potential threats to our interests and peace, what is the Pacific Fleet doing to protect American interests and promote peace in the Asia-Pacific region?  Our guiding strategy is called cooperative engagement... which means using our naval forces to engage the nations of this region in a positive way.<br>
<br>
In 1995, the Pacific Fleet contributed to this strategy through 125 exercises with 25 nations... Navy-to-Navy talks... Personnel exchanges... 800 port visits to 40 nations... And hundreds of community relations projects.  These activities show our goodwill, build partnerships, and reduce the chances of miscalculation that could result in military confrontation.<br>
<br>
Countries who may not trust their neighbors see the U.S. as an "honest broker"... with no territorial claims or ambitions in the region.  I have traveled to many of these countries and met with leaders... and discovered an overwhelming consensus on this issue:  they want the U.S. to keep its forward presence in the Pacific.  Earlier this year in Singapore, I heard Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defense, Dr. Tan Ke Yam, declare to a room of 1,000 delegates from other Asian nations during the Asia-Pacific Defense Forum:<br>
<br>
<em>"For many years now, the military presence of the U.S. has been and continues to be a factor for stability in the region."</em><br>
<br>
Our presence provides a tangible sign of American commitment and goodwill that is consistent through the ups and downs of trade disputes and other issues.<br>
<br>
In this unpredictable post-Cold War era, naval forces in particular often are the best means for what U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry calls "preventive defense."  Why naval forces?<br>
<br>
<ul>
<li>... Because naval forces can operate independently of diplomatic clearances or host country agreements... responding quickly in times of crisis.
<li>... Because they possess the power to project power ashore with carrier based aircraft, or with Marine expeditionary forces from our amphibious ships.
<li>... Because 95% of world's international trade is carried over the seas... and the ability to keep these sea highways open is of vital importance.
<li>... And because naval forces offer diverse and flexible mission capabilities.  Long range bombers are great at projecting power, but they're of little value if you're trying to evacuate an embassy, conduct peacekeeping operations, or carry out a humanitarian mission!
</ul>
But... there's always a but... naval forces are only effective when they're on the scene when they're needed.<br>
<br>
Recent tension between China and Taiwan clearly illustrates the value of our being there in Asian waters, with capable and ready naval forces.  When needed, ships of the USS Independence battle group based right here in Japan -- were only a couple of days away from Taiwan area.  Their readiness became an unmistakable expression of American commitment, communicated world-wide on CNN and other media.  As a precaution, the President underlined our resolve a few days later by ordering a 2nd battle group to the western Pacific, led by the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz.  It added up to powerful signal of U.S. Interest in a peaceful resolution of the Taiwan issue, reducing the chance of either side making a miscalculation or taking unwise action.  And, according to the USS Independence battle group commander, Rear Admiral Jim Ellis, no one aboard said "why us?"  They said "who else."<br>
<br>
This is at least the 8th time since I  became CINCPACFLT 22 months ago that Pacific Fleet forces have been called upon for real-world operational contingencies.  Others include:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... Haiti, where we loaned ships to the Atlantic Fleet.
<li>... Iraq, twice, in the falls of '94 and '95.
<li>... Rwanda... where our amphibious forces conducted an evacuation of besieged U.S. embassy personnel.
<li>... Somalia... covering withdrawal of UN forces.
<li>... the Korean peninsula... where naval presence helped deter aggression while tough negotiations concluded a framework to address the north's nuclear program.
<li>... and Bosnia... where Pacific Fleet contributed EA-6B electronic countermeasures aircraft, and Seabees to build bridges, base camps, command posts and other facilities for U.S. Troops.
</ul>
The fact is, Fleet operating tempo is as high now as in any period of the Cold War... but we're doing so with much smaller force.  Five years ago my predecessor had 250 ships and 280,000 Sailors and Marines.  Today I have 194 ships and 215,000 Sailors and Marines.  But the demand for these naval forces has remained constant... or even increased.<br>
<br>
One of the ways we're maintaining our strong presence in the Pacific even after downsizing is through our forward deployed naval forces here in Japan.. which brings me to my third point.  In the 1980's when the U.S. was building towards a 600-ship Navy, our 17 ships based in Japan were important... but today, those 17 ships are absolutely essential.<br>
<br>
With a smaller Fleet, these ships are taking a more active role in maintaining our forward presence in the western Pacific.  They are 16 steaming days closer to potential trouble spots than their counterparts based on the west coast of the U.S.  Tremendous presence is provided by having a carrier battle group and an amphibious ready group 365 days a year right across the Straits of Tsushima from the Korean peninsula and other potential trouble spots.<br>
<br>
If you were to try to duplicate that presence with rotationally deployed ships from the west coast, it would take 3 or 4 times as many ships to equal those based in Japan... allowing for transit times as well as stateside maintenance periods, training and work-ups.  Forces based in Japan also require maintenance and training periods... but, they remain in the region during these phases... still contributing to forward presence in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Besides reducing the number of ships and aircraft needed to meet Fleet requirements, our Japan-based forces probably are the most cost-effective in the American military inventory.  Japan pays over 70% of the total costs of stationing U.S. forces in Japan.  This amounted to more than 5 billion dollars in 1995.<br>
<br>
Over the years, we also have significantly upgraded and modernized our forward deployed naval forces.  We replaced the aircraft carrier USS Midway with USS Independence... with its larger and more capable airwing.  We stood up the USS Belleau Wood amphibious ready group in Sasebo... giving us a forward deployed amphibious group for the first time since the Vietnam War.  Last year we added two new mine-countermeasures ships in Sasebo to work closely with the JMDSF and Korean Navy in mine warfare training.  We substituted two Aegis cruisers, USS Bunker Hill and USS Mobile Bay for older ships... to keep our technology at the state of the art.<br>
<br>
To quantify the increased capabilities that upgrading our ships has had, consider these numbers:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>-- While the size of the Pacific Fleet has decreased by nearly 30% since 1986, the number of ships forward deployed to Japan, 17, has remained the same.
<li>-- But the total number of aircraft our forward deployed carrier can carry has increased from 75 to 90.
<li>-- The total number of combat-equipped Marines which can be lifted by our amphibious ships has more than doubled:  from 1,500 to over 3,500.
<li>-- And the missile-magazine capacity of our surface combatant ships operating from Yokosuka has nearly doubled:  from 350 in 1986 to more than 600 missiles today.  Ten years ago, those missiles were limited to relatively short-range anti-air and anti-submarine weapons.  Today our ships carry an impressive mix of sophisticated anti-air missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and precision Tomahawk cruise missiles for striking targets hundreds of miles inland.<br>
</ul>
So while the total number of ships has remained the same, the capabilities have increased by an order of magnitude.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, today we are announcing that USS Curtis Wilbur, a new guided missile destroyer currently based in San Diego, will replace the frigate USS McClusky effective this September.  Curtis Wilbur will be our first Arleigh Burke-class destroyer to be forward deployed to Japan.  Equipped with the latest generation of the Aegis combat system.  Also the first surface warship in the world to incorporate low-visibility, or stealth technology.  And it adds 91 more missiles to our forward-based forces.  By the way, Curtis Wilbur will be the first combat ship based here with a fully integrated male-female crew of officers and Sailors.  With one Arabian Gulf deployment to their credit already, this crew already has established a reputation of top performers.<br>
<br>
Curtis Wilbur's arrival this fall will give our forward deployed naval forces in Japan that much more capability... while demonstrating continued U.S. commitment to the security of the Pacific region and defense of Japan.  I hope that many of you will have the opportunity to visit this new ship, as well as others in Yokosuka and Sasebo... and to meet the fine young men and women who take them to sea.  It's awe-inspiring to watch them at work... in the combat centers, computerized propulsion plants, and on the flight deck of USS Independence.  The 18 year olds who launch and recover $25 million helicopters... you wouldn't have trusted with the keys to your car two years ago!<br>
<br>
I hope you will share these messages with your colleagues and contacts in business.  In my view, there is an important, symbiotic relationship between the U.S. Pacific Fleet and the Asian, multinational business community.<br>
<br>
We help to provide a stable environment for trade... what former Assistant Secretary of Defense Joseph Nye called the "oxygen for development."  Furthermore, the strong security relationship between the U.S. and Japan... and our very close military-to-military ties... complement our political, economic and cultural relations.<br>
<br>
You, in turn, contribute to peace by building a shared stake between nations with trade and investments... which makes conflict and its resulting instability unattractive to potential adversaries.<br>
<br>
Together, we're making Asia a more peaceful and prosperous part of the world.  I believe this is a partnership of historic proportion and global importance, as we approach what many say will be the "Century of the Pacific."<br>
<br>
Thank you again for your interest, and for this opportunity to meet with you.  If there is time remaining, I would be happy to take a few questions, to hear your comments.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
