<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Navy League Convention<br>Awards Luncheon</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Hilton Hawaiian Village, Waikiki, Hawaii (Thursday, June 20, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Good afternoon and a warm Aloha!  It's wonderful to have so many leaders of the Navy League and friends of the Navy coming together here in Hawaii for this convention.  I would like to congratulate Hugh Mayberry, Dick Fahrenwald, Jim Pitten, Michael Lilly and everyone else involved in making this convention a success. <br>
<br>
Traveling myself as CINC, I have met with Navy League councils from Honolulu and Hilo, Hawaii to Oklahoma City, Cleveland, Dallas, Seattle, Los Angeles, Charlottesville, Virginia, and elsewhere.  Therefore I know, from first-hand experience over many years, that the Navy League provides tremendous support to the Navy and other sea services.<br>
<br>
This is done by telling our story to other Americans, encouraging quality young people to serve, educating the American people about the continuing need for strong sea services and, as we just witnessed, by recognizing and rewarding excellence in our people.<br>
<br>
So... on behalf of the 250,000 Sailors, Marines and civilian employees of the United States Pacific Fleet, thank you for your strong support.  The Hawaiian concept of "ohana" comes to mind.  It literally means "family," but in concept embraces the notion of close spiritual and personal bonds.  The Navy League is part of the Fleet's "ohana," and we're delighted to have you here.<br>
<br>
Of course, it also means I have you as a captive audience here for a few minutes ... and so I'd like to take advantage of this time to share my perspectives on this vast region called the Pacific.  Will offer four observations I've made, based on nearly two years as CINCPACFLT. <br>
<br>
First, after nearly two years, I am more convinced than ever that the Asia-Pacific region is the single most important region in the world to the United States.  Your heart may be in Europe, Africa or Latin America... but your wallet is in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Rising prosperity in this region over last two decades has had a direct impact on prosperity in U.S.  Nations of Asia-Pacific account for 37% of total U.S. trade... compared with 20% for European nations.  3 million American jobs are directly related to exports and investments in Asia... and that figure is expected to rise to over 6 million within a decade.  These jobs are not low-paying "Mcjobs" of the service sector, but rather pay average 14% above non-export related jobs. <br>
<br>
The Pacific also has political importance to us:  rising global clout of Asian nations... China permanent member of u.n. security council... and Japan may soon be one as well.  And emotional importance:  9 million Americans of Asian-Pacific ancestry... 200,000 American sons and daughters lost to conflict in Pacific give us an emotional stake in its future.  Together, these factors give us... Indeed, all Americans... good reason to care about the Pacific. <br>
<br>
Second, after nearly two years in this job, convinced that we have more reason than ever to be concerned about the region.  Numerous historic animosities:  India-Pakistan, China-Taiwan, Russia-Japan, North Korea-South Korea... to name but a few. <br>
<br>
There is also much civil strife, in countries like the Philippines, Sri Lanka, Indonesia and Cambodia.  And numerous territorial disputes:  Spratly islands (China, Taiwan, Philippines, Malaysia, Vietnam, Brunei);  Takeshima-Tokto (between Japan and South Korea), and Northern Islands (between Japan and Russia). <br>
<br>
Tensions around Asia are particularly concerning when you pause to consider that Asia has:  two largest standing armies in world;  7 of the 9 largest militaries...  and 7 of 10 most numerous submarine forces.  In short, there are plenty of reasons to be concerned, especially when you consider our stake in Asia that I mentioned earlier. <br>
<br>
Third point is that, after the past two years, I feel even more strongly that America's sea services are uniquely-suited and ready to respond to security concerns in the 21st century.  Just look at some of the real world contingencies Pacific Fleet forces have responded to since August 1994:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>Reinforced forces in Arabian Gulf after Saddam Hussein massed his military near the Kuwait border... twice.
<li>Moved additional forces to the northwest Pacific when tensions escalated on the Korean peninsula.
<li>Conducted flawless amphibious withdrawal of U.N. forces from the devastated country of Somalia.
<li>Sent PACFLT units to the Atlantic and European theaters... Ships to restore democracy in Haiti, and even as we speak PACFLT EA-6B's flying over Bosnia.
<li>And most recently, sent USS Independence and USS Nimitz battle groups to waters near Taiwan to show our commitment to a peaceful resolution of tensions.</ul>
Because they operate from the sea -- independent of host-country sensitivities or diplomatic clearances -- naval forces are the ideal means for the U.S. to respond to potential crisis.  But there are even more things we do on a daily basis which contribute just as much to maintaining peace and stability in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
For example, Exercise "Cooperation from the Sea" with the Russian Navy last August -- the first-ever bilateral exercise with Russians in U.S. waters and training areas ashore.  We helped to embrace this former Cold War adversary as a future partner in peace.<br>
<br>
Or what about RIMPAC -- the largest multilateral exercise in Pacific -- bringing together over 30,000 Sailors from six nations right here in Hawaii. <br>
<br>
PACFLT units conduct more than 125 bilateral exercises with over 20 nations each year... And 800+ port visits to foreign nations annually.  We also conduct staff talks, personnel exchanges, community relations projects... all to foster goodwill and build positive relations with other nations that is consistent through the ups and downs of trade disputes and other issues.  I have traveled to many of these nations and met political and military leaders... and I've found that, almost without exception, they support continued robust U.S. presence, particularly of U.S. Navy ships and aircraft. <br>
<br>
But the Pacific Fleet today is considerably smaller than that of only 5 years ago...  196 ships vs. 250 ships... 215,000 USN/USMC vs. 250,000.  Yet our overseas presence is just as high as at anytime during Cold War. <br>
<br>
The good news is we are using remaining resources efficiently and effectively to compensate for the reduction in force, including:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>Outsourcing and civilianizing many functions that used to be done by uniformed personnel.
<li>Increased utilization of our 35,000 reserve personnel. 
<li>Consolidating ship and submarine maintenance facilities where it makes sense.  
<li>Increased reliance on our forward deployed naval forces based in Japan.  
<li>Eliminating rules and requirements that don't make sense.  
<li>And making a renewed commitment to our most important resource:  the men and women who serve.</ul>
That brings me to my fourth and final point:  people really are our most important resource.  Today's awards ceremony showed some of the fantastic men and women who make our Fleet great... And you'll see thousands more tomorrow aboard USS Kitty Hawk for those of you joining me at sea. <br>
<br>
Even the most technologically-advanced ships and aircraft are useless without trained and motivated Sailors to operate and maintain them... and supportive families backing them up.  That's why we've been careful to keep faith with them throughout downsizing... and by making a renewed commitment to quality of life.  Senior Navy and DOD leadership understands that quality of life is a readiness issue, which explains why we've actually put more money into housing, commissaries, MWR, childcare and family service centers. <br>  
<br>
We're also being careful not to let the weight of downsizing fall on our people's shoulders.  We remain committed to controlling deployment lengths and "perstempo".  By the way, we still need about 50,000 of these sharp young people a year to keep our Navy young and upwardly mobile.    As Navy League members and business and community leaders, you are some of the best recruiters he have.  Please help pass the word:  we still are hiring! <br>
<br>
In closing, I would like to remind you that your Navy and Marine Corps accounts for about 5% of the federal budget.  That means it takes 5 cents out of every tax dollar to keep us...  Forward deployed...  Engaged with other nations...  Equipped with the best possible ships and aircraft...  Manned with some of the finest young men and women in our nation...  Protecting vital U.S. interests abroad...  And maintaining peace and stability in a dangerous and unpredictable post-Cold War world.  All in all, I think you will agree that is one of the better-spent nickels from your tax dollar...  And I hope that is the message that you will take back to your communities around our great nation. <br>
<br>
Thank you all, God bless...I look forward to having you aboard Kitty Hawk tomorrow.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
