<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Naval War College<br>Current Strategy Forum</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Newport, Rhode Island (Wednesday, June 12, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Good afternoon... Or "aloha", as we say back in Pearl Harbor.  I appreciate the opportunity to come out and share my Pacific perspective with you.  Thanks to Jim Stark, Dr. Wood, and the staff of the Naval War College for hosting this forum again.  This is my 12th trip back to the East Coast since becoming CINCPACFLT... and my 3rd to Newport.<br>
<br>
But these trips to the U.S. Mainland pale in comparison to trips I've taken around the Pacific Fleet area of operations... 17 different countries visited since taking over in August '94!  And some, like Japan, on multiple occasions.  The naval operations and personal relationships shared with countries ranging from Russia to India form the backdrop for my remarks today.<br>
<br>
I'm here to talk about "Current Operations and Factors Conditioning the Use of Naval Power in the Pacific in the 21st Century"... But first, I want you to know that today your Pacific Fleet is in great shape... and to summarize our current operations.<br>
<br>
We have 194 ships and over 1600 aircraft that are operated, maintained and supported by over 250,000 superb Sailors, Marines and civilians... Located all the way from Oklahoma City to the Arabian Gulf.  While our Fleet is 30% smaller than it was in 1989, we have the best people, training and equipment we've ever had.<br>
<br>
Today we have 120 or 62% of those ships at sea.  We have 2 carriers and an amphibious ready group in the "Rim of the Pacific" exercise in the vicinity of Hawaii.  Additionally, another Pacific Fleet amphibious ready group has just entered the Arabian Gulf, and we have port visits in 6 countries throughout the area of operations.<br>
<br>
During my nearly two years in command, the men and women of your Pacific Fleet have worked hard and have served you exceedingly well.  They have participated in at least eight real-world contingencies...<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... Strengthening our presence in the northwest Pacific when nuclear talks with North Korea reached a critical state.
<li>... Deploying to the Caribbean to augment Atlantic Fleet forces in support of operations in Haiti.
<li>... Conducting an emergent evacuation of besieged American diplomats in Rwanda.
<li>... Surging to the Arabian Gulf... twice... to show force when Saddam Hussein made threatening troop movements.
<li>... Conducting a flawless amphibious withdrawal -- the first since the Korean War -- of U.N. Forces from the devastated nation of Somalia.
<li>... Contributing to the mission in Bosnia, with Pacific Fleet EA-6B's, Seabees and other support personnel.
<li>... And strengthening our presence near China and Taiwan earlier this year to show the United States' commitment to a peaceful resolution of their differences.
</ul>
As USS Independence battle group commander RADM Jim Ellis told a reporter from CNN during the China-Taiwan situation when Indy was redirected to the western Pacific, "Our people don't ask 'Why us?'... They ask 'Who else?'"<br>
<br>
The men and women of the Pacific Fleet have also made 1138 port visits to 24 countries in the Pacific Fleet area of responsibility... and have conducted over 200 mutually beneficial exercises with 19 friends and allies throughout the region... sending a strong message of our continued commitment to the leaders throughout the region who fear the U.S. Is withdrawing.<br>
<br>
But there are some warning signs on the horizon.  Budgets are tight this year, and our people are working hard -- in some cases too hard.  And we often see half of our Fleet at sea.<br>
<br>
When you analyze what that number should be given all the constraints including adequate time at home for our people and required maintenance for our equipment, the number averaged over a full year tops out at 45%... Lower than that and you have increased scheduling flexibility;  higher than that and you soon have to stop meeting selected commitments.<br>
<br>
Since 1989 when we started our downsizing, we have seen a steady rise in the average percentage of our Fleet at sea, from 39% to 44% this year... the inevitable result of a smaller Fleet continuing to be in heavy demand throughout our vast area of operations.<br>
<br>
The question today is:  what factors create that demand for naval operations in the Pacific that will shape our Fleet in the next century.  That sounds straightforward enough.  After all, the dawn of the 21st century is only four years away.<br>
<br>
But is it that easy?  After all, a lot can happen in four years!  Take 1990-1994 as an example.  That four year period saw the crumbling of the Warsaw Pact, the reunification of Germany, the collapse of the Soviet Union, the gulf war and coalition defeat of Iraq and a 30-40% reduction in the size of the Navy and our sister services...the largest reductions since World War II.<br>
<br>
So there's risk in predicting how the world, and our nation, will change over the next four years... and into the 21st century.  In fact, a given in predicting our future is certainty that the prediction will be wrong.  The real question is "how close can we get?"<br>
<br>
This difficulty in predicting the future is especially true in the Pacific, where the rate of change is staggering.  Gross domestic product growth in these nations averages 7.3%... compared to 2.2% and 2.6% for U.S. And European Union, respectively.  In fact, only one nation outside of the Asia-Pacific region -- Turkey -- has a rate higher than 6%!  The World Bank has termed this phenomenon the "Asian economic miracle" because it is unprecedented anywhere in world history.<br>
<br>
Rapid economic growth has brought about rapid growth in population as well.  Already accounting for 2/3 of the world's population, Asia will grow by an additional one billion by the year 2020.<br>
<br>
In my visits to countries throughout the Pacific and Indian Oceans, there are two recurring themes:  the first is an appreciation of the role the U.S. Navy has played over the years in providing the sense of stability so important to economic growth in the region.  And the second is an impending sense or concern as I mentioned earlier of U.S. Navy withdrawal from the region -- fueled by our downsizing and our 1992 departure from Subic Bay in the Philippines.<br>
<br>
As a result, I'm reminded each time I travel of the value placed on our presence by our allies and friends throughout the Pacific Rim and Indian Oceans.  But, of course, that presence is not without cost.  So we have to ask, "What's in it for us?"<br>
<br>
Sometimes it's not as clear back here on the East Coast, but we all must constantly remember that the Asia-Pacific region will be of increasing importance to the United States in the years ahead.<br>
<br>
The region currently accounts for 37% of our nation's two-way foreign trade, more than any other single region in the world.  For comparison, the figure is 22% with Europe.<br>
<br>
3 million American jobs, predicted to rise to 6 million over the next decade, depend directly upon our trade and investments in the region.  Triple that if you want to include the "trickle down" effect.<br>
<br>
Given our stake in Asia and the Pacific, we have every reason to stay engaged in the region... And to be not only interested -- but intrinsically and intimately involved in its future.<br>
<br>
So I would like to look ahead, and consider some of the many uncertainties on the horizon which may generate requirements for U.S. Naval operations.  I believe these uncertainties could easily involve changes as dramatic as the demolition of the Berlin Wall, and as unanticipated as the collapse of the Soviet Union.<br>
<br>
Following an examination of some of the possibilities I'd like to outline for you actions the Pacific Fleet is taking today which will influence how our naval forces operate in this region in the next century.<br>
<br>
First, a major and immediate threat to stability in the Pacific is the outcome of the stalemate on the Korean peninsula.  The U.S. has made real progress on nuclear issues over the last couple years... And the North seems to be cooperating with present inspections.<br>
<br>
But lingering questions remain about the North's leadership, military capabilities, and real intentions.  Of note is the fact that the North continues to spend nearly 25% of its gross national product on its military, despite severe famine and a stalled economy.  More than four decades after the declaration of Korean armistice, the future of the Korean peninsula remains one of the biggest question marks in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
It's quite possible we'll have an outcome within the next few years... for all the indications are that the current situation in the North cannot be sustained.  There are two relevant questions:  One, will the landing be hard or soft?... Or as some are saying, hard or very hard?... And two, what will be the future focus of a united Korean peninsula?<br>
<br>
The very hard landing -- a war on the peninsula -- would certainly be devastating in terms of human suffering and economic impact -- not only in South Korea, but throughout the Pacific because of the interdependent economies.  Even a soft or less hard landing -- collapse of the North and peaceful reunification -- will place a significant drag on the South's economy for a number of years.  As a comparison, just look at what's happening in Germany now.<br>
<br>
A second uncertainty that has become more and more visible in recent months surrounds China's plans and direction.<br>
<br>
The status of Hong Kong under China after reversion just over one year from today is a major part of that uncertainty.  Of specific interest for the Pacific Fleet is the continuance of quality Hong Kong port visits.  Currently 50-60 per year, continuing port visits to Hong Kong will be important for several reasons.<br>
<br>
First, a business-as-usual approach by the U.S. Navy can help provide both a sense of continuity and stability to Hong Kong during this significant change.  Again, to put the United States' stake in this up front, it's worth noting that there are currently more U.S. Businesses and citizens in Hong Kong than British!<br>
<br>
Second, strong Navy-to-Navy relationships are important to be able to transcend political ups-and-downs often experienced in other areas of interest.  Currently we have only 1 to 3 Navy visits to the People's Republic per year.  50-60 visits to a Chinese Hong Kong could facilitate a sense of familiarity and confidence building.<br>
<br>
And finally, Hong Kong has always been a great place for our crews to rest and relax after months of arduous sea duty -- and we'd sure like to see it stay that way.<br>
<br>
Additional large question marks concerning China include:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... Their relations with their neighbors such as Vietnam, India, and Russia;
<li>... The long term effect of their internal transition of power;
<li>... The ability to raise the standard of living of a huge population;
<li>... And the effect of competition for raw resources in the region as their economy continues to expand rapidly.
</ul>
I believe the Pacific Fleet is well-placed to have a large positive impact as we proceed ahead carefully in this critical bilateral relationship.<br>
<br>
Turning to other issues with uncertain outcomes, we need to examine the possibilities for the Spratly Island chain.  If and when these resources are discovered, we might anticipate increased tension between the six nations with competing claims on the Spratly's.<br>
<br>
Another big question is the political stability, economic recovery and the future direction of Russia -- as a formidable Pacific naval power.  Our very successful visits to Vladivostok over the past three years have revealed an interesting contrast.  On the one hand we see a severely underfunded navy struggling to retain its core competencies, and on the other hand an upbeat spirit in the Russian Far East that ultimately may allow them to share increasingly in the prosperity of the region.<br>
<br>
One area in which the Russian Navy has sustained a commitment, despite its severe financial difficulties, is its submarine force.  While there has been a significant downsizing, the remaining force is at the state of the art and would represent a formidable challenge should we ever confront each other again.  Our Navy-to-Navy relationship is solid -- a relationship we hope will aid in preserving our two nations' goodwill... and Russia's progress as a democratic nation.<br>
<br>
And there are more uncertainties: the ultimate resolution of the long-standing India-Pakistan dispute; the impact or likelihood of the introduction of ballistic missiles and weapons of mass destruction as regional military forces modernize; the question of continued U.S. access to overseas basing and ports; and the potential transmigration of religious fundamentalism into the large moderate Muslim populations in southeast Asia.<br>
<br>
In summary, there are many uncertainties that will affect the future of the Asia-Pacific region.  And any one of them could profoundly impact future requirements for naval forces and Pacific Fleet operations... because of our nation's inextricable economic, political and emotional ties to the Pacific Rim.<br>
<br>
However, as we chart our course through these various uncertainties, there are fortunately a number of enduring realities in the Asia-Pacific region that will help us with our navigation.<br>
<br>
The first certainty is that geography won't change, nor will the physics of time and distance.  The Pacific region will always be immense in size, with over 50% of the earth's surface.<br>
<br>
Major sea lines of communication and strategic straits -- choke points if you will -- will always exist throughout the region:  Malacca, Tsushima and Lomboc, to name but a few.<br>
<br>
The vast majority of commerce in material resources and products will continue to move by sea.  Presently over 95% of U.S. imports and exports travel by ship.  Keeping these vital trade routes open will remain a priority for the U.S. Navy.<br>
<br>
Reliance on our naval forces has been unchanging in our nation's 220 years of independence.  I would contend that naval forces will continue to be in demand and will be uniquely suited to protect American interests and peace throughout the Asia-Pacific region, well into the twenty-first century and beyond.<br>
<br>
That brings me to a second certainty:  the world's economy will remain global, and will be increasingly interdependent.  Accordingly, events and actions in one part of the world almost invariably have global impact...recent examples are legion. Derivatives trading in Singapore brought down Bearing's Bank -- one of Britain's oldest and most respected financial institutions. Flooding along the Yangtze in China last year caused an increase in world food prices, in particular prices for U.S. grain. Increases in the relative value of the Japanese yen has led to a resurgence in automobile manufacturing in Detroit.<br>
<br>
Global interdependency means that instability in one part of the world can do damage elsewhere. When Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990, the price of oil tripled for four months.  It cost the U.S. $200 billion in GNP and more than $1 trillion in GNP worldwide, leading to recessions in industrial nations around the globe. Tensions in the Taiwan strait earlier this year caused a near panic of a potential silicon crisis throughout the world -- particularly in California's silicon valley -- among companies that rely on Taiwan for manufacturing silicon semiconductors and feared production could be impeded.<br>
<br>
In short, global interdependence is a reality and in the 21st century, prosperity in America will continue to be inextricably linked to events overseas.<br>
<br>
A third certainty is the continuing expansion of American interests in Asia.  Economic, political, cultural and security issues in the region will impact our daily lives.  In fact, while your heart may be in the region of your heritage -- whether that be Europe, Asia, Africa or Latin America -- your wallet will increasingly be in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
First and foremost among our interests then is our economic stake in Asia.  3 million jobs (as I said before) are dependent upon this region which consumes a third of our exports... and will consume half of our exports by the year 2020.<br>
<br>
Politically, nations throughout the region are taking on greater positions of world leadership.  China is a permanent member of U.N. Security Council... and there is much discussion about Japan also taking a seat.  ASEAN countries are gaining clout throughout the world on a level akin to European Union and OPEC.  Indonesia, for example, with the worlds 4th largest population and the largest moderate Islamic population -- while increasingly friendly to the U.S. -- continues to be a leader of the non-aligned countries.<br>
<br>
Our interests are economic, political... And cultural.  With over 9 million Americans of Asian ancestry, the hearts of more and more Americans are in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
So with strong economic, political, cultural and even emotional ties to the Pacific, it follows that we have robust and continuing security interests there as well.<br>
<br>
A fourth certainty is that there will continue in the twenty-first century to be different -- and in some cases divergent -- cultural and social values among nations in the region.<br>
<br>
In some countries, for example, there are differing priorities placed on group values versus individual desires, which leads to differing interpretations over some basic issues like human rights, freedom of speech and religion, and intellectual property rights... to name a few of current interest.<br>
<br>
While the U.S. will continue to emphasize the values in which we so strongly believe, we need to recognize Asian perceptions and the potential for reduced U.S. influence caused by them.  Military-to-military contact in general -- and Navy contact in particular -- pays triple dividends in that respect. Positive professional and personal contact builds confidence and can reverse many negative images. Solid military contacts, delinked from political and economic issues, can provide an anchor during otherwise stormy seas in our bilateral relations. And finally, the vision of tremendously professional men and women equipped with formidable weapons systems can indelibly impact those who might think about becoming adversaries.<br>
<br>
With the reversion of Hong Kong in '97 and Macao in '99, the end of over two centuries of Western settlement in Asia is at hand.  While the resulting emergent sense of independence from Western influence can present challenges for economic and military presence, the United States and particularly U.S. naval forces are viewed as honest brokers... and our presence is viewed as a stabilizing influence.<br>
<br>
Our role as honest broker is enhanced by the U.S. Pacific Command's policy of "places, not bases", meaning that we would like to have continuing access to nations throughout the region for visits and mutually beneficial exercises... but we don't intend to establish new bases of the magnitude of a Subic Bay, for example.<br>
<br>
A fifth reality for naval forces as we enter the next decade is that there will be an increasing and necessary interest worldwide in the protection of our environment, both ashore and throughout our vast oceans.<br>
<br>
The U.S. Navy and the Pacific Fleet have taken a lead in this area... And some of our many environmental programs have become the model for others.  At the same time, we've got to balance our operational requirements and freedom of the seas with our environmental responsibilities.<br>
<br>
For example, low frequency analysis, which uses a very high energy sonar pulse to detect underwater objects, promises significant advances in our ability to find diesel submarines in the littorals.  However its impact on marine mammals is not fully understood... so we have worked closely with civilian researchers to ensure there is no harm.<br>
<br>
As a positive by-product these researchers have had access to sophisticated equipment and advanced data unaffordable and unobtainable by them in the past.<br>
<br>
A related concern among some nations in our region is the impact of the presence of nuclear powered warships.  Fortunately, the U.S. Navy's nuclear power safety record is such that, even with the establishment of various "nuclear free zones", our legal access to the high seas -- as well as our right of innocent passage through territorial waters -- has not been challenged.<br>
<br>
A sixth factor that will influence our operations in the Asia-Pacific region for years to come is the desire for most Asian nations to engage in bilateral vice multilateral military-to-military exercises and operations.<br>
<br>
There is no overarching security umbrella in the region similar to NATO, and for numerous social and economic reasons it appears unlikely that we will see movement toward such an organization in the future.<br>
<br>
We have encouraged more multilateral interaction at a pace acceptable to each nation, and have had some success with very carefully crafted multilateral exercises.  One of our more visible successes is a large maritime exercise now ongoing called the "Rim of the Pacific" or "RIMPAC", which has brought together the navies of six nations, along with observers from four others, in Hawaiian waters for about a month.<br>
<br>
But even in this exercise some navies cannot or will not operate with one another and the scenario has to be scripted accordingly.  In short, the progress toward multilateral contact -- and the operational efficiencies that accrue from multilateral contact --  remains slow.<br>
<br>
Our long-term goal is -- through even-handed honest brokering -- to build mutual confidence throughout the region, which brings me to a final factor in the Asia-Pacific Rim that is of great concern to us...<br>
<br>
And that is, that Asia has become the most well-armed corner of the globe, and the pace continues unabated.  The region already accounts for 7 of the 8 largest, militaries in the world, the world's two largest standing armies and 7 of 10 largest submarine forces in the world.<br>
<br>
And it continues to grow... the London Financial Times reported recently that:<br>
<br><em> "In marked contrast to declines elsewhere in the world, defense spending in Pacific Rim countries is rising rapidly."</em><br>
<br>
While U.S. And other nations have decreased military spending, military spending since 1992 has increased in real terms by 9% in East Asia, and 6% in South Asia.  Many smaller nations are increasing their drive for newer and more advanced weaponry... while arms sales is a huge and rapidly expanding market.<br>
<br>
China, with nearly 3 million men in its military, is spending twice the percentage of its GNP on defense as we... and is driving towards a blue-water Navy.  Even nations that don't increase military spending as a percentage of GNP will continue to have rapidly growing military power simply because their GNP itself is growing so rapidly.<br>
<br>
We must keep this in mind lest we become complacent.  Although U.S. is the uncontested strongest naval power in the region and in the world today, we are likely to be challenged by the latest smart weaponry, including sea-skimming missiles and information warfare against our information systems -- as well as cheaper but deadly conventional weapons like mines -- in the hands of more and more countries.<br>
<br>
It's important to bear these certainties and trends in mind as we approach the 21st century, where defense in the Pacific will become increasingly complicated.  Defense Secretary William Perry in his recent speech at Harvard's John Kennedy School outlined a policy of "Preventive Defense", saying:<br>
<br><em> "The United States has a unique historical opportunity, the opportunity to prevent the conditions for conflict and to help create the conditions for peace."</em><br>
<br>
This new strategy makes "Preventive Defense" our first line of defense... deterrence the second line of defense... and military conflict the third and last resort.  What makes Preventive Defense work is American leadership, and our ability to have a global presence.<br>
<br>
We execute Preventive Defense and the Pacific Command's strategy of Cooperative Engagement by conducting over 125 exercises annually... 800 port visits... numerous Navy staff talks... and community relations projects.  These actions foster goodwill, increase transparency, and reduce the chances of miscalculation that could result in conflict.<br>
<br>
In the Pacific, we are taking several actions to keep the U.S. Pacific Fleet in its position of continued leadership and forward presence in this vibrant region well into the 21st century.<br>
<br>
Your Pacific Fleet is staying engaged in maritime issues... As countries seek to gain more control of their surrounding waterways by seeking legal means to increase their territorial sea claims, and control of archipelagic waterways.  We are influencing decisions wherever possible, and maintaining a robust freedom of navigation operations program to challenge unreasonable and legally insupportable territorial assertions that might constrain our unfettered access to critical sea lanes.<br>
<br>
Your Pacific Fleet is fully utilizing Fleet resources to make the most of the smaller overall size of the Fleet.  Reserve forces in particular are playing a major role in that, through "contributory support" by reserve personnel, and by deploying naval reserve force ships.<br>
<br>
In fact, even as we speak two reserve frigates, USS George Philip and USS Mahlon S. Tisdale, are conducting a bilateral exercise series in Southeast Asia, freeing up active force ships for other contingency commitments.<br>
<br>
Your Pacific Fleet is refocusing on "places not bases", the Pacific Command strategy I mentioned earlier for limited logistical support from nations throughout the region.  Singapore, home of COMLOGWESTPAC and a small Fleet support contingent is a good example of this theme.<br>
<br>
And your Pacific Fleet is doing things smarter in a variety of ways... from reorganizing and streamlining chains of command... to outsourcing and civilianizing.  And we continue to draw upon the intellect and innovation of our own men and women in the Navy.<br>
<br>
Our challenge is to combine these approaches and known quantities with the range of potential possibilities -- the uncertainties -- in a meaningful way... not to predict the future, but to gain good insight into it.<br>
<br>
Our goal is to leverage the right kind of available technology so that we can keep the Pacific Fleet affordable, modern, flexible... and most importantly relevant, by being there to continue to influence events positively throughout Asia and the Pacific Rim.<br>
<br>
Thank you and God bless you all.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
