<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>COMNAVSURFPAC<br>Change of Command</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>On Board USS ESSEX, San Diego, Calif. (Friday, April 19, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Vice Admiral Robinson, Vice Admiral Krekich, crewmembers of USS Essex... Surface Warriors of SURFPAC... Family and friends.  The weather is better than the last change of command speech I gave in San Diego.  That's good news and bad news.  The bad news is I'll talk longer!<br>
<br>
I am delighted to join you today to participate in this important change of command ceremony... and to help pipe an officer, a shipmate and respected friend over the side after 33 years of dedicated service to our nation.<br>
<br>
Change of command ceremonies always stir a mix of emotions... but they especially do so when the outgoing commander is transitioning to civilian life.  Each of us shares the pride Dave and Gene and their family feel as they prepare to weigh anchor and steam smartly over the horizon to take on new challenges and enjoy continuing successes in the civilian world.  We also feel sadness as one of our Navy families leaves... and we know we will miss them.  Ceremonies such as this remind us all, people are indeed the single greatest attribute, and the absolute measure of strength in any organization.  People can be relieved, but they can never be replaced.<br>
<br>
Dave Robinson took his commission 33 years ago in 1963 from the U.S. Naval Academy.  As I was thinking about saying farewell to Dave, I was reflecting on how much the Navy... and the world... has changed since then.<br>
<br>
As an example, did you know that in 1963 the pay for a newly commissioned Ensign was $314 per month.  Today, with housing allowances, a newly commissioned Ensign stationed here in San Diego makes nearly $2400 a month.  We have made some improvements!  And all these years there is a heavy rumor that Gene has kept Dave on the same allowance as he made as an Ensign in 1963!<br>
<br>
Also, did you know that 33 years ago, there was no SURFPAC... Our surface force was broken into three separate force entities: amphibious (PHIBPAC), cruiser-destroyer (CRUDESPAC) and service (SERVPAC).  Today, there is one unifying force who oversees all of that and more... And he does a great job of it!<br>
<br>
Did you know that in 1963, Betty Friedan's famous book Feminine Mystique was published... launching the feminist movement for the rest of America.  And at that time we already had nearly 13,000 women serving for the same wages as their male counterparts.  Today, we have women aboard every class of surface ship in our Fleet, and flying fighter aircraft off the decks of carriers... like the USS Nimitz that arrived on scene for the China/Taiwan confrontation last month.<br>
<br>
And did you recall that in 1963, Martin Luther King stood on the Mall in Washington D.C. and gave his "I have a dream" speech... when a man by the name of Colin Powell was serving as a young Army Captain.  Thirty years later our military's highest ranking officer was a black man... who today is mentioned prominently as a candidate for national office.<br>
<br>
And you recall that 33 years ago, a Belknap class cruiser cost about $130 million to build? Today, an Aegis cruiser costs over one billion dollars.<br>
<br>
And 33 years ago, Japan's annual exports totaled just over $10 billion.  Today, Japan exports over $400 billion of goods each year... a 4000% increase.<br>
<br>
33 years ago, our space program was trying to play catch up with the Soviet Union... and hoping to reach the moon.  Today, our astronauts are in space together with their Russian counterparts... and we're reaching towards Mars.<br>
<br>
33 years ago as a newly commissioned Ensign, Dave Robinson was at destroyer school, learning how to fight a potential war with the Soviets.  Today, SURFPAC ships participate in bilateral exercises and goodwill port visits with Russian ships on a regular basis.<br>
<br>
While much has indeed changed over the years, much remains the same.  Take for example the following quote:<em> "Americans must look outward.  Sea commerce has a profound influence upon the wealth and strength of countries... and governs its growth and prosperity."</em><br>
<br>
Those words weren't spoken last week by someone like John Naisbitt, Alan Greenspan or Mickey Kantor... but over 100 years ago by Alfred Thayer Mahan, another Surface Warrior of some renown.  100 years later, America still depends on the sea in both peace and war.<br>
<br>
In peace we depend on it being free and open to all to sustain our standard of living... with over 95% of U.S. import and export trade being transported by the sea.  This is specially true in the Pacific and Asia, a vibrant region where trade and investments directly support over 3 million American jobs.<br>
<br>
In war, our success depends on our often demonstrated ability to control the seas at will.  These two requirements haven't changed one bit in 220 years of independence.<br>
<br>
But yes, much has changed in Dave Robinson's Navy over the past 33 years.  Much has also changed in the world at large.  In fact, much of the positive change which has occurred in our world and in our Navy over the last three decades is the direct result of the efforts of leaders like Dave.  They have made important contributions in the defense of their nation and of freedom loving peoples around the world.<br>
<br>
Engraved deep in stone over our National Archives, the building in Washington which houses our most precious documents, like the Declaration of Independence, is an admonition which every American should know by heart. It reads:<em> "Eternal vigilance is the price of liberty."</em>
<br>
Dave has been vigilant, ever on guard.  He and the many like him won the Cold War, held tyranny in check in Vietnam and then in Desert Storm, and set the stage for a more promising tomorrow.<br>
<br>
When we look at a man or woman who has spent their adult lives in the Navy, some might ask "why?".  What is it which makes a person do this for a living?  In answering these questions, there are some notions which cannot be immediately dismissed.<br>
<br>
First, people don't serve in the armed services for the money.  (though, granted, Dave does make a little more now than the $314 a month he earned in 1963!).  But good people, who are willing to work hard, who have ambition, can generally earn a good deal more on the outside.  And although military pay has become quite competitive with the civilian sector, that's still not why people do it.<br>
<br>
Second, people don't spend their lives in the Navy because it's an easy, accommodating lifestyle.  The Dave Robinson's of the Navy can expect to spend well over half their careers assigned to ships, deploying with squadrons or staffs, or in arduous overseas assignments.  This means spending a lot of time away from home, away from families and loved ones.  No, people don't serve because it's an easy life.<br>
<br>
And third, people don't spend a career in the Navy because it's risk free.  Operating ships, submarines and aircraft... and working on flight decks just like this one, where blades are spinning and the ship is pitching and rolling... can be dangerous.  Furthermore, sometimes we are called on to sail into harms way to protect our nation's freedom and the rights of our friends and allies.  The Purple Heart you see on Dave's chest is testimony to the fact that the Navy has its risks... and is not a life for the weak at heart.<br>
<br>
So why do they serve?  They serve because they have a clear sense of purpose in what they are doing... And they know they are making a difference.   Just think of some of the important things SURFPAC units have done over the last three years:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... They responded to the China-Taiwan crisis last month.
<li>... They completed the successful withdrawal of U.N. personnel from the devastated nation of Somalia (in which USS Essex participated).
<li>... They conducted an evacuation of besieged American embassy personnel in Rwanda...
<li>... They surged forces to the Arabian gulf twice when Saddam Hussein made threatening troop movements.
<li>... They showed force off of North Korea to show our nation's resolve during nuclear talks.
<li>... They conducted counter-drug operations in the Eastern Pacific and Caribbean.
</ul>
These actions... and the day to day presence of our Sailors and Marines throughout the Pacific... have contributed to peace and a brighter future.  And that's why our people choose to serve: because it is exciting and personally rewarding beyond compare when you are out there making a difference.<br>
<br>
When measured against their civilian peers, our people achieve levels of extraordinary responsibility at a very young age.  We have young Sailors who you wouldn't have trusted with your car keys a couple years ago, who today stand at the helm of this 40,000 ton ship!<br>
<br>
However, more impressively, our men and women in uniform stand apart because they are selfless patriots.  They have larger interests of the nation in their sights and their hearts.  They work tirelessly not because they have to, but because they want to.  They work until the work is done, without any overtime wages.<br>
<br>
Vice Admiral Dave Robinson is certainly such a person.  He has spent much of his life at sea... Aboard everything from small patrol boats in Vietnam...  to the aircraft carrier Teddy Roosevelt in the Mediterranean, where he served as battle group commander.  He has mastered very difficult jobs, time after time, from Main Propulsion Assistant aboard the destroyer USS Stormes... To major flag billets in Washington D.C.<br>
<br>
I can personally attest to his ability to master difficult challenges... because his job here as Commander of the Pacific Fleet's Surface Forces hasn't been easy.  Dave has led a force of nearly 100 ships, nine shore stations, more than 45,000 military and civilian personnel, and a budget of nearly 2 billion dollars.  He masterfully oversaw his force as it downsized... maintaining readiness and personnel quality of life at high levels.<br>
<br>
His accolades are too numerous to list, but I'll mention just a few:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>... He oversaw a complete force reorganization to maintain continuity of training, readiness and operations throughout his ship's deployments.
<li>... He instituted a visionary program of energy conservation which rewards ships with OPTAR funds for saving fuel.
<li>... He increased utilization of reserve assets, including integrating NRF ships into the Tactical Training Strategy and deploying NRF ships.
<li>... He oversaw the transition to regionalized maintenance, helping us consolidate surface and submarine maintenance where it makes sense to save money.
</ul>
In a wide range of programs he founded the decommissioning ship reuse pool, the oil recovery and reuse program, the hazardous material reuse and redistribution program as well as force-wide recycling.  He was always a wise steward of the taxpayers dollars.<br>
<br>
And he achieved this in sensible ways -- without fanfare, but with great regard for the force's readiness and people... people... yes, most importantly, he sought out ways to help his people.  He eliminated rules and requirements that made no sense.  He allowed many ships to move from 3 and 4 sections of duty into 5 or even 6 sections... giving his Sailors more time at home with their families when in port.  He also rebuilt the Operational Propulsion Plant Examination (OPPE) from a dreaded and demoralizing inspection into a valuable and positive training experience.  He truly loves his people... and I can tell you he has been their advocate in each and every action he has undertaken.<br>
<br>
Dave Robinson is a naval officer of unquestionable skill, character, strength, leadership and passion for this force... a force he has served well and faithfully.  Dave, I know you would be the first to give credit to the Sailors of SURFPAC who made it all happen.  But I also know that, from Bremerton to Pearl Harbor, from San Diego to the Arabian gulf, your people give you credit... and they join me in thanking you for your inspirational leadership.  You have been good for our surface force, and this old aviator has heard that every time he stepped aboard a frigate, destroyer, cruiser, amphib or CLF ship.<br>
<br>
Gene, I would be remiss if I didn't say a few words about your vital role in Dave's service to our nation and our Navy.  Every Sailor needs someone to help them navigate through the difficult shoal waters of Navy life.  You have been that navigator, friend, soulmate and more.  33 years ago, it used to be common practice to mention a spouse in a fitness report.  We can't do that anymore, but if I could you'd get perfect marks.<br>
<br>
One of our nation's great Surface Warriors, Admiral Arleigh Burke, once said:<br>
<br>
<em> "The days of our lives pass all too quickly, but when we are busy and happy, as I have been during my years in the Navy, our days leave a great store of wonderful memories."</em><br>
<br>
Dave and Gene, you will no doubt have many wonderful memories as you embark on this next chapter in your life together.  I just hope we stay in touch so I'll know where to come so I can continue to solicit your advice.  I wish you both fair winds and following seas.  God bless and keep you both.  We'll miss you.<br>
<br>
Although we're sad to see Dave go, we're pleased to have the top draft pick to replace him:  Vice Admiral Al Krekich, an experienced naval officer and Surface Warrior with 32 years experience, coming to us from the Pentagon where he was Director of Surface Warfare on the CNO's staff.<br>
<br>
Al and Bobbi, congratulations and welcome to you.  You're joining a first-rate team at SURFPAC... assuming command of an outstanding Surface Force with great people and a vitally important mission.  You bring impeccable credentials of past successes... And I know you are fully up to each and every challenge ahead.<br>
<br>
Let me close by congratulating all the men, women and families of SURFPAC for many accomplishments over the past three years.  I'd also like to thank our friends and supporters from the community who have joined us here for this special occasion.<br>
<br>
In a country that often finds itself searching for good news in the midst of concerns, you are all part of the page one headlines about the Pacific Fleet success story.<br>
<br>
Thank you all, and god bless.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
