<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>San Diego<br>World Affairs Council</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>San Diego, Calif. (Friday, April 19, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Thank you and good morning, or Aloha ... as we say back at headquarters.  As nice as Hawaii is, it's great to be in an even bigger Navy town than Pearl Harbor... and to talk to the San Diego World Affairs Council for the first time.  I appreciate the important function which World Affairs Councils serve in our communities... increasing public awareness of issues of international concern. <br>
<br>
I have to tell you, you'd be surprised at the amount of international awareness there is among our men and women in uniform...  I just came from across the bay where I was speaking at the change of command ceremony for the Commander of the Pacific Fleet Surface Force.  I talked directly to the many Sailors standing in ranks... who are on the front lines of our nation's defense... and spoke of the importance of their mission in the U.S. Navy. <br>
<br>
Afterwards, several came up to ask me questions... Not about the drinking age on our bases, or food on the messdecks... But about geopolitics and security concerns. <br>
<br>
As proud as I was in Charlottesville then, I'm even prouder to be in San Diego with you today... in a true Navy town.  Many people don't realize San Diego is the second largest naval installation in the world. <br>
<br>
There's a great partnership here between the military and civilian communities... A partnership because it has immense benefits for both parties involved.  San Diego reaps the economic benefits of having a large military presence... With $13.5 billion annually pumped into the local economy.  In fact, even after downsizing, San Diego is one of the few places whose relative piece of the shrinking defense pie has actually increased. <br>
<br>
But economics are only part of the benefit... because our people make positive community contributions as well:  from Cub Scout leaders to little league coaches and Sunday school teachers, our people contribute substantively and are an integral part of the social fabric of the communities in which we live.  Navy families consider San Diego a great place to live, and want to contribute positively. <br>
<br>
And just as our partnership provides benefit to the city of San Diego, it also provides benefit to the Navy.  We get a strategic position on our nation's Pacific coast... with a deep water port, a supportive civilian community, and great quality of life for our people. <br>
<br>
As I talk to you today, think you will see why places like San Diego, Puget Sound and Pearl Harbor will be increasingly important to our nation's defense in the next century... the Century of the Pacific. <br>
<br>
With a name like "Zlatoper", you might think I was here to talk about the situation in the Balkans.  Even for those of us with ethnic backgrounds of European, African or Hispanic roots... and therefore who have their hearts to the east or south, our wallets are in the Pacific. <br>
<br>
I've become known in Navy circles as the preacher from the west ... a missionary with a message about the growing importance of the Pacific for all Americans.  That's not a complete surprise to a group of well-informed business and community leaders like yourselves on the west coast... But I hope to add to your base of knowledge, and lay the foundation for discussion after my remarks. <br>
<br>
I'd like to share three points with you today:  why Americans should care about the Pacific;  what our concerns are in the Pacific;  and how the U.S. Pacific Fleet is addressing those concerns, even after a significant reduction in the size of the Fleet. <br>
<br>
First, why should we care about the Pacific?  There are economic, political, and military reasons why the Pacific is becoming the most important region of the world for Americans. <br>
<br>
First, the economic perspective:  we have witnessed an astounding, unprecedented growth of Asian economies.  The growth rate of developing Asian nations averaged 7.3% from 1985 to 1995 (compared to 3.4% for Japan, 2.6% for U.S. And 2.2% for Europe).  Asian gross national product now is more than 30% of the world's total ... Having surpassed the total for Europe in 1991-92 (22%).  And the Asian share of world GNP is expected to climb to 50% by the middle of the next century. <br>
<br>
The world's economic and industrial center of gravity is shifting to the Pacific.  Trends in U.S. Trade have followed this pattern:  aggregate trade with Asian nations represents 37% of total U.S. Trade... more than that of the European Union and Latin America combined.  3 million American jobs are directly related to exports and investments in Asia.  And that is expected to climb to 6 million over the next decade.  These aren't low paying "Mcjobs" of the service industry, but rather jobs which pay an average of 14% above non-export related jobs. <br>
<br>
With 3.5 billion potential customers, our ability to engage in trade and commerce with these nations is vital to our domestic economy. <br>
<br>
The region is important to the United States politically, as well.  It is a vast and diverse region (as I well know ... keeping up with developments throughout 16 time zones).  It accounts for more than half of the earth's surface and two-thirds of the world's population.  Asia includes the world's largest democracy (India), the world's two largest Islamic populations (Indonesia and India), the largest remaining communist nations (China and North Korea), and dozens of nations whose futures hang in the balance today, politically and economically. <br>
<br>
Nine million Americans of Asian or Pacific ancestry give us yet another reason to care about the region.  That means that the hearts of more and more Americans are in Asia. <br>
<br>
With these economic and political interests in the Asia-Pacific, it's no surprise why we have such strong security interests.  Asia has no over-arching security umbrella like NATO.  U.S. military presence is the one constant... providing the equilibrium for peace and security. <br>
<br>
Former Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs Joseph Nye (now Dean of the JFK School of Government), expressed it another way:<br>
<br><em> "Security is like oxygen:  you do not tend to notice it until you begin to lose it. The American security presence has helped provide this 'oxygen' for East Asian development."</em><br>
<br>
With all of these reasons to care about the Pacific, what should be our concerns?  We just saw one vivid example last month:  when differences between China and Taiwan heated up.  Such a crisis could have disrupted peace, trade, the entire region's economic growth... and our own well being.  Even though not a single shot was fired:<br>
<ul>
<li>Stock markets in the region plunged, 
<li>Investors scrambled to convert currencies to dollars and gold, 
<li>High-tech companies south of San Francisco talked of a potential silicon crisis -- akin to oil crises caused by past conflicts in the Arabian Gulf,
<li>And newspaper headlines warned ominously of closed sea lanes, rice hoarding, and instability in a region built on open trade routes and political calm.</ul>
Much is at stake in our country ... when you pause to consider that China and Taiwan are the 2nd and 4th largest overseas trading partners of the U.S. <br>
<br>
The tension between China and Taiwan is only one of several long-standing animosities in the region.  Other trouble spots include India and Pakistan, China and India, Russia and Japan, Iran and Iraq (in southwest Asia) and the Korean Peninsula, another festering issue that has been capturing headlines in the past few days.  It is particularly concerning because the North spends 25% of its GNP on defense despite a stalled economy and famine. <br>
<br>
There also is civil strife or insurgencies in more than a dozen countries, from the Philippines and Sri Lanka to Somalia and Rwanda. <br>
<br>
Many Asian nations harbor concerns about the long-term ambitions of regional powers like China and Japan. <br>
<br>
Then there is the alarming militarization of Iran, and continued threats from Iraq...all in a region that supplies oil for most of the world. <br>
<br>
As populations grow and demand for natural resources increases, we expect to see greater potential for conflict over resources.  Competing claims over the Spratly Islands has this potential... China, Taiwan, Philippines, Malaysia, Vietnam and Brunei all claim at least a portion of this area ... potentially rich in oil and other resources. <br>
<br>
And then there's Russia:  We all hope for positive development, politically and economically, in the former Soviet republics.  We conducted bilateral exercises in Hawaii with Russian Navy last year, and it was a very positive experience. <br>
<br>
But Russia still retains significant military capabilities which must be watched... particularly their submarine program, which is still alive and well. <br>
<br>
In summary, there are plenty of reasons to be concerned about our interests and prospects for peace.  And there's no shortage of military potential when you consider Asia is home to 7 of the 9 largest militaries in the world, the world's 2 largest standing armies and 7 of the 10 most numerous submarine forces. <br>
<br>
Given our growing stake in Asia, and potential threats to our interests and peace, what is the Pacific Fleet doing to protect American interests and promote peace in the Asia-Pacific region?  Our guiding strategy is called "Cooperative Engagement"... using our strong presence in the region to engage Asian nations to promote peace and stability. <br>
<br>
In 1995, the Pacific Fleet contributed to this strategy through 125 exercises with 25 nations, Navy-to-Navy talks, personnel exchanges, 800 port visits to 40 nations and hundreds of community relations projects. <br>
<br>
These activities show our goodwill, build partnerships, and reduce the chances of miscalculation that could result in military confrontation.  Countries who may not trust their neighbors see the U.S. as an "honest broker"... with no territorial claims or ambitions in the region. <br>
<br>
I have traveled to many of these countries and met with leaders... and am consistently amazed at the overwhelming consensus on this issue... They want the U.S. To keep its forward presence in the Pacific. <br>
<br>
Two month's ago in Singapore, I heard Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defense, Dr. Tan Ke Yam, declare to a room full of delegates from other Asian nations:<br>
<br><em> "For many years now, the military presence of the U.S. has been and continues to be a factor for stability in the region."</em><br>
<br>
Recent tension between China and Taiwan clearly illustrates the value of our being there in Asian waters, with capable and ready naval forces.  When needed, ships of USS Independence battle group were only a couple of days away from Taiwan area.  Their readiness became an unmistakable expression of American commitment, communicated world-wide on CNN and other media. <br>
<br>
As a precaution, the President underlined our resolve a few days later by ordering a 2nd battle group to the western Pacific, led by the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz.  These actions sent a powerful signal of U.S. interest in a peaceful resolution of the Taiwan issue, reducing the chance of either side making a miscalculation or taking unwise action. <br>
<br>
This was at least the 8th time since I became CINCPACFLT 20 months ago that Pacific Fleet forces have been called upon for real-world operational contingencies.  There was also:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>Haiti (where we loaned ships to the Atlantic Fleet)
<li>Iraq twice ... in the falls of '94 and '95.  
<li>Rwanda... where Pacific Fleet units conducted an evacuation of U.S. Embassy personnel
<li>Somalia... Covering the withdrawal of UN forces.
<li>The Korean peninsula ... where naval presence helped deter aggression while tough negotiations concluded a framework to address the North's nuclear program.
<li>and Bosnia ... Where PACFLT contributed EA-6B electronic countermeasures aircraft, and Seabees to build bridges, base camps, command posts and other facilities for U.S. troops.</ul>
The fact is, Fleet operating tempo is as high now as in any period of the Cold War, but we're doing so with much smaller force.  5 years ago my predecessor had 250 ships and 280,000 Sailors and Marines.  Today, I have 196 ships and 215,000 Sailors and Marines. <br>
<br>
Given the smaller size of the Fleet, we are stretching our resources and changing the way we do business in many respects.     I'll give you seven quick examples... and would be happy to go into detail if you have questions.  In fact, I'd be interested in hearing comparisons to how your businesses are making such changes. <br>
<br>
First -- we are eliminating rules and requirements that make no sense... What a concept for the military! <br>
<br>
Second -- we are placing increased reliance on our Forward Deployed Naval Forces.  The USS Independence carrier battle group and USS Belleau Wood amphibious ready group operate from Japan.  These forces have not been affected by overall down-sizing.  It would take 4-5 times the number of ships homeported in continental U.S. to equal their presence... and Japan pays 70% of the cost! <br>
<br>
Third -- modernization throughout the Fleet permits us to make our battle groups and amphibious groups smaller, without sacrificing most capabilities. <br>
<br>
Fourth -- we are training smarter with state of the art training facilities, electronic links to simulate forces and scenarios,   ...and a more tailored approach to training requirements. <br>
<br>
Fifth -- restructuring and re-engineering where we can achieve efficiencies, including:  smaller and more streamlined shore infrastructure; regionalized maintenance support; even reorganized battle groups. <br>
<br>
Sixth -- increased cooperation between Fleets, U.S. services, and international partners.  We have come a long way since the days when we couldn't operate effectively, or sometimes even communicate with our allies, the U.S. Army and Air Force, or between the Atlantic and Pacific Fleets! <br>
<br>
And seventh, we're utilizing our reserve forces more than ever before.  Nearly 700 units with 30,000 selected reserves... adds 22% more forces if mobilized in crisis or conflict.  In peacetime, adds dedicated and expert people and additional ships and airplanes to help me meet commitments with a much smaller active-duty force. <br>
<br>
Perhaps most important in our efforts to cover requirements with a smaller Fleet:  we are protecting our most important resource -- Navy people.  Manpower reductions have been accomplished in such a way as to retain the faith of Navy men and women.  Today, we are strongly committed to controlling deployment lengths and personnel tempo... keeping Sailors at home with their families as much as we can. <br>
<br>
I know that even the best ships and aircraft would be useless without Sailors to operate and maintain them... and supportive families backing them up.  That's why we're actually increasing the amount of money we spend on quality of life projects like housing, fitness centers and military commissaries. <br>
<br>
Navy men and women are paying us back with their loyalty, motivation and tremendous skills.  It's absolutely awe-inspiring to see the flight deck of a carrier in operation around the clock... with the same young kids that you would not have trusted with your car keys a couple of years ago! <br>
<br>
By the way, we still need about 55,000 of these sharp young people a year... to keep our Navy young and upwardly mobile.  What better recruiter could there be than a responsible and internationally-aware member of the community?   Please help pass the word:  we still are hiring! <br>
<br>
With the great men and women of the Navy today, advanced ships and aircraft, and better ways of doing business ... I am very optimistic about your Navy and the Pacific Fleet's ability to continue supporting American interests in the Asia-Pacific region. <br>
<br>
We need to be vigilant to avoid a backslide on readiness ... as we try to balance operating costs, modernization and investments for weapons systems for the future. <br>
<br>
One of my predecessors said it in these words:<br>
<br><em> "We must make certain now, and for the future, that the peace is secure.  We must remain strong.  Never again should we risk the threat which weakness invites."</em><br>
<br>
That was Fleet Admiral Chester Nimitz, 51 years ago -- a month after the end of World War Two. <br>
<br>
Today we are strong, and we are ready to support national interests in the Asia-Pacific region, and around the word.  For the Navy and Marine Corps together, this costs five cents of every tax dollar.  Can you find a better spent nickel from your tax dollar? <br>
<br>
I thank you for your support ... And for your hospitality.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
