<h1>Ribbon Cutting Ceremony:<br>Moanalua Terrace Housing</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, Hawaii (Tuesday, April 2, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Senator Inouye, Senator Stevens, Senator Akaka, Congressman Abercrombie, my flying mate back from Washington -- Congresswoman Mink and I shared an airplane Saturday night coming back here to paradise --  and our many other distinguished guests here ... Most importantly, members of our very proud Navy family -- and we are family:  I offer my warmest Aloha and a good afternoon to all of you. <br>
<br>
I always like to say what a great day this is ... and it is -- not just temperature-wise, but about what we're here for:  to see the labor of so many come to fruition, as we gather together for a very special event. <br>
<br>
As Rear Admiral Holder said, it seems like it was only a few months ago that I was at the controls of a bulldozer, with a very nervous Seabee standing-by, helping to demolish the first of Moanalua Terrace's old homes.<br>
<br>
We really have come far, and we've come there quickly.  That's a credit to a great number of key people.  I'm going to echo a lot of what you've heard from Admiral Holder already, but I think the echoes are warranted: <br>
<br>
First, there's Mike Hunt's team of builders that came out and did this great job, local craftsmen, local contractors who have done just an absolutely marvelous job of completing these fine homes ... on schedule and under budget.  We need to talk to you about some military hardware we want you to build in the near future!<br>
<br>
Most importantly, my wife, who is the housing pro in the world, if you will, has declared these quality products. <br>
<br>
Next, as Senator Inouye recognized in Congress last week, we have to thank our senior Navy leadership for their strong personnel support for improving Navy housing out here in Hawaii after a visit the Secretary made here in 1994. <br>
<br>
Third, we need to recognize our other Navy leaders and the leadership of the Department of Defense for their steadfast commitment to quality of  life, putting their money where their mouths were, and staying the course despite growing pressures on the military budget on a daily basis. <br>
<br>
And finally, a very special thank you to Senator Inouye and the entire Hawaii Congressional delegation, and Senator Stevens -- you are an honorary member of that this afternoon -- including the other members of Congress, who made some very tough choices and some very smart ones in keeping committed to supporting these housing improvements. <br>
<br>
These houses that are about to become homes that you see about you, plus the other quality of life projects underway throughout Hawaii, and throughout the fleet, can be thought of as an investment in long-term readiness of the fleet because they address our single most important resource:  our service personnel and their families. <br>
<br>
Not a day goes by that I don't find myself absolutely marveling at the quality of the women and the men that wear our uniform in the service -- the Marines and the Navy. <br>
<br>
And much of the world took notice of our Sailors just this past month when, once again, they proved themselves ready and worthy of meeting a challenge in the Western Pacific when they were called upon to demonstrate our nation's strong interest and commitment in maintaining peace between China and Taiwan. <br>
<br>
We canceled a return to homeport for the USS Independence carrier battle group and positioned them east of Taiwan to monitor Chinese military activity and to discourage miscalculation by any party involved. <br>
<br>
And then we redeployed the USS Nimitz battle group, which included Pearl Harbor ships, out of the Arabian gulf, and had them make the trip from the Arabian Gulf to the Western Pacific as an additional precaution. <br>
<br>
And then, when the battle group commander of those two carrier task groups was asked by a reporter whether his Sailors resented the delay in their homecoming, he responded, "My Sailors don't ask, 'Why us?'.  They state, with a lot of pride, 'Who else?'"<br>
<br>
And that's very, very true. <br>
<br>
Thanks to those great Sailors -- those patriots -- the crisis has subsided and we're here this afternoon to enjoy a beautiful day at the hub of the Pacific without a lot of worry about America's huge and growing economic and political interests in Asia. <br>
<br>
And thanks to projects such as this that surrounds us right now, our Sailors performing those critical missions throughout the Pacific don't have to worry about the adequacy of the housing for the families they're leaving behind. <br>
<br>
That's important because a Sailor can't do her or his best if they are worried about the well-being of their families back home.  And the Navy can't expect that Sailor to respond quickly and effectively without full support for the family back home.<br>
<br>
The most technologically advanced ships and aircraft in the world -- and that's what we have in the United States Pacific Fleet right now -- are worth very little, in fact nothing at all -- without the trained men and women to operate them. <br>
<br>
I don't have to remind our guest of honor this afternoon of those priorities, because he reminds me of them whenever we meet. <br>
<br>
He's a veteran of our armed forces, a long-time leader of the Congress, and he's a statesmen from the Pacific, who is for the Pacific. <br>
<br>
But he also knows the importance of caring for Navy men and women their families. <br>
<br>
We simply couldn't ask for a better look-out for our service members, along with the military employees throughout Hawaii, than Senator Dan Inouye. <br>
<br>
As we approach what many say will be the "Century of the Pacific," he has made certain that Hawaii will be prepared to be the strategic hub for the entire Pacific Rim. <br>
<br>
Senator Inouye, we appreciate greatly your steadfast support, and are truly honored to have you here for this very special occasion. <br>
<br>
Ladies and gentlemen, please give a warm Aloha welcome to Senator Daniel Inouye.... <br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
