<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Dallas Committee<br>on Foreign Relations</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Petroleum Club, Dallas, Texas (Wednesday, March 20, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Thank you and good afternoon, or Aloha, as we say back at headquarters.  As nice as Hawaii is ... It's great to be in the Lone Star State.  Though 3,500 miles from my headquarters, I feel very much at home here for a couple of reasons.<br>
<br>
First and foremost, there's the warm welcome you've extended.  Second, Texas is a well-known as a stronghold of traditional American values and patriotism... at least that's what I am told:  my daughter wanted to go to the University of Texas.  I'm also surrounded by Texans in the Navy.<br>
<br>
Our Surface Force Commander is Vice Admiral Dave Robinson (from Denton);  the Deputy Commander in Chief is Rear Admiral Herb Browne (from McKinney);  Chief of Staff, from the naval reserves, is Bob Smith;  also from Texas, the number one Sailor in the Navy, John Dalton, Secretary of the Navy;  and looking over my shoulder daily -- Fleet Admiral Chester Nimitz!<br>
<br>
Between these and a few thousand more Texans in the Pacific Fleet, they keep me on course ... And rooting for the right football team ... Or basketball team, in the case of Texas Tech in this year's NCAA tournament.<br>
<br>
Over the past 20 months, have put in many hours at the same desk used by Admiral Nimitz ... and living in the same quarters where he met many nights with his staff on the latest operational developments in the war.  Sometimes I wonder what he would think about the quality of officers in the U.S. Navy today.<br>
<br>
This lunch definitely will add to my good opinion of Texas.  Would like to thank James Gruppo and the Texas Commerce Bank for hosting this event.  Organizations such as Dallas Committee on Foreign Relations serve a very important function... by increasing awareness of issues of international concern.<br>
<br>
With a Slovenian name like "Zlatoper", you might think I was here to talk about the situation in the Balkans.  I'm actually here as a missionary of the Pacific.  Cultural backgrounds of many Americans, and therefore hearts, may be in Europe, but wallets are in the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Would like to share three points with you:  why all Americans should care about the Pacific;  what our concerns are in the Pacific;  and how the U.S. Pacific Fleet is addressing those concerns, even after a significant reduction in the size of the Fleet.<br>
<br>
First, why should we care about the Pacific?  There are strong economic and political reasons why the Pacific is becoming the most important region of the world for Americans.  Economic, political and military considerations prove this point.<br>
<br>
First, the economic perspective:  we have witnessed an astounding, unprecedented growth of Asian economies.  Asian gross national product is more than 30% of the world's total ... Having surpassed the total for europe in 1991-92 (22%).  Asian share of world gnp expected to climb to 50% by the middle of the next century.  Growth rate of developing Asian nations averaged 7.3% from 1985 to 1995 (compared to 3.4% for Japan, 2.6% for U.S. and 2.2% for  europe).  World's economic and industrial center of gravity is shifting to the Pacific.<br>
<br>
Trends in U.S. trade have followed this pattern:  aggregate trade with Asian nations represents 37% of total U.S. trade...  More than that of european union and latin America combined.  3 million American jobs directly related to exports and investments in Asia.  Expected to climb to 6 million over the next decade.  These aren't low paying "Mcjobs" of the service industry, but rather jobs which pay an average of 14% above non-export related  jobs.  With 3.5 billion potential customers, our ability to engage in trade/commerce with these nations is vital to our domestic economy.  I suspect many of you in business know this better than I.<br>
<br>
Region is important to the United States politically, as well.
It's a vast and diverse region (as I well know ... keeping up with developments throughout 16 time zones). It comprises more than half of the earth's surface and two-thirds of the world's population.  Asia includes:<br>
<br><ul>
<li>The world's largest democracy (India)
<li>The world's two largest islamic populations (Indonesia and India)
<li>The largest remaining communist nations (China and North Korea)
<li>Dozens of nations whose futures hang in the balance today, politically and economically.</ul>
Nine million Americans of Asian or Pacific ancestry give us yet another reason to care about the region (means that the hearts of more and more Americans are in Asia).<br>
<br>
With these economic and political interests in the Asia-Pacific, it's no  surprise why we have such strong security interests.  Asia has no over-arching security umbrella like NATO.  U.S. military presence is the one constant... providing the equilibrium for peace and security.<br>
<br>
Former Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs Joseph Nye (who's now dean of the JFK School of Government), expressed it another way:<br>
<br><em> "Security is like oxygen:  you do not tend to notice it until you begin to lose it. The American security presence has helped provide this 'oxygen' for east Asian development."</em><br>
<br>
With all of these reasons to care about the Pacific, what should be our concerns?<br>
<br>
In recent weeks, you only have to pick up the Dallas Morning News or tune into CNN to see one example.  Differences between China and Taiwan have the potential to disrupt peace, trade, the entire region's economic growth and our own well being.  Look what's happened already:  stock markets in the region have plunged, investors are scrambling to convert currencies to dollars and gold, and newspaper headlines warn ominously of closed sea lanes, rice hoarding, and instability in a region built on open trade routes and political calm.<br>
<br>
Much is at stake in our country ... when you pause to consider that China and Taiwan are the 2nd and 4th largest overseas trading partners of the U.S.  A report from California last week said that some high tech companies that rely on Taiwan for manufacturing silicon semiconductors are worried that production could be impeded.  There is talk about a potential silicon crisis -- akin to oil crises caused by past conflicts in the Arabian Gulf.<br>
<br>
The tension between China and Taiwan is only one of several long-standing animosities in the region.  Other trouble spots include... India and Pakistan;  China and India;  Russia and Japan;  in southwest Asia... Iran and Iraq;  and the Korean peninsula... where the North spends 25% of its GNP on defense despite a stalled economy and famine. <br>
<br>
There also is civil strife or insurgencies in more than a dozen countries, from the Philippines and Sri Lanka to Somalia and Rwanda.  Many Asian nations harbor concerns about the long-term ambitions of regional powers like China and Japan. <br>
<br>
Then there is the alarming militarization of Iran, and continued threats from Iraq...all in a region that supplies oil for most of the world.  As populations grow and demand for natural resources increases, expect to see greater potential for conflict over resources.  Competing claims over the Spratly Islands has this potential... China, Taiwan, Philippines, Malaysia, Vietnam and Brunei all claim at least a portion of this oil rich area. <br>
<br>
And then there's Russia... We all hope for positive development, politically and economically, in the former Soviet republics.  The Pacific Fleet conducted bilateral exercises in Hawaii with Russian Navy last year.  It was a very positive experience.  But Russia still retains significant military capabilities which must be watched... particularly their submarine program, which is still alive and well. <br>
<br>
In summary, there are plenty of reasons to be concerned about our interests and prospects for peace.  And there's no shortage of military potential when you consider Asia has:  7 of the 9 largest militaries in the world;  the world's 2 largest standing armies;  and 7 of the 10 most numerous submarine forces. <br>
<br>
Given our growing stake in Asia, and potential threats to our interests and pease, what is the Pacific Fleet doing to protect American interests and promote peace in the Asia-Pacific region?  Our guiding strategey is called "cooperative engagement"... largely by maintaining strong presence in the region. <br>
<br>
In 1995, the Pacific Fleet contributed to this strategy through 125 exercises with 25 nations... Navy-to-Navy talks... Personnel exchanges... 800 port visits to 40 nations... And hundreds of community relations projects.  These activities show our goodwill, build partnerships, and reduce the chances of miscalculation that could result in military confrontation. <br>
<br>
Countries who may not trust their neighbors see the U.S. as an "honest broker"... With no territorial claims or ambitions in the region.  I have traveled to many of these countries and met with leaders... and I am continually amazed at the overwhelming consensus on this issue: They want the U.S. to keep its forward presence in the Pacific. <br>
<br>
Two month's ago in Singapore, I heard Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defense, Dr. Tan Ke Yam, declare to a room full of delegates from other Asian nations:<br>
<br><em> "For many years now, the military presence of the U.S. has been and continues to be a factor for stability in the region."</em><br>
<br>
Recent tension between China and Taiwan clearly illustrates the value of our being there in Asian waters, with capable and ready naval forces.  When needed, ships of the USS Independence battle group were only a couple of days away from Taiwan area.  Their readiness became an unmistakable expression of American commitment, communicated world-wide on CNN and other media. <br>
<br>
As a precaution, the President underlined our resolve a few days later by ordering a 2nd battle group to the western Pacific, led by the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz (there's that Texas connection again!). <br>
<br>
It adds up to powerful signal of U.S. interest in a peaceful resolution of the Taiwan issue, reducing the chance of either side making a miscalculation or taking unwise action.  And as Secretary of the Navy Joh Dalton told Congress last week, "this is what you get when you fund the Navy and Marine Corps... These forces are forward deployed -- and ready -- as part of our sticker price!" <br>
<br>
This is at least the 8th time since I  became CINCPACFLT 20 months ago that Pacific Fleet forces have been called upon for real-world operational contingencies: <br><ul>
<li>Haiti (where we loaned ships to the Atlantic Fleet).
<li>Iraq twice ... In the falls of '94 and '95.  
<li>Rwanda... evacuation of U.S. embassy personnel
<li>Somalia ... Covering withdrawal of UN forces.  
<li>The Korean peninsula ... Where naval presence helped deter aggression while tough negotiations concluded a framework to address the north's nuclear program.
<li>And Bosnia ... Where PACFLT contributed EA-6B electronic countermeasures aircraft, and Seabees to build bridges, base camps, command posts and other facilities for U.S. troops.</ul>
The fact is ... Fleet operating tempo is as high now as in any period of the Cold War, but we're doing so with much smaller force.  5 years ago my predecessor had 250 ships and 280,000 Sailors and Marines.  Today I have 196 ships and 215,000 Sailors and Marines. <br>
<br>
Given smaller size of the Fleet, we are stretching our resources and changing the way we do business in many respects.   I'll give you seven quick examples... And would be happy to go into detail if you have  questions (in fact, I'd be very interested in parallels to your challenges of business). <br>
<br>
First -- we are eliminating rules and requirements that make no sense... What a concept for the military! <br>
<br>
Second -- increased reliance on our forward deployed naval forces.  The USS Independence carrier battle group and USS Belleau Wood amphibious ready group operate from Japan.  These forces have not been affected by overall down-sizing.  It would take 4-5 times the number of ships homeported in continental U.S. to equal their presence... and Japan pays 70% of the cost! <br>
Third -- modernization throughout the Fleet permits us to make our battle groups and amphibious groups smaller, without sacrificing most capabilities. <br>
<br>
Fourth -- we are training smarter with state of the art training facilities, electronic links to simulate forces and scenarios,   ...and more tailored approach to training requirements. <br>
<br>
Fifth -- restructuring and re-engineering where we can achieve efficiencies ... Including:  smaller and more streamlined shore infrastructure;  regionalized maintenance support;  even reorganized battle groups. <br>
<br>
Sixth -- much increased cooperation between Fleets, U.S. services, and international partners.  We have come a long way since the days when we couldn't operate effectively, or sometimes even communicate with our allies, the U.S. Army and Air Force, or between the Atlantic and Pacific Fleets! <br>
<br>
And seventh, what I call my most important force multiplier for resources -- the U.S. naval reserve.  Adds 22% more forces if mobilized in crisis or conflict.  In peacetime, add dedicated and expert people and additional ships and airplanes to help me meet commitments with a much smaller active-duty force.  Contributions of Admiral Bob Smith and reserves from the Dallas area are a great example.  Told them so at Naval Air Station Dallas this morning. <br>
<br>
Perhaps most important in our efforts to cover requirements with a smaller Fleet:  we are protecting our most important resource -- Navy people.  Manpower reductions have been accomplished in such a way as to retain the faith of Navy men and women.  Today, we are strongly committed to controlling deployment lengths and personnel tempo... Keeping Sailors at home with their families as much as we can. <br>
<br>
I know that even the best ships and aircraft would be useless without Sailors to operate and maintain them... and supportive families backing them up.  That's why we're actually increasing the amount of money we spend on quality of life projects like housing, fitness centers and military commissaries. <br>
<br>
Navy men and women are paying us back with their loyalty, motivation and tremendous skills.  It's awe-inspiring to see the flight deck of an aircraft carrier in operation around the clock... with same young kids that you would not have trusted with car keys a couple of years ago! <br>
<br>
By the way, we still need about 55,000 of these sharp young people a year to keep our Navy young and upwardly mobile.  Please help pass the word:  we still are hiring! <br>
<br>
With the great men and women of the Navy today, advanced ships and aircraft, and better ways of doing business... I am very optimistic about your Navy and the Pacific Fleet's ability to continue supporting American interests in the Asia-Pacific region.  We need to be vigilant to avoid backslide on readiness ... As we try to balance operating costs, modernization and investments for weapons systems for the future. <br> 
<br>
The Navy and Marine Corps together cost five cents of every tax dollar in order to support operations around the world 24 hours a day, wherever U.S. interests are at stake.  Can you find a better spent nickel from your tax dollar?  If you'd like to see for yourself, I encourage you to visit your Navy at San Diego, Seattle or Pearl Harbor.  We'll put you to sea, and let you spend some "quality time" with the world's greatest Sailors.  Just let Bob Smith know if you are interested, and we would be happy to arrange a personal, customized visit. <br>
<br>
I'll close with the words of a famous Texan:<br>
<br><em> "We must make certain, now and for the future, that peace is secure.  We must remain strong.  Never again should we risk the threat which weakness invites."</em><br>
<br>
Those were the words of Fleet Admiral Chester Nimitz 50 years ago, reflecting on the end of the Second World War.  We are ready and strong today, and I thank you for your support ... and for your hospitality. <br>
<br>
Thank you and God Bless you all. <Br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
