<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Association of Former Intelligence Officers</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Hale Koa Hotel, Honolulu, Hawaii (Friday, March 1, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Aloha and good day... It's a pleasure to join such a distinguished group of people who have served in our nation's clandestine services.  I know the job of an intelligence officer -- whether military or civilian -- can be a thankless job... often unnoticed and unknown to most Americans, but yet so vital to our national security.  I'm glad that AFIO is helping to show Americans the many important things that our intelligence community does on a daily basis.<br>
<br>
I'm especially happy to be talking to the AFIO group here in Hawaii -- the hub of the Pacific.  I spend a lot of time traveling around the mainland telling Americans why they should care about the Pacific (always surprises them with a Slovenian name like "Zlatoper").  I want to talk today not just about the Pacific, but also about the role that intelligence plays to me as the Fleet commander.<br>
<br>
Certainly don't need to tell a group like this what our cares and concerns are in the Pacific... But here are a few tidbits you might be interested in:  37% of U.S. trade is with Asian nations... compared with 20% for European Union.  The world's economic and industrial centers of gravity aren't shifting to the west... They've shifted.	  3 million American jobs are directly dependent upon trade and investments in Asia... growing to 6 million in the next decade.<br>
<br>
We also have significant concerns in Asia... seen just by opening a newspaper:  China's saber rattling at Taiwan... continued threats from North Korea... coupled with internal disorder caused by famine.  Disputes over Takeshima / Tokto islands and EEZ's between South Korea and Japan.  Quarrels over rights to Spratly Islands.  Historic animosities between India and Pakistan.<br>
<br>
Fortunately, the Pacific Fleet is engaged in the region... Promoting peace and stability.  Over 800 port visits and 125 exercises with nearly 25 nations annually in the Pacific Command area of responsibility.  Intel sharing initiatives are also a major component of cooperative engagement strategy:  we share not only data, but also methodology with several nations... Which enhances our interoperability.  Contrary to what you might think, intel sharing is a 2-way street... Just as we provide intel, we receive back extremely valuable information.<br>
<br>
Staff talks, Navy-to-Navy relationships, personnel exchanges and civic action projects also contribute.  They encourage transparency and reduce the chance of miscalculation which could lead to conflict.<br>
<br>
We have been credited with guaranteeing the stability of Asia... even called the "oxygen" which allows for strong economic growth.  Just a few weeks ago in Singapore, heard Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defence Dr. Tan Keng Yam say:<br>
<br><em>
"For many years now, the military presence of the U.S. has been and continues to be a key factor for stability in the region."</em>
<br><br>
This sentiment is echoed by leaders throughout Asia and the Pacific, who see U.S. presence -- particularly the routine presence of our Navy ships and aircraft -- as the key to maintaining the peace in Asia.<br>
<br>
Amazing thing is that we're maintaining this strong forward presence with a smaller Fleet.  196 ships and 215,000 Sailors and Marines today, compared with 250 ships and 250,000 Sailors and Marines five years ago.<br>
<br>
How are we keeping our strength in spite of having a smaller force?  By doing things smarter.  Eliminating rules and requirements that don't make sense.  Increased utilization of reserve assets... Using special skills that reservists have from civilian jobs (like computer programming).  Increased reliance on Forward Deployed Naval Forces assets (one ship in Japan = 4-5 continental United States based ships)  modernizing and upgrading... Allowing for smaller battle groups which actually have greater capabilities.  Fleet coordination... Standardizing our procedures and instructions so we can integrate seamlessly in the gulf or Caribbean.  Regional maintenance... Eliminating unnecessary redundancy by combining surface and sub maintenance facilities.<br>
<br>
Navy's intel community has also made some positive changes in the way it does business:  first, the intel community has become much more joint over the past 5 years.  As a Navy battle group commander in desert storm, I was seeing a Navy-specific intel picture -- different than the Army commanders on the ground were seeing... Made for some problems.  Today, we've combined our intel centers (Fleet Intelligence Center, or FIC, changed to the Joint Intelligence Center, or JIC, in 1991).<br>
<br>
They produce a common product for the different users.  Another benefit of jointness:  interoperability... Today can link real time intel data from awacs to ships, or from submarines to ground combatants... A far cry from the past.  Has resulted in more efficiency:  used to have 1200 personnel in three intel centers in Hawaii... Now 700 in one... And the product is improved.<br>
<br>
Brings me to my second point... intel is now more user friendly.  Spoke to Dennis Blair and Secretary Deutch about this last fall... There's a real push at the highest levels for a product which on-scene commanders can use easily.  Now have an information server system called "Intelink"... which is carried over our JDISS (Joint Deployable Intelligence Support System).  Intelink is as easy to use as the world wide web... Intel officers on our carriers, big deck amphibs or ashore can "surf" intel sites (CIA, NSA, CINCPACFLT, etc.) To download specific data needed for a mission.<br>
<br>
Here's an example:  an amphibioius ready group preparing for a non-combatant evacuation operation (NEO) in a place like Somalia could download imagery of Mogadishu immediately... And not have to request it or wait for it.  It makes practical intelligence available at the lowest possible level... And allows for more flexibility in missions.<br>
<br>
Third, intelligence has become more precise and closer to real time:  with the shift towards littoral or coastal warfare, our forces are much closer to the threat than ever before... A threat which today is much more sophisticated.<br>
<br>
And, where we once had targets which were fixed or stationary, today's threats move quickly.  We used to have 5 hours warning before the Bears and Badgers came... Now we may have only 15 minutes.  Receipt of raw data and near real-time analysis is critical in this type of environment.  And, as we fight in this dynamic environment, precision and accuracy are more important than ever:  from a political perspective these days, collateral damage is not acceptable, and immediate battle damage assessment is a must.  Intel needs to be just as precise, if not more, than our weapons systems themselves.<br>
<br>
It's interesting to contrast how the role that intelligence plays for me has changed over the years.<br>
<br>
As an A-6 pilot in Vietnam, it was too little too late.  We would receive warnings of SAM sites sometimes 2 or 3 days after a mission.<br>
As a battle group commander in Desert Storm, we had too much intelligence.  It was a difficult task of sorting out what was really important and what was not.  It was then that I adopted the same set of instructions Colin Powell used to give to his intel officer: tell me what you know, tell me what you don't know, tell me what you think and make sure I know which is which.<br>
<br>
And as a Fleet commander today, intel has come a long way.  Now we get a joint intel picture that is user friendly and more precise than ever.  This helps us tremendously as we downsize, allowing us to utilize our resources in the smartest possible way.<br>
<br>
Would be remiss if I didn't mention the role that Pacific Fleet units play as collectors of intelligence as well:  our forces maintain a robust collection effort... Utilizing air, surface and subsurface assets in support of both national programs and our own tactical programs.  The ability of naval forces to operate at sea gives us some unique capabilities:  surface ship outboard, special submarine missions, air reconnaissance, merchant shipping reports, to name but a few.  It makes me not just a customer, but a provider of intelligence as well.<br>
<br>
Hope I've shed some light on my views of intelligence.  From the perspective as the Fleet commander, it's absolutely vital to everything our Fleet does... From training our people to deploying our forces.  There isn't a flag officer in the Navy who wouldn't agree with that.<br>
<br>
I appreciate the opportunity to break bread with you today... Thank you and God bless you all.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
