<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>AFCEA/Naval Institute Expo Convention</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>San Diego Convention Center (Wednesday, January 24, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Good afternoon... It's a pleasure to address such a distinguished group of defense and industry professionals.  I was hoping to address you at lunch on Friday, but business in Washington demands my presence... so instead you have me today.<br>
<br>
For those of you who were at the luncheon, I know that the CNO is a hard act to follow... but at least you'll be able to see me over the podium!<br>
<br>
Being at this convention, I am amazed to stop and think how much the Navy... and indeed the entire world... has changed since Admiral Boorda and I were commissioned.<br>
<br>
Who would have dreamed back in 1963 that 33 years later...<br>
<br><ul>
<li>-- The Cold War would be over, and the threat of nuclear war would be greatly reduced?
<li>-- That the United States and Russia, once Cold War rivals, would become partners in carrying out combined disaster relief exercises off the coast of Hawaii?
<li>-- And that Russian ships would make a first-ever port visit to pearl harbor?
<li>-- Who would have guessed the impact that computers would have on every aspect of our lives?
<li>-- Who could have predicted, not just that Japan would become a great economic power, but that other east and southeast Asian economies would experience such exponential growth?
</ul>
The world today is in a rapid state of flux... So as we try to define the threats that the Pacific Fleet and the U.S. Navy will face over the next 30 years, we are left with a great deal of uncertainty.<br>
<br>
But yet we build our ships to serve us for 30-40 years... The carrier Midway, for example, served for 46 years until her retirement just a few years ago.  The A-6 was introduced into the Navy the same year I was commissioned in 1963... And the P-3 has been with us since 1961!<br>
<br>
So this afternoon, as a lead-in to the panel discussion on future international threats,  I would like to discuss some of the knowns and unknowns about the future in the Pacific... And will share with you what I, as the Fleet commander -- and therefore the customer of new technologies -- would like to see in future technologies... many of which you will no doubt help create.<br>
<br>
First, there are many uncertainties confronting us, but there are some known events... And I would like to set the stage by addressing some things that we know about the next 30 years.<br>
<br>
We know that Asia and the Pacific Rim will be a very important part of the world to the United States... There are 3 million American jobs directly dependent upon trade with Asian nations today... And that will grow to 6 million over next decade!  Over 200,000 American sons and daughters have been lost to conflict in this region during this century... And 9 million Americans of Asian or Pacific ancestry give us strong emotional ties to the region as well.<br>
<br>
Next, we know that computers and information technologies will be an integral part of warfighting... And just about everything else in the world.<br>
<br>
We know that demand for the earth's natural resources will continue to grow as its population increases... Which could lead to conflict.  The oil we have easy access to today will be a resource of competition with other Asian nations within the decade.<br>
<br>
We know that the vastness of the Pacific will continue to be an important factor for forward naval presence in the western Pacific and Indian ocean.  Even if we develop ships that can steam at 50 knots, deployments to Arabian gulf from the continental U.S. will still take nearly 10 days!<br>
<br>
We know that Asia will always have strategically important sea-lanes... The straits of Hormuz, Lomboc, Malacca and Tsushima to name just a few.<br>
<br>
We know that Hong Kong will revert to China 18 months from now.<br>
<br>
We know that the Arabian gulf region will continue to supply most of the world's fossil fuels.<br>
<br>
We know that Asia will likely continue to be one of the most well-armed corners of the world neighborhood... It presently has 7 of the 9 largest militaries in the world, the world's 2 largest armies, and 7 of the 10 largest submarine forces.<br>
<br>
We know that Asia will always be rife with historical tensions... Some so old and severe they make Bosnia look like childhood squabbling.<br>
<br>
Now those are a few of the items that we know... But there's even more that we don't know about the next 30 years.<br>
<br>
We don't know the future of the Korean peninsula... Will Korea ever reunite... And if so, what will post-unified Korea be like?<br>
<br>
We don't know which direction China will take... Will it continue its drive for a blue water Navy?  What will happen in Hong Kong after 1997?  What will China do regarding Taiwan and the Spratly Islands?<br>
<br>
We don't know Russia's political future... Although the Cold War is over, Russia still retains considerable naval capabilities that we must watch.<br>
<br>
We don't know the likelihood of continued U.S. access to forward basing... a crucial ingredient to maintaining a robust forward presence in the region.<br>
<br>
We don't know the future resolution of disputes between nations such as India and Pakistan.<br>
<br>
We don't know if weapons of mass destruction will proliferate throughout the region.<br>
<br>
We don't know what or who our future threats will be in Asia and the Pacific.<br>
<br>
We must consider these uncertainties as we plan new technologies for the future.  Smart ships... Arsenal ships... F/A-18 E/F's... New attack submarines... Open architecture communication systems... Wide area networks... Flagships with greater C4I capabilities... These are the warfighting tools which we are building today for an uncertain tomorrow.<br>
<br>
As the Fleet commander -- and therefore the customer of your technologies today -- I would like to share my perspective on what I believe is needed in these new technologies.<br>
<br>
First, your U.S. Navy's Pacific Fleet needs technologies which can be implemented quickly.  I was reading the other day that the average retail life for consumer electronics is just over 90 days... That's 90 days from the time a new product hits the shelf until it is made obsolete by a newer and more technologically advanced product!  Fortunately military technology doesn't change that fast... But it does move quickly.<br>
<br>
The process of acquisition and implementation must be done quickly and efficiently in order for us to keep the technological edge.  That means, wherever feasible and lawful, we must decentralize procurement to the Fleet level and even waterfront level.<br>
<br>
We cannot plan for, procure, and pay for new technologies in the future the way we bought new technologies in the past.  We don't have time to set up a program office and wait for 2 to 3 years until the technology is implemented... because it will be obsolete by the time it is!<br>
<br>
I'll give you an example (pull out GPS receiver)... This is a Garmin-40 hand-held Global Positioning System (GPS) receiver.  It's not much bigger than a Sony Walkman... and it gives you your exact position in longitude and latitude down to a few meters -- incredible technology.  It has numerous applications for drivers, campers, boaters and civil engineers, to name but a few.  But it could also be very useful to us in the Navy... We could put them in our landing craft... Give it to our SEAL's... Put them in our aircraft.<br>
<br>
But as incredible as this is, it's probably going to be obsolete in a few years... replaced by something the size of a wristwatch, with perhaps even greater accuracy.  We in the Fleet need to be able to purchase these quickly, and implement them into use while they're still cutting-edge technology.  And replace them quickly with newer technologies when they become available.<br>
<br>
One new program in its infancy... its first year... is NTIP -- Naval Technology Insertion Program.  It's an approach to rapid technology insertion that is managed by the Fleet community -- the customer -- instead of the procurers in D.C.<br>
<br>
NTIP makes me -- the Fleet commander -- the executive agent to buy mature technologies and rapidly insert them into use.  We purchase a mature technology -- say, for instance, a P-3 ESM suite -- which was developed but not POM'ed in the budget... We purchase one, decide how we want to use it, where we WANt to use it, and what tests we want to run... If we like it, we go back to the procurers in Washington and request more... And if we don't like it, we cancel it and we're not saddled with an unrelenting profusion of follow-on P-3 ESM suites.<br>
<br>
From my point of view, makes a lot of sense because it eliminates a number of steps in the middle... And we ultimately get new technology implemented more quickly.  It's still a "small bucks" program... $9 million this year... but is a step in the right direction towards streamlining acquisition and technology implementation.  And with technology changing as rapidly as it is, this is just the sort of innovation that will help us maintain our edge tomorrow in a world of uncertain threats.<br>
<br>
The second thing that I as the customer need in new technologies is the ability to upgrade.  I need the ability to replace individual components of systems as technology changes... without replacing the entire system.<br>
<br>
My wife can replace her old 486 processor with a Pentium chip on her computer without fanfare... But we in the Navy often seem unable to replace even a mouse without a 4 month study! We should strive to use modular inserts in ship and aircraft construction, designed to be pulled out and upgraded easily every couple of years... Because a couple of years today represents an entire generation in computing!<br>
<br>
This is all a part of what we call "open architecture"... Eliminating the "stovepipes" which used to restrict our connectivity -- and our upgradability -- in the past.  The best way to ensure we can upgrade easily is to use systems built of replaceable components made from commercial, "off-the-shelf" technology wherever possible.<br>
<br>
We obviously cannot do this with everything... Very few off-the-shelf computers are battle survivable and EMP hardened! (...but they may not have to be.)  And the majority of our technological applications aren't operational... They're administrative and routine.<br>
<br>
We're doing this with our CINCPACFLT wide area network -- or "WAN". We have established a secure "WAN" from my headquarters in Hawaii to the west coast of the U.S., Washington D.C. and Norfolk to the east... 10,000 miles across the Pacific to Japan and the 7th Fleet staff onboard USS Blueridge (afloat) in the western Pacific.  It was built entirely with commercial, off-the-shelf technology.  And because our WAN is componentized, we can easily upgrade it as technology changes (and, believe me, it will change!).<br>
<br>
So whether we're building a wide area network, making a replaceable guidance system on a missile, or just putting PC's in our offices... We need systems which we can upgrade easily, and which have removable components that can be replaced as they become obsolete.  This will be increasingly important in the future as we face a world of uncertain threats.<br>
<br>
Third and finally, we need technologies which allow us to upgrade our people.  By that I mean we need to employ new systems to hone the combat skills of our Sailors and Marines... Employing simulation and stimulation to make them sharper and more combat-ready.<br>
<br>
I'm not talking about the flight simulators in which I trained 30 years ago... Or even the elaborate team trainer simulators we've used for several years now for training CIC watch teams.<br>
<br>
I'm talking about technology that lets us conduct large Fleet-level exercises... Technology that allows entire combat teams, from multiple units, to work complex problems together spanning several time zones.<br>
<br>
With limited resources, we cannot always afford to get a full contingent of ships underway and aircraft in the air... So we will increasingly rely on virtual reality technologies to coordinate large-scale exercises involving many units.<br>
<br>
A great example of this was exercise Kernal Blitz last year off the coast of Camp Pendleton. It involved a carrier battle group, an amphibious ready group and a contingent of Marines.  The problem was we had no submarines available to play.<br>
<br>
So we put the crews of two submarines into simulators -- one in San Diego, one in new London -- and wired them into the exercise. 
As far as the crews were concerned, they were underway in their "virtual submarines", off the coast of San Clemente island, guarding the transition of Marines ashore.<br>
<br>
It was interesting to talk to the crew afterwards... They were really jazzed about the exercise.  Even though they weren't underway, they had gotten many of the same stimulations as if they had been.<br>
<br>
In the future we will rely more and more on the ability to take a ship that's out to sea, transfer the data coming from its radar and sonar to a team in another location, and let them be stimulated by that data.  One team solves the same problem that another ship is solving hundreds of miles away... With both real and simulated data.<br>
<br>
In a time of shrinking defense budgets, technology which allows for virtual training of our people is one way in which our Fleet can retain its edge in combat-readiness.<br>
<br>
So that's what I -- the Fleet commander and customer -- would like to see in the future:  rapid technology insertion, the ability to upgrade, and technologies which hone our people's skills.<br>
<br>
So much has changed since my early days in the Navy... Flying A-6's over Vietnam was a relatively simple process compared to what today's strike missions involve.<br>
<br>
In those days, a bombing mission would involve taking off from the carrier, flying to the target and dropping 15 - 1000 pound bombs.  With UHF line of sight comms, we couldn't abort or change the mission once over the horizon... And the ability to be warned of threats in midflight was very limited.<br>
<br>
Today, the same mission would involve incredible complexity.  We have far fewer aircraft and far fewer weapons to deliver, but they all have the potential to be delivered precisely, which is vital because they may cost $1 or $2 million each.  We must have the capability in mid-strike to change our mind, and modify route, target or egress... And the capability to do battle damage assessment immediately.  We have to deal with coordination with joint and coalition forces, and comply with air tasking orders that are longer than Tolstoy's War and Peace.  And we have a C4I network to support the pilot... Giving her a bubble in the sky which our pilots have never had before.  We have national sensor data downlinked directly to the pilot providing a full air picture as he or she flies in.<br>
<br>
If that's how complex a strike mission has become in 30 years, what will it be like 3 decades from now in 2025?  Being able to adapt our Fleet to missions of increasing complexity... in a world of uncertain threats... is what we need to strive for.<br>
<br>
But with the outstanding young men and women we have serving today... And the new innovations that people like you will work on... I am optimistic we can maintain our forward presence in the Pacific for years to come -- despite having a smaller overall force.<br>
<br>
I know that today's panel discussion will be fruitful and inspire ideas that we can put to use.  I'd like to stick around and participate, but have to be at the opening ceremony for the rear Admiral Roberta Hazard Center in half an hour... But I will return and I look forward to hearing a full report about your discussions.<br>
<br>
Thank you and God bless you all.<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
