<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Ford Island Causeway<br>Groundbreaking Ceremony</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, Hawaii (Wednesday, January 10, 1996)</strong><br><br>
Governor Cayetano, Admiral Macke, Admiral Hayes, General Lum, and many other distinguished guests ... aloha and good morning.  I'm pleased to take part in this historic event.  When planning began to build the Ford Island causeway, I was a young Lieutenant J.G. flying the A-6 Intruder's first combat missions over Vietnam from a Pacific Fleet aircraft carrier. <br>
<br>
Today I'm Commander in Chief of that Fleet, the A-6 is being retired, and we finally are breaking ground for the causeway.  Don't let it be said that we rush into such important projects without doing our homework! <br>
<br>
That we are here at all, even after 30 years, is a real tribute to the unique ties between the U.S. Navy and Hawaii.  This project reflects the support of the state's congressional delegation, led by Senator Inouye. <br>
<br>
Sharing the credit is the government of the State of Hawaii, led now by our distinguished guest speaker, Governor Cayetano, whom I'll be introducing in a moment.  And we must thank the City of Honolulu and the county for their cooperation in the real estate transaction that finally made it possible to move this causeway from the drawing board to this ground-breaking. <br>
<br>
This causeway will form yet another link, physically and spiritually, between the Navy and Hawaii.  I know Admiral Macke and others in uniform today would join me in saying that I am very proud of this positive relationship, and grateful for it.<br>
<br>
Hawaii is one of the very few places in the U.S. where the local share of the shrinking defense pie has actually increased, while other bases are closing around the U.S. and overseas. <br>  
<br>
Some would say that's no surprise when you consider Hawaii is strategically located at the hub of this vibrant Pacific region.  But there is more to it than that, as we scale back our activities in other strategic locations such as San Francisco and Guam.  Besides its location, the leaders and citizens of Hawaii offer a very special spirit of cooperation, support and friendship. <br>
<br>
And the participation of our guest speaker in today's ceremony is evidence of the unique partnership between the Navy and the State of Hawaii. <br>
<br>
The Honorable Benjamin Cayetano is a graduate of Farrington High School, UCLA, and Loyola Law School.  He practiced law in Hawaii for 15 years, and served 12 years in the state legislature before being elected Lieutenant Governor in 1986.  He was elected Hawaii's fifth governor in 1994. <br>  
<br>
In his distinguished career as a public servant, he has been a proponent of numerous military initiatives... including this causeway project.   More than that, he has been a friend to our Sailors and their families, and we all thank you for that support, sir. <br>  
<br>
It's my great pleasure to introduce Governor Benjamin Cayetano...<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
