<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/fukuc-d.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108110616 text/html 5631
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:18:24 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1>Presentation of<br>Legion of Merit<br>to Admiral Fukuchi</h1>
<h2>Remarks as prepared for<br>Admiral R. J. Zlatoper, USN<br>
Commander in Chief, U.S. Pacific Fleet</h2>
<hr>
<strong>CINCPACFLT Headquarters, Pearl Harbor, Hawaii (Tuesday, November 14, 1995)</strong><br><br>
Aloha and good morning.  Usually when we gather here for these ceremonies, it is to honor members of our staff... but this morning we are here to honor a very special individual who is not a member of our staff, or even of our military.  But the efforts of Admiral Takeo Fukuchi have made a positive impact on our entire Navy in the Pacific, and have contributed to the strong relationship which exists between the United States and Japan.<br>
<br>
For this special occasion, we are very pleased to have some other distinguished guests with us here today...  Consul General Amae of Japan...  Ms. Kathy Matsunami, Associate Director of the Japan-America Society of Hawaii... Walter Saito, Executive Director of the Japanese Cultural Center of Hawaii... Bruce Koppel, Vice President of the East-West Center... and Admiral Clarey and other retired Flag and General officers from the Hawaii area who are here for a conference hosted by CINCPACFLT.<br>
<br>
All are here this morning to help us pay tribute to a man who, throughout his career, has helped foster good relations between the U.S. and Japan.  But before I talk about Admiral Fukuchi, I'd like to talk about the unique relationship that exists between our two nations.  Japan and the United States are two of the world's most powerful democracies... with the world's two largest economies.  We share a common goal of seeing prosperity and freedom flourish around the globe... and by working together, we have made real progress towards achieving these goals. <br>
<br>
Our cooperative efforts have helped resolve regional conflicts, guaranteed freedom of the seas, and reduced the risk of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.  And even more importantly we have promoted democracy, respect for human rights, and free markets. <br>
<br>
It's important to remember that the Asia-Pacific region has no NATO-like security structure.  We rely on our strong bi-lateral relationships to maintain stability in this vibrant region.  Without a doubt, the most important of those bi-lateral relationships is our relationship with Japan.  Our economies are intertwined with one another... We are enamored of each other's cultures... And we share a strong partnership for peace in the form of our Mutual Security Treaty. <br>
<br>
If there is one part of our security relationship with Japan that best defines our friendship and partnership, it is without a doubt our navy-to-navy relationship.  If you were to line up a Japan Maritime Self Defense Force officer alongside a U.S. Navy officer, the only difference is that the JMSDF officer would have a <em>sakura</em> blossom where the American officer has a star.  We're almost identical in every other way... our education, our training, our tactics, our system of rank and promotion, our staff organization structures... and our values:  love of our country, personal honor, and devotion to duty. <br>
<br>
These similarities make it easy for us to be interoperable, and that allows for seamless operations with each other... like we'll see next year during RIMPAC '96... or any of our numerous bi-lateral exercises each year.  Even as we speak, we have three separate exercises ongoing with the JMSDF... and the JDS Kirishima -- Japan's second Aegis cruiser -- is exercising off of PMRF in Kauai.  Just a typical day for our navy-to-navy relationship with Japan... and a strong symbol of our friendship.<br>
<br>
One of the biggest advocates of our mutual partnership is Admiral Takeo Fukuchi... an long time friend of mine, going back eight or nine years to my days in Yokosuka on the Seventh Fleet staff.<br>
<br>
Since taking over as JMSDF Chief of Staff almost a year ago, Admiral Fukuchi has been a real partner to the U.S. Pacific Fleet.  He has been the architect of new and improved bonds of friendship and cooperation between the United States Navy and the Japan Maritime Self Defense Force... enhancing fleet interoperability, promoting bilateral planning, and confidently charting the course for our mutual maritime relations.  He understands that the relationship between our two nations, and especially between our two navies, is more important than ever in this dynamic and unpredictable post-cold war era. <br>
<br>
I am proud of our partnership, and I am pleased to call Admiral Fukuchi <em>tomodachi</em>... my "friend". <br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
