<DOCNO>WT22-B15-30</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000250-B020-148</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/cv62bg.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108110847 text/html 7133
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:20:56 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h2><center>USS INDEPENDENCE Battle Group<BR>Ends Deployment</center></h2>
<title>CV-62 Ends Deployment</title>
</center>
<hr>
The forward deployed aircraft carrier USS INDEPENDENCE (CV 62) and members of Carrier Group FIVE, along the Aegis Cruiser USS BUNKER HILL (CG 52), returned from a three-month deployment to the Arabian Gulf and western Pacific Ocean to their homeport of Yokosuka, Japan Wednesday, November 8th.<BR>
The Guided Missile Frigate USS CURTS (FFG 38) also returned fom the gulf and is currently participating in the joint U.S./Japan exercise "ANNUALEX" off the coast of Japan.  INDEPENDENCE and BUNKER HILL will be joining CURTS in ANNUALEX later this month.  Two other battle group ships, uss mobile bay (cg 53) and USS FIFE (DDG 991) remain in the Arabian Gulf in support of Operation Southern Watch.
;Highlights during the deployment included Helicopter Anti-Submarine Warfare Squadron 14 and crew members of uss mobile bay (cg 53) providing medical assistance and emergency helicopter transportation to a Spanish seaman, and Carrier Air Wing FIVE (I-5) recording the 337,000 arrested landing on board INDEPENDENCE, a record among active U.S. aircraft carriers.<BR>
The I-5 team didn't stop there.  Setting the example for high-tempo flight operations, INDEPENDENCE and Carrier Air Wing FIVE logged more than 3,500 landings and achieved a more than 99 per cent sortie completion rate.<BR>
"Logging this many landings and being able to launch aircraft as scheduled 99 per cent of the time, is a tribute to the special working relationship between independence and Air Wing FIVE," said CAPT Brian Calhoun, Commander, Carrier Air Wing FIVE, of  Eau Claire, Wisconsin.  Calhoun also pointed out the contributions of Fighter Squadron TWENTY ONE, which will decommission January 12, 1996after more than 52 years of
distinguished service flying every major U.S. navy fighter from The Hellcat to the Tomcat.<BR>
The value of joint operations was proven in late September when INDEPENDENCE completed a successful "dry hook-up" replenishment at sea with the Canadian Patrol Frigate HMCS
Calgary.  "with NDEPENDENCE's ablility to refuel at sea, both countries are able to react more quickly to any threat they may encounter," said INDY Commanding Officer CAPT David P. Polatty, III, of Annapolis MD.<BR>
In October, the staff of Destroyer Squadron FIFTEEN, the primary anti-air and sub-surface defense for Carrier Group FIVE, departed INDEPENDENCE after completing Arabian
Gulf operations.  Upon embarking in USS HEWITT (DD 966), DESRON FIFTEEN served as surface warfare commander during Exercise Foal Eagle, a combined exercise with The Republic of Korea designed to enhance rear area defense of the Republic of Korea.<BR>
According to CAPT Robert E. Smith, Commander, Destroyer Squadron FIFTEEN, U.S. and ROK forces work exceptionally well together and form a very credible deterrent to aggression.<BR>
The native of New York City said exercises like Foal Eagle "Keep Destroyer Squadron FIFTEEN's skills honed and enable us to complete our surface warfare mission."<BR>
As a member of Destroyer Squadron FIFTEEN, USS CURTS' deployment featured six maritime interception operations, one boarding and the diversion of a ship laden with illegal cargo bound for Iraq.  While all of these events supported UN sanctions
enforcement and Operation Southern Watch, the environmental highlight of the  deployment was the rescue of 10 sea turtles trapped in an abandoned fishing net.<BR>
While transiting the Indian Ocean on October 17, the crew of CURTS' SH-60B helicopter discovered a group of 10 sea turtles hopelessly entangled in an abandoned fishing
net.  The ship altered course to render assistance to the sea turtles, launched the ship's small boat and succeeded in cutting the turtles free.  The story of this rescue received national and international media attention.<BR>
USS BUNKER HILL, which celebrated its ninth birthday September 20th, served as the Battle Group's area air defense commander (AADC).  As AADC for the entire over-water gulf region, BUNKER HILL ensured that a unified tactical air "picture" was transmitted and relayed between units across approximately 9,000 square miles.<BR>
"We took our assignment as a regional warfare commander very seriously.  The ship's performance in area airspace management was virtually flawless," said BUNKER HILL Commanding Officer CAPT G. W. Schnurrpusch.   As the primary anti-air warfare (AAW) naval unit in the gulf, BUNKER HILL also managed the air battlespace for more than 700 Navy tactical air sorties.<BR>
During the deployment, USS INDEPENDENCE made port calls to Jebel Ali, United Arab Emirates; and Hong Kong, while USS BUNKER HILL made port calls to Manama, Bahrain; Jebel Ali, U.A.E; and Hong Kong.  USS CURTS made port calls to Bahrain; Muscat, Oman; and Phuket, Thailand.<BR>
While in port, INDEPENDENCE and BUNKER HILL crewmembers participated in community relations projects with their host countries.   INDEPENDENCE crewmembers assisted in the refurbishing of two children's homes, one in the United Arab Emirates and one in Hong Kong, and painted a women's home in Hong Kong.  Meanwhile, BUNKER HILL crewmembers hosted 30 students and faculty members for a ship's tour in the United Arab Emirates.<BR>
Throughout the deployment, the INDEPENDENCE Battle Group continued to meet all of its commitments while evading a nearly endless stream of powerful tropical storms.<BR>
Heading to the Arabian Gulf, the Battle Group avoided Tropical Storm Janice.  On the return trip to Japan, Tropical Storm Zack forced the Battle Group to revise its Manila port call to Hong Kong, only to depart Hong Kong ahead of schedule to avoid Super-Typhoon Angela.<BR>
As the Battle Group proceeded to its homeport in Yokosuka, Japan, Commander, Carrier Group FIVE Rear Admiral James O. Ellis Jr. said, "Whether this battle group is in Jebel Ali, or off the coast of Japan, Carrier Group FIVE will continue to show our allies and potential aggressors that well trained and capable forward deployed naval forces can always be  counted on to promote peace and stability wherever they go." 



<center>-USN-</center>
