&nbsp;<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h2><center>USS NIMITZ<br>Battle Group<br>Deployment Begins</center></h2>
<title>Nimitz Battle Group Deployment Begins</title>
</center>
<hr>
Over 10,000 Sailors and Marines from numerous Pacific naval commands will deploy to the Arabian Gulf November 27, 1995 as part of the Nimitz Battle Group.  The deployment is expected to last for six months.  Comprised of 9 ships and 10 aircraft squadrons, the Battle Group is commanded by Rear Admiral Lyle G. Bien, Commander, Carrier Group Seven.<br>
During the deployment, the Nimitz Battle Group will join forces with the PELELIU
Amphibious Readiness Group and their embarked Marines of the 15th
Marine Expeditionary Unit which deployed November 13, 1995.  Carrier
Battle Groups have been deploying with Amphibious Readiness Groups
due to a fundamental change in Navy warfighting strategy entitled
"Forward . . . From the Sea." &nbsp;In the past, single Carrier Battle
Groups would typically deploy to open ocean areas providing power
projection and air support to sea and land targets distant from the
Battle Group.  Today, with the addition of Marines and amphibious
assets, the combined group routinely operates more closely to the
shore where power projection in support of U.S. forces ashore can be
more efficiently conducted.<br>
This long-scheduled deployment is routine and not in response to any specific crisis.<br>
The forces of the Nimitz Battle Group include the following ships:<br>
<ul><li>USS NIMITZ (CVN 68), a nuclear-powered aircraft carrier homeported in Bremerton, WA.  NIMITZ is commanded by Captain Al Harms, Jr. and serves as the flagship for RADM Bien and the Commander, Destroyer Squadron TWO THREE, Commodore Barry Costello.
<li>USS PORT ROYAL (CG 73), commanded by Captain Nick Richards, is a
newly commissioned Aegis cruiser homeported in Pearl Harbor, HI.
<li>USS OLDENDORF (DD 972), a destroyer homeported in San Diego, CA, is
commanded by Commander Mark Nesselrode.
<li>USS CALLAGHAN (DDG 994), a Guided Missile Destroyer homeported in San Diego, CA, is commanded by Commander James Wisecup.
<li>USS FORD (FFG 54), a frigate homeported in Everett, WA, is commanded by Commander Ken Trass.
<li>The battle group includes two Nuclear-powered submarines, USS PORTSMITH (SSN 707) and USS BIRMINGHAM (SSN 695).  PORTSMITH is commanded by Commander Dick Corpus and is homeported in San Diego, CA. BIRMINGHAM, homeported in Pearl Harbor, HI, is commanded by Commander Mark Kenny.
<li>Two combat logistics ships, USS SHASTA (AE 33) and USS WILLAMETTE (AO 180) are commanded by Commander Norman Laws, Lr. and Commander Norma Hackney, respectively.  SHASTA is an Ammunition Ship homeported in Concord, CA. WILLAMETTE, a fleet oiler, is homeported in Pearl Harbor, HI.
<li>Carrier Air Wing NINE, commanded by Captain John Worthington,
is embarked on USS NIMITZ and includes 10 squadrons.  Three squadrons
are homeported at Miramar Naval Air Station, CA.  Fighter Squadrons 24
and 211, flying the F-14a Tomcat, are commanded by Commander Robert Wilson
And Commander Gerald Beaman, respectively.  Airborne Early Warning Squadron 112, flying the E-2C-plus Hawkeye, is commanded by Commander Brian
Roby.  Strike Fighter Squadrons 146 and 147, flying the F /A-18
Hornet and commanded by Commander Raymond Zack and Commander Robert Rutherford, respectively, are homeported in Lemoore, CA.  Flying the EA-6B Prowler, Tactical Electronic Warfare Squadron 138 is commanded by Commander James Seagle and is homeported at NAS Whidbey Island, WA.  Also homeported at Whidbey Island, Attack Squadron 165, flying the A-6E
Intruder, is commanded by Commander Mark Needler.  Four squadrons are
homeported at NAS North Island, CA.  Helicopter Anti-Submarine
Squadron EIGHT, flying SH-60 and HH-60 helicopters, is commanded by
Commander Terrence Doyle.  Fleet Air Reconnaissance Squadron 5, Detachment Charlie, flies the ES-3A and is commanded by &nbsp;Lieutenant Commander Andy Eddowes.  Sea Control Squadron 33, flies the S-3B Viking and is commanded by Commander Jeff Dickman.  Flying the C-2 Greyhound and commanded by Lieutenant Commander Rick Nichols, Fleet Logistics Support Squadron THREE ZERO, Detachment FOUR, will also be onboard.</ul>
NIMITZ last deployed in February 1993 and spent most of that deployment in the Arabian Gulf supporting United Nation's policy by enforcing the no-fly zone in southern Iraq as part of Operation Southern Watch.<br>
When NIMITZ returned to Bremerton in August 1993, she completed a nearly year-long overhaul at Puget Sound Naval Shipyard.   The Battle Group has completed a comprehensive training cycle which began in February 1995 and included nearly 150 days at sea preparing for this deployment.<br>
<br><br><br><center>-USN-</center>
