<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<br><h1><center>Naval Tradition</center></h1>
<title>Navy History/Tradition/Customs</title>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>Manning The Rails</h2>
<p>This custom evolved from the centuries old practice of "manning the yards."  Men aboard sailing ships stood evenly spaced on all the yards and gave three cheers to honor a distinguished person.
<p>Now men and women are stationed along the rails of a ship when honors are rendered to the President, the heads of a foreign state, or a member of a reigning royal family.  Men and women so stationed do not salute.
<p>Navy ships will often man the rails when entering a port, or when returning to the ship's homeport at the end of a deployment. 
<br>
