<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1><center>This Week In<br>Pacific Fleet History</center></h1>
<title>This Week In Pacific Fleet History</title>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>April 1, 1945: Operation Iceberg -<br> the Invasion of Okinawa</h2>
As a staging area for the anticipated invasion of Japan, American forces plan to seize Okinawa in the Rykus, some 325 miles south of Kyushu, nearest the enemy's home island.  A narrow, mountainous island, 60 miles long and from 12 to 18 miles in width, Okinawa is garrisoned by more than 115,000 Japanese troops.  Shunning the traditional Japanese strategy of attempting to repel an invasion at the water's edge, Japan has concentrated their forces in the rocky southern third of the island.  The invasion, the largest and most complex of the Pacific war, is conducted by Admiral Ray Spruance's FIFTH Fleet.  The U.S. landing force consists of more than 183,000 men, and encounters little resistance during the first three days after the landing.  On April 4, 1945, U.S. troops which have wheeled south, come up against Japan's Machinato Line.  &nbsp;The battle for Okinawa had begun.  Over the next three months of fighting, kamikaze attacks claimed 34 U.S. ships, damaging 288 others.  Japan lost 1,228 planes in the battle.  When the battle ended on July 2, 1945, 12,000 Americans were dead and 36,000 had been wounded.  Japan lost 100,000 soldiers in the battle.<br>
<img src="okinawa.gif"><br>
An LSM(R)s - Landing Ship Medium, Rockets - fires a salvo at Japanese positions on Okinawa.  (Official U.S. Navy Photo)

