<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1><center>Pacific Fleet History</center></h1>
<title>Pacific Fleet History</title>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>Battle of Midway</h2>
<strong>(June 2-6, 1942)</strong>--Admiral Yamamoto launched an operation designed to extend the Japanese defensive perimeter by seizing the island of Midway.  He believed that an attack on Midway will bring the American carriers out to be destroyed, completing the job begun at Pearl Harbor.<br>
Before the Battle of Midway, the Japanese had an advantage in every class of vessel, from carriers (8-3), battleships (7-0), to destroyers (55-33).<br>
This advantage didn't take them very far.<br>
In Pearl Harbor, Commander Joseph J. Rochefort's code breakers decoded the Japanese battle plans.  The key to this codebreaking included a little bit of trickery by U.S. codebreakers.  The codebreakers knew the Japanese were preparing to capture an island but they were unable to figure out which island.  All they had was a codename.  Midway was given instructions to send an uncoded message about a fictional problem at the water treatment plant.  The next day the Japanese reported on the island's water problems, using their codename for Midway island.  Now that the U.S. knew which island, setting a trap for Yamamoto's forces was easy.<br>
In the course of a day's furious fighting, planes from American carriers sank all four of the carriers assigned to Vice Admiral Nagumo's Carrier Strike Force.  This battle became the turning point in the war with Japan in the central Pacific.<br>
<hr>
