<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h1><center>This Week In<br>Pacific Fleet History</center></h1>
<title>This Week In Pacific Fleet History</title>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>July 6, 1943:<br>The Battle of Kula Gulf</h2>
Around mid-afternoon on July 5th, the Third Fleet learned that a "Tokyo Express" is enroute South from Bougainville with Japanese reinforcments for the Central Solomons.  Rear Admiral Walden L. "Pug" Ainsworth's Task Group 36.1, consisting of his flag ship, the light cruiser USS HONOLULU (CL 48), additional light cruisers USS HELENA (CL 50) and USS ST. LOUIS (CL 49), and four destroyers, makes full speed to Kula Gulf to intercept the Japanese.<br>
<br>
It meets the enemy force -- ten destroyers, seven of which are being used as transports, under Rear Admiral Teruo Akiyama -- a few minutes past midnight.  In a confused action that lasts almost until dawn, Admiral Akiyama's flagship, the NIIZUKI, is sunk and another Japanese ship, the NAGATSUKI, driven ashore, where she is destroyed by U.S. planes.<br>
<hr>
