<h1><center>This Week In<br>Pacific Fleet History</center></h1>
<title>This Week In Pacific Fleet History</title>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>July 26, 1953:<br>The Philippines or Formosa?</h2>
President Roosevelt met with General MacArthur and Admiral Nimitz in Honolulu to discuss the next steps in the war against Japan. Nimitz presented Admiral King's view that the Central Pacific drive should continue to Formosa.  However, both he and the President are convinced by MacArthur's argument that moral as well as military grounds dictate the United States proceed at the earliest possible moment to liberate the Philippines, with successive landings on Mindinao, Leyte and Luzon.<br>
<br>
The Joint Chiefs of Staff take longer to make up their minds.  The invasion of Mindinao and Leyte is not authorized until September, and the question of whether to go on to Luzon or Formosa remains unsettled until then.<br>
<br>
