<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63) hosts visitors during embark</title>

<h1>USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63) hosts visitors during embark</h1>
<h2>by JO3 Jon Saltzgiver<br>
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Aboard USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63), June 21, 1996)</strong>-- Flight operations, spectacular views of Hawaii and a visit by the Pacific Fleet commander highlighted a day at sea when Sailors aboard USS Kitty Hawk (CV 63) hosted 1,500 Navy League members attending their national convention, and more than 200 Navy Junior Recruit Officer Training Candidates (NJROTC), Sea Cadets and others on June 21.<br>
<a href="daddeck.htm"><img src="daddeck.gif" alt="Dad and Son On-Board USS Kitty Hawk" align="left" height=254 width=391></a>
In Hawaii for RIMPAC 96 with five other navies, Kitty Hawk offered a special opportunity for league members attending their annual national convention, which was held this year in Waikiki June 18-22.<br>
“Just being onboard the Kitty Hawk is an education in itself,” said Jim Pitton, the executive director of the Navy League’s Honolulu Chapter. “Here you have kids mostly who are in their early 20s launching multi-million dollar airplanes and handling weapons and just seeing how professional they are amazes you.”<br>

<a href="hilndemo.htm"><img src="hilndemo.gif" alt="Marines Fast Rope Onto USS Kitty Hawk" align="left" height=254 width=391></a>

During the eight-hour trip, visitors were given ship tours by the crew, observed demonstrations of firefighting gear aboard the ship and a display of guns used by the ship’s Marine detachment.  The weapons ranged from a pistol and a shotgun to the military’s newest belt-fed machine gun.<br>
Three hours into the voyage, the commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Fleet, Adm. Ronald Zlatoper, arrived by helicopter with a special guest, retired Capt. Gerald Coffey, a former Vietnam prisoner of war.<br>
Coffey, who was shotdown shortly after taking off from this same carrier during the Vietnam war commented, “I’ve always said the Kitty Hawk owed me a landing.”<br>
This day, that debt was paid.<br>
Coffey joined the other guests on the flight deck to witness the Navy’s most sophisticated aircraft hurtle off the deck. F-14 Tomcats, F/A-18 Hornets, S-3 Vikings and other aircraft were launched and recovered a short distance from the enthralled crowd.  <br>

<a href="flyover.htm"><img src="flyover.gif" alt="Carrier Air Wing 11 demonstrates Navy air" align="left" height=247 width=400></a>

“It looks different in real life compared to the way it looks in the movies,” said Joyce Clark, president of the Long Beach, Calif. chapter of the Navy League, and a first time visitor aircraft carrier. “Seeing the planes take off in front of you gives it a more personal touch to what happens in real life and, it helped me better understand what goes on up here.”<br>
“It’s amazing to see how quickly the planes took off from the ship,” said Stanley Bednar Jr., an NJROTC student from Anchorage, Alaska. “They look slower when you see this sort of thing on television, and seeing the real thing happen makes it look more impressive.”<br>

<a href="collis.htm"><img src="collis.gif" alt="Retired Pearl Harbor CO Visits USS Kitty Hawk" align="left" height=320 width=250></a>

The trip also showed how far the Navy and technology have advanced over the years, Navy League members were quick to point them out.<br>
“From an operational and readiness standpoint, it hasn’t changed that much at all,” said Don Clark of the Long Beach, Calif. Navy League Chapter and a retired Navy captain.  “The Sailors aboard our ships today are better prepared and qualified.”<br>
He added, “The Navy is more mechanized and that enables the ships to use somewhat less manpower to get the job done,” <br>
For John Stephens of the Pensacola, Fla., Navy League Chapter, only one thing seemed different from when he retired from the Navy in 1965.  <br>
“The only thing that I have seen that looks different on this trip is the fact that women are now stationed aboard the ship,” Stephens said. “It’s good to see that there is now an opportunity for everyone aboard an aircraft carrier.”<br>
Everyone packed the hangar bay for a buffet breakfast and lunch while members of the Pacific Fleet Band performed.<br>
Throughout the day, they were able to purchase souvenirs from the carrier and its airwing -- from baseball hats and boxer shorts to photographs and Zippo lighters.<br>
Adm. Zlatoper also presented awards to NJROTC students from around the western United States during a short ceremony in the hangar.<br>
“It was nice of him to take time out of his busy schedule to come to our graduation,” said James M. Sneed, one of the NJROTC students from Eagle River, Alaska, “it was a really big honor.”      <br>
<a href="zapjrotc.htm">
<img src="zapjrotc.gif" alt="CINCPACFLT Presides Over JROTC Graduation Ceremony" align="left" height=247 width=400></a>

After the ceremony, Adm. Zlatoper used the ship’s announcement system to thank the Navy League and the other guests for coming on board.  <br>
He also thanked the crew of the Kitty Hawk for their hard work and extra effort for hosting the guests and their successful completion of their participation in RIMPAC 96.<br>
“It’s evident that you all worked very hard to prepare the ship for this event,” he said. “You have a lot of reasons to be proud and I thank you for all your efforts.”<br>
He added, “I know that all the Navy Leaguers and special guests we have aboard join me in thanking you not only for your performance but also for your warm hospitality.”<br>
After returning the guests to Pearl Harbor the Kitty Hawk returned to its homeport of San Diego.<br>
Navy League Convention Chairman Dick Fahrenwald of the Hawaii Chapter summed up the experience by asking, “What do we do for an encore?”<br>
<br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
