<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>"SALTS" KEEPS SUPPLIES FLOWING</title>
<h1>"SALTS" Keeps Supplies Flowing</h1>
<h2>By JO1 Catherine Kurchinski</h2>
<hr>
<strong>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii, June 21, 1996</strong> -- Without supplies and repairs parts, U.S. Navy ships would be "dead in the water."<br>
That's why the Navy depends on SALTS -- Streamline Automated Logistics Transmission System -- a computer software system that processes supply orders for the fleet.  Everything from paper clips to power tools are ordered via the computer.<br>
<a href="satdish.htm"><img src="satdish.gif" alt="Electronics Tech Repositions Dish" align="left" height=266 width=400></a>
Helping to keep the logistics pipeline flowing for the largest naval exercise in the Pacific -- Exercise Rim of the Pacific, RIMPAC '96 -- are two Naval Reserve SALTS units, one based in Pearl Harbor, and the other in San Diego (Supporting the Atlantic Fleet are two Naval Reserve SALTS units on the East Coast, one in Norfolk, and one in Philadelphia.)<br>
With more than 40 ships from six Pacific nations involved in RIMPAC '96, including the U.S., Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea, reservists are playing key roles in the exercise.<br>
"When a ship in the fleet has a problem with their SALTS system, we provide support," said Electronic Technician 1st Class Wayne Waffird, a reservist assigned to SALTS Detachment 120, Pearl Harbor.  "During RIMPAC, we helped the USS Independence and  USS Kitty Hawk with their SALTS systems."<br>
State-of-the-art technology is used to transmit information to ships at sea, said Waffird.  "We have an international marine satellite terminal that we use to send e-mails.  When the  USS Kitty Hawk had a problem with their software, we sent them a fix via E-mail."<br>
RIMPAC, conducted every two years, improves coordination and interoperability of joint forces in maritime tactical and theater operations.  More than 40 ships front six Pacific nations, including U.S., Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea were involved in this year's exercise.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
