<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC Sailors Lock Horns in Sports Tourney Finals</title>
<h1>RIMPAC Sailors Lock<br>
Horns in Sports<br>
Tourney Finals</h1>
<h2>by JO2 James E. Scott</h2>
<hr><br>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, HI (June 20, 1996)</strong> -- Hearts pounded, teeth gnashed and muscles flexed during last weekÕs final phase of  the 1996 RIMPAC Sports Tournament.<br>
Teams from Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan, Korea, and the U.S. clashed in a myriad of events ranging from basketball to volleyball, all sponsored by MCI.<br>
Sailors from USS Kitty Hawk (CV 63) dominated the tournament, but the men of USS Chosin (CG 65) stood their ground to protect the "home turf" in the softball competition.<br>
"These tournaments get bigger every year," boasted Frank DelGaudio, Fleet Recreational Coordinator. "This year, we had more participants than ever."<br>
DelGaudio credits the turnout to the large amount of  publicity the tournament received. "I personally want to thank the recreation officers for keeping their individual units informed about the events. They really got things cooking."<br>
<a href="runner.htm"><img src="runner.gif" alt="Running On Empty" align="right" height=246 width=400></a>
A total of 405 runners competed in the 5K RIMPAC Fun Run.<br>
When the starting pistol fired, the screaming horde sprung forward like a savage beast lunging for the kill. But, it was Lt. Doug Ebbers, an H-65 helicopter pilot from Coast Guard Air Station, Barbers Point, who first crossed the finish line, with a time of 16:25.<br>
"I was very excited about the race," exclaimed Ebbers. "When I looked around at the other participants, I saw that there was a wide variety of talent.<br>
My initial strategy was to stay in pace with the lead runners. But after a quarter-mile, I felt pretty good, so I broke away from the pack, and set my own pace.<br>
"I had just placed 5th in the Hard Rock Cafe 5K Fun Run the previous week," he added, "and I was still quite sore. But, I gave it all I had, and won. It was nice to come in first for a change."<br>
In team sports, the men of USS Kitty Hawk seem determined to make their mark. In basketball action, they slam-dunked their way through the 39-teamm competion to squeak by USS Essex (LHD 2) 44-43 in the championship game.<br>
Kitty Hawk showed their strength again in soccer, as they kicked their way through the 39-team bracket to a 3-1 victory over USS Independence (CV 62).<br>
<a href="vball.htm"><img src="vball.gif" alt="BUMP...There It Is" align="left" height=444 width=300></a>
And, in indoor volleyball competition, the "Hawk's" men tore through the 21-team roster to trample JDS Yuugiri (DD 153) 15-4, 15-4 in the final match.<br>
Even in tennis, Kitty Hawk proved unstoppable as Ensign Matt Kowalsky aced his way through 59 other players, to win with a score of 6-1, 6-2 in the final.<br>
But in the softball arena, the "Hawk" met its match. The sweltering heat only seemed to feed the fire of USS Chosin's War Dragons, who scorched their way through the 58-team, single-elimination tournament to decimate the Kitty Hawk 12-2 in the final game.<br>
The War Dragons, who were leading the intramural league with a record of 19-1, were well-prepared to slug it out.<br>
"We really put our hearts and souls into the final competition," declared Operations Specialist 1st Class Johnny L. Graves, coach of the champion War Dragons. "Our motto is 'never give up.' From player one to the three extra guys on the bench, everyone got involved.<br>
"Our strength lies in our defense," he bragged. "A lot of teams hit better than us, but we have some of the best defense on the island.<br>
"We come from a ship of 400, so our selection is limited; the Kitty Hawk has over 5,000, so they pretty much have pick of the litter. It was a challenge, but we dived in headfirst, and came out on top."<br>
In other sports action, USS Coronado  (AGF 11) proved to be the best of 35 teams in the 4-man sand volley ball contest, smoking USS Chosin 11-9, 11-6 to take the championship.<br>
All in all, some 3,400 participants competed in this second phase of RIMPAC sports events.<br>
"I think this says something about the camaraderie that exists between the navies of the world," concluded DelGaudio. "This is a great opportunity for shipmates from around the world to get together and compete in a friendly atmosphere, and unwind a little bit."<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
