<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>MARINES OPPOSE RIMPAC AMPHIB LANDING</title>
<h1>On the Other Side:<br>
Marines Oppose RIMPAC 96<br>
Amphib Landing</h1>
<h2>By JO2 José V. Tolentino</h2>
<hr>
<strong>BARKING SANDS, Kauai, June 20, 1996</strong> -- While US Marines are usually on the offensive, Kaneohe-based India Company, Third Battalion, Third Marines, recently played the opposition force during RIMPAC.<br>
<a href="lookout1.htm"><img src="lookout1.gif" alt="On the Lookout for Invading Forces" align="left" height=269 width=400></a>
Company Commander Captain Steven M. Neary and his 87 Marines played the role of a fictitious enemy for a simulated amphibious assault at PMRF (Pacific Missile Firing Range), here, on June 15.  The event served as the climax for the maritime training exercise RIMPAC 96.<br>
The Essex Amphibious Task Group (ATG), led by the helicopter carrier/assault ship USS Essex  (LHD 2), included the landing assault craft USS Cleveland (LPD 7), and USS Harpers Ferry (LSD 49).  They launched the amphibious force from the Camp Pendleton, California-based 11th MEU (Marine Expeditionary Unit).<br>
Given the invaders' overwhelming numerical and technological superiority one would think that Neary's young "Devil Dogs" would have fled with their tails between their legs upon being designated as the exercise's opposing force.  Such was not the case with these stalwart defenders.<br>
<a href="warning1.htm"><img src="warning.gif" alt="Sending Out the Signal: Enemy Forces Approach" align="right" height=450 width=300></a>
Neary was elated over the opportunity presented to him and his rifle company to portray a fictitious enemy nation.<br>
"This amphibious landing is wonderful practice in preparing them for upcoming deployments,"  he said, the day prior to the assault.<br>
Corporal Jacob D. Butz 's enthusiasm for his company's role in the scenario stemmed from slightly different reasons.<br>
Because he and his fellow Marines were portraying an undisciplined enemy country, they were not required to maintain the usual Marine Corps discipline and decorum.<br>
"It's a nice break from the norm," the 20 year old Montvale, NJ native said. "We get to wear civilian attire, act crazy and go swimming."<br>
"If this were a real Marine scenario, and my men were portraying themselves," Neary explained, "we would have mined the beaches first and then moved into the mountains.<br>
"The amphibious assault is the 'bread-and-butter' of the Marine Corps; we were the ones who invented it.  I would not want to be in the real-life role of the enemy country."<br>
But that was not the case that early Saturday morning when the amphibious assault scenario began.  Neary's men faced "bombardment" by both air and water from the oncoming invaders.<br>
After the invasion force determined that the Neary's defenders were put out of action, it then proceeded to unleash more than several waves of landing craft and air-cushioned assault vehicles.<br>
<a href="cleangun.htm"><img src="cleangun.gif" alt="Always Being Ready Means Having a Clean Gun" align="left" height=450 width=300></a>
These well armed forces steamrolled their way through the beach defenses, and proceeded to disgorge their fearsome cargo of men and tanks at various points along the invasion front.<br>
The assault exercise lasted for about four hours.  Neary's defenders, although exhausted by the oppressive heat and seemingly endless waves of landing craft and enemy tanks and men, did come away with a renewed appreciation of their service branch's trademark mode of attack.<br>
"This exercise was definitely useful in our overall training," said Lance Corporal. Michael R. Brown, a 20 year old native of Virginia.  "The toughest thing about it was the hot weather, the sand's bad effect on our weapons, and the chance of getting dehydrated."<br>
The scenario also provided Neary's men useful insight into the invasion force's skill in executing its assault.<br>
"Those guys were coming off the tracs (landing craft) too slow," remarked Kansas native Lance Corporal Ryan G. Dixon. "They were too laid-back and slow in their attack.  They should have come out harder and more aggressive.
"But, if there was something that they did right, it would be that they coordinated the communication between their people very well."<br>
"This exercise was definitely a benefit for us," Neary said.  "It was good to have been able to assume a different role, rather than just being the aggressor all the time, and constantly being evaluated.<br>
"It also reaffirmed the Marine Corp concept of the individual Marine and his importance to the Marine on his right and left during wartime."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
