<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/rimraid.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108112844 text/html 5248
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:40:54 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>MARINES PERFORM HELO RAID</title>
<h1>Marines Perform Helo Raid</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Dave Kistler</h2>
<hr>
<strong>ABOARD USS ESSEX, Pacific Ocean, June 12, 1996</strong> -- Helicopters buzzed off the coast of  Oahu, setting the stage for  Marines to recover captured cryptological equipment from the Capmid Unification Forces as part of RIMPAC '96.<br>
Marines from the 11th  Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU) and the Marine Medium Helicopter Squadron (HMM)-166 reinforced, conducted special urban tactics  at Marine Corps Base Hawaii on the afternoon of June 12th.<br>
Approximately 60 members of Kilo Company, bound for the base, left from USS Essex aboard several CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters  shortly after UH-1N Huey and AH-1W Super Cobra helos conducted assault element maneuvers.<br>
The mission was for the Marines to search for the missing equipment, secure it and return to the ship within a one hour time frame.<br>
<a href="mioload.htm"><img src="mioload.gif" alt="Marines Prepare for Helo Raid" align="left" height=267 width=400></a>
For this scenario, the Hawaiian islands were divided in two, creating the countries of Pacifica and Capmid.   Pacifica was comprised of the islands of Oahu, Kauai, Niihau, and Kuala Rock.  Capmid consisted of the islands of Hawaii, Maui, Molokai, Lanai and Kahoolawe.<br>
The RIMPAC players were divided into bi-lateral and multi-national forces.  The bi-lateral force, located in the western pacific, was composed of the USS Independence Carrier Task Group and the Japanese Maritime Self Defense Force.<br>
In the eastern pacific the USS Kitty Hawk Carrier Task Group, Australian, Canadian, Republic of Korea and Chilean forces made up the multi-national force.<br>
Cpl. Chris Corb of Kilo Company 2nd platoon stated, "The assault element goes in first to clear the way, and then the security element will land".  The helos offloaded members of Kilo Company on the landing strip of the base and then enhanced from there.<br>
Corb, a squad leader for the Second Platoon, said, "We moved from building to building, doing things such as room clearing.  Eventually we found the equipment and began to pull back to get picked up by the helos".<br>
Time for this mission was slotted for about an hour and fifteen minutes, but only took the Marines thirty-two minutes.<br>
When asked why this type of  training was so important, the 20 year old Corb stated, "This type of training is done before each deployment.  But mainly they are to help us learn to work together and to know how each other is thinking".<br>
<a href="harrier1.htm"><img src="harrier.gif" alt="Marine Harrier Returns to Deck of USS Essex" align="left" height=448 width=300></a>
He also said, "I like these drills because our leaders can make the simulations as real as possible and still make them safe".<br>
Corb has had first hand experience with these types of missions.  He was part of a actual mission like the simulated one in Somalia.<br>
But unlike Corb, Cpl. Derek Anderson of the First Platoon has never been involved with a real one.<br>
Anderson, a stick leader for his platoon in Kilo Company, said, "I like these training evolutions.  As a stick leader, I'm responsible for four other Marines, making sure they board the helos safely and that their gear is squared away".<br>
He also stated that he likes to have that kind of responsibility.  "Our job is to go into a situation like that and set up security, defense and to quicken response time  for the other elements such as the Landing Craft Air Cushions (LCAC) and the Assault Amphibious Vehicles (AAV)".<br>
Overall, the 24 year old Anderson thought it was good evolution.  "The only thing that surprised us was that the terrain was a little thicker than we thought."<br>
Once the objective is recovered from these types of missions the MEU will return to the ships, check their gear in and get de-briefed.  These evolutions, such as the scenarios played out in RIMPAC '96, are sure to prove to be invaluable.<br>
With the ever changing role of the U.S. military and the seemingly shrinking world environment,  the Marine Corps will undoubtedly be prepared for whatever they are faced with.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
