<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/amphib1.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108112926 text/html 9860
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:41:35 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Marines make a perfect landing</title>
<h1> Marines Make<br>a Perfect Landing<br>
to Close Out<br>RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>By JO1(SW) S.A. Thornbloom</h2>
<hr>
<strong>BARKING SANDS, Kauai, June 18, 1996</strong> -- First, shrill screams filled the clouds.  Then, grinding, clanking sounds rolled in from the sea.  And soon, staccato reports and sulfur smells hung in the early morning air.<br>
Finally, an ominous buzz grew louder and louder as the modern landing craft hit the beach.<br>

<a href="lcacland.htm"><img src="lcacland.gif" alt="LCAC hits the beach" align="left" height=256 width=400></a>

The United States Marine Corps had landed from the sea as part of RIMPAC 96.<br>
The sounds and smells came from Navy F-14s and Marine Corps Harrier jets streaking through the air providing cover, amphibious assault vehicles moving quickly through the soft sand and .50-caliber and 20mm weapons firing blank ammunition.<br>
Meanwhile, the huge helicopter-like propellers of air-cushioned landing craft laden with Marines and equipment took their positions on the Pacific Missile Range Facility's beach property to suppress an insurgent uprising.<br>
Nearly 700 Marines from the 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit (MEU) landed in RIMPAC's fictional country of Pacifica to stop rebels from overthrowing the government.<br>
It was all part of the training for the Marines from Camp Pendleton, Calif., and Kaneohe Bay, Hawaii, and a chance to show their stuff during a simulation of the possible scenarios the MEU could be ordered to respond to during their upcoming deployment to the Western Pacific.<br>
Real missions in Grenada, Haiti, Somalia and Liberia demonstrate the importance of practice this type of amphibious landing during an exercise such as RIMPAC, according to MEU officials.<br>
"Amphib landings are the bread and butter of the Marine Corps," said Marine Corps Capt. Mark Sojourner, the landing coordinator on shore for 11th MEU.  "It's the reason for being."<br>
Those "from the sea" attacks have been a Navy-Marine Corps specialty since it was developed in World War II.  During that war, amphibious assaults led to victory in the Pacific as Marines charged onto the beaches of Tarawa, Guam, Saipan, Iwo Jima and Okinawa, to name a few.<br>

<a href="lcacload.htm"><img src="lcacload.gif" alt="LCAC off-loads men and machines onto the beach" align="right" height=268 width=400></a>

Gen. Douglas MacArthur turned the tide of the Korean War with a gutsy landing at Inchon in 1951 that liberated Seoul and trapped the North Korean army between two forces.<br>
Successful Marine amphibious landings continue to show the importance of that tactic, even as recently as the 1991 Persian Gulf War, when the Marine Corps feigned an amphibious landing on Falaka Island near Kuwait to confuse Iraqi defenders.<br>
"That (effective feint in Operation Desert Storm) was a big play in allowing the Marines, the Army and other nations' units to be as successful as they were," said Sojourner, an AH-1 Cobra helicopter pilot from Camp Pendleton.<br>
The RIMPAC amphibious landing began very early in the day off Kauai's west coast  with nearly 40 ships from the United States, Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea sailing silently beyond the horizon, preparing for the landing.<br>
RIMPAC is held every two years to improve coordination and interoperability of joint forces in maritime tactical and theater operations.<br>
"The Marines are lucky enough to jump on board (during RIMPAC) and participate with the Navy and all the other nations in the exercise," said Sojourner.<br>
Amphibious landings have always been an "all-Marine show," with the U.S. Navy and Marine Corps working together, he said.  But during RIMPAC, other countries wanted to see how the landing was conducted.<br>
"The other Pacific nations in the exercise are curious about how we do amphibious landings and ask questions, but they don't actually participate in the operation."<br>
Sojourner, who was in charge of setting up the beach for the landing, went on to say, "We have some foreign ships (like HMAS Perth) provide naval gunfire during an assault while the other countries observe.  But these landings are really just the (U.S.) Navy and Marine Corps working in a nice, integrated team to provide an effective fighting force."<br>

<a href="usmcover.htm"><img src="usmcover.gif" alt="Marine on the beach" align="left" height=264 width=400></a>

This scenario included plenty of training for the Sailors aboard the amphibious ships USS Harpers Ferry (LSD 49), USS Essex (LHD 2) and USS Cleveland (LPD 7).  As part of the Amphibious Task Force, each of these vessels had the responsibility to get the MEU into position and quickly dropped-off close to the beach.<br>
The Marines of the MEU and Marines from Kaneohe, who portrayed the rebel force, also said how important the training in RIMPAC has been in preparing them as a cohesive unit for the rest of their deployment.<br>
Lance Cpl. Adam Aldrich of India Company, 3rd Battalion, 3rd Marines at Kaneohe Bay, served as one of the beach defenders.  The Edmond, Okla., native said he was on the beach to give the MEU some "high-quality training" as they prepare for their West Pac deployment.<br>
Even though his squad of rebels were on a suicide mission by defending the beach against such a large force, the training his team provided to the MEU was invaluable to everyone, he said.<br>
And by portraying "the bad guys," Aldrich's small group got a chance to see what the MEU had to overcome once it hit the beach.<br>
"Through bettering them," he said, "we better ourselves."<br>
Lance Cpl. Daniel Blackwell from Bolingbrook, Ill., agreed with his rebel cohort.<br>
"We're here to aggress the MEU and die," the Kaneohe Marine explained.  "We're helping them in their training by playing the role of a (fictitious) Third World country (called Capmidia).  In that role we have limited weapons and tactics, but we still make them think and react quickly."<br>
With wave after wave of assault vehicles -- amtracks with about 15 "grunts" packed in each -- moving toward the Capmidian rebels, the insurgents were forced to flee and eventually were captured or "killed" and defeated.<br>
The operation was then able to continue unabated as second, third and fourth waves of hovercraft, known as LCACs (Landing Craft Air Cushion), brought the MEU's heavy equipment, including six-wheeled Land Assault Vehicles (LAV) with 20mm cannon and trucks carrying ground-to-air avenger missiles.<br>



<a href="usmcland.htm"><img src="usmcland.gif" alt="Marines get ready to leave after a day at the beach" align="left" height=256 width=400></a>

Sojourner said every MEU has to go through several phases before heading out on deployment.<br>
He referred to the phases as learning to crawl, walk and run, and said participating in RIMPAC was the beginning stage, where the MEU's Marines and Sailors received their initial training on how to properly perform an amphibious landing.<br>
RIMPAC also gives the MEU their first opportunity to conduct a landing, according to Sojourner.<br>
After RIMPAC, the unit then goes right into a fleet exercise.  During this stage, the MEU trains with the fleet as it transits the Pacific.  Sojourner said coordination between the fleet and the MEU is essential.<br>
"They (the Marines) get to do the shipboard procedures (such as planning the different missions) before moving to land," he said.  "The MEU has a designated set of missions they practice.  (On ship) they train and try to improve on  these missions."<br>
The final evaluation, or stage, is the joint task force exercise.  That's where everything is put together for a final grade and the unit looks to be awarded a MEU SOC (Special Operations Capable) designation.<br>
The designation, according to Sojourner, means the MEU is ready to respond to any crisis that may arise while on deployment.<br>
"Giving the MEU an opportunity to practice and train during RIMPAC makes the unit and the Marine Corps a more effective fighting force because of the combined use of arty (artillery), air and naval gunfire all at one time and making sure it's all coordinated," Sojourner said.<br>
For the MEU's few good men, however, the amphibious landing during RIMPAC 96 wasn't just about training-- it was also a pretty big rush.<br>
Lance Cpl. Lynn Berendsen, an amphibious assault vehicle driver from Lawrence, Kansas, said he likes exercises such as RIMPAC because "I get to splash off the ship numerous times and it gives me a huge adrenaline rush every time."<br>
<em>JO1 Andy Wellmann contributed to this story</em>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
