<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Fleet Mail Center 'Delivers'</title>
<h1>Fleet Mail Center 'Delivers'</h1>
<h2>By JO1 Catherine Kurchinski</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Honolulu, HI, June 14, 1996 </strong> -- 
Neither rain, sleet, nor saltwater keeps the mail from being delivered at sea.<br>
<a href="malhndlr.htm"><img src="malhndlr.gif" alt="Mail Handlers prepare load for delivery to ships" align="left" height=461 width=300></a>
Thanks to the Navy's Fleet Mail Center, based at the U.S. Postal Service Main Office in Honolulu, thousands of  military personnel  involved in the largest naval exercise in the Pacific -- RIMPAC 96 -- are getting their mail on time.<br>
With more than 40 ships from six Pacific nations, including the U.S., Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea, participating in RIMPAC, postal clerks are extra busy.<br>
"Our main goal is service to the fleet," said Postal Clerk 1st Class Sidney Dawson, leading petty officer for the Fleet Mail Center. "We don't let the mail sit around; we get it out as quickly as we can."<br>
Getting the mail out quickly takes teamwork, stressed Dawson. Seven active-duty postal clerks are assigned to the Fleet Mail Center, along with two mail detachments from USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63) and USS Independence (CV-63), and three Naval Reserve logistical units based at Hickam Air Force Base.<br>
<br><br><br><a href="indyxprs.htm"><img src="indyxprs.gif" alt="aircrew off-loads mail from Indy Battle Group" align="right" height=268 width=400></a>
The U.S. Postal Service is also pitching in by providing extra equipment, such as forklifts.<br>
"The relationship with the United States Postal Service has been outstanding," said Dawson. "Things run smoothly when you have all the equipment you need."<br>
The Fleet Mail Center sorts, routes and bags the mail for each individual ship. Then it's trucked to a nearby hangar at Hickam Air Force Base where it's loaded on four aircraft,  C-2A Greyhounds. Two detachments from VRC-30 are working around the clock to transport mail, cargo and passengers to the fleet. "We're delivering about 25,000 pounds of mail daily," said Dawson.<br>
<a href="pilot.htm"><img src="pilot.gif" alt="COD pilot gives thumbs up prior to take off" align="right" height=440 width=300></a>
"When they announce 'mail call' on the ship's loudspeaker (1MC), you can hear the rumblings of anticipation," said Yeoman Chief (AW) Daryl Nielsen, administrative chief for VRC-30, Detachment 5, based at Atsugi, Japan.<br>
When RIMPAC 96 ends June 21, the mail will keep on moving.<br>

"During the last RIMPAC we moved 325,000 pounds of mail," said Dawson. "Flexibility is the key to success here; there's no set schedule. We have to be ready on a moment's notice. When the mail comes in, we deliver."<br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
