<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>

<title>USS RAINIER Plays Key Role During RIMPAC 96</title>
<h1>USS RAINIER Plays Key<br>
Role During RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Rita Bargeloh</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Aboard USS RAINIER (AOE-7), Pacific Ocean, June 7, 1996</strong> -- This ship isn't equipped with the latest in sophisticated weaponry.<br>
And you won't see supersonic F-14 Tomcats landing on its deck.<br>
But the fast combat support ship USS Rainier (AOE-7) still plays a vital role in RIMPAC 96 and the fleet.<br>
The Rainier is a one-stop shop from which other ships in the carrier battle group receive everything from bombs and bullets to fuel, food and fresh Sailors.<br>
<a href="aoe7helm.htm"><img src="aoe7helm.gif" align="left" height=275 width=400></a>
The ship, homeported in Bremerton, Wash., is in essence a floating city.  It provides its crew of 579 men and women with a barber shop, laundry facilities, medical and dental care, a post office, a store, eating places, workshops and laboratories.<br>
Also within its 753-foot-long hull, Rainier can store 20,000 gallons of water for its crew, and five 250-ton-capacity air conditioners keep the ship cool while generators supply more than 12.5 million watts of power.<br>
But it is primarily there for others:  Rainier's cargo refrigerators are capable of holding 400 tons of food, and it can store and deliver more than 6.5 million gallons of fuel.  That's enough fuel to fill the average automobile 364,000 times.<br>
It can also carry 1,800 tons of ordnance and 250 tons of non-refrigerated bulk items.<br>
In addition to hauling all those goods on deployment, Rainier must be able to deliver them while on the go.  And that is its main mission:  To conduct prompt underway replenishment operations, or UNREPs, with other ships.<br>
There are basically two ways to accomplish that:  Connected replenishment, or CONREP, where other vessels maneuver alongside Rainier; and vertical replenishments, or VERTREP, where helicopters deliver the goods.<br>
Before vertical replenishment operations, "flight quarters" is announced throughout Rainier to notify crew members that helicopter operations will be taking place on the flight deck and to stay clear of the area.<br>
But Boatswain's Mate 3rd Class Joe Waddell, a native of Gainesville, Fla., is among the Sailors who head to the flight deck just in case.<br>
He's a nozzleman on the flight deck fire party's number one fire hose.<br>
"The fire party's main purpose is to stand by in case of a casualty during flight operations," Waddell said.  "We need to be ready to put the fire out and help injured personnel."<br>
This is Waddell's first major deployment with the ship and his first experience with RIMPAC.<br>
"The hours have been very long -- an average of 10 to 12 hours daily whenever we do vertical replenishment, and sometimes more than that," he said.<br>
Waddell also helps prepare cargo loads so they can be attached to the helicopters and taken to the other ships.<br>
"We work until midnight sometimes just doing that, then get up at 5 a.m. and start all over again," he said.<br>
<a href="aoe7mess.htm"><img src="aoe7mess.gif" align="right" height=261 width=400></a>
According to Rainier's flight deck safety officer, Boatswain's Mate Chief Petty Officer (SW) B. Krause, the ship has done as few as two vertical replenishments a day and as many as 700 in a day.<br>
"Sometimes one lift can be accomplished in under 30 seconds if it's all staged right prior to the lift," he said.  "Since RIMPAC began (on May 17), we've done approximately 1,500 vertical replenishments."<br>
There are just as many dangers during connected replenishments as there are during vertical replenishment, according to Electrician's Mate 1st Class Rollie Jara,  a Hawaii native and one of several on-deck safety supervisors during those operations.<br>
Jara and the other safety supervisors roam among six connected-replenishment stations aboard Rainier to make sure everyone is wearing safety equipment, including hard hats, goggles and life vests.<br>
"My job is to ensure that personnel who operate the winches, which transport the fuel hoses from our ship to the receiving ship, are doing things in a safe manner from start to finish," he said.<br>
One of the most crucial job during an underway replenishment is steering the ship since there's always the danger of a collision -- especially in bad weather.<br>
During underway replenishment, a master helmsman -- someone with at least 200 hours experience at the helm --  is called to steer the ship.<br>
Boatswain's Mate 3rd Class Robert Lekfield is such a Sailor.<br>
"A master helmsman has to keep the course within a half-degree at any time," explained Lekfield, a Tomahawk, Wis., native.<br>
Keeping these large vessels on such a precise, steady path is so difficult -- yet so important -- that Lekfield says he would be replaced with another master helmsman if he got "any more than a half-degree off course."<br>
U.S. Navy regulations state that ships stay 150 to 220 feet apart during an underway replenishment.  But other navies don't follow the same rules.<br>
"I was a little scared the other day when we had an Australian ship come (a little too close) alongside," Lekfield said.  "(But) after our captain told them to slide out a little bit we were fine."<br>
Lekfield has spent about 60 to 70 hours a week steering the ship during RIMPAC 96, but says every day brings a new experience.<br>
"Sometimes the steering wheel feels sluggish, like it doesn't want to cooperate," he said.  "Other times you might get rough seas or calm seas.  Either way, you still have to stay focused."<br>
And either way, with or without the fanfare, the fleet depends on ships like Rainier to keep it in business.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
