http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/tower.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108114028 text/html 5539
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:52:38 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>"Eyes" above Pearl Harbor keep ships moving </title>

<h1>"Eyes" above<br>
Pearl Harbor<br>
Keep ships moving</h1>
<hr>
<h3>by JO1 Catherine Kurchinski<br>
RIMPAC Combined Information Bureau</h3>

<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI., June 10, 1996)</strong> --  Ship horns are blaring.  Tugboats are steaming.  And this harbor is buzzing with activity.<br>
It's 9:30 in the morning at the Naval Station Pearl Harbor Control Tower and signalmen are on watch at one of the busiest harbor control towers in the Pacific.  With the world's largest maritime exercise going on -- RIMPAC 96 -- Pearl Harbor's Port Control Division is extra busy ensuring safe passage for the hundreds of ships and submarines moving in and out of the harbor. <br>
Today, the tower's status control board reveals 21 ships and 13 submarines in port.  Near the end of the exercise, the number of visiting ships and submarines is expected  to increase dramatically. <br><a href="smphtwr.htm"><img src="smphtwr.gif" alt="Sailor manages Pearl Harbor tower" align="left" height=246 width=400></a>
"During peak periods we'll have 44 'out-of-towners' and five additional subs," said Lt. Cmdr. Ira Stokes, who oversees the naval station's operations.  "Volume-wise we handle more ships and submarines than any harbor on the West Coast except San Diego.  We're a transit port, and we catch everything that goes out to the Pacific and everything coming back." <br>
Perched atop the tower some 161-feet high, the signalmen have a commanding view of the entire harbor. <br>
"We can see everything from (the entrance to Pearl Harbor) to Merry Point Landing," said Signalman 2nd Class (SW) Raymond Behnke. <br>
And with the tower's "Big Eye" binoculars, they can zoom in on anything within an 18-mile radius. <br>
"I love the view up here," Behnke said.  "It's the best place to watch the Fourth of July fireworks!" <br>
Twenty-five World War II veterans witnessed fireworks of a different kind from this tower. <br>
"Those guys had a front row seat of the bombing of Pearl Harbor," said Signalman 1st Class Kevin Wilson.  A wooden plaque engraved with their names was mounted in the tower in their honor. <br>
Keeping the tower operating around-the-clock demands two 12-hour shifts.  Signalmen  work three days, then get three days off. <br>
"We're pretty much married to the tower for 12 hours," said SM2 Paul Sauvie, a harbor control dispatcher who directs ship traffic.  The tower receives daily "move sheets" from Port Operations that list vessels arriving or departing that day. <br>
The dispatcher on watch then communicates with harbor pilots and tugboat craftmasters via marine-band radio to keep vessels steadily moving in or out. <br><a href="rnbowtug.htm"><img src="rnbowtug.gif" alt="a rainbow arches down to a fleet tug in Pearl Harbor" align="left" height=520 width=350></a>
"All the ships obtain permission from the control tower before they move," Sauvie said. <br>
Although he was trying to find a berth for a submarine involved in RIMPAC, "it's actually a quiet day today," he said.  "The phones are usually cranking and the radio blaring. <br> 
(The other week) I had my busiest day.  Between moving assets and ships, I coordinated 63 moves." <br>
Harbor Control Sailors not only direct harbor traffic, they are responsible for playing a recording of the national anthem during morning and evening colors. <br>
During RIMPAC, the national anthems of Australia, Japan, Canada, Chile and Republic of Korea must be played along with the United States' during morning colors. <br>
"This is a number one priority," says Wilson.  "If we mess this up, everyone on the base knows about it." <br>
Because of the number of songs, morning colors last nearly eight minutes.  A few Sailors have jokingly lamented the fatigue of saluting for such a long period under the hot Hawaiian sun. <br>
With the intense responsibilities associated with harbor control and the added burden of a major exercise, the pace in the tower can be pretty hectic. <br>
"The stress factor can go up," Wilson said.  "But we have to keep a cool head and be professional at all times.  We can't let the ships detect any of our stress because we're port control, and we have to be in control." <br>
<br>
<br>
<strong>(JO1 Catherine Kurchinski is a Reservist assigned to the RIMPAC Combined Information Bureau.)</strong>

<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
