<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC 96 Missile Exercise a success</title>

<h1> RIMPAC 96 Missile Exercise a success </h1>
<hr>
<h2> by JO3 Dean Nazario<br>
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h2>

<strong>( ABOARD USS ANTIETAM (CG-54) , June 9, 1996)</strong> -- A cruise missile skims the ocean surface at twice the speed of sound toward the guided-missile cruiser USS Antietam (CG-54).<br>
Inside the ship's dark combat information center -- a nerve center of computer consoles, radar screens and large multi-colored displays -- Petty Officer 3rd Class Jason Janco, a radar console operator, reports "Missile inbound." <br><a href="misslkln.htm"><img src="misslkln.gif" alt="after a missile launch Sailors clean launch system before next launch" align="right" height=516 width=350></a>
The ship's sophisticated SPY-1A radar is used to detect and track the incoming missile, launched from a land base less than five miles away. <br>
With only seconds to react, Sailors target the missile, and the anti-air warfare coordinator recommends to the missile systems supervisor that the ship fire upon the incoming threat.
The supervisor acknowledges, and the coordinator issues a "kill order." <br>
"Kill track number -- with birds." <br>
The supervisor presses the fire authorize button on his console, and the "bird" -- a Standard Missile 2 Block III -- blasts from a vertical tube in Antietam's deck near the bow. <br>
With a bang and a whoosh, the Standard Missile is on a collision course with the cruise missile. <br>
It's over in seconds.<br>
Target engaged and destroyed.  The ship can sail another day. <br>
This time the scenario was fictional, but the stress was real.  Antietam -- one of a dozen ships participating in a missile exercise off Kauai -- launched a real Standard Missile against a 22-foot-long, ramjet-powered target called a Vandal. <br>
"For RIMPAC, we were allotted four missiles to shoot -- three Standard Missile 2 Block IIIs (SM-2 Bk III) and one Harpoon," Antietam's commanding officer, Capt. William Doud, announced to his crew.  "The men in the ship's Operations and Combat Systems Department successfully launched all four weapons. <br>
"That's a big plus, and it's an unusual event for any ship to get to shoot that many weapons in such a short period of time." <br>
<a href="missile.htm"><img src="missile.gif" alt="sea sparrow launches from USS CUSHING (DD-985)" align="left" height=289 width=400></a>
Ships and aircraft from the United States, Canada, Australia and the Republic of Korea participated in the exercise, part of the biennial RIMPAC 96 exercise. <br>
U.S. units included USS Cushing (DD-985), USS Antietam (CG-54), USS Cowpens (CG-63), USS Reid (FFG-30), Helicopter Anti-submarine Squadron Light 43 (HSL-43) and HSL-47, Patrol Squadron 46 (VP-46), two F-14 Tomcats and two F/A-18 Hornets, and an EA-6B Prowler from Tactical Electronic Warfare Squadron (VAQ-135). <br>
Other participants included the Canada's HMCS Regina (FFH-334), HMCS Huron (DDGH-281), HMCS Winnipeg (FFH-338) and HMCS Algonquin (DDGH-283); Australia's HMAS Perth (DD-38), HMAS Newcastle (FFG-06), HMAS Sydney (FFG-03) and Royal Australian Air Force F-111Cs; and Korea's ROKS Cheju (FF-958).<a href="pmrfmisl.htm"> <br><img src="pmrfmisl.gif" alt="A lone PMRF worker walks beside a Vandal rocket being transported for launch" align="right" height=513 width=300></a>
The simulated enemy cruise missiles were launched from the Pacific Missile Range Facility (PMRF) at Barking Sands, Kauai, the world's largest instrumented, multi-environmental (subsurface, surface, air and space capabilities) range in the world. <br>
PMRF provided the "playground" for the forces to conduct their exercises using surface, aerial and subsurface targets, communications and data links, precision radar tracking and scenario control rooms. <br>
"During RIMPAC, we'll provide tracking information on exactly how close the target hits were," said Capt. Thomas Daniels, PMRF's commanding officer.  "Some of the weapons systems that are being tracked have telemetry, and when things don't go as planned, the telemetry data helps to explain why operations didn't work." <br>
Daniels stressed that safety is key during such exercises:  "You can't fire your missiles just anywhere.  You need a safe area.  That's why PMRF is one of the safest places to conduct these exercises.  We have the radar and telemetry coverage and the air assets to ensure that it's done in a very safe manner.  We can also ensure the firing zones are clear of any hazards so there are no incidents or mishaps." <br>
In the missile exercises, ships waited in an area called the "safety box," located a few miles south of PMRF between Kauai and Niihau.  They would then sail north to the engagement area to launch their missiles. <br>
A variety of scenarios took place. <br>
The destroyer Cushing, for example, fired a Sea Sparrow missile and destroyed a BQM-74E target drone that simulated an enemy cruise missile skimming above the ocean surface. <br>
In an anti-ship scenario, an SH-60 helicopter from HSL-43 launched its anti-ship Penguin missile and struck a floating target barge.  Cushing, Antietam, a RAAF F-111C and HMAS Newcastle launched Harpoon anti-ship missiles at the barge as well. <br>
In another surface-to-air scenario, seven ships cruised slowly through the missile range when two cruise-missile-like BQMs were launched at them from PMRF and two more were launched from a U.S. Air Force C-130. <br>
This was the first time Petty Officer 3rd Class Michael Lyon, a fire controlman aboard Antietam, launched a Standard Missile. <br>
"It was a rush watching the bird (SM-2) fly after I pushed the fire authorize button," said Lyon, who had practiced this scenario 15 times in simulation since RIMPAC started.  "I was the junior man in the work center and my supervisors felt I was capable of shooting a Standard Missile at a target, one of the most difficult scenarios in the (exercise)." <br>
In another exercise scenario, Antietam launched Harpoons at a floating target barge beyond the horizon with targeting support from U.S. Navy helicopters. <br>
"This was a 40-mile strike on the target, and it was a direct hit," said Lt. Cmdr. Dan Keller, Antietam's executive officer. <br>
Petty Officer 2nd Class Tim Sheriff, an operations specialist aboard Antietam, said,  "In a real wartime situation, we'd only have minutes, maybe even seconds, to launch a Harpoon at a hostile target." <br>
This was Sheriff's first time firing a Harpoon. <br>
In addition to the missile launches from the ships, air-to-air combat training also took place during the Missile Exercise. <br>
In four scenarios, F-14 Tomcats from the aircraft carrier USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63) fired about 20 missiles and destroyed an equal amount of BQM-74E target drones. <br>
In another exercise, an S-3 Viking, F/A-18 Hornets, EA-6B Prowlers, a P-3C Orion and F-14s launched Harpoon anti-ship missiles and other missiles to successfully sink a floating hulk, Jung Sheng 8. <br>
In a theater ballistic missile defense exercise, ships were to test their radars tracking two AQM-37C target drones launched from a U.S. Navy A-6 Intruder. <br>
The Aegis cruisers Cowpens and Antietam successfully tracked the targets' ballistic courses to record heights. <br>
The drone climbed to a record-breaking 235,000 feet, said PMRF Fleet Branch Head Stewart Burley.  "We never saw one of these target drones fly higher than 90,000 feet." <br>
This was the first such test during a RIMPAC exercise.  It was also the first RIMPAC with anti-ship Penguin missile shots. <br>
"RIMPAC 96 provides an opportunity for foreign nations to come to PMRF and test their individual defensive weapons systems safely so they may be able to defend their nation in the event of a real threat," Range Scheduler Thomas Thomason said. <br>
"Each nation requested a specific scenario and target to test their weapon systems so they could maximize their training." <br>
PMRF's flexibility to meet those requests makes it a valuable contributor to military exercises in the Pacific. <br>
"If they (other nations) meet their objectives, they may plan to participate again in the next RIMPAC," Thomason said.  "They may also want to come back to PMRF to test newly developed or advanced systems.  In turn, this advertises the range for us." 
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
