<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>USS ESSEX Impresses Admiral During Visit</title>
<h1>USS ESSEX Impresses Admiral During Visit</h1>
<h2>By JO2 David J. Myers</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Aboard USS ESSEX, Pacific Ocean, May 25, 1996 </strong> -- Everybody likes to show off just a little bit, and USS ESSEX (LHD 2) is no exception.  Recently, ESSEX had the opportunity to strut her stuff, and showcase how the "Gator Navy" works.<br>
This opportunity came about when RADM Peter A. C. Long, commander, Cruiser and Destroyer Group FIVE (COMCRUDESGRU 5), came aboard from USS ANTIETAM (CG 54) on May 25 to get a good look at what amphibious ships and their embarked Marines are all about.<br>
CAPT William J. Marshall III, Commander, Amphibious Group FIVE, Commanding Officer CAPT Thomas F. Radich, and 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit Commander Officer COL. Robert B. Blose, all greeted the admiral when he came aboard.<br>
They then took him to a briefing where they explained many of the elements of the Amphibious Task Group (ATG), and how it works.  The admiral was particularly interested in communications and data flow between the different elements of the ATG.<br>
<a href="lhd2eng.htm"><img src="lhd2eng.gif" align="left" height=274 width=400></a>
Long then toured the ship from the Combat Information Center to the well deck and by all accounts was impressed with what he saw.  According to Marshall, "His comments reflected nothing but admiration for (ESSEX') commitment to excellence and a strong appreciation of the combined strength of the Navy/Marine team."<br>
While that may sound like a mouthful, the upshot is the admiral was so impressed with the "Iron Gator" that he wants to come back again and observe how the ATG works from the back of an LCAC.<br>
Before he left, Long was presented with an ESSEX ballcap and a photo book, which included pictures of the ESSEX in action and photos from his own trip.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
