http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/usmcpay.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108114721 text/html 4652
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 11:59:28 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>ESSEX Marines Cash In On Payday</title>
<h1>ESSEX Marines Cash In On Payday</h1>
<h2>By J02 David J. Myers</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Aboard USS ESSEX, Pacific Ocean, May 25, 1996 </strong> -- Of all the things that Sailors and Marines look forward to, payday has to rank right at the top.  Now, through the efforts of the USS ESSEX and 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit's disbursing departments, payday for the Marines just got better.<br>
After a successful test program during RIMPAC '96, it looks like all shipboard Marines will be able to get paid through the ship's Automated Teller Machine (ATM) system during WESTPAC.  This is the first time ever that a continuous program has been set up to pay embarked Marines through the shipboard ATM system.<br>
<a href="marinpay.htm"><img src="marinpay.gif" align="right" height=274 width=400></a>
In a review conducted on May 20 by Navy Management Systems Support Officer (NAVMASSO) and Naval Supply Systems Command (NAVSUP), the ESSEX trial program was found to have worked perfectly.
USS HARPERS FERRY (LSD 49) and USS CLEVELAND (LPD 7), members of the ESSEX Expeditionary Amphibious Task Group, plan to implement the system for WESTPAC.  In the future, all ships will implement a similar system to ESSEX and this next generation pay system will revolutionize how service members are paid.<br>
Marines are already happy about the results.  SSGT Nathan Portman of the 11th MEU said the program, was "living up to all my expectations."  He added, "It's like having your own personal vault and a key to access it whenever you desire."<br>
Marines had been paid through shipboard ATMs before, most recently in the Atlantic fleet, but only on a non-permanent basis.  The ESSEX new program not only streamlines the process, but makes it easy to use on an ongoing basis.<br>
Much of the credit for the program, according to Disbursing Officer LTJG David B. Gartrell, goes to DK1 (SW) Felix Carranza.  Gartrell said that when Commanding Officer CAPT Thomas F. Radich asked if Marines could be paid through the ESSEX ATMs like Sailors were, the ESSEX Supply Officer, CDR Chris R. McKelvey, said "We can make it happen, Captain."<br>
"The goal," according to McKelvey, "was to device a process that is transparent to the customer, as well as the entire disbursing function, including automated data processing with the Marine Finance Activity in Kansas City.<br>
"Then," said Gartrell "Carranza took the ball and ran with it."<br>
Carranza looked for a procedure for the program.  Finding no official procedure, he simply created his own.  He then took his idea to NAVSUP, and after a meeting that included representatives from 11th MEU and Defense Financial and Accounting Service, Cleveland, sold them on the idea.  On May 15, the first 46 trial Marines were paid.<br>
Carranza said that the system requires close cooperation between the ESSEX and the Marines.  "They do 50 percent, and we do 50 percent."  Explaining how the system works, Carranza said, "The ship is like a bank.  The MEU opens an account with us by writing us a check, and then the Marines are able to withdraw their money."<br>
Of course, detailed record-keeping and careful cross-checking makes the system more complicated than it sounds, but the trial program went off without a hitch, and Gartrell expects the system to work well on WESTPAC.<br>
In yet another example of joint cooperation, the ESSEX/11th MEU team has found a way to make life easier for all.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
