<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>MILITARY SEALIFT COMMAND PUMPS LIFE INTO RIMPAC FORCES</title>
<h1>Military Sealift Command<br>
Pumps Life into RIMPAC Forces</h1>
<h2>By JO2 Jose V. Tolentino</h2>
<hr>
<strong>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii, June 21, 1996</strong> -- Gasoline powers a car and the four MSCPAC (Military Sealift Command, Pacific) ships do the same for the exercise RIMPAC (Rim of the Pacific) 96.  They provide the fuel, ammunition, and other resources, the staging area in the Pacific Ocean for this massive international naval training exercise.<br>
The MSCPAC participants included the USNS Guadeloupe (T-AO 200), USNS Walter S. Diehl (T-AO 193), USNS Assertive (T-AGOS 9), USNS Victorious (T-AGOS 19), and USNS Effective (T-AGOS 21).<br>
Since 1971, MSCPAC's 24-ship force has effectively carried out its replenishment function by providing Navy Fleet Auxiliary Force support to naval forces, Special Mission support to the Department of Defense, and Strategic Sealift to deploy and sustain U.S. forces in carrying out national objectives in the Pacific, Indian Ocean, and Persian Gulf areas.<br>
MSCPAC's direct support of fleet units in the Pacific allows Navy warships to remain at sea for long periods.  This replenishment function is carried out by MSCPAC's Naval Fleet Auxiliary Force and includes vessels such as fleet oilers, supply ships, an ammunition ship, fleet ocean-going tugs and ocean surveillance vessels.<br>
The special mission needs of  the Defense Department are met by specialized ships involved in laying and retrieving communication cables, tracking missiles, and oceanographic research.<br>
Underscoring the impact of RIMPAC to MSC personnel,  ship's master Captain Mark A. Payne of the oiler USNS Effective (T-AGOS 21), "It is important because it helps to continue the good relationships we have with our allies."<br>
With more than 44 ships, 250 aircraft, and 30,000 military personnel taking part in RIMPAC, the biggest challenge for MSC remains the planning of its support for the exercise.<br>
"We have to figure out what supplies ships want from us, what we can provide them, and whether we have enough to give out," said Operations Specialist Chief Petty Officer Doug Ruggles, Assistant Officer-in-Charge for the USNS Walter S. Diehl, one of 18 new Kaiser class oilers capable of storing 180,000 barrels of oil and fueling two ships simultaneously while underway.<br>
Once that equation is solved, MSCPAC can bring to bear the combined talents of its 1,800 civil service mariners.  Although a small number of military personnel serve aboard many of the command's ships, they serve primarily as communications support personnel.  The majority of the crew, from the captain down to the steward, are federal civilians.<br>
"MSC is the largest employer of merchant seamen in the country," said Borden.  "It offers excellent training, decent pay, civil service benefits,  new ship assignments every six months, and excellent training."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
