<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>PACIFIC MISSILE RANGE FACILITY SUPPORTS RIMPAC 96</title>
<h1>Pacific Missile Range Facility Barking Sands Supports RIMPAC 96 Missile Exercise</h1>
<h2>by JO3 Dean Nazario</h2>
<hr>
<strong>BARKING SANDS, Kauai, June 18, 1996</strong> -- Most of the major operations for Exercise Rim of the Pacific 96 would not be possible without the Pacific Missile Range Facility.<br>
Located on the western shores of Kauai, Hawaii, PMRF offers the military a "playing field" to conduct a number of training opportunities, including amphibious landings, missile launches and other coastal warfare operations.  The versatile facility also is used for testing and evaluating air, surface and subsurface weapons systems.<br>
PMRF commanding officer Capt. Thomas Daniels likens the facility to a football stadium:  "We provide a field in which ships, aircraft, ground troops and military members can train.  Like a football team, they need a field to play on that gives them feedback on what they're doing.<br>
"PMRF provides data and feedback so that we know from both training and (test and evaluation) missions exactly what happened and why it happened."<br>
The missile range provides feedback and other support to its users through radar, underwater instrumentation, telemetry and other sophisticated electronics.<br>
One of its facilities is the new Range Operations Control Center, which resembles NASA's Mission Control Center in Houston.<br>
Workers at three identical workstations use the Navy Tracking and Display System to monitor missile launches and coastal operations for exercises such as RIMPAC 96.  The tracking system uses state-of-the-art software and hardware to support real-time tracking and display, as well as data archiving and post-exercise analysis.<br>
"These computers maintain local underwater- and air-tracking data using conventional radar and video systems," Range Scheduler Thomas Thomason said.<br>
Operators are able to provide instant replay capability on video to let the ships know what occurred, how it occurred and to use the results to improve their training.<br>
"It lets them know of their performance almost immediately after their missile launch so they can learn from it and perhaps do better next time, or repeat the same success," Daniels said.<br>
"PMRF has an excellent geography to conduct missile exercises like the RIMPAC 96 (missile exercise).  It has high ridgelines that drop vertically off into the ocean."<br>
For example, Kokee Park, an elevation of 3,800 feet above PMRF, was used as a surrogate airborne platform during the Mountain Top Exercises early this year, which demonstrated an advanced concept technology in cruise missile defense using the Cooperative Engagement Capability (CEC).<br>
Its geography is rare, making the island a national asset.  Its lack of encroachment makes PMRF virtually free of commercial air traffic and ocean traffic.<br>
"We can ensure nearly 100 percent of the time, the range and the surrounding waters will not be inhibited by such traffic," Thomason said.<br>
Its 42,000 square miles of range provide wide open spaces to conduct a multitude of operations.  "PMRF is the only facility you can conduct subsurface, surface, air and space operations simultaneously," Daniels said.<br>
It has 1,000 square miles of undersea range.  By extending the undersea range close to the shore line, "it enables us to have a deep water to shallow water" undersea, anti-submarine warfare, capability, Daniels said.  "Right now, we only have a deep water practice facility for ships.<br>
"Some of today's systems will not work the same in shallow water as they do in deep water because of oceanographic phenomena," he said.  "When you transition from deep water to shallow water, you change the way you need to fight the battle."<br>
PMRF's $27 million shallow water testing range is scheduled for completion in 1997.<br>
"We don't conduct many spaceflight missions," Daniels said, "but we have the capability to track satellites and the space shuttle as backup to the main spaceflight tracking stations."<br>
Kauai's natural coastal environment and open ocean area supports theater missile defense (TMD) and theater ballistic missile defense (TBMD) operations.  "In TBMD, PMRF launches targets that fly into space and track their course of action back down to Earth," Daniels said.<br>
Moreover, PMRF is close to the rest of the Hawaiian military complex (on Oahu).<br>
It can support joint U.S. military operations like the recent CEC/Mountain Top exercises, as well as combined, or multinational, military operations like RIMPAC 96.<br>
In addition to PMRF's military programs supporting fleet exercises, it also has an aggressive environmental program of recycling paper, aluminum and green waste.  It also maintains a seabird nesting sanctuary for wedgetail shearwater, it uses approved lighting to avoid disorienting Newell shearwater, and provides a nesting habitat for the laysan albatross.<br>
There are 113 naval officers and enlisted members out of the total 918 people stationed at the facility, and Daniels is proud of every one of them.<br>
"We've got a phenomenal group of Sailors at PMRF," Daniels said.  "They're involved in many community service activities including the annual Waimea Town Celebration, the Adopt-a-School Program, the Toys For Tots Program and highway and beach cleanup.<br>
"Sailors also work on our aircraft and boats, keeping those assets operational for 100 percent availability," he said.  "In the past two years, we never lost a single mission due to lack of aircraft or target availability."<br>
For the facility's "good neighbor" contributions to the island, it has earned several awards.  April 1995 was proclaimed PMRF Month by the mayor for superior community service.  PMRF was named by the State of Hawaii Department of Education, Kauai District, as the Outstanding Business Education Partner of 1994.<br>
PMRF's origins date back 40 years ago when the Navy came to Kauai needing a place to test its Regulus I surface-to-surface guided missile.  Regulus I was introduced into the fleet in 1955, and remained operational until it was replaced by Polaris in 1961.<br>
Since 1958, PMRF has performed more than 6,000 major training and T&E operations.  Customers have included the U.S. military and foreign navies, NASA and many university and contractor research and development programs.  It is the lead range in the Pacific for Aegis cruiser Combat System Ship Qualification Training prior to its initial deployment.<br>
PMRF is one facility that was able to survive the military's drawdown.  "In the past couple years, there were fears that the Base Realignment and Closure Commission (BRAC) would close the facility," Daniels said.  "What resulted was the reverse.  The spotlight was put on PMRF highlighting all its unique features such as wide open spaces, lack of encroachment and natural geography.<br>
"In 1995, PMRF had more business than it has had since 1983, when a lot of money was being poured into the military," Daniels said.<br>
PMRF's economic impact on Hawaii totaled more than $100 million in Fiscal Year 1995.  More than 7 percent of that money was poured into the tourist industry.<br>
"Although we've been going through a downsizing over the past five years, 1995 was the biggest year we've had," Daniels said.  "That says people are recognizing the capabilities of PMRF and are coming here more often.<br>
"If we can support the fleet in providing them with the best possible training they could receive in a safe manner, that will be the real benefit -- a bonus to fleet readiness."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
