<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC CHALLENGES EOD PROFESSIONALS</title>
<h1>RIMPAC Challenges EOD Professionals</h1>
<h2>By JO1 Andy Wellman</h2>
<hr>
<strong>MARINE CORPS BASE HAWAII, Kaneohe, June 17, 1996</strong> -- We've got them, they've got them. Mines, bombs, missiles and other high explosive devices are in the military hardware inventories of every nation. No matter who has them they can be just as dangerous to their owners as to their targets.<br>
The joint service multi-national exercise, RIMPAC 96, being held in Hawaii is providing explosive ordinance disposal units with training that emphasizes the safe handling of wanted and unwanted explosives.<br>
One scenario played out during this biennial "war game" began as Marine Staff Sgt. Ken Couch of the Kaneohe Marine Base Explosive Ordinance Disposal (EOD) detachment reported a bomb to the exercise's EOD command post.<br>
At the other end of the line, members of the Australian Clearance Diving Team Four, encamped at a weapons storage depot across the island, were being dispatched.<br>
The information given in the report claimed several aircraft on the Kaneohe flightline had been destroyed and the one that remained had a canvas covered box on the floor of the cockpit.<br>
Inside the box was a booby-trap fashioned from a wind-up clock wired to a smoke bomb located in the back of the plane. It was set to go off three hours from the time the call was placed.  The parcel was placed by members of the Marines and Navy Training and Evaluation Units.<br>
In all, it took nearly an hour and a half for the team to pack their gear and drive 30 miles to the Marine base to begin work on the simulated bomb.<br>
At the scene the first task for Team Four was to question the caller who reported the explosions to determine everything he had done and seen since the bombings began.  Next they establish a  safety zone around the plane and the area where they would assemble their bomb disposal tools.<br>
One of the primary tools used to disarm bombs is a small cannon, called the RAKE (remote access kinetic entry device) by the Aussies.  The device is an 18 inch long tube which was filled with water. Once filled the tool is capped and an explosive charge is inserted into the other end.  The charge is set off electronically through long wires from a detonator set up a safe distance away, blasting the water into the bomb.<br>
The premise behind the tool's operation is that if you blow the bomb apart, faster than its internal circuitry can detonate its explosives, it can be handled safely.<br>
With the RAKE assembled and filled with water it was time to approach the aircraft.  For the purposes of RIMPAC the airframe of a old scrapped-out F-4 fighter was used.<br>
The clock continued to tick down.<br>
Australian Chief Petty Officer Terry Smith took the job of analyzing the parcel and placing the RAKE.<br>
After placing the RAKE in the jet, Chief Smith followed the wire running back to the detonator outside the danger zone. The warning "Stand Clear" was given and then a countdown began.  Five, four, three, two, one, BOOM!<br>
Cautiously Smith left from the safe zone and again climbed onto the wing.  After a few minutes he emerged from the cockpit and shook his head in disappointment.  The RAKE had not sufficiently spread the bomb's components and another attempt would have to be made.<br>
Chief Smith again returned to the safety zone to reload the water cannon and plan the next shot with the rest of his team.<br>
More than two hours and 45 minutes had now passed without the bomb being disarmed.<br>
Concern now spread among the evaluators over whether or not the Australians next attempt might involve some real danger should the booby-trap go off while the next RAKE was being placed.  The charge was small but could, as one evaluator put it, "ring his bell."  No one wanted to risk causing an injury for the sake of training.<br>
The observers debated and decided to let them continue but only a few ticks were left on the clock.<br>
As the Australian Chief was returning a rifle-like crack reported from within the cockpit. A stunned look flushed over the Chief's face as it was immediately apparent that time had run out.<br>
Observer Chief Warrant Officer Earl Dennis, of the U.S. Navy's San Diego Mobile Unit 7 spoke out. "Go ahead and lie down Chief. You're not dead but, if this were real, you would need to be medevaced."<br>
Hearing the blast Lt. Scott Craig, the Australian officer in charge hurried to the scene to carry the "wounded" chief back to the safe zone.<br>
All that was left for Team 4 to do was to phone the EOD command post to report the device had "high ordered" (detonated) and arrange for medical support.<br>
"We don't always win," said Couch.  "EOD is dangerous work, but exercises like this really help prepare you for actual situations."<br>
The evaluator raised questions on the tactics Team Four used, their sense of urgency and other decisions that might have changed the outcome. "We're not here to judge them," Couch says, "We tell them what we noticed and how we would have handled the different parts of the exercise."<br>
"There are many ways to handle bombs," says AOC Marc Bond of EOD Mobile Unit 7, "No matter what you do or how long it takes, if you beat the device you've won.  It just didn't happen today."<br>
The basic mission of EOD is to prevent a detonation and to protect life and limb to the utmost. That in mind the Australians and Americans headed into the Kaneohe Marine Base Hawaii's EOD office for more discussions behind closed doors.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
