<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Reserve Squadron Supports Special Operations During RIMPAC 96</title>

<h1>Reserve Squadron Supports<br>
Special Operations<br>
During RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>By JO1 Catherine Kurchinski</h2>
<hr>
<strong>Pearl Harbor, HI, June 14, 1996 </strong> -- 
In the cover of darkness, a U.S. Navy HH-60H  'Sea Hawk' helicopter lands in an abandoned sugar cane field on the island of Oahu. To the naked eye, the helo is nearly invisible. Outside of the aircraft, inside the cockpit and cabin, no lights can be seen. Night vision goggles are worn by the pilots and crew.<br>
Jumping out of the helo in quick succession are six Navy SEALS, armed with M-16 semi-automatic rifles. Jungle green paint covers their faces, revealing only the whites of their eyes. Hunched down, they scan their surroundings. Slowly and quietly, they move undetected through the field toward their target.<br>
These Navy SEALS are part of the Combined  Special Operations Task Force in Exercise Rim of the Pacific, or RIMPAC 96, being held in and around the Hawaiian Islands.  And helping SEALS to do their job are Reservists from Helicopter Combat Support Special Squadron 5 (HCS-5), Pt. Mugu, Calif.<br>
"Helicopter support for SEALS during special warfare operations is one of our primary missions," said Lt. Cmdr. Matt Ragan, a Naval Reservist and one of 34 pilots assigned to the squadron. "We take them wherever they need to go to perform their mission."<br>
HCS-5, along with its sister squadron, HCS-4, Norfolk, Va., perform combat search and rescue operations, as well as special warfare operations,  including inserting (delivering) and extracting (picking up) SEALS via a Special Patrol Insertion and Extraction Rig (a cable attached to the aircraft SEALS use to climb down during airborne operations), fast rope, parachute drops, and vertical shipboard search and seizure (SEALS landing aboard enemy ships.)<br>
This highly-trained, tightly-knit squadron of Reservists and TAR's (Training and Administration of Reserves) can deploy anywhere in the world within 72 hours, said Lt. Cmdr. Jeff Bright, squadron maintenance officer.<br>
During exercises such as RIMPAC 96, squadron members hone their skills and work  directly with their active-duty counterparts.<br>
"We had the chance to work with the Australian Special Forces for the first time," said Cmdr. Douglas Moret, squadron commanding officer. "It was both challenging and rewarding working through and resolving  the operational differences our two units encountered during this joint exercise. It was a priviledge and a pleasure to work with such a professional group."<br>
More than 40 ships from the U.S., Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea are involved in this year's exercise. Conducted every two years, RIMPAC improves coordination and interoperability of joint forces in maritime tactical and theater operations.<br>
Lt. Jeffrey Bowman, a Navy SEAL and operations officer at Seal Delivery Vehicle Team 1, Ford Island, said his unit has conducted seven operations so far with HCS-5. "They are serving a direct support role for insertion (landing) and extraction (picking up) of Special Operations Forces," Bowman said.<br>
Moret, an 18-year veteran who joined the squadron last year, said he's been "very, very pleased with his squadron's performance during RIMPAC 96.<br>
"The coordination has been good. The execution by everyone has been absolutely stellar. This is our second RIMPAC, so we have corporate knowledge from the first one, which is always helpful. The missions we've done thus far have been almost perfect."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
