http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/vp65ops.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108115358 text/html 7119
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 12:06:09 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>VP-65 aircrews support RIMPAC operations</title>

<h1>VP-65 aircrews support RIMPAC operations</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Denise Garcia<br>Naval Air Reserve Point Mugu, CA, Public Affairs Office</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(June 12, 1996)</strong> -- Naval Reservists from Patrol Squadron Six Five (VP-65) stationed at Naval Air Weapons Station Point Mugu, Calif., are in Hawaii completing their Annual Training in support of Rim of the Pacific (RIMPAC) operations 1996.  RIMPAC is one of the largest maritime exercise conducted by the U.S. designed to enhance interoperability with our allies.<br>
 VP-65 flies the turbo-prop P-3C Orion and is the only Reserve Force Squadron participating in RIMPAC that specializes in undersea warfare.  “The P-3 is the most flexible aircraft in the Navy’s arsenal,” said Cmdr. Richard Hayes, VP-65's Commanding Officer.  “It  performs undersea warfare, surface warfare, surveillance, reconnaissance, over-the-horizon targeting, radio communication relay, and just about anything the Task Force Commander can think of.”<br>
VP-65 and Japanese P-3 aircrews are training to ensure that they can work together in the event of a global crisis.  “Each mission is designed so that we always turn over to a Japanese P-3,” said Hayes.  “We take turns tracking submarines and ships.  During a shift change, we pass the target’s course, speed and position to the relieving P-3 so it can continue the surveillance.”<br>
How does the aircrew gather information to pass onto the Japanese P-3?  There are 12 crew members: three pilots, two navigators, two flight engineers, three sensor operators, one in-flight technician, and one in-flight ordnanceman.  Each play a significant role to successfully complete its assigned mission.<br>
The pilot is the aircraft commander.  He flies the aircraft and is responsible for its position and tactical operations.  “The pilot ensures the plane is positioned right so that the sonobuoys drop right, or the photographs are taken correctly, and so it can ultimately drop a weapon on a target,” Hayes said.<br>
At stations behind the cockpit, sit two navigators.  One is called the Tactical Coordinator (TACCO).  The TACCO develops a plan-of-action that will be most effective in carrying out the aircraft’s mission.  He analyzes the collected information from the aircrafts supporting stations and continuously monitors, reviews, and revises the plan-of-action as the situation dictates.  Although the pilot has final weapons release authority, the TACCO assists the pilot in determining what weapon to use, and where and when to release it.<br>
The Geographic Navigator, who sits next to the TACCO, uses charts and a computer to track the aircraft’s global position and its position in relation to the target.  “I’m not only the navigator,” said Lt. Cmdr. Roy Wesley, of El Dorado Hills, Calif.  “I also keep track of everything that goes into the computer, and print the information for post-flight analysis.”  The navigator is also responsible for all communication between other aircraft, ships, and the command center.  “I help the TACCO in keeping track of the tactical picture, too,” said Wesley.  “He does it electronically and I do it manually, so that we have a back-up in case the computer dies.”   <br>
Next, are the sensor operators.  The P-3s drop sonobuoys into the ocean which have microphones that record undersea noises.  Different submarines have different characteristics, and the two Acoustic Operators can identify a sub by the sound it makes in the water.  According to Hayes, the Acoustic Operators can also tell which country the submarine belongs to.<br>
The third sensor station is the Non-Acoustic Operator.  He operates the radar systems and the Magnetic Anomaly Detector (MAD).  “A submarine is a big iron object underwater which creates a disturbance in the earth’s magnetic field,” said Petty Officer 1st Class Ralph Santiago, an aviation warfare systems operator.  “When we fly over a sub, I detect the disturbance on the MAD system, and right then, we know where the sub is and we can immediately drop a weapon after positively identifying it as the enemy,” continued Santiago, who is from Poway, Calif.<br>
The aircrew can’t complete its mission without the In-Flight Technician (IFT) and the Flight Engineer (FE).  The IFT ensures the computer systems are working correctly.  “I’m usually the first person to the plane before a flight,” said Petty Officer 2nd Class Mark Krajeck, an aviation electronics technician.  “I turn on all the avionics and do some preliminary checks to make sure everything is functional, and I get the computer ready so when the crew boards they can immediately do their further, detailed station checks.”  Krajeck, who is from Camarillo, Calif., also said that during a flight, if all systems are working correctly, he assists in visually locating other aircraft and submarines.<br>
The FE is the pilots right-hand man.  He has a thorough knowledge of all systems and equipment in his control, and their operation during normal and emergency conditions.  “Before take off, I perform all exterior and interior systems checks, record who and how many people are on board, calculate the aircraft’s cargo and ensure the cargo’s weight is distributed evenly,” said Petty Officer 3rd Class Richard Trecero, an aviation electronics technician.  During the flight, Trecero monitors the engines and system flight station controls and indicators.  “If there are any malfunctions, the pilots looks to the FE to see what needs to be done to either continue the mission safely, or to return to base,” continued Trecero, who is from Pueblo, Colo.<br>
“Our Reservists’ performance is outstanding,” said Hayes.  “We’ve met all our mission and training requirements for Annual Training.  In doing so, we’ve worked closely with our ‘regular Navy’ counterparts and all the other RIMPAC participants to perform this exercise safely and professionally.”<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
