<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>

<center><h2> VP-65 Meets<br>
Maintenance<br>
Challenges</h2>
<h4>By JO2 Denise Garcia</h4></center>
<hr>
<strong>(Barbers Point, HI., June 13, 1996)</strong> -- 
The Naval Reservists of Patrol Squadron Six Five (VP-65) from Naval Air Weapons Station Point Mugu, Calif., recently arrived at Naval Air Station Barbers Point, Hawaii, to participate in Rim of the Pacific (RIMPAC) 1996 training operations.  RIMPAC is an integrated exercise which includes elements of all U.S. Armed Forces, and forces from Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and South Korea.<br>
VP-65 flies the turbo-prop P-3C Orion and is the only Reserve Force Squadron participating in RIMPAC that specializes in undersea warfare.<br>
Before leaving Point Mugu in mid-May for RIMPAC operations, the Maintenance Department "phased" four P-3s, which is an in-depth inspection of the aircraft.  All fluids and filters were changed, flight controls and engine components were lubed, and the planes were inspected for cracks, corrosion and leaks.  "We bust them down to parade rest and look them all over," said Chief Petty Officer Jo Klippel, the Quality Assurance Chief.  The process takes approximately three days to complete.<br>
Since arriving in Hawaii the squadron has logged nearly 200 flight hours.  This  schedule keeps the Maintenance Department running.  Teamwork and dedication play a critical role in the success of all maintenance evolutions.  VP-4, which is hosting VP-65, assists in briefing crews with current station policy and procedures.  "We brought most of our own parts," said Klippel, "but we've had to look to VP-4 for assistance, and we've used the base's parts pool.  Their support has allowed us to fly all our assigned missions."<br>
The maintenance personnel, or "maintainers," make up a 1/3 of approximately 80 Reservists currently performing their two-week Annual Training (AT).  "One of the biggest challenges the Maintenance Department faces is the transition from mission readiness training to real-time Fleet operations," said Lt. j.g. Todd White, the Maintenance Material Control Officer.<br>
"We've had repair tasks requiring two days to complete, encompassing multiple work shifts," White said.  "We have streamlined our shift schedules to provide around the clock support of flight operations and enhance squadron morale," continued White, who is from San Jose, Calif.<br>
"During the flight to Hawaii, one of the planes had to shut down an engine because metal was detected in the oil," said Petty Officer 1st Class Jim Ward, an aviation electrician's mate from Chatsworth, Calif.  "As soon as the plane landed we began to fix it."<br>
The P-3s carry a variety of sophisticated anti-submarine warfare equipment to detect, identify, and if necessary, destroy enemy submarines.  These systems always need to be cool.  With the temperatures and humidity factors in the 90s, the P-3s' air conditioning systems are working a lot harder and need frequent repairs.  "We've had to change three engine drive compressors," said Klippel.  Engine drive compressors in the air conditioning unit supplies air for pressurizing and cooling of the aircraft.<br>
"The biggest challenge for the administrative side of the Maintenance Department is keeping track of the aircraft status board," said Petty Officer 2nd Class Sherrie Cummings of Knoxville, Tenn.  Cummings, an aviation administrationman, uses the Naval Aviation Logistics Command Management Information System (NALCOMIS) to track the aircrews flight hours, aircraft readiness, part numbers and maintenance requirements.  "Everyone here is on the go," Cummings said, "and it's a challenge to log the correct numbers to properly reflect aircraft status.  These numbers are important so we can perform the proper maintenance on the aircraft," she continued.<br>
"We are thrilled to be at Naval Air Station Barbers Point to provide contributory support for RIMPAC '96," said Cmdr. Richard Hayes, VP-65's Commanding Officer.  "Many of our personnel are completing their two-week Annual Training, and I can't think of a better environment to obtain that training.  Our people and aircraft are ready for the best RIMPAC ever."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
