<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC 96: NEO training aids in real world missions</title>

<h1>Marines evacuate Americans:</h1>
<h2>NEO training aids in real world missions</h2>
<h3>by Cpl. Marc Ayalin, USMC</h3>
<hr>
<strong>(Kaneohe Bay, HI., June 11, 1996)</strong> -- The painful cries of injured and frightened American citizens echoed through the U.S Embassy compound in the fictional country of Pacifica June 10 and 11, as Marines and Sailors evacuated refugees from this war-torn island nation.<br>
The simulated Noncombatant Evacuation Operation was part of the RIMPAC '96 six- week training exercise for the 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit, who is preparing for an upcoming Western Pacific deployment in September.<br>
RIMPAC '96 is the largest Naval exercise in the Pacific. More than 30,000 Marines Sailors, Soldiers, Airmen and Coast Guardsmen representing the United States, Japan, Chile, the Republic of Korea, Australia and Canada were involved in the biennial event conducted in and around the Hawaiian Islands. <br>
"Currently, the Marine Corps is conducting a real world NEO in Monrovia, Liberia," said Capt. Scott Lopez, 11th MEU Public Affairs Officer. "Should this contingency arise for the Marines and Sailors of the 11th MEU during their deployment, they've had realistic training to successfully accomplish the mission."<br>
The 36-hour event involved more than 400 Marines and Sailors from the 11th MEU, including elements of India Company, 3rd Battalion, 3rd Marines and Combat Service Support Group-3.<br>
 Prior to the NEO, ethnic tensions between the governments of Pacifica and Capmid, a neighboring country desiring to unify both nations, began to escalate. A Capmidian-sponsored insurgency jeopardized the safety of U.S. citizens and third country nationals. As a result, the U.S. Embassy, its staff and the Military Survey Liaison Team from the 11th MEU were ordered to coordinate the evacuation with their Amphibious Task Group (USS ESSEX, USS HARPERS FERRY and USS CLEVELAND)counterparts positioned off shore. <br>
"Once this becomes a military operation, the ambassador would usually defer to military leaders and work together with them to accomplish the mission," said LtCol. Richard E. Jannell, executive officer, 11th MEU.<br>
Aboard the USS ESSEX, Marines and Sailors of Battalion Landing Team, 3rd Bn., 1st Marines, were tasked to execute the operation. Immediately, command elements of BLT 3/1 began planning their course of action. On land, insurgent Pacificans sympathetic to Capmid, showed their aggression by assassinating the mayor of a local town. This act posed a threat to the safety of U.S. citizens, therefore a small force from the ATG augmented the MSLT to provide added security at the embassy.  <br>
The Pacificans, some of whom were employees of the embassy, were unable to seek asylum in the U.S. This prompted them to vent their anger by conducting drive-by shootings on the embassy the night before the evacuation. <br> 
"The most important aspect is the security of the U.S. citizens and embassy personnel," said CWO2 Ed Coffer, Ground Defense Security Officer, 11th MEU. "The most difficult thing however, is unknown threats such as not knowing who the enemy is and what's his capability."<br>
The morning of the evacuation began unfriendly as more than a hundred riled protesters stood outside the embassy carrying slogans saying, "U.S. GO HOME!" The protest grew intense as Marine security forces told the crowd to return to disperse. Water balloons, soda cans and burned newspaper were launched from the crowd hitting Marines as they tried to avoid the falling objects.<br>
In order to pacify and disrupt the angry crowd's concentration, Marine reservists from the 3rd Civil Affairs Group, psychological operations detachment, Camp Pendleton, Calif., played a repetitive high-pitched wailing sound over a loudspeaker on the embassy roof. At first, efforts were effective as protesters began dispersing. However, they immediately regrouped after the sounds ceased.<br>
"If you really relay the right message and make your target audience passive, you can avoid armed conflict," SSgt. Jose C. Piedra, 3rd Civil Affairs Group, Camp Pendleton.<br>
Suddenly, the protest became a riot as the crowd broke through the wire barriers rushing the embassy's compound. The rioters nearly entered the embassy before being driven back by Marine sniper fire from the embassy rooftop. One rioter simulated getting hit in the leg and was carried away by two other rioters.<br>
Seconds after shots had been fired, the crowd began to flee the area. Within minutes the embassy grounds were silent. Broken glass and debris lay throughout the area as Marines assessed damage.<br>
Twenty minutes after the area was secure, the first wave of evacuees began to approach the already battered embassy. Families desperate to exit the country flocked to the front gate of the embassy. Some evacuees were injured from local insurgents out to assault U.S. citizens. <br>
To counter the threat of a Sapper attack, each individual was thoroughly searched for weapons or contraband before entering the embassy compound.  Inside the embassy, a medical triage site was set up to treat the injured. Emergency medical cases were first priority and were processed for immediate evacuation.<br>
In a timely manner, the refugees both able and injured, were bused to one of two evacuation control centers where processing continued. At the ECCs, individuals were categorized into different groups such as males and females under or over the age of 18, pregnant women or eligible family members of U.S. citizens. Afterwards, they were carried on several five-ton trucks to one of two extraction sites where Air-Cushioned Landing Crafts, Landing Craft Utility boats and CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters took them to one of the ATG ships. <br>
As the helicopters and landing crafts began leaving the sites, the Marines and Sailors of the 11th MEU began closing down. Soon the evacuees would be reunited with family and friends back in America.<br> 
<br>
<br>
<center>-USMC-</center>
<br>
<br>
