<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>P-3 SQUADRONS DO THEIR PART</title>
<h1>P-3 Squadrons Do Their Part to Make Sure the Pacific Rim is Secure</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Andrew Cramer</h2>
<hr>
<strong>BARBER'S POINT, Hawaii, June 10, 1996</strong> -- For threats on or beneath the sea, nothing beats a P-3C Orion aircraft, according to an Australian navy lieutenant who flies the four-engine turboprop.<br>
"The biggest thing for us as P-3 pilots to take away from RIMPAC is how the other countries crews operate their aircraft," said Australian navy pilot Lt. Gavin Sordelli.<br>
"We're all familiar with the capabilities of the other countries' aircraft, but the more we fly together, the more we see how each other handles day-to-day crisis, and the better pilots we become."<br>
The Australian squadron Sordelli is with, as well as P-3 squadrons from the United States and Canada, were in Hawaii as part of the multi-national force as part of RIMPAC 96.  The Japanese also brought one of their P-3 squadrons, and together with the U.S., make up the opposing bi-lateral force.<br>
The two other countries participating in the biennial exercise -- the Republic of Korea and Chile -- sent some P-3 air crews to observe operations and deployment strategies.<br>
"RIMPAC is very helpful, in that we get to put our P-3C through paces with our allies and all our ships on a single mission," said U.S. Navy Lt. Brad Dunham, a P-3C pilot with Patrol Squadron Nine (VP-9).<br>
"Basically, it allows us to become more competent with things we don't see and deal with that often, like another country's anti-submarine warfare tactics," said Dunham, whose squadron is stationed at Barbers Point Naval Air Station on Oahu.<br>
Having six countries involved in a month-long exercise would seemingly confuse things, but Lt. Scott Howell, another VP-9 pilot, said it doesn't.<br>
"The thing that unites all Maritime Patrol Aircraft (MPA) like the P-3 is that we all do things essentially the same all over the world," he said.<br>
"MPA level of professionalism is so high that we know without a doubt that we can do our mission together."<br>
Originally derived from the Electra passenger airliner, the P-3 has been in production for more than 30 years.<br>
It is a workhorse for nine nations, performing anti-surface and anti-submarine warfare missions, as well as search and rescue, maritime patrol and mining.<br>
Canada flies a modified version of the P-3C, the CP-140 Aurora, said Maj. Fred Bigelow, executive officer of Canada's 407th squadron.<br>
"A big difference between our aircraft and that of other P-3s is our CP-140 can't fire on an opposing ship or sub," Bigelow said.  "So for our part, we do surface surveillance and target anything we find for the American or Australian P-3s."<br>
The standard P-3C is equipped with AGM-86 Harpoon anti-ship missiles, torpedoes and depth bombs.  It also can carry two AIM-9L Sidewinder air-to-air missiles for `self-defense.'<br>
According to Bigelow, P-3 pilots, tactical officers, communicators and ground crew would agree that working in a busy theater with five other nations is a realistic scenario.<br>
"In the future, something like the (Persian) Gulf War or Bosnia-Herzegovina will always be another coalition environment," said Bigelow, "and therefore it is very necessary to work with as many of our allies on a regular basis as we can."<br>
The South American nation of Chile bought eight P-3A Orions from the United States in 1993.<br>
For its first RIMPAC, Chile's navy sent four pilots to observe P-3C flights, said Lt. Mario Folch, a pilot with Chile's navy.<br>
"Chile, and especially the Chilean navy, is making a great effort to operate on a wider scope in the Pacific," said Folch.  "Adding P-3s is just one way to do this."<br>
Flying with American and Australian aircrews has given Chile's pilots much-needed experience, he said.<br>
"Right now, we only use our P-3As for surface surveillance," he said.  "RIMPAC allows us to talk with our counterparts and trade information so we can expand our P-3A use to things like anti-submarine warfare in the future."<br>
Lt. Jorge Germain, a Chilean navy tactical officer, said flying with American and Australian P-3 crews has been useful.<br>
"Just working alongside the American and Australian crews and seeing how all of us do the same job has been very helpful to us," Germain said.  "The P-3 helps us increase our standing with other countries by giving us a larger role in the defense of the Pacific Rim."<br>
Royal Australian Navy flying officer Robert Tucker said learning about other countries' P-3s is important, especially when the aircrews have to work with one another in a crisis.<br>
"When a crisis develops somewhere in the Pacific, you aren't out there by yourself -- you have to use all the other forces from other countries," Tucker said.  "When we're all in the air like this at once, it can get pretty nasty if you don't know what you're doing."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
