http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/prince.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108115425 text/html 6613
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 12:06:35 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title> Two Princeton Sailors recall mine damage </title>

<h1>Two Princeton Sailors<br>recall mine damage</h1>
<hr>
<h2>By JO1(SW) S.A. Thornbloom<br>
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office </h2>

<strong>( PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii, June 7, 1996)</strong> -- On Feb. 18, 1991, at 7:16 a.m., the crew of the guided-missile cruiser USS Princeton (CG-59) was rocked from their morning routine after two Iraqi mines exploded beneath the ship in the Persian Gulf during Operation Desert Storm.<br>
For Operational Specialist 1st Class Bryan Pacheco, the shock of seeing light flashing through a gash in the ship's overhead is as bright today as the sun shining above him here in Hawaii. <br>
"I was in berthing and the vivid thing I remember was seeing daylight when I looked up because there was a crack on the quarterdeck," said the Las Vegas native, who today is the leading petty officer in Princeton's Combat Information Center (CIC). <br>
Lt.j.g. Gerald Papenfuss, who was an operational specialist chief and the watch supervisor in the ship's CIC that morning, remembered "a lot of confusion." <br>
"The lights went out and the ship went dark," he said.  "We had everything happen from flooding to the weapons system going down and a loss of steering." <br>
The two Princeton crewmembers, who left the ship for other commands shortly after returning home from the Persian Gulf War, are back on board the Ticonderoga-class Aegis cruiser participating in RIMPAC 96. <br>
The Princeton, fully recovered and repaired from the devastating mine damage, is the flagship for the Multi-National Force in the biennial exercise that involves six rim-of-the-Pacific nations. <br>
Standing near the aft Harpoon missile tubes, Pacheco and Papenfuss looked back on that unforgettable morning when the two "bottom-influence" mines exploded beneath their ship.  Such mines are designed to detonate beneath a ship, buckling the hull. <br>
As they looked at the deck that Pacheco says looked like "a giant pair of pliers had been taken to it," they agreed it was probably the crew's training that saved Princeton. <br>
"You can't say enough about how much training you can do on firefighting and dewatering," said Papenfuss, from Toledo, Ohio.  "People that go to training that haven't experienced anything like that think that half the time they're just walking through the motions.  When it comes down to doing it they're really pretty thankful they know exactly what to do.  It ends up saving a lot of lives." <br>
The pair also recalled how the crew's training clicked in automatically as the they fought to repair the damage to keep the ship afloat. <br>
"On the way over (to the gulf) we had trained and trained so everyone's response was pretty reflexive," said Papenfuss.  "They just ran and did what they normally did during training." <br>
The crew's discipline and the fact they look out for each other also helped prevent a lot of casualties, Pacheco added. <br>
"We only had a few cuts and bruises," he said.  "The only major casualty was to our bow mine watch, who was flipped over and cut an artery in his neck and shattered one of his knees." <br>
After the crew did what they could to get the damage under control, the ship was towed to Bahrain for further assessment and to be shorn up by USS Jason (AR-8).  The repair ship welded I-beams onto the main deck and along the sides. <br>
"Everybody went to work to try to get the ship in the best condition we could," said Papenfuss. <br>
The cruiser was then towed to a dry-dock facility in the United Arab Emirates for two months of further repairs.  While in dry-dock, the damaged portion of the hull was cut away and replaced so the ship could leave the gulf ahead of the battle group, slowly steaming under its own power for its San Diego homeport, Papenfuss said. <br>
"We went ahead because we had to go at a slower speed," he said.  "But the battle group did catch up with us so we could all arrive back home together." <br>
After returning home Princeton faced several more months of extensive shipyard repair.  Cracks to the superstructure had to be fixed.  Decks had to be replaced.  The tubes to the aft Harpoon missiles were realigned and the propeller shafts were straightened. <br>
It was a job that showed how important shipyard facilities are to the Navy, according to Lt. Cmdr. Matthew Sharpe, Princeton's current executive officer. <br>
"Princeton is here (today) because damage control happened effectively and because we have the industrial facilities, the skills and the dedication to be able to build and repair ships.  We should recognize the importance of that capability in the role it played in Princeton coming back on line and the role it plays in the future." <br>
Both Gulf War veterans and Princeton's present crew share a sense of pride of where the ship has come from the terrible damage it suffered five years ago.  According to Sharpe, the ship is "better than new today" because of the experience gained and remembered from the mine hit. <br>
"Princeton, more than most, has an appreciation for warfare and damage control readiness," he said.  "If anything the mine hit brought that into focus." <br>
Sharpe added "the memory of that drives us to a higher damage control standard" and proves how that standard enables Princeton to continue to be; a front-line ship today ready for any mission and a valuable asset to exercises like RIMPAC 96.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center>
<table border=0 cell padding=15 width=70%>
<tr>
<th><A HREF="/rimpac.htm"><img src="anchor6.gif"><h5>RIMPAC 96<br>Homepage</h5></A></th>
<th><A HREF="/r96prels.htm"><img src="anchor6.gif"><h5>RIMPAC 96<BR>News Releases</h5></A></th>
<th><a href="r96advis.htm"><img src="anchor6.gif"><h5>RIMPAC 96<br>Advisories & Memoranda</a></h5></A></th>
