<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Oil cleanup lessons spill over to RIMPAC 96</title>

<h1>Oil cleanup lessons spill over to RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>By JO1(SW) S.A. Thornbloom
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI., May 31, 1996)</strong>-- The black oily crude that crept through and congealed in Pearl Harbor in this month didn't put a stop to RIMPAC 96 or daily Navy operations.  But it did start organizers and Naval Base officials thinking about the what-ifs and what-to-dos if a Navy oiler had run aground during this year's exercise instead of a pipeline breaking at Chevron's Waiau facility.<br>
At a conference in Pearl Harbor Naval Shipyard's auditorium last week, officials discussed the recent spill, the lessons learned and how to apply those lessons to future spills that involve the Navy.<br>
"What happened to Chevron could happen (again),'' said Carolyn Winters, a spokeswoman from the Naval Base Environmental Office and coordinator of the conference.<br>
Winters said the Navy has fuel pipelines adjacent to Pearl Harbor and is responsible for Navy and merchant tankers in the harbor.  The Navy also maintains several bulk storage facilities on the Naval Station.<br>
This is why oil-spill response training is always scheduled to be a key component of the exercise.<br>
"What we planned was an area-wide, Naval Base-level, table-top exercise with equipment deployment," Winters said.  "(But) we postponed the oil spill exercise specifically because of the real thing that happened on May 14."<br>
The Naval Base intends to hold a large exercise later this year, she added.<br>
According to Winters, the environmental office and RIMPAC officials were planning to hold a large scale oil spill drill.  The plan had called for the involvement of a fleet vessel, major area Navy commands and participation by elements from Third Fleet.<br>
"The benefit of holding it (the drill) during RIMPAC was to get that fleet involvement," said Winters.  "Third Fleet has also expressed they're interest in elevating environmental concerns and issues within the fleet.  So, ideally, it would have worked well to hold it when we have maximum fleet participation."<br>
During the actual spill last month, several local units did get a chance to participate and see what it's like to respond to a potential environmental disaster.<br>
"We lent out a lot of oil booms, the services of all our crafts and about 15 to 20 people to the cleanup operation,'' said Chief Warrant Officer Mark Pierson, Salvage Department head for Mobile Diving and Salvage Unit 1.  "Oil spills in general are not a part of our mission but in this case we were available and willing to help."<br>
MDSU-1 normally works at salvaging damaged ships that have run aground or have sunk, but according to Winters they were a tremendous help during the Chevron spill.<br>
"They play a double role,'' she said.  "They've got wonderful diving and salvage expertise and then that 'can do' attitude.  So, having a strong team (like MDSU-1) to supplement the rest of the Navy commands is great; you couldn't ask for more."<br>
But becoming a strong team means training and RIMPAC plays an important part in providing an exercise big enough for MDSU-1 to ply their trade.<br>
"The big part (of RIMPAC) is the learning phase and once you get through the learning phase then everything else will just fall right into place," said Hull Technician 1st Class Donovan Motley, who explained that in RIMPAC, MDSU-1 was scheduled to salvage a ship that had sunk and was blocking the harbor.<br>
And salvaging a ship that has sunk or run aground means emptying the ship of fuel or oil to lighten the vessels to raise or move it.  To many MDSU-1 members, that's why they get calls to respond to harbor spills.<br>
"Right here at this point of the harbor, (on Hickam Air Fore Base) we're the quickest asset the Navy has for an oil spill,'' said Motley.<br>
To MDSU-1 commanding officer, Cmdr. Mike Freeman, being able to respond quickly when called upon is extremely important to the entire ecological balance of Pearl Harbor and a concern for everyone who travels around it.<br>
"It's very important to the environment. Whenever there's quick response to save a ship that's run aground or had a collision with another ship we're here to take care of those ships.  We're well trained and we practice those skills routinely so that when they need us we're ready," said Freeman.<br>
Being ready is also one of the major lessons learned at the conference, and according to Winters.  Another is becoming "one Navy" on the afloat and shore sides so that everyone is working as one unit to combat and manage the spill, she said.<br>
"So we need to train, exercise and always be ready to respond to a spill in a very effective manner."<br>
Winters hopes Sailors will remember the ugliness of the slick and thick, black sludge creep toward the Arizona Memorial and Naval Station and why it's important to the environment for everyone "to respond quickly and go to war against this type of disaster."<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
