<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>USS Princeton a temporary workplace For five nations' sailors</title>

<h1>USS Princeton a temporary workplace for five nations' sailors</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Andrew Cramer<br>
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI., June 5,1996)</strong>--From the pier and even onboard, the USS Princeton (CG-59) looks like just about any other Aegis cruiser.  But a closer look reveals sailors in uniforms very different from the U.S. Navy's and even languages not usually heard aboard a U.S. ship.<br>
That's par for the course, however, for the headquarters ship of RIMPAC 96's Multi-National Force (MNF).<br>
The MNF commander, Royal Australian Navy <a href="ranaobio.htm">Rear Adm. Chris Oxenbould</a>, is guiding U.S., Australian, Canadian, South Korean and Chilean forces from aboard the guided-missile cruiser for the duration of the roughly month-long exercise.<br>
The RIMPAC scenario has the Multi-National Force in opposition to a bi-lateral force composed of U.S. and Japanese assets.<br><a href="r96bout2.htm"><img src="r96bout2.gif" alt="ROK-U.S. Sailors on Princeton" align="right" height=230 width=343></a>
Advance teams from the various countries started arriving May 18 to transform Princeton into a suitable staff headquarters, said Royal Canadian Navy Lt. David Cooke, a battle watch officer on the Princeton.<br>
"It was kind of slow getting set up, trying to keep track of everything and figuring out who was going to do what," Cooke said.  "The U.S. folks had classes set up to help us learn how their systems worked, like for message traffic and communications, and that was very helpful."<br>
Having a versatile command ship like USS Princeton ready to work makes an important exercise like RIMPAC easier to handle, said Chilean navy Lt. Fernando Contreras, another of the MNF's three battle watch leaders.<br>
"Chile does many exercises that are important to us, but RIMPAC is more important because it involves so many more nations," Contreras said.<br>
This is the first time the South American nation is participating in RIMPAC, which started in 1971.<br>
"Anytime we can improve our skills, we try to make the most of it," Contreras said.  "It is nothing but a good thing to get to know people of other navies, because both of us learn, grow and improve as a result."<br>
There's also much to be gained on a personal level as well, sailors say.<br>
Once U.S. Navy Chief Operations Specialist (Surface Warfare) James Chantland started talking to and getting to know the other navies' sailors, no one seemed so foreign anymore.<br>
"There's not that much of a difference between us when you get right down to it," he said.<br>
South Korean battle watch officer Lt. j.g. Lee Sunz-Han said South Korea has participated in the biennial exercise since 1990, but this is his first RIMPAC and things were really confusing the first few days.<br><a href="mnfpos.htm"><img src="mnfpos.gif" alt="U.S. & Chilean Navy Sailors" align="left" height=421 width=300></a>
"Getting to know everyone and how things work on a staff command was the most difficult part," Lee said.  "Now that I do understand, thanks to the U.S. Navy crew and other officers from all countries involved, things are going much smoother.<br>
"For example, when there was a word or phrase I did not understand, one of my new shipmates was always there to help me through."<br>
USS Princeton isn't really set up specifically to be a command ship, Chantland said.<br>
"A big reason behind us being chosen was scheduling," he said.  The cruiser finished its last deployment to the Persian Gulf in October 1995.<br>
The ship also has a large communications suite and enough extra room for all the meetings, he added.<br>
That extra room and great communications set-up is what made USS Princeton ideal for the command ship platform, said Royal Australian Navy Lt. Cmdr. John Rourke, also a battle watch officer.<br>
"We need to maintain good feedback with all the ships out at sea," Rourke said, "and (those) ships tell us that the communication has been good."<br><a href="cg59fact.htm"><img src="cg59.gif" alt="USS Princeton (CG 59)" align="right" height=255 width=400></a>
Technology aside, "there have been a few teething problems as far as languages and different interpretations of the same word go," he said.  "But we are working well together."<br>
Rourke credits Princeton's crew with enabling the different nations to work together so well.<br>
"They really bent over backwards for us and have given more than they should have."<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
