<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Multi-national group of Navy Meteorologists participate in RIMPAC 96 </title>

<h1>Multi-national group of Navy Meteorologists participate in<br>RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>by JO3 Dean Nazario
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI., June 5, 1996)</strong>-- One of the keys to RIMPAC 96's success is beyond anyone's control: The weather.<br>
But that doesn't mean it's being ignored.  On the contrary, it is being continuously monitored by folks at the Naval Pacific Meteorology and Oceanography Center (NAVPACMETOCCEN) Pearl Harbor.  <br>
During the exercise, U.S. Navy and Royal Australian Navy personnel will be continuously watching for storms and rough seas and reporting this data 24 hours a day to the participating ships at sea.  A large portion of RIMPAC's mission success relies on what the forecasters tell the fleet.<br>
"There are two different cells (of forecasters)," said Royal Australian Navy Lt. Cmdr. Craig Roy. "One is the Combined METOC Forecasting Unit, sponsored by  NAVPACMETOCCEN, set up to support the (Multi-National Force and Bi-Lateral Force).  They're producing area forecasts and tactical forecasts for both forces upon request."<br>
The other cell consists of seagoing meteorological and oceanography representatives, said Roy, combined METOC officer for the Multi-National Forces (MNF) and oceanographer with the Australian navy's Maritime Headquarters.<br>
Representatives are onboard HMAS Perth (DDG-38), HMCS Algonquin (DDGH-38), USS Essex (LHD-2), USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63), USS Cushing (DD-985), USS Cowpens (CG-63) and USS Kamehameha (SSN-642).  Some are also stationed at Special Operations Task Force on Ford Island, Naval Air Station Barbers Point and Hickam Air Force Base.<br>
"The attachments we have at sea come from the U.S. Navy, the Royal Australian Navy and the Canadian navy," Roy said.  <br>
There are several products established for RIMPAC, including a homepage set up by the center to provide real-time information for safety and tactical purposes, he said.  <br>
There are also a number of special tactical oceanographic information charts to give amphibious forces and ships operating in coastal waters highly detailed information about particular landing areas.<br>
"Satellite photographic imagery on coastal areas helps enhance meteorological and oceanographic features," said Lt. Cmdr. Bruce Hagaman, staff oceanographer for Commander, Cruiser Destroyer Group One, stationed on the San Diego-based aircraft carrier USS Constellation.  "(Oceanographic) experts add known features such as currents, tides and shoals, and put that together on a large color photographic image of the coastal area to be used in amphibious warfare planning or other coastal activities."<br>
This data is provided to all the players -- the Marines, the Mine Warfare/Explosive Ordnance Disposal Teams, the Special Operations Task Force -- so they can plan different operations throughout the course of RIMPAC.<br>
Roy and Hagaman are working together for the first time in RIMPAC exercises.  The Australian navy and U.S. Navy meteorologists have joined together to learn how each other operates and look forward to improving their weather forecasting techniques. <br>
"We're developing a very good rapport with other nations," Roy said.  "There's (an Australian navy) officer working closely with a U.S. Navy officer; and both navies are also integrating with the Canadians, South Koreans and Chileans as well.<br>
"We hope to learn from each other and become better trained after the exercises to handle any joint or combined contingency."
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
