<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Reservists Provide 'Real World' Support for RIMPAC 96</title>

<h1>Reservists Provide 'Real World' Support for RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>By JO1 Catherine Kurchinski
RIMPAC Command Information Bureau</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(HICKAM AIR FORCE BASE, Hawaii, June 5, 1996)</strong>-- Naval Reservists are playing a key role in the largest maritime exercise in the world -- RIMPAC 96. Members of three Naval Overseas Air Cargo Terminal Units (NOACT), and VP-66, Willow Grove, are keeping the logistics pipeline flowing for more than 40 ships from six Pacific nations, including the U.S., Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and the Republic of Korea. NOACT units involved are NOACT E208; NOACT G113, Springfield, Mo.; and NOACT C213, Lincoln, Neb. NOACT E208 arrived in May to help establish a Forward Logistics Support Site, based at Hickam Air Force in Honolulu, Hawaii.<br>
"We deliver cargo, mail, personnel and repair parts to the fleet," said Lieutenant Commander Tom Welke, skipper of the Atlanta unit. "Mail and repair parts are delivered within 24 hours to the ships involved in the exercise. Sailors are particularly happy to receive mail on a timely basis."<br>
<a href="malhndlr.htm"><img src="malhndlr.gif" align="left" height=461 width=300></a>
Welke's unit handles some 7,000 pounds of mail and 60,000 pounds of cargo daily. RIMPAC 96, conducted every two  years, improves coordination and interoperability and joint forces in maritime tactical and theater operations.<br>
"This is an outstanding training opportunity for all NOACT personnel; it allows us to provide substantial real-world support," said Welke. <br>
Providing support to forward Navy installations and deployed ships is not new for Naval Reserve NOACTS. During Operation Desert Shield/Storm, five NOACTS performed missions at Forward Logistics Support Sites in Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Egypt. NOACTS proved critical in supporting air cargo operations at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, during Haitian and Cuban refugee crises in 1994. <br>
Because of past successes and increased visibility, the number of NOACTS increased from five in 1991, to 13 today. Two Naval Reserve NOACTS are located in Atlanta; others are based in Charleston, S.C.; Greenville, S.C.; Knoxville, Tenn.; Lincoln, Neb.; Omaha, Neb.; Minneapolis, Minn.; Savannah, Ga.; Kansas City, Mo.; Springfield, Mo.; Sacramento, Calif.; and Oklahoma City, Okla.<br>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Editor's Note:  The reserve units participating in RIMPAC 96 are from Atlanta, GA., Springfield, MO., Lincoln, Neb., and Omaha, Neb.</strong>

<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
(Catherine Kurchinski is a Naval Reserve Journalist assigned to the Navy Public Affairs Center Unit 106, Norfolk, Va.)
<br>
