<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>

<h1>RIMPAC 96 Bi-Lateral Forces suspend all live-fire training</h1>
<h2>Safety review affects Japanese-U.S. portion of six nation exercise only</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI, June 4, 1996)</strong> --Japanese and some of the U.S. Naval forces operating in the Central Pacific in Exercise RIMPAC 96 have suspended all live fire training events following the accident involving an A-6 Intruder yesterday.<br>
The Independence Battle Group and the nine Japanese ships participating in the Bi-Lateral Force portion of the exercise are conducting a safety review until an investigation of the mishap is complete and a cause of the accident is determined.  Safety is the number one priority in Exercise RIMPAC 96 and is paramount in the conduct of all operations associated with the exercise.<br>
Training, including live fire exercises, are scheduled and will be conducted by others participating in the Multi-National Force portion of RIMPAC 96.  These forces include U.S., Chile, Australia, Canada, and the Republic of Korea.<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
