<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/a6accdnt.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108115507 text/html 3590
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 12:07:17 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>A-6E involved in gunnery exercise accident</title>
<h1>RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>A-6E Intruder involved in ship-to-air gunnery exercise accident</h2>
<h3>Pilot and navigator eject safely as plane crashes in Pacific</h3>
<hr>

<strong>(Pearl Harbor, Hi., June 4, 1996)</strong>--A U.S. <a href="http://www.navy.mil/navpalib/factfile/aircraft/air-a6.html">A-6E "Intruder"</a> jet aircraft towing a target for ship-to-air gunnery practice apparently was damaged inadvertently by gunfire from a Japanese destroyer and crashed
in the Pacific Ocean about 1,600 miles west of Hawaii.  Both crew members of the aircraft ejected and were recovered in good condition.<br>
The accident took place at 4:15 p.m. local time, June 3 (7:15 p.m. in Hawaii and 1:15 a.m. EDT, June 4) in the course of a mid-Pacific exercise called “RIMPAC 96.”  Five “rim of the Pacific” nations besides the United States are taking part in this training from May 22 through June 21.  The officer in overall command of the exercise is Vice Adm. Conrad C. Lautenbacher Jr., U.S. Navy, commander of the U.S. Third Fleet.<br>
The accident involved the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force ship <a href="dd153.htm">JDS Yuugiri</a>, a 450-foot long, 3,550-ton destroyer engaged in training with other Japanese and U.S. ships as they move from Japan toward waters off Hawaii.  The A-6 aircraft was assigned to Attack Squadron 115 operating from the aircraft carrier USS Independence.  The ship and squadron are
forward-based in Japan and are among the U.S. forces taking part in RIMPAC.<br>
When the accident occurred, the aircraft was towing a target drone -- a missile about 5-feet long and a foot in diameter -- for gunnery practice by Yuugiri’s <a href="http://www.navy.mil/navpalib/factfile/weapons/wep-phal.html">close-in weapons systems</a>, a high rate-of-fire gun.  The crew of the A-6 lost control of their aircraft.  They ejected successfully and were picked up by a small boat from the Japanese ship.  With no serious injuries, they subsequently were transferred by helicopter back to the carrier Independence.<br>
The pilot’s name is Lt. Cmdr. William E. Royster, 33, of Kansas City, Mo.
The bombadier/navigator is Lt. Keith A. Douglas, 30, of Birmingham, Ala.<br>
U.S. and Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force authorities are investigating the accident.<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
