<title>RIMPAC 96 players meet for a different kind of war games</title>

<h1>RIMPAC 96 players meet for a different kind of war games</h1>
<h2>by PH1 William R. Goodwin<br>
Naval Base Pearl Harbor Public Affairs</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, HI., May 31, 1996)</strong>-- Pearl Harbor's Richardson Field caught fire last week.<br>
However, there were no fire trucks needed. This fire was put out with Gatorade. <br>
Chile's "red-hot" soccer team from CS Lynch (FF 07) "burned" a determined Australian HMAS Perth (DDG 38) soccer team in the final minute of the RIMPAC Soccer Tournament's championship game. Lynch's Cpl. Juan Valencia kicked the winning goal to defeat the "Aussies" in a midday sun that threatened to take victims of its own.<br><a href="soccer2.htm"><img src="soccer2.gif" alt=" RAN defender kicks the ball past Chilean player" align="right" height=293 width=400></a>
Sportsmanship prevailed over the "heat of competition" when the gracious Chilean victors chanted and clapped as the Perth team received their second place trophies. "It was very difficult because the Australian team as you know are very physical," said Pedro Tirapegui Ceron, a Lynch player. "They were also very friendly and they played fair."<br>
Soccer was only one of the five sporting events that "ignited" Pearl Harbor for this year's istallment of RIMPAC Sports Tournament, sponsored by MCI Telecommunications. One-hundred and four teams representing six countries clashed in basketball, softball, sand volleyball, indoor volleyball and soccer. <br><a href="soccer1.htm"><img src="soccer1.gif" alt="U.S. player headers ball past RAN defender" align="right" height=338 width=320></a>
"The competition was fierce," exclaimed Frank DelGaudio, Fleet Recreation Coordinator since 1986, who dashed from event to event to hand out trophies. "Each RIMPAC, the players seem more intense than the previous one. It's amazing that many of the teams are formed just to compete in this tournament and show a tremendous ability to come together and work as a team. If the actual RIMPAC exercise is anything like this, I believe the participants take their work very seriously."<br>
About the same time the soccer championship was decided on Richardson Field, Bloch Arena was "set ablaze" when USS Cimmaron's (AO 177) basketball team "extinguished" any hope USS Essex's (LHD 02) had of a victory in the basketball final. Cimmaron worked their way past 24 teams and beat Essex 41 to 32 in the championship.<br>
"They (Essex) beat us twice earlier in the season," said Engineman 3rd Class John James. "We went into the semi-finals as the underdogs, but we didn't feel that way. We played at the top of our game and came out on top, because we did a good job on defense."<br><a href="bsktball.htm"><img src="bsktball.gif" alt="Fast break" align="left" height=360 width=250></a>
Other RIMPAC tournament highlights included a softball championship that was hard for the USS Harpers Ferry (LSD 49) team to pull off against USS Lake Erie's (CG 70) team, but the 15-11 victory over the Lake Erie team yielded a handsome first-place trophy for the Harpers Ferry team.<br>
USS Leftwich's (DD 984) 4-man Sand Volleyball team spiked, blocked and dug their way to a 11-2, 9-11, and 11-7 victory over the PMT/CSS-1 team to "net" a first-place finish.<br>
Subase Gym became a "towering inferno," when USS Willamette's (AO 180) Indoor Volleyball team "snuffed out" USS Ingersoll's (DD 990) eight-man volleyball team.<br>
RIMPAC '96 is a communication and coordination exercise. RIMPAC '96 Sports Tournament was more than "just exercise" for the 500 "fired-up" participants.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<strong>Statistics provided by Frank DelGaudio, Fleet Recreation Coordinator</strong><br>
