<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title></title>

<h1>Marines lend a hand in Waimea</h1>
<h2>School playgrounds, WWII Marine memorial, local food bank benefit</h2>
<h3>by Cpl. Marc Ayalin, USMC</h3>
<hr>
<strong>(Pohakuloa Training Area, HI., May 27, 1996)</strong> -- Marines from Battalion Landing Team, 3rd Battalion, 1st Marine Regiment volunteered their services to the city of Waimea, Hawaii May 27, as part of a three-phase community relations project to benefit residents in the local community.<br>
The project was headed by Chaplain (LCdr.) Chin Van Dang, 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit, and Chaplain (Lt.) William M. Middleton, BLT 3/1, both of whom brought together Marines and two Navy Religious Programmers from various detachments throughout the BLT 3/1 to assist in the project's tasks. <br>
The project involved painting and restoring safety areas and playground facilities at the Waimea Elementary and Intermediate School and beautifying the Camp Tarawa Memorial, a large plaque embedded in stone signifying the 2nd and 5th Marine Divisions' efforts during World War II. In addition, food donations to "The Island of Hawaii Food Bank" were coordinated to the benefit of more than 60 charities throughout the island of Hawaii.<br>
"Part of the Chaplain's and RP's job is to organize these community relations projects to benefit both the military and the local community," said RP3 Joseph M. McCoy, 11th MEU.<br>
The first job took place May 25, as a group of five Marines and Sailors spent the day  sprucing up the Camp Tarawa Memorial by cleaning and polishing its metallic exterior. Inscribed on the memorial read, "Camp Tarawa 1943-1945. The 2nd and 5th Marine Divisions. Trained here to bring peace to the Pacific." <br>
The second project became the day's highlight as a group of 15 Marines and Sailors gathered at the school at 9 a.m. Sunday, May 26, to begin painting yellow safety striping on all walkways, curbs and other high risk areas such as the stairways leading to several classrooms. During the painting, Marines also spiced up the playground area for the children by repainting the lines of an old game of "Four Square" and creating three more along a wide cement pathway.   <br>
"I think we saved the school a lot of money," said RP2 John K. Simokat, BLT 3/1. "I also think that the kids will have many hours of fun from the work we did."<br>
Some of the Marines were glad that they had a chance to do work that benefitted the school.<br>
"It feels good to do something for the community we're defending," said LCpl. Brian M. Dite, D Co., 1st Light Armored Reconnaissance. "It's not often we get to do something for the community and when you do, it makes a big impact."	<br>
This painting job wasn't the first time Marines were called to give the school a hand. <br>
"In the past, the Marines have done land clearing, grubbing and leveling to create additional playground space," said Art Souza, Assisitant principal of the school. "Discussions for future work include plans to build an adult size softball field for joint community and school use."<br>
At the end of the day, members of the school's staff showed their appreciation to the volunteers by throwing a small picnic consisting of sandwiches, chips, Hawaiian iced tea and a Polynesian delight, strawberry/guava nectar.   <br>
On May 28, at the Pohakuloa Training Area, food donations to the IHFB kicked off as Marines loaded a truck with unused food portions from Meals Ready to Eat, canned goods, and produce. Items included;  2,000 1-ounce packets of apple jelly, 1,800 1-ounce packets of grape jelly, 5,000 1.5-ounce packages of peanut butter, 4,140 2 gram packets of coffee, four cans of corn and 25 pounds of fresh green peppers.<br>
"The food bank liked the donations of MREs because those items don't need refrigeration and some of the needy don't have any refrigerators," said Steve Trout, PTA Operations Officer.<br>
Some of the needy are former military personnel who live in remote places far away from town and are too proud to ask for help. One good thing that the IHFB does for them is personally deliver the food when there is any available, explained Trout. <br>
s the 11th MEU continues to prepare for an upcoming six month deployment in September, its Marines and Sailors will continue to foster good community relations by participating in more restoration projects like those at Waimea.<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USMC-</center>
<br>
<br>
