<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC 96: Scout teams and Light Armor learn to work together</title>

<h1>Fire & Maneuver:</h1>
<h2>Scout teams and Light Armor learn to work together</h2>
<h3>by Cpl. Marc Ayalin, USMC</h3>
<hr>
<strong>(Pohakuloa Training Area, HI., May 25, 1996)</strong> -- The sound of machine-gun fire echoed across the range May 25, as a five-man team of scouts from Delta Co., 1st Light Armored Reconnaissance Battalion, crouched down to witness their foe's destruction during a fire and maneuver exercise for RIMPAC '96. <br>
The exercise was part of a six week training evolution for Battalion Landing Team, 3rd Battalion, 1st Marine Regiment, preparing for a six-month Western Pacific Deployment with the 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit in September. The daylong event brought more than 90 Marines and Sailors together to work out section coordination between Light Armored Vehicle support and scout fire and maneuver tactics.<br>
"The mission of our scout teams is to provide local security for our vehicles and conduct long range patrols," said SSgt. Thomas A. Brown, 1st Platoon Sergeant, D Co., LAR. <br>
During long range patrols, scout teams may come in contact with the enemy and be unable to repel fire without the aid or support of their mechanized counterparts. At the Army's expansive training facility, the Marines were able to hone coordination skills. <br>
The 800-meter course featured manually operated pop-up targets positioned at various locations along the range. It also featured several propane-filled tanks rigged to simulate machine-gun and mortar fire when triggered by a course controller. <br>
After receiving a safety brief, the first team of five scouts boarded an LAV and entered the range. 200 meters down range, the scout team exited the vehicle and began their arduous journey on foot. Quietly, the team maneuvered through the lavic micro-terrain indigenous of Hawaii's Pohakuloa Training Area. Over small mounds of lava rocks and passing the dried bushes of the range, the team came in contact with the enemy for the first time. Four full-figured silhouetted pop-up targets appeared 50 meters away including one moving target which traveled left to right.<br>
The sound of simulated machine-gun fire filled the air as the course operator triggered the propane tanks. The scout team scurried to find cover and concealment from the nearest mound or bush. Suddenly, the team leader shouted, "Right fire team - rush!" The assault was on. As two Marines ran toward the objective, others provided cover. Down went one target and then another, but the targets reappeared to simulate a larger opposition force. <br>
As the Marines got closer, the controller slowed down the targets' repetition. Then, almost at once he ceased the target's movement. The fire fight was over for now.<br>
Not a minute passed when suddenly the team began receiving enemy fire from their left flank. The team took cover and returned fire, but this time it was too much and the team leader had to call in for vehicle support. Hastily, he popped a can of green smoke to signal the vehicles while at the same time telling his Marines to stay down.<br>
Two LAVs moved up from the rear and took position before firing down range. Upon confirming the scouts' position, the two vehicles engaged the enemy with their 7.62 mm coaxial machine-guns.<br>
"I try to keep my fire suppression as accurate as possible so the scouts can advance or find another position," said LCpl. Craig A. Comello, an LAV crewman and gunner.<br>
One minute later the team leader popped a can of yellow smoke to signal a cease fire in order to continue the assault. Aggresively, two Marines ran toward the objective while the rest of their fire team covered them with gunfire. Leapfrogging towards the enemy and using rocks and bushes for cover and concealment, the fire team stopped 25 feet from the bunker and some trenches to prepare for their attack.<br> 
"Attack!" shouted the team leader.<br>
Like a scene from the Civil War, the Marines charged at the enemy's position across an open field firing a barrage of rounds towards the trenches. As they approached the stronghold the Marines spit rounds into the trenches to kill the enemy. The fire team had no casualties to report and the enemy was overrun. After regrouping, the team proceeded to move forward in their original direction. <br>
About 300 meters away, eight targets appeared in the distance and in between another bunker began simulating firing rounds. Once again the green smoke was used and the LAVs suppressed the enemy. This time the distance was much longer and the Marines had to rush along  more rugged terrain. <br>
"This course is the most challenging by far since I've been in the Marine Corps," said LCpl.  Joseph V. Enzensperger, D Co., 1st Plt. "I've never done a course with so much distance."<br>
After the LAVs ceased fire, the team began leapfrogging again across the range while Marines covered each other with automatic fire. As they approached their final objective, the team leader shouted for the Marines to attack. With one last breath, the Marines screamed their war cries and charged the enemy's last stronghold for the final time. <br>
Upon taking the bunker, the Marines set up in a defensive posture in case there were any additional hostilities. Behind the bunker, the team laid in the prone position while the team leader called to be extracted from their position. Suddenly, 10 pop-up targets appeared another 200 meters down range. The hard chargers of Delta Company maintained fire and suppression until they could be picked up.<br>
When the LAVs arrived, two men got in one vehicle while being covered by their fellow Marines. The rest proceeded as the LAV's guns sent a massive barrage of steel rain upon the enemy. Within seconds the vehicles were off and the course was complete. <br>
Throughout the day, the rest of D Company ran through the course, hitting, rolling, coordinating fires with the LAVs and practicing small unit fire and maneuvers. In the end, the Marines had gained a new perspective about their combat skills.<br>
"I' ve gained more confidence in controlling my team during the assault on the objectives," said LCpl. Hank W. Eddy, 1st Plt., D Co.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USMC-</center>
<br>
<br>
