<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Harbor Tugs Support RIMPAC Break Out</title>

<h1>Pearl Harbor tugboat crews help RIMPAC ships "breakout"</h1>
<h2>JO1(SW) S.A. Thornbloom</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, May 23, 1996)</strong>--When 19 ships “broke out” of Pearl Harbor last week to begin the first phase of RIMPAC 96, a key to the operation was a small fleet of tugboats from Pearl Harbor’s Service Craft Unit.<br>
It’s a fleet that doesn’t get as much attention or recognition as the aircraft carriers, cruisers, destroyers, frigates and other ships participating in this year’s exercise, but any harbor observer can see that the tugs are very important to RIMPAC.<br>
From before dawn to dusk, the tiny tugs swirled about, churning up the harbor bottom as they safely guided the larger vessels to open sea.<br>
“It’s a good experience to be a part of it (RIMPAC),” said Seaman Elizabeth Hupf, from Medford, Ore., a crew member aboard tugboat Tuskeegee (YTB-806).  “With all these countries being here and to be able to see it all is great, but it’s still just a part of our job.”<br>
According to Tuskeegee’s crew, pushing and pulling the massive tonnage of naval vessels out to sea during RIMPAC’s port breakout made for a very busy day.<br>
“It’s more hectic,’’ said Chief Boatswain’s Mate Rex Cain, driver and captain of Tuskeegee.  “Usually when there’s a lot of ships moving, we just do one right after the other so it can be more difficult.”<br>
To another Tuskeegee crew member, Seaman Carrie Jackson of Las Vegas, Nev., “Just being able to work together and get things done makes the work go by faster.”<br>
But even while the work goes by faster, the day can still be very long during a port breakout.<br>
Tuskeegee’s nine-member crew, along with crews aboard the unit’s four other tugs, started their day before dawn on the day of the breakout.<br>
At 5 a.m., the crew prepped Tuskeegee to get underway. By 6 a.m., the tug was guiding a submarine, USS San Francisco (SSN-711), to an ammunition pier.<br>
Then, one after another, the armada of RIMPAC ships were escorted away from their moorings and out to sea.  From USS Antietam (CG-54) and USS Essex (LHD-2) to HMAS Sydney and HMCS Winnipeg -- whether the ships were American, Canadian or Australian --  the tug pushed and pulled, guiding the larger ships into Pearl Harbor’s open channel.<br>
“I always try to think of three or four moves ahead on a day like today,” said Cain, a native of Helena, Mont., who has been driving his tug around Pearl Harbor for three years.  “If you don’t look ahead, you’ll get to the ship and think ‘What do I do now?’ ”<br>
Cain added that a part of looking ahead is thinking about the easiest and safest way to handle a ship.<br>
“Usually it’s whatever the harbor pilot wants us to do,” he said.  “The pilot makes the call on whether we’ll do a headline or stern tow.  I just try to be prepared for what they may tell us to do.”<br>
A “stern tow” -- where the tow line goes over the tug’s stern -- is better because “a tug has more power going forward than pulling in reverse on a headline,” Cain said.  But a stern tow is also more dangerous because there’s a greater chance of the line snapping.<br>
Regardless of the method, Tuskeegee’s crew relies on teamwork.<br>
“We really trust each and know each other well on a personal level as well as a work level,” said Seaman Dancie Freeman, from Douglasville, Ga.<br>
Cain said his crew of six women and two men “work together very well as a team.  And they know what the team concept is and they understand it.  You don’t hear a lot of squabbling or bickering.”<br>
Although most RIMPAC 96 ships are now operating at sea, the tugs of Service Craft Unit will keep busy guiding non-RIMPAC participants in, out and around the harbor.  But toward the end of June, Cain said, his team of Sailors will be ready for even more long, hectic days aboard Tuskeegee when the exercise’s ships all return to port.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
