<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC 96 gets underway</title>

<h1>RIMPAC 96 gets underway<br>
with "port breakout"</h1>
<h2>by JO2 Andrew Cramer</h2><br>
<hr>
<strong>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii, May 23, 1996 </strong> -- Nearly 20 ships and submarines from five nations sailed out of Pearl Harbor Thursday in response to a simulated enemy threat.<br>
Frigates, oilers, amphibious assault ships and destroyers -- carefully moved out of the harbor as part of a "port breakout" in Exercise Rim of the Pacific.<br>
Knowing how to avoid a threat is key in any warfare situation, said Ensign Neil Willmann, public affairs officer aboard USS Reid (FFG-30).<br>
"A `port breakout’ is necessary when a battle group gets word that an area outside their port is a threat, whether it’s from an enemy plane, ship or sub," Willmann said.<br>
"The group commanders have to find a way to get their fleet out of port and either avoid or destroy the enemy threat before the threat can do damage to a ship."<br>
In Thursday’s simulation, the nation of Pacifica received word that an enemy sub from the nation of Capmid was patrolling the waters outside Pearl Harbor.<br>
One by one, each ship from the battle group slid out the harbor’s channel with a specific task to accomplish and a specific area to patrol, said Royal Australian Navy Cmdr. James Goldrick, executive officer for the guided-missile destroyer HMAS Perth.<br>
"Giving each ship an exact function within an exercise will give you a clearer picture of what to expect if all of us ever had to do this for real," Goldrick said.<br>
The first ships and subs to reach the open sea formed a defense net around the harbor’s mouth to protect the most important ship in the group, or the High Value Unit (HVU), from the enemy threat, according to Willmann.<br>
"Once the other ships firmly establish their position, they signal the HVU that it is safe to exit the port," he said.<br>
The amphibious assault ship USS Essex (LHD-2) served as the HVU, said the ship’s public affairs officer, Lt. Cmdr. Julia Spinelli.<br>
"Usually a carrier will be the center of a battle group," Spinelli said.  "Since neither of the two carriers (that are participating in RIMPAC), USS Independence or USS Kitty Hawk, are here yet, Essex is the next most important asset."<br>
Once the HVU has moved to the center of the defense net, the entire group sails off in formation to its destination, sometimes while still trying to locate the enemy threat, Spinelli said.<br>
Goldrick compared RIMPAC to a symbiotic relationship.<br>
"We learn just as much about other nations’ ways and means as they learn about us," he said.  "It is very much a mutually beneficial relationship.<br>
"By practicing in a demanding environment, naval forces gain clearer communication, and thereby, a more close-knit relationship."<br>
More than 40 ships, 250 aircraft and 30,000 military personnel will be involved in RIMPAC 96.  In addition to the United States, military personnel from Australia, Canada, Chile, Japan and South Korea are participating.  The exercise will last until June 21.<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
