<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Chilean Navy Celebrates Navy Day during RIMPAC 96</title>

<h1>Chilean Navy celebrates Chilean Navy Day in Hawaii during<br>RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>by JO3 Dean Nazario</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, Hi., May 23, 1996)</strong>--Every seagoing nation has history of naval battles won and lost and heroes who are honored and remembered each year.<br>
This year, Sailors from two Chilean ships celebrated their "Navy Day" while in port Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, during their first participation in Exercise Rim of the Pacific (RIMPAC 96).  These Sailors are joining 30,000 Sailors and Marines from six nations to improve cooperation and interoperability at sea.<br>
Sailors and officers of the frigate Almirante Lynch (PFG-07) and submarine SS Simpson hosted a Chilean Navy Day reception in Pearl Harbor May 21 for the Chilean community in Honolulu; RIMPAC Sailors from four other nations, including Australia, Canada, the Republic of Korea and the United States; and local Hawaiian community members.<br>
"The Chilean Navy was born with the Republic of Chile in 1818," said Capt. Cristian Gantes, commanding officer of Almirante Lynch.<br>
Chile declared Navy Day May 21 a national holiday in 1915 to commemorate the naval battles of Iquique (north coast) and Punta Gruesa during a war that Chile fought against Peru and Bolivia in 1879.<br>
"In the Battle of Iquique, our major naval hero, Cmdr. Arturo Prat, commanding officer of the corvette Esmeralda, was killed after boarding an enemy vessel in an attempt to take the ship," Gantes said.   "He died with 140 of his men."<br>
Chilean ships maintained a blockade of the then Peruvian port of Iquique.   In the early morning of May 21, 1879 the two weakest units of the Chilean Fleet - Esmeralda and Covadonga -- engaged the strongest units of the Peruvian Fleet -- the steamship monitor Huascar and the ironclad Independencia.<br>
"Boys the contest is unequal," Prat said to his crew.  "Our flag has never been lowered before the enemy, and I hope this isn't the occasion for that to happen.  As long as I live that flag will be in its place (on top of the mast)."<br>
The Chileans put up a strong fight and refused to surrender.  Impatient with the long struggle, the Huascar bore down full steam on the Esmeralda and rammed the ship.<br>
"In order to maintain the blockade, Prat decided to board the Huascar," Gantes said.  Prat ran a few steps toward the bridge, but was shot and killed by an enemy sailor.<br>
The Huascar rammed the Esmeralda two more times before sinking the Chilean ship, but the crew continued fighting under Prat's orders.  Only 59 of Esmerelda's Sailors were saved, but their effort was not in vain.  The last object to disappear was the Chilean flag firmly fastened to the mast.<br>
"It was very important at that time," Gantes said, because this battle united the Chilean people into supporting the war effort.  "The way that Prat died with those men was recognized even by the enemy."<br>
At the end of the combat, the Covadonga managed to ground the Independencia and force a surrender.  The Huascar was later captured on October 8, 1879.  "The Huascar is still afloat to this day and resides in Talcahuano, Chile," Gantes said.<br>
"It's (Navy Day) a holiday because the Chilean people realize their navy played an important role in the past, and they commemorate the war heroes who led the country to victory," Gantes said.  "It's a big celebration all over Chile with military and civilian ceremonies and school parades."<br>
In addition, the new Esmeralda, a tall sail training ship, normally pays port visits to Pearl Harbor during her training cruises around the world.<br>
"Chile Navy Day is important to us because the navy and the Chilean people remember our heroes," said S1 Raul Ramirez, Almirante Lynch mechanical electrical technician.<br>
The ships arrived in Pearl Harbor earlier this month, and this is the first time the Chilean units will be participating in RIMPAC 96.<br>
"We are increasing our naval participation with the United States," Gantes said.  "It is important to the Chilean navy to project power in the Pacific theater.  To that end, we must maintain a naval presence here and be ready to participate in peacekeeping missions."<br>
The Chilean Navy has participated in past exercises with the United States, and the Aegis cruiser USS Vincennes (CG-49) is currently in Chile conducting a joint exercise.<br>
"This demonstrates the increased participation with the U.S. Navy," Gantes said.<br>
Gantes hopes the Chilean navy can learn more about operating in a multi-national force and contribute to interoperability.<br>
"Interoperability is not something that can be worked out on paper," he said.  "You have to physically participate in the exercise, communicate and train effectively with other navies."<br>
<br><br><br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
