<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Foreign Navies Participate in RIMPAC 96</title>

<h1>Foreign Navies Participate in RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>by JO3 Dean Nazario</h2>
<hr>
<strong>(1996)</strong>--The U.S. Navy, Royal Australian Navy, and the navies of Chile, Canada, Japan and Republic of Korea will participate in RIMPAC 96.<br>
As in past RIMPAC exercises, forces are divided into two groups -- U.S. and Japanese units will form the Bilateral Force (BIF), and the other countries along with units from the United States will form the Multi-National Force (MNF).<br>
<h3>Australia</h3>
The Royal Australian Navy has participated in of each of the 15 RIMPAC exercises, which began in 1971.  Four of their ships are in Pearl Harbor to participate in Exercise RIMPAC 96.<br>
The four ships arrived in Pearl Harbor, in mid-May, led by Rear Adm. C. J. Oxenbould, Australia's maritime commander and head of RIMPAC's Multi-National Force.  The ships are Perth (DD-38), Newcastle (FFG-06), Sydney (FFG-03) and Success (AOR-304).<br>
Some of the RIMPAC training to be accomplished in Hawaiian waters this year include a missile exercise at the Pacific Missile Range Facility, Barking Sands, Kauai.<br>
"They (the exercises) give us a chance to operate not only with the U.S. Navy but also with other nations we don't normally have a chance to operate with," Muller said.  "We see it as a way of cooperating with friendly forces in the Pacific."<br>
Also participating are various Royal Australian Air Force aircraft including P-3Cs and F-111s, two Special Air Service Regiment patrols and a mine countermeasure clearance diving team.<br>
"The objective we hope to achieve from RIMPAC is to maintain our high standards of operations, maintain and improve our training techniques and improve interoperability," said five-time RIMPAC sailor Lt. Andrew Jackman, warfare officer with HMAS Newcastle.<br>
<h3>Chile</h3>
Although this is the first time Chilean naval forces are taking part in RIMPAC, the South American nation has recently participated in several bilateral exercises with the U.S. Third Fleet.  Cmdr. Cristian Gantes Young, commanding officer of the PFG Almirante Lynch, will lead the Chilean forces.<br>
PFG Almirante Lynch is a Leander class, general-purpose frigate built in Scotland and commissioned in 1974.  In February 1975, it arrived at the Chilean port of Punta Arenas and joined a squadron in Valparaiso.<br>
The Lynch is the Chilean navy's third ship to bear that name.  It honors the 
memory of Vice Adm. Patricio Lynch Solo De Zaldivar, one of the most distinguished men in Chilean naval and military history.<br>
The steam turbine-driven ship holds a crew of 267 officers and enlisted men.
Joining the Lynch for RIMPAC is the "O"-class diesel-electric submarine SS Simpson, which used to be the U.S. Navy's USS SPOT until it was turned over to Chile in 1962.<br>
Simpson is the third submarine of the Chilean navy to bear the name of Vice Admiral Roberto Simpson, the Chilean fleet's commander in chief around 1830.  It has a crew of nine officers and 37 enlisted men.<br>
<h3>Canada</h3>
Five Canadian ships -- Algonquin (DDGH-283), Protecteur (AOR-509), Winnepeg (FFH-338), Huron (DDGH-281) and Regina (FFH-334) --and five helicopters will take part in RIMPAC 96.  Capt. Glenn Davidson, commander of the Canadian Defense Force's Maritime Operations Group Two, is leading the Canadian Task Group.<br>
The group will be joined by six CF-18 fighters and various other aircraft.  In all, 1,300 Canadian Forces personnel will participate in RIMPAC.  Canada was one of the original RIMPAC participants in 1971, and this year's group is the largest yet.<br>
<h3>Japan</h3>
This is will be the ninth RIMPAC for the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force.
The JMSDF presence, led by Rear Adm. Hideaki Kaneda, commander of Escort Flotilla Four, will operate in a bi-lateral group with a U.S. aircraft carrier, cruisers and destroyers.<br>
Participating Japanese units include eight destroyers, a submarine, a fleet support ship and a squadron detachment of P-3C Orion patrol aircraft.
The JMSDF's main missions are to defend Japan from maritime invasion and to secure the safety of maritime traffic around the country, which is surrounded by the sea.  Other missions include contributing to a more stable security environment and responding to large-scale disasters.
The JMSDF is capable of conducting a variety of operations, including anti-submarine, anti-aircraft, anti-surface craft, mine laying, electronic warfare and other missions depending on the threat.<br>
<h3>Republic of Korea</h3>
Republic of Korea units have participated in the three previous RIMPAC, and are returning to join the Multi-National Force with Australia, Canada, Chile and some U.S. units.<br>
Capt. Hak Je Cho, commander of Korea's Anti-Submarine Warfare Squadron 51, will retain overall command of ROK forces throughout the exercise.  He also will be leading two frigates, the ROKS Kyungbuk (FF-956) and ROKS Cheju (FF-958).<br>
The Korean navy has its origins in the Korean Coast Guard, created in 1945.  Since then, the ROK navy has strengthened its combat capability by acquiring more ships.  The navy, which started with a few patrol-and-torpedo boats, acquired destroyers in the 1960s and 150 combat vessels and two submarines since 1990.  The navy will have eight submarines by 1998.<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
