<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Final Exercise for the Intruder</title>
<br>
<br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96</h1>
<h2>A-6E Intruder to retire after RIMPAC 96</h2>
<h3>by JO2 Andrew Cramer</h3>
<hr>

<strong>(Pearl Harbor, Hi., May 22, 1996)</strong>--One last hurrah.<br>
One last bow before the curtain falls.<br>
RIMPAC 96 will be the last major exercise for A-6E Intruders, the carrier-based attack bomber that has seen combat over Vietnam, Libya and Iraq.<br>
"I'm sure they're gonna go out with a bang and carry the fleet like they always have," said Lt. Cmdr. Walter Klein, who was an A-6E bombardier-navigator with attack squadron VA-52 out of Naval Air Station Whidbey Island from 1987-90.<br>
Two attack squadrons will participate in RIMPAC 96:  VA-115 Eagle Halls as part of Carrier Air Wing 5 aboard the USS Independence (CV-62) and VA-95 Green Lizards as part of Carrier Air Wing 11 aboard USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63).<br>
Even though RIMPAC 96 is the last major exercise an A-6E will participate in, its history will keep its memory alive, according to Klein, currently a cruise missile strike planner with the U.S. Pacific Command, headquartered at Camp H.M. Smith in Halawa. <br>
"I'd always wanted to fly A-6s," he said, "and when I got my wings in 1986, I was lucky that was where the Navy put me." <br>
The A-6 became operational in February 1963 as a sub-sonic, all-weather attack aircraft.  The A-6E made its maiden flight in 1970 and was approved for service in December 1972 after further testing.  It can deliver rockets, missiles or up to 28 500-pound bombs.  <br>
The Intruder worked around the clock in Vietnam, conducting attacks on targets with pinpoint accuracy unavailable through any other aircraft available at that time, according to the Defense Department.<br>
In 1986, Navy A-6E Intruders and Air Force FB-111s penetrated the sophisticated Libyan air defense systems in a joint strike against Libyan terrorist-related targets.<br>
The aircraft was also used extensively during the Persian Gulf War, providing precision bombing on a wide range of targets.<br>
"One of the things I remember most about the Intruder was it's incredible range," Klein said.  "Because it was configured to handle extra fuel, it could fly longer than any fighter we’d had."<br>
According to "Jane’s All the World’s Aircraft," the U.S. government originally planned to update the A-6E fleet with the A-6F Intruder II and A-6G.  Congress, however, withdrew funding in fiscal year 1989.<br>
The planes are being phased out because of advancements in technology and electronics, Navy officials said.  Various models of the more-advanced F/A-18 Hornet strike fighter are being used to a greater extent.<br>
"The A-6 is the most potent attack aircraft ever made as far as ability to strike at night," Klein said.  "That's a unique property of it.  While the new F-18's have the advantage of state-of-the-art technology, they aren't as versatile."<br>
The A-6E Intruder also has a few Hollywood films to its credit, most recently "Flight of the Intruder" starring Danny Glover.<br>
"I do not want to see the A-6 go out," Klein said.  "I think it's a mistake to mothball it completely because it could do so many other things.  It's a very sad day."<br><br><center>-USN-</center><br>
<img src="intruder.gif" alt= "" align=right align=bottom height=288 width=427>
An A-6 Intruder waits its turn to launch amid the venting steam of an aircraft carrier's catapult. (Official U.S. Navy Photo)
<br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
