<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>RIMPAC 96 Overview</title>

<h1>RIMPAC's Back:</h1>
<h2>1996 Version promise to be bigger and better than ever</h2>
<h3>by JO1(SW) Scott Thornbloom</h3>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, May 22, 1996)</strong>--In the 25 years since the first RIMPAC, the maritime exercise has grown into a truly Rim-of-the-Pacific achievement.<br>
Australia and Canada accepted U.S. invitations to the 1971 RIMPAC.  This year, the world's largest naval exercise will host more than 30,000 service members from six nations, including the South American nation of Chile for the first time.<br>
"The U.S. Pacific Fleet is forging close and positive relationships with the navies of other nations throughout Asia and the Pacific Rim," said Adm. R.J. Zlatoper, the fleet's commander in chief.<br>
"These informal partnerships contribute directly to USCINCPAC's strategy of Cooperative Engagement," he said.  "They also demonstrate that, in the post-Cold War era, the U.S. Navy remains committed to promoting peace, progress and prosperity throughout this vital part of the world."<br>
RIMPAC 96 began Wednesday, May 22, and runs through June 21.  Along with the three original participants, South Korea returns for a fourth consecutive time and Chile is sending a frigate and submarine for their first appearance.  Japan is back for its ninth RIMPAC, participating in the bi-lateral portion of the exercise with the United States.<br>
"Working with other Pacific Rim nations builds a feeling of mutual cooperation," said Vice Admiral Conrad C. Lautenbacher, who commands the U.S. Third Fleet and will serve as the exercise's overall commander from aboard his command and control ship, USS Coronado (AGF-11).  "It builds a sense of stability for all our interests in the various regions of the Pacific.  And it builds cooperation between our navies and other units which are operating in the exercise."<br>
Although the ultimate goal of the exercise has remained the same throughout the years -- to enhance cooperation among Pacific allies and promote stability in the region -- RIMPAC has evolved to reflect changing times.<br>
The first RIMPAC was conceived during the Cold War, when the Soviet threat forced the United States to focus resources on preparing for war on the open sea -- in the "blue water."<br>
Today's naval forces are vastly reshaped to stabilize potential threats and to operate effectively in the seas' shallow "brown water" areas near land, called littoral areas.<br>
<img src="hmasffgs.gif" alt= "" align=left align=middle height=328 width=402>
"RIMPAC 96 is an excellent example of training in the littoral," Lautenbacher said.  "We have included exercises that encompass all facets of littoral warfare; from undersea warfare, surface warfare (and) air warfare, (to) strike and power projection missions across the beach."<br>
Though the Cold War years are now gone, many unstable situations continue to pose potential dangers to the economic and security interests of countries along the Pacific Rim.<br>
With fewer U.S. forces and bases overseas today, forward-deployed naval forces represent the backbone of America's defense and are an indispensable front-line instrument of U.S. foreign policy.<br>
Many of those forward-deployed forces are participating in RIMPAC 96, including the aircraft carrier USS Independence (CV-62), USS Bunker Hill (CG-52), USS Fife (DD-991), USS O'Brien (DD-975), all homeported in Yokosuka, Japan.<br><h3>
</h3>RIMPAC 96 Highlights
This year's RIMPAC will involve more than 44 ships of all types, about 250 aircraft and more than 30,000 personnel.<br>
The exercise will test the coordination and teamwork of the participating naval forces and "it will also include joint operations with our Air Force, and our Coast Guard, and, of course, our Marine Corps," Lautenbacher said.<br>
That becomes all the more important as the branches of the U.S. military continue to look for better ways and more opportunities to operate together.
Operations will take place at a hectic rate on shore, in the air, and on 
and below the ocean surface:
<ul>
<li>In addition to day and night air operations from the carriers Independence and USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63), land-based aircraft will be flying out of Hickam Air Force Base, Naval Air Station Barbers Point and Marine Corps Base Hawaii, Kaneohe Bay.
<li>A mock embassy rescue, similar to the recent one in Liberia, will be staged. 
<li>An amphibious landing at Barking Sands will be launched from USS Essex (LHD-2), USS Cleveland (LPD-7) and USS Harpers Ferry (LSD 47).
<li>Aegis cruisers like USS Cowpens (CG-63) and USS Antietam (CG-54) will defend against missile attacks while providing a screen for the carriers.
<li>Special Warfare SEAL Teams will conduct a number of missions.
<li>The Coast Guard will operate along the shoreline, keeping harbors open and participating in maritime interdiction operations that involve teaching other units how to properly board a suspicious ship.
<li>The last major exercise for A-6 Intruder aircraft.
</ul>
<h3>The Scenario</h3>
	The scenario for RIMPAC 96 is fabricated and does not portray any existing situation in the world today.  As the exercise unfolds RIMPAC naval forces will have opportunities to practice their capabilities in littoral and crisis situations.<br>
		A Multi-National Force (MNF) is sent to enforce United Nations sanctions. and Bi-Lateral Force (BIF) responds.  This places the two naval forces in opposition. and a series of events occur which results in escalated tensions and specific responses using naval forces.<br>
	Following the exercise, units will return to Pearl Harbor for port visits and exercise debriefs.  They will continue to forge new bonds of camaraderie as Pearl Harbor Naval Station's Morale, Welfare and Recreation Department offers a host of tours and sight-seeing bargains.  MWR is also sponsoring a number of sporting activities to further the growing friendship between ships and nations of the Pacific Rim.<br>
	Officials of this year's exercise hope the 15th RIMPAC is the best yet, but will look for continued support among Pacific Rim nations.
	"The U.S. Pacific Fleet will continue to support these as a catalyst for cooperation between other naval and military forces in the region," Adm Zlatoper said, "promoting understanding, building confidence, and laying the foundation for future cooperative efforts in peacekeeping and response to humanitarian need."<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
