<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle height=191 width=250>
<title>Oahu readies for RIMPAC impact</title>

<h1>RIMPAC 96:</h1>
<h2>Oahu readies for RIMPAC impact</h2>
<h3>By JO1(SW) S. A. Thornbloom</h3>
<hr>
<strong>(Pearl Harbor, Hi, May 22, 1996)</strong>--In years past, RIMPAC has become the perfect marriage of Hawaii's top two industries -- tourism and the military.<br>
When Exercise Rim of the Pacific last sailed into Hawaiian waters two years ago, sailors and their friends and family members dropped about $15 million into the Islands' economic coffers.  With more than 40 ships arriving for RIMPAC 96, that total is expected to jump to $20 million, and Hawaii's tourism industry is waiting with eager anticipation.<br>
"We don't really have any hard numbers yet,'' said Janis Togashi, of the state Department of Business, Economic Development and Tourism.  "But we do expect the impact to be equal if not more than it was in 1994."<br>
The military's contribution to Hawaii's economy is second only to tourism.  So with 30,000 service members playing tourist here through the rest of May and most of June, the influx of their dollars should be felt by many.<br>
"The eating and drinking establishments will definitely benefit from RIMPAC,'' said Togashi, "but there's no doubt that other tourist establishments, from hotels to shopping centers, will also benefit."<br>
Hotels, especially in Waikiki, will see a rise in their economic growth over the next month, and so will souvenir shops, restaurants and other businesses, according to a spokesman for Outrigger Hotels, which is Hawaii's largest hotel chain.<br>
"(RIMPAC) will bring more jobs to Waikiki and help fill our restaurants and our gift shops,'' Barry Wallace said.<br>
Moreover, the normally slow months of May and June should see hotel occupancy jump from about 70 percent to 80 percent, he said.<br>
And that, according to Wallace, happens even though many sailors sleep on board their ships at night.<br>
"Curiously some of the U.S. sailors do that," he said. "Maybe they're saving their money or they've been here before.  But most of the foreign crews immediately come to Waikiki."<br>
Even though the visitor base on Oahu takes a big jump, the "neat thing is they're not displacing any current visitors to the Islands,'' Togashi said.  That, too, might be because many sailors sleep aboard ship at night.<br>
Bill Paty, chairman of Military Affairs at the state Commerce Department, calls RIMPAC a major infusion of cash to the economy because sailors rent cars, buy souvenirs and check out the night spots.<br>
"It's one of the biggest things to happen on the Island,'' Paty said.<br>
He compared RIMPAC to Japan's Golden Week, where Japanese workers and their families take a week off each summer to travel and attend festivals.  "You talk about Golden Week, this is our Golden Week."<br>
Paty said Hawaii residents and businesses try to make sure they are extending the Aloha spirit to visiting sailors, rather than reaching out a hand to make money.<br>
"We know they (service members) are doing a heck of a good job and we really appreciate it," said Paty, himself a World War II veteran who parachuted into France on D-Day.  "I hope they all enjoy their stay here, not because they're bringing a paycheck, but because they want to be here."
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
