<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle>
<title>RIMPAC 96 uses Internet connection</title>

<center><h1>RIMPAC 96 uses Internet connection</h1>
<hr>
<h5>story by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire<br>	
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h5><br></center>
Information on the world's largest naval exercise can now be accessed on the World Wide Web in one of the largest electronic postings dedicated to a single event.<br>
The site contains the latest news on the nearly 100 commands, 44 ships and approximately 60 units participating in Exercise Rim of the Pacific 96, which is being conducted from May 22 through June 21 in and around the Hawaiian Islands.  The site is managed by U.S. Pacific Fleet Public Affairs and the RIMPAC Combined Information Bureau (CIB).<br>
Getting details about the exercise onto the Internet is an important goal for the CIB's leader, Navy Cmdr. Keith Arterburn.<br>
"We wanted to be able to reach as many people as possible with information about RIMPAC 96," he explained.  "The location of the exercise -- in the middle of the Pacific Ocean -- keeps some media from covering this important exercise.  The Internet allows media and interested individuals to follow the exercise."<br>
The website, which can be found through the U.S. Pacific Fleet homepage at www.cpf.navy.mil, contains fact sheets on participating units, Biographies of exercise commanders and information on daily activities.<br>
"We are trying to update it daily with photos and information so that people following the exercise from around the world know what happened that day," Arterburn said.  "Our site provides one-stop shopping for information.  When you see the size of the site and the amount of information we are adding, it gives you an idea of the complexities surrounding the largest naval exercise in the world, RIMPAC 96.<br>
Six Pacific-rim nations -- Australia, Japan, South Korea, Canada, the United States and, for the first time, Chile -- are participating in the biennial exercise.  Although this is the 15th RIMPAC, it is the first for the "information age."<br>
"I believe this is the first time that an Internet site has been used in direct support of a major military exercise," Arterburn said.  "We've checked the Internet carefully and haven't found any record of it being used like this before."<br>
Telling the Navy story directly to anyone with access to the Internet is a daunting challenge for Arterburn and his staff.<br>
"One of the challenges is to gather the basic information on as many of the players as possible," Arterburn said.  "We have active hyperlinks directly to the Canadian, Japanese and Australian websites.  We've tried to use hyperlinks wherever possible, but this technology is so new that we've found ourselves creating much of the material ourselves."
Still, the results made the challenge worth it, Arterburn said.<br>
"Using this cutting-edge technology is exciting because you see information provided to so many more people now," he said.  "It's impressive to see the communications loop come full circle so quickly.<br>
"The event happens, the reporter's story gets published, and then people 'read all about it.'  That used to take days.  Now the reader can access the information in as little as an hour of the event occurring."
The RIMPAC website also makes detailed news about naval operations accessible on a level not available before.<br>
"Sailors sail the seas out of sight of most people, but the RIMPAC 96 Internet site allows anyone to find out what they are doing for the nation today.  Media coverage is limited by space and time, but the Internet lets us tell people what sailors and Marines did today at sea."<br>
The website was accessed 70 times during a 48-hour period, "and we're just getting started," Arterburn said.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
<br>
<br>
