<img src="rimpac4.gif"  alt= ""align=left align=middle>
<title>HMAS SYDNEY Arrives for RIMPAC 96</title>
<h2>Aloha Mate! RIMPAC's Back!</h2>
<center><h1>HMAS SYDNEY Arrives for RIMPAC 96</h1></center>
<hr>
<center><h5>story and photos by JO1(SW) S. A. Thornbloom<br>	
Pacific Fleet Public Affairs Office</h5><br></center>
<img src="hmassyd1.jpg" alt= (Photo Here) "" align=left align=middle height=152 width=291><br><br><br><br><br><br><h6>With the USS Arizona Memorial in the distance, Australia's HMAS Sydney (FFG-03) slowly makes its way to pier Bravo 24 at Pearl Harbor Naval Station. The ship arrived in port to prepare for participation in RIMPAC Official (U.S. Navy Photo</h6><strong>(Pearl Harbor, 03 May, 1996)</strong>--HMAS Sydney (FFG-03) pulled into Pearl Harbor on May 3,  1996 along with an Australian armada of three ships, marking the return of RIMPAC.  Sydney, HMAS Perth (DD-38), HMAS Newcastle (FFG-06) and HMAS Success (AOR-304) made up the contingency from Down Under that will be operating from Hawaii for the next couple of months.  The ships are the first to arrive for RIMPAC 96, which takes place every two years in and around the waters of Hawaii.<br>
<img src="hmassyd2.jpg" alt "" align=left align=middle height=298 width=200>RIMPAC 96 will include land, sea and air forces from the United States, Australia, Canada, Japan, The Republic of Korea and, for the first time, Chile.  It is the largest exercise held in the Pacific and brings together maritime forces to conduct muti-national and bi-lateral, combined training operations from May 22 through June 21. 
First conducted in 1971, RIMPAC 96 will be the 15th exercise held.  The exercise will include more than  44 ships, 250 aircraft and 30,000 sailors, soldiers, airmen, Marines and Coast Guardsmen.  The major portion of the operation will take place in June. Following the tactical phase of RIMPAC 96, units will return to Pearl Harbor for exercise debriefs and liberty.<br>
The officer in overall command of RIMPAC 96 is Vice Admiral Conrad C. Lautenbacher Jr., Commander U. S. Third Fleet.  Operational command of individual units during the exercise will be the responsibility of respective national commanders.<br>
<h6>An Australian sailor on board HMAS Sydney (FFG-03) raises his country's national ensign during morning colors after the ship's arrival. (Official U.S. Navy Photo)</h6>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<center>-USN-</center>
