<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpf.navy.mil:80/ranaobio.htm 199.124.15.66 19970108115846 text/html 3845
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 12:10:57 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<title>Rear Admiral C.J. Oxenbould, AO, RAN</title>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="mc.gif" align="right" height=349 width=280 hspace=5 vspace=5>
<center><h1>Rear Admiral<br>
C.J. Oxenbould, AO, RAN</h1>
<h2>Commander,<br>
Multi-National Force</h2></center>
<hr>
Rear Admiral Chris Oxenbould joined the RAN College in 1962 as a 15 year old entry. Following graduation from the College at Jervis Bay, he received further training in a variety of Fleet Units and the United Kingdom.<br>
In 1972 he commenced Warfare and Navigation sub-specialist training in the United Kingdom, returning the following year to a posting in HMAS TORRENS. Following a shore posting on the staff of the Commander Australian Mine Warfare and Patrol Boat Forces, he joined the HMAS HOBART in 1976 and during this period in HOBART the ship circumnavigated the world to participate in the USA Bi-centennial activities in New York.<br>
Rear Admiral Oxenbould returned to the United Kingdom later in 1976 to undergo the Advanced Navigation Course. Subsequent postings included HMAS DUCHESS, the Navigation School, HMAS WATSON and HMAS SUPPLY.<br>
In 1981, Rear Admiral Oxenbould attended the RAN Staff Course. On completion he was promoted to Commander and took up a posting at the Navigation School, HMAS WATSON, as Course Officer for the inaugural RAN Long Navigation Course.<br>
From 1982 until 1984, Rear Admiral Oxenbould served in Fleet Headquarters, before assuming command of HMAS CANBERRA in April 1984. During his time in CANBERRA the ship conducted two Asian and one South West Pacific deployments. He was promoted to the rank of Captain at the end of 1985, and proceeded to Navy Of fice to serve on the Navy's Review Team of the Defence
Report.<br>
Postings to the United States Naval War College and to Navy Of fice as Director Naval Force Development were followed in May 1989 by command of HMAS PERTH. While in PERTH, the ship completed a major modernisation and following trials and workup deployed to south East Asia. Rear Admiral Oxenbould was promoted to Commodore in October 1990 prior to assuming the appointment as the Commander of the Australian Task Group for Operation DAMASK in the Arabian Gulf, and served in this position throughout the Gulf War. As a result of this service he was made an Officer of the Order of Australia, a member of the Order of King Fahd bin Abdul Aziz (Saudi Arabia) Third Class and was awarded the U.S. Bronze Star medal.<br>
Rear Admiral Oxenbould was posted as the Director General, Naval Policy and Warfare in Navy Office from June 1991 to September 1992. In September 1992 he took up the position of Director General Joint Operations and Plans, Headquarters Australian Defence Force. On 4 December 1993 he was promoted to his current rank and joined Navy Of fice as the Assistant Chief of Naval Staff (Personnel). He was appointed as the Maritime Commander Australia on 13 April 1995.<br>
The Rear Admiral and his wife Michele have two daughters.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
