<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac3.gif" alt= "" align=left align=middle height=145 width=190>
<img src="sealusmc.gif" alt= "" align=right align=middle height=145 width=151>
<br><center><h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<br><br>11th Marine Expeditionary Unit</center></h1>
<hr>

<h1>Colonel Robert B. Blose, Jr.</h1>
<h2>Commanding Officer
11th Marine Expiditionary Unit<br>
(Special Operations Capable)</h2>
Colonel Robert B. Blose, Jr. was born in Lewistown, Pennsylvania on 26 January 1950.  He received a Bachelor of Science degree in Social Science and History from Lock Haven University, Lock Haven, Pennsylvania.  He was commissioned a Second Lieutenant in the United States Marine Corps in August 1971.<br>
Upon completion of The Basic School, Marine Corps Development and Education Command, Quantico, Virginia, Colonel Blose was assigned to the 2nd Reconnaissance Battalion, 2nd Marine Division, Marine Corps Base, Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, where he served as a Platoon Commander, Assistant Operations Officer, and Adjutant.  He attended both the Airborne School and Ranger School at Fort Benning, Georgia in 1973 and then attended Aerial Observer School at New River, North Carolina.<br>
Colonel Blose served from October 1974 to November 1975 with 2nd Battalion, 4th Marine Regiment, 3rd Marine Division.  During that period he also served with the 9th Marine Amphibious Brigade and participated in the evacuation of the American Embassies in Phnom Penh, Cambodia and Saigon, Vietnam.  In May 1975 Colonel Blose reported to 1st Recruit Training Battalion, Marine Corps Recruit Depot, Parris Island, South Carolina, serving as Series Commander, Company Commander, and Battalion Operations Officer.  From May 1978 to January 1979 he attended the Infantry Officers’ Advanced Course, as well as the TOW Trainer Course and Dragon Trainer Course at Fort Benning, Georgia.<br>
He was then assigned to the 1st Marine Regiment, 1st Marine Division, Camp Pendleton, California, where he served as a Rifle Company Commander, and Weapons Company Commander with 1st Battalion, 1st Marines;  Battalion Operations Officer with 3rd Battalion, 1st Marines; and finally as the 1st Marine Division’s G-3 Training Officer.<br>
In June 1982, Colonel Blose was ordered to the Naval War College, Newport, Rhode Island, to attend the Naval Command and Staff College.  While there he earned a Master of Arts Degree in International Relations from Salve Regina College, Newport.<br>
From July 1983 until July 1986, Colonel Blose was the Commanding Officer of Recruiting Station, Buffalo, New York.  He was then assigned to the Air/Ground Exchange Program where he served as the Assistant Operations Officer of Marine Aircraft Group 16, 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing, Marine Corps Air Station, El Toro, California for two years.<br>
In October 1988, he was transferred to the 1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade, MCAS Kaneohe Bay, Hawaii, where he served as the G-3 Operations/Training Officer until October 1989 when he assumed command of 2nd Battalion, 3rd Marines.  His battalion served as an element of Task Force Taro with the 1st Marine Division in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait during Operations Desert Shield and Desert Storm.<br>
In July 1991 he was assigned to the National War College in Washington, D.C..  Upon graduation in 1992 he was assigned to the U.S. Special Operations Command, MacDill Air Force Base, Florida, for duty as the Deputy Chief and later Chief, Mission Area Assessment Division (J-5).  In June 1993 Colonel Blose was reassigned as Executive Officer to the Commander-in-Chief, United States Central Command, a position he held until August 1994.<br>
Colonel Blose assumed command of the 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit, 9 September 1994.<br>
Colonel Blose’s medals and decorations include:  the Defense Superior Service Medal, Bronze Star Medal with Combat "V", the Defense Meritorious Service Medal, Meritorious Service Medal w/1 star, Combat Action Ribbon, Navy Unit Commendation w/1 star, Meritorious Unit Commendation w/3  stars, National Defense Service Medal w/1 star, Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal w/2 stars, Vietnam Campaign Medal w/ 1 star, Southwest Asia Service Medal w/3 stars, Humanitarian Service Medal w/2 stars,Sea Service Deployment Ribbon w/4  stars,   USMC Recruiting Ribbon, Kuwait Liberation Medal, and the Kuwait Liberation Medal (Kuwait).<br>
Colonel Blose is married to the former Mary Sarah Phillips of St. Paul, Minnesota.  She is a Commander in the U.S. Naval Reserve.  They have one son, Robert III.<br>
<hr>
<h5>Source - 11th MEU</h5><br>
