<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac2.gif" alt= "" align=left height=290 width=379>
<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>Airborne Early Warning Squadron 117<br>(VAW-117)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Airborne Early Warning Squadron 117 (VAW-117)</title>
<hr>
<pre>
<h2>Airborne Early Warning Squadron 117 (VAW-117)<br>Wallbangers</h2>
Homeport.........................NAS  Miramar, San Diego, CA.
Commanding Officer...............Commander Nicholas A. Trongale, USN
<strong>
Squadron manning:</strong>
Officers.........................32
Chiefs...........................14
Junior Enlisted..................125
</pre>

<strong>Aircraft Type:</strong><br>
Northrop Grumman E-2C (Group II) Hawkeye.  Four aircraft are assigned to the squadron.<br>
<a href="vaw117px.htm"><img src="vaw117.gif" alt="VAW-117 E2-C aircraft" align="left" height=320 width=400></a>
The E-2C Hawkeye is a high-wing all weather carrier and shore based airborne early warning and control aircraft.  It is considered to be the most capable airborne early warning aircraft in the world.  The aircraft is powered by two Allison T56-A-427 turbo-prop engines with constant speed Hamilton Standard propellers.<br>
The aircraft's maximum takeoff/launch weight is 55,000 lbs and can recover aboard the aircraft carrier at a maximum weight of 46,500 lbs.  Maximum airspeed at sea level is 345 knots with a landing approach speed of 120 knots.  On a typical mission the aircraft will fly at 25,000 feet and remain on station for 4 hours.  The E-2C is easily identified by its 24 foot diameter rotodome and four vertical tails.<br>
The avionics suite includes a detection system with airborne early warning and IFF radars, passive detection system, a data processing and display system, a communications system including radio data links, and a navigation system.<br>
The E-2C flightcrew will normally consist of a pilot, copilot, combat information center officer, aircraft control officer, and radar officer.<br>   

<strong>Mission Areas</strong><br>
Airborne early warning, command, control and communications.  The aircraft provides early warning of approaching enemy aircraft and vectors fighter aircraft to intercept.  The Hawkeye can also provide strike and traffic control, area surveillance, search and rescue guidance, navigational assistance and communications relay.  The E-2C is "the eyes and ears of the fleet". <br>

<strong>Squadron History</strong><br>
Carrier Airborne Early Warning Squadron ONE HUNDRED SEVENTEEN was established at NAS North Island, CA on 1 July 1974, as a unit of Fighter Airborne Early Warning Wing, U.S. Pacific Fleet.  The squadron received its first E-2B aircraft in October 1974, and commenced operational flying.  In May 1976, the squadron moved to it's present home station NAS Miramar, San Diego, CA.  The squadron has deployed with Carrier Air Wing SEVEN aboard the USS INDEPENDENCE (CV-62),  Carrier Air Wing TWO aboard the USS RANGER 
(CV-61), Carrier Air Wing ELEVEN aboard the USS ENTERPRISE (CVN-65) and USS LINCOLN (CVN-72) and is presently assigned to Carrier Air Wing ELEVEN aboard the USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63).<br>
<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
