<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac2.gif" alt= "" align=left height=290 width=379>
<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>Fighter Squadron 213<br>(VF-213)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Fighter Squadron 213 (VF-213)</title>
<hr>
<h2>Fighter Squadron 213 (VF-213)<br>World Famous Fighting Blacklions</h2>
<pre>
Homeport..............................NAS Miramar, San Diego, CA
Commanding Officer....................Commander William G. Bond, USN

<strong>Squadron Manning</strong>
Officers..............................37
CPO's.................................21
Enlisted..............................258

<strong>F-14A Tomcat</strong>
Length................................62' 8.5"
Wingspan..............................64'1.5" (Fully Extended)
                                      38'2.5" (Swept)
                                      33' 3.5" (Oversweep)
Gross Weight..........................42,000 lb. (Empty)
                                      72,000 lb. (Maximum)
Crew..................................2 (Pilot, Radar Intercept Officer)
Maximum Airspeed......................780 KIAS/1.88 Mach
Maximum Altitude......................50,000 FT Service Ceiling
</pre>
<strong>Weapons</strong>
<ul>
<li>Air-to-Air
<li>AIM-54 Phoenix (Long Range/Radar Missile)
<li>AIM-7  Sparrow (Medium Range/Radar Missile)
<li>AIM-9  Sidewinder (Short Range/IR Missile)
<li>Air-to-Ground
<li>MK-80 Series General Purpose Bombs
<li>Laser Guided Munitions
</ul>
<br>
<strong>Mission</strong><br><a href="vf213pic.htm"><img src="vf213.gif" alt="VF-213 F-14 aircraft" align="right" height=320 width=400></a>
The F-14A Tomcat was built by Grumman Aerospace as a Long Range 
Supersonic Interceptor. Built around the AWG-9 Radar and the AIM-54 Phoenix, the F-14 is capable of detecting and engaging targets in excess of 100 NM. The variable geometry wingsweep design provides the Tomcat with an expanded flight envelope, making it an excellent dogfighting platform. The extended range and large payload capacity of the Tomcat makes it an excellent strike aircraft capable of carrying a variety of Air-to-Ground ordnance, including Laser Guided Munitions.<br>
The F-14 is the only shipboard platform with the ability to carry the Tactical Air Reconnaissance Pod System (TARPS). The TARPS Pod gives the Tomcat and the Navy the World's premiere Photo-Reconnaissance capability. Because of the versatile design of the airframe and the variety of capable systems available to it, the F-14 will continue to be valuable asset to the Carrier Battle Group well into the 21st century.<br><br>
<strong>History</strong><br>
The Fighting Blacklions of VF-213 were commissioned as a Navy Fighter Squadron on 22 June 1955 at NAS Moffett Field, California. The BLACKLIONS flew the F-2H3 Banshee during their first deployment aboard USS BON HOMME RICHARD (CV-31) then transitioned to the F-4D Skyray for their next two deployments on USS LEXINGTON (CV-16). By their third WESTPAC deployment aboard the "LEX", they were flying the F-3H2 Demon, giving the squadron 
their first capability with the newly released AIM-7 Sparrow air-to-air missile.<br>
In June 1961, the squadron moved to its new home at NAS Miramar - "FIGHTERTOWN USA." Three years later, in February 1964, the BLACKLIONS took a quantum leap forward in fighter capability by accepting the first of their new F-4 Phantoms. In November 1965, VF-213 joined Carrier Air Wing 11 and began the first of six combat deployments to Southeast Asia aboard USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63). This deployment marked the first use of the Phantom as a conventional bomber, a role destined to make the Phantom a mainstay of the U.S. Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps.<br>
Over the next seven years, the BLACKLIONS flew over 11,500 combat missions and delivered over 6,000 tons of ordnance. On 20 December 1966, LT D.A. McRae and ENS D.N. Nichols downed an enemy AN-2 Colt for the squadron's first kill. In March 1971, VF-213 became the first fleet squadron to fly the Phantom more than 1,000 hours in a single month.<br>
In December 1976, VF-213 transitioned to the Navy's premier supersonic fighter - the F-14A Tomcat. April 1982 found a new mission for the BLACKLIONS when they began training with the Tactical Air Reconnaissance Pod System, or TARPS. In September of that year, the squadron began their first deployment aboard USS ENTERPRISE (CVN-65). During Indian Ocean Operations, the BLACKLIONS again set the standard by flying the longest tasked carrier flight for a Tomcat when they completed a 1,775 mile TARPS flight.<br>
During WESTPAC  88, the BLACKLIONS took an active role in ensuring the safe transit of reflagged tankers through the Persian Gulf and the Straights of Hormuz. That same deployment saw VF-213 in action in the Operation Praying Mantis naval conflict with Iran on 18 April 1988.<br>
The BLACKLIONS were awarded the prestigious "BOOLA BOOLA" award in March 1989 for their aggressive professional completion of all missile test firings that year. That fall, VF-213 and CVW-11 went around-the-world on ENTERPRISE's final west coast deployment, dropping her off in Norfolk, Virginia for refurbishment.<br>
In September 1990, VF-213 and CVW-11 went back to the shipyards of Norfolk, VA to embark on the Navy's newest nuclear powered aircraft carrier: USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN (CVN-72). After a successful transit around the horn of South America, ABE took up residence at her new home in Alameda, California.
In 1991, the BLACKLIONS deployed on USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN's maiden cruise to the WESTPAC in support of Operation Desert Storm. Day and night Combat Air Patrol flights over Kuwait enforced the United Nation's sanctions on Iraq, while TARPS missions recorded the devastation of Kuwait oil fields.<br>
The BLACKLIONS shone brightly in 1992. VF-213 won the coveted "MUTHA" award and took honors as the Pacific Fleet's top fleet squadron when they won the 1992 Fighter Derby. The squadron deployed for the second time aboard USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN in 1993, participating in Operation Southern Watch over Iraq and Operation Restore Hope in Somalia. Upon their return to "FIGHTERTOWN", VF-213 began a turnaround for their next deployment during which they again won the "MUTHA" award; the final "MUTHA" trophy awarded. From April to October 1995, the BLACKLIONS again deployed aboard LINCOLN in support of Operation Southern Watch. The squadron once again made history by having all fourteen Tomcats airborne at once over the skies of Iraq and Kuwait.<br>
VF-213 is currently in the middle of an eleven month compressed turnaround schedule. In October of this year, the squadron will cross-deck back to the USS KITTY HAWK for another WESTPAC deployment. The  BLACKLIONS of VF-213 continue to maintain their commitment to excellence as they have throughout their forty year history.<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
<hr>
