<!--Maintained by JOC(SW) C.A. McIntire-->
<!--Code N00pa2b-->
<!--phone: (808) 471-3769-->
<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac2.gif" alt= "" align=left height=290 width=379>
<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<br>Strike Fighter Squadron 22 (VFA 22)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Strike Fighter Squadron 22 (VFA 22)</title>
<hr>
<h2>Strike Fighter Squadron 22 (VFA 22) Fighting Redcocks</h2>
<pre>
Homeport........................................NAS Lemoore, CA.
Commanding Officer..............................Commander Wade Tallman, USN

Squadron Manning
Officers........................................24
Chiefs..........................................13
Enlisted........................................181
</pre><dl>
<dt><strong>F/A-18C Hornet</strong>
<dd>Single-seat Night Fighter/Attack aircraft 
<dd>Built by McDonnell Douglas Aircraft Company
<dd>Powered by two General Electric F404-GE-400 Afterburning Turbofans rated at 16,000 lbs each
<dd>"Fly By Wire" flight control system
<dd>Integrated Avionics package with the Hughes APG-65 radar as the primary sensor
</dl>
<strong>Armament</strong>
<dl><dt>Air-Air	           
<dd>AIM-120
<dd>AIM-7
<dd>AIM-9
<dd>20MM Gun
<dt>Air-to-Ground
<dd>All weapons in the Navy inventory
</dl>
<strong>Mission</strong><br>
The F/A-18 was the first aircraft designed from the ground up to
be a true dual mission aircraft.  This gives the pilot the
 ability to instantly switch from the ground attack role to the air to air role with the push of a button.  Strike planners now have the ability to put more precision bombs on target with less or no dedicated fighter support required.  The "Night Vision Goggle" equipped Lot 12 hornets are capable of all weather intercept, identify and destroy missions as well as day and night ground attack missions.<br><br><a href="vfa22pic.htm"><img src="vfa22.gif" alt="VFA-22 F/A-18 aircraft" align="left" height=320 width=400></a>
<strong>Command History</strong><br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" of Strike Fighter Squadron 22 have been a critical part of Naval Aviation for almost 50 years.  Originally commissioned as Fighter Squadron 63 at NAS Norfolk, Virginia in 1948, the squadron's official designation was changed to Attack Squadron 22 in July 1959.  Today, the 194 enlisted men and women and 24 officers of Strike Fighter Squadron 22 are based in Lemoore, California and maintain and fly the FA-18C Night Attack "Hornet".<br>
The first Redcock aviators flew the F-8F "Bearcat" and succeeding pilots have progressed through the F-4U "Corsair", F-9F "Panther", F-9F-6/8 "Cougar", FJ-4B "Fury", A-4 B/C/F "Skyhawk", and the A-7E "Corsair II" before transitioning to the FA-18C "Hornet".<br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" have been called into action repeatedly over the years including three combat deployments during the Korean War and six combat deployments during the Vietnam War.  On the final Vietnam deployment, VA-22 participated in the critical mining of Haiphong Harbor and intensive air strikes into North Vietnam helping to force renewed peace negotiations.<br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" received the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle Efficiency "E" for three consecutive years during the period from 1979 through 1981, an unprecedented accomplishment. Additionally, the command was awarded the 1981 CINCPACFLT Golden Anchor retention award among all deployable squadrons in the Pacific Fleet and the COMLATWINGPAC John L. Nicholson retention award for both 1980 and 1981.  The squadron also received the
RADM Clarence Wade McClusky Award during 1981 as the best Attack Squadron in the United States Navy.  Also during this period from 1979-1981, the "Fighting Redcocks" were awarded the Meritorious Unit Commendation for unmatched fulfillment of the Navy wide goals of combat readiness and personal retention while deployed with Carrier Air Wing 15 and shorebased in Lemoore, California.<br>
In January 1982, VFA-22's Operational Commander was changed to Carrier Air Wing 11 which deployed aboard the USS KITTY HAWK (CV 63).  In 1983, the command received the COMNAVAIRPAC nomination for the RADM Clarence Wade McClusky Award and was presented with the prestigious LTJG Bruce Carrier Award for excellence in Aviation Maintenance.<br>
The squadron made operational history in December 1985 by being the first west coast squadron to successfully launch an AGM-88 HARM (High Speed Anti-Radiation Missile) resulting in a direct hit.  This was the first firing of a HARM missile built up in a ship's magazine.<br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" 1986 deployment took the squadron around the world by transiting the Suez Canal into the Mediterranean Sea in response to Libyan actions.  The command was awarded a Meritorious Unit Commendation for operations including those off the coast of Libya.  Additionally in 1986, the command once again won the LTJG Bruce Carrier award as a result of their exceptional maintenance department.<br>
Upon return to the United States, the squadron developed and produced the 1987 "Great Western Shootout" which involved United States Navy, United States Air Force and National Guard and German Luftwaffe pilots participating in a joint services power projection exercise against state-of-the-art adversary threats. Led by "Fighting Redcock" pilots and jets, the exercise provided invaluable joint training for all involved.  Shortly after the "Great Western Shootout", the squadron deployed to Nellis Air Force Base, Nevada to operate with the United States Air Force during a "Red Flag" exercise, the first squadron from LATWINGPAC to participate in "Red Flag" in over seven years.<br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" were again chosen as the recipient of the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle Efficiency "E" in 1987.<br>
In 1988, the squadron was deployed aboard the USS ENTERPRISE (CVN 65) and found themselves participating in the escort of tankers through the Arabian Gulf during the Ernest Will Operation.  On April 18, 1988, VA-22 jets were involved in disabling the Iranian Frigate SAHAND with precision guided weapons and free fall bombs in what was termed a "measured response" to Iranian actions in the Arabian Gulf.<br>
In 1990, after an around the world cruise on the USS ENTERPRISE (CVN 65), the "Fighting Redcocks" retired their A-7E aircraft ending over 20 years of service with the "Corsair II". Redesignated Strike Fighter Squadron 22 in May 1990, the command transitioned to the FA-18C Night Attack Hornet.<br>  Operational requirements dictated an accelerated transition and the "Fighting Redcocks" became completely combat qualified in the new aircraft in record time and recorded the highest scores awarded by COMSTRKFIGHTWINGPAC on all squadron turnaround inspections.<br>
Deploying in 1991 aboard the USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN (CVN 72), VFA-22 participated in Operation Fiery Vigil, providing assistance in evacuating US Servicemen and their dependents from the Philippines after the eruption of Mount Pinatubo.  Following this event, the squadron continued to the Arabian Gulf participating in operations during the withdrawal of forces from Desert Storm. The "Fighting Redcocks" were again presented with the 1991 COMNAVAIRPAC Battle Efficiency "E" award for command excellence.<br>
In 1993, the "Fighting Redcocks" again deployed aboard the USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN (CVN 72) to the Arabian Gulf and participated in Operation Southern Watch enforcing the United Nations southern no fly zone over Iraq.  Before returning home, the squadron diverted to the coast of Somalia providing air support during Operation Continue Hope.  VFA-22 was the first squadron to deploy with the advanced FA-18 91C software in their aircraft and the first to operate with the AIM-120 AMRAAM missile on this cruise.  The year was highlighted by the squadron's receipt of the COMCARGRU 3 and CVW-11 nomination for the 1993 COMNAVAIRPAC Battle Efficiency, RADM Clarence Wade McClusky and Estocin awards for excellence.<br>
The "Fighting Redcocks" were among the first west coast squadrons to integrate women into combat units and participated in several "Air Warrior" exercises with United States Air Force and United States Army units during the turnaround cycle.  After a six monthly deployment to the Western Pacific in 1995, the integration is a proven success.<br>
Today, after a very short turnaround cycle, the men and women of VFA-22 are deployed aboard the USS KITTY HAWK (CV 63) in preparation for another Western Pacific deployment in October.<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
