<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>Strike Fighter Squadron 94 (VFA-94)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Strike Fighter Squadron 94 (VFA-94)</title>
<hr>
<h2>Strike Fighter Squadron 94 (VFA-94)  Mighty Shrikes</h2>
<a href="vfa94pic.htm"><img src="vfa94.gif" alt="VFA-94 F/A-18 aircraft" align="left" height=320 width=400></a>
Strike Fighter Squadron 94 is one of nine squadrons in Carrier Air Wing 11 currently participating in RIMPAC  96 aboard the USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63).  July through September will be spent working up for a six month deployment to the Persian Gulf in October. <br>
VFA-94, along with the two other Hornet squadrons, are the battle group's primary power projection force. With the aid of the FLIR (forward looking infrared) and NVG's(night vision goggles), the Hornet can deliver precision guided ordinance all weather, day or night. This capability reduces the number of aircraft and ordinance needed to fulfill a mission which increases the striking power of the carrier. <br>
<br>
<strong>Mission</strong><br>
Establish and maintain maximum combat readiness to conduct carrier-based power projection and war-at-sea operations.<br>
<pre>
Homeport.........................Naval Air Station, Lemoore, California
Commanding Officer...............Commander Matthew J. Boyne, USN
Personnel........................Approximately 200,  23 officers
Aircraft.........................12 - F/A-18C Hornets (Lot 12)
Empty Weight.....................23,500 lbs
Operational Weight...............24,500 lbs
Maximum Airspeed.................Mach 1.8
Thrust per F404-GE-400 engine....10,700 (Military Thrust)
                                 16,000 (Maximum Afterburner)
</pre>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
<hr>
