<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac2.gif" alt= "" align=left height=290 width=379>
<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:Strike Fighter Squadron 97 (VFA-97)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Strike Fighter Squadron 97 (VFA-97)</title>
<hr>
<h2>Strike Fighter Squadron 97 (VFA-97) Warhawks</h2>
<pre>
Homeport.................................NAS Lemoore, CA
Commanding Officer.......................Commander Scott H. Swift, USN

<strong>Squadron manning</strong>
Officers.................................22
Chiefs...................................13
Enlisted.................................183
</pre>

<strong>Aircraft Type & Mission</strong><br>
The squadron flies the F/A-18A "Hornet", a Multi-role Strike Fighter built by MACAIR. The aircraft consists of two turbofan afterburner engines capable of over 16,000 lbs of thrust. In the Air-to-Air arena, the Hornet can carry multiple AIM-9 "Sidewinders" and the AIM-7 "Sparrow" missiles. Air-to-Ground, the Warhawks can deliver over 3 tons of ordnance, both "dumb bombs" and "smart weapons".<br><br>
<strong>Squadron History</strong><br>
The Warhawks were commissioned as Attack Squadron 97 in June 1967 and after a brief period flying the A-7B Corsair became the second Navy squadron to transition to the A-7E Corsair II.  A year later, VA-97 was "feet dry" over enemy territory as it flew numerous strike missions against North Vietnam from the "steel decks" of the USS CONSTELLATION (CV-64). The majority of these strikes were flown to interrupt the steady stream of war materials headed southward.<br><a href="vfa97pic.htm"><img src="vfa97.gif" alt="VFA-97 F/A-18 aircraft" align="left" height=320 width=400></a>
In 1969, the Warhawks were once again off the coast of Vietnam carrying the war to the enemies front step.  During this time VA-97 pioneered the use of some of the new "smart" weapons such as the television guided Walleye bomb and Shrike anti-radiation missiles. That year the squadron also received the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle "E" award for efficiency in combat training and operations.<br>
From 1973 to 1975 the Warhawks were aboard the USS ENTERPRISE (CVN-65) conducting flight operations in South China Sea to protect American evacuees and Vietnamese refugees attempting to leave South Vietnam.  Two years later, in 1977,  the Warhawks won the "Triple Crown" of Naval Aviation by receiving the Admiral C. Wade McClusky Award, the CNO Aviation Safety Award and the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle "E" during the same competitive cycle.  This seldom seen feat was the result of hard work by all hands within the squadron.<br>
During the period 1979 to 1983, VA-97 was attached to Carrier Air Wing 14 on board USS CORAL SEA (CV-43).  Most of the 1979 WESTPAC cruise was spent on Camel Station in the Gulf of Oman, in direct support of our Government's efforts to extract  the U.S. embassy hostages held in Iran.
In 1984, the Warhawks became an invaluable asset to Carrier Air Wing 15, deploying aboard USS CARL VINSON (CV-70).  From 1984 to 1988, the Warhawks made three deployments to the Persian Gulf arena and twice participated in operation "Earnest Will", which consisted of escorting U.S. Flagged Tankers through the Gulf.  In 1989, the Warhawks were once again recognized as the finest Light Attack Squadron in the Pacific, winning the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle "E".<br>
1990 was another busy year for the Team Warhawk as they completed their 15th WESTPAC and transitioned to F/A-18A Hornet.  The Warhawks were the last west coast fleet squadron to fly the venerable and battle tested A-7E Corsair II.  The official end to the Corsair era came on 24 January 1991, when Attack Squadron 97 was redesignated Strike Fighter Squadron 97.<br>
During the period 1991-1993 the squadron was aboard USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63) and joined CAG-15 as the carrier was brought "Around the Horn" of South America to it's present home port, San Diego, California. The squadron's 16th deployment began in November 1992. During this eventful WESTPAC, the squadron participated in Operation Restore Hope in Somalia and flew actual combat sorties during Operation Southern Watch in Iraq.<br>
Strike Fighter Squadron Nine Seven was one of the few squadrons not to be decommissioned when CAG-15 was disestablished in March of 1995. Currently VFA-97 is deployed onboard USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63) with CVW-11, keeping watch over the events unfolding in the Pacific, adding another chapter to the Warhawks battle tested history.<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
