<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>Sea Control Squadron TWO NINE<br>(VS-29)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Sea Control Squadron TWO NINE (VS-29)</title>
<hr>
<h2><br>Sea Control Squadron TWO NINE (VS-29)</h2>

<pre>Homeport........................Naval Air Station North Island,
                                San Diego CA
Commanding Officer..............Commander Mark S. Boensel, USN

<strong>Squadron Manning</strong>
Officers........................43
Chiefs..........................10
Enlisted........................171

<strong>S-3B Viking</strong>
Wing Span.......................68' 8"
Length..........................53' 4"
Max Takeoff Weight..............52,500lbs
Engines.........................Two GE TF34 Turbofans
                                9275lbs thrust each
Max Airspeed....................450 KIAS/0.79 M
</pre>
<strong>Weapons Loadout</strong>
<ul>
<li>MK 80,  MK 20 Bombs
<li>MK 30,  MK 50,  MK 60 Mines
<li>MK 46 Torpedo
<li>2.75", 5" Rockets
<li>AGM 84 Harpoon Anti Ship Missile
<li>TALD Airborne Decoy   
</ul>

<strong>Mission</strong><br>
The S-3B Viking is a four seat,  high-wing,  jet-powered,  twin-engine,  carrier based aircraft with direct attack capability designed to provide Battle Group support in the following mission areas:
<ul>
<li>Undersea Warfare (USW)
<li>Surface Warfare (SUW)
<li>Strike Support
<li>Air Refueling.
</ul>
<a href="vs29pic.htm"><img src="vs29.gif" alt="VS-29 S-3 aircraft" align="left" height=320 width=400></a>
The Viking carries a variety of surface and subsurface search equipment with integrated target acquisition and sensor coordinating systems that can collect, process, interpret,  and store USW and  SUW  data.<br>
<strong>Command History</strong><br>
Commissioned 1 April 1960 the VS-29 Dragonfires have protected the fleet in all major oceans of the globe with aggressive and imaginative tactical employment of the S-2 Tracker and the S-3A/B Viking.  The squadron flew the S-2 Tracker from 1961 until 1975 when it transitioned to the S-3A.  The S-3A was flown until 1992, at which time the Dragonfires transitioned to the S-3B.  <br>
Highlights of  VS-29's history include assisting in the recovery of the Mercury space capsules in 1962 and 1963 and operations in the South China Sea in 1964 after the Gulf of Tonkin Incident with North Vietnam. VS-29 made several deployments to the Gulf of Tonkin throughout the Vietnam conflict.  Furthermore,  after transitioning to the S-3A the Dragonfires achieved a Naval Aviation first by flying a 1700 mile carrier-launched overwater flight from the USS Enterprise in the Indian Ocean to the island of Diego Garcia. In 1982, While embarked on the USS Carl Vinson, VS-29 earned the distinction of being the first Viking squadron to make an "Around the World Cruise". <br> 
More recently,  while embarked on the USS Abraham Lincoln,  the VS-29 Dragonfires have participated in Operation Fiery Vigil (the evacuation of the Subic Naval Base after the eruption of Mount Pinatubo in the Philippines),  Operation Southern Watch in support of the United Nations' sanctions against Iraq,  and Operation restore hope in support of the United Nations' humanitarian mission in Somalia.<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
