<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>Fleet Air Reconnaissance Squadron FIVE<br>(VQ-5 Det Bravo)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>Fleet Air Reconnaissance Squadron FIVE (VQ-5 Det Bravo)</title>
<hr>
<h2>Fleet Air Reconnaissance<br>Squadron FIVE (VQ-5 Det Bravo)<br>Sea Shadows</h2>
<pre>
Homeport...........................NAS North Island, San Diego, CA
Commanding Officer.................Lieutenant Commander Michael Pease, USN

<strong>Squadron Manning</strong>
Officers...........................10
CPO's..............................2
Enlisted...........................38
</pre>
<strong>Aircraft Type</strong><br>
Lockheed ES-3A utilizing advance avionics systems.  Carries a crew of four-Pilot, Electronic Warfare Combat Coordinator (EWCC), and two Electronic Reconnaissance Operators. <br>

<strong>Mission</strong><br>
To provide tactical reconnaissance capability to an operational commander.  Mission can be performed whether operating from an aircraft carrier or from remote land bases.  Specific missions might include Indications and Warnings (I&W), Command and Communications (C3), Over-the-horizon Targeting (OTH-T), and passive Electronic Warfare (EW) in support of the full range of naval operations.<br>
<a href="vq5pic.htm"><img src="vq5.gif" alt="VQ-5 ES-3A aircraft" align="right" height=320 width=400></a>
<strong>Brief synopsis of the squadron</strong><br>
Fleet Air Reconnaissance Squadron FIVE was officially established on 15 April 1991 operating from NAS Agana Guam.  VQ-5 was created 
to provide battle group commanders with a replacement for the EA-3.  The squadron had received its total complement of eight ES-3A's by June 1994.  Flying from landbased detachment sites, the squadron supported several major exercises, including Annualex 92, Encouterex, and Team Spirit 93.
The Navy's first operational cruise for the ES-3A began in November 1993 when DET ALFA deployed aboard the USS INDEPENDENCE (CV-62) in support of Operation Southern Watch in the Persian Gulf.  Subsequent detachments have deployed aboard the USS CARL VINSON (CVN-70), USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63), USS CONSTELLATION (CV 64), and the USS ABRAHAM LINCOLN (CVN-72) in the Western Pacific and the Persian Gulf, supporting Operations Southern Watch, Tandem Thrust 94 and Korean contingency operations.<br>
From stand up in 1991 to full operational status by 1993, VQ-5 compiled an envious record of accomplishments, earning the COMFAIRWESTPAC nomination for the Safety "S" and ultimately winning their first COMNAVAIRPAC Battle "E".  In July 1994, VQ-5 changed homeport from NAS Agana Guam to NAS North Island San Diego and was officially established as a resident command on 01 October 1994.  Today, VQ-5 is at full operational strength and has flown over 7800 hours accident free since its establishment. In 1994, the squadron flew over 3900 hours, a five fold increase over optempo during the first year of operations.<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - CVW-11</h5><br>
