<html>
<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - VRC-30
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="vrc30.JPG"></a><img src="ACvrc30.JPG"></a><br>
<h2> Fleet Logistics Support Squadron THREE ZERO</h2><br>
<br></center>
</b>
<P> 
    The primary mission of the Fleet Logistics Support Squadron THREE ZERO (VRC-30) Det 5 "PROVIDERS" is to provide the transport of high-priority cargo, mail and passengers between aircraft carriers at sea and shore bases throughout the Pacific Theater.  In addition, Det 5 is capable of providing airdrop/paradrop support for Special warfare Units of any branch of service.  Det 5 flies three C-2A greyhounds, better known as the C.O.D. (Carrier Onboard Delivery), emblazoned with the "NF" markings of the Operational Commander, Carrier Air Wing FIVE (CVW-5). <br><br>

    The C-2A is a twin engine aircraft manufactured by Grumman.  Maximum payload capacity is 10,000 pounds with the ability to carry 26 passengers.  Det 5 supports USS INDEPENDENCE (CV 62), and Commander Fleet Air Western Pacific (COMFAIRWESTPAC). <br><br>

Fleet Logistics Support Squadron THREE ZERO (VRC-30) of San Diego, CA, recently expanded it's Theater of Operations to include the Kanto Plains of Japan.  The disestablishment of the VRC-50 "FOO-DOGS" on September 29, 1994 at Andersen AFB, Guam led to the establishment of the VRC-30 Det 5 "PROVIDERS" on August 7, 1994, at NAF Atsugi.  VRC-30 Det 5 is the first and only permanently forward deployed carrier logistics detachment in the Navy. <br><br>

    Detachment 5 currently consists of seven officers and thirty-four enlisted troops, with the final manning requirements arriving by July 1995.  Arriving on August 7, 1994, temporary personnel from San Diego were initially assigned to Det 5 to provide services to the USS INDEPENDENCE during its final at sea period before dry dock, carrying a total of 84 passengers and 20,000 pounds of cargo.  The permanent personnel who have since replaced the temporary personnel are ordered to Japan for two to three years.  The first was AE2 Houston Johnson who arrived on July 8, 1994, and was assigned temporarily to AIMD, awaiting the detachment arrival.  AE2 Johnson was command advanced on November 16, 1994, to AE1 by CDR J.D. Fowler, Commanding Officer of VRC-30, on a visit to Japan. <br><br>

    The stand up process culminated in a "Change of Charge" ceremony.  LCDR J.A. Hubbard relieved CDR L.C. Shaffer-Vanaria on December 1, 1994 as Officer in Charge of VRC-30 Det 5.  On that day the first Det 5 C-2A Greyhound aircraft was flown by LT M.D. Laslo, LT J.K. Mitchell, and ADC R.J. Holsworth.  The detachment has three aircraft assigned with side numbers 430, 431, and 432. <br><br>

    Det 5 has devoted many hours, working extremely long days, weekends, and holidays in an attempt to stand up the det and keep the aircraft flying.  Prior to operations in December, the detachment underwent a Material Condition Inspection (MCI)/ Maintenance Programs Assist (MPA) on November 14, 1994 to determine if the PROVIDERS were safe for flight.  The results of the MCI were in the det's favor, safe for flight.  The results of the MPA were outstanding.

<br><br>
</P>
<br><br>

