<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR>HMAS SYDNEY<br>(FFG 03)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>HMAS SYDNEY (FFG 03)</title>
<hr>
<img src="ffg3.jpg" alt= "" align=right align=middle height=213 width=400>

<h2>HMAS SYDNEY<br>(FFG 03)</h2>
Commissioned on 29 January 1983, HMAS SYDNEY is one of six guided missile
frigates in service with the Royal Australian Navy. Powered by two gas turbine engines, the ship is capable of speeds up to 30 knots.  SYDNEY is a long range escort with the ability to provide area air defence, anti-sub-marine warfare, surveillance, reconnaissance and interdiction. She can counter simultaneous threats from the air, surface and sub-surface environments. The ship's principal weapons are Standard anti-air missiles and
Harpoon anti-ship missiles, both of which are launched from a Mk 13 launcher on the forecastle. A 76 mm rapid fire gun to counter both air and surface threats is fitted forward of the funnel and one 20 mm Phalanx close-in weapon system (CIWS) for anti-missile defence is fitted above the helicopter hangar. Two Mk 32 triple torpedo tubes are fitted to the ship for close-in anti-submarine defence. Long range radars and the 5-70B-2 Seahawk helicopter are the primary means by which targets are located
and classified.	The ship has a normal complement of 212 personnel, of whom 36 are female. SYDNEY has deployed to the Middle East three times during her career. On the first occasion she took part in Operation Desert Storm, the action against Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War, for which she earned a Meritorious Unit Citation. The second and third times were to the northern Red Sea in support of United Nations sanctions against Iraq during 1991/92 and from June to December 1993.<br>
The name SYDNEY has been carried by three former RAN warships; a light cruiser which served from 1913 to 1928; a second light cruiser from 1935 to her loss in 1941 and an aircraft carrier/fast troop transport, from 1948 to 1973.<br>
<br>
<pre>
<strong>Ship's Data</strong>
Keel Laid down..........................16 January 1980
Launched................................26 September 1980
Commissioned............................29 January 1983
Builder.................................Todd Pacific Shipyards, Seattle, USA
Displacement............................4, 100 tons
Length..................................138 metres
Beam....................................13.7 metres
Speed...................................30 knots 
Ship's Company..........................212

<strong>Armament</strong>
Harpoon anti-ship missiles
Standard anti-air missiles
One 76mm gun
Two Mk 32 triple anti-submarine	torpedo tubes
One Phalanx Mk 15 close-in weapon system
	
<strong>Aircraft</strong>
Two 5-70B-2 Seahawk helicopters

<strong>Machinery</strong>
Two General Electric LM2500 gas	turbines geared to one controllable pitch propeller
</pre>
<br>
<h5>Source - HMAS SYDNEY</h5><br>
