<br><br>
<h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<BR><br>CS SIMPSON (SS 21)</h1>
<br><br><br>
<title>CS SIMPSON (SS 21)</title>
<hr>
<img src="ss21.jpg" alt= "" align=right align=middle height=263 width=400>
<h2>CS Simpson<br>(SS 21)
</h2>
This is the third submarine of the Chilean Navy to bear the name.  The first one of the three "O" class submarines built in England in 1928; the second was one of the two "209" Class built in Germany for the Chilean Navy in 1984.<br>
The name has its origins in Vice Admiral Roberto SIMPSON who was Commander in Chief of Chilean Fleet.  During the war against Peru and Bolivia Confederation in 1836 to 1839.  He won over Confederation Fleet in the Battle of Casma.<br>
After the war he was Commander in Chief of the Chilean Navy and in the finish of his life he was a delegate in the Chilean parliament.  He died in 1877.<br>
<h3>Characteristics</h3>
<pre>
Displacement
Surfaced........................................1,260 tons
Submerged.......................................1,400 tons

Speed
Surfaced........................................11 knots
Submerged.......................................21.5 knots

Main Machinery..................................Diesel-Electric motors

Torpedo Tubes...................................8 (on Bow)

Propeller.......................................1

Dimensions......................................195.2 feet long
                                                20.3 feet wide
                                                18 feet tall

Complement
Officers........................................9
Enlisted........................................37
</pre>

<hr>
<h3>Submarines In The Chilean Navy
</h3>
Submarine activities in Chile go as far back as 1886 when Mr. C. Flachs designed and built a Submarine which he intended to sell to the Chilean Navy.  His boat turned out to be a cigar shaped tube 13 meters long, had a crew of six and carried a small cannon for surface actions and a "Submarine Cannon" of which no details are available.  The boat was successfully tried, but unfortunately when the official demonstration was presented to the President  of the Republic who in fact was invited to participate in the trials but very wisely refused the boat submerged amid the cheers of the crowds but never again surfaced.<br>
The second adventure recorder, is the submarine designed by Mr. J. Huber, prefabricated in Santiago assembled in Talcahuano in 1896.  It had a displacement of  15.5 tons, was 8 meter's in length and had a crew of five.  It was propelled by an 8 H.P. electric motor and its batteries had endurance of ten hors.  
This boat was successful on trails but did not attract the attention of the Naval authorities of the time.<br>
The first submarines built for the Navy were the "IQUIQUE" and the "ANTOFAGASTA" in 1913 in the U. S. A. but these were diverted to Canada when the first world war broke out.  Due to the fact that the Royal Navy took two Battleship and number of Destroyers being built for two Battleship and number of Destroyer being built for Chile in U. K. yards between 1912 and 1914, the R. N. ceded five "H" Class Submarines being built at the Electric Boat Company in America.  Chile purchased on more and on the 4th of July 1917 the six submarines were commissioned with the names of famous Araucanian women; Quidora, Tegualda, Fresia, Guale, Rucmilla Guadcolda.  These were magnificent boats and served for thirty eight years in the Navy.<br>
In 1928 three "O" Class boats were built by Vickers-Armstrong Ltd., for Chile and commissioned in 1929, they were the "O'BRIEN", "THOMSON", and "SIMPSON".  These submarines were scrapped in 1957 after twenty eight years of very good service.<br>
The U.S. Navy in 1962 turned over to the Chilean Navy the USS SPOT and USS SPRINGER and they served with the names of "SIMPSON" and "THOMSON".<br>
"O'BRIEN" and "HYATT" ordered in 1970, will fulfill the requirement of replenishing and modernizing the submarine branch of the Chilean Navy.<br>
Moreover the Oberon class, the Chilean Navy has two U-209 Submarine class which were commissioned between the months of September and December of 1984.<br>
The crew for Chilean Submarines was trained, between 1917 and 1982, at the Submarine School in Valparafso.<br>
At the present, the Submarine School is on the Naval Base of Talcahuano.<br>
<br>
<hr>

<h3>Generaciones De "Simpson"</h3>

Durante el periodo entre ambas guerras mundiales, la importancia del submarino como arma ofensiva va en aumento, es asi como en 1980 solo un pais contaba con ellos y a fines de 1939 eran 266 los que los poseian, entre ellos Chile.<br>
Desde comienzos de siglo, el alto mando de la Armada se intereso en la significativa contribucion que el submarina podia aportar al Poder Naval.<br>
La Posibilidad de contar con submarinos oceanicos que incrementaran la potencialidad de la fuerza operativa de la epoca, se tranformo en una realdad con el desarrollo que habian alcanzado los submarinos despues de finalizada la Primera Guerra Mundial.<br>
A principios de 1928, se imparten las ordenes para adquirir tres submarinos de 1520 toneladas y son designadas las dotaciones que se componian de 5 oficiales y 47 hombres por submarino.<br>
La construccion se llevo a efecto en los Astillros de la firma Vickers Armstrong Ltda., en la ciudad de Barrow-In-Furness en Inglaterra.<br>
Fueron unidades modernas para su epoca y estaban dotadas con todos los adelantos conocidos hasta ese momento.  Tenian un andar maximo en superficie de 15 nudos.  Sumergidos lograban alcanzar 8 nudos por una hora, contando para ello con dos motores electricos de propulsion.  Para atacar, tenian 6 tubos lanzatorpedos a proa y 2 a popa, ademas de un canon de 120 m/m. para acciones en superficie.<br>
Los sumergibles fueron bautizados con nombres que recuerdan a los ilustres heroes de nuestra Armada; Almirante don Roberto SIMPSON Simpson y los Capitanes de Fragata Don Manual THOMSON Porto y don Jorge O'BRIEN.<br>
El 16 de Diciembre de 1929 izo su insignia de Comorodo de Flotilla el Capitan de Navio (SM.)  Don Julio ALLARD Pinto en uno de los submarinos y el 27 de ese mismo mes zarpo con las tres unidades hacia Chile, recalando el 15 de Marzo en Quintero, donde fue revistada la fllotilla por el Presidente de la Republica, General don Carlos IBANEZ Del Campo.<br>
El buque madre de submarinos "ARAUCANO", recalo al pais en 1930, pocos meses despues de la llegada de los submarinos tipo "O".  La dotacion del BMS., era de 350 tripulantes incluyendo 22 Oficiales.<br>
Como apoyo a los submarinos en repqraciones o en reserva, existio, en lo que se llamaba "Arsenales de Talcahuano", una Base de Submarinos que funciono con el nombre de "Subdepartamento de Submarinos"<br>
Para desempenar su importante funcion contaba con;molo de atraque, una  maestranza de combustion interna con fundicion y taller de niquelado un hospital de baterias para almacenarias y mantenerlas, una planta destiladora, un panol de requestos y varios de consumos, un casino de Oficiales,  un cuartel para personal una denstistica,, una cancha de tenis y otra de futbol y Oficinas para la Comandancia, Segunda Comandancia, Secretaria, contadura y Sala de Conferencias.<br>
Esta infraestructure fue disuelta a principios de la decada del 60, siendo distrubuidos sus medios y recursos en el antiguo Arsenal, actual planta industrial de ASMART Talcahuano.<br>
<br>
<br>
<h5>Source - Chilean Navy</h5><br>
