<html>
<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - VFA-192
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="vfa192lg.gif"><img src="vfa192pl.jpg"></a><br>
<h2> Strike Fighter Squadron ONE NINE TWO </h2><br>
<br></center>
</b>
<P> 	Strike Fighter Squadron One Nine Two, the World Famous Golden Dragons, are members of Carrier Air Wing Five embarked in the USS Independence (CV 62) and homeported in Yokosuka, Japan.  The squadron's strength is 22 officers, 10 chief petty officers, and 180 enlisted men. <br><br>

	The World Famous Golden Dragons look back on an illustrious history spanning more than fifty years.  The squadron was established  on 26 March 1945, standing up with the F5F Hellcat.  Since then, the Dragons have flown an impressive lineup:  the F4U Corsair, F9F-5 Panther, F9F-6 Cougar, FJ-4B Fury, A-4D Skyhawk, and the A-7E Corsair II.  Today, the Dragons patrol the skies with the Navy's newest and most capable aircraft ever, the F/A-18 Hornet. <br><br>

	While flying the F9F-5 Panther from the USS Oriskany (CVA 34), the Golden Dragons participated in the filming of the 1953 classic, "The Bridges of Toko Ri".  The squadron aded "World Famous" to its moniker as a result of its appearance in the film. <br><br>

	In 1959, the Dragons started flying the highly successful A-4 Skyhawk from the decks of the USS Bon Homme Richard (CVA 31) and the USS Ticonderoga (CVA 14).  The A-7 Corsair II replaced the A-4 in 1970.  The Dragons flew their Scooters and Corsairs in the skies over Vietnam on six combat deployments between 1964 and 1973.  LCDR Michael  J. Estocin, a Golden Dragon, earned the Congressional Medal of Honor for his gallantry and courage on the 20th and 21st of April 1967 while flying on a missle suppression mission.  In his memory, the Navy's award for the best F/A-18 squadron is called the Michael J. Estocin Award. <br><br>

	After their success in Vietnam, the Dragons made two Mediterranean cruises aboard the USS America (CV 66).  Later, the squadron joined Carrier Air Wing Nine and sailed in the USS Ranger (CV 61).  Between cruises, the Dragons deployed "Marine style" with Marine Air Group Twelve.  The squadron flew its 12 A-7E Corsair II's across the Pacific in June, 1985, and began operating from MCAS Iwakuni, Japan.  During this unique deployment, then VA-192 provided air support for Marine ground units operating throughout the Western Pacific region. <br><br>

	The Golden Dragons returned to their homes in Lemoore, California, in December that year.  The following month, the squadron was redesignated Strike Fighter Squadron 192 (VFA 192), and received its first of 12 McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornets in May.  In November the Dragons again flew to Japan, this time to establish themselves as permanent members of Carrier Air Wing Five (CVW-5), the Navy's only forward deployed air wing. <br><br>

	While deployed to Japan, the Dragons established themselves as the leaders of the air wing.  In 1989 the squadron received the Commander, Naval Air Force U. S. Pacific Fleet Battle Effectiveness Award, and was later honored with the Michael J. Estocin Award. <br><br>

	On October 2, 1990, the Dragons set sail for the troubled waters of the Arabian Gulf.  The United States had set in motion a firm response to Iraqi aggression against its neighbor, and CVW-5, embarked in USS Midway (CV 41), was chosen to support that stand.  When hostilities broke in January 1991 the Dragons were at the tip of America's sword, raining HARM anti-radiation missles onto Iraqi missile batteries on the first night of Operation Desert Storm.  The Golden Dragons played a crucial role in the conflict by delivering, with pinpoint accuracy, 730,200 pounds of ordnance onto its assigned targets.  The squadron defended the battle group against air and surface targets.  The squadron defended the battle group against air and surface attack while flying Combat Air Patrol and Armed Surface Reconnaisance missions.  The Dragons did not lose an aircraft or pilot during the conflict. <br><br>

	The squadron traded its battle tested F/A-18A's for newer F/A-18C's in September, 1991, as CVW-5 completed an historic swap from the Midway to the Independence in Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.  The Dragons deployed again to the Arabian Gulf in 1992 and continue to lead Naval Aviation at America's Tip of the Sword. 

<br><br>
</P>

