<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - VA-115
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="Va115cr.jpg"></a><img src="Va115pl.jpg"></a><br>
<h2> Attack Squadron ONE ONE FIVE</h2>
<h2>Command History </h2><br>
<br></center>
</b>
	<P> On 10 October 1942, the predecessor of Attack Squadron ONE ONE FIVE (VA-115) was commissioned as Torpedo Squadron ELEVEN (VT-11) by the Navy Department.  Pilots and crews found themselves strapping into the "new" Grumman designed TBM AVENGER, a carrier based torpedo bomber affectionately known in the fleet as the "Turkey."  So began the history of one of the oldest naval aviation squadrons still in commission in the Pacific Fleet, a history which grows more distinguished each year. <br><br>

	In June 1943, CVG-11 pilots conducted the first daylight raids on Bougainvilla and the Solomon Islands from USS HORNET (CV-12).  They also made bombing attacks on such places as Manda, Villa, and Rahili during desperate fighting for the Solomons and New Georgia.  When the war ended, Torpedo Squadron ELEVEN was redesignated Attack Squadron TWELVE ABLE (VA-12A). <br><br>

	VA-12A underwent extensive retraining before embarking aboard USS VALLEY FORGE (CVA-45), then the Navy's newest carrier.  The globe-circling cruise that ensued was the first for a Navy Air Group, and a milestone for the squadron. A symbolic globe was later to become part of the squadron's official emblem. <br><br>

	In July 1948, VA-12A was again redesignated, this time as Attack Squadron ONE ONE FIVE (VA-115).  In addition, the Navy's newest, most powerful, and what was to be its last propeller-driven fighter-bomber, the Douglas built AD-1 SKYRAIDER, replaced the older TBM's. <br><br>
	During the Korean War, VA-115 flew 2,268 combat missions involving close air support, long range strikes, and reconnaissance missions.  For its outstanding performance in destroying enemy targets, the squadron was awarded the Presidential Unit Citation. <br><br>

	During the peacetime deployment that followed, the squadron adopted the nickname "ARABS" after a passage through the Suez Canal and was named the winner of the coveted Battle Efficiency Award in 1960.  In October 1965, the squadron returned to Southeast Asia, this time on board USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63), to aid the U.S. effort in South Vietnam.  While serving on the line for six months in the Gulf of Tonkin, VA-115's twenty  aircrew flew 2,051 sorties, 8,012 hours, and delivered 6,920,000 pounds of ordnance against enemy targets. <br><br>

	In September 1966, VA-115 became an integral component of Carrier Air Wing FIVE; however, the squadron was decommissioned in July 1967.  In 1970, VA-115 was recommissioned and relocated at NAS Whidbey Island, Washington while transitioning to the Grumman A-6A INTRUDER. <br><br>

	In 1971, as part of CVW-5  on board USS MIDWAY (CV-41), VA-115 made their first WESTPAC combat deployment in the A-6A Intruder.  For their subsequent April 1972 deployment to the Vietnam conflict, the Arabs were awarded the Presidential Unit Citation.  In September 1973, MIDWAY and VA-115 became part of the Navy's only forward deployed battle group when they changed their homeport to Yokosuka, Japan.  In April 1975, MIDWAY was again called to Vietnam to participate in Operations EAGLE PULL and FREQUENT WIND, the evacuation of Saigon. <br><br>

	VA-115 was the last actively commissioned Navy squadron to fly the A-6A/A-6B, transitioning to the A-6E in the summer of 1977.  In March 1978, VA-115 changed their nickname from "ARABS" to "EAGLES." <br><br>

	In 1980, the squadron received the new A-6E TRAM aircraft and was awarded its second consecutive Battle Efficiency award from COMNAVAIRPAC.  In September 1983 the EAGLES provided rescue support following the Soviet shootdown of Korean Airlines Flight 007 in September 1983. <br><br>

	In 1985, VA-115 was named "West Coast Intruder Squadron of the Year,"  and in October 1987, the squadron decreased in size to nine aircraft with the addition of the "NIGHTHAWKS" of VA-185 to CVW-5.  The EAGLES then deployed to the Indian Ocean, providing safe passage for reflagged Kuwaiti tankers in the Persian Gulf during Operation EARNEST WILL.  In 1988, the EAGLES participated in the Summer Olympic Games security operations off the coast of Korea. <br><br>

	On October 2, 1990 the EAGLES deployed to the North Arabian Gulf in support of Operation DESERT SHIELD.  On the 17th of January 1991, EAGLE Intruders were among the first to launch from USS MIDWAY to mark the beginning of Operation DESERT STORM.  During the six week war against Iraq, the EAGLES phenomenal performance included 463 combat sorties which resulted in 953 total combat hours and 724,000 pounds of ordnance delivered on enemy targets throughout Iraq and occupied Kuwait.  The squadron also led CVW-5 in the destruction of Iraqi naval vessels with 12 confirmed kills, all without a single loss of aircraft or men. <br><br>

	In July 1991, VA-185 disestablished, transferring many of her aircraft, officers, and men to the EAGLES.  After an August 1991 transit to Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, a historic cross deck move from USS MIDWAY (CV-41) to USS INDEPENDENCE (CV-62) was completed.  In September, the EAGLES received six of the fleet's newest A-6E SWIP aircraft. <br><br>

	In April 1992 VA-115 deployed on board USS INDEPENDENCE to the Arabian Gulf, where they participated in the initial phase of Operation SOUTHERN WATCH in support of United Nation resolutions against Iraq.  During three weeks of conducting around the clock flight operations, EAGLE aircrew flew 115 combat missions over Iraq.  For their superb performance, the EAGLES were awarded the Meritorious Unit Commendation.  In November 1993, the EAGLES, with a complete complement of A-6E SWIP aircraft, deployed to the Persian Gulf in support of Operation SOUTHERN WATCH. By the close of the deployment, the EAGLES boasted tremendous statistics to include a 99% sortie completion rate that encompassed 618 consecutive sorties and earned the CVW-5 "Golden Wrench Award". Two months later the squadron deployed once again to participate in RIMPAC Exercises. The EAGLES again distinguished themselves as the  workhorse of CVW-5 by achieving a 100% sortie completion rate and providing a long range medium attack platform for the Air Wing to exploit the opposition. In addition, VA-115 received four of six new aircraft that were to be delivered during the summer of 1994 to give the EAGLES passive Night Vision capability.  The EAGLES extended their string of consecutive deployed sorties without a miss to over 1300. <br><br>

     In September 1994, VA-115 participated in its final Medium Attack Advanced Readiness program, deploying to Andersen AFB, Guam.  For sustained meritorious performance from 1 October 1993 to 31 December 1994, the EAGLES were awarded yet another Meritorious Unit Commendation.  In April 1995 VA-115 deployed onboard USS INDEPENDENCE for their Tailored Training Assessment and to the Gulf of Thailand for COBRA GOLD.  In July 1995, the squadron competed for the second year in a row in the Intruder Derby at NAS Whidbey Island, Washington.  The EAGLES were named Intruder Maintenance Squadron of the Year for 1995. <br><br>

     In August 1995, VA-115 commenced its final Indian Ocean/Arabian Gulf deployment, participating in Operation SOUTHERN WATCH/VIGILANT SENTINEL, INDIGO DESERT and EAGER ARCHER. <br><br>

	A "can do" spirit and team effort have been VA-115's trademarks for over fifty years.  In keeping with their motto, the EAGLES have consistently demonstrated that they are, and continue to be, the "Best Attack in WESTPAC." <br><br>
</P>
<br><br>

