<html>
<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - VAW-115
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="vaw115.jpg"></a><img src="vaw1152.jpg"></a><br>
<h2>Carrier Airborne Early Warning Squadron ONE ONE FIVE</h2><br>
</center>
</b>
<P>
<center><h2>THE GRUMMAN E-2C HAWKEYE AIRCRAFT</h2></center>

 <p>The E-2C mission of Airborne Early Warning and Control (AEW&C)
consists of detecting, identifying, and tracking long range threats
to the carrier battle group.  Additional missions include air
intercept and air combat control, surface search and surveillance
control, strike control for coordinated attacks, communications
relay, and search and rescue control. </p>

  <p>In addition to the United States, four other countries
currently employ the E-2C Hawkeye aircraft:  Egypt, Israel,
Singapore and Japan.  The aircraft may be easily identified by its
24-foot diameter rotodome and four vertical tails.  The E-2C flight
crew will normally consist of a Pilot (P), Copilot (CP), Combat
Information Center Officer (CICO), Aircraft Control Officer (ACO),
and Radar Officer (RO). </p>

  <p>There are two versions of E-2C Hawkeye aircraft being flown by
the U.S. Navy.  Built during the early 1970s, the "Group 0" uses
the APS 138 radar and is powered by two Allison T-56-A-425
turboprop engines with constant speed Hamilton-Standard propellers. 
Each engine develops a maximum of 4,600 Indicated Horsepower (IHP)
at takeoff.  The "Group II" began entering the U.S. Fleet in the
early 1990s and is scheduled to replace all remaining "Group 0"
aircraft within the next ten years.  The "Group II" uses the APS-
145 radar (which provides improved detection) and is powered by two
T-56-A-427 turboprop engines with a maximum of 5,100 IHP at
takeoff. </p>

<h3>AIRCRAFT WEIGHTS (GROUP 0)</h3>
<pre>
     Basic Weight...........................39,561 lbs / 17,980 kgs<br>
     Operating Weight (zero fuel)...........40,600 lbs / 18,454 kgs<br>
     Combat Weight (60 percent fuel)........48,040 lbs / 21,836 kgs<br>
     Takeoff  Weight (100 percent fuel).....53,000 lbs / 24,091 kgs<br>
</pre>
<h3>AIRCRAFT DIMENSIONS (GROUP 0) </h3>

<pre>     WING SPAN: <br>

          Wings spread...................80 feet 7 inches / 24.6 m<br>
          Wings folded...................29 feet 4 inches / 8.94 m<br>
          Prop tip to prop tip...........35 feet 5 inches / 10.8 m<br>

     LENGTH:  57 feet 7 inches / 17.6 m<br>

     HEIGHT:  18 feet 4 inches / 5.6 m<br></pre>

<br>(Weights and dimensions for Group II aircraft are slightly higher) <br><br>





   <h3><center>   UNITED STATES NAVY E-2C HAWKEYE SQUADRONS</h3></center> 

  <p>  There are currently 11 E-2C squadrons in the U.S. Navy.  The
East Coast squadrons, located in Norfolk, Virginia are:  VAW-120
"Greyhawks" (training squadron), VAW-121 "Blue Tails", VAW-123
"Screwtops" (currently transitioning to Group II aircraft), VAW-
124 "Bear Aces", VAW-125 "Tiger Tails", and VAW-126 "Seahawks". 
Flying "Group II" Hawkeyes, the West Coast squadrons, located in
Miramar, California are: VAW-112 "Golden Hawks", VAW-113 "Black
Eagles", VAW-116 "Sun Kings" and VAW-117 "Wall Bangers".</p>

    <p>Considered a West Coast squadron, the VAW-115 "Liberty Bells"
are attached to Carrier Air Wing 5, embarked on the USS
INDEPENDENCE (CV-62), as part of Forward Deployed Naval Forces
homeported in Yokosuka, Japan.  Its home airfield, Naval Air
Facility (NAF) Atsugi, is located in Ayase-Shi, Japan.  Due to
its overseas location, the Liberty Bells enjoy a myriad of
opportunities and challenges that are unique to forward deployed
units.  Being in the Far East, Carrier Air Wing FIVE often enjoys 
exciting liberty portcalls to Hawaii, Thailand, Philippines,
Australia, Singapore, Republic of Korea, and Hong Kong.  Since
USS INDEPENDENCE does not follow the traditional deployment
schedule of aircraft carriers homeported in the United States
(six months at sea followed by one year in port), VAW-115 engages
in a diverse and dynamic training schedule, often participating
in multinational exercises and joint cooperation with U.S. Air
Force assets. </p><br>

<h3><center>CARRIER AIRBORNE EARLY WARNING SQUADRON
ONE ONE FIVE (VAW-115)</center></h3><br>

 <center><h3>COMMAND COMPOSITION AND STRUCTURE</h3></center>

 <p>   VAW-115 is commanded by Commander Richard B. Wren, U.S. Navy,
a native of Washington, D.C.  The Executive Officer, Commander
Robert J. Schoppe, U.S. Navy, is a native of Philadelphia,
Pennsylvania.  The squadron is composed of 30 officers and 128
enlisted personnel.  VAW-115 flies and maintains five "Group 0"
E-2C Hawkeyes, call sign "Liberty", tailcode "NF".</p><br>

 <h3><center>SQUADRON NEWS</h3></center>  

   <p>    Approaching 25,000 safe flight hours, the Liberty Bells
recently celebrated their 29th birthday.  In his remarks to the
squadron, Commander Rick Wren attributed such achievement to the
all hands commitment to the principles of safety and
professionalism.  VAW-115 now stands as the only remaining squadron
from the original Carrier Air Wing 5. </p>

    <p>   VAW-115 will be holding its change of command on 11 July 1996. 
Commander Rick Wren will be relieved by Commander Robert Schoppe. 
Commander Wren will proceed to the Naval War College, Newport,
Rhode Island. <br></p>

                 <h3><center>   CURRENT STATUS (1 May 1996 - 2 July 1996) </h3></center><p>     The Liberty Bells are currently underway in support of RIMPAC
1996, a multinational exercise which includes combat forces from
U.S. Army, Air Force, Navy, Marine Corps and Coast Guard and also
Australian, Canadian, Chilean, and South Korean navies.  The
forces of RIMPAC will span the Pacific Ocean from the Canadian to
the Australian coastlines and will culminate in multiple,
simulated battle scenarios in the Hawaiian operating areas. 
Aircraft participating in RIMPAC include U.S. Air Force KC-130H,
KC-135, F-16C, B-52Hs and B-1B; Marine Corps KC-130s, AV-8Bs and
F-16N; Carrier Air Wings from the USS INDEPENDENCE (CV-62) and
USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63); Air National Guard E-3 B/C AWACS and F-
15A, and Naval Patrol Aircraft (P-3C) from Australia, Canada and
the United States.  Port calls include Manila, Republic of the
Philippines and Hawaii. </p><br>


 <h3><center>   COMMAND HISTORY</h3></center>  

   <p>   Carrier Airborne Early Warning Squadron ONE ONE FIVE
(VAW-115) was commissioned on 20 April 1967.  During its
assignment to Attack Carrier Wing 2, VAW-115 completed three
deployments to the Western Pacific Ocean aboard USS RANGER
(CVA-61). </p>

    <p>  The squadron transitioned from the E-1B "Willie Fudd" to the
E-2B in 1970 and joined Carrier Air Wing 5 aboard USS MIDWAY
(CV-41).  VAW-115 made two extensive deployments between May 1971
and April 1973 involving combat missions in the Gulf of Tonkin. 
On 11 September 1973, the Liberty Bells departed Alameda,
California, embarked on USS MIDWAY bound for Yokosuka, Japan to
become part of the only carrier and air wing to homeport outside
the continental United States.  For the period January 1973
through June 1974, VAW-115 was awarded the COMNAVAIRPAC Battle
Efficiency "E" as the finest E-2B Squadron in the Naval Air
Force, U.S. Pacific Fleet.  During April 1975, the USS MIDWAY
participated in operation FREQUENT WIND off the coast of South
Vietnam during the evacuation of Saigon.  In October 1975, MIDWAY
departed Yokosuka for the first of many cruises to the Indian
Ocean. </p>

   <p>   The operational expertise of VAW-115 was recognized with the
Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) Aviation Safety Award in January
1976.  In March 1976, the Bells received their second consecutive
Battle Efficiency "E" award and the "AEW Excellence" Award.  In
1977 the squadron earned its second consecutive CNO Safety Award. 
During 1978 the Liberty Bells were again awarded the Battle
Efficiency "E" and the "AEW Excellence" Award.  With only two
days notice, VAW-115 began its third Indian Ocean deployment in
April 1979.  The achievements during the three-month cruise
resulted in the award of a Navy Unit Commendation as well as the
Navy Expeditionary Medal.  September started the squadron's
fourth Indian Ocean deployment. </p>

 <p>     As a result of the Iranian seizure of the American Embassy in
Tehran and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, the cruise was
extended into February 1980 and the squadron was again awarded the
Navy Expeditionary Medal, as well as the Meritorious Unit
Commendation.  The fifth and sixth Indian Ocean deployments, from
August through November 1980 and February through June 1981,
yielded two more Navy Expeditionary Medals.  In the fall of 1982,
the Liberty Bells became the first VAW squadron to operate in the
Northern Pacific in over ten years.  In the spring of 1983, another
NORPAC deployment put VAW-115 in a three carrier battle group for
FLEETEX '83.  In September 1983, VAW-115 participated in the
search, rescue and salvage operations following the tragic
shootdown of Korean Airlines Flight 007 off the coast of northern
Japan.  The squadron was awarded a Meritorious Unit Commendation
and a Letter of Appreciation from the Republic of Korea.  VAW-115
was awarded a Meritorious Unit Commendation for extensive
operations conducted by Battle Group ALFA from July 1982 through
May 1984.  Also in 1984, the Liberty Bells left on their seventh
and longest deployment to the Indian Ocean in January 1984,
spending 111 consecutive days at sea. </p>

  <p>    In the spring of 1985, VAW-115 transitioned to the E-2C
Hawkeye.  Following this transition the Liberty Bells embarked for
another Indian Ocean cruise, returning to Atsugi in October.  On
31 December, 1985, a formal sister-squadron relationship with the
JASDF 601 AEW Squadron was signed, thus beginning a new era of
cooperation between the U.S. and the Japanese in the field of
mutual defense.  Deploying again in April 1987, the squadron and
CVW-5 operated in several exercises with the Royal Australian Navy
and a HARPOONEX in July with USAF B-52s.  Flying from Atsugi in
September, VAW-115 and units of VQ-1 supported contingency
operations for FREEDOM OF NAVIGATION conducted by the USS OLDENDORF
in the Sea of Japan.  The squadron again deployed to the Indian
Ocean on 15 October to support EARNEST WILL tanker escort
operations in the North Arabian Sea and Persian Gulf.  While off
Singapore, the Liberty Bells held exchange visits and flights with
Royal Singaporean Air Force (RSAF) 111 AEW Squadron and signed a
sister-squadron agreement on 20 February 1988.  VAW-115 was awarded
it's fourth Battle Efficiency "E" for the period July 1986 to
December 1987.  This deployment also resulted in VAW-115 being
awarded the Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal for support of
escorting reflagged tankers in the Persian Gulf.  In August 1989,
Battle Group ALPHA left Japan for another Indian Ocean cruise, with
stops in Singapore and Thailand.  Following a brief time
"on-station" in the Indian Ocean, the MIDWAY made port visits to
Mombasa, Kenya, and Perth, Australia.  Shortly after departing
Subic Bay, Philippines, Battle Group ALPHA was involved in
contingency operations in support of the Philippine government
during operation CLASSIC RESOLVE, earning VAW-115 the Armed Forces
Expeditionary Medal. </p>

<p>      On 2 October 1990 Battle Group ALPHA left Japan, deploying in
support of Operation DESERT SHIELD.  Enroute, VAW-115 sent an
airplane to Singapore on 18 October to participate in
sister-squadron flights with the Singaporean E-2 squadron, RSAF
111.  During Operation DESERT SHIELD, VAW-115 flew in support of
various exercises:  IMMINENT THUNDER, FREE LUNCH,  EAGER ANVIL, and
BEACON FLASH.  While at sea in support of Operation DESERT STORM,
the Liberty Bells flew 691.3 total flight hours and 179 combat
sorties.  In late February 1992, VAW-115 participated in sister-
squadron operations, including exchange flights, with the JASDF 601
AEW, thus broadening the mutual defense between the U.S. and
Japanese.  On 23 May 1992, the Liberty Bells left Japan, deploying
for four months to the Persian Gulf, returning in October 1992. 
During their deployment, VAW-115 supported Operation SOUTHERN
WATCH, controlling USN, USAF, and coalition air forces over the
skies of southern Iraq.  On 17 November 1993, CVW-5 and VAW-115
departed for a 4-month deployment to the Persian Gulf,
participating in several exercises including a combined MINEX in
the Gulf of Thailand and sister-squadron operations with the RSAF
111 E-2 Squadron.  In December 1993, VAW-115 participated in cross
aircrew training with the 963 AWACS in support of Operation
SOUTHERN WATCH, deploying to Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.  VAW-115 went on
to fly 125 sorties with 100 percent completion rate during January
and February of 1994.  After returning from deployment in mid-March
of 1994, VAW-115 set sail in support of RIMPAC '94 in June,
controlling and conducting numerous War-at-Sea strikes, and joint
combined surface and air scenarios.  During the period of mid-July
through August 1994, tense political conditions with North Korea
necessitated CVW-5 and VAW-115 maintaining a "Ready-for-Sea"
posture, alternating sea periods with short inport periods in
support of national emergent operational tasking.  The Bells'
performance through the course of 1994 earned the squadron the
Commander Naval Air Force, U.S. Pacific Fleet's Battle "E" Award. </p>

 <p>  While operating in the Gulf of Thailand in May 1995, VAW-115
provided AEW for numerous overland strike and air defense
exercises.  In September 1995, the Bells returned to the Persian
Gulf region in support of Operation SOUTHERN WATCH.  In November
1995, the Liberty Bells flew in support of ANNUALEX, a joint United
States/Japan exercise.  The Bells flew numerous AEW, War-at-Sea,
strike and air defense missions that included control of U.S. Air
Force and Japanese self-defense force assets. </p>

   <p>  In February 1996, VAW-115 participated in exercise VALIANT
USHER.  Working in South Korean airspace with U.S. Air Force
assets, VAW-115 provided AEW and airborne control  in coordinated
strikes, amphibious landings and combat search and rescue
operations.  Prior to its return to Japan, the USS INDEPENDENCE was
delayed off the coast of Taiwan due to escalating tensions between
China and Taiwan. </p>

    <p>  As the only forward deployed E-2C Hawkeye squadron in the
United States Navy, VAW-115 continues to lead the way in readiness
and performance while operating in the highly demanding environment
of the Far East and Western Pacific. </p><br>



<h3><center>   VAW-115 PUBLIC AFFAIRS</h3></center>    

  <p>  If there are any comments or questions concerning the E-2C
Hawkeye aircraft or VAW-115 "Liberty Bells", or if interested in
squadron memorabilia (t-shirts, patches, pen/pencils, photos, 
etc.), write to: </p><br>

<strong>     VAW-115 PAO<br>
     FPO AP 96601-6403<br>
     U.S. (if outside the U.S.) <br><br></strong>

                       <em><strong>FLY NAVY!!!</strong></em>
<br><br>

<br><br>
</h5></P>
