<html>
<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - VS-21
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<img src="vs21lg.gif"></a><img src="vs21P.JPG"></a><br>
<h2> Sea Control Squadron TWO ONE<br> "Fighting Redtails" </h2><br>
<br></center>
</b>
<P> 


	The origin of VS-21 can be traced back to March 26, 1945 when Escort Carrier Air Group FORTY ONE (CVEG-41) was established.  This new squadron was formed by merging Fighting FORTY ONE (VF-41) and Torpedo FORTY ONE (VT-41).  VF-41 was equipped with the Ryan FR-1 "Fireball" fighter-bomber, earning the distinction of becoming the first navy squadron to fly a jet powered aircraft.  VT-41 flew the Grumman TBM-3E "Avenger", the finest carrier-based patrol/attack aircraft of its day.  Together under one command, they formed a very formidable anti-submarine "Hunter-Killer" team.  On November 15, 1946, CVEG-41 was redesignated as Escort Carrier Air Group ONE (CVEG-1) to become one of only two air groups dedicated to developing carrier-based Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW) tactics and conducting fleet ASW operations.  In early 1948, the FR-1 "Fireball" was replaced by the Grumman F6F-5N "Hellcat" night fighter-bomber.  On September 1, 1948, CVEG-1 was redesignated as Composite Squadron TWO ONE (VC-21).  VC-21 retained only the extremely capable patrol/attack TBM-3E "Avenger" as fighter-bombers were no longer deemed necessary to the ASW role. <br><br>

	In April 1950 VC-21 was redesignated as Air Anti-Submarine Squadron TWO ONE (VS-21).  Three months later, on July 4, 1950, the Fighting Redtails became the first carrier-based squadron to depart the United States for the Korean War.  Flying the TBM-3E from Japan, a squadron detachment assisted in the evacuation of wounded from Kotori Airstrip near the Chosan Reservoir prior to its loss to communist Chinese ground forces.  After the squadron returned to NAS North Island, San Diego, in February 1951, VS-21 began transitioning to the Grumman AF-2 "Guardian" series aircraft.  Again, the Redtails returned to the two plane search-attack/hunter-killer concept with the AF-2W "Hunter" and AF-2S "Killer" team. <br><br>

	In December 1954, VS-21 became the first West Coast VS squadron to receive the new Grumman S-2F "Tracker".  The "Tracker" was specifically designed as a single mission ASW platform, combining both the search-attack and hunter-killer missions into one aircraft.  Following their successful deployment on the USS PRINCETON (CVS-37), the Redtails were awarded the Commander, Naval Air Force, United States Pacific Fleet Battle Efficiency "E", the first VS squadron to ever win this widely coveted award.  After follow-on deployments on USS KEARSAGE and USS PHILIPPINE SEA, VS-21 divided to become the new VS-21 and her sister squadron, VS-29. <br><br>

	The "Sixties" was a decade of support roles and expanding tactical responsibilities.  After assisting in the recovery of two Project Mercury capsules, SIGMA 7 and FAITH 7, VS-21 made her first deployment to the South China Sea in support of Vietnam operations.  It was here that the new role of shipping surveillance and interdiction was first introduced to the VS community as a primary mission. <br><br>

	In 1974, VS-21 was selected to introduce the Lockheed S-3A "Viking" ASW aircraft to the fleet.  The twin turbo fan powered "Viking", with its advanced electronics, computer technology and high performance flight capabilities, was designed to meet the increasingly lethal Soviet guided-missile submarine threat of the 1970's.  VS-21 sailed into the Mediterranean Sea onboard USS JOHN F. KENNEDY (CV-67) on the first Viking deployment in February 1975.  That same year, the "Redtails" won the Battle Efficiency "E", the CNO Safety Award, and the Captain Arnold J. Isbell Trophy for ASW excellence.  Since then, VS-21 has made multiple deployments on the USS CONSTELLATION (CV-64), USS KITTY HAWK (CV-63), USS RANGER (CV-61), and the USS ENTERPRISE (CVN-65), ending with her famous "Round the World" cruise of 1990. <br><br>

	Leading the charge again, VS-21 was selected by Commander, Naval Air Force, United States Pacific Fleet to be the first West Coast squadron to transition to the Lockheed S-3B.  This transition was complete in April 1991 following training at NAS Cecil Field, Florida.  The "Bravo" version maintains the same airframe and flight systems as the S-3A, but incorporated an extensive Weapons System Improvement Program that added an advanced imaging capable ISAR RADAR, state-of-the-art Electronic Support Measures (ESM) and Electronic Counter Measures (ECM) systems, and vastly improved ASW capability.  In addition to ASW, the S-3B now employs the AGM-84C Harpoon anti-ship missile in the anti-submarine warfare (ASUW) role and uses its superior ESM system to passively locate and track targets as an independent electronic warfare (EW) platform.  In August 1991, VS-21 embarked aboard USS INDEPENDENCE (CV-62) and joined Carrier Airwing FIVE (CVW-5) to become the first permanently forward deployed VS squadron in the history of the United States Navy.  In keeping with the S-3B's phenomenal multi-mission capability, VS-21 was redesignated as Sea Control Squadron TWO ONE, in September 1993.  The "Fighting Redtails" now reside with the rest of CVW-5 at NAF Atsugi, Japan. <br><br>

	VS-21 has been awarded the Meritorious Unit Commendation, the Navy Expeditionary Medal, two Armed Forces Expeditionary Medals, the Joint Meritorious  Unit Award, six Commander Naval Air Force United States Pacific Fleet Battle Efficiency "E" Awards, five Chief of Naval Operations Safety Awards, four Arnold J. Isbell Awards for ASW Excellence, the Commander, Air Anti-Submarine Wing United States Pacific Fleet Top Torpedo Award, the Commander Mine Warfare Command "Miner of the Year" Award, two Golden Anchor and one Silver Anchor Awards, and most recently, the Commander Seventh Fleet Award for ASW Excellence.

<br><br>
</P>
<br><br>

