<html>

<title>CO, USS CLEVELAND (LPD 7)</title>

<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="lpd7co.gif" alt=""ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=MIDDLE width=280 height=342></h1>
<h1>Captain<br>
Larry W. Nelms, USN</h1>
<h2>Commanding Officer,<br>
USS CLEVELAND (LPD 7)</h2>
Captain Larry W. Nelms was born in Farmington, Missouri. He holds a Bachelor of Science Degree from Southeast Missouri State University in Zoology and Chemistry and a Master of Science Degree from the Naval Postgraduate School. He entered the Navy through the Aviation Officer Candidate Program and was designated a Naval Aviator in May 1972.<br>
His first assignment was with Helicopter Anti-Submarine Squadron FOUR, "The Black Knights" embarked in the USS TICONDEROGA (CVA 14), USS KITTY HAWK (CV 63) and USS RANGER (CV 61). In December 1975, he reported to Helicopter Anti-Submarine Squadron TEN as an instructor pilot and COMNAVAIRPAC H-3 NATOPS evaluator. His next tour, August 1978, was as Air Boss aboard 
USS DENVER (LPD 9) where he earned his Surface Warfare Officer (SWO) designation. Following the USS DENVER, Captain Nelms attended Naval Postgraduate School where he received a Master of Science Degree in Manpower, Personnel and Training Analysis. In December 1982, he reported back to Helicopter Anti-Submarine Squadron FOUR, where he served as Administrative, Maintenance and Operations Officer while on board USS CARL VINSON (CVN 70). Subsequently, he served in OPNAV Washington DC as Flag Administrative Aide to OP- 12 (Total Force Programming and Budgeting 
Division). Captain Nelms reported to Helicopter Anti-Submarine Squadron TWO, "World Famous Golden Falcons" as Executive Officer in December 1986 and assumed command in May 1988. The squadron was awarded the Battle "E" and CNO Safety Award during his tour. Following his command tour, he reported to COMNAVAIRPAC in November 1989 where he served as Helicopter Training and Readiness Officer. In March 1991 he reported to USS INDEPENDENCE (CV 62) as Executive Officer.  While there, the ship replaced the USS MIDWAY (CV 41) in Yokosuka, Japan. In August 1992, his tour 
was again in Washington DC, where he attended the INDUSTRIAL COLLEGE OF THE ARMED FORCES (ICAF). Following ICAF he reported to COMNAVAIRPAC as ACOS for Aircraft Carrier Training and Assessment (N7). Captain Nelms assumed the duties as Commanding Officer of USS CLEVELAND (LPD 7) on 20 January 1995.
<br>
Captain Nelms' awards include the Meritorious Service Medal (3), Navy Commendation Medal (3), Navy Achievement Medal, Navy Expeditionary Medal, Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal, Southwest Asia Service Medal, Humanitarian Service Medal and several Unit and Service Awards. 
<br>
<br>
<br>
