<body background="chalk.jpg">
<img src="rimpac3.gif" alt= "" align=left align=middle height=145 width=190>
<img src="sealusmc.gif" alt= "" align=right align=middle height=145 width=151>
<br><center><h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<br><br>11th Marine Expeditionary Unit</center></h1>
<hr>
<h1>Lieutenant Colonel Robert E. Gerlaugh</h1>
<h2>Commanding Officer
Marine Expeditionary Unit Service Support Group -- 11
</h2>
Lieutenant Colonel Robert E. Gerlaugh was born May 1, 1952 in Louisville, Kentucky.  He graduated from Old Centre College, Danville, Kentucky in May 1975 with a Bachelor of Arts Degree in Economics.  He was commissioned a Second Lieutenant in the Marine Corps May 27, 1975.<br>
LtCol. Gerlaugh graduated from The Basic School at Quantico, Virginia in December 1975 and was ordered to Naval Air Station, Pensacola, Florida.  In May 1976 he was transferred to the 2nd Marine Division, Camp Lejeune, North Carolina for duty.  Assigned to 6th Marine Regiment, he served as a Rifle Platoon Leader, Weapons Platoon Leader, Rifle Company Executive Officer and Headquarters Company Commander.<br>
Upon completion of this tour in 1978 LtCol. Gerlaugh was transferred to the 3rd Marine Division, Okinawa, Japan where he served as the Regimental Embarkation Officer for the 9th and 4th Marine Regiments.  In May 1979 he was transferred to the 1st Marine Brigade, Kaneohe Bay, Hawaii where he served initially as the Assistant Logistics Officer for Marine Aircraft Group-24 and then as the Logistics Officer for 1st Battalion, 3rd Marine Regiment.<br>
In August 1981 LtCol. Gerlaugh was ordered back to Quantico, Virginia to attend the Advanced Communications Officer's Course, Communication Officer's School.  Upon graduation in June 1982 he was ordered to attend the Logistics Officer's Course, Landing Force Training Command, Little creek, Virginia.  Upon graduation he reported to the U. S. Army Field Artillery School, Ft. Sill, Oklahoma in October 1982 for duty as the Marine Logistics Instructor.<br>
In August 1985 LtCol. Gerlaugh was ordered to the 7th Marine Expeditionary Brigade, Marine Corps Air Ground Combat Center, Twentynine Palms, California where he served as the Maritime Prepositioning Force  Officer.  In July 1988 he attended the College of Naval Command and Staff, Newport, Rhode Island where he earned a Masters Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies as well as a Master of Arts Degree in International Relations from Salve Regina College.<br>
Upon graduation in June 1989 LtCol. Gerlaugh reported to Plans, Policies, and Operations Division, Headquarters Marine Corps, Washington, D.C. where he served as the Maritime Prepositioning Force Program Officer.  In November 1991 he was promoted to his present rank.  In August 1992 he was ordered to attend the Marine Corps War College, Quantico, Virginia.  Upon graduation in June 1993 he was reassigned as a faculty advisor at the Marine Corps Command and Staff College.<br>
In July 1995 LtCol. Gerlaugh was transferred to First Force Service Support Group, Camp Pendleton, California where he served as the G-3 Plans Officer.  In February 1996 he was reassigned to his current billet as the Commanding Officer, MSSG-11 and shortly thereafter, selected for Colonel.<br>
His awards include; the Meritorious Service Medal w/ 2 Gold Stars, Marine Corps Expeditionary Medal, National Defense Service Medal, and the Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.<br>
LtCol. Gerlaugh is married to the former Kathleen Joy Creveling of Clinton, Iowa.<br>
<hr>
<h5>Source - 11th MEU</h5><br>
