<br><center><h1>RIMPAC 96<BR>Multi-National Force:<br><br>11th Marine Expeditionary Unit</center></h1>
<hr>
<h1>Stinger Missile System</h1>
The primary function of the Stinger Weapons System is to provide close-in, surface-to-air weapons fire for the defense of forward combat areas, vital areas, and installations against low altitude air attacks.<br>
The Stinger is a man portable, shoulder-fired guided missile system which enables a Marine to effectively engage low-altitude jet, propeller driven and helicopter aircraft.  Developed by the United States Army Missile Command, the Stinger was the successor to the Redeye Weapon System.<br>
The Stinger is a "fire-and-forget" weapon employing a passive infrared seeker and proportional navigation system.  This system is also designed for the threat beyond the 1990s, with an all-aspect engagement capability, and IFF (Identification-Friend-or-Foe), improved range and maneuverability, and significant countermeasures immunity.<br>
The missile, packed within its disposable launch tube, is delivered as a certified round, requiring no field testing or direct support maintenance.  A separable, reusable gripstock is attached to the round prior to use and may be used again.<br>

<h3>SPECIFICATIONS</h3>
<pre>
Range..........................................1 to 8 kilometers
Speed..........................................Supersonic in flight
Crew...........................................2
Warheads.......................................High explosive
Rate of fire...................................1 missile every
                                               3 to 7 seconds
Fuzing.........................................Penetration, impact,
                                               self destruct
Length.........................................5 feet
Weight.........................................12 pounds
Weight Fully armed.............................34.5 pounds
Propulsion:....................................Dual thrust solid 
                                               fuel  rocket motor
Manufacturer...................................General Dynamics/
                                               Raytheon Corporation

</pre>
