<!--e-mail: u00pa2b@cpf-emh.cpf.navy.mil-->
<html>
<title>CO,HMAS SYDNEY (FFG 03)</title>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<h1>Commander<br>
C.W. Darby, RAN</h1>
<h2>Commanding Officer,<br>
HMAS SYDNEY (FFG 03)</h2>
Commander Campbell Darby was raised on his parents property in North Western New South Wales. He attended Quirindi High School, before joining the Royal Australian Naval College, at Jervis Bay in 1973 Initial training was undertaken in a variety of ships and culminated in the award of a Bridge Watchkeeping Certificate in HMAS VAMPIRE in 1976. As a junior officer he undertook duties as the Executive Officer of the Papua New Guinea Landing Craft PNGS BUNA, and the Assistant Principal Warfare Officer (PWO) and Master Gunner of HMAS VAMPIRE.<br>
Promoted to Lieutenant in 1978 he was posted to the Naval College in 1979 as a Divisional Officer, before being selected for PWO training in the UK. PWO training was successfully completed in 1981 before undertaking an exchange posting with the Royal Navy on HM Ships RHYL and BERWICK in 1982/83.  This period was a career highlight involving many and varied deployments and being very rewarding professionally.  Returning to Australia, he was posted as the Operations Officer and ASW Officer of HMAS BRISBANE in early 1984.  Accompanied by his family, the newly promoted LCDR Darby was posted back to the UK in mid-1985 to teach prospective PWOs at the Royal Navy's School of Maritime Operations. HMS DRY AD.<br>
From the UK, a second career highlight ensued - this time a posting in command of the Fremantle Class Patrol Boat, HMAS IPSWICH, based in Cairns. This was followed by a posting to Maritime Headquarters (Sydney) in 1990 as the Fleet Anti Submarine Warfare Officer and a period as Commander Operations at the time the RAN was undertaking operations against Iraq in the Persian Gulf.  During this period he was also selected for promotion to Commander.<br>
Commander Darby was posted to the Canberra area in 1991 and completed a study into the RAN's Mine Warfare Forces before taking up the position of Assistant Director of Naval Officers' Posting responsible for career management of all officers of Lieutenant Commander rank and below.  This was followed in 1994 by a period of 12 months in the Directorate of Force Development working principally in the area of Naval Infrastructure development. Selection for major ship command has been undoubtedly the major career highlight and Commander Darby assumed command of HMAS SYDNEY on 13 July 1995.<br>
Commander Darby was married in 1978.  His wife Shani currently lives and works in Canberra with their two daughters Sarah (aged 13) and Jonanna (aged 11). They own a small property on the outskirts of Canberra, a home to numerous horses, dog's, cats and chooks and other itinerant stray animals. His interests include his family, all sports, particularly playing, tennis and golf and equestrian pursuits.<br> 
<br>
<br>
<br>
