<html>
<head>
<title>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE - Deputy Commander
</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><img src="dcag.jpg"></a><br>
<h2> CAPT Richard J. Mauldin <br><br>
Deputy Commander <br>
Carrier Air Wing FIVE<br></h2>
<br>
</center>
<p> 
A native of Porterville, California, Captain Mauldin enlisted in the Air Force in 1967. Trained in Chinese Mandarin at Lin Kou Air Station, Taiwan, he flew in RC-135 aircraft based out of Offutt Air Force Base, Nebraska.  Upon being honorably discharged in May 1975, he attended the University of Nebraska at Omaha, graduating in December 1976 and was designated a Naval Flight Officer in November 1977. </p>

<p> Captain Mauldin's first fleet squadron tour was with VAW 117 where served from March 1978 to March 1981.  While a member of the "WALLBANGERS," Captain Mauldin made two Western Pacific/Indian Ocean deployments with CVW-2 aboard USS RANGER (CV 61). </p>

<p> Assigned to VAW 110, the E-2C Fleet Replacement Squadron, in March 1981, Captain Mauldin served as flight instructor, NFO Training Officer and COMNAVAIRPAC E-2B NATOPS Evaluator. He returned to sea duty in July 1984, assigned to VAW 115 "LIBERTY BELLS," the Navy's only forward deployed E-2C squadron. During this tour he served as Administrative Officer and Maintenance Officer while participating in one Indian Ocean deployment and numerous joint and combined exercises in the Western Pacific operating area aboard USS MIDWAY (CV 41).  He was also instrumental in transitioning VAW 115 to the E-2C "HAWKEYE." </p>

<p> In January 1987, Captain Mauldin was Assigned to the Naval Military Personnel Command in Washington, D.C., attached to the Aviation Officers' Assignment Branch. He initially served as the VAW, VRC (PROP) Detailer and Interservice Transfer coordinator and subsequently, as the Sea Coordinator.  In July 1989 he returned to VAW 110 as the Executive Officer, serving in that capacity for 18 months. </p>

<p> In April 1991, Captain Mauldin reported as Executive Officer of VAW 115, assuming command of the "LIBERTY BELLS" in June 1992.  During this tour he helped establish the no-fly zone over southern Iraq. </p>

<p> Following this tour he attended the Naval War College, graduating in March 1995 with a Master of Arts Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies.  Captain Mauldin reported as Deputy Commander, Carrier Air Wing FIVE in August 1995. </p>

<p> Captain Mauldin has received the Meritorious Service Medal, Air Medal (2 awards), Navy & Marine Corps Commendation Medal (2 awards), Battle "E" Award (2 awards), Navy Expeditionary Medal, National Defense Service Medal (2 awards), Sea Service Deployment Ribbon (5 awards), and various other Air Force and Navy Awards. </p>

<p> Captain Mauldin is married to the former Linda Blackburn of Porterville, California.  They have three sons: Kirk, Kent, and Kyle and three daughters Kimberli, Kelli, and Kasi. </p>
 


</body>
