<html>
<body background="chalk.jpg">
<IMG SRC="cpf_logo.gif" alt= ""align=right align=middle></hi>
<h2><center>USS NEW ORLEANS<BR>Amphibious Readiness Group<BR>Ends Deployment</center></h2>
<title>NEW ORLEANS ARG Ends Deployment</title>
</center>
<hr>
The NEW ORLEANS amphibious ready group (ARG) returned to
San Diego December 22, 1995 after a highly successful six month western Pacific deployment. &nbsp; While deployed the ARG participated in numerous exercises to include Infinite Moonlight 95 in Jordan, Eager Mace 96-1 in Kuwait, and neon falcon in the gulf. &nbsp; Additionally the Sailors and Marines of the ARG hosted two very successful receptions, entertained numerous distinguished visitors and conducted more than 20 community relations projects in four countries.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The first stop for the NEW ORLEANS ARG, after its 23 June departure from San Diego, was Okinawa, Japan. &nbsp; The ships arrived July 11 for four days of sustainment training to exercise the U.S. Navy and Marine Corps team's ability to project combat power ashore.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During Okinawa operations, Vice Admiral Archie Clemins, Commander, U.S. Seventh Fleet, and Rear Admiral W. F. Doran, Commander Amphibious Group ONE, visited the NEW ORLEANS ARG. &nbsp; The July 13 visit allowed the admirals to talk with Sailors and Marines and tour all four ships.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After Okinawa the ships headed for Hong Kong then went on to a five day maintenance and training availability in Singapore. &nbsp; In Hong Kong, members of the ARG relaxed, shopped and took advantage of tours. &nbsp; On 26 July the ships arrived in Singapore where the 11th MEU(SOC), Naval Special Warfare Task Unit and Explosive Ordnance Disposal Detachment conducted a variety of individual and unit training at several sites throughout Singapore and conducted a community relations project.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The NEW ORLEANS ARG departed Singapore July 31 for its first stop in the Fifth Fleet area of responsibility; Aqaba: Jordan. &nbsp; The four ships arrived in the seaport city August 15 to conduct exercise Infinite Moonlight 95 which lasted until August 30.
The ships had not even moored before the off-load of Marines and equipment began. &nbsp; Helicopters from Marine Medium Helicopter Squadron (HMM)-164 began to off-load Marines and equipment to the Al Qatranah Training Area 194 miles away from Aqaba. &nbsp; Once pier side, the ships continued the off-load of the 11th MEU(SOC) entirely by ships' cranes in less than 21 hours.
Approximately 1,600 leathernecks made the trek inland where they endured temperatures in excess of 100 degrees during 10 days of training. &nbsp; While ashore the Marines interacted with Jordanian soldiers both professionally and socially. &nbsp; The 11th MEU(SOC) Marines established 14 live-fire ranges and conducted 113 separate live fire events. &nbsp; The field operations wrapped up with a combined U.S.-Jordanian brigade level live-fire exercise.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Back in the port, the ships hosted tours and numerous distinguished visitors. &nbsp; A reception, co-hosted by the Deputy Chief of Mission, Mr. Robert Beecroft and Vice Admiral Scott Redd, Commander U.S. Naval Forces Central Command and Commander Fifth Fleet, was held on the flight deck of USS NEW ORLEANS on August 22. &nbsp; Guests included Jordanian government officials, community leaders and businessmen as well as several foreign diplomats and attaches.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was something for everyone in Aqaba. &nbsp; Whether it was learning to say "Thank You" in Arabic or sampling the local cuisine, NEW ORLEANS ARG Sailors and Marines formed a bond of trust, cooperation and friendship with their Jordanian hosts. &nbsp; The Jordanian people expressed their best wishes for a safe journey and their hope for a future visit.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The ARG set sail for its next stop Jebel Ali, United Arab Emirates (U.A.E.). &nbsp; The ships arrived September 7 and stayed until the morning of September 19. &nbsp; This port visit was the first opportunity for the ARG to conduct major maintenance since it
Departed San Diego. &nbsp; Sailors and Marines worked hard to repair equipment and conduct preventive maintenance, but it was not all work. &nbsp; Marines and Sailors continued to build positive Arab-American relations through the completion of 10 community relations projects.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After completion of all maintenance, the NEW ORLEANS ARG departed Jebel Ali and headed towards Kuwait city, Kuwait, to conduct exercise Eager Mace 96-1, an interoperability exercise between U.S. forces and the Kuwaiti military. &nbsp; The ARG arrived September 21 and after completion of the off-load of embarked Marines headed back to sea for realistic underway training in the ever volatal Arabian Gulf.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;While Marines conducted exercise Eager Mace 96-1 ashore, the ships of the NEW ORLEANS ARG participated in exercise Reliant Gorilla which was designed by Amphibious Squadron SEVEN, with Carrier Group FIVE staff support, to develop the blueprint for ARG/Carrier Battle Group (CVBG) interoperability. &nbsp; This exercise was the first of its kind in the Arabian Gulf and will form the basis for future Fifth Fleet ARG/CVBG operations.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During exercise Eager Mace, tethered KC-130 aircraft from Marine Fixed Wing Aerial Refueling Squadron (VMGR)-352 conducted the first in flight refueling of Kuwaiti F/A-18's. &nbsp; During this 19 day exercise, the 11th MEU(SOC) conducted joint and combined training exercises which demonstrated the abilities and professionalism of a forward deployed force. &nbsp; As Eager Mace 96-1 came to an end, the Marines and Sailors of the 11th MEU(SOC) were visited by Brigadier General E. R. Langston, Deputy Commanding General 1st Marine Expeditionary Force, who stated, "You really shined in the desert and did a superb job of demonstrating the MEU's capabilities. &nbsp; Job well done". &nbsp; At the completion of the exercise the NEW ORLEANS ARG returned to Kuwait to embark the 11th MEU(SOC).<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Members of the NEW ORLEANS ARG Naval Special Warfare Task Unit (NSWTU) and Marine forces participated in Exercise Neon Falcon October 9-15. &nbsp; This exercise is part of a series of exercises which helped test and develop local gulf defense capabilities. &nbsp; The highlight of the exercise, and a first in the Arabian Gulf, was pier side and at sea dry deck shelter launch and recovery training on board a fleet subMarine by 11th MEU(SOC)'s Force Reconnaissance Platoon and Amphibious Squadron SEVEN's NSWTU.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During the period 13-23 October, each ARG ship had the opportunity to moor in Bahrain for a brief port visit. &nbsp; Each ship was visited by the Secretary of the Navy John H. Dalton on either 19 or 20 October. &nbsp; During the visit, the Secretary received a brief tour, conducted an awards ceremony and fielded a variety of questions from Sailors and Marines. &nbsp; He said the Sailors and Marines should take pride in their mission accomplishments, the traditions they uphold and in the country's gratitude for the sacrifices they and their families make.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On the evening of October 19, a reception was held on board the uss NEW ORLEANS to honor the secretary. &nbsp; The reception's co-hosts were the U.S. ambassador to bahrain, the honorable david m. Ransom, and commander Fifth Fleet, vadm redd. &nbsp; Over 300 bahraini government, military, business and community leaders as well as several foreign diplomats and attaches attended the reception. &nbsp; Guests received a short tour to include a static display of embarked helicopters. &nbsp; The
Evening concluded with brief remarks by vice admiral redd and the secretary of the Navy, after which the dignitaries participated in a cake cutting ceremony. &nbsp; Also, while in bahrain mgen frank libutti, commanding general 1st Marine division, visited the ARG, toured each ship and visited with Marines. &nbsp; During his stay he promoted and presented awards to a number of Marines.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After departure from Bahrain, the NEW ORLEANS ARG put to sea and participated in Exercise Reliant Gorilla October 25-27. &nbsp; The purpose of this exercise was to integrate the ARG and middle east force combatants into a cohesive maritime superiority force during the absence of a carrier battle group and to enhance joint operations in the Arabian Gulf. &nbsp; Middle east based Air Force A-10 aircraft were used in war at sea strikes coordinated by Navy air controllers. &nbsp; The exercise concluded with the takedown of a simulated sanctions violator (Maritime Prepositioning Squadron 2 supplied motor vessel William Baugh for the target ship) by a combined Navy/Marine Maritime Special Purpose Force. &nbsp;Another first, this exercise was extremely successful and the NEW ORLEANS ARG, along with her middle east force cruiser destroyer counterparts, performed flawlessly.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The NEW ORLEANS ARG departed the Fifth Fleet area of Responsibility November 10 with a sense of pride and accomplishment. &nbsp;Each sailor and Marine individually, and as a team, took comfort in the knowledge that they served their country, improved Arab-American relations, maintained forward presence and demonstrated America's commitment to this vital region.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After completion of three months of Middle East/Arabian  Gulf operations, the ARG began its return transit home via western Australia.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On November 20, Sailors and Marines manned the rails in their whites, as the NEW ORLEANS ARG entered the ports of Fremantle and Bunbury, Australia, for a five day port visit. &nbsp; The USS NEW ORLEANS (LPH-11), USS JUNEAU (LPD-10) and USS COMSTOCK (LSD-45) visited the city of Fremantle and the USS MOUNT VERNON (LSD-39) visited the city of Bunbury.
While in port, Sailors and Marines of the NEW ORLEANS ARG took tours, shopped for last minute Christmas presents and relaxed. &nbsp; Tours ranged from wine tasting to an adventure day tour in the famous Australian outback. &nbsp; Others took time to go to the beach, sunbathe and catch up on letter writing and reading. &nbsp; Additionally, the Navy and Marine Corps team volunteered their time for seven community relations projects. &nbsp; Further, the Sailors and Marines proudly displayed their ships and embarked equipment to the citizens of Australia for more than 6,000 visitors who toured some of America's finest warships.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the United States Thanksgiving Day is traditionally spent with one's family. &nbsp; For the NEW ORLEANS ARG, this day saw Sailors and Marines opening up their ships and their hearts to celebrate this special day with Australia's less fortunate youth. &nbsp; While USS JUNEAU and USS COMSTOCK hosted nearly 100 disadvantaged children to a traditional american thanksgiving dinner, USS NEW ORLEANS provided a special tour and treats to 150 physically challenged children. &nbsp;Captain Donald K. Bullard, Commanding Officer USS NEW ORLEANS and Colonel Robert B. Blose, Jr., Commanding Officer 11th MEU(SOC) personally hosted the children on their tour of USS NEW ORLEANS.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Australian port visit offered an excellent opportunity for the Sailors and Marines to relax, have fun and give something of themselves. &nbsp; The NEW ORLEANS ARG bid a fond farewell to their wonderful and gracious Australian hosts November 25.
After Australia the NEW ORLEANS ARG stopped for a one day visit to Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, to off-load Marine equipment, brief the Pacific Fleet Commander and Marine Forces Pacific Commander and pick up tigers. &nbsp; Tigers are friends and family members of Sailors and Marines who have the opportunity to share life at sea with their sponsor. &nbsp; During the transit to San Diego, the tigers witnessed ARG/MEU capabilities to include an air show by embarked helicopters and vip tours of the ships, which included embarked Marine equipment. &nbsp;Many of them completed an aggressive training program to earn honorary crew member status.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Early on 21 December the NEW ORLEANS ARG arrived off the coast of California and off-loaded the 11th MEU(SOC). &nbsp; With loved ones eagerly awaiting their arrival at sites throughout southern California, members of HMM-164, ACU FIVE, MSSG-11, Battalion Landing Team 2nd Battalion, 1st Marine Regiment (BLT 2/1), and helicopter Combat Support Squadron ELEVEN (HC-11) debarked ARG ships by land and sea.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With friends and family on the piers, the Sailors and Marines of the NEW ORLEANS ARG returned to San Diego with a tremendous sense of pride in all their professional and personal  accomplishments.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The NEW ORLEANS ARG is commanded by captain r. B. Ormsbee, Commander Amphibious Squadron SEVEN, and is composed of over 4,000 Sailors and Marines.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The 11th MEU(SOC) is commanded by Colonel Robert B. Blose, Jr. Units of the 11th MEU(SOC) include BLT 2/1, HMM-164 (REIN) and MSSG-11. &nbsp;  U.S. Navy support elements include detachments from Assault Craft Units ONE and FIVE, Beach Master Unit ONE, Tactical Air Control Squadron ELEVEN, Navy Special Warfare Command, Fleet Information Warfare Center Det, Helicopter Combat Support Squadron ELEVEN and Mobile Medical Augmentation Readiness Team FIVE.<br>


<center>-USN-</center>
