<html>SEC Proposes Technical Amendments To Rules Regulating Money Market
Funds</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/tax/mony/monyhead.gif"  alt="Money Manager's Compliance Guide"></center>
<hr>
<h2>SEC Proposes Technical Amendments To Rules Regulating Money Market
Funds</h2><P>
<body>
The Securities and Exchange Commission Dec. 18, 1996, proposed technical

amendments to rules and forms governing the operation of money market funds

under the Securities Act of 1933 (1933 Act) and the Investment Company Act of

1940 (1940 Act) (61 FR 66621).<p>

The proposal revises the regulation of money market funds under Rule 2a-7 of the

1940 Act, advertising rules for money market funds under Rule 482 of the 1933

Act, and Forms N-1A, N-3 and N-4. In addition, the proposal makes conforming

revisions to Rules 2a41-1, 12d3-1 and 31a-1 under the 1940 Act.<p>

<h3>Revisions to Rule 2a-7<p></h3>

In March 1996, SEC adopted final amendments, known as the March amendments, to

Rule 2a-7 (61 FR 13956, March 28, 1996). The amendments tightened the

risk-limiting conditions on tax-exempt money market funds and addressed the

treatment under Rule 2a-7 of certain instruments, such as asset-backed

securities (ABSs). Industry participants immediately raised concerns about the

complexity of the amendments and the terminology used in the rule, which in many

cases did not reflect common market usage.<p>

In response to concerns, SEC released an interpretive letter containing

questions  and answers from the commission staff. Because of the rule's

complexity and the need to read the rule in conjunction with the interpretive

letter, SEC later suspended the effective date of Rule 2a-7 until technical

amendments were developed (for information, see "Rule 2a-7 Changes on Hold

Pending Corrections," October 1996 Bulletin, p. 1).<p>

In addition to making technical corrections, the proposed amendments to Rule

2a-7 revise terminology used in the rule to reflect common market usage and

codify positions taken by SEC staff in the interpretive letter. The proposed

amendments also modify several of the March amendments so that the treatment

accorded instruments such as guarantees in the rule more closely reflects the

treatment accorded to those instruments by the financial markets, SEC said.<p>

One significant change in the proposed amendments is the replacement of

references to "puts" and "unconditional puts" with a new term "guarantee." The

change was proposed to address industry confusion regarding the types of

unconditional credit support that may be used to comply with the rule's credit

quality requirements. Designed to unconditionally support the credit of the

security's issuer, guarantees include letters of credit, financial guaranty

(bond) insurance and unconditional demand features, SEC said.<p>

Proposed amendments also permit funds to rely solely on the credit quality of

the issuer of a guarantee in determining the credit quality of the security, as

long as the guarantee is rated by a nationally recognized statistical rating

organization (NRSRO) and the rule's notification requirement is satisfied. Funds

also would be exempt from issuer diversification standards for securities

subject to unconditional guarantees from a non-controlled person, as defined in

the proposal.<p>

The rule provides for a three-day safe harbor, meaning a taxable or national

tax-exempt fund may invest up to 25 percent of its total assets in the

first-tier securities of a single issuer for up to three business days. The

proposal restores unintentionally omitted language stating that a fund may not

make more than one investment during the three-day period, SEC said.<p>

The commission also proposed to modify the rating requirement for ABSs and

synthetic securities to exempt from the rating requirement any ABS or synthetic

security substantially all of whose assets consist of obligations from one or

more municipal issuers. Revisions to Rule 2a-7 clarify that an ABS subject to a

guarantee would itself not be required to be rated by an NRSRO.<p>

<h3>Advertising Rule Revisions<p></h3>

The amendments proposed to Rule 482 would clarify the formula used by money

market funds to calculate yield. To resolve industry questions about the

calculation of yield, SEC proposed to limit the income included in the yield to

investment income. In addition, SEC proposed to amend Forms N-1A, N-3 and N-4 to

reflect the change in yield calculation.<p>

The commission also proposed amendments to Rule 482 under the 1933 Act and Rule

34b-1 under the 1940 Act that would require the total return used in

advertisements and sales literature to cover a period of at least one year. In

addition, SEC proposed requiring that total return quotations in advertisements

and sales literature be accompanied by a current yield quotation that is

computed in accordance with applicable rules and set forth with equal

prominence. The changes are designed to prevent investors from being misled by

the presentation of a money market fund's short-term total return in lieu of its

yield, SEC said.<p>

SEC also solicited comments on appropriate methods of disclosing non-investment

income and an appropriate compliance date for the technical amendments. Comments

on the proposed technical amendments are due by Jan. 24. For more information,

contact Marjorie Riegel, senior counsel for the Office of General Counsel in

SEC's Division of Investment Management, at (202) 942-0660.



</body> 


