<html>
<head>
<title>USDA Offers Prior Labeling Approval Q&amp;A</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/food/foodhead.gif" alt="Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law"></center>
<P>
<h2>USDA Offers Prior Labeling Approval Q&amp;A</h2>
<P>
In conjunction with the Food Labeling Division, the Processing Operations Staff (POS) compiled its first Inspection Operations list of questions and answers and information on the new prior labeling rule. POS issued the list of questions and answers (printed below) to Inspection Operations Supervisory Personnel for use during work unit meetings or when providing guidance and clarification to field personnel on the new rule and FSIS Directive 7221.1, Prior Labeling Approval.
</P>

<P>
PRIOR LABELING APPROVAL QUESTION AND ANSWER SET #1
</P>

<P>
<B>1. Q. When the new prior labeling rule becomes effective on July 1, 1996, are all labeling files to be returned to establishments, even those associated with Partial Quality Control (PQC) programs or for export to specific countries only?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. Yes. On July 1, 1996, inspectors should return all copies of labels and label approval transmittals and any other labeling records from the FSIS labeling file to plant management. It is the responsibility of plant management to maintain copies of labels and all supporting documentation i.e., formulations and processing procedures, for all labels in accordance with 9 CFR 317.4, 317.5, 381.132, and 381.133, including those associated with PQCs or for export only. 
</P>

<P>
<B>2.  Q.  If inspectors no longer have labeling files, what information should they use to perform the formulation and similar tasks as scheduled by Process 06 of PBIS?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. Inspectors should continue to perform Process 06 tasks in the same manner as prior to July 1, 1996. In accordance with 318.6 of the Meat Regulations and 381.180 of the Poultry Regulations, establishments still must provide inspectors with accurate formulation and product composition information upon request. However, there is no specific form or format required. Nonetheless, the information must be complete enough for inspectors to verify plants' compliance with any applicable requirements through the performance of Process 06 tasks. 
</P>

<P>
<B>3.  Q. Should inspectors have plants provide them with copies of product formulations for their files? </B>
</P>

<P>
A. No. Product formulations are proprietary information which belongs to establishments and should not be in inspectors' files or in the possession of an inspector except when [inspectors} are performing inspection tasks related to those formulations. 
</P>

<P>
<B>4. Q. Since most labeling can now be used without prior Agency approval, do inspectors now need to "approve" establishments' product formulations prior to them producing the product?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. No, inspectors will not be providing establishments with prior approval of their formulations. However, when performing processing inspection through PBIS Process 06, inspectors will verify if product formulations and compositions are in compliance with any applicable regulations or product standards, and that ingredients are accurately listed on the finished product label in order of descending predominance. 
</P>

<P>
<B>5. Q. It has been stated that under the new rule, establishments can transfer labels between plants without direct Agency involvement but with "proper" documentation. Is this true, and if so, what is proper documentation?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. Under the new prior labeling rule, establishments are responsible for transferring labels, wrappers, or containers bearing the official mark (with or without establishment numbers) between official establishments. In fact, FSIS Directive 7221.1, 6/20/96, cancels FSIS Directive 7231.3, "Control and Use of Labels." The FLD [Food Labeling Division] will no longer review and approve labels for transfer. However, the transfer of labels and their subsequent use must be properly documented by establishments, and said documentation must be available to FSIS inspection personnel. In this case, "proper documentation" includes all of the information formerly documented by inspectors on FSIS Form 7227-1, "Permit to Ship Meat or Poultry Labels Between Official Establishments," that is, names and addresses of shipping and receiving plants, date, quantity of labels shipped, product name, restrictions if any, and signature of responsible plant officials. There is, however, no official form or format for the information, and inspectors would not need to grant prior approval, file copies of the paperwork, or sign the plants' documentation.
</P>

<P>
Establishments will still need to maintain inventory control of transferred labels and some type of identification or coding to distinguish labeled products as to the establishment of origin in the event of a recall.
</P>

<P>
<B>6. Q. After July 1, 1996, if a plant has labels which were approved by FLD or an IIC [Inspector In Charge] previously, do inspectors or plants need to request official rescindment from FLD?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. No. There is no need to rescind previously approved labels; the regulatory requirement to rescind obsolete labels has been eliminated. It is up to plants to purge their own files of obsolete labels if and when they choose to do so. FLD's Label Audit System will request samples of labels which are in active use by plants.
</P>

<P>
<B>7. Q. If an establishment submits a label to FLD which can be approved generically, will FLD review and  approve it?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. FLD generally will not review and approve labeling which is eligible for generic approval. However, FLD will allow establishments to voluntarily submit for review and approval sketch labeling for standardized products (e.g., frankfurters or chicken croquettes) that are listed in the regulations or the [FSIS] <I>Standards and Labeling Policy Book</I>. FLD will not review and approve standardized single- ingredient products, e.g., ground beef.
</P>

<P>
<B>8.  Q.  While performing the new PBIS Task 07B01a2, should inspectors document deficiencies if plants are not meeting the Labeling Regulations; for example, if labels are not approved as required, are not technically accurate, or are missing mandatory features? </B>
</P>

<P>
A. The revised PBIS Task 07B01a2 is a two-step process. Step 1: Inspectors select finished product labels to verify that they contain the mandatory label features and that they accurately represent the finished product. If any of the applicable mandatory labeling features are missing from the label, or the label does not accurately reflect the finished product, inspectors should record a major deficiency, retain the product, and require plants to take corrective and preventive actions. 
</P>

<P>
Step 2: The labels are then to be sent to FLD for audit. The FLD Label Audit System will determine if plants have appropriately approved their labels and if the labels are technically accurate. If the FLD Label Audit System identifies inappropriately approved or inaccurate labels, then FLD will initiate corrective actions directly with the establishment. Inspection personnel will be notified of any actions to be taken.
</P>

<P>
<B>9. Q. When performing new PBIS Task 07B01a2, what is meant by the term "accurately reflects finished product"?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. It is not the Agency's intention for inspectors to be in-plant label reviewers. However, inspectors should observe the label(s) selected for audit and the product(s) to which it is applied to verify compliance with general labeling requirements. Inspectors should determine if the correct label is being placed on the finished product. For example, if a product is labeled "Beef Franks," the meat component of the finished product must be beef and not any other species. Or, if a product is labeled "Pepperoni Pizza," it must contain pepperoni. If these general labeling requirements are not met, inspectors should follow FSIS Directive 7221.1, 6/20/96.
</P>

<P>
The Agency will further review labels to determine their technical accuracy through the FLD Label Audit System. For example, determining appropriate product names and which standards apply, correct letter size and height, etc., are the purview of FLD. If inspectors have questions on labels in these regards, they should not retain product but may forward the label to FLD for further review and any follow-up actions.
</P>

<P>
<B>10. Q.  Do labels bearing nutrition labeling information, e.g., Nutrition Facts, need to be approved by FLD?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. Yes. Nutrition labeling information must be approved in sketch by FLD. Once a label with nutrition information is sketch-approved by FLD, the establishment can make generic labels based on the sketch. Quantitative changes, except for serving size, can be made to the nutrition information provided they are accurate and consistent. Nutrition labeling that was approved prior to July 1, 1996, would not have to be resubmitted to FLD for approval.
</P>

<P>
<B>11. Q. With the deletion of Policy Memo 096, "Approval of Labels for Experimental/Sample Products," what is the inspectors' role in regard to label approval and production limits?</B>
</P>

<P>
A. Under the new prior label approval regulations, it is the plant's responsibility to approve experimental or sample product labels under the generic labeling category for consumer test product labels. Consequently, inspectors are no longer involved with approving such labels and are not to monitor or control the amount of production of such product.
</P>

<P>
<B><I>FOR MORE INFORMATION:</I></B>
</P>

<P>
Establishments can call the prior labeling approval hotline at 800-336-3747.
</P>


