<html><title> High Court Strikes Preemption Protection for 510(k) Devices</title>
<body>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/feds/fedshead.gif" alt="FDA Enforcement Manual">
<P>
<h2>High Court Strikes Preemption Protection for 510(k) Devices</h2>

The U.S. Supreme Court ruled June 26 in <i>Medtronic Inc. v. Lohr</i> that the
preemption language in the Federal Food, Drug &amp; Cosmetic Act (FD&amp;C Act)
does not protect premarket notification (510(k)) devices from state law tort
claims (1996 U.S. LEXIS 698 (No. 95-574)) (21 USC &#167;360k). <P>

The <i>Medtronic</i> decision is significant not only because it could result in
an
increase of personal injury lawsuits, but also because it is the Court's only
device-specific preemption ruling and, accordingly, will influence all state
product liability suits brought against device manufacturers.<P>

In a prepared statement, Medtronic Inc. said that the Court's decision returns
the legal situation for all manufacturers of 510(k) devices to the position they
faced before 1993, when the courts first began holding that product liability
claims were preempted by federal rules, based on the Court's 1992 nondevice
preemption decision in <i>Cippolone v. Liggett Group Inc.</i> (112 S.Ct. 2608
(1992)).<P>

<h3>Background</h3><P>

The U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida held that the Medical
Device Amendments of 1976 (MDA) preempted Lora Lohr's state law negligent design,
negligent manufacture, failure to warn and strict liability claims based on
injuries resulting from the alleged failure of a pacemaker lead manufactured by
Medtronic Inc.<P>

On appeal, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit held on July 3,
1995, that only the negligent manufacture and failure to warn claims are
preempted. Following the Eleventh Circuit's ruling, Medtronic petitioned the
Supreme Court, Lohr cross-petitioned, and the Court granted both cases a
consolidated review.<P>

On April 23, the Court heard the case, addressing several critical preemption
questions: (1) Whether or not the MDA ever preempts a state law tort action; and
(2) If so, does the MDA preempt the state-law tort claims brought by Lohr (see
"Supreme Court Hears <i>Medtronic Inc. v. Lohr</i> ...," June 1996, p. 8). <P>

The Court's 5-4 decision in <i>Medtronic</i> upholds the Eleventh Circuit's
ruling that
the negligent design and strict liability  claims are not preempted and therefore
may be pursued.  The decision reversed the Eleventh Circuit's ruling that Lohr's
negligent manufacture and failure to warn claims are preempted. Thus, the Supreme
Court found none of Lohr's claims are preempted. The case has been remanded to
Florida state court. <P>

<h3>'Requirement' Definition Debated</h3><P>

During oral arguments, Medtronic suggested that the MDA's preemption provision
precludes all common law claims against a device manufacturer and that the term
"requirement" should be given a consistent reading, even though Congress did not
explicitly state its intentions.  <P>

Because the statutory language of the preemption provision is ambiguous -- it
uses the term "requirement" several times without clarifying what those
requirements include -- "if Congress intended to preclude all common-law causes
of action, it chose a singularly odd word with which to do it," Justices John
Paul Stevens, Anthony Kennedy, David Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg opined.  <P>

Their opinion states that Medtronic's argument "is not only unpersuasive, it is
implausible" because it has "the perverse effect of granting complete immunity
from design defect liability to an entire industry that, in the judgment of
Congress, needed more stringent regulation in order 'to provide for the safety
and effectiveness of medical devices....'"  <P>

In the dissenting opinion, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote that state common
law damages actions "do impose 'requirements' and are therefore preempted" when
they differ from the FD&amp;C Act's requirements.  Citing <i>Cippolone</i>, in
which
the Court evaluated the presumption against preemption for cigarettes, Justice
O'Connor stated that there is a conflict between the statute's language and a
general understanding of common law damages actions.  She asserts that if the
plain language of the statute is recognized, then preemption must prevail.  <P>

"The plurality's reason for departing from this reading are neither clear nor
persuasive," Justice O'Connor wrote. <P>

<h3>Deference to FDA?</h3><P>

The issue of deferring to the FDA to establish preemption parameters was the
subject of debate during oral arguments, and the justices were divided about
whether or not such deference is appropriate.<P>

Justice Stevens wrote in the plurality opinion that the ambiguity in the statute
gives "substantial weight" to deferring to the agency's view of the statute. In a
separate opinion, Justice Steven Breyer agreed that when Congress' intent is
ambiguous, courts may infer that the relevant administrative agency possesses "a
degree of leeway to determine which rules, regulations, or other administrative
actions will have a [preemptive] effect." <P>

In its implementing regulations for preemption, the FDA states that state
requirements are preempted only when there are <i>specific</i> federal
requirements
applicable to a particular device, rendering any <i>divergent</i> state
requirements for
devices different from, or in addition to, the specific federal requirements (21
CFR &#167;808.1(d)). <P>

Justice Breyer interpreted the agency's use of the word "specific" as narrowing
the "universe of federal requirements that the agency intends to displace at
least some state law." This analysis of specificity was a central point in
Justice Breyer's concurring opinion, creating the 5-4 majority against
preemption. <P>

Justice O'Connor contended that deference to the agency is inappropriate because
she interpreted the term requirement to encompass state common law causes of
action. "Where the language of the statute is clear, resort to the agency's
interpretation is improper," she writes. Further, she wrote that the statute
"makes no mention of a requirement of specificity ...." <P>

<h3>Design Unprotected by 510(k)</h3><P>

The Court's opinion states that the 510(k) process does not offer protection from
state negligent design claims because it was developed to maintain the status quo
with respect to the marketing of existing devices and their substantial
equivalents.<P>

"That status quo included the possibility that the manufacturer of the device
would have to defend itself against state-law claims of negligent design," the
opinion states. <P>

Although Justice O'Connor wrote that the FDA's good manufacturing practice and
labeling requirements should preempt Lohr's negligent manufacture and failure to
warn claims because they impose additional requirements, she agreed with the
plurality that Lohr's defective design claim is not preempted by the 510(k)
process, because that process "merely evaluates whether the Class III device at
issue is substantially equivalent ...."  <P>

It should be noted, one device law attorney states, that courts still can
consider preemption for devices cleared through the premarket approval (PMA)
process, because these devices already have been approved by the FDA as having
met federal safety and efficacy requirements. In not ruling on preemption for PMA
products -- and because the majority against preemption was slim -- the Court
left open the issue of preemption protection for PMA devices.<P>

Medtronic said that it was pleased that the Court did not rule out the potential
for preemption for PMAs, "where the FDA has a much more detailed design review
process," an issue currently under review in the lower courts. <P>

<h3>Reaction to the Ruling</h3><P>

The <i>Medtronic</i> decision is considered a victory for consumers by Public
Citizen
Litigation Group, which argued for Lohr before the Court.  Public Citizen
attorney Brian Wolfman stated that "the Supreme Court recognized that the purpose
of the medical device laws is to protect consumers ... not to immunize
manufacturers from liability." <P>

Conversely, House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas J. Bliley (R-Va.) aligned
himself with industry and commented that the June 26 decision "reverses 20 years
of federal law exempting medical devices approved by the FDA from lawsuits in the
State Courts." <P>

The Health Industry Manufacturers Association (HIMA) is disappointed in the
Court's decision because it may represent a "potential step backwards for medical
device innovation," according to Alan Magazine, HIMA's president. "Unfortunately,
[the] decision may have the immediate impact of subjecting medical device
companies to a confusing maze of differing state product tort liability laws,"
Magazine said.<P>

Wayne K. Barlow, vice chairman of the Medical Device Manufacturers Association
(MDMA), agreed that the decision could have a significant impact on small
companies.<P>

"This is a setback for medical device innovation," Barlow said. "This decision
has more of an impact for the small companies, who tend to be far more
innovative." <P>

However, the Court's opinion states that "nowhere in the materials relating to
the Act's history have we discovered a reference to a fear that product liability
actions would hamper the development of medical devices."<P>

<hr>
<center><h4>MDA Preemption in the Courts -- a Chronology</h4></center><P>

<font size=-1>
Editor's Note: Cases are listed in chronological order within the designated year.<p>

<b>1992</b><P>

<i>Slater v. Optical Radiation Corp.</i> (961 F.2d 1330, 7th Cir.)<P>

State claims for defective design and failure to warn relating to an
investigational device are preempted.<P>

<b>1993</b><P>

<i>King v. Collagen Corp.</i> (983 F.2d 1130, 1st Cir.)<P>

State claims for breach of warranty are preempted because they create a
requirement "in addition to" the MDA.<P>

<i>Stamps v. Collagen Corp.</i> (984 F.2d 1416, 5th Cir.)<P>

State claims for product liability, failure to warn and negligence are preempted
because they are state requirements "relating to safety or effectiveness."
Decision limited to Class III devices.<P>

<b>1995</b><P>

<i>Michael v. Shiley, Inc.</i> (46 F.3d 1316, 3rd Cir.)<P>

State claims relating to a Class III device and arising from voluntary express
warranties and promotional materials are not preempted. Court holds that express
warranties are not a form of state-imposed regulatory requirements and that
misleading advertisements violate a general duty not to deceive.<P>

<i>Lohr v. Medtronic, Inc.</i> (56 F.3d 1335, 11th Cir.)<P>

Negligent design and strict liability claims for Class III 510(k) device are not
preempted because there are no existing federal design requirements.<P>

<i>Feldt v. Mentor Corp.</i> (61 F.3d 431, 5th Cir.)<P>

Negligent design claims for Class III 510(k) device are not preempted because
there are no existing federal design requirements.<P>

<i>Duvall v. Bristol-Meyers Squibb</i> (65 F.3d 392, 4th Cir.)<P>

State negligent design claims are preempted because the 510(k) process is itself
a federal requirement with full preemptive effect.<P>

<i>English v. Mentor Corp.</i> (67 F.3d 477, 3rd Cir.)<P>

Court holds that 510(k) process is itself a federal requirement with full
preemptive effect.<P>

<i>Mitchell v. Collagen Corp.</i> (67 F.3d 1268, 7th Cir.)<P>

State negligent design and strict liability claims are preempted, but
adulteration claim is not.<P>

<i>Kennedy v. Collagen Corp.</i> (67 F.3d 1453, 9th Cir.)<P>

State common laws claims were brought under law of "general applicability," not
under law representing a positive state enactment and thus are not preempted.
Court holds that common law claims are never preempted and rejects presumption of
preemption for Class III devices.<P>

<b>1996</b><P>

<i>Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr</i> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 698 (No. 95-574))<P>

Supreme Court holds that 510(k) requirements do not preempt liability claims but
leaves open whether premarket approval (PMA) products are protected from state
law claims.<P>

<i>Mitchell v. Collagen Corp.</i> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4286 (No. 95-1323))<P>

Remanded to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit.<P>

<i>Collagen Corp. v. Kennedy</i> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4296 (No. 95-1644))<P>

Petition for <i>certiorari</i> denied.<P>

<i>Mentor Corp. v. Feldt</i> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4284 (No. 95-1037))<P>

Remanded to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.<P>


