<HTML> 
<HEAD> 
<TITLE> Telecom issues dominate watershed NATOA conference</TITLE> 
</HEAD> 
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/info/tube/tubehead.gif" alt=" Multichannel Video
 Compliance Guide"></center><P>

<h2>Telecom issues dominate watershed NATOA conference</h2>

<h3><i>Cable takes back seat to planning, rights-of-way</i></h3><P>

While cable regulation is still in force, the days of the local official who only
wears the cable regulator's hat may be numbered. <P>

This was the message of the 16th annual National Association of
Telecommunications Officers and Administrators (NATOA) conference. Local
regulators, speakers said, must conceive of their responsibilities in much
broader terms than as simply cable regulators to keep pace with sweeping
regulatory and technological changes and negotiate effectively with new wireline
and wireless providers seeking to offer a variety of telecommunications services
in their locality. <P>

A telling sign was what topics were on the conference agenda -- and those that
were omitted. The NATOA gathering was dominated by discussions on rights-of-way
issues, telecommunications planning and local telephone competition, while
multichannel video issues were of secondary concern. As a sign of technological
convergence and emerging local telephone and video competition, little
distinction was made between telephone and cable companies. And, the role of the
FCC was less prominent in the minds of many conference speakers, who focused more
on how localities can develop policies to manage the regulatory challenges of
local competition.<P>

Indeed, the 1996 conference signified a watershed moment for local governments.
While the 1995 conference attempted to grapple with imminent, groundbreaking
telecommunications legislation, and its impact on cable regulation, the 1996
meeting set out to develop a new view of local telecommunications regulation and
the responsibilities and obligations local officials have to their
communities.<P>

Major themes of the conference included: <P>
<UL>
<LI>Local officials are no longer just cable administrators, but must become
adept at broad telecommunications planning for their communities.<P>
<LI>Managing public rights-of-way and ensuring that all providers -- whether
video, telephony or data networking -- pay a fair market price for their use is
one of the most important functions of local telecommunications administrators.
<P>
<LI>As information technology plays an increasingly prominent role in the
economy, local telecommunications authorities will have an unprecedented
influence in determining the economic vitality and future of their communities
through their telecommunications policies. <P>
<LI>Local agencies can no longer work in isolation since the issues before them
are too complex and can often be solved only through interdepartmental
coordination. <P>
<LI>The next round of regulatory battles will be fought at the state level -- not
the FCC. Indeed, state legislatures are being besieged by telecommunications
lobbyists attempting to reduce city powers over their telecommunications affairs.
</UL> <P>

<h3><i>Where is telecom heading?</i></h3><P>

Where is telecommunications regulation heading? To the state house.<P>

According to many conference speakers, now that the 1996 act has passed,
telecommunications providers are shifting their lobbying energies from the FCC to
influencing how state telecommunications legislation is crafted. "A lot is going
on in state legislatures," warned  Adrian Herbst, an attorney at Fredrikson &amp;
Byron, Minneapolis, "and the telephone companies are lobbying there to narrow the
authority of local governments." <P>

"Every state will be looking at a major legislative debate in January 1997,"
remarked Nick Miller, attorney at Miller, Canfield, Paddock &amp; Stone,
Washington, D.C., adding that it was uncertain whether local governments were
really prepared to defend their interests. <P>

Wireline telecommunications generates $184 billion per year, Miller said, with
telephone, competitive access and long distance providers generating almost eight
times more revenue per year than cable television. Miller said rights-of-way fees
from the telecommunications market could generate roughly $18 billion in annual
revenue for local governments. With the financial stakes so high, Miller said,
telecommunications companies will aggressively lobby to curtail local power, and
he exhorted local franchise authorities to make all telecommunications providers
pay the true economic value for using public rights-of-way. <P>

<h3><i>'Old' cable vs. 'new' cable</i></h3><P>

We are also in the midst of the transition from "old cable to new cable"
according to Dan Brenner, vice president for law and regulatory policy at the
National Cable Television Association. "Cable is a much different business today
than it was at the time of the 1992 Cable Act."<P>

Speaking on the future of telecommunications from a national industry
perspective, Brenner said "old cable" was preoccupied with rate regulation, PEG
access and filling up unused channel capacity; "new cable" faces vigorous MMDS
and DBS competition from larger and more sophisticated players, emerging threats
from local exchange carriers and a dearth of channel capacity. And, as a sign of
the times, Brenner said most of his regulatory work at NCTA is on
telecommunications -- not cable.<P>

John Hunter, vice president of the United States Telephone Association, said most
telephone companies will seek to offer video service "through a traditional cable
franchise," adding that more than 300 local exchange carriers already offer video
service, most in rural areas.<P>

What is the role of local government as phone competition heats up? Hunter
emphasized that local governments need to ensure a level-playing field for all
competitors. Brenner argued local governments should focus on achieving "real
competition, which is facilities-based -- not just reselling," where phone
companies rent wires from local exchange companies to provide local service. And,
he added, "governments should be less concerned about price regulation." Most
importantly, Brenner said, local governments should seek above all to "do no
harm" in attempting to regulate and implement local competition.<P>

<h3><i>The local perspective</i></h3><P>

While rights-of-way issues, a major subject, the conference, Norman Sinel, an
attorney with Arnold &amp; Porter, Washington, D.C., contended that "towers and
tower sites will be the biggest issue" affecting local governments. Addressing a
session on the local government perspective of telecommunications, Sinel said the
time of being simply a cable regulator is over, with the new complexities of
local competition in a multitude of services, rights-of-way management, zoning
and tower issues.<P>

And don't expect the FCC to be the friend of localities, Sinel said, charging
that the commission is "aggressively attempting to  displace local government to
foster [its] doctrinaire concept of national telecommunications" in which it
"wants everybody in the way to get out of the way." Sinel contended that the FCC,
states, cable companies and telephone companies all want to impinge on local
government authority. <P>

Nick Miller suggested that local governments should see "telecommunications as a
tool to make society function better" rather than as an end in itself. But,
echoing Sinel, Miller reminded attendees that telecommunications companies will
pick "a forum where cities have the weakest voice, such as in the FCC," and will
attempt to "take advantage of local policy makers' ignorance on issues, such as
tower siting." To counter telecommunications companies, Miller recommended that
cities:<P>
<UL><P>
<LI>pool resources on legal battles;<P>
<LI>develop model local telecommunications ordinances and rights-of-way
agreements;<P>
<LI>execute a media and community relations initiative; and<P>
<LI>prepare and defend for litigation.</UL><P>

Miller said legislative battles are "inevitable in every state," but that the
basic city interests -- rights-of-way property rights, among others -- are
clearly defined and should be defended. <P>

<h3><i>The new age of telecom planning</i></h3><P>

To help regulators understand local competition and complexities of rights-of-way
management, the conference focused on telecommunications planning at the local
level.<P>

In a panel session on this topic, Adrian Herbst told attendees that to be
effective telecommunications planners, they "should no longer think in terms of
cable companies, and telephone companies, but in terms of the services they
offer." Local regulators, he said, need to distinguish between video and
telecommunications services. To this end, a sound telecommunications plan should
encompass three areas: <P>
<UL><P>
<LI>public rights-of-way;<P>
<LI>antenna towers; and <P>
<LI>community needs. </UL><P>

"Now is the key time to be proactive." That was the message from attorney Joseph
Van Eaton, who touted the virtues of developing a proactive plan so
telecommunications firms don't dictate their terms of service. "If you're always
on the defensive," the attorney from Miller, Canfield, Paddock &amp; Stone,
Washington, D.C., said, "your revenue is at risk." Knowing your
telecommunications needs, he said, requires coordinating planning city-wide with
the management information systems, public works and financial departments. This,
in turn, requires a thorough assessment of your city's telecommunications
needs.<P>

The centerpiece of a telecommunications plan is deriving fair compensation for
use of the public rights-of-way: "Every time you dig up the streets, the road's
life is decreased and road budgets increase," Van Eaton said, warning that if
cities "are not fairly compensated for rights-of-way usage, they are essentially
subsidizing telecommunications companies." <P>

Van Eaton said telcommunications companies are expressing "anti-city" rhetoric to
the FCC, and attempting to educate the FCC staff on their point of view, while
the commission is not really aware of what cities are thinking. Van Eaton
suggested contacting FCC staff on what cities are doing to implement the 1996 act
and renew franchises. Currently, he claimed, all the FCC is hearing (from telecom
companies) is that "cities are abusing their power." <P>

<h3><i>Preparing for a 'telestuff'</i></h3><P>

What will be the impact of wireless communications on local governments? <P>

Hal McCombs, an attorney at Duncan, Weinberg, Miller &amp; Pembroke, Washington,
D.C., advised local communities to prepare for a flurry of wireless "telestuff"
that will be coming soon to localities: new personal communications services,
local multipoint distribution service, millimeter waive 40 GHz services, wireless
competitive access providers, enhanced specialized mobile radio services, 18 GHz
services, etc.<P>

What does this all mean? More and more transmitter sites will have to be built
and more potential zoning conflicts in local communities over towers in
residential neighborhoods. <P>

Larry Beer, with the consulting firm SBA of Denver, Inc., said that while 30,000
wireless tower sites have been built thus far, another 100,000 tower sites will
be built in the next five to 10 years. Beer said "to expect as many 10 carriers
per market." Local governments, Beer said, will be affected by new demands for
zoning, and for leasing municipal facilities, which could be a new source of
revenue for cities. <P>

With all of this activity, Beer warned attendees "to be prepared to handle a
greater caseload of wireless permit applications." It is imperative, Beer said,
to clarify division responsibilities between the planning department and
telecommunications regulators, which "can't work at cross-purposes" if good
telecommunications planning is to be accomplished. <P>

<h3><i>Navigating through refranchising</i></h3><P>

Before commencing negotiations with cable operators on a franchise renewal, make
sure you thoroughly assess the past performance of the operator, said Ila Feld,
an attorney with Leibowitz &amp; Associates, P.A., Miami, at a session on
refranchising.<P>

Feld offered a few tips on preparing for renewal negotiations:<P>
<OL>
<LI>Assess your community's needs and "pay careful attention to subscribers'
needs."<P>
<LI>Assess the cable operator's performance -- "be knowledgeable about the
operator before sitting down to negotiate." Feld advised attendees to be able "to
go point-by-point through the previous franchise agreement to verify whether the
operator has satisfied all of its obligations."<P>
<LI>Know what kind of system the operator is. Hire outside consultants and
engineers if necessary to understand the technical features of the cable
system.<P>
<LI>Do a financial audit of the system. Make sure all payments have been
made.</OL><P>

<h3><i>A rapprochement with TCI?</i></h3><P>

In one session, local government officials were invited to sit down with multiple
system cable operators to discuss a variety of  issues. TCI Communications
representatives and local franchisers overseeing TCI systems, discussed issues
such as franchise renewals, customer service, telecommunications franchising, and
rights-of-way.<P>

A number of franchisers were annoyed that they had received "boilerplate"
documents from TCI systems seeking renewals. This tactic, the franchisers said,
creates an adversarial tone immediately. TCI representatives denied that the MSO
uses boilerplate documents for renewals as a corporate policy, and emphasized
that the franchisers must have a realistic appraisal of what their community
needs and what the TCI's affiliate can afford. For example, "it doesn't make
sense for every market to warrant a 750 MHz upgrade based on return of investment
analysis," a TCI rep said. The TCI rep also said that operators are concerned
about "opening up their books to everyone" when franchisers ask financial
information. <P>

With regard to customer service, one franchiser suggested that TCI should have
people manning call centers who live in the community that customers are calling
from. Another gripe: some franchisers thought TCI's billing policies in their
service areas were unnecessarily confusing and caused an inordinate amount of
late fees accruing to customers. <P>

What must subscribers do to get new programming carried on their TCI system?
There is no simple formula on the number of subscribers it takes to get new
programming added, a TCI rep said. One constraint is the bulk programming
agreements the national MSO enters into, making it hard to take off a network in
only a few systems. In addition, removing programming often generates opposition,
too. TCI does do national polling, the TCI rep said, to determine what
programming it should carry.<P>

The TCI reps emphasized that upgrades should be "market driven" and a "business
decision made on a case-by-case basis." But franchisers suggested that the MSO
should not pre-emptively remove upgrade considerations from renewal discussions,
but rather justify their unwillingness to upgrade with local financial and
business data. <P>
<P>

<h3><i>Tips on telecom planning</i></h3><P>

Susan Littlefield, cable regulatory administrator for St. Louis, offered a few
tips on telecommunications planning for administrators at the NATOA conference.
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Don't confuse the difference between being a landlord and a regulator. "Local
governments are generally landlords first and regulators second," Littlefield
said, and the use of public rights-of-way should be conceived as the renting of
public property in which the local government is the landlord. Littlefield
reminded attendees that "landlords have the right to determine appropriate
compensation for use of their property."  
<LI>Make sure similar services receive the same treatment: "Similar providers of
similar services must be subject to similar requirements, so that no provider
receives unequal or preferential treatment." 
<LI>Research the telecommunications businesses seeking to use the rights-of-way:
"Invite various prospective telecommunications providers to talk about their
business" to learn as much as possible about the the financial and technical
dimension of their businesses.
<LI>Think of yourself as both a consumer and regulator. A number of presenters
emphasized that local governments are the largest consumers of telecommunications
services in their cities, which gives them leverage in any negotiations with
telecommunications providers. 
<LI>Know where all of the rights-of-way are located so that a thorough evaluation
of a local government's needs and assessments can be made.
<LI>Create interdepartmental coalitions or task forces to figure out the best
approach to regulation and compensation. 
<LI>"Saving money is as good as making money: In-kind payments can be a great
form of rental compensation if you have identified needs," she said. 
<LI>"Talk to adjacent local governments about their policies. This makes sense,"
Littlefield said, "as cable operators increasingly cluster their systems."
</OL><P>



<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/info/tube/tube.html"><img
src="/tpg/info/tube/smalltube.gif" alt="Return to Multichannel Video Compliance
 Guide Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/infoprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr>
