<HTML> 
<HEAD> 
<TITLE>Supreme Court splits on access channel indecency ban</TITLE> 
</HEAD> 
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/info/tube/tubehead.gif" alt=" Multichannel Video
 Compliance Guide"></center><P>

<h2>Supreme Court splits on access channel indecency ban</h2>

The Supreme Court has ruled that cable operators can ban indecent material on
leased access channels, but are prohibited from exercising the same control over
public, education and government (PEG) access channels. In a June 28 decision,
the High Court also limited the ability of cable operators to segregate and block
indecent programming that they choose to carry. <P>

It was a mixed decision for the cable industry, which saw only one of the three
decisions issued by the High Court go in its favor. In a 7-2 decision, the court
upheld the leased access indecency provision of the 1992 Cable Act, but voted 6-3
to strike down the provision allowing cable operators to segregate and block
indecent programming on leased access channels. Finally, the High Court voted 5-4
to strike down the PEG access indecency provision.<P>

The case combined several previous cases that had challenged the Communications
Act's provisions regarding indecent programming on access channels. Under the act
and FCC regulations, cable operators are allowed to ban "indecent" programming on
PEG channels. They are also entitled to prohibit such programming from leased
access channels, or, if they choose to carry it, place it on blocked channel,
available only to subscribers who request to view it. Congress enacted these
restrictions when passing the 1992 Cable Act in response to complaints that
children could easily watch sexually oriented programming on access channels. The
provisions also reversed language in the 1984 Cable Act that forbids cable
operators from exercising any editorial control over what programmers offered
subscribers. <P>

A lower court had ruled that the FCC's indecency regulations, which permitted
cable operators to ban or block "indecent" programming on leased access and PEG
channels, do not violate free speech rights. <P>

In <i>Alliance for Community Media vs. FCC</i> (Appendix V:5), the three High
Court decisions reversed in part the lower court decision. The U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia held that the indecency provisions for both
leased and PEG access did not create an unlawful "state action" abridging free
speech because the cable operator has editorial discretion over the content
carried on its system. The appeals court also said that access channels are not
public forums in which speech curbs would face the strictest level of scrutiny.
<P>

In an opinion delivered for the Court, Justice Stephen Breyer affirmed the rights
of cable operators to assert editorial control over indecent programming on
leased access channels. Breyer said the provision was consistent with both the
First Amendment and a compelling government interest in protecting children from
indecent programming. The reason: the provision simply enables a cable operator
to ban indecent programming on its system if it wants, rather than imposing a
federal requirement to do so. Thus, Breyer said, the provision is "a
constitutionally permissible way to protect children from the type of sexual
material that concerned Congress, while accommodating both the First Amendment
interests served by the access requirements and those served in restoring to
cable operators a degree of the editorial control that Congress removed in 1984.
. . ." <P>

But Breyer, in a separate opinion, said the segregate-and-block provision
violated the First Amendment because, unlike the provision permitting cable
operators to restrict indecent programming on leased access channels, "it does
not simply permit, but rather requires, cable system operators to restrict speech
by segregating and blocking" indecent programming. Breyer said the "restrictive
effects" of this provision on free speech include requiring subscribers to
request indecent programming 30 days in advance and "the written notice
requirement," which could deter viewers from requesting the program for fear of
an inadvertent public disclosure of their request. Finally, Breyer cited the
"added costs and burdens" that this requirement imposes on cable system operators
that could be a disincentive to their carrying indecent programming. <P>

The ban on indecent programming on PEG channels was also deemed 
unconstitutional. Writing for three judges among the majority, Breyer based this
decision on two factors: cable operators have not made it a practice to interfere
with the content on these channels and, historically, there have not been
problems with indecent PEG access programming warranting giving cable
operator-imposed restrictions. <P>

In a concurring opinion, Justice David Souter, alluding to the difficulty of
regulating the media when it is in state of technological flux, advocated a
cautious approach to content regulation, stating, "We should be shy about saying
the final word today about what will be accepted as reasonable tomorrow." <P>

But Justices Anthony Kennedy and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, while concurring with the
rulings on the PEG access and segregate-and-block restrictions, blasted the
majority for upholding the ban on indecent programming on leased access channels.
The justices said that decision "was an evasion of any clear legal standard" and
that the majority's willingness to cite the complexities of regulating speech on
emerging media technologies as justification for speech restrictions obfuscates
the "straightforward issue . . .of whether the government can deprive certain
speakers, on the basis of the content of their speech, of protections afforded
all others." Further, they said, "if the plurality is concerned about
technology's direction, it ought to begin by allowing speech, not suppressing
it." <P>

NCTA President and CEO Decker Anstrom lauded the High Court's decision allowing
cable operators "to exercise editorial control over indecent programming on
leased access channels, and to do so without being required to put it on a
particular channel." Anstrom added that "the decision will give cable companies
some further ability to protect the interests and concerns of our customers." But
Anstrom was disappointed that "editorial control was not extended to public
access channels as well." <P>

<h3><i>Precedents?</i></h3><P>

Are there any legal principles from this case on the First Amendment and the
cable industry that could set a precedent? "It's a work in progress," said Robert
Corn-Revere, an attorney with the Washington, D.C., law firm of Hogan and
Hartson, which represents Playboy Entertainment Group in its attempt to overturn
federal enforcement of a scrambling provision of the 1996 Telecommunications Act
(see July 1996 <i>Monthly Bulletin,</i> Page 5). <P>

Corn-Revere said the Supreme Court "is not yet ready to make a final
pronouncement on the level of First Amendment scrutiny that should apply to
cable," but added that there could soon be an emerging consensus on the Court as
to the strength of First Amendment review. And, he said, the High Court in this
case only upheld the right of cable operators to have editorial control over what
goes on their systems: "All of the justices agreed that no burdens should be
imposed." <P>

Both the segregate-and-block provision and the 1996 act's scrambling provision
impose burdens on subscribers and raise serious privacy issues, Corn-Revere
maintained. "Scrambling," he contended, "would cost tens of millions of dollars
to implement and require technicians to make a special installation at the home
of subscribers wanting to view indecent programming." Scrambling raises the
imposition of excessive burdens and privacy concerns, Corn-Revere argued, which
the majority of the Court in the indecency case already recognized as sound
reasons for not restricting free speech. <P>

<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/info/tube/tube.html"><img
src="/tpg/info/tube/smalltube.gif" alt="Return to Multichannel Video Compliance
 Guide Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/infoprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr>
