<html> <title> SEC To Introduce Proposals Calling For Mutual Fund Prospectus Simplification</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/tax/mony/monyhead.gif"  alt="Money Manager's Compliance Guide"></center>
<hr>
<h2> SEC To Introduce Proposals Calling For Mutual Fund Prospectus Simplification</h2><P>
<body>

The Securities and Exchange Commission plans to propose several rules to assist

the mutual fund industry in providing investors with prospectus documents that

are more user friendly, because the commission's efforts over the last few years

to encourage the industry to simplify prospectuses under existing rules have

been largely unsuccessful, according to Heidi Stam, associate director in SEC's

Division of Investment Management.<p>

Fund prospectuses gradually have been changing to provide investment and risk

disclosures in better, more readable formats, but funds have been slow to

initiate the process, Stam said. Funds that have simplified prospectuses

generally have been direct marketed funds, where the prospectus is not only used

for information but also for marketing, she said.<p>

<h3>Risks Involved in Simplification</h3><p>

Industry has been slow to change the traditional statutory prospectus, because

simplification is time consuming, resource intensive, and has the potential to

increase a fund's liability risk, according to Pamela Wilson, senior partner

with Hale and Dorr, an outside counsel to John Hancock Funds Inc. "It takes time

to summarize information right" and the simplification process offers the mutual

fund industry "the reward of more liability risk" if not done properly, she

said.<p>

Despite the perceived risks, several funds have initiated the process because of

a desire to create a document that an investor can read and understand without

the assistance of a lawyer, Wilson said. "One of the industry's main jobs is to

keep investors involved in the process," she said. The industry "pays too high a

price when it gives an investor a document that he cannot understand" simply to

protect itself from litigation, she said.<p>

<h3>John Hancock Changes Process Dramatically<p></h3>

According to Wilson, one of the most striking prospectus simplification

processes undertaken to date was initiated by John Hancock Funds, an investment

company whose funds are sold through brokerage firms. John Hancock recently

introduced several simplified prospectuses that dramatically depart from the

traditional, boilerplate prospectus, she said.<p>

According to Thomas H. Connors, an attorney and second vice president with John

Hancock Advisers Inc., prospectus simplification is not about leaving

information out, it is about stating information in a clear, concise manner,

minimizing jargon and reducing repetitiveness. Simplification does not

necessarily have to increase liability risks; it can add to "the quality of risk

disclosure and highlight the risks in a more powerful and apparent" manner, he

said.<p>

John Hancock rethought every aspect of the prospectus and retained an outside

writer and design firm to bring a fresh perspective to the process, Connors

said. John Hancock requested no-action relief from SEC to change the format of

the prospectus, add an additional color to the document and change some of the

statutory verbiage to lower-case letters, among other things, he said. It also

deleted repetitive information and moved more technical data to the statement of

additional information, thus removing it entirely from Form N-1A.<p>

The goal was to produce simplified prospectuses that use plain language and put

information into manageable segments, Connors said. Through the simplification

process, John Hancock consolidated 34 separate fund prospectuses into six

prospectuses grouped by investment objective, resulting in an 80 percent

reduction in production costs and lower legal review costs, Connors said. John

Hancock decided to consolidate and simplify the prospectuses to make it easier

for investors to compare the risks and management styles of funds that have

similar objectives, he said.<p>

According to Connors, the new prospectuses have received favorable reviews from

investors and brokers alike. The simplification has helped brokers help

investors more effectively, he said. "Any good quality communication undoubtedly

gives a fund a leg up on its competition," he said. The end result of the

process is an educational tool that can be used by the broker and investor, and

also is a powerful risk disclosure document, he added.<p>

SEC was helpful throughout the consolidation process, and John Hancock worked

closely with the commission to produce its simplified prospectuses, Wilson said.

The primary impediment to prospectus simplification seems to be the industry and

its lawyers, and not SEC and the states, she said.<p>

According to Paul Gallagher, principal and assistant general counsel with the

Vanguard Group, a direct marketed fund, "John Hancock deserves a lot of credit

for their innovation; it was something we didn't expect from a broker-sold

fund." Vanguard also recently rewrote their prospectuses to make them more

understandable for investors. Unlike Hancock, Vanguard did not request no-action

relief from SEC, Gallagher said.

</body> 

