<html>
<head> 
<title>Device Industry, Doctors Suspicious of FDA's Changing Regulatory Role</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/sell/sellhead.gif"  alt="FDA Advertising and Promotion
Manual">
<P>

<h2>Device Industry, Doctors Suspicious of FDA's Changing Regulatory Role</h2>

The FDA's increasingly restrictive regulatory approach to the promotion of

medical devices by monitoring physician training, modifying the premarket

notification (510(k)) submission and expanding the scope of enforcement is

"inconsistent with the demands of the marketplace," an industry representative

told a recent Health Industry Manufacturers Association (HIMA) meeting.<p>

The agency's policies on comparative claims, continuing medical education (CME)

and indications for use are "very conservative" and fit poorly with a changing

healthcare marketplace that places a premium on information, Michael McCulley,

assistant general counsel of Johnson &amp; Johnson, said at the July 11 HIMA

conference. <p>

Susan Alpert, director of the Office of Device Evaluation (ODE) in the FDA's

Center for Devices and Radiological Health (CDRH), defended the agency's current

approach, asserting that it is CDRH's mission to ensure that claims are

"supported by valid scientific evidence."<p>

<h3>Indications Requirement</h3><p>

In February, the ODE sent a letter to device manufacturers informing them that

they must include in their 510(k) submissions a separate sheet identifying the

specific indications for use for which a substantially equivalent determination

is sought, Alpert noted (see &#182;624). This requirement, which modifies an

existing procedure, is "driven by the labeling claims" made by the device

manufacturer, and "will reduce confusion between the agency and 510(k)

submitters on which indications for use have been cleared." <p>

She stated that "intended use" is defined as what a product "technically does,"

while the "indicated use" refers to the populations and therapeutic settings for

which the device is appropriate. Based on what they want their devices to do and

for whom, manufacturers ultimately determine the extent to which clinical trials

will be necessary to support any promotional claims, Alpert said. She contended

that the separate indications-for-use sheet will make it easier for companies to

show substantial equivalence in the 510(k) submission. Some industry members

contend that the sheet also makes it easier for CDRH to cross-reference future

promotional claims with clinical data.<p>

McCulley agreed that a device's indication for use necessarily impacts on its

marketing, but accused the FDA of "rewriting the rules" so that companies must

more narrowly define indications and consequently curtail promotional claims.

McCulley characterized this shift as similar to the FDA's current practice for

pharmaceuticals. <p>

<h3>Enforcement Challenges<p></h3>

McCulley said the regulatory maze faced by companies is broader than just FDA

requirements because other government agencies with regulatory, enforcement or

reimbursement interests in medical devices affect marketing strategies. The

Office of Inspector General for the Department of Health and Human Services, the

Department of Justice, the Federal Trade Commission, and state agencies all

present regulatory challenges to device promotion, McCulley said (see sidebar,

below). <p>

The rise of managed care also has created market challenges for manufacturers,

he added. As a result, advertising and promotion in this new environment is "in

flux ... and the demand for information about products and what those products

can do has increased at a tremendous pace," McCulley said. Unfortunately, the

FDA is restricting the communication of such information, he commented. <p>

McCulley cited recent CDRH Warning Letters as examples of the agency's departure

from traditional enforcement concerns, such as claims for unapproved uses or

quality of life, fraudulent or misleading claims, fair balance issues, and use

of testimonials (see &#182;912; App. IV). In Johnson &amp; Johnson's estimation,

McCulley said, the FDA now is focusing on:<p>

<ul><li>Whether promotional claims match indications listed in the 510(k);<p>

<li>Specific claims derived from broad indications;<p>

<li>Company-provided devices for hands-on training;<p>

<li>Cost-effectiveness claims (see &#182;622);<p>

<li>Comparative and superiority claims (see &#182;621); and<p>

<li>Company-sponsored CME seminars (see &#182;631).</ul><p>

<h3>No Interference</h3><p>

McCulley further contended that the FDA's policies represent "a venture by the

agency into [regulating] the practice of medicine" because they block patient

and physician access to product information. However, Alpert and Byron Tart,

director of CDRH's Promotion and Advertising Policy Staff, disagreed with that

position. Although CDRH regulates anyone who promotes and markets devices,

including doctors, it does not regulate physicians as they work with individual

patients, Alpert said. <p>

Tart acknowledged that CDRH will step in when a doctor promotes a specific

device for an off-label use, citing a letter from the division to doctors

regarding the promotion of excimer lasers for photorefractive keratectomy as an

appropriate regulatory action to protect consumers.<p>

Moreover, CDRH will investigate physician training for devices when a

manufacturer is involved with the program, Tart said. Regulation of the practice

of medicine is a "gray area" for the FDA, Tart noted, because the FTC has

jurisdiction over the manner in which doctors market their practices (see

&#182;331). <p>

David Goldberg, chief of dermatologic surgery at the New Jersey Medical School,

told HIMA conference attendees that physicians have "a sense" that the agency is

expanding its authority over the practice of medicine and are uncomfortable with

this interference. <p>

<h3>CDRH Responds<p></h3>

Tart acknowledged that the marketing of devices "is crossing into new areas,"

such as direct-to-consumer advertising, promotion to managed care entities and

Internet communications. The FDA's effort to develop agency-wide policies in

these areas also impacts on CDRH's operations, Tart told the HIMA conference

attendees. He maintained that all FDA Centers are working together in response

to industry concerns that medical products be treated equally for purposes of

regulation and enforcement, and that the FDA is involving industry more in

guidance development.<p>

Tart conceded that his division has issued more Warning Letters recently for

nontraditional violations. He urged recipients to respond to such letters

promptly and, if they believe the FDA's position may be incorrect, to explain

why. Although the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research recently has issued

notices of violation (NOVs) for promotion violations instead of Warning Letters,

CDRH still sees the Warning Letters "as a valuable tool," Tart told the <I>Monthly Bulletin</I> (see &#182;911). <p>

"The use of the term [notice of violation] is a misnomer," Tart said. In his

view, an NOV is a communication with a firm about a potential problem about

which the agency would like more information, and should be used only for minor

issues. <p>

<p>

<hr>
<h4><center>New Challenges for Device Companies<p></h4></center>

<FONT SIZE="2">Speaking at a July 11 meeting sponsored by the Health Industry Manufacturers

Association (HIMA), Michael McCulley, assistant general counsel of Johnson &amp;

Johnson, commented on the changing regulatory environment governing the

promotion of devices. When developing a device and its marketing campaign,

McCulley said, companies must now ask themselves whether the product:<p>

<ul><li>Complies with FDA requirements;<p>

<li>Is covered by Medicare/Medicaid coverage and reimbursement rules;<p>

<li>Is subject to government contracting rules;<p>

<li>Is offered in a manner consistent with the anti-kickback, anti-referral

requirements;<p>

<li>Is subject to the "best price" regulations; and<p>

<li>Is affected by any state requirements.</ul></FONT>





<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/sell/sell.html"><img src="/tpg/food/sell/smallsell.gif" 
alt="Return to FDA Advertising and Promotion Manual Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
