<html> <title> President Signs Broad Regulatory Reform Legislation To Eliminate Securities

Overlaps
Fund</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/tax/mony/monyhead.gif"  alt="Money Manager's Compliance
Guide"></center>
<hr>
<h2>President Signs Broad Regulatory Reform Legislation To Eliminate Securities

Overlaps</h2><P>
<body>

President Clinton Oct. 11 signed broad securities reform legislation designed to

eliminate the regulatory overlap between states and the federal government and

simplify regulations governing mutual funds and corporate securities. The

National Securities Markets Improvement Act of 1996 also will reduce Securities

and Exchange Commission registration fees and stabilize SEC's funding structure,

according to a written statement released by the White House.<p>

Clinton said the "legislation represents the most significant overhaul of the

securities regulatory structure in decades" and achieves the "difficult task of

improving the efficiency of the financial markets without compromising investor

protections." SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt agreed and applauded Congress for its

show of bipartisanship.<p>

In an attempt to relieve the investment industry from conflicting and burdensome

regulation by state and federal securities authorities and recognize the

national character of markets, the law streamlines regulatory authority by

dividing responsibility for financial market activities between SEC and

states.<p>

Under the law, SEC is given broad exemptive authority under both the Securities

Act of 1933 (1933 Act) and the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 for all national

market and large investment advisor activities. The law amends the Investment

Company Act of 1940 (1940 Act) to exempt from state regulation any security

issued by a registered open-end or closed-end investment company. In addition,

the law preempts states from regulating securities offered by mutual funds and

stocks listed on the New York Stock Exchange, American Stock Exchange, NASDAQ

and other exchanges identified by SEC as providing comparable listing

standards.<p>

Because the law precludes state regulators from reviewing SEC filings including

investment company prospectuses and advertising published by or on behalf of the

fund, the preemption is expected to alleviate the difficulties funds currently

encounter from inconsistent state regulation of fund disclosure practices and

investment policies.<p>

In addition, broker-dealers and others are expected to benefit from the division

of SEC and state activities because they will no longer be subject to "dozens of

differing state net capital and books and records requirements," Clinton said.

The law also provides SEC with broad authority to require investment companies

and their affiliates to preserve and maintain additional books and records, but

prohibits SEC from disclosing a fund's internal compliance records to persons

requesting them under the Freedom of Information Act.<p>

Although states lose regulatory authority over certain securities and mutual

funds, they retain authority to bring enforcement actions against fraudulent

conduct, to require investment company issuers to file--for notice purposes--any

document filed with SEC under the 1933 Act, and to continue to impose the same

filing and registration fees on investment companies that are currently in

effect. As a result of the preemption, state enforcement activity is likely to

focus now on sales practices, according to industry experts.<p>

Under the law, state regulators were given responsibility for smaller issues and

investment advisors with smaller portfolios--those with client assets of less

than $25 million. According to industry experts, the new law may create

uncertainty for attorneys who advise smaller investment advisers, because many

states do not have rules on investment advisers.<p>

The changes are expected to give SEC the authority to deal with individual

situations and address "misleading" fund names or ones that use words such as

"government," "guaranteed" or "insured" in a manner that causes investors to

incorrectly conclude that their investments are guaranteed by federal or state

authorities.<p>

Under the new law, SEC also is required to adopt rules that will allow funds to

create new advertising prospectuses that are not limited by statutory prospectus

information. This change will allow funds to communicate directly with investors

and to distribute an advertising prospectus without a statutory prospectus.<p>

The law amends the 1940 Act to increase the flexibility of the investment

company industry to create "funds of funds" without undergoing the

time-consuming and expensive SEC exemptive application process. In addition to

codifying the expansive positions taken by SEC in several recent exemptive

orders on funds of funds, the law provides SEC with the authority to grant, by

rule or order, additional exemptions to investment companies wanting to

establish funds of funds as the marketplace changes.<p>

The law also provides SEC with $20 million of additional funding to supervise

investment advisers, cuts fees that public corporations pay for routine filings

with SEC by $850 million over 10 years, and lets brokerage firms borrow from

financial institutions other than banks.


</body> 

<foot>

