<html>
<head>
<title>Supreme Court's Preemption Decision in Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr Hurts 510(k)s</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device
Regulation"></center>
<P>
<h2>Supreme Court's Preemption Decision in <I>Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr</I> Hurts 510(k)s</h2>

<P>
The U.S. Supreme Court ruled June 26 in <I>Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr</I> that the preemption language in the Federal Food, Drug &amp; Cosmetic Act (FD&amp;C Act) does not protect premarket notification (510(k)) devices from state law tort claims (21 USC &#167;360k, see App. I). 
</P>

<P>
The <I>Medtronic</I> decision is significant because it largely extinguishes the opportunity for immunity from common law suits for products cleared through the 510(k) process (1996 U.S. LEXIS 698 (No. 95-574)). Importantly, the Court denied a lower court's determination that preemption from labeling and manufacturing claims was appropriate, even though specific FDA requirements existed in those areas. The FDA's regulations state that state requirements are preempted if there are federal "counterpart regulations" in place (see &#182;1300).
</P>

<P>
In a prepared statement, Medtronic Inc. said that the Court's decision returns the legal situation for all manufacturers of 510(k) devices to the position they faced before 1993, when the courts first began holding that product liability claims were preempted by federal regulatory requirements, based on the high court's 1992 nondevice preemption decision in <I>Cippolone v. Liggett Group Inc.</I> (112 S.Ct. 2608 (1992)), (see "Presumption Against Preemption ...," p. 3). 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Background</H3>
</P>

<P>
The U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida held that the Medical Device Amendments of 1976 (MDA) preempted Lora and Michael Lohrs' state law negligent design, negligent manufacture, failure to warn and strict liability claims based on injuries resulting from the alleged failure of a pacemaker lead manufactured by Medtronic Inc. and implanted in Lora Lohr.
</P>

<P>
On appeal, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit held on July 3, 1995, that only the negligent manufacture and failure to warn claims were preempted. Following the Eleventh Circuit's ruling, Medtronic petitioned the Supreme Court, the Lohrs cross-petitioned and the Court granted both petitions for review (see "Supreme Court to Review 510(k) Preemption Issues ...," March 1996, p. 1).
</P>

<P>
On April 23, the Court heard the case, addressing two critical preemption questions: (1) Whether or not the MDA ever preempts a state law tort action; and (2) If so, does the MDA preempt the state law tort claims brought by the Lohrs (see "Supreme Court Hears <I>Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr</I> ...," June 1996, p. 1). 
</P>

<P>
The Court's 5-4 decision in <I>Medtronic</I> upholds the Eleventh Circuit's ruling that the negligent design and strict liability claims are not preempted and, therefore, may be pursued. The decision, authored by Justice John Paul Stevens, also reverses the Eleventh Circuit's ruling that the Lohrs' negligent manufacture and failure to warn claims are preempted. Thus, the Supreme Court found none of the Lohrs' claims to be preempted. The case has been remanded to Florida state court.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>'Requirement' Debated</H3>
</P>

<P>
During oral arguments, Medtronic suggested that the MDA's preemption provision precludes all common law claims against a device manufacturer and that the term "requirement," which appears in numerous places in the statute, should be given a broad reading, even though Congress did not explicitly state its intentions in that regard.

</P> 
<P>
The Court rejected Medtronic's argument that the term "requirement" means general requirements. Indeed, the opinion states that Medtronic's argument "is not only unpersuasive, it is implausible" because it has "the perverse effect of granting complete immunity from design defect liability to an entire industry that, in the judgment of Congress, needed more stringent regulation in order 'to provide for the safety and effectiveness of medical devices.'" 
</P>

<P>
Instead, the Court reasoned that based on the purpose of the FD&amp;C Act -- to protect consumers -- an appropriate deference to the FDA's interpretation of the term requirement -- to mean a specific requirement for a particular device -- common law torts would not be preempted by the Act. Justice Stevens, joined by Justices Anthony Kennedy, David Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, wrote in the plurality opinion that "if Congress intended to preclude all common-law causes of action, it chose a singularly odd word with which to do it." In other words, consistent with its reasoning in past cases, the Court concluded that it was not "the clear and manifest purpose of Congress" to preempt common law torts. 
</P>

<P>
In dissent, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor (writing on behalf of Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas and Chief Justice William Rehnquist), wrote that state common law damages actions "do impose 'requirements' and are therefore preempted" when they differ from the FD&amp;C Act's requirements. Citing <I>Cippolone</I>, in which the Court applied its historical presumption against preemption of state laws relating to the regulation of cigarette promotion, Justice O'Connor stated that there is a conflict between the statute's language and a general understanding of common law damages actions. She asserted that if the plain language of the statute is recognized, then preemption must prevail. 
</P>

<P>
"The plurality's reason for departing from this reading are neither clear nor persuasive," Justice O'Connor wrote. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Deference to FDA?</H3>
</P>

<P>
Whether the Court should defer to the FDA for such purely legal issues as preemption was a hot issue of debate during oral arguments before the Court. Although the justices were divided about whether or not such deference should be shown the FDA for issues like preemption, nonetheless the Court concluded that deference is appropriate in <I>Medtronic</I>. 
</P>

<P>
Justice Stevens gave the FDA's view, as expressed in its regulations, "substantial weight" (21 CFR &#167;808.1(d), see App. II). In a separate opinion, Justice Steven Breyer agreed that when the statute is ambiguous, the relevant administrative agency possesses "a degree of leeway to determine which rules, regulations, or other administrative actions will have a [preemptive] effect." In this case, it is not surprising that the Court deferred to the FDA because the Court did not view the preemption issue as separate from the rest of the Act that the agency is charged with enforcing. In other words, the FDA's expertise in the regulatory arena was germane to determining the scope of preemption. 
</P>

<P>
Accordingly, in rejecting preemption, the Court relied upon the FDA's view that preemption only applies when there are <I>specific</I> federal requirements applicable to a particular device, rendering inapplicable any <I>divergent</I> state requirements for devices different from, or in addition to, the specific federal requirements (21 CFR &#167;808.1(d), see App. II). 
</P>

<P>
The Court's acceptance of the specificity or narrowness of the FDA's regulations is the cornerstone of its opinion, and was a central point in Justice Breyer's concurring opinion, thus creating the 5-4 majority against preemption. 
</P>

<P>
Justice O'Connor contended that deference to the agency is inappropriate because she interpreted the term requirement to encompass state common law causes of action. "Where the language of the statute is clear, resort to the agency's interpretation is improper," she wrote. Further, she wrote that the statute "makes no mention of a requirement of specificity." 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Design Unprotected by 510(k)</H3>
</P>

<P>
The Court's opinion stated that the 510(k) process does not offer protection from state negligent design claims because it was developed to maintain the status quo with respect to the marketing of existing devices and their substantial equivalents.
</P>

<P>
"That status quo included the possibility that the manufacturer of the device would have to defend itself against state-law claims of negligent design," the opinion states. 
</P>

<P>
Justice O'Connor wrote that the FDA's good manufacturing practice and labeling requirements should preempt the Lohrs' negligent manufacture and failure to warn claims because they impose additional requirements. However, she agreed with the plurality that the Lohrs' defective design claim is not preempted by the 510(k) process, because that process "merely evaluates whether the Class III device at issue is substantially equivalent." 
</P>

<P>
It should be noted, one device law attorney states, that courts still can consider preemption for devices cleared through the premarket approval (PMA) process, because specific devices will be found to have met federal safety and efficacy requirements. The Court did not have a PMA preemption question before it, and did not directly address preemption in the PMA context. Nonetheless, the Court's opinion does not appear to leave much room for the preemption of state common law actions, the attorney told the <I>Bulletin</I>. Because the majority against preemption in <I>Medtronic</I> was slim, a PMA preemption issue likely will be before the Court in the future, the attorney predicted. 
</P>

<P>
Medtronic said that it was pleased that the Court did not rule out the potential for preemption for PMAs, "where the FDA has a much more detailed design review process," an issue currently under review in the lower courts. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Reaction to the Ruling</H3>
</P>

<P>
The <I>Medtronic</I> decision is considered a victory for consumers by Public Citizen Litigation Group, which argued for the Lohrs before the Court. Public Citizen attorney Brian Wolfman stated that "the Supreme Court recognized that the purpose of the medical device laws is to protect consumers ... not to immunize manufacturers from liability." 
</P>

<P>
Conversely, House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas J. Bliley (R-Va.) aligned himself with industry and commented that the June 26 decision "reverses 20 years of federal law exempting medical devices approved by the FDA from lawsuits in the State Courts." 
</P>

<P>
"Who will be willing to supply American patients with pacemakers and heart pumps, knowing they can be hauled into any one of 50 State Courts even if they scrupulously comply with the rigorous standards set forth by the FDA?" Bliley said in a prepared statement.
</P>

<P>
The Health Industry Manufacturers Association (HIMA) is disappointed in the Court's decision because it may represent a "potential step backwards for medical device innovation," according to Alan Magazine, HIMA's president. "Unfortunately, [the] decision may have the immediate impact of subjecting medical device companies to a confusing maze of differing state product tort liability laws," Magazine said.
</P>

<P>
The decision also could have a significant impact on small companies, according to Wayne K. Barlow, vice chairman of the Medical Device Manufacturers Association. "This is a setback for medical device innovation," Barlow said. "This decision has more of an impact for the small companies, who tend to be far more innovative." 
</P>

<P>
However, the Court's opinion states that "nowhere in the materials relating to the Act's history have we discovered a reference to a fear that product liability actions would hamper the development of medical devices."
</P>

<HR>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT>Presumption Against Preemption Thwarts Industry</H4>

<P>
<FONT SIZE="2">Many in the medical device industry had hoped that the U.S. Supreme Court would resolve in industry's favor the outstanding questions and conflicting interpretations of preemption at the circuit court level when it considered <I>Medtronic, Inc. v. Lohr</I> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 698 (No. 95-574)). Indeed, Medtronic asked the Court in its petition to remove "this burden on innovation" presented by disparate opinions in the lower courts. 
</P>

<P>
Until the Court's decision, manufacturers had hoped that preemption immunity from product liability lawsuits would continue for premarket notification (510(k)) devices. Indeed, the overriding belief was that preemption covered all device clearances, including 510(k)s, premarket approvals (PMAs) and investigational device exemptions (IDEs). 
</P>

<P>
This interpretation, as held recently by the U.S. Courts of Appeals for the Third and Fourth Circuits, favored preemption for devices cleared through the 510(k) process (in <I>Duvall v. Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.</I> (65 F.3d 392 (4th Cir. 1995) and <I>English v. Mentor Corp.</I> (67 F.3d 477 (3d Cir. 1995)), respectively).
 
</P> 
<P>
These courts' presumption toward preemption was challenged in 1995 by the following three appellate decisions:
</P>

<P>
<OL TYPE="1" START="1">
	<LI>The Eleventh Circuit's decision in <I>Lohr v. Medtronic Inc.</I>, regarding the lack of federal design requirements inherent in the 510(k) process (56 F.3d 1335, 11th Cir.);
</P>

<P>
	<LI>The Fifth Circuit's decision in <I>Feldt v. Mentor Corp.</I>, which denied preemption of design claims involving a Class III 510(k) device (61 F.3d 431, 5th Cir.); and 
</P>

<P>
	<LI>The Ninth Circuit's decision in <I>Kennedy v. Collagen</I> (67 F.3d 1453, 9th Cir.), which held that the reference to requirements in the preemption language does not include requirements imposed through state common law suits.
</OL>
</P>

<P>
Significantly, the <I>Medtronic</I> decision will limit the application of preemption severely in the future, one device attorney said, adding that there are still considerations to be made in the PMA and IDE areas. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Pending Cases</B>
</P>

<P>
The impact the <I>Medtronic</I> decision will have on device product liability cases currently pending is great. Among other cases, the Supreme Court already has remanded since the June 26 decision two cases to the appellate level -- <I>Mitchell v. Collagen Corp.</I> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4286 (No. 95-1323)) and <I>Mentor v. Feldt</I> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4284 (No. 95-1037)) -- and has denied <I>certiorari</I> for another: <I>Collagen Corp. v. Kennedy</I> (1996 U.S. LEXIS 4296 (No. 95-1644)). 
</P>

<P>
In a prepared statement, Medtronic states that it was surprised that the Court had reversed the trend in which the overwhelming majority of lower courts had limited product liability claims for devices cleared through the 510(k) process.
</P>

<P>
"Medtronic sought this ruling to insure that inconsistent standards created by [f]ederal and [s]tate law would not inhibit future medical innovation and limit patient choices," the statement said. </FONT>
</P>
 





