<html> 
<head>
<title>FDA Alleges High Deviation Rate During Drug and Device Inspections</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/feds/fedshead.gif" alt="FDA Enforcement Manual">

<h2>FDA Alleges High Deviation Rate During Drug and Device Inspections</h2>

<P>
The FDA has modified several of its enforcement practices during the past few years, but recently released data for fiscal year 1995 (FY '95) (Oct. 1, 1994 - Sept. 30, 1995) suggest little change in the high deviation rates alleged in plant inspections and, for some products, continued increases in official actions taken.
</P>

<P>
The FY '95 data, which recently were released for the first time, show that the FDA alleged deviations in 61 percent of drug inspections and 56 percent of medical device inspections, both of which represent increases over the previous fiscal year (see "Establishment Inspections, Deviation Rates, FY 1992 - FY 1995," below).  The inspectional deviation rate was 40 percent for food and cosmetics and 38 percent for biologics.
</P>

<HR><CENTER><H4 ALIGN=LEFT>Establishment Inspections, Deviation Rates, FY 1992 - FY 1995</H4>
</CENTER>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="fedsoct1.gif"><P>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="2"><B>Source</B>: FY 1995 Data recently published in the <I>FDA Enforcement Story, Fiscal Year 1995</I>. Prior year data originated from FDA Quarterly Activities Report, fiscal years 1992-1994.
</FONT>
</P>
<HR>
<P>
Although the proportion of these deviations considered "serious" by the agency is unreported, the upward trend in violations seen during medical device inspections was accompanied by a substantial climb in the number of device Warning Letters issued, which increased by 10 percent over FY '94, to an all-time record of 656 (see charts, below;  "CDRH Official Sends Mixed Messages on Enforcement," November 1995, p. 1)
</P>

<P>
However, in other product areas, the FDA data show either consistent or downward trends in official enforcement actions. For drugs, the number of Warning Letters declined to 329 for FY '95 from 402 in FY '94, while food and cosmetic Warning Letters rose slightly to 318, up from 301.
</P>

<P>
Fluctuations in FDA enforcement data may reflect many different factors, but experts say that the current trends reflect agency strategies that rely heavily on: the product approval process to ensure compliance, improved targeting through computerized record keeping, and, particularly, an agency desire to maintain low visibility because of congressional pressure to lighten regulatory burdens.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Shifting Landscape?</H3>
</P>

<P>
One strategy that experts believe has been employed at the agency is the use of "untitled letters." Unlike the Warning Letter, the untitled letter is not an official notice for violations of law and does not attract the same level of publicity. Some experts have estimated that the agency currently issues hundreds of untitled letters each year.
</P>

<P>
However, in cases involving new product applications, the FDA frequently can achieve its compliance objectives by putting an application on hold, rather than using an "official" enforcement action. Roughly one-third of new drug applications (NDAs) are withheld due to good manufacturing practice (GMP) deviations detected by the FDA during preapproval inspections (see "FDA Cites Leading Deviations in Withholding NDA Approvals," September 1996, p. 1).  In addition, drug-related preapproval inspections can be funded through user fees -- meaning that the FDA expends little or none of its regular budget for inspections associated with a pending drug application.
</P>

<P>
The exception to this trend would appear to occur in medical devices, where no user fees exist and where enforcement data show no downward trends. Further, roughly 98 percent of devices are cleared through premarket notification, a process usually not involving preapproval inspection.
</P>

<P>
In food and cosmetic products, the number of FDA enforcement actions has changed minimally, but the agency's figures may not reflect a growing number of independent state actions in enforcing the food labeling provisions of the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act (FD&amp;C Act). During 1995, states received new authority to directly enforce the federal food labeling laws without ongoing FDA oversight.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Import Shift</H3>
</P>

<P>
Perhaps the greatest change occurring during FY '95 was the partial automation of the FDA's import processing system, which has enabled the agency to improve its targeting of imported products -- particularly drugs and devices.
</P>

<P>
The new system is part of the Operational and Administrative System for Import Support (OASIS), which currently is awaiting full implementation (see &#182;912). OASIS enables the FDA to issue "may proceed" notices automatically for a majority of products, while focusing its attention on priority products at the U.S. ports of entry. 
</P>

<P>
Not surprisingly, the system appears to have dramatically cut down the number of product entries sampled by the FDA: During FY '95, the agency sampled 28,007 entries, 47 percent fewer than the 52,380 entries sampled during FY '94.
</P>

<P>
However, the total number of import detentions stayed relatively unchanged, and even increased for drugs and medical devices. Drug-related import detentions jumped by 26 percent to 5,646 and medical device detentions increased by 3 percent, to 6,426. Detentions of biological products jumped by nearly 150 percent, from 41 to 100. FDA sources indicated that automatic detentions -- without sampling of the product -- accounted for most of these increases. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Injunctions, Prosecutions and Seizures</H3>
</P>

<P>
The changes in routine FDA enforcement actions were not accompanied by dramatic change in the number of court cases brought during this time period, although the number of injunctions increased by roughly one-third, from 16 to 21. Prosecutions for criminal violations of the FD&amp;C Act stayed the same during FY '95 -- at eight -- as in the previous year. Seizure actions continued to fall, reaching an all-time low of 73.
</P>

<P>
Missing, however, from both injunctions and prosecutions in FY '95 and during the current year was the high-profile publicity that previously accompanied many such actions. In fact, the agency even canceled its quarterly publication of enforcement statistics and highlights, which had been published routinely since 1991.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Outlook</H3>
</P>

<P>
Although the recently released FDA figures offer some hope for industry that the FDA may be seeking less public forms of enforcement, few industry experts see any substantial change in the FDA's zealous pursuit of what it believes are serious deviations to its regulations.  
</P>

<P>
In fact, some experts believe that the FDA is even less predictable than in previous years, and may even be moving toward tighter regulation of drug and medical device manufacturing through more prescriptive, exacting GMP rules. At press time, no comprehensive data for 1996 had been released.
</P>

<HR>
