<html>Education, Preparation Are Keys To Surviving New Breed of SEC
Examination</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/tax/mony/monyhead.gif"  alt="Money Manager's Compliance Guide"></center>
<hr>
<h2>Education, Preparation Are Keys To Surviving New Breed of SEC
Examination</h2><P>
<body>
<i>By Anthony R. Mansfield and Kevin M. Broadwater</i><p>

Registered investment advisers with more than $25 million in assets under

management can expect more frequent examinations from the Securities and

Exchange Commission, in the wake of the National Securities Markets Improvement

Act of 1996.<p>

The law, which was signed by President Clinton in October, handed over

inspection responsibility for investment advisers managing less than $25 million

in assets to the states, allowing SEC examiners to focus more attention on large

advisers (for more information on the law, see "President Signs Broad Regulatory

Reform Legislation To Eliminate Securities Overlaps," p. 1, November 1996).<p>

Preceding this shift in responsibility, SEC's Office of Compliance Inspections

and Examinations (OCIE) developed a new approach to investment adviser

inspections, targeting advisers that have a greater potential for

noncompliance.<p>

Under the new approach, OCIE may select specific areas for review based on its

assessment of the quality of a firm's compliance systems, rather than conducting

a traditional comprehensive examination that reviews every aspect of an

adviser's operations.<p>

Because OCIE is tailoring the scope of its examinations to the perceived

adequacy of an adviser's existing compliance system, advisers may wish to

re-examine their compliance policies to develop strategies that are designed to

show OCIE examiners that they have effective compliance procedures in place.

Following are some suggestions for investment advisers to use in preparing for

an OCIE examination.<p>

The logical first step in preparing for an examination is to ensure that

adequate compliance systems exist for all aspects of the adviser's operations.

This review should include a comprehensive examination of all policies and

procedures, with a view to ensuring that all required procedures are up to date

and reflect current regulatory interpretations.<p>

Advisers for mutual funds should re-evaluate their procedures and amend them if

necessary to reflect recent regulatory developments in areas such as personal

securities trading, aggregation of client orders with fund orders, and

amendments to Rule 2a-7 of the Investment Company Act of 1940. In addition,

advisers should ensure that any representations made as a condition for

no-action or exemptive relief are still accurate, and should review any

undertakings made as a condition for no-action or exemptive relief to determine

whether they have been effected and appropriately documented.<p>

Mutual fund advisers also should evaluate procedures for ensuring that the

fund's investment limits as stated in the prospectus are not exceeded. Finally,

advisers should review their recordkeeping and documentation requirements and

procedures. While this process may seem arduous and time-consuming, the time

spent reviewing and revising procedures in advance of an SEC inspection could

amount to time and money saved in doing the same work later, but under SEC

scrutiny.<p>

<h3>Role of Compliance Department</h3><p>

Another useful exercise is to review the way compliance is managed. Advisers

should periodically review the role of the compliance department in monitoring

operations to look for any weaknesses. Most investment advisers rely on the

legal or compliance department to handle compliance matters, but, quite often,

compliance matters are handled in a haphazard fashion. The time pressures of

managing compliance for a large fund combined with the potential for simple

human error means that compliance issues will sometimes be missed. A harried and

overburdened compliance staff will invite SEC scrutiny about its effectiveness

and possibly call into question all of an adviser's compliance efforts.<p>

In addition, the compliance department should look beyond day-to-day compliance

issues to focus on systemic compliance mechanisms. The review of the compliance

department should address questions such as: Is personal trading by investment

professionals effectively monitored? Are there written procedures for ensuring

that compliance functions are carried out? Are there clear lines of reporting

and responsibility for compliance personnel? Is there a way to monitor and

evaluate the effectiveness of the compliance department itself? Is the

compliance department adequately staffed with trained professionals?<p>

Resolution of these issues will produce a stronger compliance department that is

less likely to overlook potential violations, and will demonstrate to SEC that

the adviser takes its compliance responsibilities seriously.<p>

<h3>Role of Management Personnel</h3><p>

Because an adviser's management personnel may be among the first interviewed by

SEC examiners, it is important that they be involved in, or at least aware of,

the firm's compliance systems. Active involvement enables management to

understand the challenges faced by the compliance department and helps to foster

a compliance culture. The more distant management is from the operations of the

compliance department, the easier it is for investment professionals to remain

unconcerned about potential violations. OCIE examiners will look to see how

involved management is in compliance operations when assessing the overall

compliance culture of the adviser.<p>

Managing investment company and other client assets requires attention to

federal and state securities laws, tax laws, the Employee Retirement Income

Security Act, and other laws. The procedures established to comply with these

laws can be lengthy and complicated. Many advisers maintain a compliance manual

containing these procedures. However, it is still difficult for investment

professionals to remain up to date on every aspect of their operations.

Accordingly, the compliance department should conduct regular periodic

educational seminars to help keep their investment professionals current on

regulatory developments. These educational efforts should also be directed at

reminding the investment professionals of their obligations under applicable

laws and the firm's compliance procedures. A consistent educational effort

throughout the firm is one more way to show SEC that the adviser has an

appropriate regard for compliance.<p>

<h3>Mock Examinations</h3><p>

After the review of compliance procedures and the resolution of any potential

weaknesses in compliance monitoring or reporting, the adviser should determine

how best to demonstrate to SEC that its compliance controls are adequate. Many

advisers have engaged outside counsel to conduct mock examinations to give

senior management, portfolio managers and compliance personnel practice in

responding to SEC examiners. This process also serves to educate the adviser's

personnel on the firm's existing compliance procedures and the role of the

compliance department.<p>

Mock examinations are also an excellent way to test the compliance awareness of

the adviser's personnel. Weaknesses can easily be identified and immediately

corrected. As part of the mock examination, all individuals who are likely to be

interviewed by the SEC examiner should be instructed on how to respond to

questions. In addition, all personnel should be made aware of the value of

demonstrating the company's high regard for compliance. <p>

At the end of the mock examination process, the adviser's personnel should be

able to respond to the examiner's questions by referring to the appropriate

compliance procedure that governs his or her conduct. In this way, the adviser

is able to point out its compliance procedures and demonstrate that its

personnel are aware of the procedures. By having the adviser's personnel

highlight its compliance systems, the adviser may be able to limit the scope of

the SEC examination.<p>

<I>Anthony R. Mansfield is a partner in the New York law firm of Seward &amp;

Kissel. Kevin M. Broadwater is an associate in the firm's Washington office.

This piece was adapted from an article that appeared in the Oct. 23 edition of

The Review of Securities and Commodities Regulation, published by Standard &amp;

Poor's Corp. 
</I>

</body> 

<foot>

