<html></H3>
<head>
<title>Industry Decries FDA Proposed Drug GMP Rule </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/feds/fedshead.gif" alt="FDA Enforcement Manual">

<h2>Industry Decries FDA Proposed Drug GMP Rule </h2>

<P>
The FDA's proposed rule on good manufacturing practices (GMPs) for drugs suggests a new philosophy toward manufacturing controls that could result in far greater burdens and cost than current drug GMPs, according to industry comments on the May 3 proposed rule.
</P>

<P>
"PhRMA believes that the issues raised by this proposed rule represent such a radical departure from long-standing philosophy for [GMP] regulation that the proposal should be withdrawn," states the Pharmaceutical Researchers and Manufacturers of America (PhRMA) in its comments. "This new approach with specific detailed requirements identified within the regulation, will inhibit the flexibility necessary to implement innovations and advances in manufacturing systems." 
</P>

<P>
"It is clear that the cost to comply with the proposed GMP revisions will be significantly more than the $2.9 million estimated in the Proposed Rule," states the Generic Pharmaceutical Industry Association (GPIA) in its comments. "The cost for validating time limits for each phase of production alone could cost every firm hundreds of thousands of dollars."
</P>

<P>
The proposal, "Current Good Manufacturing Practices; Proposed Amendments of Certain Requirements for Finished Pharmaceuticals," creates more specific, detailed parameters for manufacturing controls of finished pharmaceuticals than exist today, with a particular emphasis on validation procedures (61 FR 20104; see "FDA Proposes Tighter GMP Controls," July 1996, p. 1). The comment period on the proposed rule closed Sept. 30.
</P>

<P>
"The main purpose for the change did concern process validation," John Dietrick of the Division of Manufacturing and Product Quality, within the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research (CDER), affirmed during a recent conference of the Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society in Washington, D.C. Dietrick explained that although the proposed GMP rule encompasses far more than just validation, it was intended to provide new validation definitions and specific requirements for protocols, documentation and quality assurance (QA) approvals.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Blend Sample Sizes</H3>
</P>

<P>
Chief among the objectionable provisions identified by industry is the requirement under proposed 21 CFR &#167;211.110 that sampling and testing of in-process materials and drug products be based on unit dose samples.
</P>

<P>
"Unit dose sampling may not be appropriate or achievable," states the GPIA, explaining that the dynamic nature of powder blends makes for an "inexact science" when sampling, and thus unit dose sampling would likely lead to rejection of many good batches. Also, the methods proposed in the regulation would be inappropriate for dosage forms other than oral solids; for all products, testing of finished dosage forms would offer far more accurate results, argues GPIA.
</P>

<P>
Similarly, in its comments, PhRMA "strongly objects" to the unit dose sampling provision and questions its appropriateness within the regulation.
</P>

<P>
Although he acknowledged problems with this provision, the FDA's Dietrick did not say that the agency is prepared to completely abandon the concept of unit dose testing.
</P>

<P>
"We've probably gotten more comments on this than any other section," Dietrick said. "We prefer that sampling be small, near the dosage size, but we've received many comments that [this] is impossible for 15 to 20 percent of products.
</P>

<P>
"I still believe that [unit dose testing] should be done for these products when it does work," he added. "I'm only going to recommend that sampling be small enough to prevent masking nonuniformity and large enough to provide accurate results."
</P>

<P>
Dietrick added that a second requirement under proposed section 211.110 requiring that validation samples be representative of the blend is really intended "to allow sampling from either the blender or the drums," provided that a validated method is used.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Record Keeping</H3>
</P>

<P>
A second objectionable provision identified by commenters is proposed section 211.180, requiring manufacturers to maintain validation records, including validation batch records, for as long as the validated process is being used.
</P>

<P>
"The proposed language could be interpreted to require that all batch records associated with that process be retained as long as the validation records [are retained]," states PhRMA.
</P>

<P>
"Our intent was to require that validation records -- protocol, batch and testing records and the final report -- be maintained as long as that process is being used," Dietrick said, explaining this provision.
</P>

<P>
"Some of the comments indicated that this was being misunderstood to require that all batch records for all batches made with that validated system be maintained for that length of time," Dietrick added. "That's not what we meant to say, but if that's what is being interpreted then we'll have to change that."
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Definitions</H3>
</P>

<P>
Definitions in the proposed rule under proposed section 210.3 revise several existing terms and establish specific meanings for the first time for the following terms: validation protocol, process validation, methods validation, equipment suitability, process suitability and manufacturing process. 
</P>

<P>
In its comments, PhRMA objects to 10 of the definitions in the rule, including "validation protocol," "reworking," "manufacturing process," and "process suitability." In addition, PhRMA proposes that two new definitions be added, for "retrospective validation," and "change control" to delineate elements in the broad definition of manufacturing process used by the agency.
</P>

<P>
Although he did not mention specifics, Dietrick indicated that changes to the definitions may be forthcoming -- particularly to previously existing terms.
</P>

<P>
"We had a few comments on these, some of them expressing concern that we were changing definitions that had been used in the past," Dietrick said. "We didn't intend to do that -- we don't want to add more confusion to the process and we'll take a close look at it before it becomes final."
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>QC Responsibilities</H3>
</P>

<P>
Another key issue identified by commenters was the designation of the "quality control (QC) unit" as the principal unit responsible for assuring and overseeing validation efforts (proposed section 211.22).
</P>

<P>
"It appears that the FDA is not clearly defining the separation of [quality assurance] and [quality control] units," states the GPIA, explaining that the two functions must be delineated and provision made for conduct of validation by other company departments.
</P>

<P>
Dietrick explained that although the rule is intended to vest ultimate responsibility for validation with the QC unit, that does not mean that it is the only unit authorized to conduct validation.
</P>

<P>
"The comments on these are generally [concerning] the team approach to validation and sharing of responsibilities," he said. "We did not intend to say that all validation must be done by the QC unit -- we're only attempting to be consistent with other QC sections and give authority for final approval to QC."
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Maximum Time Limits</H3>
</P>

<P>
Another provision that sparked industry protests is a new requirement under proposed section 211.111 that manufacturers validate maximum time limits for completion of each phase of production, including storage, as part of process validation.
</P>

<P>
"Validating storage steps would place an undue burden on firms to either incorporate holding times during process validation or to place all these iterations up on stability," the GPIA argues. "We strongly believe that only critical, time-sensitive process phases require validation .... [T]imes for non-time-sensitive phases or between phases should not require validation, but should be required through overall time limits."
</P>

<P>
However, Dietrick did not indicate that the provision was perceived by FDA to represent a significant change from existing requirements.
</P>

<P>
"The existing [section] 211.111 now requires that firms establish time limits on production .... [T]his change only adds the requirement to validate those time limits," he said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Outlook</H3>
</P>

<P>
Although Dietrick did not provide details of FDA deliberations on all provisions of the proposed rule, he did state that the agency intended to weigh the comments carefully before issuing a final rule. He offered no predictions on when the rule would be published.
</P>

<P>
Questions about the proposed rule can be directed to John Dietrick, (301) 594-0098, or via e-mail at: dietrickj@cder.fda.gov.
</P>

<HR>
<P>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>New Design Controls Come With One-year Enforcement Moratorium</H4>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
The FDA's quality systems final rule imposes new design control requirements on device manufacturers, but eases the compliance burden through a two-stage implementation process and a one-year moratorium on enforcement actions (61 FR 52602). 
</P>

<P>
In addition to imposing design control requirements, the new rule -- published Oct. 7 -- revises several aspects of the existing good manufacturing practice (GMP) regulations and harmonizes manufacturing control requirements with international standards. The quality systems rule "embraces the same 'umbrella' approach to the [GMP] regulation that is the underpinning of the original [GMP] regulation," according to its preamble. 
</P>

<P>
Although the rule will become effective June 1, 1997, enforcement of the design control provisions will not formally begin until June 1, 1998. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Enforcement Timetable</B>
</P>

<P>
Because of industry concerns about preparing their operations for the design control requirements, the FDA has decided to implement the final rule in two phases. As of June 1, 1997, all elements of the quality systems provisions of the final rule will become effective (stage one). However, as long as manufacturers "are taking reasonable steps to come into compliance," the FDA will implement a one-year transition period for design control requirements with a "mid-course review" (stage two). 
</P>

<P>
If a firm is not in compliance with the design control rules during stage one, the FDA will not take any official action (including recording observations on FDA Form 483s, the issuance of Warning Letters or the initiation of enforcement cases) (see &#182;339, Tab 400). Rather, the FDA investigator will issue observations of design control problems found during inspection on a separate "design control inspectional strategy report" that will become a part of the manufacturer's establishment inspection report. However, device manufacturers must take steps to come into compliance during stage one. 
</P>

<P>
To prepare for the phase-in of the design control requirements, the FDA plans to develop a design control inspection strategy by April 1997 and to hold training for industry and agency investigators. In December 1997, the FDA will review the findings from the first six months of inspections, including the design control strategy reports issued to manufacturers. 
</P>

<P>
In early 1998, the agency will hold a public meeting to discuss the findings and to further explore industry's concerns. The FDA also will review whether the final design control requirements "are appropriate to obtain the goals expressed" by the agency and may publish revisions if warranted. The FDA indicates it will extend the date for compliance with the rules if it determines more time is necessary for full implementation of the design control provisions.
</FONT></P>


<hr>
