<html>
<head>
<title>FDA Mulls Labeling for Free Glutamate Content</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/food/foodhead.gif" alt="Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law"></center>
<P>
<h2>FDA Mulls Labeling for Free Glutamate Content</h2>

<P>
A recent scientific finding that monosodium glutamate (MSG) can cause adverse reactions (when eaten without food) has prompted the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to consider establishing requirements for the labeling of foods with either MSG or other forms of free glutamates.
</P>

<P>
In an advance notice of proposed rulemaking in the Sept. 12 <I>Federal Register</I> (61 <I>FR</I> 48102), FDA says that the Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology (FASEB) recently found that oral ingestion of three or more grams of MSG without [solid] food can cause adverse reactions in certain otherwise healthy individuals. (The full text of the notice is provided in this monthÕs update to the <I>Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law</I> manual.)
</P>

<P>
The FASEB findings were based on an analysis of test data in which human subjects were given MSG or a placebo with either water or fruit juice. There were no available scientifically valid studies involving ingestion of MSG with solid foods, an FDA spokesperson said. She explained that although a [solid] food matrix might attenuate some of the effects of MSG, FDA feels that the non-[solid] food test results should be the baseline.
</P>

<P>
<H3>FDA Seeking Comments on Several Issues</H3>
</P>

<P>
Under current FDA regulations, when MSG is used as an ingredient in a food it must be declared in the ingredient statement. This is true even when MSG has been added indirectly as part of another ingredient (e.g., a spice blend that includes MSG).
</P>

<P>
The agency is seeking public comment on whether additional labeling requirements are necessary to protect glutamate-intolerant customers from adverse reactions and, if so, how such labeling should be implemented. FDA is also seeking comments on establishing formal criteria for the use of claims regarding the absence of MSG to ensure that labels bearing such claims are not misleading.  It also seeks feedback on whether such criteria should be based on a defined threshold level of free glutamate in a finished food, on the ingredients used in the food, or both.
</P>

<P>
While MSG is the most well-known and widely used form of free glutamate for enhancing the flavor of foods, other salts of free glutamate, such as monopotassium glutamate and monoammonium glutamate, also have flavor-enhancing properties. In addition to MSG, glutamic acid, glutamic acid hydrochloride, monoammonium glutamate, and monopotassium glutamate all must be declared in ingredients statements as well. For this reason, FDA considers foods whose labels say ÒNo MSGÓ or ÒNo added MSGÓ to be misleading if the food contains ingredients that are sources of free glutamates, such as hydrolyzed protein.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Label Declarations for Free Glutamate</H3>
</P>

<P>
Free glutamate occurs naturally in various foods and in food substances that are used as finished foods, or it can be produced by hydrolysis of proteins, in which case the presence of free glutamate in the food is not required to be declared on the label under existing regulations. Naturally occurring free glutamate is not required to be declared in the ingredient statement because it is not an added ingredient; rather, it is a natural constituent of the food, like protein or a vitamin. 
</P>

<P>
Similarly, when a food that contains naturally occurring free glutamate is used as an ingredient in another food, the free glutamate is not required to be declared in the ingredient statement of the finished food. Rather, the ingredient containing the free glutamate is declared in the ingredient statement by its common or usual name. 
</P>

<P>
This policy that it is the ingredients and not the constituents of a food that must be declared also applies when a food that contains free glutamate produced by protein hydrolysis is used as an ingredient in another food. (An ingredient is defined as a substance used to fabricate a food: for example, chocolate might include such  ingredients as chocolate liqueur, sugar, and milk. A constituent is defined as a naturally occurring part of an ingredient. A constituent of milk, for example, would be lactose.) In that situation too, the glutamate-containing ingredient must be declared in the ingredient statement of the finished food, but free glutamate need not be declared as an ingredient. 
</P>

<P>
Because the average consumer is unaware that free glutamate is essentially equivalent to MSG, or that ingredients like hydrolyzed soy protein, autolyzed yeast extract, tomato paste, and parmesan cheese contain free glutamate, declaration of these ingredients by their common or usual names does not indicate to the consumer that an MSG-like substance is present in the food.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Hidden Ingredients</H3>
</P>

<P>
A number of consumers, particularly those with an adverse reaction to MSG, have told FDA they believe that manufacturers use ingredients such as hydrolyzed protein and autolyzed yeast expressly to add free glutamate to a food while hiding its presence.
</P>

<P>
Until recently, FDA felt that the scientific literature did not provide a public health basis on which to impose special labeling requirements for such ingredients or for foods that contain free glutamate. In light of recent findings of the Life Sciences Research Office of FASEB, however, FDA is reconsidering the need for labeling to inform individuals who experience adverse reactions to glutamate about its presence in a food.
</P>

<P>
The FASEB study indicated that an unknown percentage of the population might react to MSG and develop MSG symptom complex, a condition characterized by one or more of the following symptoms:
</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Burning sensation in the back of the neck, forearms, and chest;<BR>
	<LI>Numbness in the back of the neck, radiating to the arms and back;<BR>
	<LI>Tingling, warmth and weakness in the face, temples, upper back, neck, and arms;<BR>
	<LI>Facial pressure or tightness;<BR>
	<LI>Chest pain;<BR>
	<LI>Headache;<BR>
	<LI>Nausea;<BR>
	<LI>Rapid heartbeat;<BR>
	<LI>Bronchospasm (difficulty breathing) in MSG-intolerant people with asthma;<BR>
	<LI>Drowsiness; and <BR>
	<LI>Weakness.
</UL>

<P>
Comments should be sent by Nov. 11, 1996 to the Dockets Management Branch (HFA 305), Food and Drug Administration, 12420 Parklawn Drive, rm. 1-23, Rockville, MD, 20857.
</P>



<hr>
<center>
