<head>
<title>Quality Systems Final Rule Is Issued, Goes Into Effect June 1997</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device
Regulation"></center>
<P>
<h2>Quality Systems Final Rule Is Issued, Goes Into Effect June 1997</h2>

<P>
Following several years of debate and refinement, the quality systems concept became a reality on Oct. 7, when the FDA published the medical device quality systems final rule in the <I>Federal Register</I> (61 FR 52602, see App. II, App. III). The quality systems final rule incorporates elements of the existing good manufacturing practice (GMP) regulation, harmonizes manufacturing control requirements with international standards, and imposes new design control requirements on manufacturers of new device products. 
</P>

<P>
The FDA published a proposed rule in November 1993 and released to the public a revised working draft final rule in July 1995. The final rule's preamble addresses hours of public debate and hundreds of industry comments on those versions, and strives to respond to criticisms that the previous incarnations were too prescriptive.
</P>

<P>
"The agency's final rule embraces the same 'umbrella' approach to the [GMP] regulation that is the underpinning of the original [GMP] regulation," the preamble to the final rule states (61 FR 52606, see App. III). "Because this regulation must apply to so many different types of devices, the regulation does not prescribe in detail how a manufacturer must produce a specific device." 
</P>

<P>
Although the entire rule will become effective June 1, 1997, enforcement of the design control provisions will not formally begin until June 1, 1998. 
</P>

<P>
<H3>Background</H3>
</P>

<P>
The addition of design controls "will save lives and will greatly reduce the risks from unrecognized design flaws," according to an FDA "Talk Paper" issued Oct. 4. The FDA was authorized to require preproduction design controls by the Safe Medical Devices Act of 1990. This change was prompted by studies conducted by the FDA and the Department of Health and Human Services' Inspector General (IG), which found that a significant number of device problems could be attributed to inadequate design controls. 
</P>

<P>
Specifically, the FDA found that approximately 44 percent of quality problems leading to voluntary device recalls could be attributed to errors or deficiencies that were designed into the products, and could have been prevented by adequate design controls. The IG's study report cited similar problems, and found that the percentage of design-related problems was even higher for software used to operate medical devices.
</P>

<P>
"A subsequent study of software-related recalls for the period of fiscal year (FY) 1983 through FY 1991 indicated that over 90 percent of all software-related device failures were due to design-related errors, generally, the failure to validate software prior to routine production," the preamble states (see "Design Controls and Software Are a Good Mix ..." p. 6).
</P>

<P>
<H3>Two Major Changes</H3>
</P>

<P>
The two primary changes implemented as the quality systems rule made its way through the rulemaking process are related to the scope of the new rule: whether or not component manufacturers are covered by the rule, and whether or not the definition of manufacturers includes servicers and refurbishers. 
</P>

<P>
Many industry members had objected to the application of the rule to component manufacturers because they feared doing so would increase product costs, provide limited added value and lead many component manufacturers to discontinue supplying the device industry (see "Manufacturers Express Common Concerns ...," October 1995, p. 1). The agency indicated last year that it would be willing to delete this requirement provided that all safety issues were being addressed elsewhere in the regulation. The preamble to the final rule states that purchasing controls and acceptance requirements (new 21 CFR &#167;&#167;820.50, 820.80), see App. II) "are sufficient to provide the needed assurance that suppliers, contractors and consultants have adequate controls to produce acceptable components." 
</P>

<P>
Accordingly, the agency has removed the provision requiring component manufacturers to be covered by the quality systems rule. 
</P>

<P>
Further, the FDA was unable to reach consensus regarding whether or not servicers and refurbishers should be treated as manufacturers under the regulation. At the GMP Advisory Committee meeting in September 1995, the committee was sharply divided on this issue. The agency chose to exclude this provision from the final rule and "elected to address application of the ... requirements to persons who provide servicing and refurbishing functions outside the control of the original manufacturer in a separate rulemaking later this year, with another opportunity for public comment." 
</P>

<P>
<H3>Enforcement Timetable</H3>
</P>

<P>
Based on industry concerns about changing their operations in preparation for the new requirements -- especially design control requirements -- the FDA has decided to implement the final rule in two phases. As of June 1, 1997, all elements of the quality systems final rule will become effective. However, provided that manufacturers "are taking reasonable steps to come into compliance," the FDA will implement a one-year transition period for design control requirements with a mid-course review (see "CDRH Holds Workshop ...," October 1996, p. 5). 
</P>

<P>
During the first phase -- from June 1997 until June 1998 -- the FDA will not take any official action (including observations on FDA Form 483s, the issuance of Warning Letters or the initiation of enforcement cases), if a firm is not yet in compliance with the design control requirements. Rather, the FDA investigator will issue observations of design control problems found during inspection on "a separate design control inspectional strategy report." 
</P>

<P>
The design control inspectional strategy report will become a part of the manufacturer's establishment inspection report, but the observations relating to design control requirements "will not be included in any [W]arning [L]etters or regulatory actions during this initial one-year period," the preamble states.
</P>

<P>
The FDA reminds industry that it is required to take steps to come into compliance during this period, and that the agency "can, at any time, take action against unsafe or adulterated medical devices under different regulatory or statutory requirements." 
</P>

<P>
To prepare for the phase-in of design controls, the FDA intends to develop a design control inspection strategy by April 1997, with training held for industry and agency investigators during April and May of next year. 
</P>

<P>
<H3>Mid-course Review Results</H3>
</P>

<P>
In December 1997, the FDA will review the design control findings resulting from the first six months of inspections, including the strategy reports given to manufacturers during this period. Reports will be reviewed to determine the following:
</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
<P>
	<LI>Clarity of information obtained;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Appropriateness of collected information regarding design control requirements;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Appropriateness of the inspectional strategy questions;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Manner in which investigators are writing out their obligations; and
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Any requirements that appear to be problematic for manufacturers or where there might be confusion regarding what the regulation requires. 
</P>
</UL>

<P>
In early 1998, the agency intends to hold a public meeting to discuss the findings from this review and further explore industry's concerns. Additional public meetings, workshops or training sessions could be held following that meeting. At that point, the FDA also will be reviewing whether or not the final design control requirements "are appropriate to obtain the goals expressed" by the agency, and could publish revisions based on this review. 
</P>

<P>
In addition, the FDA indicates that if it determines that either the agency or the industry needs more time to fully implement the design control provisions, the agency will extend the implementation date for compliance with these requirements. 
</P>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER><H4>Compliance With New Quality Systems Rule Can Be Good and Bad, Industry Rep Says</H4>
</CENTER></P>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
As the quality systems final rule becomes a reality, many companies are seeing only the downside, such as added costs, more paperwork and less decision control, according to Robert Bard, vice president of regulatory and legal affairs at I-Flow Corp.
</P>

<P>
However, device regulatory affairs managers also should recognize the upside of the new rule, because it provides them with better controls over other departments (such as research and development), a bridge to international harmonization, a rationale for hiring more support staff and, ultimately, a higher quality product to support. 
</P>

<P>
"Some requirements tell us we need to do things differently from ISO 9000, differently than we do it today," Bard told attendees of a Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society meeting. "Although the new rule includes 30 modified definitions and requires at least 50 documents, we do a lot of this [document generation] already." 
</P>

<P>
However, Bard also predicted that the new rule would bring about the "death of small start-ups" that "operate on a shoestring," because it will be difficult for a two- to five-person company to "survive the sum total" of all the new requirements.  
</P>

<P>
Larger companies may need more people, incur more costs and experience slower product development times, but should be able, with the help of consultants as needed, to ride out the changes the new rule brings, Bard said.
</P></FONT>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/xray/xray.html"><img src="/tpg/food/xray/smallxray.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to Medical Device Regulation Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
