<html>
<head>
<title>CDRH Seeks Input on Device Software Policy That Promotes Industry</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device Regulation"></center>
<P>
<h2>CDRH Seeks Input on Device Software Policy That Promotes Industry</h2>

<P>
Recognizing that the state-of-the-art for medical device software "has moved past" FDA efforts, the Center for Devices and Radiological Health (CDRH) is looking to the medical device and software industries for insight on the best way to regulate this product area, according to CDRH Director Bruce Burlington, who spoke at a recent public workshop held in Bethesda, Md.
</P>

<P>
"We believe that by working with you at this stage, where our ideas are just beginning to form, that regulators, regulated industry and users can come up with a rational and reasonable approach that will protect the public health, as well as promote the development of a vigorous industry," Burlington told attendees of the Sept. 3-4 workshop co-sponsored by the FDA and the National Library of Medicine. Burlington admitted that the regulation of software is "a conundrum" for the agency.
</P>

<P>
"We want to understand where software is a medical device and where the public and public health protection will be achieved by the exercise of regulatory controls that [apply] to medical devices," he said. To date, the FDA essentially has concluded that if software has an intended use that relates to health care, particularly in the area of diagnostic decision-making, it is a device (see &#182;233).
</P>

<P>
However, because the FDA's approach to regulating devices is risk-based, Burlington explained that the agency does not wish to exercise controls where a device poses no hazards. However, if a device is part of an overall diagnosis process, then that product must be regulated, he said. Such high-risk devices would include computer-assisted diagnostic devices, automated test systems (such as those that determine which specimens need human review and which do not) and radiation therapy planning systems. 
</P>

<P>
"We need your help," Burlington said. "We need information on what can and what has gone wrong. Without information on the risks of software ... we will not be able to apply rational and proportionate controls that will serve our purpose of protecting the public health." 
</P>

<P>
Stressing that the agency "has to get the answer right," Burlington called on industry to help the agency categorize products according to risk to public health, and to help establish "bright lines" and clear decision points that lead to classification levels and the regulatory controls that apply to them. 
</P>

<P>
Although the agency set forth three major topics for discussion -- classification and risk-based criteria, alternatives to premarket notification requirements for certain medical software, including a "software quality audit" concept, and distribution issues related to software commercialization -- classification tops the FDA's priority list, according to agency officials. 
</P>

<P>
"We need to be able to identify and classify those low-end products to exempt them, because unless they are ... classified and exempt by regulation, they are ... subject to all requirements, " said Harvey Rudolph, deputy director of CDRH's Office of Science and Technology. "So we have to go through the classification process ... because the sooner we deal with it, the better it will set us up for the future," he said.
</P>

<P>
Although no time frame for issuing a new software policy has been set, the agency plans to address emerging issues "as best we can" during the "next 12 months" and develop a proposed policy, Rudolph said (see "Device Software Policy: Years in the Making," below). It is anticipated that the agency will hold additional workshops to discuss software issues. 
</P>

<HR>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT><CENTER>Device Software Policy: Years in the Making</CENTER></H4> 

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
Although medical software technology has become more complex and part of significantly more medical device products during the past seven years, regulated industry has been stuck with an FDA draft software policy that was last revised in 1989, a situation that was described in 1994 by an FDA official as "distasteful," and which may continue in the months ahead while the agency formulates the new policy.
</P>

<P>
Because of the increased complexity and prevalence of medical software and a lack of updated guidance since 1989, the FDA, software manufacturers and health care practitioners have "misunderstood or misinterpreted the provisions and exemptions" in the current policy, according to a "points of discussion" document issued by the agency in preparation for a public workshop held Sept. 3-4 in Bethesda, Md. (see "CDRH Seeks Input on Device Software Policy," p. 1). 
</P>

<P>
The 1989 draft policy informally described a program to limit FDA's regulatory reach over software. Specifically, the draft policy identified jurisdictional limitations over software and described a number of exemptions, including several exemptions that were not the result of rule making and, therefore, had no legal effect. Nonetheless, the agency has followed this draft policy's provisions for seven years. 
</P>

<P>
For devices subject to FDA regulation, the 1989 draft policy states that all medical software is subject to adulteration and misbranding provisions of the Federal Food, Drug &amp; Cosmetic Act (FD&amp;C Act) (21 USC &#167;&#167;351, 352, see App. I), that most devices would be subject only to these provisions, and that some devices would fall under good manufacturing practice regulations (21 CFR &#167;820, see App. II) and also need premarket notifications (510(k)s). 
</P>

<P>
The FDA's device regulations and authorities do not apply to software that is intended to perform traditional "library" functions (i.e., those storage, retrieval and dissemination functions carried out using medical textbooks and journals) or software that performs general accounting, communications or educational functions that do not affect the diagnosis or treatment of patients. General purpose software, software used in nonclinical research and software that is altered by a practitioner for use in his or her own practice also is exempt from the regulations. However, all other software -- including components and accessories -- are regulated by the FDA. 
</P>

<P>
Software components and accessories are regulated in the same manner and to the same degree as the parent device. In FDA's workshop document the agency identifies a component as integral parts of such devices as infusion pumps, pacemakers and magnetic resonance imaging devices. 
</P>

<P>
In identifying software accessories, the FDA has determined that if the software is specified or intended for use with a classified device, or directly interfaces with another device for transfer of data to and from the other device, the software is an accessory. Software for calculation of rate response for a cardiac pacemaker, for off-line analysis of electroencephalogram data or for radiation treatment planning would be considered regulated software. 
</P>

<P>
The FDA had promised to issue a new software policy by the end of 1994, which was slated to re-evaluate FDA's regulation of "stand-alone software (i.e., software that is neither a component nor a part of a medical device) and delete the 1989 "competent human intervention" provision which stated that unclassified software that can be overridden by health professionals is exempt from 510(k) requirements (see "Revised CDRH Software Policy ...," June 1994, p. 7). 
</P>

<P>
The "competent human intervention" exemption was intended to apply to medical software that generated data that could be interpreted and, if necessary, overridden by, a health professional. However, this provision has been misinterpreted to apply to all medical software devices, including any device that simulates artificial intelligence and stores and compresses data -- such as diagnostic X-ray systems or other radiological diagnostic products -- unless previously classified.
</P>

<P>
In January 1996, the FDA held a meeting to discuss a three-tiered classification approach for computer-aided diagnostic devices. Harvey Rudolph, deputy director of the Center for Devices and Radiological Health's Office of Science and Technology, explained the challenges of this approach at the Jan. 26 meeting. 
</P>

<P>
Although low-risk products exempt from review would fall into the bottom category and high-risk devices subject to premarket approval or 510(k) requirements would be placed in the top category, he said that the most challenging obstacle would be defining the criteria for moderate-risk products that possibly could be reviewed under a third-party certification process (see "FDA Renews Effort for Device Software Policy ...," March 1996, p. 4).
</P>
</FONT>
<HR>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT><CENTER>Better Defining Software Risk Criteria</CENTER></H4>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
To help identify risks associated with a medical device software product, as part of a software classification process, the FDA held discussions with several trade associations prior to its September software policy workshop. These discussions yielded the following criteria, with examples, for the FDA to consider when making classification decisions about software products. Participants at a September workshop to address software regulation complained that the criteria often only made sense for the specific example cited.
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>The seriousness of the particular disease or condition which the medical software device is intended to diagnose, cure, mitigate, treat or prevent and how the software contributes to the user's decision making for diagnosis or clinical management of the patient.
</P>
	
<P>
	<B>Example:</B> Software designed to call attention to imminent hazard conditions in an intensive care unit would be placed in a higher classification level than software that provides long-term storage for diagnostic radiologic information.
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>The amount of time available before using the information provided by the medical software device, i.e., the time until a therapeutic or additional diagnostic intervention must be implemented by the health care provider after the results of the software have been provided.
</P>
	
<P>
	<B>Example:</B> An EKG reading and analysis package device whose output is "SHOCK NOW" may be placed in a higher class than a device that provides a proposed reading with a notation that the rhythm itself should be checked.
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>Whether the data output is provided or manipulated in a novel or nontraditional manner or whether decision trees within the software depart from customary use.
</P>
	
<P>
	<B>Example:</B> If the system's algorithms, parameters, internal decision trees or other output manipulations depart from customary use it may be regulated differently than if it results in a traditional data presentation.
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>Whether the software device provides individualized patient care recommendations.
</P>
	
<P>
	<B>Example:</B> If the software provides general advice or information, like a library, article or textbook, it may be placed in a lower class than software designed to provide a specific recommendation for a specific patient.
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>Whether the mechanism by which the software device arrives at a decision is hidden or transparent.
</P>
	
<P>
	<B>Example:</B> If the limitations on the process are made known to the user, such as data contraction, deletion, editing or simplification, this may affect classification. Also, the methods used to make comparisons to normative databases and the ways normative databases are created may be factors in classification. 
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>Does the product provide new capabilities for the user?
</P>
</UL>

<P>
Although the FDA has indicated that it has not yet determined how the criteria would be applied in an objective and consistent way during classification, it is attempting to gather risk information that will help resolve classification issues. The FDA sought public comment during the workshop regarding whether or not any or all of these criteria are necessary to assess risk, if these criteria are comprehensive enough to assess risk, and how the criteria should be combined in a model to limit potential risk to patients. However, no consensus was reached and it is likely the FDA will hold additional workshops on specific issues in the future.
</FONT></P>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/xray/xray.html"><img src="/tpg/food/xray/smallxray.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to Medical Device Regulation Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
