<HTML> 
<HEAD> 
<TITLE>RBOC entry into video fraught with regulatory conflicts</TITLE> 
</HEAD> 

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/info/tube/tubehead.gif" alt="The Multichannel Video
 Compliance Handbook"></center><P>

<h3>Special Report</h3><P>
<h2> RBOC entry into video fraught with regulatory conflicts</h2>
It's been generally smooth sailing for the regional Bell operating companies
(RBOCs) in implementing their video service business plans: Ameritech has been
awarded 25 cable franchises; BellSouth has bought wireless cable properties and
is beginning to build full service networks; US West bought Continental
Cablevision; and PacTel, NYNEX and Bell Atlantic are constructing digital
wireless cable systems and broadband networks. By all indicators, competition
between RBOC and cable video services is beginning to emerge in pockets across
the country.<P>

But the most intense battles between the RBOCs and the cable industry may reside
more in the FCC and the courts than in the marketplace. That's because major
legal issues still need to be resolved before regulation can recede into the
background and competition can move to the forefront. <P>

The issue raising the most ire with the cable industry is the potential by RBOCs
for cross-subsidization, in which revenue from telephone ratepayers is used to
finance the construction of video service networks. Relatedly, the cable industry
advocates stringent cost allocation rules to ensure that RBOCs cannot
cross-subsidize. <P>

While the RBOCs and cable industry seem satisfied with the general principles of
the 1996 act, the details are still being ironed out in FCC proceedings and
federal courts. For example, the FCC has yet to release new cost allocation rules
and the commission's telephony interconnection order is stuck in federal court.
<P>

<h3><i>Charges of cross-subsidization</i></h3><P>

Accusations of cross-subsidization have been hurled at the RBOCs every time they
launch a new video service project. Because telephony is a much more lucrative
business than video programming distribution, the National Cable Television
Association (NCTA) has been vigilant in trying to ensure that the RBOCs not
engage in "anticompetitive conduct" by adding costs onto telephone rates to pay
for new video services. <P>

The 1996 act states that "a telecommunications carrier may not use services that
are not competitive to subsidize services that are competitive." But until all of
the regulatory protections are in place, the cable industry will not breathe any
easier. <P>

"It's irrational for telephone companies to not want to cross-subsidize," said
David Nicoll, an attorney with NCTA. The reason: telephone rates are currently
inflated, he said, providing RBOCs with plenty of excess revenue. Nicoll said
rates would be lower if phone competition truly existed, and cited the fact that
the FCC's recommended rates in its interconnection order are significantly lower
than RBOCs' current telephone rates. This, he contends, makes it difficult for
RBOCs to resist using revenue from telephone ratepayers, especially since a
substantial percentage exceeds the actual cost of providing telephone service.<P>

A representative from the United States Telephone Association was unavailable for
comment on these issues.<P>

Another cable-related concern is how to allocate costs for excess capacity
already constructed by telcos and new RBOC networks that can carry both voice and
video. NCTA has contended that "local telephone companies appear to have
constructed substantial excess capacity in anticipation of offering video
transmission," adding that the "costs of excess capacity should not be borne by
telephone ratepayers."<P>

A case in point is the conflict between BellSouth and Georgia and Tennessee cable
operators, which features many of the elements instigating conflict between RBOCs
and cable over video service: accusations of cross-subsidization, built-out
excess video capacity, unconventional cable franchising and claims of
discriminatory behavior. <P>

The Georgia and Tennessee cable operators have accused BellSouth of subsidizing
its entry into video service by:<P>
<UL><P>
<LI>laying excess co-axial cable without a franchise and paying for it from
telephone revenue;<P>
<LI>overcharging for services such as caller-ID and call-waiting in order to
subsidize video services; and<P>
<LI>discriminating against cable operators by overcharging for conduit and
pole-attachment space and foreclosing equal access to conduit space by favoring
its own video service.</UL><P>

This case illustrates the difficult issues still to be resolved surrounding the
RBOC entry into video. Most important, it could force BellSouth to justify its
expenditures on video services and set a precedent for how all RBOCs justify
video service investments. Also, the conflict makes clear that there still is no
guidance from the FCC on how telephone profits are defined and how these profits
can be used to build video systems. What's more, the commission may have to
establish complex accounting and monitoring mechanisms to avoid these types of
accusations in the future. <P>

<h3><i>Waiting on cost allocation</i></h3><P>

For Steve Effros, president of the Cable Telecommunications Association (CATA),
the cost allocation issue tops all of his concerns about RBOC entry into video
service. "We can't compete with what is still a monopoly service," he said,
adding that "the FCC has promised for four years ... to complete cost allocation
rules." <P>

As an example, the current open video system rulemaking is mired in conflict over
the issue of potential cross-subsidization. The FCC was supposed to complete OVS
cost allocation rules by October, but the complexity of the undertaking and RBOC
opposition to the proposed rules led to their postponement.<P>

While not opposing Bell Atlantic's OVS certification request for Dover Township,
N.J., (see November 1996 Monthly Bulletin, Page 11) NCTA believes it is
inappropriate to certify OVS providers without first having cost allocation rules
in place. According to NCTA, "cost allocation rules are essential to protect
consumers and competitors against anticompetitive cross-subsidy." <P>

In a brief on the issue to the FCC, NCTA said, "So long as the incumbent local
exchange carrier's telephone monopolies continue, the risk continues that
telephone rates in excess of costs will be used to subsidize video services, and
telephone customers will become unwilling contributors to an incumbent local
exchange carrier's anti-competitive strategy." <P>

The New Jersey Cable Telecommunications Association (NJCTA) claimed Bell Atlantic
is subsidizing its Dover Township system with revenue from telephone ratepayers.
In a brief filed with the FCC, NJCTA said, "If the commission does nothing, it
will allow tens of millions of dollars to slip into regulated telephone accounts
undetected." To this end, NJCTA requested that the FCC investigate how investment
capital allocated to the OVS system is assigned. <P>

NCTA's Nicoll said the only way to monitor telco cross-subsidization is to do an
audit. That aside, the challenge for the FCC is to determine how to allocate
common costs associated with facilities that can provide both voice and video
linking the telephone company's central office to customers. The cable industry
has suggested that telco expenditures should be governed by a fixed allocation
factor in which some percentage of the plant is allocated to each service. Under
this scheme, if 50 percent of the costs of the integrated network are for
telephone service, then 50 percent of the cost of the video portion of the
network could be subsidized by revenues from the telephone users of the network.
<P>

Another possible solution is to require that RBOCs offer video service in a
separate subsidiary from their telephony operations, including for OVS. The cable
industry contends that structural separation is necessary because telcos have a
strong incentive to misallocate costs associated with video programming services.
Furthermore, the cable industry claims, accounting safeguards can only go so far.
According to Leland Johnson, a consultant for NCTA, "the separate affiliate
requirement would help ensure that 'hidden' transactions do not occur between the
parent and the affiliate." <P>

And NCTA has also told the FCC that "structural separation is important in OVS
because certain telephone companies have previously announced plans to invest
billions of dollars in integrated plant," making "the separate subsidiary tool
absolutely essential to aid in the detection of cost and resource
misallocations." <P>

John Seiver, an attorney with the Washington, D.C., firm of Cole, Raywid &amp;
Braverman, which represents Georgia and Tennessee cable operators in their
complaint against BellSouth, said the cable industry needs to be aware that cost
allocation issues extend to any case where there is the possibility of joint
facilities being used, including wireless cable facilities.<P>

Seiver contends that the legal delays in implementing the interconnection order
could further tilt the advantage in favor of the RBOCs. "The playing field is
clearly skewed because it's easier for telcos to get into video than it is for
cable to get into telephony," he said. Seiver added that the impact local
franchisers could potentially have on competition between telcos and cable
operators should not be underestimated. <P>

This has to do with how municipalities award telecommunications franchises.
Seiver points to the conflict in Kansas between Classic Telephone, an MSO, and
the Kansas towns of Hill City and Bogue. Classic, which Seiver represents,
applied for a telecommunications franchise to be the second telephony provider,
but was denied because the towns preferred to have only one service provider. The
FCC has ordered both towns to grant a franchise to Classic (see this issue, page
7). According to Seiver, the damage has already been done. "The longer a local
government delays granting a franchise, the more opportunity the local monopoly
telephone company has to take subscribers and siphon off revenue before the cable
operator can enter the market," he said, adding that local governments "will do
whatever they want to on this issue." <P>

CATA's Effros would eliminate all local power to regulate telecommunications and
give it to the states, which regulate the RBOCs. "The states are supposed to
regulate telephony and the 1996 act said cities couldn't do it," Effros said. "If
cable has to negotiate with 14,000 cities to get into telecommunications
services, it is at a severe disadvantage to DBS and telcos," he said, adding that
"we won't see facilities-based competition if cities are allowed to regulate
cable telephony." <P>

Another issue of concern for cable operators and local governments alike is the
accusation by Georgia and Tennessee cable operators that BellSouth is
"cherry-picking" franchises by first laying co-axial cable in only the most
affluent areas without getting a cable franchise. RBOCs could potentially create
de facto cable systems in affluent areas by laying co-axial cable first, and then
telling local governments it will only serve the areas where it has laid cable.
<P>

<h3><i>Joint marketing restrictions?</i></h3><P>

Another issue related to cross-subsidization will be the possible restrictions on
how the RBOCs can market voice and video services.<P>

The 1996 act is silent on the issue of the joint marketing of telephone and video
programming services. The RBOCs do not want the FCC to impose any marketing
restrictions. Nor do they want regulators to determine the manner and degree in
which video service is bundled with other services. <P>

NCTA has advocated to the FCC that RBOCs should be prevented from referring
customers to their video divisions unless they provide the same service to
competing cable operators. "When a new resident enters a new community, one of
the first things to do is call the phone company to get phone service," said
David Nicoll. "Phone companies will get an unfair advantage if they can also
offer video service when it has a monopoly over an essential service like
telephony." <P>

Nicoll said joint marketing restrictions should be lifted only when there is
competition in a local telephone market from another telephony provider. Effros
agreed, adding that restrictions have to exist since "abuse could be so easy."
<P>

Effros also believes that restrictions on the bundling of services is the only
fair way to realize effective competition. "RBOCs should have to wait until
everyone can bundle video and voice, in which all competitors are not foreclosed
from entering telephony," he said, adding that "effective competition should go
both ways -- telcos should not be allowed into cable until cable can get into
their business." <P>

<h3><i>Pole and conduit attachments</i></h3><P>

The 1996 act requires incumbent telephone companies offering video services to
impute the rates for pole attachments and conduit facilities to their costs of
providing video service. This means that phone rates should be reduced, according
to the NCTA, because RBOCs can only charge for use of a pole based on their own
use of it for telephone service -- not what it costs them to offer both video and
telephone service on the pole. <P>

A major concern for cable is to ensure access to all poles and conduits. NCTA's
Nicoll said since "cable companies don't have the same access to poles that
utilities do, we're concerned that pole attachments are always available on just,
reasonable and nondiscriminatory terms." <P>

As part of the complaint he filed for the Tennessee and Georgia cable operators,
Seiver claims BellSouth is opening trenches to lay co-axial cable without
notifying local cable. Notification is important, Seiver said, because when a
telco gives access to its easements, it is supposed to be open to everybody. In
addition, Seiver said BellSouth was charging $6 when the true cost should be 30
cents. <P>

CATA's Effros said the key issue is for the cable industry to simply enforce FCC
rules prohibiting telcos from discriminating against cable operators. "The RBOCs
are not allowed to discriminate, but they're doing it," he said, citing an
ongoing case in which Ohio cable operators have charged Ameritech with violating
pole attachment regulations.<P>

<i>Next Month: What are the video strategies of the major independent
telcos?</i><P>

<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/info/tube/tube.html"><img
src="/tpg/info/tube/smalltube.gif" alt="Return to The Multichannel Video
 Compliance Handbook Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/infoprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr>
