<html><head> <title>
Warning Letters Take Back Seat to NOVs on DDMAC's Enforcement
Agenda</title></head>
<body>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/sell/sellhead.gif"  alt="FDA Advertising and Promotion
Manual">
<P>

<h2> 
Warning Letters Take Back Seat to NOVs on DDMAC's Enforcement Agenda</h2>
<P>

Warning Letters no longer represent the FDA's primary enforcement tool for
advertising and promotion violations by pharmaceutical manufacturers, according
to Minnie Baylor-Henry, acting director of the Division of Drug Marketing,
Advertising and Communications (DDMAC) within the Center for Drug Evaluation and
Research (CDER).<P>

"Companies need guidance, not more Warning Letters," she said, signaling a shift
in DDMAC's enforcement methods and a philosophical departure from other CDER and
FDA divisions (see &#182;912).<P>

Although the division will continue to issue Warning Letters when appropriate,
DDMAC is re-examining how it communicates policy initiatives to the drug
industry, Baylor-Henry told attendees at a Feb. 26 conference. Her office
intends to follow the full notice-and-comment rulemaking procedures of the
Administrative Procedures Act and is "not going to let Warning Letters be the
first statement of policy" on an advertising and promotion issue, she
promised.<P>

The agency issued no Warning Letters for drug promotion violations in calendar
year 1995, reflecting a steady downward trend in the number issued since 1992
(see &#182;930). Similarly, the Center for Devices and Radiological Health has
issued fewer Warning Letters each year since 1993, though the yearly totals
remain significantly higher than those issued for drugs (see &#182;950). The
Center for Biologics Research and Evaluation also has issued fewer Warning
Letters for violations of its advertising policies (see &#182;940).<P>

<h3>Preventive Advice<P></h3>

Speaking at a Drug Information Association meeting in New York, Baylor-Henry
characterized 1996 as a "period of reflection at DDMAC." Her division is in the
process of re-evaluating all of the guidelines it issued since 1970 and has
found that many of them are outdated. DDMAC also plans to improve communications
with drug companies by emphasizing cooperation over enforcement, Baylor-Henry
said.<P>

In that spirit, DDMAC sent out 767 advisory letters in response to
manufacturers' requests for comments on launch campaigns, press releases,
continuing medical education programs and other marketing materials during
fiscal year 1995, she told attendees. This represents a 14 percent increase in
such letters over fiscal year 1994, Baylor-Henry reported. Baylor-Henry
emphasized that the submission of launch materials for preclearance is not
mandatory, but noted that DDMAC is willing to review a launch campaign as a
proactive approach to compliance with FDA regulations (see &#182;412).<P>

Despite efforts to work with drug manufacturers to ensure compliance, DDMAC sent
out 163 Notices of Violation (NOVs) in fiscal year 1995, Baylor-Henry said. NOVs
generally are issued for violations viewed as not serious enough to warrant a
Warning Letter, but serious enough to warrant an official record. They include a
description of the alleged violation, a statement of the actions DDMAC regards
as appropriate remedies, and a time period for the company to respond with its
intentions to correct the alleged violation. Unlike Warning Letters, which are
signed by the district director, NOVs are signed by the individual reviewer and
are not made public (see &#182;911).<P>

Baylor-Henry noted that recent NOVs have mandated corrective actions within a
specific time period -- a tactic previously reserved for Warning Letters.<P>

<h3>Violation Patterns<P></h3>

Although the noncompliant promotional materials cited in 1995 reflected a
wide-range of regulatory and policy offenses, some patterns of violations
emerged, Baylor-Henry said (see "Recent Promotion Violations Generating NOVs,"
p. 4). Remedies for non-compliant promotional materials ranged from requiring
companies to disclose the source of supporting data where appropriate to
mandating corrective advertisements, Baylor-Henry told conference attendees.<P>

DDMAC's philosophy of "working with the industry" does not mean that there are
fewer advertising and promotion violations by drug companies, Baylor-Henry
noted, reiterating that Warning Letters will be issued when necessary.
Nevertheless, DDMAC "will not send out a Warning Letter when an NOV will
suffice," she said.<P>

Speculating on where DDMAC draws the line between advertising violations that
require a Warning Letter and those that warrant an NOV, a food and drug law
attorney told the <i>Monthly Bulletin</i> that the agency's shift away from Warning
Letters likely has little to do with a change in the degree of industry
compliance with its regulations. Rather, the FDA is attempting to keep a low
profile in light of litigation pending against it and congressional reform
efforts, he said.<P>

<hr>
<center><h4>Recent Promotion Violations Generating NOVs<P></h4></center>

<font size=-1>According to Minnie Baylor-Henry, acting director of the FDA's Division of Drug
Marketing, Advertising and Communications, the following missteps in promotional
materials for prescription drugs warranted Notices of Violation (NOVs) sent from
her office to drug sponsors:<P>

<UL><li>Making comparative safety or efficacy claims, or quality-of-life claims based
on nonclinical data (see &#182;421);

<li>Making representations about the product in a reminder piece (see
&#182;416);

<li>Omitting a pregnancy warning;

<li>Failing to cite source information for nonclinical claims;

<li>"Burying" supporting data for claims in a footnote;

<li>Using an incorrect "Orange Book" rating;

<li>Including only selective information from a study;

<li>Distributing home-made pieces;

<li>Listing a dosing recommendation inconsistent with labeling;

<li>Making safety and efficacy claims prior to approval (see &#182;401);

<li>Making inaccurate comparative claims;

<li>Failing to submit the required data on a Form 2253;

<li>Failing to meet the requirements for an accelerated approval product (see
&#182;425);

<li>Claiming superiority over an approved generic;

<li>Failing to have a fair balance of risk and benefit information (see &#182;413);
and

<li>Failing to cite clinical studies to support claims.<P></font></UL>


</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
