<html> <title> FDA Announces Device Enforcement Pilot Program Initiatives</title> <body>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/feds/fedshead.gif" alt="FDA Enforcement Manual">
<P>

<H2 ALIGN=LEFT>FDA Cites Leading Deviations in  Withholding NDA Approvals</H2>

<P>
Deviations related to incapable manufacturing plants, inadequate good manufacturing practices (GMPs) and poor laboratory-related controls continue to prompt "withhold" recommendations during FDA preap-proval inspections, according to data presented by FDA Compliance Officer Rick Friedman at a recent Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society conference in Washington, D.C.  
</P>

<P>
Together, the three leading deficiencies accounted for 54 percent of all the deviations supporting recommendations to withhold approval of new drug applications (NDAs) and abbreviated new drug applications (ANDAs) from March 1995 through March 1996, Friedman said at the July 23 conference.
</P>

<P>
During this period, the agency conducted 395 inspections in connection with 681 pending applications. Of these applications, 118 received withhold recommendations -- which typically mean that an NDA or ANDA is removed from the review list until the firm corrects the deviations and, in most cases, the FDA conducts a second inspection to verify the corrections (see ¦752).
</P>

<P>
Although the proportion of withhold recommendations issued was lower during this 12-month period than in previous years, the FDA data show that many firms continue to struggle with the basic manufacturing requirements associated with product approvals. It is also noteworthy that the types of deviations most frequently cited vary substantially between NDAs and ANDAs -- suggesting that some companies may not approach quality control issues with the same level of scrutiny for both types of submissions.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Leading Deviations</H3>
</P>

<P>
For both NDAs and ANDAs, the FDA found that the single most common deviation was plants deemed incapable of producing the drug (see chart, below).  This deviation comprised 31 percent and 22 percent of the deviations alleged in withhold recommendations for NDAs and ANDAs, respectively.
</P>

<CENTER><P>
<H3>Leading Deviations, FDA Withhold Recommendations<BR>
March 1995-March 1996</H3>
</P>

<IMG SRC="fedssept1.gif" ALT="This chart shows the 13 leading deviations of NDAs and ANDAs">
</CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
Source: Rick Friedman, Compliance Officer, CDER Division of Manufacturing Quality, July 23 Presentation at Regulatory Affairs Professional Society. Total withheld NDAs and ANDAs, March 1995-March 1996: 118 out of 681 reviewed.
</P></FONT>

In a follow-up interview with the <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, Friedman elaborated on the circumstances that most often lead to a "plant not capable" withhold designation.
</P>

<P>
"It's usually very clear-cut," Friedman said. "In some cases, they simply haven't received the manufacturing equipment yet." 
</P>

<P>
Friedman said that when equipment is present and properly installed in plants, inspectors then will examine qualification studies conducted on the equipment, in accordance with standard operating procedures (SOPs). "They need to demonstrate that the equipment is going to operate according to specifications," he said.
</P>

<P>
A closely related deviation, inadequate process development, comprised approximately 8 percent of NDA and ANDA deficiencies, which the FDA says is particularly common in six-month priority application inspections.
</P>

<P>
"This refers to batch records that are not specific or complete, particularly with respect to operating ranges," Friedman said. Other examples of common process development deviations mentioned by Friedman include lack of operating ranges and processes that are not supported by development data.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>"Numerous GMPs," Laboratory Controls</H3>
</P>

<P>
Similarly, Friedman said that withhold recommendations citing "numerous GMP" deviations typically reflect obvious and pervasive GMP-related deficiencies.  Although this broad category of deviations comprised only 11 percent of all deviations alleged for NDAs, it occurred in 20 percent of those for ANDAs, possibly suggesting less rigorous quality control among firms submitting ANDAs.
</P>

<P>
"This means there are fundamental problems that may or may not be product-specific," Friedman said.
</P>

<P>
Although laboratory controls is itself a GMP requirement, it was independently cited in 14 percent of NDA and 12 percent of ANDA withhold recommendations. 
</P>

<P>
"We often find that [companies] have not calibrated their equipment, or when an out-of-specification result is obtained their retest SOP is too arbitrary or is not being followed," Friedman said, as examples of common laboratory-related violations. Friedman added that FDA inspectors also look to see that the retesting schedule is created by the appropriate company personnel and in accordance with SOPs.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Validation Failures</H3>
</P>

<P>
Validation problems comprised only 9 percent of the NDA and ANDA deviations cited. However, when such studies are required, validation data must be carefully reviewed and understood.
</P>

<P>
"Validation is generally not required before receiving approval unless it's a sterile application, which means that you would need certain qualification studies," Friedman said, adding that inadequate sterility is a "big issue" in some plants with aseptic processes.  
</P>

<P>
However, regardless of whether or not a firm is required to conduct validation studies prior to approval, all firms that do so should pay attention to their validation findings.
</P>

<P>
"It's a problem if a firm has conducted validation studies, but they show a lack of reproducability," Friedman said.  Friedman added that industry continues to have problems with scale-up batches for commercial production, a problem that sometimes prompts companies to conduct a full-scale test batch during or prior to validation test batches.
</P>

<P>
"I see a lot of companies doing a full scale batch before they do the three validation batches" he said, explaining that many 
</P>

<P>
companies are able to obtain FDA permission to subsequently market their full scale test batches, if the FDA does not find problems in the subsequent validation batches and identical processes were used.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>ANDA Fraud </H3>
</P>

<P>
Another noteworthy figure among the ANDA deviations is evidence of fraud in 7 percent of deviations alleged, which compares to only a 1 percent frequency among deviations for NDAs.
</P>

<P>
Although Friedman declined to comment on the nature of any fraud the FDA believes it has found, he indicated that typically such violations involve findings of discrepant data.
</P>

<P>
"We are always concerned when there are discrepancies between the drug application and the raw data found at the firm," he said. "Discrepancies always increase our scrutiny of other raw data that is reviewed at the firm."
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Outlook</H3>
</P>

<P>
Although an overall drop in the proportion of withhold recommendations is an encouraging sign for industry, withheld approvals continue to result from nearly one in five preapproval inspections. As in the past, FDA officials continue to cite poor record-keeping as an underlying cause of many of the specific GMP violations that are alleged (see "Poor Record-keeping at Heart of Drug GMP Violations ...," July 1996, p. 3).
</P>

<P>
The recently proposed drug GMP rule also affect the preapproval inspection process, if the rule is finalized in its present form (see "FDA Proposes Tighter Drug GMP Controls," July 1996, p. 1). This new regulation, along with separate, recently issued guidance documents on scale-up and post-approval changes, will create more specific requirements for manufacturing process and equipment controls -- meaning that firms will have less flexibility in establishing and following GMP procedures.
</P>

<hr>
<center>
