<HTML> 
<HEAD> 
<TITLE> Passage of telecom bill this year remains uncertain
</TITLE> 
</HEAD> 
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/info/tube/tubehead.gif" alt=" Multichannel Video
 Compliance Guide"></center><P>

<h2>Localities, homeowners' associations lose ability to restrict antenna
use<P></h2>

Rules aimed at giving alternative programming providers an equal shot at the
video marketplace, while at the same time curbing local restraints on the use of
antennas, were released last month by the Federal Communications Commission.<P>

Issued under a mandate in the 1996 Telecommunications Act, the FCC rules
invalidate measures that "impair" a viewer's ability to receive signals from
multichannel video programming providers that use antennas, including direct
broadcast satellite (if the satellite dish is less than 1 meter in diameter;
larger in Alaska), multichannel multipoint distribution service (except where the
"mast" of the antenna is higher than 12 feet), local multipoint distribution
service and broadcast television. The rules cover installation, maintenance or
use of antennas to receive video programming.<P>

Many local governments, homeowners' associations, condominium boards and other
bodies have enacted laws, zoning ordinances, covenants, etc., that prohibit or
greatly restrict the use of antennas. Some forbid them outright, while others
place conditions (such as requiring fees or permits, elaborate landscaping or
narrow location specifications) that effectively render the satellite unusable.
Congress, in passing the 1996 act, viewed such measures as debilitating to
competition, because they put DBS, MMDS and other satellite providers at a
disadvantage to providers (such as cable operators) that don't rely on satellites
for subscribers to receive programming.<P>

The rules apply to property an antenna user owns (either directly or indirectly)
and has exclusive use of or control over. In a future rulemak-ing the commission
will decide if the prohibition should apply to the installation of antennas on
property owned by a landlord or on common property controlled by a condominium or
homeowners' association.<P>

According to the commission, a restriction "impairs" if it:<P>
<UL>
<LI>unreasonably delays or prevents use of;<P>
<LI>unreasonably increases the cost of; or<P>
<LI>precludes a subscriber from receiving an acceptable quality signal from one
of the antennas. Safety restrictions or restrictions designed to preserve
historic districts may still be enacted and enforced. </UL><P>

Once effective (a date has not been set), the rules will apply to all existing
local laws, covenants, zoning ordinances and similar rules that restrict antenna
use. No "grandfathering" provision was included.<P>

<h3><i>Modified stance</i></h3><P>

The final rules represent a modification of the initial position the FCC took on
local zoning restrictions, when it planned to widely pre-empt local authority
over antenna use. Instead, in the final version, the commission acknowledged that
local governments and other bodies should be able to enforce restrictions that
affect safety and historic preservation concerns.<P>

<h3><i>Do's and don'ts</i></h3><P>

The FCC maintained that the rules balance local concerns with its mandate to
eliminate restrictions that are perceived as unnecessary barriers to competition.
In short, restrictions that are roundly applied (i.e., don't unfairly single-out
antennas), affect but do not impair antenna use, or satisfy justifiable safety or
historic preservation issues are acceptable. To illustrate, the commission gave
examples of what would and would not be allowed under the new regulations. For
example, a city can:<P>
<UL>
<LI>require that antennas be painted to blend in with its background (but not
interfere with reception);<P>
<LI>require that antennas be placed so that they're not visible from the street
(as long as reception is not impaired); or<P>
<LI>assess fees to screen antennas (as long as costs are imposed to screen air
conditioners, trash cans or other similar devices in the neighborhood).</UL><P>

On the other hand, the city would violate the FCC rules if it were to:<P>
<UL>
<LI>create extra "hurdles" for consumers to overcome before using an antenna
(e.g., requiring permits or prior community approval before an antenna is
installed or charging a special fee for using an antenna) if those requirements
apply to one programming signal provider but not another;<P>
<LI>require that relatively unobtrusive DBS antennas be screened by expensive
landscaping (one example cited was a requirement that MMDS antennas be made to
look like a tree with leaves); or<P>
<LI>mandate that antennas be placed in positions that would significantly degrade
or prevent signal reception.</UL><P>

<h3><i>Safety, historic preservation</i></h3><P>

As noted, the rules make exceptions for local restrictions that relate to safety
or historic preservation concerns. For example, the commission said local rules
that prohibit antennas from being installed on fire escapes, dictate how far from
power lines antennas can be located or require proper grounding of antennas are
acceptable, even if they impair signal reception. However, a local body must
state in the text of the rule, its preamble or legislative history that the
restriction is safety-related. (A separate document explaining the safety reasons
would suffice, so that local bodies need not amend existing codes to satisfy the
FCC rule.)<P>

Safety restrictions can be no more burdensome on antenna users than necessary to
achieve the safety goal.<P>

Also, historic preservation concerns may be taken into account when setting
antenna-use restrictions. Areas listed or eligible to be listed in the National
Register of Historic Places are exempt from the FCC rules and may restrict
antenna use. However, such restrictions must be applied uniformly (that is, an
historic area could not restrict antennas while at the same time allow other
modern devices that could arguably have the same detrimental effect on the
historic nature of the area).<P>

<h3><i>Waivers</i></h3><P>

Under the rules, disputes between a governing body and a resident over the
restricted use of an antenna can be resolved by the FCC or a court deciding
whether the restriction is valid (e.g., is safety-related or affects historic
preservation). Additionally, the local body can petition the FCC to waive the
regulation if it has "highly specialized or unusual" concerns about antenna
installation, maintenance or use. The local government or association that is
seeking to restrict antenna use -- and not the consumer -- has the burden of
proving that the restriction is valid. <P>


<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/info/tube/tube.html"><img
src="/tpg/info/tube/smalltube.gif" alt="Return to Multichannel Video Compliance
 Guide Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/infoprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr>
