<html>
<head>
<title>Investigational IVD CPG Surfaces, Encourages Certification to End Commercialization</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device Regulation"></center>
<P>
<h2>Investigational IVD CPG Surfaces, Encourages Certification to End Commercialization</h2>

<P>
After years of discussion about how to regulate research use only (RUO) and investigational use only (IUO) <I>in vitro</I> diagnostic (IVD) devices that are being promoted and distributed commercially for purposes other than research and investigation, the FDA has released a new draft compliance policy guide (CPG). It "encourages" -- but does not require -- manufacturers to establish certification programs to ensure the proper use of these products throughout the distribution chain (see "What Is a Commercialized IVD?," below). 
</P>

<P>
A previous draft version of the CPG released in 1993 had required certification programs to "establish an audit trail of the use of the product from manufacturer or importer to the end user." This provision was hotly contested by IVD manufacturers, who argued they had no control over research carried out by pathologists or other researchers using the manufacturer's IVDs. Such protests may have led the agency to suggest that a certification program is just "one way to demonstrate compliance" with the regulations. 
</P>

<P>
However, although the agency does not require certification programs, it clearly is the FDA's expectation that IVD manufacturers should collect and maintain "documentary evidence" that will "establish limited distribution and use," according to language used in the new CPG (CPG 7124.32). 
</P>

<P>
The agency is instituting this policy because the commercialization of investigational IVDs "has resulted in the widespread use of laboratory tests with unproven performance characteristics," the CPG states. "Use of such tests may mislead providers of medical diagnosis and treatment and cause serious adverse health consequences to unknowing patients." 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>30-month Window</H3>
</P>

<P>
The FDA recognizes that immediate regulatory action against many commercialized IVDs could result in adverse public health consequences because such tests have become the standard of care and have been in clinical use for many years. Accordingly, the agency is providing manufacturers of certain commercialized devices with 30 months to collect data, submit a premarket approval (PMA) application, a premarket notification (510(k)) submission or a product license application (PLA), and get approval or clearance for their products. 
</P>

<P>
The FDA believes that the 30-month time frame "is a reasonable period for gathering safety and effectiveness data and obtaining agency review for clearance or approval." During this time period, unapproved IVDs must be labeled as research or investigational use devices and must not carry any labeling claims indicating that safety and effectiveness or any performance characteristics have been established for any indicated use. Manufacturers have a grace period of three months from the issue date of the CPG to comply with these labeling requirements. 
</P>

<P>
It also should be noted that IVDs entering the market after the issue date of the CPG will not be granted the 30-month period to come into compliance with the regulations. These devices are expected to have agency clearance or approval prior to being commercialized. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>High-risk IVDs Targeted</H3>
</P>

<P>
The agency also states in the CPG that it will take immediate regulatory action during the 30-month grace period to remove violative, high-risk products from the marketplace. The CPG defines such "enforcement priority category I" devices as IVDs that:
</P>

<OL>
	<LI>Meet all of the following criteria:
<UL>
	<LI>	The IVD is being used as a stand-alone test for diagnostic, monitoring or screening procedures;
	
	<LI>	The test result may lead to a significant medical decision or intervention (e.g., organ removal, surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, drug treatment with potentially severe toxicity or quarantine); and
	
	<LI>	The FDA determines there is inadequate scientific proof of the IVD's safety and effectiveness; or
</UL>
	
<P>
	<LI>Are used for diagnosis or prognosis in humans for which there are no data on human use or only anecdotal data to support safety and effectiveness; or 
</P>	

<P>
	<LI>Whose manufacturer fails to comply with labeling requirements, fails to begin a clinical or scientifically valid study to collect data on the device's safety and efficacy, or fails to obtain a PMA or PLA approval or 510(k) clearance within 30 months of the CPG's issue date.
</P>

</OL>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Certification Programs</H3>
</P>

<P>
As noted above, the FDA is encouraging IVD manufacturers to establish certification programs to "assure that the distribution and use of their IVDs will be controlled and limited to use in scientifically sound research or investigations." Although a certification program is not required, companies should be aware that the FDA will be less likely to take an enforcement action, including seizure, injunction, criminal prosecution and imposition of civil  penalties, if the manufacturer has a formal program or system that yields documentation demonstrating the firm's control of its investigational or research devices. The CPG suggests that all parties in the distribution chain should certify that the product will be used only for the purposes of gathering data to support submissions to the FDA and will not be used for diagnostic purposes without confirmation by another medically established diagnostic device or procedure. 
</P>

<P>
For IUO devices, the FDA states that an effective certification program might include:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>Written and signed manufacturer, importer or distributor certifications that the product is being distributed properly, and written and signed certifications from individuals, laboratories or health care institutions that they will comply with the investigational use of the device;
</P>
	
<P>
	<LI>Procedures for ensuring that all written, printed or graphic matter used to describe the device complies with labeling requirements; and
</P>	

<P>
	<LI>Procedures for maintaining records of written certifications to establish an audit trail. 
</P>
</UL>

<P>
RUO device certification programs might include, at a minimum:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>Certification that the IVD is used for laboratory research and not used for a diagnostic or therapeutic purpose; and
</P>

<P>
	<LI>Certification that the research is not intended for determining the safety and effectiveness of the IVD. 
</P>
</UL>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>CPG Status</H3>
</P>

<P>
Because the CPG still is in draft form, according to agency sources, it is not yet being implemented in the field. The FDA will publish a notice of availability of the final CPG in "the near future," an agency source told the <I>Bulletin</I>. It is likely the CPG will not be finalized until the FDA's recently proposed rules seeking to classify or reclassify immunohistochemical reagents and kits and analyte-specific reagents become final (see "'Home Brew' Test Reagents to Be Restricted," May 1996, p. 10).
</P>

<HR>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT>What Is a Commercialized IVD?</H4> 

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
The FDA's regulations detail specific requirements for <I>in vitro</I> diagnostic (IVD) devices, but allow an exemption from investigational device exemption requirements under 21 CFR &#167;812.2(c)(3), provided the following conditions are met (see &#182;383; App. II):
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>The devices are in the laboratory stage of development, and labeling does not represent the device as effective and prominently states "For research use only. Not for diagnostic procedures."; or 
</P>
<P>
	<LI>The devices are being shipped and delivered for testing to compare their usefulness to that of recognized products prior to full commercial marketing, and their labeling states: "For investigational use only. The performance characteristics of this product have not been established" (21 CFR &#167;809.10 (c) (2); see App. II).
</P>
</UL>

<P>
According to the new draft FDA compliance policy guide (CPG) (section 300.800), a "research use only" IVD is considered to be commercialized if the device is being used for investigational purposes (such as a clinical study with as few as one patient) where the test results will be reported to the patient's physician or medical records or will be used to assess the patient's condition (even if confirmatory tests or procedures are used).
</P>

<P>
An "investigational use only" IVD is considered to be commercialized, the CPG states, if it is:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>Labeled or promoted with statements indicating the devices are safe or effective prior to agency approval or clearance; or
</P>

<P>
	<LI>Distributed to any party not involved with the conduct of a clinical trial to determine safety and effectiveness. 
</P>
</UL>
</FONT>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/xray/xray.html"><img src="/tpg/food/xray/smallxray.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to Medical Device Regulation Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
