<html>
<head>
<title> Congressional Scrutiny, Proactive Credo Drive FDA Enforcement Efforts</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/sell/sellhead.gif"  alt="FDA Advertising and Promotion
Manual">
<P>

<h2> Congressional Scrutiny, Proactive Credo Drive FDA Enforcement Efforts </h2>
<p>

Companies seeking insight into the FDA's compliance concerns with respect to

promotion have been hampered by the lack of publicly available enforcement

documents. Experts disagree on why the agency has shifted away from issuing

Warning Letters as a policy-making tool.<p>

Speaking at the Drug Information Association's annual meeting June 12 in San

Diego, one food and drug law consultant noted that FDA's Center for Drug

Evaluation and Research (CDER) has issued few Warning Letters for advertising

and promotion violations in recent years (see &#182;935).<p> 

In fact, CDER's Division of Drug Marketing, Advertising and Communications

(DDMAC) issued no Warning Letters for such violations in calendar year 1995,

reflecting a steady downward trend in the number issued since 1992 (see &#182;930;

"Warning Letters Take Back Seat to NOVs...," May 1996, p. 1).<p>

<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>FDA Philosophy</H3>

The consultant attributed the dearth of enforcement documents to two factors.

First, although the FDA disclaimed that it requires preclearance of

direct-to-consumer (DTC) advertising in a recent <i>Federal Register</i> notice, most

companies still submit their DTC promotional materials to the agency for review

prior to dissemination (see &#182;430; "FDA Disclaims Preclearance of DTC Ads," July

1996, p. 1). This voluntary preclearance process weeds out violative DTC ads,

thereby reducing the need for later enforcement action in the form of Warning

Letters, the consultant said.<p> 

Second, DDMAC appears to have adopted the new, overall philosophy that it is

better to play a proactive role in enforcing its advertising policies than to

play a reactive one, he said.<p>

While there is nothing inherently wrong with this philosophy, one major drawback

of its practical implementation is that "the thought processes that lead up to

the policy are not public and therefore nobody else can understand or benefit

from" the agency's mechanisms for these decisions, the consultant commented.<p>

This leads to "a reinvention of wheels on a continuous basis," he said, adding

that as a result, there is no way to compare what "you are doing as a company to

what other companies have gone through" with their ad campaigns.<p> 

<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Laying Low</H3>

 The FDA may be maintaining a low enforcement profile due to the highly charged

reform atmosphere on Capitol Hill, contended David Adams, a partner in the

Washington, D.C.-based firm Olsson, Frank and Weeda. The agency's policies on

advertising and promotion, particularly the dissemination of information on

off-label uses, is a significant part of what is fueling congressional reform

efforts, Adams noted. Thus, it is "quite probable that the agency has not wanted

to appear to be overly aggressive on enforcement during the pendency of reform

legislation," he added.<p>

Alan Slobodin, counsel to the House Commerce Committee's Subcommittee on

Oversight and Investigations, agreed. Although both the Senate and House FDA

reform proposals are "quite modest, they have engendered a great deal of

controversy," he told DIA attendees.<p>

According to Slobodin, FDA has been reacting to what is going on the Hill and in

the courts, and the House Oversight and Investigations subcommittee is taking

note. For example, he said, FDA "is now articulating its statutory mission in a

more detailed, nuanced way than it has been before."<p>  

The agency's "former mantra was 'protect the public health' which led to a very

aggressive stance on dissemination of off-label information," he noted. Now, the

FDA has adopted more of a "dual mission": protecting the public health balanced

with getting products to market, he explained.<p>

Slobodin also observed that the FDA has said it has a mission to advance

scientific research, and that Commissioner of Food and Drugs David Kessler has

stated that the agency must be committed to "fairness, objectivity and

even-handedness." However, as commendable as these multiple missions and goals

may sound individually, as applied to policies on promotion, they may conflict

with each other, Slobodin cautioned.<p>

<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Monitoring NOVs</H3>

Congressional scrutiny likely has driven FDA "underground" on enforcement, as

evidenced by the decreased use of Warning Letters and the increased use of

Notices of Violation (NOVs) (see &#182;911). Slobodin revealed that Rep. Joe Barton

(R-Texas), chairman of the subcommittee, requested 163 NOVs issued by DDMAC in

fiscal year 1995 for committee review. The purpose of the review is to determine

whether the 163 NOVs were in keeping with the handful of violation "patterns" 

identified by DDMAC Director Minnie Baylor-Henry last year, Slobodin said (see

"Recent Promotion Violations Generating NOVs," May 1996, p. 3).<p>

"We are keeping our options open as far as what we will do when we've looked at

them, Slobodin said. Congress may want to provide a summary of all of them and

then make them available to the public."<p> 

The consultant supported that proposal, noting that "the easiest solution [to

the lack of compliance guidance through Warning Letters] is to make NOVs

available so that [industry] can see what the violations are... and try to figure

out what the broad policy implications are" based on DDMAC's actions against

individual companies.<p>

<hr>

<h4><center>CBER Follows CDER Lead, Disclaims Preclearance<p></center></h4>

<font size=-1>The FDA's Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research's (CBER's) Advertising

and Promotional Labeling Staff (APLS) no longer will require companies to

preclear their advertising and promotion materials, APLS Senior Regulatory

Review Officer Toni Stifano said at the Drug Information Association's annual

meeting June 12 in San Diego.<p> 

The announcement comes on the heels of the agency's recent <i>Federal Register</i>

notice clarifying the absence of a preclearance requirement for

direct-to-consumer (DTC) promotional materials (61 FR 24314) (see "FDA Disclaims

Preclearance of DTC Ads" July 1996, p. 1). CBER's absolute requirement of

preclearance for all promotional materials long has been one of the key elements

distinguishing its policies from those of the Center for Drug Evaluation and

Research (CDER) (see &#182;511).<p> 

While CDER merely requested voluntary submission of DTC and launch materials --

and precleared nothing else except by special request of the company -- CBER's

APLS historically has mandated submission of all "promotional labeling" for all

biologics for which licenses are pending, for licensed products for which there

is a significant amendment, or for newly approved products.<p>

The difference between CDER's and CBER's approaches to preclearance stems from

the separate laws governing the regulated products. Drugs are regulated under

the Federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act (FD&amp;C Act), which precludes preclearance

of advertising except in "extraordinary circumstances" (FD&amp;C Act &#167;502(n); see

&#182;412; App. I). Biologics are regulated under the FD&amp;C Act and the Public Health

Service Act, which contains no such prohibition.<p>

Stifano noted that as part of the Clinton administration's "reinventing

government" initiative, CBER recently issued a proposal to drop the policy

requiring preclearance for ads accompanying a supplemental license application

for an approved biologic (61 FR 2739) (see "CBER to Harmonize Ad Rules with

CDER," May 1996, p. 4). However, implementation of CBER's commitment to end

preclearance is stalled by concerns that the Center is violating existing

regulations that remain in place until the proposal is finalized.<p> 

To clarify the situation, CBER plans to issue a <I>Federal Register</I> notice "in the

very near future that explains that we are in fact going to implement this full

tilt prior to the final rule being published," Stifano said. In the meantime,

the Center is "changing some of the verbiage that is going out with the

approvable or approval letters to state that 'you may wish to submit your

introductory campaigns for our preclearance, for our review,'" she added.<p> 

Stifano made clear that she supports voluntary submission of launch materials.

Voluntary preclearance allows CBER to be proactive, she explained. Such

submissions give industry "an opportunity to get a reading from us early on what

we find to be acceptable versus not acceptable and it will help industry in the

long run, preventing Warning Letters or [notices of violation]."<p>

"Voluntary submission is a value-added service," Stifano said, declining to make

a recommendation to companies undecided about whether to send in their

promotional materials following the policy change. Stifano said that CBER will

continue to work very closely with CDER to harmonize policies in this area.</font><p>



<hr>
