<html>
<head> 
<title>Device Group Calls for Pilot Committee To Advise DDMAC on Guidance Practices</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/sell/sellhead.gif"  alt="FDA Advertising and Promotion
Manual">
<P>

<h2> Device Group Calls for Pilot Committee To Advise DDMAC on Guidance Practices</h2>


The Indiana Medical Device Manufacturers Council Inc. (IMDMC) is urging the FDA

to adopt negotiated guidance development procedures "to encourage greater public

participation in the development of the first draft of guidance documents." <p>

The IMDMC recommends the FDA establish a diverse committee to advise the Center

for Drug Evaluation and Research's Division of Drug Marketing, Advertising and

Communication (DDMAC) on how to develop guidance for industry on promotion

issues.<p>

However, the FDA's Center for Devices and Radiological Health (CDRH) issued an

internal memorandum establishing interim "good guidance practices" (GGPs) for

use while the agency considers the issue. Those interim GGPs may not require

involvement of the public at any level for certain types of guidances, the CDRH

memo states.<p>

<h3>Public Participation<p></h3>

The IMDMC's proposal comes in response to the agency's March 7 <i>Federal Register</i>

notice requesting input on its treatment and use of guidance documents and on

how to both improve and involve the public in the guidance process (61 FR 9181)

(see "FDA and Industry Must Partner to Develop Better Guidances, Expert Says,"

July 1996, p. 1). <p>

The issue of GGPs was raised by the IMDMC in a May 1995 citizen petition filed

with the FDA, and was followed by a public meeting on the subject in April. The

IMDMC also is part of the recently formed <I>ad hoc</I> Guidance Document Task Force --

composed of 13 medical products trade groups -- which submitted separate comments

to the agency.  <p>

In its comments, the IMDMC calls on the agency to more fully involve the public

in the guidance development process by creating interdisciplinary committees

that include all of the constituencies affected by the proposed policy. The

IMDMC suggests that the agency initiate a pilot program of negotiated guidance

development through an advisory committee to assist DDMAC. <p>

DDMAC is an appropriate choice for a pilot program for the following three

reasons, according to the device group's comments:<p>

(1) It is one of the major divisions within the FDA that operates without input

from any advisory committee;<p>

(2) There is a "desperate need for guidance [from DDMAC] on a wide variety of

marketing practices"; and<p>

(3) Marketing issues are well-suited for interdisciplinary review because they

involve legal, scientific and business concerns.<p>

<h3>Simpler Process<p></h3>

In its comments, the IMDMC urges the agency to focus on defining clearly the

types of communications that will be subject to GGPs, rather than on the

"nomenclature" of the documents themselves. The FDA should "focus on the

substance of a communication, rather than its form," the group states,

suggesting that the agency define guidance documents as any "communications that

in effect announce a regulatory expectation to a broad audience." <p>

The IMDMC proposes that once the initial draft of the guidance document is

complete, it should be subjected to "broad public comment" through a two-tier

process that is simpler and more efficient than the three-tier process described

in the FDA's <i>Federal Register</i> notice. <p>

The two-tier system would be based on the varying need for expediency in issuing

the guidance, the group's comments note, with the first tier including those

documents for which the FDA has the opportunity to solicit comments in advance

of publication.<p>

The second tier would include those guidances "which because of the public

interest cannot wait for advance public comment" before issuance. The IMDMC's

plan would eliminate a third tier envisioned by the FDA as consisting of

documents that include a single notice stating that public comments are welcome.

<p>

The group recommends the agency use the <i>Federal Register</i> as the vehicle to

communicate the progress of the guidance development process and that the agency

also publish the final document there. Once the final document is in use, the

IMDMC calls on the FDA to adopt auditing and monitoring procedures to confirm

that staffers are following GGPs, particularly to ensure that FDA employees are

not using guidance documents as binding rules.<p>

<h3>Task Force Comments<p></h3>

The Guidance Document Task Force comments elaborate on the IMDMC's admonishment

that the FDA avoid using guidance documents as binding policy by specifically

cautioning the agency to cease using "unofficial vehicles such as [W]arning

[L]etters, speeches and press releases" to communicate guidance so as not to

undermine GGPs. <p>

The task force states it is especially concerned that "when FDA adopts GGPs that

impose responsibilities on the agency, the agency staff will have added

incentive" to fall back on the easier, unofficial communications. The agency

should train staffers in GGPs to reduce this risk, the task force says.<p>

Like the IMDMC, the task force suggests much greater public input in the

guidance development process, predicting that this "would go a long way toward

improving the content of guidance[s]" it complains are unclear and outdated.

Public input also would help the agency better prioritize those areas for which

guidance is necessary, the task force adds.<p>

<h3>CDRH's Lead<p></h3>

CDRH issued an internal memorandum June 6 entitled "Standard Operating

Procedures for the Development and Use of CDRH Guidance Documents" which was

circulated to the Office of Device Evaluation Review staff. The memo establishes

interim GGPs for use "while the [a]gency formulates its strategy for dealing

with this important issue." <p>

 However, unlike the IMDMC and task force proposals -- which would mandate public

input at some stage for all documents that "meet the threshold determination for

what constitutes guidance" -- the CDRH procedures require the document authors to

meet with management "to discuss whether comment from outside parties should be

solicited." The CDRH memo explains that public comment is not needed for those

guidance documents that "simply capture current practices." To assist staff in

making this threshold determination the memo includes a decision tree. <p>

The memo also requires CDRH staff to distinguish those draft guidances

distributed for comment and those "released for actual use," suggesting that it

plans to continue implementing informal guidance policies. Moreover, the CDRH

memo recommends staffers use several channels of distribution for documents for

which public comment will be sought, including, but not limited to, publication

in the <i>Federal Register.</i><p>

The memo does note that guidance documents in any form "do not confer legally

enforceable rights or responsibilities on either the FDA or the public" and

should not be treated as such. In addition, the memo reminds CDRH staff that all

guidance documents are subject to public comment even after they become

effective and that the developmental process is "a continuous one." The Center

states that it will conduct training in the FDA's GGPs as they are

implemented.<p>




<hr>
