<html>
<head>
<title>FDA to Clarify Dietary Supplement Structure/Function Notification Process</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/food/foodhead.gif" alt="Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law"></center>
<P>
<h2>FDA to Clarify Dietary Supplement Structure/Function Notification Process</h2>

<P>
Dietary supplement labels bearing "structure/function" claims would need to include a disclaimer that the FDA has not evaluated this statement, according to a proposed rule published Sept. 27 in the <I>Federal Register</I> (61 FR 50771, see App. III). A structure/function claim is a truthful, nonmisleading statement that describes the benefits of a nutrient or dietary ingredient on a "classical" nutrient deficiency disease or describes general well being from consumption of a nutrient or dietary ingredient.
</P>

<P>
The disclaimer would read as follows: "This statement has not been evaluated by the Food and Drug Administration. This product is not intended to diagnose, treat, cure or prevent any disease." 
</P>

<P>
The FDA has proposed the regulation to streamline the procedure that requires dietary supplement companies to notify the FDA within 30 days of marketing a product that bears a structure/function claim on the label.
</P>

<P>
After the notification requirement became effective as Sec. 403(r)(6) of the Dietary Supplement Health and Safety Act (DSHEA), the FDA received timely notification from some manufacturers. However, it also has received inquiries from other companies that "reflect uncertainty about what must be done to notify the agency about a statement of this type for a dietary supplement product." 
</P>

<P>
In addition, the agency has received numerous notifications for statements that are unacceptable because they indicate that the product does intend to cure, treat, mitigate, diagnose or prevent disease. These types of claims are not authorized by DSHEA. Accordingly, the FDA advises companies that if they continue to market the product with these claims, they risk regulatory action by the agency.
</P>

<P>
The proposed rule states that dietary supplement manufacturers, packers or distributors must notify FDA's Office of Special Nutritionals within 30 days after first marketing a dietary supplement that bears a structure/function claim as described in DSHEA. It also would require companies to include in the notification the name of the dietary supplement (including the brand name), the name of the dietary ingredient about which the claim is being made, and the text of the structure/function statement.
</P>

<P>
This information will allow the agency to clearly identify which product the company is referring to, and whether the statement is of the type that can appropriately be made.
</P>

 
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/food/food.html"><img src="/tpg/food/food/smallfood.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
