<html>
<head>
<title>Allergen Labeling Concerns FDA, Consumers</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/food/foodhead.gif" alt="Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law"></center>
<P>
<h2>Allergen Labeling Concerns FDA, Consumers</h2>

<P>
Consumers share the FDA's concerns that some allergens are not being declared on the food label due to misinterpretation of the exemptions for ingredient labeling, according to comments received recently by the agency on proposed revisions to flavor labeling regulations.
</P>

<P>
In a notice to manufacturers dated June 10, 1996, the agency noted that there are two "very narrow exemptions" from ingredient labeling requirements. One, 21 CFR &#167;403(ii), provides that spices, flavorings and colorings may be declared collectively without naming each one; the other, 21 CFR &#167;101.100(a)(3), exempts incidental additives such as processing aids that are present in only insignificant levels and do not have any technical or functional effect in the finished food from ingredient declaration. 
</P>

<P>
Because very small amounts of allergen present in a food can cause an adverse reaction in sensitive people, no level of allergen present in food can be considered insignificant, the FDA said. 
</P>

<P>
In the June notice, the agency asked manufacturers "to examine their product formulations for ingredients and processing aids that contain known allergens that they may have considered to be exempt from declarations incidental additives ... and to declare the presence of such ingredients in the ingredient statement." Using the name of the ingredient and a parenthetical statement "processing aid" would be acceptable, the FDA indicated.
</P>

<P>
<H3>What Is an Allergen?</H3>
</P>

<P>
Although the FDA has not formally defined "allergens," it did issue a 1992 policy statement recognizing milk, eggs, fish, crustacea, mollusks, tree nuts, wheat and legumes, particularly peanuts and soybeans, as known allergens (57 FR 22984).
</P>

<P>
"The voluntary declaration of an allergenic ingredient of a color, flavor, or spice could be accomplished by simply naming the allergenic ingredient in the ingredient list. Other, non-allergenic ingredients that are exempt from declaration would remain unlisted," the FDA wrote.
</P>

<P>
In its recent request for comments on the labeling of natural and artificial flavors (see  "Proposed Changes to Specific Labeling Regs ...," p. 1) the FDA received 114 comments from consumers concerned about "hidden" ingredients in their food, specifically monosodium glutamate (MSG) and other substances they fear are masked by phrases such as "flavorings" or "natural flavorings." 
</P>

<P>
Consumers felt the terms "natural flavors" and "artificial flavors" were too broad, and urged the FDA to ensure that every substance present in the food be listed on the label. For example, the National Organization Mobilized to Stop Glutamate (NoMSG) wrote in comments:
</P>

<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>"All sources of MSG (including MSG-containing compounds) must identify this substance when added to foods. Our position is that the word 'flavoring' is vague, frequently deceptive, and has been used as a subterfuge for widespread addition of monosodium glutamate- containing substances in foods." 
</BLOCKQUOTE></P>

<P>
Another group of consumers suffering from the autoimmune disease celiac sprue stressed that they must avoid certain ingredients.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Industry Response</H3>
</P>

<P>
Several industry groups also addressed the allergy issue in their comments. The National Seasoning Manufacturers Association, for example, wrote:
</P>

<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>"FDA should publish a list of allergens that must be listed by common or usual name when used in a food additive or a flavoring. This would eliminate hydrolyzed vegetable proteins with the associated glutamates, egg products, dairy products, yeasts, fish, crustaceans, meat by-products (e.g., gelatin, blood protein), etc. from being labeled as "Natural Flavors" with the associated health and religious problems." </BLOCKQUOTE>
</P>

<P>
Because consumers were united in their concerns that foods were not adequately labeled, and called on FDA to ensure that some form of labeling requirement for allergens be established, it is likely that the agency will carefully consider allergen labeling provisions. 
</P>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/food/food.html"><img src="/tpg/food/food/smallfood.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to U.S. Food Labeling Law Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
