<html> <title> Court Rules on Whether Workers Were 'Subject To' Pay Docking </title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/file/filehead.gif" alt="FLSA Employee Exemption Handbook">
<P>
<h2>Court Rules on Whether Workers Were 'Subject To' Pay Docking</h2>
<body>
<h3><i>New Jersey Engineers' Case Marks the First Time 3rd Circuit Considers the
Controversial Issue</i></h3>

In an overtime compensation suit involving engineers, yet another federal appeals
court has ruled that an employer's improper pay docking policy violated the Fair
Labor Standards Act (FLSA) salary basis test, even though that policy was never
actually enforced.<P>

In <i>Balgowan v. New Jersey Department of Transportation,</i> No. 95-5276 (3rd
Cir. May 16, 1996), engineers sued their employer claiming unpaid overtime
compensation. The state transportation department contended that the engineers
were exempt from the FLSA as professionals, but the employees disagreed. They
argued, among other things, that they were not paid on a salary basis as required
by the act because their pay had been subject to docking for reasons prohibited
by U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) salary basis regulations (29 CFR
&#167;541.118).<P>

DOL's salary basis rules place tight restrictions on when an FLSA-exempt
employee's pay may be docked without the exemption being lost (see &#182;220-228
of the <i>Handbook</i>). In recent years, controversy has arisen over when an
employee is actually "subject to" an employer's pay reduction policy. The
question has been reviewed by several federal appeals courts, and to date, their
interpretations have varied (see diagram below).<P>

For example, some federal appeals courts, including those covering the 8th, 5th
and 11th Circuits, have concluded that an employee may still qualify for a
professional exemption from the FLSA even if the employer has a policy that
<i>theoretically</i> could result in the employee's pay being docked. In other
words, the professional exemption may still apply, these courts reason, if a
violative pay-docking policy is in place but no deduction in wages has actually
occurred.<P>

Conversely, other federal appeals courts, including those covering the 2nd, 9th
and District of Columbia Circuits, have interpreted "subject to" differently.
Specifically, these courts have ruled that any time the <i>potential</i> for a
deduction in an exempt employee's pay exists, the employee is not paid on a
salary basis. The mere existence of a violative pay docking policy, these courts
conclude, is enough to destroy the exemption.<P>

Until <i>Balgowan,</i> the 3rd Circuit had not ruled on this question.<P>

<h3>The Engineers' Complaint</h3>

The court began its analysis by carefully reviewing the transportation
department's pay docking policy. The court found that the policy allowed for an
employee's suspension without pay for infractions such as tardiness,
insubordination and neglect of duty.<P>

DOL regulations (29 CFR &#167;541.118(a)(5)) allow employers to dock an
employee's pay for infractions of safety rules of major significance without
losing the exemption. But the regulations state that these safety rules include
"only those relating to the prevention of serious danger to the plant, or other
employees, such as rules prohibiting smoking in explosive plants, oil refineries
and coal mines."<P>

The appeals court found that the employer's practice of docking pay for
tardiness, incompetence and other non-safety-related reasons violated the salary
test. "These infractions exceed the scope of the safety exception to the
professional exemption," the court said.<P>

<h3>Status of the Pay Docking Policy</h3>

As a follow-up argument, the employer contended that the professional exemption
should nevertheless be retained for the workers because the employer had never
actually enforced the pay docking policy and no engineer had ever suffered a
reduction in pay because of it. In essence, the employer asserted that an actual
docking of pay had to occur before the engineers could lose their status as
exempt professionals.<P>

Considering the stance of the other federal appeals courts with regard to the
issue, the 3rd Circuit embraced the decisions by the D.C., 2nd and 9th Circuits.
The 3rd Circuit concluded that being "subject to" reductions in pay for minor
non-safety-related reasons does not require actual docking of pay to have
occurred.<P>

"We conclude that the language of [29 CFR &#167;541.118(a)(5)] would be strained
by holding that an employee is 'subject to' a reduction only if an actual
reduction has occurred," the court said. "We believe that the [transportation
department's] disciplinary policy, even if not enforced, renders the engineers'
salary contingent rather than fixed."<P>

"We believe this approach more accurately comports with reality," the court
continued. "This approach is also consistent with the policy that the FLSA is a
remedial act and exemptions from its coverage are to be narrowly construed
against employers."<P>

"Finally, it would be rather arbitrary to hold that whether an employer qualifies
for the professional exemption shall be determined by the employees' collective
good behavior," the court pointed out. "If one employee violates the disciplinary
policy and is docked, so the argument goes, all the employees would lose the
professional exemption and be entitled to FLSA-required overtime rates."<P>

The court also reasoned that an unenforced employment policy, like the one the
transportation department claimed to have adopted, causes confusion as to whether
that policy is in effect and should be followed.<P>

<h3>Other Issues</h3>

The appeals court also considered several other points in reaching its decision.
For example, the court ruled that the transportation department did not qualify
for relief under the FLSA's so-called "window of correction" provisions (29 CFR
&#167;541.118(a)(6)) because the employer's pay docking error was not
"inadvertent." In addition, because the transportation department is a public
employer, the court reviewed the applicability of the FLSA's salary basis test
for the engineers' work both before and after Sept. 6, 1991.<P>

In September 1991, DOL amended its salary basis regulations to permit public
employers to dock the pay of exempt employees for partial-day absences. Citing
prior case law on this issue, the court ruled that the salary test did not apply
to the engineers prior to Sept. 6, 1991. Therefore, the engineers need only meet
the "duties" portion of the professional exemption to qualify before that date,
the court said.<P>

The engineers conceded that they met the duties test prior to September 1991;
therefore, they were exempt from the FLSA's overtime provisions. With regard to
the engineers' exempt status after that date, the court held that the salary test
had not been met (due to the docking for other than major safety reasons).
Consequently, the engineers were non-exempt and due overtime for that period.<P>

<img src="/tpg/person/file/fileaug.gif" alt="This chart is titled How Federal Appeals 
Circuits Have Split on 'Subject To'">
</body> 

<foot>

