<html> <title>Columbia University Found Not Liable Under Title VII for Failure to
Investigate Sexual Harassment Claims, Court Rules</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/sink/sinkhead.gif" alt="Educator's Guide to Controlling Sexual Harassment">
<P>
<h2>Columbia University Found Not Liable Under Title VII for Failure to
Investigate Sexual Harassment Claims, Court Rules</h2>

<body>
After affirming a jury's finding that the sexual harassment allegations of a
Columbia University employee against her co-worker were unfounded, the U.S.
District Court for Southern New York June 28 ruled that the school was not liable
under Title VII for failure to investigate the accuser's complaint.<P>

The court said that "even if the law were such to impose liability on an
employer" for a failure to investigate, Columbia University would not have been
liable because a "sufficient evidentiary basis" did not exist for a finding
against the school.<P>

<h3>The Alleged Harassment</h3>

While a student at Columbia, plaintiff Sharon Karibian in 1986 began working on a
fundraising project within the university. She claimed that her supervisor, Mark
Urban, "pressured her into having sexual relations" with him intermittently
between 1987 and 1989.<P>

According to Karibian, Urban had engaged in "unwelcome sexual activities" with
her and had indicated that "she would receive employment advantages if she
submitted" to his advances and disadvantages if she did not. In her claims
against Urban, Karibian alleged that he committed two types of sexual harassment:
quid pro quo and hostile environment.<P>

Urban conceded that he had "pursued Karibian romantically" and that a sexual
relationship had developed between them. However, he asserted that their
relationship was consensual.<P>

Based on the evidence presented, a jury found that Urban did not sexually harass
Karibian. Though not specifically stated in the court's opinion, one of the
deciding factors in the verdict was a series of conflicting statements made by
Karibian concerning her relationship with Urban.<P>

Karibian's characterization of the relationship at trial contradicted records
made of her discussions with two university employees with whom she met to
discuss the relationship and alleged abuse. Karibian testified at trial that
Urban had "forced, violent sexual intercourse" with her on two occasions in early
and mid-1988, and added that undesired "activities of a sexual nature" continued,
with a break of several months, until the spring of 1989.<P>

However, the notes of a clinical psychologist with whom Karibian met on eight
occasions in 1988 indicated that her "problem, as described in detail to [the
psychologist], was Karibian's anxiety about being able to hold Urban as a
boyfriend," the court noted. Karibian said nothing to the psychologist about
unwelcome advances, or the use of force or violence in connection with the
relationship, records showed.<P>

According to a member of the university's panel on sexual harassment with whom
Karibian consulted later in 1988, Karibian told her "repeatedly that she had
willingly engaged" in the relationship, but now wanted to end it and feared that
if she tried, she might suffer consequences at work. Karibian later denied that
she had made statements indicating that the relationship was voluntary.<P>

<h3>Employer Liability for Investigations</h3>

Although the jury did not find that Urban sexually harassed Karibian, it did
conclude, in response to one of Karibian's claims, that the university received
notice of the alleged harassment in September 1988, well before the time the
school acted on the complaint in 1990. The jury also affirmed Karibian's claim
that the university failed "to take reasonable steps to determine the facts about
Karibian's complaint and take appropriate remedial action," the court said.<P>

In light of the jury's finding that the school failed to act on the harassment
complaint, the court was faced with determining whether the school's failure was
a "valid issue under the law." In other words, the court was asked to decide
whether the school could face liability under Title VII or the New York Human
Rights Law for not acting on the complaint, even though the complaint had been
invalidated.<P>

Title VII of the Civil Rights Act prohibits (among other things) sex
discrimination in employment (42 U.S.C. &#167;2000e), as does the New York law in
question. The court found that neither statute "has any language expressly
creating liability for failure to investigate and remedy a complaint of
discrimination." The laws do provide certain specific protections, such as a bar
against retaliation for harassment complaints, but as the court stated, "[n]o one
contends that the failure to investigate and remedy a complaint" is equivalent to
retaliation or any other conduct protected by the statute.<P>

Case law establishing an employer's obligation to investigate sexual harassment
claims was cited by Karibian, but the court found that the evidence failed to
support her claim because in the cited cases, the accused employees had been
found guilty of sexual harassment.<P>

The court recognized that "one might believe" that employers have a "moral or
ethical duty" to investigate claims, but added that this is distinct from a
statutory duty. And while the court acknowledged that conducting investigations
that are fair to both accuser and accused is difficult, it said that despite the
lack of statutory obligation, employers have a "strong incentive" to conduct
investigations of harassment complaints to avoid or curb liability in cases where
sexual harassment <i>does</i> exist.<P>

<h3>The University's Investigation</h3>

The court next examined the university's response to Karibian's complaint. In
September 1988, Karibian took advantage of two university options for dealing
with possible harassment:<P>

<UL>
<LI>she discussed the alleged harassment with a member of the university's panel
on sexual harassment (as stated above); and <P>

<LI>she discussed Urban's actions with a worker in the school's Office for Equal
Opportunity and Affirmative Action (EEOA).</UL>

Although the court determined that both procedures are "entirely confidential,"
Karibian claimed that these actions constituted notice to the school of alleged
harassment.<P>

Columbia University students and employees who believe they are being harassed
also have an option to file a complaint under an appropriate school grievance
procedure, the court noted. This option is not confidential; individuals who file
a complaint initiate an investigation of their claims. Karibian did not take
advantage of this option and in fact specifically asked the EEOA employee that
"there be no investigation at that time," the court said. After her meetings with
the above individuals, her sexual relationship with Urban continued.<P>

Despite Karibian's argument to the contrary, the court determined that Karibian
had not made a complaint "under circumstances which would allow Columbia to
engage in investigative and corrective measures until early 1990." At that time,
Karibian informed one of Urban's superiors of his alleged misconduct. (By this
time, their sexual relationship had ended, and the misconduct allegedly took the
form of retaliation, or "detrimental employment actions.")<P>

Urban's superior then reported the complaint to John Borden, deputy vice
president of the division where Karibian and Urban worked. At that point, the
court said, "[i]mmediate steps were taken both to investigate the complaint and
to provide a remedy to Karibian."<P>

First, the university took steps to ensure that Urban and Karibian never had to
meet alone in their business dealings. Then, deciding to take "a more drastic
step," the university removed Urban as Karibian's supervisor in February. In
April, the school requested and received Urban's resignation (but not because of
the sexual harassment allegations).<P>

According to the court, "it is difficult to understand how Columbia could have
done more than it did to investigate Karibian's complaint and to provide remedial
measures." Because of the absence of university liability in the case, the court
granted a motion by Columbia to set aside an award of $450,000 in damages the
university was slated to pay the accuser.<P>

In the original trial, an array of other claims, such as complaints of
retaliation by Urban, Columbia and Borden under state law, had been dismissed.
The court dismissed motions by Karibian attempting to reinstate these and other
claims.<P>

For more information on this case and an analysis of both quid pro quo and
hostile environment sexual harassment, see the March 1994 <i>Monthly
Bulletin,</i> page 1. (<i>Karibian v. Columbia University,</i> S.D.N.Y, No. 91
Civ. 3153, June 28, 1996)
</body> 

<foot>

