<html> 
<head>
<title>FLSA Amendments Revise Pay Rule for Certain Computer Professionals</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/file/filehead.gif" alt="FLSA Employee Exemption Handbook">
<P>
<h2>FLSA Amendments Revise Pay Rule for Certain Computer Professionals</h2>
<h3><i>Meanwhile, Comp Time Bill Makes Headway in Congress</i></h3>

A newly enacted amendment to the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) fixes at $27.63
the amount a computer professional must be paid per hour to qualify for
exemption from the act. The amendment was enacted as part of a law (H.R. 3448,
P.L. 104-188) that raises the federal minimum wage 90 cents per hour by Sept. 1,
1997.<P>

The amendment, which takes effect Oct. 1, 1996, adds to the FLSA a provision
establishing the minimum hourly wage a computer worker must receive to qualify
for exemption from the overtime protections of the act -- provided he or she
meets other duties requirements also set forth in the amendment (see &#182;531
of the <i>Handbook</i>). Currently, FLSA implementing regulations, as set forth
in the <i>Code of Federal Regulations</i> (CFR), provide that exempt computer
professionals be paid on a salary basis, or be paid an hourly rate of at least
6.5 times the minimum wage (29 CFR &#167;541.312). The new law removes the 6.5
multiplication factor from the rules and establishes the flat $27.63 rate.<P>

The new amendment means that FLSA implementing regulations and the statute
provide two different minimum wage standards for exempt computer professionals
who are paid by the hour: $27.63, under the FLSA, and 6.5 times the increased
minimum wage, under the U.S. Department of Labor's (DOL) existing regulations.
According to a source at the DOL, employers should rely on the new amendment,
which supersedes the DOL's rules. "Basically," the DOL said, "this [amendment]
freezes the law as it is now." Therefore, employers will henceforth be held only
to the $27.63 hourly minimum, regardless of future increases in the minimum
wage.<P>

The source added that DOL's rules will be amended to reflect the change, but
could not predict when such an amendment would come.<P>

H.R. 3448, the bill containing the amendment, was approved by Congress Aug. 2
and signed by President Clinton Aug. 20. The law includes various tax reform
provisions, many geared toward helping small businesses.<P>

Under the law, the minimum wage will increase to $4.75 per hour effective Oct.
1, 1996. A second increase, to $5.15, will occur Sept. 1, 1997. The effective
dates were established by a House-Senate conference committee; earlier versions
of the bill would have set earlier dates for the two steps of the increase.<P>

In general, all employees covered by the FLSA must be paid at least the minimum
wage, which was set at $4.25 per hour in March 1991 (see &#182;101 of the
<i>Handbook</i>).<P>

In addition to the changes for computer professionals, the new law contains a
measure revising the "tip credit system." Rather than paying "tipped" employees
50 percent of the minimum wage plus tips, employers may now pay workers $2.13
per hour plus tips (as under the previous system, the resulting amount must at
least equal the minimum wage). The law also enacts an "opportunity wage"
provision, which permits employers to pay new employees under 20 years old at a
rate of $4.25 per hour for their first 90 days of employment. Both provisions
are effective Oct. 1.<P>

<h3>Comp Time Bill Approved in House</h3>

A second FLSA-related bill (H.R. 2391), which would give private sector
employees the option to receive compensatory time off in lieu of overtime pay,
passed the House July 30. The original version of the bill was introduced by
Rep. Cass Ballenger, R-N.C., on Sept. 21, 1995.<P>

Pursuant to the FLSA, employers are required to pay their non-exempt employees
at a rate of time and one-half for all hours worked over 40 in a week.
Ballenger's bill would alter the FLSA to allow private employers to offer their
employees paid time off (or "comp time") in lieu of overtime pay, an option
currently enjoyed in the public sector.<P>

Employee use of comp time under the bill would be voluntary, and employers could
grant comp time only if provided for by a collective bargaining agreement (or
similar agreement made by an employee representative), or an agreement entered
into by the employee before work began.<P>

The bill also provides, among other things, that comp time granted as overtime
compensation would be given at a rate of time and one-half, the same rate at
which cash overtime is awarded. At the end of each calendar year (or other
pre-established 12-month period), an employer would have to give employees cash
in exchange for all unused comp time they had accrued.<P>

The bill also provides that an employee's entrance into a comp time agreement
could not be a "condition of employment." Under the legislation, employers could
not "directly or indirectly intimidate, threaten or coerce" employees into
agreeing to receive comp time rather than cash for overtime or using comp time
once it is accrued. Employers that violated these rules would be liable under
the legislation for monetary penalties.<P>

Under the bill, private sector employees could accrue up to 240 comp time hours.
Employees who exceeded these limits would receive cash overtime payments for the
additional hours.<P>

Ballenger said in introducing the bill that offering employees a choice between
overtime pay and comp time would "help ease the burdens of juggling work and
personal responsibilities." But at a hearing on the bill held last December,
several Democrats on the House Workforce Protections Subcommittee expressed
concern that the legislation did not guarantee a sufficient degree of protection
for employees.<P>

Since its introduction, several provisions attempting to create increased worker
protections have been added to the bill. Nevertheless, opponents of the bill are
still concerned about employee rights, worrying, for instance, that the bill
would allow employers to force workers to accept comp time instead of overtime
pay.<P>

The Senate Aug. 1 placed the comp time bill on its legislative calendar, but the
date of the bill's initial consideration in the Senate remains unclear.<P>

Other comp time proposals recently have been offered by President Clinton and
members of the Senate. The president discussed his version of a comp time
proposal at a June 24 conference held in Nashville, Tenn. Also, legislation
similar to Ballenger's bill (S. 1129) was introduced Aug. 7, 1995, in the Senate
by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. (see September 1995 <i>Current Developments,</i>
Page 8). The Ashcroft legislation was referred to the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee.


