<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gag Rules: A Bad Storm Rising or A Mild Summer in a Teapot?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN=
bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<hr>
<center><H1>Specialty Capitation Manual:</H1>
<H2>Rate Setting, Evaluation and Implementation</H2></center>
<hr>

<H2>Gag Rules: A Bad Storm Rising or A Mild Summer in a Teapot?</H2>
<H3>by C Keith Powell, Esq.</H3>
Recently &quot;gag rules&quot; -- limits on provider communication in managed
care organization (MCO) and insurance company contracts -- have received
much unfavorable publicity. Several states -- including Massachusetts, New
York, Maryland, and Georgia -- have passed legislation prohibiting MCOs,
insurance companies, or other entities from forbidding providers from discussing
treatment options with patients. Federal legislation also is being considered.<BR>
<BR>
It has been suggested that the public health and safety demand nothing less
than allowing providers, without restriction, to make any statements whatsoever,
including slander against the MCO and disclosure to competitors of proprietary
information. If this destroys managed care, so much the better, according
to the popular press. After all, managed care supposedly is killing people,
forcing fine doctors into disreputable behaviors that they are somehow helpless
to resist, and generally undermining society. [See &quot;Media Perspectives
of Gag Clauses,&quot; below.]<BR>
<BR>
A problem arises when one asks to see provider contract provisions that
specifically restrict physicians in their discussions of treatment options.
While everyone has heard of them, it is impossible to locate a provision
that has the effect of preventing the discussion of treatment options. A
common provision often alleged to prevent the discussion of treatment options
is that of U.S. Healthcare [see &quot;Gag Clauses -- Before and After,&quot;
below], which was the basis for the Time magazine article that gave recent
impetus to much of the public furor over gag rules.<BR>
<BR>
The majority of the statements that, on the surface, go further toward explicit
limits on treatments are &quot;pre-certification&quot; rules intended to
avoid dangerous and unnecessary treatments, and have operated in that fashion.
Even these statements have been pared back willingly - usually even unilaterally
- by MCOs in response to recent publicity on gag rules. The reason why MCOs
are so willing to clarify that these provisions do not limit discussion
of treatment options is simply that they were never operated in such a way
in the first place, and would be unenforceable were such an effort made.
<H4>The MCO Perspective</H4>
First, consider a hypothetical version of the gag rule that would try to
prevent a physician from discussing treatment options with a patient. Such
a rule would almost surely be legally unenforceable as counter to public
policy and probably inconsistent with informed consent laws. <BR>
<BR>
Also, personal injury law is flexible and capable of responding to new situations
by inventing new wrongs to be redressed. An effort to prevent discussion
of treatment options would likely expose the MCO to a dangerous new claim.
Beyond legal issues, the public relations effect would be devastating. Ethical
providers would abandon the MCO in large numbers and form competitors.<BR>
<BR>
Of course, this prohibition does not apply to proper managed care procedures,
for example, pre-certification requirements. Properly applied, these managed
care procedures not only prevent injury and death through unnecessary and
inappropriate procedures but also (via cost savings creating lower premiums)
make all health care services available to people who would not otherwise
have them without managed care. MCOs should aggressively pursue all appropriate
managed care procedures and should resist any efforts to claim that such
procedures are attempts to keep physicians from discussing treatment options
with patients.<BR>
<BR>
Second, consider confidentiality and antidisparagement clauses. Any business
needs to protect against the improper disclosure of information that could
damage the business and against slander of the company. These are ancient
rights that, to a great extent, already exist in common and statutory law,
and their proper inclusion in provider contracts not only maximizes protection
of these valuable rights but also puts providers on notice that proper,
ethical behavior is expected. <BR>
<BR>
Beyond the needs of the average business, such as a fried chicken fast-food
chain (which tries to protect its &quot;secret herbs and spices&quot; and
fights dishonest claims that its food is not fit to eat), the MCO has an
especially strong need for such protection. The provider supply situation
plus hostile legislation, such as any willing provider laws, puts the MCO
in the unusual situation of being forced to deal, supposedly on a partnership
basis, with providers of services who are openly hostile to the MCO and
would like to see managed care destroyed so that they can return to the
days of fee-for-service.<BR>
<BR>
On this distinctly unlevel playing field (in which the MCO's worst enemies
can force it to do business with them, but it has no such power to force
a physician to contract with it), the MCO needs all available power to force
providers to behave in a way that respects its confidential information
and does not disparage it. When the MCO is forced to deal with physicians
who claim that confidentiality and antidisparagement clauses keep them from
discussing treatment options with patients, and that managed care is forcing
them to practice experiemental surgery, the MCO needs all the help it can
get. Every MCO should use confidentiality and antidisparagement clauses
to the maximum permitted extent to give themselves as much of the protection
as possible that other businesses - including health care providers - have.
<H4>The Specialty Care Provider Perspective</H4>
First, specialists need to be sure of what they think they see in the MCO's
contract. Most gag rule language has every appearance of legitimately protecting
MCOs from improper disclosure of confidential information and disparagement.
There is no evidence of attempts to enforce them in any other way. The great
majority of the accusations of such behavior comes from sources with a strong
antimanaged care bias and fall apart quickly under scrutiny; the very few
others are &quot;maybes&quot; at best, and unenforceable and ineffective
at that.<BR>
<BR>
Second, the best way of avoiding problems with required but unacceptable
contract provisions is to refuse to do business with their purveyors. MCOs
cannot force specialists to contract with them. A specialist can certainly
continue to practice on a fee-for-service basis. If the specialists prefers
to work with MCOs, he or she can find a different one, maybe one that is
provider owned. If there is no other MCO in the area, or none without offensive
contract provisions, the specialist can get together with other physicians
equally offended by the provisions and start their own MCO. If few or no
other physicians are so offended, the specialist should consider re-examining
his or her interpretation of the MCO provisions and behaviors to be sure
that the perception is reasonable.<BR>
<BR>
If the specialists wish to do business with an MCO that they feel is insisting
on an improper contractual provision, talk to the MCO. All evidence suggests
that they are sensitive to specialists' concerns and may be willing to change
the provision. Even if they are not willing to change the provision in all
provider contracts (possibly because they believe that most physicians interpret
it differently), they might change it in this case. If this sounds naive,
consider that when Dr. Himmelstein found the provision of U.S. Healthcare
offensive, he supposedly crossed it out before signing, and the amended
contract was accepted without complaint. U.S. Healthcare did not seem to
consider the entire matter very important, and other MCOs seem to agree.<BR>
<BR>
While specialists should not commit contract fraud, it is always possible
that in a rare situation they could find themselves confronted with a contract
situation that they did not previously know existed at the time that they
were forced to make a decision on the mater being addressed. Under these
conditions specialists should recall that the courts will try to enforce
public policy in favor of communication on legitimate areas such as treatment
options. <BR>
Specialists will probably find shelter under the informed consent laws of
their state. A number of states have enacted legislation specifically to
protect the right to discuss treatment options. Statutes and strong public
policy generally override contract provisions in conflict. Specialists can
certainly count on the press and politicians being on their side on this
issue. Of course, this is not a recommendation to use this line of reasoning
to commit fraud against an MCO by knowingly accepting such contract provisions
and later claiming ignorance of them.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, specialists should try to be fair and reasonable. MCOs have very
low profit margins, and exist in an extremely competitive environment. They
have to deal with many specialists who would like to see their organizations
fail. Specialists would not want others disclosing their confidential business
information or disparaging they, and they should not mind agreeing not to
disclose the MCO's confidential business information or disparage it. <BR>
<BR>
It is not true, as some try to claim, that the terms &quot;confidential
information&quot; and &quot;disparagement&quot; can mean anything. Such
terms in provider contracts will be construed strictly against the drawer
of the contact and liberally in favor of the public policy supporting a
patient's right to such information. Particularly in the legal setting,
it is almost unimaginable that these concepts could be confused with doctor-patient
discussions of treatment alternatives, particularly given the informed consent
laws and relevant public policy. To a great extent, clauses on confidential
information and disparagement only reflect existing legal rights, and they
are eminently reasonable in the environment in which MCOs have to operate.
<BR>
<HR>
<H3>Media Perspectives of Gag Clauses</H3>
1. &quot;What's needed is not just protection for doctors from gag orders,
but protection from consumers against the werewolves who may lurk in the
shadows of managed care.&quot; [&quot;Consumers Need Protection From Managers
of Managed Care,&quot; by Laurel Shackelford, the [Louisville?] Courier-Journal,
June 2, 1996, Sec. d page 2.]<BR>
This is the end of an article, the body of which covers the testimony of
a physician who in 1987 &quot;caused the death of a man&quot; when as an
&quot;executive physician&quot; with an HMO she &quot;denied him a necessary
operation to save his heart.&quot; Note that the MCO was blamed even though
it hired a physician to determine if requested surgery was necessary, and
the physician then supposedly decided to label as unnecessary an operation
that was, in fact, necessary.<BR>
<BR>
2. &quot;Today MCOs allow primary care physicians to make the treatment
decisions rather than having them approved by physicians directly on staff
with the MCO. Things are much worse now than when such procedures had to
be cleared with the MCO, because today the primary care physician is no
longer a patient advocate and is likely to deny care in order to reduce
costs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
This a paraphrased statement made by a physician explaining that while MCOs
were once blamed for requiring approval by a physician at the staff level
for care that the primary care physician wanted to give, they should now
be blamed for giving full authority to the primary care physician.<BR>
<HR>
<H3>Gag Clauses -- Before and After</H3>
<I>U.S. Healthcare's original gag clause, which became the subject of media
attention, reads:</I><BR>
Physicians shall agree not to take any action or make any communication
which undermines or could undermine the confidence of enrollees, potential
enrollees, their employers, their unions, or the public in U.S. Healthcare
or the quality of U.S. Healthcare coverage. Physicians shall keep the Proprietary
Information [payment rates, utilization review procedures, etc.] and this
Agreement strictly confidential.<BR>
<BR>
<I>What follows is the HMO's revision to the above clause:</I><BR>
(1) Physician shall have the right and is encouraged to discuss with his
or her patients pertinent details regarding the diagnosis of the patient's
condition, the nature and purpose of any recommended procedure, the potential
risks and benefits of any recommended treatment, and any reasonable alternatives
to such recommended treatment.<BR>
<BR>
(2) Physician's obligations not to disclose Proprietary Information do not
apply to any disclosures to a patient determined by Physician to be necessary
or appropriate for the diagnosis and care of a patient except to the extent
such disclosure would otherwise violate Physician's legal or ethical obligations.<BR>
<BR>
(3) Physician is encouraged to discuss U.S. Healthcare's provider reimbursement
methodology with Physician's patients, subject only to Physician's general
contractual and ethical obligations not to make false or misleading statements.
Accordingly, Proprietary Information does not include descriptions of the
Quality Care Compensation System methodology under which Physician is reimbursed,
although such information does include the specific rates paid by U.S. Healthcare
due to their competitively sensitive nature.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
