<html> 
<head>
<title> Public Employer's Guide to FLSA Employee Classification </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/jobs/jobshead.gif" alt="Public Employer's Guide to FLSA Employee Classification"></center>

<h2>Courts Base FLSA Rulings Against State Workers on <i>Seminole</i>
Decision</h2>

Two district courts recently dismissed claims filed by state employees against
their employers under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), ruling that the U.S.
Supreme Court's decision in <i>Seminole Tribe of Florida v. Florida,</i> 116 S.
Ct. 1114 (1996), protected states from private actions by state employees
brought in federal court.<P>

In <i>Seminole,</i> a five-justice majority of the Court struck down a provision
of the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act (IGRA) (25 U.S.C. &#167;2710(d)(7)), which
was passed by Congress under the Indian Commerce Clause of the U.S.
Constitution. The provision required states to negotiate in good faith with
Native American tribes to enter into tribal-state compacts governing conduct of
gaming activities on Indian reservations. The provision also gave federal courts
jurisdiction over causes of action brought by Native American tribes to enforce
the states' obligation to negotiate such compacts.<P>

Pursuant to the provision, the <i>Seminole</i> tribe sued the state of Florida and its
governor for injunctive relief to force the governor and the state to enter into
negotiations for a tribal-state compact on gaming. However, the Supreme Court
ruled that Florida and its governor were immune from such a suit pursuant to the
11th Amendment.<P>

<h3>Highway Patrol Employees</h3>

In <i>Whitesell v. Moore,</i> No. 5:96-CV-292-BR2 (E.D.N.C. Aug. 14, 1996),
Robert Whitesell, an employee of the North Carolina State Highway Patrol, filed
charges against the state and the state's secretary of crime control and public
safety, claiming he was misclassified as exempt under the FLSA and was owed
compensation for overtime hours worked for the department. Citing several court
rulings, the department asked the court to dismiss Whitesell's claims, arguing
that the 11th Amendment barred FLSA claims against a state government.<P>

For example, relying on the Supreme Court's decision in <i>Edelman v.
Jordan,</i> 415 U.S. 651 (1974), the defendants argued that a state's own
citizens or the citizens of another state may not file suit against the state
for money damages under the 11th Amendment. The defendants said that the 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in <i>Gray v. Laws,</i> 51 F.3d 426 (1995),
extended this protection to state officers acting in their official capacity.
Further, the defendants said, in <i>Seminole,</i> the Supreme Court held that
states "may not be sued in federal court unless they consent to it in
unequivocal terms or unless Congress, pursuant to a valid exercise of power,
unequivocally expresses its intent to abrogate the immunity."<P>

The district court in <i>Whitesell</i> noted that Congress passed the FLSA under
its authority granted in the Interstate Commerce Clause of the Constitution.
However, the Court in <i>Seminole</i> "overruled prior case law and held that
'Article I [the Interstate Commerce Clause] cannot be used to circumvent the
constitutional limitation placed upon federal jurisdiction,'" the district court
stated.<P>

Moreover, because the FLSA was established under Congress' Interstate Commerce
Clause authority, the law cannot dismiss the state's 11th Amendment immunity.
"Plaintiff cannot raise his claim against defendants, a state and its officer
acting in his official capacity, in this court," the district court ruled.<P>

The plaintiff acknowledged that <i>Seminole</i> prevented "Congress from granting him a
right to sue defendants." However, he argued that the state and its official
"implicitly" relinquished their immunity under the 11th Amendment "by choosing
to comply with FLSA and causing its employees to legitimately rely on that
compliance."<P>

To decide the question, the district court again turned to the <i>Seminole</i>
decision. The Supreme Court in <i>Seminole</i> held that to determine whether
Congress properly has abrogated the states' sovereign immunity, two questions
must be asked:<P>
(1) has Congress unequivocally expressed its intent to abrogate the immunity;
and<P>
(2) has Congress acted pursuant to a valid exercise of power?<P>

Using this standard, the court concluded that the state's compliance with the
FLSA was not voluntary, but required by Congress. The district court therefore
found that "defendants have not 'unequivocally' waived their 11th Amendment
immunity."<P>

<h3>New York State Employees</h3>

In the second case, <i>Close v. State of New York,</i> No. 94-CV-0906, 1996 U.S.
Dist. LEXIS 12330 (N.D.N.Y. Aug. 19, 1996), 404 employees of the state alleged
they were not paid for overtime hours worked under the FLSA. They sought
compensation for the overtime, liquidated damages and attorneys' fees.<P>

In February 1996, the U.S. District Court for Northern New York issued a
memorandum decision and order holding that the state had violated the FLSA for
not properly compensating its employees for overtime hours worked. However, the
state recently filed a motion to dismiss the case and vacate the previous ruling
under the Supreme Court's <i>Seminole</i> finding, claiming the district court
did not have jurisdiction to hear the case.<P>

The state employees argued that the <i>Seminole</i> decision did not change a
state's responsibilities under the Interstate Commerce Clause; <i>Seminole</i>
only dismissed states' 11th Amendment immunity under the Indian Commerce Clause,
the plaintiffs said. However, the court stated that "the Indian Commerce Clause
is a greater transfer of power from the states to the federal government than is
the Interstate Commerce Clause," and dismissed that portion of the employees'
argument.<P>

Responding to the employees' second claim that the state had relinquished its
immunity by consenting to the suit, the court responded that "judicial
recognition of constructive waiver has been extremely rare." Only when Congress
clearly indicates its intent to make states responsible in federal court for
certain actions, and the state "voluntarily chooses" to undertake such actions,
can states waive their 11th Amendment immunity, the court noted. "This is not a
situation where a state knew beforehand that an inevitable cost of engaging in
an activity and deriving its benefits was consent to be sued," the court
ruled.<P>

The plaintiffs also claimed that the <i>United States Code</i> allowed actions
under the FLSA "against an employer (including a public agency) in any federal
or state court of competent jurisdiction" (29 U.S.C. &#167;216(b)), calling into
question the constitutionality of the FLSA as it applies to states. Therefore,
according to plaintiffs, the U.S. Attorney General must certify the FLSA
constitutionality issue before the court can proceed. The district court
responded that "because the constitutional issue is so clear in this case
following the Supreme Court's ruling in <i>Seminole Tribe,</i> however, there is
no reason for the court to await the outcome of the certification."<P>

The district court followed the <i>Seminole</i> ruling, stating that it "no
longer [had] subject-matter jurisdiction over the state's violation of the Fair
Labor Standards Act," and vacated its memorandum decision against the state.<P>

<h3>Implications of the <i>Seminole</i> Decision</h3>

In light of the <i>Seminole</i> case, it appears that state employees may no
longer bring FLSA suits in federal court against their employers. The
<i>Whitesell</i> and <i>Close</i> decisions illustrate this assumption. Absent
the state's consent, such suits arguably violate the 11th Amendment to the
Constitution. Whatever the final result, the 11th Amendment immunity argument
poses some excellent grounds to dismiss pending federal cases, although private
actions presumably still may be brought in state courts.
<hr>
<center>
