<html> <title>Device BIMO Inspections Continue to Stress Data Integrity Issues<p></title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/clin/clinhead.gif" alt="Guide to Good Clinical Practice">
<P>
<h2>Device BIMO Inspections Continue to Stress Data Integrity Issues<p></h2>
<body>

Medical device sponsors and researchers need to be mindful of both the basic
parameters of FDA clinical research regulations and of the specific requirements
for their types of products -- particularly given the agency's emphasis on
fraudulent submissions under its applications integrity policy (AIP), according
to Charma Konnor, the new director of bioresearch monitoring (BIMO) within the
Center for Devices and Radiological Health (CDRH).<p>

In an exclusive interview with the <i>Monthly Bulletin</i>, Konnor explained that small
device firms in particular need to focus on FDA regulations and guidance for
conducting and managing device clinical trials, if they want to avoid potential
product approval delays due to AIP violations.<p>

"From what I've seen, particularly smaller firms need access to information so
they can comply," Konnor said. "Under the applications integrity policy if these
firms don't have the right guidance they can suffer financially."<p>

<h3>AIP Basics</h3><p>

The AIP is an overreaching FDA compliance policy guide formally entitled "Fraud,
Untrue Statements of Material Facts, Bribery, and Illegal Gratuities" issued in
1991 (CPG 7150.09, see App. III). Under the policy, the FDA can investigate and
require corrective actions by product sponsors if they have submitted false or
misleading information to the agency related to a product application.<p>
"From a bioresearch monitoring standpoint, our core concerns are the quality and
integrity of the data," Konnor said. "The next step in integrity is fraud ...
we're talking about altered data, data that [are] omitted on purpose or data
that [are] fabricated. We do find this and it is something we do look for," she
added.<p>

Konnor affirmed that because submission errors or omissions often reflect
underlying deviations in clinical trial conduct, record keeping or monitoring,
an AIP-related violation often can trigger FDA actions against clinical
investigators and institutional review boards (IRBs), in addition to a rejection
of a product application.<p>

<h3>Common Deviations</h3><p>

Often related to AIP violations are the following common deviations by device
sponsors, IRBs and clinical investigators that occur during the course of
clinical trials, which Konnor said closely parallel those found in drug related
studies:<p>

<ol><li>Informed consent -- Both a failure to obtain and document consent or to do
so in a timely manner (before study enrollment) (21 CFR &#167;812.150, see App.
II for all sites);<p>

<li>Failure to notify IRBs and FDA of protocol changes -- Failure of clinical
investigators to inform their sponsor, IRB and the FDA of substantial changes
that impact on the scientific basis or safety of their study  (21 CFR
&#167;812.150(4));<p>

<li>Record keeping problems -- Compliance by device sponsors, IRBs and clinical
investigators with the FDA's applicable record-keeping requirements,
particularly in documenting informed consents, and in filing progress and change
reports and adverse event reports (21 CFR Subpart G).</ol><p>
Konnor added that many such violations found during FDA inspections reflect
sloppiness in the transfer of data from patient records to case report forms, or
onto reports between the various parties responsible for the clinical trial (see
chart below).<p>


<center><img src="/tpg/food/clin/clinjuly1a.gif"></center><P>



<h3>Significant Risk Determination</h3><p>

Another concern, Konnor said is that many firms have difficulty making a proper

determination of whether a device is "significant risk" (SR) or "nonsignificant

risk" (NSR). <p>

SR devices require approval of an application for investigational device (IDE)

by the FDA, but no such approval is needed for NSR products (see Information

Sheet: "Significant Risk and Nonsignificant Risk Medical Device Studies," App.

III).<p>

Konnor stressed that IRBs play a critical role in the SR/NSR determination,

after a sponsor has made an initial judgment. FDA regulations also require that

a sponsor notify the FDA if the IRB disagrees with its SR/NSR determination (21

CFR &#167;812.150(9)).<p>

"IRBs continue to improve their cuts on SR and NSR determinations," she said.

"But we continue to see enough insufficient SR and NSR determinations that this

still remains a concern to us and we're exploring how to get the word out."<p>

<h3>Device Accountability</h3><p>

Another important issue in device clinical trial management, Konnor said, is

accountability by sponsors and clinical investigators for investigational

products (21 CFR &#167;&#167;812.110, 812.150). Under the regulations, sponsors

and investigators must keep careful records of devices shipped, received,

administered, and left over during the course of a clinical trial (21 CFR

&#167;812.140, see App. II).<p>

"Accountability continues to be a problem," Konnor said. "Clinical investigators

and sponsors have a responsibility to know what they're shipping out ... how

many ... and who they are going to.<p>

"In some instances [devices] are being distributed beyond the agreed-upon

parameters of the study, beyond the patients enrolled in the study," she added.

"In other cases [the problem] can be people not keeping track of their study

articles.<p>

"The bottom line is those who assume responsibility for monitoring studies

should also be responsible ... for the devices they're handling," Konnor

said.<p>

<h3>IRB-specific Issues</h3><p>

Konnor said that leading problems for IRBs are approval of studies after

research has been initiated, and failure to conduct adequate continuing

reviews.<p>

"They're not all giving approval of studies before they have started --

sometimes it happens in reverse order," Konnor said. "In other studies we see no

approval -- period -- and the study is ongoing."<p>

Konnor added that other, leading operational issues include failure to conduct

annual continuing reviews, inadequate written procedures and poor record

keeping. In part, she said, these problems stem from IRB staffing issues.<p>

"Frankly, sometimes they don't have enough staffing or inappropriate staffing,"

Konnor said, echoing the concerns of her counterparts in the drug area. "What

we're talking about is people who can do the job that's necessary," she

said.<p>

<h3>Communication is Key</h3><p>

Although Konnor affirmed that her office continues to rigorously enforce the

agency's requirements, she stressed that greater emphasis is being placed on

promoting industry's voluntary compliance.<p>

Accordingly, Konnor said her office increasingly is relying on untitled letters,

rather than highly publicized Warning Letters or other enforcement actions. She

reported that her office has issued 21 untitled letters and six Warning Letters

for bioresearch violations since Oct. 1, 1995. "We are in an era now where we've

got to do this differently," Konnor said. <p>

"We are not shooting from the hip and sending Warning Letters just to generate

numbers," she added "We're trying to identify what the problems and the needs

are and then work with [industry] so they understand what their responsibilities

are."



</body> 


<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/food/clin/clin.html"><img src="/tpg/food/clin/smallclin.gif"
alt="Return to Guide to Good Clinical Practice Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/fdaprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
