<html> 
<head>
<title> FLSA Employee Exemption Handbook </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/file/filehead.gif" alt="FLSA Employee Exemption Handbook">
<P>
<h2>Computer Professional's Suit Centers on Worker's Duties</h2>
<h3><i>Court is Among First to Interpret Application of DOL's 1992
Rules</i></h3>

In one of the first Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) overtime suits to address
application of the special 1992 federal rules governing computer professionals,
the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals recently held that an employer did not
present enough evidence to prove that its technical writer/documenter was exempt
from the act.<P>

In 1992, the U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) issued rules (29 C.F.R.
&#167;541.303; see Appendix II of the <i>Handbook</i>) establishing strict
standards for determining when certain highly paid computer employees could
qualify for a special FLSA exemption for computer-related occupations. The 1992
rules provide a means of exempting such workers that is different from the
method of qualifying exempt administrators and executives under the traditional
"long" and "short" tests (see Tab 500).<P>

The plaintiff in the case, Stephen Bohn, worked as a technical writer/documenter
in the software and training departments of Park City Group Inc., and was paid
$47,000 annually. After the company terminated Bohn's employment for
inadequately performing his duties, he brought suit claiming he was improperly
denied overtime pay for hours worked in excess of 40 in a workweek.<P>

The U.S. District Court for Utah granted Park City Group's motion for summary
judgment, ruling that Bohn was an exempt employee "because his primary duty was
as either a computer professional or an artistic professional." Bohn challenged
the ruling, and the appeals court reversed and remanded for trial the lower
court's decision.<P>

<h3>The Short Test for Professionals</h3>

Under the FLSA, employers generally must pay time and one-half overtime to an
employee for all hours worked over 40 in a workweek, unless the worker is
specifically employed in a "bona fide executive, administrative or professional
capacity" (29 U.S.C. &#167;207(a)(1)) or qualifies for another type of
exemption. The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in <i>Corning Glass Works v. Brennan</i>
(417 U.S. 188, 196-97 (1974)) that an employer bears the burden of proving an
employee's exempt status.<P>

FLSA regulations provide both a long test and short test for determining an
employee's exempt status as a professional. The level of Bohn's salary made him
subject to the short test, the 10th Circuit said.<P>

Under the short test for professionals, an employee must perform work that
requires the consistent exercise of discretion and independent judgment and
consists of one of the following:<P>
<UL>
<LI> work requiring advanced knowledge in a field of science or learning
customarily acquired by a prolonged course of specialized intellectual
instruction and study;<P>

<LI> teaching, tutoring, instructing or lecturing in the activity of imparting
knowledge as a teacher in the school system or educational establishment or
institution by which he is employed; or<P>

<LI> work that requires theoretical and practical application of highly
specialized knowledge in computer systems analysis, programming and software
engineering, and who is employed and engaged in these activities as a computer
systems analyst, computer programmer, software engineer or other similarly
skilled worker in the computer software field, as provided in
&#167;541.303.
</UL>

An employee also will meet the short test for professionals if his or her
primary duty consists of "work requiring invention, imagination, or talent in a
recognized field of artistic endeavor" (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.3).<P>

"The district court apparently found that based on undisputed facts, [Bohn's]
primary duty involved work either as a professional in an artistic endeavor or
as a computer professional," the appellate court said. Bohn, however, maintained
that the lower court erred in granting summary judgment to his employer because
questions of material fact remained concerning the duties he performed. He
argued that the nature of his duties did not qualify him for exemption under
DOL's 1992 rules.<P>

<h3>The 1992 Rules</h3>

DOL's 1992 rules recognize that expertise and skill required for the computer
professional exemption normally are attained through a combination of education
and experience in the field (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(c)). Consequently, in lieu
of a formal educational requirement, the rules list specific primary duties that
typical computer professionals perform. The rules (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b))
state that a bona fide computer professional's primary work must involve at
least one of the following:<P>
<UL>
<LI> the application of systems analysis techniques and procedures, including
consulting with users, to determine hardware, software or system functional
specifications;<P>

<LI> the design, development, documentation, analysis, creation, testing or
modification of computer systems or programs, including prototypes, based on and
related to user or system design specifications;<P>

<LI> the design, documentation, testing, creation or modification of computer
programs related to machine operating systems; or<P>

<LI> a combination of the aforementioned duties, the performance of which
requires the same level of skills.<P>
</UL>

Bohn graduated from Southwest Missouri State University with a bachelor's degree
in elementary education, then earned 13 semester hours toward a master of arts
in educational media and technology at Brigham Young University. He also had
worked previously in the computer and instruction fields. This experience led
the appeals court to conclude that "[o]verall, [Bohn's] education and experience
allow but do not compel a finding that he had the skill and expertise required
to meet the computer professional exemption." Therefore, the court turned to
Bohn's primary duties to determine whether they met the requirements of 29
C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b).<P>

<h3>Bohn's Duties</h3>

Park City Group hired Bohn as a "documenter at the documentation project manager
level." The job description for the position contained several computer-related,
instructional and supervisory duties. Among them were the following:<P>
<UL>
<LI> being comfortable with several operating systems;<P>

<LI> producing innovative solutions for a variety of complex problems;<P>

<LI> guiding users in formulating requirements;<P>

<LI> arbitrating conflicts between individuals;<P>

<LI> reviewing the work of lower employees;<P>

<LI> formulating decisions on broad policy and standards issues; and<P>

<LI> demonstrating in-depth knowledge and understanding of the software
development business.<P>
</UL>

Bohn claimed that he did not perform the duties outlined in the description,
however. Instead, he maintained that he spent most of his time on "basic word
processing, photocopying, collating and talking with other employees, and
minimizing the amount of time he spent doing technical writing."<P>

This account contradicted an earlier affidavit he submitted in which he
testified that he performed many of the duties outlined in the job description.
The district court ruled that though Bohn may have performed many of the
clerical tasks, they "were not duties and responsibilities assigned to him."<P>

Bohn also argued that "his work did not require the highly specialized computer
skills described in [29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b)]." Park City Group had relied on
those rules to classify Bohn as exempt.<P>

"On their face, [Bohn's] duties and accomplishments appear to reflect high-level
skills, but without more we cannot determine whether they involve the depth of
knowledge the law requires for the professional exemption," the appeals court
said. The court also ruled that the district court had relied too heavily on the
level of Bohn's salary when it ruled he was a professional. "Based on the record
before us we cannot agree that [Park City Group] met [its] burden to show that
no issues of material fact remained on this question," the 10th Circuit held.<P>

The appellate court also examined the issue of Bohn's exemption as an artistic
professional, stating that "recognized fields of artistic endeavor include
'music, writing, the theater and the plastic and graphic arts.'" FLSA
regulations state that, when writing is considered, essayists, novelists and
scenario writers who chose their own subjects, and writers for advertising
agencies are considered artistic professionals (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.302(c)(2)).
"Given these regulations we doubt plaintiff's duties as a technical
writer/documenter could qualify for an artistic professional exemption," the
court said.<P>

The 10th Circuit ruled that the district court erred by granting Park City Group
summary judgment because issues of material fact remained pertaining to Bohn's
job duties. The appellate court reversed the lower court's decision and remanded
the case for trial. (<i>Bohn v. Park City Group Inc.,</i> No. 95-4086, 1996 U.S.
App. LEXIS 22626)

