<head>
<title>Computer Employee's Duties Focus of Exemption Case </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/fair/fairhead.gif" alt="Fair Labor Standards
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>Computer Employee's Duties Focus of Exemption Case</h2>
<H3><I>Court is Among First to Interpret Application of DOL's 1992 Rules</I></H3>

In one of the first Fair Labor 	Standards Act (FLSA) overtime 	suits to
address application of the special 1992 federal rules governing computer
professionals, the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals held Aug. 28 that an
employer did not present enough evidence to prove that its technical
writer/documenter was exempt from the act.<P>

In 1992, the U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) issued rules (29 C.F.R.
&#167;541.303; see Appendix II) establishing strict standards for determining
when certain highly paid computer employees could qualify for a special FLSA
exemption for computer-related occupations. The 1992 rules provide a means of
exempting such workers that is different from the method of qualifying exempt
administrators and executives under the traditional "long" and "short" tests (see
Tab 200 of the <I>Handbook</I>).<P>

The plaintiff in the case, Stephen Bohn, worked as a technical writer/documenter
in the software and training departments of Park City Group, Inc., and was paid
$47,000 annually. After the company terminated Bohn's employment for inadequately
performing his duties, he brought suit claiming he was improperly denied overtime
pay for hours worked in excess of 40 in a workweek.<P>

The U.S. District Court for Utah granted the employer's motion for summary
judgment, ruling that Bohn was an exempt employee "because his primary duty was
as either a computer professional or an artistic professional." Bohn challenged
the ruling, and the appeals court reversed and remanded for trial the lower
court's decision.<P>

<H3>The Short Test</H3><P>

Under the FLSA, employers generally must pay time and one-half overtime to an
employee for all hours worked over 40 in a workweek, unless the worker is
employed in a "bona fide executive, administrative or professional capacity" or
is otherwise exempt from the act (29 U.S.C. &#167;207(a)(1)). FLSA regulations
provide both a long test and short test for determining whether an employee is an
exempt professional. The level of Bohn's salary made him subject to the short
test, the 10th Circuit said.<P>

Under the short test for professionals (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.3), an employee must
perform work that requires the consistent exercise of discretion and judgment and
consists of one of the following:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>work requiring advanced knowledge in a field of science or learning
	customarily acquired by a prolonged course of specialized intellectual
	instruction and study; <P>

	<LI>teaching, tutoring, instructing or lecturing in the activity of imparting
	knowledge as a teacher in the school system or educational establishment or
	institution by which he is employed; or <P>

	<LI>work that requires theoretical and practical application of highly
	specialized knowledge in computer systems analysis, programming and software
	engineering, and who is employed and engaged in these activities as a computer
	systems analyst, computer programmer, software engineer or other similarly
	skilled worker in the computer software field, as provided in &#167;541.303.<P>
</UL>

An employee also will meet the short test for professionals if his or her primary
duty consists of "work requiring invention, imagination, or talent in a
recognized field of artistic endeavor" (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.3). <P>

A "good rule of thumb" for establishing an employee's primary duty, the court
noted, is to determine what task comprises at least 50 percent of an employee's
time. <P>

However, the court added, with regard to the short test, an employee's primary
duty is usually the task "that is of principal value to the employer" rather than
"collateral tasks" that may make up more than half the worker's time. Bohn
maintained that the lower court erred in granting summary judgment to his
employer because questions of material fact remained as to whether his primary
duty characterized him as a computer or artistic professional.<P>

<H3>The 1992 Rules</H3><P>

DOL's 1992 rules recognize that expertise and skill required for the computer
professional exemption normally are attained through a combination of education
and experience in the field (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(c)). Consequently, in lieu
of a formal educational requirement, the rules list specific primary duties
typical computer professionals perform. The rules (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b))
state that a bona fide computer professional's primary duty must involve at least
one of the following:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>the application of systems analysis techniques and procedures, including
	consulting with users, to determine hardware, software or system functional
	specifications;<P>

	<LI>the design, development, documentation, analysis, creation, testing or
	modification of computer systems or programs, including prototypes, based on and
	related to user or system design specifications;<P>

	<LI>the design, documentation, testing, creation or modification of computer
	programs related to machine operating systems; or<P>

	<LI>a combination of the aforementioned duties, the performance of which
	requires the same level of skills.<P>
</UL>

The court found that Bohn possessed a bachelor's degree in elementary education
and had earned credit towards a master of arts in educational media and
technology. He also had worked previously in the computer and instruction fields.
This experience led the appeals court to conclude that "[o]verall, [Bohn's]
education and experience allow but do not compel a finding that he had the skill
and expertise required to meet the computer professional exemption." Therefore,
the court turned to Bohn's primary duties to determine whether they met the
requirements of 29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b).<P>

<H3>Bohn's Duties</H3><P>

The company hired Bohn as a "documenter at the documentation project manager
level." The job description for the position contained several computer related,
instructional and supervisory duties. Among them were the following:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>being comfortable with several operating systems;<P>

	<LI>producing innovative solutions for a variety of complex problems;<P>

	<LI>guiding users in formulating requirements;<P>

	<LI>arbitrating conflicts between individuals;<P>

	<LI>reviewing the work of lower employees;<P>

	<LI>formulating decisions on broad policy and standards issues; and<P>

	<LI>demonstrating in-depth knowledge and understanding of the software
	development business.<P>
</UL>

In addition, a job description for Bohn's technical writing position provided,
among other things, that such an employee would need to optimize the expenditure
of company funds, have knowledge of trends in documentation techniques and
methods and be able to write and edit materials on a number of different subject
matters.  <P>

Bohn, however, claimed that he had not performed the duties outlined in the
descriptions. Instead, he maintained that he had spent most of his time on "basic
word processing, photocopying, collating and talking with other employees, and
minimizing the amount of time he spent doing technical writing."<P>

This account contradicted an earlier affidavit he submitted in which he testified
that he performed many of the duties outlined in the job descriptions. The
district court ruled that though Bohn may have performed many of the clerical
tasks, they "were not duties and responsibilities assigned to him." <P>

Bohn also argued that "his work did not require the highly specialized computer
skills described in [29 C.F.R. &#167;541.303(b)]." The company had relied on
those rules to classify Bohn as exempt. <P>

According to the appeals court, "[o]n their face, [Bohn's] duties and
accomplishments appear to reflect high level skills, but without more we cannot
determine whether they involve the depth of knowledge the law requires for the
professional exemption." <P>

The court also ruled that the district court may have relied too heavily on the
level of Bohn's salary when it ruled he was a professional. The court said the
employer "failed to provide the kind of detailed information" about Bohn's
primary duty and "the computer skill required in this area of 'high tech" work"
to allow a classification of the employee as a computer professional. <P>

<H3>The Artistic Professional Exemption</H3><P>

The appellate court also examined the issue of Bohn's artistic professional
exemption, stating that "recognized fields of artistic endeavor include 'music,
writing, the theater and the plastic and graphic arts.'" FLSA regulations state
that, when writing is considered, essayists, novelists and scenario writers who
chose their own subjects, and writers for advertising agencies are considered
artistic professionals (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.302(c)(2)). "Given these regulations
we doubt plaintiff's duties as a technical writer/documenter could qualify for an
artistic professional exemption," the court said.<P>

The 10th Circuit ruled that the district court erred by granting Park City Group
summary judgment because issues of material fact remained pertaining to Bohn's
job duties. The appellate court reversed the lower court's decision and remanded
the case for trial. (<I>Bohn v. Park City Group, Inc.</I>, 10th Cir., No. 95-4086, 1996
U.S. App. LEXIS 22626) <P>

