<html>
<head>
<title>EEOC issues guide on coordinating ADA, workers' comp</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/able/ablehead.gif" alt="ADA Compliance Guide"></center>
<P>
<h2>EEOC issues guide on coordinating ADA, workers' comp</h2>


The EEOC issued new guidance in September on the ADA and workers' compensation laws, highlighting many
troublesome questions facing employers, including when they may refuse to return injured employees to
work, what they may ask and which reasonable accommodations they must provide after a work injury.
Throughout the guidance, the EEOC cautions employers that workers' compensation concerns and
determinations do not supersede ADA mandates.<P>

For example, workers' compensation costs may not be used to justify adverse employment actions against
individuals with disabilities, the EEOC asserts. But an employer may fire or refuse to hire a person who
would pose a direct threat. (The EEOC defines direct threat as posing a "significant risk of substantial harm
to the health or safety of the individual or others that cannot be eliminated or reduced by reasonable
accommodation.")<P>

"Where an employer refuses to hire a person because it assumes, correctly or incorrectly, that, because of
a disability, s/he poses merely some increased risk of occupational injury (and, therefore, increased
workers' compensation costs), the employer discriminates against that person on the basis of disability,"
the EEOC states.<P>

The EEOC also maintains that employers may not rely exclusively on a workers' compensation
determination that an employee has a permanent or total disability when deciding if an employee is a
qualified individual with a disability covered under the ADA. (Several courts have rejected the EEOC's
similar position that representations of total disability for purposes of receiving disability benefits does not
bar ADA coverage (see p. 9).)<P>

However, it also asserts that such a determination may be relevant in assessing whether a worker can
perform essential functions with or without reasonable accommodation or return to work without posing a
direct threat.<P>

An employer also may not require that an employee with a disability-related work injury be able to work
"full duty" in order to return if full duty includes marginal functions and the employee can perform all
essential functions with or without a reasonable accommodation.<P>

Furthermore, the employer, rather than a rehabilitation counselor, physician or other specialist, must
determine whether an employee poses a direct threat, the EEOC states. But an employer may consult with
such specialists about an employee's functional limitations, abilities and possible reasonable
accommodations.<P>

<H3>Permitted questions and exams</H3><P>

An employer may ask disability-related questions or require a medical examination of an injured employee
if the questions and exams are job-related and consistent with business necessity. "This requirement is met
where an employer reasonably believes that the occupational injury will impair the employee's ability to
perform essential job functions or raises legitimate concerns about direct threat," the EEOC states. <P>

But the questions and exams must solely concern the work injury and its effect on the employee's ability to
perform essential job functions without posing a direct threat. <P>

An employer also may ask disability-related questions or require a medical exam of a worker with an
occupational injury to ascertain the extent of its workers' compensation liability, as long as the questions
and exams are "consistent with the state law's intended purpose of determining an employee's eligibility for
workers' compensation benefits."<P>

And if an employee with an occupational injury asks for a reasonable accommodation, the employer may ask
for documentation if the need for accommodation is not obvious. <P>

However, the EEOC cautions, "while the employer may require documentation showing that the employee
has a covered disability and stating his/her functional limitations, it is not entitled to medical records that
are unnecessary to the request for reasonable accommodation."<P>

<H3>Reasonable accommodation</H3><P>

For those workers with disability-related work injuries, an employer must provide reasonable
accommodations; relying solely on workers' compensation laws may violate the ADA. For example, an
employer's reasonable accommodation duty is not satisfied by placing an injured worker in a workers'
compensation vocational rehabilitation program, the EEOC provides.<P>

An employer does not have to accommodate every employee with a work injury, because not all work
injuries are covered by the ADA. (The ADA defines "disability" as an impairment that substantially limits a
major life activity, record of such impairment or being regarded as having such an impairment.)<P>

But the ADA prohibits an employer from discharging covered, injured employees who are temporarily
unable to work where it would not impose an undue hardship to provide leave as a reasonable
accommodation. (In addition, under the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA), private and public sector
employers of 50 or more employees must provide up to 12 workweeks of unpaid job-protected leave to
eligible employees for certain specified family and medical reasons, including a serious health
condition.)<P>

And if leave would pose an undue hardship, the employer must consider whether it would cause an undue
hardship for the employee to temporarily fill a vacant, equivalent position for which he or she is qualified.
If an equivalent position is not available, the employer must look for a vacant position at a lower level. If no
such position is available, continued leave is not required.<P>

While an employer also must reallocate marginal job duties as a reasonable accommodation, it may not
reassign a worker with a disability-related job injury without first trying to accommodate the worker in
his or her original job. <P>

Such accommodations might include modifying equipment or offering a part-time work schedule.
"Reassignment should be considered only when accommodation within the employee's original position is not
possible or would impose an undue hardship," the EEOC states. <P>

However, if accommodation in the original position is not possible, the employee must be reassigned to an
equivalent vacant position if available (and lower- graded position if not), as long as he or she is qualified
for the vacant job and no undue hardship results. The employer does not have to create a new position,
create a light duty position or "bump" another employee (see p. 12).<P>

An employer may provide an accommodation that requires a worker to remain on the job even if he or she
requests leave under the ADA. <P>

However, discriminatory leave policies are prohibited. The EEOC states "if an employee with a
disability-related occupational injury does not request a reasonable accommodation, but simply requests
leave that is routinely granted to other employees (e.g., accrued paid leave or leave without pay), an
employer may not require him/her to remain on the job with some type of adjustment unless it also
requires employees without disabilities who request such leave to remain on the job with some type of
adjustment."<P>

Moreover, the FMLA prohibits employers from requiring employees qualifying for FMLA leave to remain on
the job with an adjustment, the EEOC notes.<P>

<H3>Light duty</H3><P>

Although employers do not have to create light duty positions, the EEOC states that "in some cases, the only
effective reasonable accommodation available for an individual with a disability may be similar or
equivalent to a light duty position. The employer would have to provide that reasonable accommodation
unless the employer can demonstrate that doing so would impose an undue hardship."<P>

For example, if a worker is injured off-the-job, an employer may deny a request to create a light duty
position, but must still reasonably accommodate the worker (including reassigning marginal functions),
potentially resulting in a restructured job that resembles light duty.<P>

Although the ADA does not require the creation of light duty positions, it does not prohibit employers from
"making a workplace modification that is not a required form of reasonable accommodation under the ADA
for an employee with an occupational injury in order to offset workers' compensation costs," the EEOC
provides.<P>

However, it warns that a policy of creating light duty jobs for occupationally injured employees is
prohibited if it has an adverse impact on a class of individuals with disabilities and there is not a
job-related reason consistent with business necessity for the policy.<P>

Further, an employer that reserves light duty positions for employees with occupational injuries must
consider reassigning employees with disabilities who are not occupationally injured to such jobs as a
reasonable accommodation, the EEOC maintains. But if an employer has only temporary light duty positions,
it does not have to provide a permanent light duty position for a worker with a disability-related
occupational injury.<P>

The EEOC's guidance is included in this month's supplement.<P><HR>

<H4>Tips: Ensure the confidentiality of medical records<P></H4>

<FONT SIZE="2">Employers must maintain in separate medical files all information obtained from post-offer medical
examinations and disability-related inquiries. This includes medical information on an applicant's or
employee's occupational injury or workers' compensation claim. The EEOC recommends that employers keep
medical files in a separate, locked cabinet apart from where personnel files are stored and designate who
can have access to the file.<P>

A file's information may not be disclosed, except to:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
		<LI>supervisors to inform them about necessary work restrictions or accommodations;<P>
	
		<LI>first aid and safety personnel, when appropriate, if the disability might require emergency treatment or procedures in case of fire or other evacuations; or<P>

		<LI>government officials investigating compliance with laws prohibiting discrimination based on disability.<P>
</UL>

An employer must keep medical information confidential even if someone is no longer an applicant or an
employee.<P>

Also, relevant information from a file may be disclosed to state workers' compensation offices or "second
injury" funds, and to insurance companies when they require a medical examination to provide health or life
insurance for employees.<P>

[Source: EEOC technical assistance manual.] <P></FONT>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/able/able.html"><img
src="/tpg/person/able/smallable.gif"  alt="Return to ADA Compliance Guide Home
Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [
ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
