<html> <title> Officials may be liable for recommending former employee</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/sink/sinkhead.gif" alt="Educator's Guide to Controlling Sexual Harassment">
<P>
<h2> School officials may be liable for recommending former employee who had history
of sexual misconduct</h2>
<body>
<P>
School authorities who recommended a former employee -- known to have engaged in
various types of sexual wrongdoing -- may be liable to a student enrolled at the
hiring school, the California Court of Appeal held Dec. 15. <P>

According to Randi W., a thirteen-year-old student of Livingston Middle School,
vice principal Robert Gadams "negligently and offensively touched, molested, and
engaged in sexual touching," while she was in his office. Prior to his employment
with Livingston Middle School, Gadams had been employed by various other school
districts from which he was allegedly forced to resign for sexual misconduct.<P>

Before he was hired by Livingston Middle School, Gadams obtained recommendations
from various individuals who worked for his former employers. Among these
individuals were Gilbert Rossette, an official in the Mendota School district,
where Gadams worked between 1985-1988; Richard Cole, an official of Tranquility
High School District and Golden Plains Unified School District, where Gadams was
employed between 1986-1990; and finally, Gary Rice and David J. Malcolm,
officials in the Muroc Joint Unified School District, where Gadams worked in or
around 1990 and 1991.<P>

While employed in the Mendota School District, Gadams allegedly was involved in
sexual misconduct with female students which, according to the complaint, was
known by Rossette. Despite this purported knowledge, in his recommendation of
Gadams, Rossette set out numerous positive aspects of Gadams' tenure in Mendota
and concluded that "I wouldn't hesitate to recommend Mr. Gadams for any
position!"<P>

Similarly, while employed by Golden Plains Unified School District, Gadams had
been the subject of various complaints by parents, which according to the
complaint, led to Gadams' "resigning under pressure from Golden Plains due to
sexual misconduct charges." Despite this situation, Cole recommended Gadams,
listing his various strong points as an instructor and administrator and stating
that "he would recommend him for almost any administrative position he wishes to
pursue."<P>

Gadams was also allegedly forced out of his next position, again for sexual
harassment of female students. Despite his alleged knowledge of this, David
Malcolm wrote of Gadams in his recommendation as "an upbeat, enthusiastic
administrator who relates well to the students" and who was "in large part"
responsible for the campus of the Boron Junior/Senior High School being "a safe,
orderly and clean environment for students and staff." Malcolm concluded that he
would recommend Gadams "for an assistant principalship or equivalent position
without reservation.<P>

Randi W. claims in her complaint that these recommendations were made "with
actual malice, corruption and actual fraud since these defendants knew the true
facts regarding Gadams and knew that an injury to a child by Gadams would
probably result." In accordance with this, Randi W. pursued theories of
negligence, negligent hiring, negligent misrepresentation, fraud, negligence per
se, and violation of Title IX. The lower court dismissed her complaint, ruling
that the facts alleged failed to establish that the above-named officials owed a
legal duty to her. Randi appealed to the California Court of Appeal.<P>

With respect to Randi's general negligence claim, the appeals court found that
there was no liability because the officials did not have a "special
relationship" with either Gadams or Randi at the time of the alleged molestation,
nor did they have any ability to control Gadams. Accordingly, the trial court's
ruling on this issue was affirmed. <P>

Similarly, the lower court did not err when it dismissed the "negligent hiring"
count, the court said, noting that it knew of no case that extended the negligent
hiring theory to a non-employing defendant. Nor did the lower court err when it
dismissed Randi's Title IX count, the court said. "Nothing in the language of
title IX . . . suggests that such a cause of action could extend to educational
institutions which have no direct relationship to the plaintiff," the court
wrote.<P>

However, with respect to the claims of negligent misrepresentation, fraud, and
negligence per se, the lower court erred when it dismissed Randi's complaint
without allowing her the right to amend her complaint so she could establish why
the officials owed any duty to her, the court ruled.<P>

<h3>Failure to disclose can equal misrepresentation</h3><P>

The court said that the failure to disclose certain information can constitute
misrepresentation and may also be interpreted as "the giving of false
information," as stated in California's tort law. While mere nondisclosure is
generally not actionable, quoting from <i>Rogers v. Warden</i>, 20 Cal.2d 286, 289
(1949), the court said that the law has long recognized that "although one may be
under no duty to speak as to a matter, if he undertakes to do so, either
voluntarily or in response to inquiries, he is bound not only to state truly what
he tells but also not to suppress or conceal any facts within his knowledge which
materially qualify those stated. If he speaks at all he must make a full and fair
disclosure." And, as stated in <i>Cicone v. URS Corp</i>., 183 Cal.App.3d 194, 201
(1986), "One who is asked for or volunteers information must be truthful, and the
telling of a half-truth calculated to deceive is fraud."<P>

Here, the recommendation letters were given to an educational placement office
and each made an unqualified recommendation for Gadams' employment in other
school positions, the court said. "In our opinion the facts allegedly known by
respondents, but not disclosed in the recommendation letters, 'materially
qualify' the facts disclosed about Gadams' conduct at the respondents' schools
and render the letters misleading half-truths," the court wrote. The court said
that under the circumstances as alleged here, California law protects third
parties, such as Randi. Accordingly, the court concluded that the officials owed
a duty to Randi not to negligently or intentionally misrepresent Gadams'
desirability to prospective employers. Thus, the facts as alleged in Randi's
complaint established an adequate duty to support both the negligent
misrepresentation and fraud counts, the court found. Further, California law
imposes on officials a duty to report known or reasonably suspected incidents of
child abuse. Because of this duty, the officials in this case had a mandatory
duty to report the acts committed by Gadams. Thus, Randi's claim of negligence
per se should not have been dismissed by the lower court without its granting her
leave to amend her complaint, the court ruled. (<i>Randi W. v. Livingston Union
School District</i>, Cal.Ct.App., No. F020849, Dec. 15, 1995) <P>


</body> 

