<HEAD>
<TITLE>Structuring Specialty Care Capitation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN=
bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<hr>
<center><H1>Specialty Capitation Manual:</H1>
<H2>Rate Setting, Evaluation and Implementation</H2></center>
<hr>

<H2>Structuring Specialty Care Capitation: Deciding Which Specialties to
Capitate to Maximize Savings</H2>
<H3>by John H. Straub</H3>
Managed care organization (MCO) administrators should not feel it is necessary
to capitate all of their specialty care provider networks just because it
is popular to capitate. Some of the best reimbursement strategies used by
MCOs capitate only 40 percent or less of specialty care providers. MCOs
should capitate specialty areas that produce the greatest savings with capitation
arrangements, and not all specialties are good candidates for utilization
savings.<BR>
<BR>
Specialty capitation should not be viewed as an &quot;all or nothing&quot;
proposition. There is no real advantage to capitating all the providers
in the network because some specialty practice areas cannot produce enough
utilization management savings to warrant capitation. These specialists
are better compensated through negotiated fee-for-service arrangements mutually
beneficial to both the MCO and the specialty care provider.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Careful Analysis Required</B><BR>
<BR>
In practice, capitation is neither desirable nor economically practical
when the need for a particular specialty service is limited to only a few
medical situations per year, especially when these incidences of illness
or episodes are not high-cost medical services and are short term. The decision
to capitate requires careful analysis of the network's overall utilization
experience and projection of future medical services. <BR>
<BR>
The types of medical episodes or diagnoses that are chronic - such as diabetes,
cardiac disease, or certain forms of cancer - are high maintenance and require
large doses of specialty care services. MCOs should review their utilization
experience, seeking out situations of high cost similar to those listed,
to begin the process of determining where medical utilization savings might
be created through capitation.<BR>
<BR>
Specialty capitation has grown in popularity because it has produced utilization
savings primarily from the viewpoint that specialists will find better ways
to diagnose and treat patients when they become responsible for the cost
of care under capitation risk contracts. Under the risk contract, the provider's
objective is to improve the patient's health more quickly without performing
a wide range of tests and treatments that produce only marginal results.
Using tests that look for &quot;outlier&quot; types of diagnoses are not
good candidates for front-line testing. Tests that identify the more common
diagnoses become the mode of practice under managed care.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Confusion Over Capitation's Role</B><BR>
<BR>
For many MCO administrators, health care providers, and specialists themselves,
there has been great confusion as to where capitation fits into the framework
of managed care. The greatest part of the confusion or misunderstanding
stems from the belief that managed care principles dictate that providers
must be reimburse through fully capitated contracts, and anything less is
not managed care. The other part of the myth is that capitation is managed
care and everything else, such as utilization management, quality assurance,
and provider access, are secondary to the development of a capitated reimbursement
system.<BR>
<BR>
This perception can be detrimental to the success of an MCO if the administrators
truly believe that profitability through decreased utilization and quality
will suddenly fall into place once all specialists are activated into a
fully capitated reimbursement system. Capitation cannot operate in a stand-alone
mode without the help of the other disciplines of managed care.<BR>
<BR>
The reality is that specialty care capitation is only one of the tools of
managed care, which, in combination with discounted fee-for-service arrangements
and other managed care tools, has the potential to create efficiency and
effectiveness within the provider network. Utilization management and quality
assurance combined with the appropriate provider reimbursement arrangement
create the total managed care environment.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Examine Several Variables</B><BR>
<BR>
MCO administrators must examine several variables to determine which network
specialists are good candidates for capitation and which specialists should
be compensated through a discounted fee schedule, or arrangement other than
capitation. If the variable analysis determine that no utilization savings
will be generated, the MCO will not capitate the specialist.<BR>
<BR>
The variables to examine in deciding which specialists should be capitated
include: 
<UL>
<LI>the frequency of utilization, 
<LI>the book of business being served, 
<LI>potential utilization savings, 
<LI>the supply of specialists, 
<LI>cost of treatment, and 
<LI>the types of diseases being treated. 
</UL>
Selecting the specialty care providers that will be capitated depends on
a careful analysis of all the above variables and their importance to the
MCO's service area.<BR>
<BR>
There is no one set of rules to dictate which group or type of specialists
can or cannot be capitated. Any specialty can be capitated. A good capitation
candidate will depend on the needs of the MCO seeking to contract for specialty
care services. Generally, subspecialists in narrowly defined fields will
not be considered good candidates for capitation, because little utilization
cost savings can be realized when the incidence of utilization is so low.<BR>
<B><BR>
Realizing Utilization Savings</B><BR>
<BR>
Utilization savings can be realized for both the MCO and the specialty care
provider in a number of ways. For the MCO, utilization savings can occur
when the specialty care provider follows established protocols set by the
MCO that suggest patterns of treatment to assist the patient in healing
faster or to prevent additional illness through preventive care practices.
An example of preventive care is to educate the MCO's members to initiate
exercise and dietary programs that may assist in keeping members out of
inpatient settings.<BR>
<BR>
Other utilization savings can be realized by the MCO when specialists reduce
unnecessary testing that does not fall under the specialist's capitation
arrangement. Reducing costs in areas of medical treatment not under the
responsibility of the capitation agreement sets up the potential for the
MCO to reward the specialist with incentive payments. MCOs have learned
that utilization savings increase dramatically when incentives represent
a major piece of the capitation reimbursement package. In some of the more
effective reimbursement plans, the incentives pay more than the monthly
per member per month capitation rates.<BR>
<BR>
Specialty care providers realize utilization savings when they reduce the
amount of unnecessary testing for which they are responsible under the terms
of the capitated contract. The fewer tests done means additional savings
to their practice. They also realize utilization savings when MCOs include
incentive plans that may pay bonuses for holding bed days per 1,000 below
a targeted amount.<BR>
<BR>
From the MCO's perspective, there is no economic advantage to enter into
a capitation agreement with certain specialty providers if there is little
or no demand for the specialist's services or if no utilization savings
can be realized. Reaching the conclusion that there will not be much demand
or savings from utilization savings for a given specialty service, however,
is not always a clear-cut decision. Predicting utilization frequency can
be difficult.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Decisions Based on Past Experience</B><BR>
<BR>
The MCO's decision to contract under capitation becomes even more difficult
in situations in which the membership is constantly growing and changing
along with the needs for different medical services. The MCO can never be
sure which specialists may be in demand from one year to the next. MCOs
will usually capitate for services that are most commonly needed in their
service areas based on past experience of incidence and regional projections
furnished by consulting actuaries.<BR>
<BR>
Studies of utilization practices also have assisted MCOs in determining
where savings can be realized in certain specialty practices. MCO utilization
management teams have shown that there are certain specialties that can
exercise greater utilization control than other specialty practices. MCOs
will target those specialties and offer capitation reimbursement plans combined
with incentive programs to reduce waste and realize medical savings in the
delivery of health care. [See <I>To Capitate or Not to Capitate - That Is
the Specialty</I> below.]<BR>
<BR>
Pediatric neurologists, as an example, probably would not be capitated in
a commercial book of business because their medical services are used infrequently
compared to the total medical services of the total patient or membership
base participating in the MCO. The need for a pediatric neurologist on a
full time or fully dedicated basis would not be that tremendous and the
utilization savings are generally not that significant under this type of
specialty. The MCO would therefore seek a specialist of this type outside
the network on the spot market or contract within the network on a discounted
fee-for-service arrangement.<BR>
<BR>
Under a Medicaid risk contract, however, it may be appropriate to capitate
a pediatric neurologist. The frequency of illness requiring the neurologist's
services may be greater than under a commercial plan, since the members
of most Medicaid programs are predominately children.<BR>
<BR>
MCOs should weigh all the variables to determine the most appropriate capitation
reimbursement package suitable to their demographic service area to produce
the best results in terms of profitability and quality of care.<BR>
<HR>
<H2><CENTER>To Capitate or Not to Capitate - That Is the Specialty</CENTER>
</H2>
Cost of service and the ability to control utilization play important roles
in the MCO's decision to capitate a particular specialty. The following
specialties are the best candidates for capitation, as they tend to be high
cost and offer the potential of increased savings through capitation agreements:
<UL>
<LI>allergy, 
<LI>cardiology, 
<LI>dermatology, 
<LI>gastroenterology 
<LI>general surgery, 
<LI>oncology, 
<LI>opthalmology, 
<LI>optometry, 
<LI>orthopedcs, 
<LI>otolaryngology, 
<LI>pathology, 
<LI>plastic surgery, 
<LI>psychiatry, 
<LI>radiology, and 
<LI>urology. 
</UL>
The following specialties tend to be lower cost or have fewer opportunities
to realize utilization savings and tend to be excluded from capitation agreements:
<UL>
<LI>anesthesiology, 
<LI>cardiac surgery, 
<LI>chiropractic care, 
<LI>endocrinology, 
<LI>hematology, 
<LI>nephrology, 
<LI>neurosurgery, 
<LI>obstetrics/gynecology, 
<LI>oral surgery, 
<LI>podiatry, and 
<LI>pulmonology. 
</UL>
The HMO Warren Surveys identify the following specialties as the ones most
often capitated: 
<UL>
<LI>allergy, 
<LI>cardiology, 
<LI>dermatology, 
<LI>general surgery, 
<LI>opthalmology, 
<LI>orthopedics, 
<LI>otolaryngology, 
<LI>psychiatry, 
<LI>radiology, and 
<LI>urology. 
</UL>
<HR><I>John H. Straub is a CPA and a financial consultant to the health
care industry. Mr. Straub also is an author of the </I>Specialty Capitation
Manual<I>.<BR>
</I><HR><BR>
