<html> <title>FDA Stalls in Finalizing Investigator Financial Disclosure
Rule</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/clin/clinhead.gif" alt="Guide to Good Clinical Practice">
<P>
<h2>FDA Stalls in Finalizing Investigator Financial Disclosure Rule</h2>
<body>

The FDA continues to face discordant objections of industry and academic

researchers over its proposed clinical investigator financial disclosure rule,

prompting some experts to question whether or not a final rule will be issued at

all. <p>

During a March 29 meeting, the FDA Science Committee sought further input from

interested parties, eliciting diverse objections within the research community,

particularly between industry and academic researchers. <p>

"I wouldn't be surprised if they don't go forward at all because of the

confusion and diversity of opinion on this issue," Marlene Tandy, director and

counsel at the Health Industry Manufacturers Association (HIMA) said during a

follow-up interview. Tandy believes the agency also has had to reconsider its

proposal because of the vast burden and complexity the agency itself would face

if the rule were implemented in its present form. <p>

"I think . . . they realize the proposed rule is too far out there," Tandy said.

"I am hoping that the FDA's management officers want the agency to go in a

different direction." <p>

<h3>Slow Progress </h3><p>

The FDA's path in issuing a final rule has meandered through two Science Board

meetings and one public hearing (held July 20, 1995) since the proposed

financial disclosure rule was published in the Sept. 22, 1994 <i>Federal

Register</i> (59 FR 48708, see App. III; "Industry Assails Sweeping Financial

Disclosure Rule," September 1995, p. 4). In addition to numerous testimonies,

the FDA received 47 comments on the proposed rule, many of which sharply

criticized the agency for imposing burdensome and unnecessary requirements. <p>

At the center of the debate for both the FDA and the research community is

whether or not a "threshold" for disclosure of financial interests should be

used, and, if so, how such information ought to be reported to the agency. Other

issues for researchers include what the agency will do with collected

information and how it will proceed in determining whether or not an "undue

influence" exists in a scientific study. <p>

As published, the proposed rule would oblige investigators to provide their

institutions with detailed information on equity interests that exceed $5,000 or

5 percent of the holdings of a publicly traded company sponsoring the research

(59 FR 48708, see App. II). This is a substantially lower threshold than that

used in a similar final rule of the Public Health Service (PHS), which

establishes a reporting requirement for equity interests or remuneration of at

least $10,000 (see 60 FR 35810, see App. V; "PHS, NSF Finalize Investigator

Disclosure Rules," September 1995," p. 6; ). The PHS rule requires only that

individual conflicts be reported internally before the grant award, while the

FDA proposed rule requires investigator certifications during the trial

selection process. <p>

<h3>Rescission Retreat </h3><p>

Although reportedly few details of the agency's progress were revealed at the

meeting, one positive determination made by the FDA is a decision not to

prohibit outright or require divestment of certain financial interests. An

agency background paper released by the Science Board states that the FDA has

"decided against" prohibiting any financial interests or requiring investigator

divestiture. <p>

"FDA concluded that such a prohibition would disproportionately and unfairly

penalize certain sponsors such as small device and biotechnology firms," the

backgrounder states. <p>

<h3>Industry Outcry </h3><p>

The signs of a more moderate approach at the FDA may reflect the vociferous

protests of industry groups, which have been concerned partly because the FDA

does not presently review any financial information of private U.S. firms. <p>

"This is a very tricky one and we are potentially impacted more than other

industries," Alan Goldhammer of the Biotechnology Industry Organization (BIO)

told the <i>Monthly Bulletin. </i><p>

"There are some forms of compensation that are a potential problem," Goldhammer

conceded, but he added that the rule, as proposed, would be far more burdensome

than necessary and likely would have a serious impact on start-up biotech firms.

<p>

Similarly, HIMA's Tandy said that device sponsors are concerned about an

overwhelming burden if the proposed rule is finalized in its present form. She

explained that the rule, if ever finalized, should be streamlined through the

use of a far higher threshold (of $25,000) and a simple "check-off" procedure to

indicate the presence of a potential conflict of interest. <p>

<h3>Mixed Academic Support </h3><p>

As compared to industry researchers, federally funded researchers appear to have

fewer reservations toward an FDA disclosure rule because they already are

subject to the PHS final rule. As a result, federal grantees are pushing for

harmonization of the FDA proposal and the PHS final rule. <p>

"We need a uniform federal system for conflict of interest," David Blake, M.D.,

of the American Association of Medical Colleges (AAMC), told the Monthly

Bulletin. Blake added that the proposed rule would create excessive burdens for

both researchers and the FDA, which would have little need for the reports in

most cases. <p>

"FDA has said that, in reality, they need this information only in a small

percentage of cases," he said. <p>

Blake explained that his organization, like HIMA, also favors a simple

"check-off" disclosure process whereby investigators would indicate whether or

not a financial interest exists. Blake proposed that if a financial interest

exists and the FDA determines that findings of a particular trial are unusually

favorable, then the agency would be able to request more detailed information,

evaluate the potential for bias, and weight their evaluation of the clinical

evidence accordingly. <p>

Blake also suggested that the FDA-proposed requirement for up-front, full

disclosure of equity interests above the threshold is problematic because the

FDA's intentions and internal procedures are not entirely clear. <p>

"FDA has never told us what they're going to do with this information," Blake

said. "It would be a great mistake for FDA reviewers to see this information and

then be biased in their review of the application." <p>

<h3>Threshold Debate </h3><p>

Like Tandy, Blake and other academicians also favor a higher disclosure

threshold.  <p>

"People have underestimated the size of this burden," Blake said. "The biggest

problem is to try to unburden the system by having a fairly high <i>de

minimus</i> value." <p>

Another area of agreement between academic and industry researchers appears to

exist in the timing of investigator disclosures. Although the FDA proposes that

companies submit certifications along with the new drug application (NDA), the

proposed rule also requires that these certifications be based on disclosures

obtained from investigators at the time they are selected for the clinical

trial. The PHS rule, in contrast, requires only that investigators submit a list

of potentially conflicting financial interests by the time the institution

submits its grant application. <p>

"I think it's clear that a 'just in time' regulation is more appropriate," Blake

said. <p>

<h3>FDA Disagrees </h3><p>

The FDA has issued no official indication of its intentions in revising the

proposed rule, but Office of Drug Evaluation 1 Director Robert Temple, M.D.,

indicated to the <i>Monthly Bulletin </i>that he believes the agency has a

legitimate purpose in pursuing the rule. Although Temple offered no predictions

as to the final content of the rule, he did say that there is a willingness to

consider revising the reporting threshold. <p>

However, Temple disagreed that the meeting represented diverse opinions on how

the disclosures should be implemented. <p>

"The people who testified at this meeting were not so far apart on this, I was

struck by that," Temple said.<p>

When asked whether or not the FDA is considering a rule that would harmonize

disclosure requirements with those of the PHS, Temple ruled out any possibility

of such an approach. <p>

"There's no way these two rules can be the same," he said. "The PHS and FDA

rules are completely different rules, with completely different functions. <p>

"People are missing the point Ñ we want to know if investigators have an

interest in the study," Temple added, explaining that detailed disclosures are

considered essential by the agency. "If we perceive that a person has a

substantial financial interest in the outcome then I have no doubts that we'll

ask about the particular concerns." <p>

<h3>Outlook </h3><p>

Although Temple's intransigence may suggest continued support for the financial

disclosure proposal within the agency, industry experts say that the agency's

course on the disclosure rule ultimately may reflect heavy congressional

pressure for deregulation.<p>

In fact, the FDA background statement notes "considerable" congressional

attention to the issue and concedes that major drug and device firms do not

participate in payment schemes that would trigger the type of disclosures set

forth in the FDA proposed rule. <p>

Accordingly, some experts suggest that it is questionable that the agency will

proceed with such a controversial measure while broad FDA reform proposals are

still pending in Congress. At press time, no publication date for a final rule

on financial disclosures had been announced.


</body> 

