<html>
<head>
<Title> Proposal Would Add Performance Test Option to UL 58 Steel Tank Standard</Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC = "/tpg/enviro/ustt/ustthead.gif" alt="Underground Storage Tank Guide"><P>


<h2> Proposal Would Add Performance Test Option to UL 58 Steel Tank
Standard</h2><P>

A proposal sent by Underwriters Laboratories (UL) May 30 to industry

representatives would change the method used to calculate the steel thickness

required by the organization's standard for underground storage tanks (USTs)

storing flammable and combustible liquids.<p>

In addition to incorporating the Roark equation for calculating steel thickness,

the proposed revisions to the 61-year-old UL 58, <i>Steel Underground Tanks for

Flammable and Combustible Liquids</i>, would add a performance test that would apply

to tank designs that do not fit the Roark equation.<p>

The proposal also invited comment on structural improvements in tank heads, head

joints, lift lugs and other areas. Many of these changes were proposed about a

year ago, but were never finalized.<p>

UL sent the bulletin soliciting comments on the proposal to its industry

advisory conference for UL 58; the industry advisory group for UL 1746, <i>External

Corrosion Protection Systems for Steel Underground Storage Tanks</i>; UL's fire and

casualty councils and subscribers to the UL 58 standard. Comments are due Sept.

3, and UL plans to finalize the revisions by the end of the year.<p>

In March, UL proposed revisions to UL 1746 that would incorporate the Roark

equation for calculating tank wall thickness and modify the current external

pressure test (see <i>Bulletin,</i> April 1996, p. 1). If the proposed revisions to

both standards are finalized, the revisions would make UL 58 similar to UL 1746

by eliminating the steel-gauge specifications table in favor of the Roark

equation and by adding the performance test. <p>

The revisions are a step toward the eventual merger of the two standards,

according to Jon Brannan, associate managing engineer with UL. UL expects the

demand for UL 58 steel tank designs that do not include external corrosion

protection to diminish in the next five to 10 years, making a separate standard

unnecessary, he said. Plain steel tanks would still be available as UL-listed

components under the combined standard if people wanted to purchase them and

apply their own external corrosion protection, he said.<p>

<h3>Reason for the Changes</h3><p>

The current UL 1746 allows the manufacture of tanks with walls of thinner steel

than those allowed under the current UL 58. These reduced wall thickness (RWT)

tanks "do not provide a sufficient factor of safety to withstand the external

pressure USTs experience during service, particularly with marginal quality

installations and with the use of poor backfill," according to the Steel Tank

Institute (STI). <p>

STI proposed that UL change the shell thickness specifications of both standards

because STI "became aware of [RWT] tanks which were alleged to have buckled in

service, or during integrity testing," according to an article in the STI

newsletter, <i>Tank Talk</i>. STI specifications do not allow RWT tanks, according to

STI's Lorri Grainawi.<p>

The revisions to UL 1746 were prompted by industry concerns, Brannan said, but

"there have been no UST failures as the result of a deficiency in the UL 1746

standard." In addition, adding a performance test to UL 58 will allow

opportunities for innovative tank designs, he said.<p>

<h3>The Roark Equation</h3><p>

Leslie Scott, president of Trusco Tank Inc., said the proposal is better than

the old fabrication standard because the Roark equation will take into account

the length, diameter and burial depth of each tank. Considering a tank's

configuration when determining structural requirements will make the degree of

safety more consistent among the various UL 58-listed tanks, he said. Because

the current UL 58 categorizes tanks by diameter, some shorter tanks were built

stronger than they needed to be, he said. Trusco manufactures tanks under both

UL 58 and UL 1746.<p>

Scott criticized the proposal for not specifying how the Roark equation should

be applied in certain situations, such as when a tank has stiffeners or

bulkheads. Although the proposal allows a 25 percent increase in tank length if

a stiffener is added at the tank's midpoint, it does not address the use of a

bulkhead at the midpoint or an off-center stiffener, Scott said. Wayne Geyer of

STI explained that the proposal addresses bulkheads by treating them as

stiffeners, despite differences in their impact on the structural strength 

of the tank.<p>

In addition, the proposal allows a 40 percent increase if two stiffeners are

added at one-third points in 

the tank, but there are many other configurations, Scott said. Trusco builds

multi-compartment tanks, he noted.<p>

The performance test was proposed, in part, to address potential design

variations that may not be covered by the equation, Brannan said.<p>

Sullivan D. Curran of the Fiberglass Tank and Pipe Institute also expressed

concerns about relying solely on the Roark equation as proposed. "While the

Roark equation may be used to compute the standard steel plate thickness for a

'simply supported plate,' it was not derived ... to be used to determine the

allowable thickness for a 'supported plate' of common construction materials,

including steel," Curran said.<p>

Geyer noted that STI sponsored extensive testing to verify the applicability of

the Roark equation before proposing that UL incorporate it into the

standards.<p>

Curran also noted that the proposal does not include references to support the

factors used by UL for Modulus of Elasticity of Steel and Poisson's Ratio. The

factors used in the proposal differ from those used in several designer

handbooks and other standards and would allow the use of thinner steel, he

said.<p>

Institute members support the steel tank industry's efforts to assist UL in

developing valid tank standards and maintaining the credibility of the UL label,

Curran said. Institute members manufacture "virtually all" of the UL-listed

fiberglass USTs, he added.<p>

<h3>The New Performance Test</h3><p>

The performance test in the UL 58 proposal is the same  test proposed for UL

1746, Brannan said. The external pressure test would require that the tank

withstand burial in at least five feet of water for one hour. The proposed test

is different from the test now used under UL 1746, in which the tank is

supported by backfill.<p>

STI believes that the proposed test is superior to the current version. It is

not good engineering practice to rely too heavily on backfill for the tank's

structural integrity because the type, compaction and moisture content of

backfill can vary substantially, STI said. Using water instead of backfill makes

the test more consistent and repeatable, Grainawi said.<p>

However, STI believes that standards should rely on engineering calculations

like the Roark equation when possible, reserving performance tests for cases

when the equations are not applicable. "It is far more important to base

requirements on engineering design calculations rather than on performance

tests," STI said. This philosophy is consistent with structural standards

developed by other organizations, STI noted.<p>

Curran favored a switch from a fabrication guideline to a performance standard,

but not the "either-or" approach that was proposed. Curran questioned the

rationale for changing the UL 1746 performance test, noting that the current

test has been used for 30 years in other UST standards. <p>

Improper installation and backfill should be addressed by environmental

regulations, code requirements and standard industry practices, Curran said.

However, Geyer noted that in actual practice, local code officials may lack the

training and resources to fully implement these requirements.<p>

<hr>
