<html> <title> Court applies Title VII to Student's Title IX claim</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/sink/sinkhead.gif" alt="Educator's Guide to Controlling Sexual Harassment">
<P>
<h2> Court applies Title VII hostile environment theory to Student's Title IX
claim</h2>
<body>
<P>
<b><i>Does a school district have a duty to protect students from sexual
harassment by their peers?</i></b><P>

Although a school district does not have a constitutional duty to take
affirmative action to prevent sexual harassment by students, the U.S. District
Court for Western Missouri ruled that such a duty may arise under Title IX.<P>

Jennifer Bosley, a minor student in the Kearney R-1 School District, complained
that she was sexually harassed by other students while riding the school buses.
Specifically, she complained that while on the bus, students sang sexually
inappropriate songs, a boy hit her on her bottom, another boy rubbed himself and
took his shirt off and brushed up against some of the girls, a boy accused
Jennifer of being a homosexual, and another boy claimed that Jennifer was having
sex with a frog and that she had AIDS.<P>

After all of these incidents occurred, Jennifer's mother complained to the school
officials, including the superintendent, the assistant superintendent, the
principal of Jennifer's school, and the principal of Kearney Intermediate School.
After concluding that no satisfactory action had been taken by the school
district, Mrs. Bosley removed her children from the school district. <P>

Ultimately, Mrs. Bosley brought suit against the school district under 42 U.S.C.
1983 and 20 U.S.C. 1681. Specifically, it was alleged that the school district
(1) violated Jennifer's constitutional rights to privacy, substantive due
process, equal protection and other constitutional rights; (2) failed to fulfill
its duty to stop inappropriate sexual harassment and thereby intentionally
discriminated against Jennifer by causing her to be excluded from, and denying
her the benefits of, a federally funded educational program; (3) negligently
failed to protect students from sexual harassment; and (4) breached a duty
arising from the school/student relationship the district had with Jennifer --
specifically the duty to protect Jennifer and provide her a place of safety. In
counts five, six and seven, Mrs. Bosley alleged claims on behalf of herself for
loss of services and medical expenses, for loss of consortium, and for
slander.<P>

In rejecting most of these claims before trial, the court said that, except in
certain limited circumstances, "state and local governmental entities have no
duty under the substantive component of the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth
Amendment to protect the life, liberty and property of its citizens from private
actors." Circumstances where such a duty arises include situations where the
state takes a person into custody and holds her there against her will -- such as
where an individual has been incarcerated or involuntarily committed to a mental
hospital. In these situations, a state is constitutionally required to provide
adequate food, shelter, clothing, and medical care, and in addition, must provide
those in its custody reasonable safety from themselves and others, including
private actors.<P>

The court found that the case at hand was not comparable to the above situations.
Here, Jennifer Bosley was not taken into custody by the school district and held
against her will. Rather, she was simply a student enrolled in the district's
schools, the court said. The fact that her mother removed her from the school
district indicates that she could have done this at an earlier time and "was not
wholly dependent on the school district to protect her daughter," the court
added. <P>

Thus, the court concluded that Bosley's assertion of a substantive due process
violation under &#167;1983 must fail as a matter of law because "compulsory
school attendance does not create the custodial relationship necessary to impose
constitutional liability on the defendant school district for failing to protect
Jennifer Bosley against alleged sexual harassment by her fellow students."
Further, the court said that it could not conclude that the school district
treated Bosley differently from the male students in the same or similar
circumstances, thus, it said her equal protection claims under &#167;1983 must
fail as well.<P>

The court further concluded that sovereign immunity barred Bosley's claims of
negligence and breach of a duty owed to her by the school district by reason of a
special relationship between schools and their students. Because the underlying
claim cannot survive summary judgment for the school district, Mrs. Bosley can
have no derivative claim for loss of services and medical expenses, the court
said. Under Missouri law, Mrs. Bosley cannot recover for loss of consortium.
Finally, the court dismissed Mrs. Bosley's claim of slander for failure to plead
the facts of her claim with particularity. <P>

<h3>Hostile environment under Title IX</h3><P>

However, with respect to the allegations brought under Title IX, the court denied
the school district's motion for summary judgment and allowed Bosley's claim to
go forward. Relying on the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in <i>Franklin v. Gwinnett
County Public Schools</i>, 503 U.S. 60 (1992), the court said that Title VII law
provides standards for enforcing the anti-discrimination provisions of Title IX.
Further, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission's guidelines instruct
agencies to consider Title VII standards when determining whether an employer has
violated Title IX, the court said. Finally, the Office for Civil Rights uses
Title VII's hostile environment standard when determining whether an educational
institution has failed to take proper remedial action when dealing with
student-to-student sexual harassment.<P>

Thus, the court found that Title VII principles should be used to determine
whether there was intentional discrimination under Title IX. Hostile environment
sexual harassment is actionable when it is sufficiently patterned and pervasive,
the court said. Quoting from <i>Harris v. Forklift Systems, Inc</i>., 114 S.Ct. 367
(1993), the court said that in making this determination, the adjudicator must
consider "the frequency of the discriminatory conduct; its severity; whether it
is physically threatening or humiliating, or a mere offensive utterance; and
whether it unreasonably interferes with an employee's work performance." <P>

To impute conduct to an employer where the claim involves harassment by peers, it
must be established that the employer knew or should have known of the hostile
environment and took insufficient remedial action, the court added.<P>

Thus, to establish a claim against a school district in cases of
student-to-student harassment, it must be shown that "(1) the plaintiff was
subjected to unwelcome sexual harassment; (2) the harassment was based on sex;
(3) the harassment occurred during the plaintiff's participation in an
educational program or activity receiving federal financial assistance; and (4)
the school district knew of the harassment and intentionally failed to take
proper remedial action."<P>

"Once a school district becomes aware of sexual harassment, it must promptly take
remedial action which is reasonably calculated to end the harassment," the court
concluded. The court found that based on the allegations presented by Bosley,
there were genuine issues for trial. Further, the court concluded that the school
district had ample notice of its potential liability for damages when it failed
to take adequate remedial actions to prevent the continued harassment of Bosley.
(<i>Bosley v. Kearney R-1 School District</i>, W.D. Mo., No. 93-0759-CV-W-9, Oct. 19,
1995) 

</body> 

