<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What MCOs Need to Know About Medicare</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/pattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif"><BR>
<HR>
<H1><CENTER>Medicare Managed Care Manual</CENTER></H1>
<HR>
<H2>What MCOs Need to Know About Medicare</H2>

<H3>EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW: PART ONE OF TWO</H3>
Not only is the marketing of a Medicare risk contract difficult because
of the scrutiny with which the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA)
examines a managed care organization's material, but often MCOs may not
understand the unique needs and characteristics of senior consumers.<BR>
<BR>
Today's senior is a financially savvy, sophisticated consumer who sees himself
or herself as an active player, not as someone on the sidelines in a rocking
chair, according to one marketing expert. <BR>
<BR>
In Part I of this exclusive interview, Thomas Hayes, senior vice president
and director of marketing services for The Senior Network, Inc., based in
Stamford, CT, offers managed care organizations (MCOs) insights into the
unique characteristics of marketing risk contracts to seniors, specific
considerations in marketing to senior women, the effect of the baby boom
population on marketing risk contracts, and strategies on working with HCFA.<BR>
<HR><B><I>Bulletin: </I></B>What are some of the unique characteristics
of marketing a Medicare managed care plan?<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Hayes:</I></B> Compared with marketing other products, one of the
most unique characteristics of marketing managed care is that many seniors
have a strong bias against the product itself. This makes marketing an uphill
battle because the product already starts with a strike against it.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, unlike most products and services, such as a detergent or soap,
the physical connection between an MCO and the senior is tenuous. After
enrollment, a senior may never interact with the MCO for extended periods
of time. This lack of contact also places an added burden on the marketing
material (and telemarketers) because the material must forge a link between
the MCO and the senior. <BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Bulletin: </I></B>Demographically, a significant percentage of Medicare
beneficiaries are women. How would you characterize today's senior woman?<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Hayes:</I></B> Today's senior woman, between the ages of 65 and 74,
is an extremely sophisticated consumer. She also is financially savvy, but
what I believe distinguishes her most is that she is, at this stage in her
life, able to turn her attention toward herself. To illustrate what I mean,
in one survey we did, senior women said that they were now able to take
a bath instead of a shower. It is not that the senior woman wants to see
herself as rocking her life away in a chair, but that, having done for others,
it is now all right to do for herself. <BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Bulletin: </I></B>What can a marketing piece do to reach this segment
of the population?<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Hayes:</I></B> To reach senior women, I believe it is necessary to
portray them as busy. I think it is a mistake to show a senior sitting down
and reading a book because that is not how they see themselves. It's not
necessary to show them mountain biking or hang gliding, but it is crucial
to show them doing something - jogging, taking a hike with their grandkids
- an activity that shows them physically able to participate in life.<BR>
<BR>
Interestingly, we have found that men often are an easier sell for managed
care products. As a group, men show less identification with a particular
physician, and are more willing to try something new if it will reduce their
medical expenses.<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Bulletin: </I></B>Do you foresee major changes in the &quot;average&quot;
Medicare beneficiary as more baby boomers become eligible for benefits?
What will these changes entail in terms of marketing?<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Hayes: </I></B>I believe that attention focused on the baby boomers
as an attitude rather than a demographic segment is overblown, especially
by the media and in advertising. <BR>
<BR>
There are substantial differences, for example, between a person born in
1946 at the start of the boom, and one born in 1964, at the boom's end.
Certainly, I see members of the baby boom generation, as they become eligible
for Medicare, exerting force on the market, but it is a force through numbers,
rather than through attitude. More importantly, I think it is important
to understand that their entrance into Medicare is still 15 to 20 years
away, and that the current population of seniors has needs that must be
addressed, especially if an MCO wants to be in existence in the year 2013.<BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Bulletin: </I></B>What are the three most important things that HCFA
looks for in examining marketing material? <BR>
<BR>
<B><I>Hayes: </I></B>The three crucial things we have found to be true in
working with HCFA on marketing material are: 
<UL>
<LI>a recognition of the firm rules that HCFA has issued, for instance regarding
lock-in provisions; 
<LI>clarity of communication, that is, a senior should have no difficulty
at all understanding the rules laid out in the marketing material; and 
<LI>tonality, which means that the material should balance communication
and interest in making the plan's design understandable and being a sales
tool. 
</UL>
One thing that we have found in working with HCFA is that there is a variance
across the country, not only in terms of process, for instance in approval
of marketing material, but even in terms of actual wordings at times, with
certain phrases being unquestioned in some parts of the country, while in
others the same phrasings have caused difficulty. <BR>
<BR>
A related development that we are seeing more recently is in state insurance
commissions wanting to see marketing material and becoming involved in the
approval process with regard to marketing material. I foresee these commissions
as becoming more and more involved in the marketing process as managed care
becomes more prevalent, and this will add another regulatory hurdle that
an MCO must overcome to market its plans. n<BR>
<BR>
Part II of the interview will focus on the role of telemarketing in offering
a risk contract, what to look for in choosing an outside marketing firm,
and how to maximize the relationship between an MCO and a marketing firm.
Part II will appear in next month's <I>Bulletin</I>. <BR>
<HR>

