<HTML>
<TITLE>
Major Implications for RCRA Corrective Action in EPA Policy Statement</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/fixx/fixxhead.gif" ALIGN=top></center>

<H2>Major Implications for RCRA Corrective Action in EPA Policy Statement</h2>
<BODY>

<P>
<I>By David P. Flynn, Esq.<BR>
Phillips, Lytle, Hitchcock, Blaine &amp; Huber</I><P>
<P>
The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) recently 
issued a &quot;policy statement&quot; in the <I>Federal 
Register</I> (60 F.R. 53, (3/20/95)) that has major implications 
for the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) 
corrective action program and for facilities subject 
to both Superfund and RCRA jurisdiction.<P>

Historically, it has not been clear which program, the 
Comprehensive Environmental Response Compensation and 
Liability Act (CERCLA, or &quot;Superfund&quot;) or 
RCRA (or a mixture of both) would be relevant to the 
investigation and remediation of a site that met the 
criteria for both programs.  With this &quot;policy 
statement,&quot; EPA has indicated that in such a set 
of circumstances, the RCRA program can take the lead 
in framing the investigative and remediation requirements 
for such sites.<P>

EPA states in the policy statement that it is agency 
policy to delete RCRA facilities from the National 
Priorities List before an ongoing cleanup is complete 
if the site will be &quot;adequately addressed&quot; 
in the RCRA corrective action program under an existing 
RCRA permit or RCRA order.  In addition, the agency 
will &quot;defer&quot; from listing a site on the National 
Priorities List (NPL) if there is a mechanism in place 
to ensure that the investigative and remedial needs 
will be addressed under the RCRA corrective action 
program.<P>

The agency has identified several reasons for this policy. 
First, EPA states that this deletion/deferral policy 
will &quot;free CERCLA's oversight resources for use 
in situations where another authority is not available.&quot; 
This justification may evidence EPA's desire to speed 
up the Superfund remediation process as well as reduce 
the number of sites on the NPL by moving sites into 
the RCRA program, which would also would allow a number 
of sites to be delegated to those states that have 
authorized corrective action programs.<P>

Another reason stated for the deletion/deferral policy 
is to &quot;avoid possible duplication of effort and 
the need for an owner/operator to follow more than 
one set of regulatory procedures.&quot;  From this 
stated justification it appears that this policy has 
been driven, at least in part, by programmatic differences 
and conflicts within the agency at sites that can be 
considered both a CERCLA and RCRA site.  In the past, 
at least, the agency has not been troubled by the burden 
of duplication of effort on the regulated community.<P>

EPA has enumerated several factors or criteria that 
must be considered in a situation where a site is being 
considered for &quot;deletion&quot; from the NPL, and 
the remedial program being deferred to the RCRA program. 
If there is &quot;uncertainty&quot; as to whether 
the criteria have been met, deletion of an NPL site 
generally will be inappropriate.  The deletion factors 
set out in the policy statement include:<P>

<OL>
<LI>If evaluated under EPA's current policy, the site 
would be eligible for a deferral (<I>i.e.</I> would not be 
included on the NPL list);<BR>

<LI>The site is currently being addressed by RCRA corrective 
action authorities under an existing enforceable order 
or permit that contains corrective action requirements;<BR>

<LI>Response under RCRA is progressing adequately; and 
<BR>

<LI>Deletion would not disrupt an ongoing CERCLA response 
action.<P>
</OL>
There are several scenarios where the ability to delete 
or defer a site from NPL listing, and proceeding under 
the RCRA program, may be beneficial to a facility owner/operator.<P>

First, to the extent that portions of a site would be 
considered discrete solid waste management units or 
corrective action management units <I>and</I> such areas are 
not currently accessible due to current operations, 
the investigation and remediation of those areas under 
the RCRA corrective action program may be deferred 
until such time as active use ceases or the areas otherwise 
become &quot;accessible.&quot;<P>

Second, the goals and objectives of the remedial program 
could be more advantageous to a facility owner or operator 
under the RCRA corrective action program.  Oftentimes, 
the RCRA program will look at the facility boundary 
as the &quot;point of compliance&quot; for exposure 
purposes at an active facility, and determine cleanup 
objectives on that basis. Conversely, the CERCLA program 
often requires that a remedy meet stringent cleanup 
requirements at an<I>y point</I> at or beneath the site.  
This difference could have a multi-million dollar impact 
on the cost of the investigation and remedial program 
for a facility.<p>

There are costs and benefits to this EPA policy.  A 
facility owner affected by this policy will have to 
evaluate, on a case-by-case basis, whether it makes 
sense to seek deletion of an existing NPL site or attempt 
to defer the listing of other sites, and proceed under 
the RCRA corrective action program.<P>

</BODY>
<foot>

