<html> <title> Student's Sexual Harassment Claims Dismissed As Untimely </title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/sink/sinkhead.gif" alt="Educator's Guide to Controlling Sexual Harassment">
<P>
<h2> Student's Sexual Harassment Claims Dismissed As Untimely </h2>
<body>

A student seeking monetary damages from a school district after claiming she was
sexually harassed by a temporary school employee failed to file her complaint on
time, Louisiana's 4th Circuit Court of Appeal ruled recently. The appellate
ruling affirms a decision by a district court dismissing the complaint.<P>

The action was brought by Vertis Bowers on behalf of her daughter Krishell, an
elementary school student. The claim stemmed from an incident that took place on
Nov. 6, 1991, in which a group of several students, including Krishell, reported
to their principal that their substitute teacher, Alvin Pierre, had "touched them
inappropriately, namely, fondled their breasts," according to the court.<P>

After learning of the alleged incident, the school principal contacted the police
department, and the teacher was arrested for "sexual misconduct." The principal
testified that the teacher did not return to work after his arrest.<P>

On the date of the incident, a detective was called to the school to investigate
the alleged sexual misconduct. At that time, the detective took Krishell's
statement and gave her a copy of his business card. The next day, he spoke to
Krishell's mother, he said, to discuss her daughter's statement to him regarding
the alleged misconduct.<P>

Bowers filed her sexual harassment complaint against the school district on Jan.
6, 1993, more than a year after the alleged incident took place. She sought
recovery in the form of damages from the school under Article 2315 of the
Louisiana Civil Code, a statute which provides that when an individual is harmed,
the responsible party is liable for reparations.<P>

<h3>Knowledge of the Abuse</h3>

On Oct. 19, 1994, the school district filed a motion asserting that due to
Bowers' long silence on the issue (during which time she did not urge her claim),
her claim was not valid. In response, Bowers submitted an amended petition
defending her failure to submit the claim more quickly. A Louisiana district
court granted the school's motion, and Bowers appealed.<P>

According to Bowers' amended petition, the teacher had threatened the students he
molested and told them not to tell anyone of his improper actions. This fact, the
petition said, "combined with the traumatic results of the molestation, prevented
Krishell from talking about [the incident] with her mother."<P>

The court learned that through communication with both the detective and the
school principal, Bowers had been informed in 1991 that Pierre had sexually
abused students at the school, including her daughter. In her petition, however,
Bowers claimed she did not learn "in any substantial way" of the <i>extent</i> of
the abuse or the "forms of the abuse" until the summer of 1992. In fact, she said
that until that time, she had known only that "some sexual violation(s) had
occurred."<P>

The plaintiff also argued that Krishell had never shared with her mother all the
details of the misconduct, a fact that Bowers attributed to the "psychological
and emotional damage [the child] suffered." Krishell "could not and did not
convey" the facts of the abuse to her mother, the petition said. Bowers said that
she got some information from her daughter about a year after the incident.<P>

The court heard testimony indicating that during the period of more than a year
between the alleged abuse of her daughter and the filing of her complaint, Bowers
did not take any action to withdraw her daughter from the school.<P>

<h3>The Court's Reasoning</h3>

Bowers maintained that the district court, in dismissing her petition, had failed
to apply the doctrine of <i>contra non valentem,</i> which holds that a legal
action cannot be time-barred if an individual is <i>unable</i> to bring the
action. The plaintiff also maintained that in cases of child molestation, the
deadline for filing a claim is "suspended until the child victim's parents learn
of the abuse, the extent of the abuse and the various forms of the abuse."<P>

The appellate court countered that the district court <i>had</i> applied the
doctrine of <i>contra non valentem,</i> and that the deadline for filing the
claim had been properly considered. Bowers admitted that on Nov. 6, she had known
that her daughter had been molested and that the molestation included "fondling
of the breast," the court said. The fact that she failed to find out any further
details was "her own fault."<P>

The court found that to learn more about the abuse, Bowers could have brought her
daughter to counseling, obtained a copy of the police report on the incident, or
actually gone to the school to discuss it with the principal. (Bowers claimed
that she had tried unsuccessfully to contact the principal by leaving phone
messages for her.)<P>

If Bowers felt unable to do these things, the court said, she could have "at the
very least immediately consulted a lawyer." Citing a precedent case, the court
said that a plaintiff is "deemed to know that which he could have learned from
reasonable diligence."<P>

According to the court, <i>contra non valentem</i> only suspends a deadline for
filing a claim until a plaintiff has a "reasonable basis to pursue a claim." In
this case, this basis for action existed as of Nov. 6, 1991, the court
concluded.<P>

Because the complaint was not filed on time, the appeals court affirmed the
district court's decision to dismiss the claim. (<i>Bowers v. Orleans Parish
School Board,</i> La. Ct. App., 4th Cir., No. 95-CA-2530, May 29, 1996)

</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/sink/sink.html"><img
src="/tpg/person/sink/smallsink.gif" alt="Back to Educator's Guide to Controlling Sexual Harassment Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
