<html> <title>Hospitals Prevail in Device Medicare Suit</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/clin/clinhead.gif" alt="Guide to Good Clinical Practice">
<P>
<h2> Hospitals Prevail in Device Medicare Suit </h2>
<body><p>
Certain government restrictions prohibiting Medicare reimbursement for

investigational devices were ruled invalid as part of a recent summary judgment

in favor of 25 research hospitals in the U.S. District Court for the District of

California, Western Division (<i>Cedars Sinai Medical Center, et al. v. Donna

Shalala, No. CV-95-2902)</i>.<p>

The April 8 court ruling is considered a pivotal victory for the hospitals,

which faced potential investigations and prosecutorial action by the Inspector

General (IG) of the Department of Health and Human Services for having accepted

reimbursement for investigational devices between 1986 and 1994.<p>

At issue in the case is Health Care Finance Administration's (HCFA's)

retroactive enforcement of an informal 1986 Medicare Manual Instruction, which

originally was issued without notice-and-comment rulemaking, as required by the

Administrative Procedures Act (APA). <p>

Although HCFA continued to reimburse hospitals for investigational devices for

several years despite the 1986 instruction, the agency began to halt the

payments and seek remuneration from some hospitals after formalizing the policy

in August of 1994. However, by then the IG already had subpoenaed 132 research

hospitals, including the 25 plaintiff hospitals.<p>

<h3>HCFA Confusion</h3><p>

According to one of the plaintiffs' attorneys, Robert A. Klein, the 25 hospitals

were concerned that if left unchallenged, the IG would attempt to retroactively

disallow the Medicare charges, and even seek penalties under alleged deviations

from Medicare fraud and abuse rules. <p>

Klein also told the <i>Monthly Bulletin </i>that he believed his client had

cause for concern, in light of HCFA's history in prior cases of retroactively

penalizing hospitals for reimbursement issues that arose from confusing or

improperly implemented policies. <p>

An April 12 release by the American Association of Medical Colleges states that

a number of institutions ceased device clinical trials as a result of the 1994

IG investigation. More recently, in 1996, HCFA's Seattle Regional Office

requested additional documentation and began reviewing the subpoenaed records of

nine hospitals, which was expected to result in recoupment of payments for

alleged overpayments relating to the IDEs.<p>

<h3>1986 Instruction</h3><p>

The HCFA policy at issue is contained in a 1986 Medicare Manual Instruction

which states that unapproved devices are "considered investigational" by

Medicare and are not "reasonable and necessary" for the diagnosis or treatment

of disease.<p>

Prior to 1986, intermediaries determined reimbursement on a case-by-case basis,

in order to determine whether or not a treatment was "reasonable and necessary."

This practice continued despite the 1986 instruction, until HCFA issued a "blue

book" memorandum in August 1994, reiterating the 1986 policy.<p>

Subsequently, in 1995, HCFA issued a formal rule partially reversing this policy

and allowing reimbursement for "non-experimental" IDE devices (see "Medicare to

Cover Certain IDE Devices," November 1995, p. 6).<p>

However, research hospitals that received reimbursements for investigational

devices during the time period at issue -- from 1986 through 1994 -- could be

held responsible for returning these funds and even assessed penalties if HCFA

were allowed to treat the 1986 instruction as a binding regulation.<p>

<h3>Procedural Victory</h3><p>

Although the government contended in its defense that the 1986 instruction was

merely interpretive of the Medicare statute (42 U.S.C. &#167;1395hh(a)(2)), the

plaintiff hospitals argued successfully that the instruction was a substantive

rule subject to full rulemaking procedures under the APA. <p>

Because HCFA did not follow APA rulemaking procedures, the court ruled that

Medicare Hospital Manual section 260.1, Medicare Intermediary Manual section

3151.1 and Medicare Carriers Manual section 2303.1 are invalid. Although the

decision pertains only to the 25 plaintiff hospitals, it could serve as an

important precedent for research hospitals that obtained Medicare reimbursement

for treatments involving IDEs from 1986 through 1994.<p>

Sources familiar with the case said that a government appeal of the decision may

be likely, but at press time, no such appeal had been announced.<p>

<hr><p>

<p>

<h4><center>IDE Reimbursement Time Line</h4></center><p>

<font size=-1>Listed below are the major events in FDA and Health Care Finance

Administration (HCFA) policy preceding the recent court decision

(<i>Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, et al. v. Donna Shalala, No.

CV-95-2902)</i>.<p>

<b>July 1986</b>: Medicare Hospital Manual section 260.1 is added, disallowing

reimbursement for medical devices "not approved for marketing."<p>

<b>August 1986 - July 1994</b>: Despite the 1986 instruction, Medicare fiscal

intermediaries continue to reimburse services involving investigational devices.

<p>

<b>January 1994</b>: The Office of Inspector General of the Department of Health

and Human Services issues subpoenas to 132 research hospitals seeking patient

records involving the use of unapproved medical devices. <p>

<b>August 1994</b>: HCFA issues a memo reiterating its policy on coverage of

unapproved investigational devices, and intermediaries begin to enforce the 1986

instruction.<p>

<b>May 1, 1995</b>: 25 of the subpoenaed hospitals file a complaint for

declaratory and injunctive relief, alleging that the 1986 instruction is a

substantive regulation, unlawfully promulgated outside of the Administrative

Procedures Act. <p>

<b>November 1995</b>: HCFA formally issues regulations allowing for

reimbursement of certain "nonexperimental" (Category B) IDE devices. Other,

"experimental" (Category A) devices are deemed not reimbursable.<p>

<b>April 8, 1996</b>: U.S. District Court for the District of California,

Western Division, issues a summary judgment in favor of plaintiffs,

<i>Cedars-Sinai, et al.</i>,  finding that the 1986 Medicare Hospital Manual

section 260.1 is invalid.</font> <p>


</body> 

