<html> <HEAD><TITLE>Draft California Permit Takes a 'Common Sense' Approach</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif>
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/strm/strmhead.gif" alt="Stormwater Permit
Manual"></center></IMG><P>



<H2>Draft California Permit Takes a 'Common Sense' Approach</H2>

<body><p>

The California State Water Resources Control Board (SWRCB) has extended until

Dec. 1 the deadline for members of industrial monitoring groups to submit group

monitoring plans. Sampling and monitoring requirements for all industrial

stormwater permittees also are postponed until Dec. 1.<p>

In addition, the board is circulating a new draft of the state's next industrial

general permit. The revised draft differs significantly from the original

permit, which expired Nov. 17.<p>

SWRCB had announced in July that deadlines for monitoring groups were postponed

until further notice, while regulators continued to work out details of the new

permit. But in late September, SWRCB Executive Director Walt Petit directed

groups to submit monitoring plans by Oct. 15. The abrupt change of plans and

short notice period sparked an angry response from industry, which in turn

resulted in an additional grace period, according to attorney William Funderburk

Jr., with the Los Angeles law firm of Radcliff, Frandsen, Tricker and Dongell. 

<p>

Funderburk said he is "encouraged by" provisions of the revised draft permit

that appear to recognize the variable quality of stormwater runoff. "There are a

lot of problems that our clients have with the draft permit, but we are

generally encouraged."<p>

Funderburk likened runoff from stormwater to fugitive air emissions. Unlike

regulations for stationary air sources and process wastewater discharges that

are measurable and reliable, stormwater discharges are highly unpredictable. 

<p>

"We need to come up with creative ways to regulate these fugitive or mobile

sources," Funderburk said. For example, requirements for best available

technology economically achievable (BAT) and best conventional pollutant control

technology (BCT) should give maximum flexibility to individual facilities to

design their own standards. BAT/BCT standards should not be in the hands of

regulators, and more importantly, they should not be designed by citizen groups,

he said. <p>

According to SWRCB, the draft permit is an attempt to address a variety of

concerns raised by monitoring group leaders, regional water board stormwater

staff and others. Requirements for receiving water limitations, stormwater

pollution prevention plans (SWP3s), monitoring, and group monitoring would

change, if the draft permit is adopted.  <p>

For example, under the draft permit, if a discharger failed to reduce a

pollutant that causes a violation of a water quality standard--despite having

implemented all best management practices (BMPs) that are technically and

economically achievable--the discharge of that pollutant would be considered in

compliance with receiving water limitations, provided the discharger obtains

approval from the water board. Under the old permit, dischargers that violated

receiving water limits, despite having fully implemented BMPs, could be found in

violation of the permit. <p>

"The loosely defined terms of the permit cut both ways," Funderburk said. "For

companies that read it closely they can conceivably get by on spending minimum

amounts to comply," he said. But there's a fine line between minimum compliance

and knowing how the permit will be enforced by various third parties, he said.

"So there's a minimum standard and a practical standard. We would prefer that

the practical standard be more refined and allow individual facilities greater

flexibility to define BAT/BCT for their own circumstances," he said.<p>

According to information provided by SWRCB, the old permit did not provide

enough detail about the major components of the SWP3. Furthermore, the old SWP3

requirements were inconsistent with EPA's new multi-sector permit. In the draft

permit, SWP3 requirements are revised to be more descriptive and explanatory,

and have been renumbered to more closely follow those in the federal

multi-sector permit, SWRCB said. The draft permit also would require an annual

compliance audit as part of the SWP3, it said. <p>

Monitoring requirements also would change under the draft permit. For example,

dischargers who comply with the general permit and have analyzed six samples

would be eligible for reduced sampling and analysis. Under the old permit,

dischargers were required to perform sampling and analysis twice a year,

regardless of the results. The draft permit also would extend the duration of

the rainy season, as defined in the permit, by two months; allow sampling in the

first hour of a storm, rather than the first half-hour; and remove the

definition of "significant storm," so that facilities could sample any storm

that produces a discharge.<p>

The draft permit also would recognize watershed monitoring as a viable

alternative to monitoring at an individual facility. Watershed monitoring would

have to be approved by the regional water board.<p>

Requirements for members of monitoring groups also would change. Under the draft

permit, two samples from all participating facilities in a given group would be

required over the life of the five-year general permit. The old permit required

two samples per year from the same 20 percent of participating facilities. The

draft permit also would require late filers to sample four times during the life

of the permit. Previously, late filers who joined groups were subject to the

same reduced sampling as other group members. <p>

"In terms of trends for the whole country, it's significant that California's

leading water agency essentially appears to be headed in a somewhat more common

sense regulatory direction," Funderburk said. "It's not deregulatory, but it

doesn't regulate through a buckshot, one-size-fits-all approach," he said. <p>

A public hearing on the permit was scheduled for Nov. 12. The permit can be

downloaded from the Internet at http://www.swrcb.ca.gov.

</body>
<foot>
