<html> <title>FDA Cites High Foreign Clinical Violations</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/clin/clinhead.gif" alt="Guide to Good Clinical Practice">
<P>
<h2>FDA Cites High Foreign Clinical Violations</h2>
<body>
Drug sponsors and clinical investigators need to verify compliance with FDA
regulatory requirements when clinical studies originally conducted for European
registration are subsequently used in support of U.S. new drug approval (NDA)
submissions, according to FDA officials. <p>

Overall, the FDA reports that foreign studies have nearly twice the violation
rate of U.S. studies for basic FDA requirements such as protocol adherence and
adequate record keeping (see chart, below). In large part, this violation rate is
associated with studies originally conducted outside of an investigational new
drug (IND) application that are subsequently submitted by sponsors.<p>

<center><img src="/tpg/food/clin/clinjuly2a.gif"></center><P>

"The overwhelming majority of these studies were conceived for submission for
foreign drug registration, not U.S. registration," said Alan Lisook, M.D.,
clinical investigations branch chief within the Center for Drug Evaluation and
Research (CDER), in prepared remarks for a recent industry seminar held in
Israel. "It was only <i>post-facto</i> that they were submitted to the FDA.<p>

"Studies not performed under IND, in order to be accepted in support of NDA
claims, must meet the ethical requirements of the Declaration of Helsinki, or
the laws of the country in which the research was conducted, whichever
represents the greater protection of the individual," Lisook said.<p>

<h3>FDA Requirements</h3><p>

In providing an overview of FDA's policy with respect to foreign studies, Lisook
said current agency regulations allow the FDA to accept foreign studies as the
principal "adequate and well-controlled" studies used for U.S. marketing
approval, but only if they are applicable to the U.S. population and medical
practice and were performed by medically competent investigators. <p>
Although the regulations do not necessarily require on-site inspections, FDA's
current policy is to audit all foreign studies providing the basis for drug
approval if no such domestic studies also exist. This policy also is applied to
studies supporting "major" drug supplements. In addition, the FDA will launch
"investigator-oriented" inspections when it finds specific circumstances that
warrant further investigation (see "Leading Issues That Prompt FDA Investigator
Inspections," below).<p>

<h3>Different Requirements</h3><p>

During its foreign inspections, the FDA will consider whether or not a study
meets its minimum threshold for compliance, through meeting the requirements of
the country in which it is conducted or the principles of the Declaration of
Helsinki. During this process, Lisook said that the FDA looks foremost for
review and approval (even if done orally), of a protocol by an appropriate
review committee, and use of informed consent.<p>

Lisook reported that the "major thrust" of the agency's audits in such
situations is to examine the validity of data submitted. He said three related
circumstances or violative conditions commonly are found that lead to a
recommendation that studies be rejected:<p>

<ol><li><i>Nonavailability of data for audit.</i> Typically, this problem becomes apparent
before an inspection is launched but after the sponsor is requested to schedule
an inspection.<p>

<li><i>Failure to follow protocol.</i> Examples of this type of violation, which is
relevant to all studies submitted to the FDA, include misreporting of drug
therapy and/or drug dosage or of disease remission; enrollment of ineligible
subjects; or inadequate blinding.<p>

<li><i>Unreported concomitant therapies.</i> The FDA requires that any administration
of concomitant therapy that might interfere with a study drug be reported as
such. Lisook said this problem is "particularly prevalent" in countries where
"polypharmacy" is common practice.</ol><p>

Other common violations cited by Lisook that are considered serious, but will
not necessarily warrant rejection of a study, include: consent form
deficiencies; inadequate drug accountability; failure to obtain institutional
review board (IRB) approvals; and failure to list subinvestigators in a study
(see "Drug Clinical Site Inspection Increase During Fiscal Year 1995," April
1995, p. 1).<p>

<h3>FDA Recourse</h3><p>

Lisook said that most clinical investigators are sent one of three types of
letters following an inspection of their clinical site. The bulk of letters sent
by the FDA (71 percent) are called "information letters," which identify
deviations from FDA clinical trial regulations, but without requiring a written
response. A second type of letter simply acknowledges that an inspection has
occurred, without alleging any deviations. These are used in 20 percent of
inspections.<p>

The third type of letter -- the FDA Warning Letter -- is used to address
deviations of "significant importance" that require prompt action by clinical
investigators. Although controversial, Warning Letters have been used for
alleged violations by foreign clinical investigators whose studies were used to
support an NDA (see "Warning Letter Sparks Controversy Over FDA Jurisdiction,"
September 1995, p. 1). Lisook said that Warning Letters are sent to
approximately 9 percent of clinical sites (see Tab 1100).<p>

<h3>FDA Sanctions</h3><p>

In the cases in which serious deviations are alleged, the FDA also can pursue a
range of sanctions against investigators, including disqualifications,
restrictions on receiving investigational drugs and even criminal prosecutions.
To date, the FDA has pursued such actions against 115 clinical investigators.
<p>

Although the more extreme clinical sanctions typically involve situations in
which willful deception of the agency occurred on the part of an investigator,
investigators are held accountable for data integrity, generally, and should
implement appropriate systems.<p>

Many of the inadvertent issues involving data integrity can be either averted or
minimized through routine quality control audits of foreign clinical sites,
Lisook said.<p>

<hr>
<h4><center>Leading Issues That Prompt FDA Investigator Inspections</h4></center><p>

<font size=-1>Described below are the leading reasons or observations for which FDA
bioresearch inspectors launch "investigator-oriented" inspections of clinical
sites, according to Alan Lisook, M.D., chief of the clinical investigations
branch, within the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research. These types of
inspections formerly were called "for-cause" inspections, and comprise roughly
10 percent of FDA clinical inspections. <p>

<ul><li><b>Large Volume of Work:</b> Researchers appear to have undertaken a "large number"
of investigational drug studies, or studies spanning very different areas of
medicine;<p>

<li><b>Research Out of Specialty:</b> Investigators doing research out of his/her
specialty area;<p>

<li><b>Aberrant Efficacy or Safety:</b> Researchers report efficacy or safety data that
appear to be "too good to be true" as compared to the findings of other
physician researchers;<p>

<li><b>Unrealistic Enrollment:</b> Researchers appear to have too many patients enrolled
than could be reasonably expected for the given disease and location in which
the study is occurring;<p>

<li><b>Overconsistent Lab Results:</b> Researchers report laboratory results consistent
beyond normal biologic variation or that are inconsistent with results submitted
by other investigators;<p>

<li><b>Media Attention:</b> Studies that have attracted significant media attention that
is anticipated to result in high demand for the subject drug;<p>

<li><b>Scientific Merit:</b> A study considered truly important such that it merits
in-depth examination;<p>

<li><b>Sponsor Complaints:</b> Sponsor representatives report to the FDA that they have
difficulty in obtaining case report forms or other problems relating to the
trial; and<p>

<li><b>Subject Complaints:</b> The FDA receives a complaint from a study subject about
alleged violations of subject rights or the study protocol.</ul></font><p>





</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
