<html>
<head>
<title>Courts, agencies and 105th Congress to reshape rights of people with
disabilities</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/able/ablehead.gif" alt="ADA Compliance
Guide"></center>
<P>
<H3><I>Disability rights in 1997</I></H3>
<h2>Courts, agencies and 105th Congress to reshape rights of people with
disabilities</h2>

The 105th Congress, which convenes Jan. 7, may not be the main branch of
government redefining the ADA during 1997. Instead, the courts and federal
agencies may play a much larger role in helping to define this law further. <P>

While the courts and agencies influence the development of ADA law, Congress may
focus its attention on the reauthorization of two other significant laws
prohibiting discrimination based on disability: the Rehabilitation Act and
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA). <P>

Nevertheless, some business lobbyists and disability advocates anticipate that
there might be proposals to amend the ADA. <P>

<H3>Supreme Court</H3>

Although the U.S. Supreme Court has not yet heard any ADA case, at least three
decisions it will issue this year may have a significant impact on disability
rights.<P>

Stephen Gold and Diane Coleman, attorneys for Not Dead Yet, and American Disabled
for Attendant Programs Today, have filed a brief in <I>Vacco v. Quill</I>, C.A. No.
95-1858, a right-to-assisted-suicide case that the Supreme Court has agreed to
hear.<P>

In their brief, Gold and Coleman asserted that if the Court were to uphold a
constitutional right to assisted suicide or authorize its legalization by states,
it would be sanctioning "a lethal form of discrimination which violates the ADA."
Gold and Coleman maintained that people with severe disabilities, including
nonterminal disabilities, are potential victims of a right to assisted
suicide.<P>

The Court will consider whether to affirm the judgment of the 2nd U.S. Circuit
for the Court of Appeals, which held that there is a constitutional right to
assisted suicide under the Equal Protection Clause. <P>

"With respect to the protection of minorities, the poor and the nonmentally
handicapped, it suffices to say that these classes of persons are entitled to
treatment equal to that afforded to all those who now may hasten death by means
of life-support withdrawal," the 2nd Circuit said.<P>

The Court also will decide two title VII cases that may also affect ADA's
coverage of small employers (<I>Walters v. Metropolitan Educational Enterprises</I>, see
August 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 11, concerning how to count employees when
defining a title VII employer) and whether the ADA prohibits employers from
retaliating against former employees (<I>Robinson v. Shell Oil Co.</I>). <P>

The ADA clearly prohibits employers from retaliating against employees and
permits them to sue once they are former employees. Title VII prohibits
discrimination based on race, gender, religion and national origin.<P>

<H3>LD students and voc/rehab</H3><P>

Jane Jarrow, president of Disability Access Information &amp; Support in
Columbus, Ohio, said that college and university service providers would be
particularly interested in court decisions affecting students with learning
disabilities and college and university documentation requirements and
substitution policies.<P>

"Another major issue that still looms on the horizon for disability service
providers in higher education is a resolution of the current 'stand-off' between
post-secondary education and the vocational rehabilitation [voc/rehab] system,"
she said. <P>

Some voc/rehab agencies have refused to pay for modifications or accommodations
provided by post-secondary service providers to students who also are voc/rehab
clients, claiming that postsecondary institutions must bear the cost alone (see
September 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 8).<P>

<H3>Justice</H3><P>

The civil rights division at Justice, which enforces Titles II and III of the
ADA, will be under new leadership in 1997 due to the resignation of Assistant
Attorney General Deval Patrick, who left to spend more time with his family in
Massachusetts. <P>

Liz Savage, special assistant to Patrick, said, "Deval will be missed. We'll move
on and continue to vigorously enforce the ADA." <P>

"We intend to maintain a balanced enforcement program," Savage said, noting that
Justice does not focus on one issue. <P>

Justice will continue its outreach and technical assistance to small businesses
and expects to expand its use of mediation and alternative dispute resolution,
she noted.<P>

<H3>EEOC</H3><P>

The EEOC also has undergone changes at the top, with the recent resignation of
two of its five commissioners, Gaull Silberman and Joyce Tucker. <P>

While Silberman has been succeeded by Reginald Jones, Tucker's successor has not
yet been chosen.<P>

Commissioner Paul Miller said that the EEOC is considering issuing new policy
guidances in the coming year on plaintiffs who receive Social Security benefits,
long-term disability benefits disparities and psychiatric disabilities.<P>

 Miller also said that he wants to see more ADA enforcement for people with
developmental disabilities (e.g., mental retardation and cerebral palsy). <P>

The EEOC has brought its first claim on behalf of individuals with mental
retardation against Hertz (see August 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 5).<P>

Peggy Mastroianni, the EEOC's associate legal counsel, noted that the EEOC would,
as it stated in its national enforcement plan, continue enforcing claims raising
unresolved questions about reasonable accommodation, qualified individual with a
disability, undue hardship and direct threat. She added that the EEOC's ADA staff
would be looking very closely at psychiatric disabilities, people who apply for
other benefits, how the ADA affects temporary employees and reasonable
accommodations. <P>

Although the commission has analyzed reasonable accommodation in its regulations
and technical assistance manual, Mastroianni noted that it has never issued
policy guidance on reasonable accommodation.<P>

She said there are very interesting issues concerning "how the ADA plays out with
temporary employment agencies." <P>

For example, she said the pre-employment inquiry analysis is "a little different"
with temporary employees since there is the question of whether a conditional
offer is made by the temporary agency or its client (i.e., a business using a
temporary agency to perform its work).<P>

<H3>Access Board</H3><P>

The Justice Department and Access Board recently issued proposed guidelines on
children's facilities (see September 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 1), and will be
reviewing comments and preparing final rules. <P>

The Access Board also will review the proposed changes to the ADA Accessibility
Guidelines (ADAAG) in preparation for drafting a proposed rule to revise and
update ADAAG (see December 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 1).<P>

The Access Board also is working on regulatory negotiation on play areas
(concerning playground equipment), and a notice of proposed rulemaking for
outdoor developed areas (e.g., sports facilities, golf, boating and fishing
facilities, amusement facilities). <P>

Justice and the Access Board are working on a final rule for sections of ADAAG
concerning courtrooms, judicial, legislative, regulatory facilities and detention
and correction facilities.<P>

In addition, the Access Board will continue working on guidance for making
telecommunications equipment and customer services premises equipment
accessible.<P>

<H3>Rehabilitation Act</H3><P>

Congress will probably not tinker with section 504's prohibition on disability
discrimination by federal fund recipients, said Sallie Rhodes, director of client
assistance program training at the National Association of Protection &amp;
Advocacy Systems (NAPAS).<P>

Instead, Congress will focus on return-to-work solutions and getting people off
Social Security rolls when it considers reauthorizing the Rehabilitation Act,
Rhodes maintained. <P>

She said that state voc/rehab agencies increasingly are coming under fire for not
getting the job done and a push already is under way to depend more on private
rehabilitation providers. <P>

In addition to trying to cut costs, privatization will be considered in response
to complaints that voc/rehab agencies are not providing effective services for
people with severe disabilities, Rhodes said. <P>

She characterized privatization as "a bad solution to a very severe resource
problem," and said voc/rehab will "still be a player" since it has used private
providers for years.<P>

<H3>IDEA</H3><P>

People with disabilities have their educational interests at stake as Congress
will try again to reauthorize IDEA. (IDEA provides disabled elementary and
secondary students with a free, appropriate public education requirement.)<P>

Last year, Congress came close to reauthorizing IDEA. The House approved a
proposal to permit cessation of services for students causing certain
disciplinary problems (e.g., having a weapon or drugs in school). <P>

However, Congress could not reach consensus and agreed only to extend IDEA
appropriations for a year. <P>

Many disability rights advocates fear that this proposed exception to IDEA's
"stay-put" rights (during any challenge to a change in placement, the child must
remain in the current educational placement) will resurface. <P>

Curtis Decker, NAPAS' executive director, maintained, "We know if these kids are
thrown out of school they become juvenile delinquents, but they make improvements
if services continue."<P>

<H3>Possible ADA amendments</H3><P>

The 104th Congress, which many feared would limit the reach of the ADA, ended up
expanding its coverage to apply to the legislative and executive branches of the
federal government (see December 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 1). <P>

However, the motive may have not been a desire to strengthen disability laws, but
instead to eradicate the perceived hypocritical position of the federal
government exempting itself from the very laws it enacted.<P>

Some business lobbyists remain critical of several aspects of the ADA, and
proposed amendments to the ADA may result. Mary Reed, a lobbyist for the National
Federation of Independent Business (which represents many small businesses),
maintains that the ADA has many problems that need correcting. Reed said these
problems include no exemption for small businesses; vague definitions of
"qualified individual with a disability," "undue hardship" and "readily
achievable"; and excessive penalties.<P>

Gina McDonald, president of the National Council on Independent Living, contended
that the ADA "remains vulnerable" to backlash. <P>

"Clearly we believe that ADA will be under attack again. The most vulnerable
parts will be enforcement, especially of title III, definition of who is a person
with a disability and time lines for cities and states to be in compliance."<P>

One of the 104th Congress' proposed changes to the ADA may not resurface as
quickly as it would have had Rep. William Zeliff, R-N.H., not retired. Zeliff was
one of the main sponsors of the Drug-Free Workplace and Public Safety Assurance
Act of 1996 (H.R. 4017), which proposed amending the ADA and section 504 by
allowing employers to consider an  individual's record of past illegal drug or
alcohol abuse when he or she is applying for or has a "safety-sensitive" job (see
October 1996<I> Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 14).<P>

Rejecting criticisms of the ADA, McDonald said the media needs to focus more
attention on the law's benefits to society. <P>

She also said that Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., may introduce a community
attendant services act that would establish a national program of community-based
attendant services for people with disabilities and promote this alternative to
institutional services.<P>

During the 104th Congress, Feingold introduced a similar bill (the Long-Term Care
Reform and Deficit Reduction Act, S. 85), which was referred to Senate Committee
on Finance. <P>


<hr>
<center>
