<head>
<title>Plan advocates narrowing of work area exemption</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/able/ablehead.gif" alt="ADA Compliance
Guide"></center>
<P>
<H3><I>Report says ADAAG overhaul needed</I></H3><P>
<h2>Plan advocates narrowing of work area exemption</h2>
A recently issued report proposes that the ADA Accessibility Guidelines (ADAAG),
an accessibility standard for new construction and alterations, undergo some
changes of its own. Most notably, it suggests narrowing ADAAG's current exemption
for work areas. <P>

David Harris, chair of the 22-member ADAAG review advisory committee, stated, "We
have developed a comprehensive set of recommendations that will help result in
the next edition of the ADAAG being compatible with available technologies, yet
flexible enough to allow the prompt and efficient use of appropriate new
technologies and practices."<P>

But while the committee has proposed greater flexibility in some parts of its
proposed ADAAG, its suggested changes to the work area exemption would impose
more stringent requirements.<P>

Under the current ADAAG and committee's proposed ADAAG, workplace common areas
(e.g., rest rooms, kitchens, meeting rooms) must be accessible. However, unlike
the current ADAAG, the committee's proposed version would exempt only individual
work stations rather than "work areas."<P>

This change would not have a significant impact on many office buildings, which
already have individual work stations (e.g., offices and cubicles) for most of
its employees. <P>

But the change would have a dramatic impact in work settings where individual
work stations are placed in more general work areas that are currently exempt
under ADAAG. Such general work areas would include many restaurant kitchens and
manufacturing plant floors.<P>

The committee proposed retaining most other current ADAAG's substantive
standards. <P>

However, it suggested loosening up some absolute requirements and providing
instead a range of acceptable dimensions. For example, ADAAG currently requires a
bench in an accessible dressing room to be 24 inches by 48 inches. The committee
recommended this be changed to 20 inches to 24 inches in depth and at least 42
inches in length.<P>

A few other recommendations would institute stricter standards. For example,
ADAAG currently requires in places of assembly with fixed seating at least one
accessible wheelchair location for seating capacities from four to 25, two for 26
to 50 seats and four for 51 to 300 seats.<P>

By contrast, the report proposes requiring at least two wheelchair spaces for
assembly areas seating 50 or less, four for 51 to 100 seats and five for 101 to
300 seats.<P>

<H3>New format</H3><P>

While the committee recommended leaving most of ADAAG's current standards intact,
it proposed completely reorganizing ADAAG's format. ADAAG currently is divided
into 10 sections. (Sections 11-14 still are interim and section 15 was proposed
recently, see September 1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 1). Although the committee has
proposed 10 chapters, any resemblance between its proposed structure for ADAAG
and ADAAG's current organization ends there.<P>

The committee recommended separating "scoping" requirements (e.g., how many
features and which spaces must be accessible) entirely from its technical
requirements (e.g., the range of dimensions that must be met for areas to satisfy
accessibility standards). Although ADAAG currently places many scoping
requirements at its outset, the proposed ADAAG sets them off in their own
chapter.<P>

Another proposed format change -- the committee suggested expanding a few
subsections in ADAAG (e.g., subsections on accessible routes and built-in
furnishings) into chapters of their own. <P>

Other suggested changes in format include adding several new charts to help
clarify standards. For example, charts showing the required number of accessible
rooms for accessible transient lodging (e.g., motels and dorms) show that
facilities with 51 to 75 rooms must have three accessible rooms and one room with
a roll-in shower. The chart does not say whether the room with a roll-in shower
may be one of the three accessible rooms or must be an additional accessible
room.<P>

The committee's proposed chart would instead have separate columns showing the
number of required accessible rooms without roll-in showers, accessible rooms
with roll-in showers and total number of required accessible rooms.<P>

For a copy of the report, contact the Access Board at (202) 272-5434 (voice),
(202) 272-5449 (TTY) and ask for publication S-29. <P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/able/able.html"><img
src="/tpg/person/able/smallable.gif"  alt="Return to ADA Compliance Guide Home
Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [
ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
