<html>
<head>
<title>Mental health parity law enactedp</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/able/ablehead.gif" alt="ADA Compliance Guide"></center>
<P>
<h2>Mental health parity law enacted</h2>

Mental health advocates have won a major victory, the enactment of the Mental Health Parity Act of 1996,
mandating that employers offer similar health insurance coverage for both physical and mental illnesses. Its
enactment follows a failed attempt to include it in the health insurance portability reform bill (September
1996 <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>, p. 14).<P>

While a breakthrough in mental health coverage, however, many employers' health benefit plans will not be
required to provide parity under this new law. (Employers are not required to provide parity under the
ADA.)<P>

On Sept. 5, the Senate adopted the parity act as an amendment (introduced by Sens. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.) to H.R. 3666 (an appropriations bill for the Departments of Veterans Affairs
and Housing and Urban Development). House-Senate conferees accepted the language and President Clinton
signed it into law on Sept. 26.<P>

The act will prohibit group health plans from capping aggregate lifetime or annual benefits for mental health
service but not for medical or surgical services. Most insurance policies include a $50,000 lifetime cap for
treatments for mental illness, while physical illnesses, like cancer or heart disease, are capped at $1
million or more, Domenici maintained.<P>

Domenici praised House members for accepting the Senate-approved mental health parity language, stating,
"This has been a very long and difficult effort, but I'm pleased that we have finally succeeded. ... This
represents a first step by the Congress to bring the nation to terms with caring for the millions of
Americans who suffer from these diseases of the brain."<P>

<H3>Exemptions</H3>

Although a significant piece of legislation, the act was scaled back significantly from the one originally
introduced. Instead, in a compromise with employers, proponents agreed to exempt businesses with fewer
than 50 employees and delay the effective date until 1998.<P>

Moreover, the amendment will not apply if it increases premiums by 1 percent or more, as a result of
language added by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.<P>

Paul Fronstin, research associate with the Employee Benefits Research Institute, said that Gramm's
amendment will result in the parity amendment having a "very limited impact on employers." However, he
said the act does not clarify whether employers must first provide parity and then see if their premiums
are affected or instead may "opt out" from providing parity based on actuarial projections. <P>

The Congressional Budget Office has estimated that employers will incur a cost of less than 2/10 of 1
percent in health premiums by providing parity, or about 60 cents in additional costs per member per
month.<P>

Lee Carty, director of communications at the Bazelon Center for Mental Health Law in Washington, D.C.,
said that employees in Maryland and Minnesota did not see their rates increase by the threshold 1 percent
after those states enacted mental health protections. <P>

Carty noted the limits of the law's reach, describing it as a "first step in providing equality for people who
have mental illness and first step in fairness." She said the parity act will not prohibit employers from
having lower copayments for people who have mental disabilities than people who have physical disabilities.
Further, employers will not have to provide mental health coverage under the law, she stated.<P>

While the EEOC provides that parity is not required under the ADA for people with mental and physical
disabilities, Shelley Jackson, a staff attorney at the Bazelon Center, said mental health advocates will
challenge differences in health care coverage  under the ADA and the Mental Health Parity Act. Such
disparities "stand in the way of people with mental disabilities trying to gain self sufficiency through
employment," she said.   <P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/able/able.html"><img
