<html> 
<head>
<title> Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/wage/wagehead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor
Standards Act">
<P>
<h2>Recent Congressional Hearing Addresses Community College Employees, Teen Drivers </h2>
<P>

After raising the minimum wage and clarifying the compensability of employee commuting time, the 104th
Congress turned its attention to the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) one last time before adjournment. <P>

On Sept. 12, the House Economic and Educational Opportunities Subcommittee on Workforce Protections
discussed three notable FLSA bills. They covered classification of community college employees, teenagers
driving on the job and law enforcement training compensation. <P>

Rep. Randy Tate (R-Wash.) and a panel of private- and public-sector representatives discussed the topics,
although significant action on the measures is not expected until the 105th Congress begins work next
spring. <P>

<H3>Exemption for Certain College Employees</H3><P>

One bill (H.R. 2134) discussed at the hearing would grant an exemption from the overtime provisions of the
FLSA to "classified" employees (support staff workers) at community colleges who also served as
"certified" teaching employees. Classified employees include such school workers as custodians, cafeteria
workers, bus drivers and secretaries. The bill in question, introduced July 17, 1995, by Rep. George P.
Radanovich, R-Calif., would add a provision to the FLSA at 29 U.S.C. 213(b) (see Appendix I of the
<I>Guide</I>).<P>

Currently, under the FLSA, when an employee serves in two different capacities for the same employer and
is paid at different rates for these duties, the hours worked in both jobs must be combined, and, if the
weekly total exceeds 40, overtime must be paid for the excess hours. Also, an employer must ensure that
both rates of pay are reflected in the employee's "regular rate of pay" (the basis for overtime calculation)
by adding the compensation for both jobs and dividing by the number of hours worked (to get a "weighted"
average, see &#182;510 of the <I>Guide</I>). <P>

Hearing witness Don Hall spoke on behalf of the American Association of Classified School Employees and a
related California state association in support of the bill. Hall formerly worked in two different capacities
at the same community college in California as both a painter (a classified employee) and an art history
instructor (a certified employee).  <P>

Hall did not receive overtime pay for hours he worked over 40 in a week until the U.S. Department of Labor
(DOL) found in a May 28, 1991, Wage and Hour Division opinion letter that an employee in a similar position
was entitled to pay for overtime hours at the adjusted rate described above. Hall then lost the art
instructor position and was forced to seek certified employment at another community college. <P>

At the hearing, Hall agreed that employees in his position should receive compensation for overtime work in
their regular positions as classified employees (the Radanovich bill would provide such a protection).
However, he said, his work as a teacher was an "entirely different line of work" from his job as a painter,
and it was "only by coincidence that the employer for each position [was] the same."   <P>

Moreover, while Hall stressed that the unions he represented would not support amendments to the FLSA
that would "compromise its crucial protections of the American worker," he maintained the Radanovich
legislation "has been carefully crafted in a manner that in no way threatens the integrity" of the act. He
pointed out that the bill's use of the terms "classified position" and "certified or other academic capacity"
would limit its scope, applying the legislation only to the "group of employees who have asked for the
exemption." <P>

<H3>Teenage Drivers on the Job</H3><P>

Meanwhile, Rep. Tate led a discussion on the regularity with which employees under age 18 should be
permitted to drive automobiles on the job under the FLSA's child labor provisions. Current FLSA
implementing regulations require that on-the-job driving for minors be limited to operation of vehicles
(under a certain weight and during daylight hours) that is "occasional and incidental to the minor's
employment" (29 C.F.R. &#167;570.52; see Appendix II of the <I>Guide</I>). <P>

According to Tate, the current DOL definition of "occasional" is no more than once a week and four times a
month on average. The term "incidental," Tate said, means no more than 20 percent of work in a workday
and 5 percent in a workweek. A bill (H.R. 2089) introduced July 20, 1995, by Tate would alter the
regulations to stipulate only that driving by minors "not be the primary duty of the minor's employment."
<P>

In 1994, DOL imposed fines on certain businesses for allowing minors to drive in situations other than "rare
and emergency situations," a practice that Tate criticized. Hearing witness Ed Fitzpatrick, a representative
of the Washington State Auto Dealers Association, pointed out that the "rare and emergency situations"
standard is higher than the "occasional and incidental" standard set forth in the regulations. This DOL
action, he said, has thwarted the efforts of many employers who wanted to "offer job opportunities to
teenagers and provide them with meaningful work experience," but now have cut back on such positions out
of fear of being fined by DOL.      <P>

Tate and a representative of the Child Labor Coalition of the National Consumers League (who opposed the
bill) clashed on the issue of safety in teenage driving. While Tate cited a study indicating the threat of
accidents is no worse for minors than adults, the critic pointed to statistics naming teenage drivers as
those with the worst accident records, adding that driving by minors on the job is simply unsafe (see
&#182;&#182;740, 750).<P>

A law enforcement training time bill (H.R. 4172) was also discussed at the hearing and would exempt law
enforcement officers from the FLSA's overtime protections while they attended apprenticeship training
programs. All three bills were referred to the House Committee on Economic and Educational Opportunities;
H.R. 2134 and H.R. 2089 were subsequently referred to the Subcommittee on Workforce Protections.<P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/wage/wage.html"><img src="smallwage.gif"  alt="Back to
Employer's Guide to Fair Labor Standards Act Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [
ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
