<head>
<title>9th Circuit Affirms Its Stand on When Workers Were 'Subject to'
Docking</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/fair/fairhead.gif"></center>
<P>
<h2>9th Circuit Affirms Its Stand on When Workers Were 'Subject to' Docking</h2>

In two separate rulings issued Aug. 2, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals held
that a worker, exempt under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), may be "subject
to" improper pay deductions if an express policy for such deductions exists, even
if the worker has not experienced any deductions. <P>

The rulings followed several recent decisions by other federal appeals courts
concerning the "subject to" question. Several of these courts have agreed with
the 9th Circuit that the mere existence of a violative pay-docking policy may
destroy an employee's FLSA exemption (<I>Balgowan v. New Jersey Department of
Transportation,</I> No. 95-5276 (3rd Cir. 1996), <I>Current Developments,</I> July 1996,
page 1). Other federal appeals courts (including those for the 5th, 8th and 11th
Circuits) have held that prohibited pay docking generally needs to have occurred
for the exemption to be lost. <P>

Although the reasoning used by the 9th Circuit in its Aug. 2 rulings was
consistent with its stance on the issue, the findings returned in the two cases
it reviewed were dissimilar. In <I>Hackett v. Lane County</I> (No. 95-35283, Aug. 2,
1996), the court found that the exempt employees in question -- supervisors in a
sheriff's office -- had not experienced improper pay reductions, nor had they
been "subject to" improper deductions due to an employer's "express policy." In
<I>McGuire v. City of Portland, Ore.</I> (No. 95-35391, Aug. 2, 1996), however, the
court ruled that the employer did have in place a specific policy that made the
employees -- fire battalion chiefs -- "subject to" improper deductions, even
though no actual pay docking had occurred. <P>

<H3><I>Hackett v. Lane County</I></H3>

The FLSA provides that, in general, employees are entitled to overtime payments
for all hours worked in excess of 40 per week. A worker classified as a bona fide
executive, administrative or professional (EAP) employee, however, is exempt from
the overtime provisions of the law. In <I>Hackett</I>, the sheriff's office supervisors
had been classified by their employer as exempt executives or administrators. <P>

To qualify for one of the EAP exemptions, an employee must meet the requirements
of both the FLSA's "duties test" and the "salary test" for the exemption in
question. The fact that the employees in <I>Hackett</I> satisfied the duties test, as
either executives or administrators (see Tab 200 of the <I>Handbook</I>), was not in
dispute. <P>

To meet the FLSA's salary basis test (see &#182;222 of the <I>Handbook</I>), an employee
must, in general, regularly receive "a predetermined amount constituting all or
part of his [or her] compensation, which amount is not subject to reduction
because of variations in the quality or quantity of the work performed" (emphasis
added; 29 C.F.R. &#167;541.118(a), Appendix II, pages 49-50). <P>

Salaried employees must be paid for any week in which they perform work, but need
not receive payment for weeks in which no work is performed. Also, deductions
from the pay of a salaried employee taken in increments of less than one week are
generally not permissible for a week in which an employee performs any work.
However, an employer may dock employee pay for less than one week's work for
violations of safety rules of major significance -- that is, rules "relating to
the prevention of serious danger" (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.118(a)(5), Appendix II,
page 50). <P>

The supervisory employees in <I>Hackett</I> asserted that they did not meet the salary
basis test because their pay was "subject to wage deductions pursuant to
disciplinary suspensions unrelated to safety violations, and lasting for periods
of less than a week." The U.S. District Court for Oregon held that the employees
were not subject to unlawful suspensions, and the 9th Circuit affirmed.<P>

According to the appeals court, the employees conceded that they had not actually
received a disciplinary suspension of less than a week. However, this fact alone
did not resolve the case. The "critical question," the court said, was whether
the employees were "subject to" an improper suspension, rather than whether their
pay had actually been docked.<P>

In <I>Barner v. City of Novato</I> (17 F.3d 1256 (1994)), the 9th Circuit ruled that
where no actual pay deduction has occurred, to establish that an employee has
been subject to such a deduction, an employer must have in place an "express
policy" allowing improper pay docking. Applying this standard to <I>Hackett</I>, the
appeals court reviewed two documents it said could have established the existence
of such a policy: a personnel manual for public safety employees and a manual
that applied to all county employees.<P>

The court stated that neither of the manuals expressly permitted a disciplinary
suspension prohibited by the FLSA for exempt workers. The public safety manual
"provide[d] for disciplinary suspension without pay for a multitude of
infractions," but did not specify how long such a suspension would last, the
court said. Further, the second manual provided that employees could receive
disciplinary suspensions of less than one week only for major safety violations,
a practice permitted by the act.<P>

The court found that the two manuals, when read together, "create[d] an express
policy against disciplinary suspensions [except for major safety violations] for
increments of less than a week." Because the employer did not violate the salary
basis test in this regard, the court found that the employees were exempt from
receiving overtime under the FLSA.<P>

<H3><I>McGuire v. City of Portland, Ore.</I></H3> <P>

In <I>McGuire,</I> the second case reviewed by the court, fire battalion chiefs, like
the sheriff's office employees in <I>Hackett,</I> had been deemed administrators or
executives. However, in <I>McGuire,</I> and in contrast to <I>Hackett,</I> the court found that
the employees had <I>not</I> been paid on a salary basis, because their employer -- a
city -- had subjected them to partial-week pay reductions for infractions of
regulations other than major safety rules.<P>

The court found that the city's "express, published policy" provided that all
city employees could "suffer disciplinary suspensions with loss of pay for a
variety of offenses and infractions." The policy permitted, contrary to the FLSA,
an unpaid suspension in a week in which an employee had performed work.<P>

The city argued that its policy did not destroy the workers' FLSA-exempt status
because none of the battalion chiefs had ever received such a reduction and the
city did not intend to impose one. However, citing its precedential ruling in
<I>Abshire v. County of Kern</I> (908 F.2d 483 (1990)), in which the court held that
"employees were not salaried where an express policy provided for 'invalid'
deductions, even though the county had never in fact imposed such deductions,"
the court rejected the city's argument. The employer had an "express policy"
subjecting the employees to improper pay deductions, the court found. Therefore,
the court ruled that the battalion chiefs were not paid on a salary basis.<P>

In a related argument, the city also maintained that certain provisions of the
FLSA that prohibit workers from receiving certain pay reductions preclude public
employers from "taking advantage of" the EAP exemptions, and therefore are
contrary to congressional intent. But while the 9th Circuit recognized that
principles of public accountability necessitate that public employers be allowed
to dock exempt employee pay for partial-day absences (see &#182;222 of the
<I>Handbook</I>), the court did not apply this reasoning to the practice of disciplinary
suspensions.<P>

Quoting the U.S. Department of Labor, the court concluded that "employers have a
broad array of disciplinary means available with which to satisfy public
accountability without defeating the executive or administrative exemption." <P>



