<html> 
<head><title>Chicken Pox Was a Serious Health Condition</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/time/timehead.gif" alt="Family and Medical Leave Handbook">
<P>
<h2>Chicken Pox Was a Serious Health Condition </h2>
<P>
An employee suffering from chicken pox should have been placed on medical leave under the Family and
Medical Leave Act (FMLA) instead of having his employment terminated for absenteeism, the U.S. District
Court for Northern Ohio ruled recently.<P>

William George filed suit against his employer, Associated Stationers Inc., alleging it violated his rights
under the FMLA when it terminated him for excessive absences from work. George was employed as part of
the company's "flex-force" team comprised of seasonal employees hired to work in the company's
warehouse.<P>

From Feb. 9, 1994, through Dec. 12, 1994, George missed six days of work, was late three days and
worked one partial day. Marco DeSciscio, George's supervisor, issued the employee a written warning
about his attendance problems that included the statement that "another occurrence will result in further
disciplinary action up to and including termination."<P>

On Dec. 31, 1994, George began to feel ill; his condition worsened over the next several days until on Jan.
3, 1995, vesicles  covered his skin. George called DeSciscio and informed the supervisor that he could not
report to work because he had chicken pox. DeSciscio met with the company distribution supervisor and the
area manager, and they decided to terminate George's employment.<P>

Several days later George went to the hospital emergency room, where he was examined and diagnosed
with chicken pox. The attending physician instructed George to stay home from work until the vesicles had
dried up and to return in one week for a check-up. The physician testified that "because the skin vesicles
were evident at the time of George's visit . . . his was a 'highly contagious condition' and thus he was unable
to go to work until the period of contagion had passed." George was cleared to return to work after his
follow-up examination.<P>

<H3>Chicken Pox as a 'Serious Health Condition'</H3><P>

Associated Stationers conceded that they knew George did not report to work because he had chicken pox.
They said that he was terminated in accordance with the company's attendance policy and argued that
chicken pox was not a serious health condition as defined in the FMLA.<P>

Under the law, a serious health condition is defined as "an illness, injury, impairment or physical or mental
condition that involves . . . continuing treatment by a health care provider" (29 U.S.C. &#167;101(11), see
Appendix I of the <I>Handbook</I>). The U.S. Department of Labor's (DOL) regulations further define continuing
treatment to include an incapacity of three or more consecutive days and "treatment two or more times by
a health care provider" (29 C.F.R. &#167;825.114(a)(2)(i)(A), see Appendix II of the <I>Handbook</I>). The
regulations do not stipulate a time period in which the two "treatments" must take place.<P>

Associated Stationers argued that the FMLA was intended "to cover only those employees with chronic or
debilitating conditions." The regulations explicitly cover "chronic and debilitating conditions" (29 C.F.R.
&#167;&#167;825.114(a)(iii)-(iv)), but neither the regulations nor the statute limit the definition of
serious health condition to just such illnesses, the court noted. <P>

DOL's regulations exclude such conditions as the common cold, ear aches and upset stomach from
classification as a serious health condition (29 C.F.R. &#167;825.800). However, the court stated that
"here [George] had the requisite two treatments . . . was told by his physician that he could not work until
the vesicles were covered . . . and was contagious until at least January 9. This is a different situation than
that of an employee suffering from an ear ache or common cold."<P>

The employer also claimed that a serious health condition required an employee to prove that he or she
could not perform the "essential functions of his job as those functions are defined by the Americans with
Disabilities Act [ADA]." However, the court pointed out that the regulations under FMLA state that the
FMLA's "serious health condition" and the ADA's "disability" are two distinct and separate concepts, "and
must be analyzed separately" (29 C.F.R. &#167;825.702).<P>

The court also noted that George was not required by the FMLA to invoke the law in order to be covered by
its stipulations. Once the employee contacted the company and explained his health-related situation, "the
obligation shifted to the employer to determine whether leave was sought under the act and to obtain any
additional information," the district court said, citing the U.S. District Court for Middle Tennessee (<I>Brannon
v. Oshkosh B'Gosh Inc.</I>, 897 F. Supp. 1028 (1995)). The court ruled that George had a serious health
condition as defined under the FMLA at the time of his termination.<P>

<H3>The Employer's Attendance Policy</H3><P>

George's suit also maintained that his employer's attendance policy violated the FMLA. Associated
Stationers argued that its policy was not a violation, but merely stated that "the attendance policy . . .
simply required that employees report illnesses, including medical documentation thereof, and that a
medical leave, if properly documented, will count as one 'occurrence' regardless of the length of said
leave."<P>

Associated Stationers cited several court cases decided under the ADA to show that absenteeism was a
valid basis for termination. However, the court noted that the ADA was established to level "the playing
field for disabled individuals to allow them to compete with nondisabled employees," while the FMLA "was
designed to entitle employees to take reasonable leave for medical reasons." The district court ruled that
the ADA cases cited were irrelevant.<P>

The court classified the employer's policy as "no-fault," meaning that an employee's absence other than for
vacation was classified as an "occurrence" and counted in the company's point system, which was the basis
for its disciplinary actions.<P>

The FMLA specifically states that FMLA leave cannot be counted under "no fault" attendance policies as an
occurrence (29 C.F.R. &#167;825.220(c)). "An attendance policy which does not except as an 'occurrence'
an absence caused by a serious medical condition violated the [FMLA]," the court ruled, adding that if an
employee's last absence was due to a serious health condition as defined by the FMLA, the employer "may
not terminate the employee based upon its absenteeism policy."<P>

The district court ruled in favor of George's motion for summary judgment on the issue of liability and
overruled Associated Stationers' similar motion for dismissal. (<I>George v. Associated Stationers Inc.,</I> N.D.
Ohio, 932 F. Supp. 1012, June 3, 1996; 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 14670)<P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/time/time.html"><img src="/tpg/person/time/smalltime.gif" alt="Return to Family
and Medical Leave Handbook Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
