<html> 
<head><title>Arbitration Ruled Enforceable for FMLA Claims</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/time/timehead.gif" alt="Family and Medical Leave Handbook">
<P>
<h2>Arbitration Ruled Enforceable for FMLA Claims</h2>

Claims brought under the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) are subject to compulsory arbitration
clauses contained in employment agreements signed by employers and employees, the U.S. District Court
for Northern Texas held recently.<P>

P. Stephen Satarino brought suit against his employer, A.G. Edwards Inc., claiming the firm had violated his
rights under the FMLA and the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) when it terminated his employment
after he suffered serious injuries in an automobile accident. These injuries compromised his
information-processing abilities, and made him unable to work for as long or as productively as he did prior
to the accident.<P>

The employee maintained that Edwards interfered with his right to take leave under the FMLA for medical
care and physical therapy. Satarino also argued that Edwards retaliated against him for exercising his
FMLA rights, did not post the required FMLA notices and failed to make the required updates to the
employee handbook, and discriminated and retaliated against him for opposing discriminatory FMLA
practices.<P>

Edwards argued that Satarino's claims should be dismissed because the employee had agreed to "binding and
enforceable arbitration" of his claims when he signed a Supplementary Training Agreement for an
Investment Broker, an Investment Broker Agreement and a National Association of Securities Dealers Inc.
Form U-4. The employee signed these forms in conjunction with his employment with Edwards.<P>

The training agreement stated that:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Any controversy or dispute arising between [Satarino] and Edwards in respect to this agreement or [his]
employment by Edwards shall be submitted for arbitration before the New York Stock Exchange, Inc., or the
National Association of Securities Dealers, Inc.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The broker agreement contained a section entitled "Arbitration," which stated:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>[Satarino] agree[s] that any controversy or dispute arising between [Satarino] and Edwards in respect to
this agreement or [his] employment by Edwards shall be submitted for arbitration before the New York
Stock Exchange, Inc., or the National Association of Securities Dealers, Inc.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The Form U-4 that Satarino signed provided as follows:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>I agree to arbitrate any dispute, claim or controversy that may arise between me and my firm, or a
customer, or any other person, that is required to be arbitrated under the rules, constitutions, or by-laws
of the organizations indicated in Item 10 as may be amended from time to time and that any arbitration
award rendered against me may be entered as a judgement [sic] in any court of competent jurisdiction.<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
Citing the U.S. Supreme Court's holdings in <I>Moses H. Cone Memorial Hospital v. Mercury Construction
Corp.</I>, 460 U.S. 1, 24, 74 (1983), and <I>AT&amp;T Technologies Inc. v. Communications Workers of
America</I>, 475 U.S. 643, 650 (1986), the district court stated that the Federal Arbitration Act set a
"liberal policy favoring arbitration agreements" and that any doubts about the applicability of an arbitration
clause should be decided in favor of arbitration. In addition, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which has
jurisdiction over the Texas district court, recently ruled that a claim of discrimination brought under Title
VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 was subject to mandatory arbitration (<I>Rojas v. TK Communications Inc.</I>,
87 F.3d 745 (1996)).<P>

The district court applied Rojas to the immediate case, stating that "the three agreements are
unquestionably of adequate breadth to support compulsory arbitration." The court noted that both the
training and broker agreements' arbitration clauses stated that "any controversy or dispute" between
Satarino and Edwards with respect to Satarino's employment must be arbitrated. Form U-4 contained
similar language.<P>

Satarino, citing the U.S. District Court for Southern New York's ruling in <I>Hoffman v. Aaron Kamhi Inc.</I>, 927
F. Supp. 640 (1996), argued that because the arbitration clauses did not explicitly refer to the FMLA or
ADA, an employee could not be forced to arbitrate such claims (see December 1996 <I>Current Developments</I>,
page 7). However, the district court distinguished the facts in <I>Hoffman</I> from those in the present case on
the basis that <I>Hoffman's</I> arbitration provision was "poorly worded and ambiguously phrased."<P>

Moreover, the Texas district court added that it was bound by the decisions of the 5th Circuit, so "to the
extent that <I>Hoffman</I> would require a different result, <I>Rojas</I> controls," the court said.<P>

Satarino did not specifically address <I>Rojas</I>, but maintained that FMLA and ADA claims are distinct from
actions brought under Title VII and, thus, "particularly inappropriate for arbitration." The 5th Circuit has
not addressed whether FMLA and ADA claims can be subjected to compulsory arbitration, but the district
court predicted that the appellate court would uphold such employment agreements due to its lack of
hesitancy in the <I>Rojas</I> decision.<P>

The district court cited the Supreme Court's holding in <I>Gilmer v. Interstate/Johnson Lane Corp.</I>, 500 U.S.
26 (1991), where the Court stated that if Congress had not intended FMLA claims to be resolved through
arbitration, "it will be discoverable in the text of the [act], its legislative history, or an 'inherent conflict'
between arbitration and the [act's] underlying purposes." Although the FMLA does not explicitly provide for
arbitration of claims, the law "contains nothing to suggest that agreements to arbitrate are unenforceable,"
the court said, ruling that contractual agreements to arbitrate FMLA claims were enforceable. (<I>Satarino v.
A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.</I>, N.D. Texas, Civil Action No. 3:96-CV-1587-D, Oct. 23, 1996) <P>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/time/time.html"><img src="/tpg/person/time/smalltime.gif" alt="Return to Family
and Medical Leave Handbook Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
