<html>
<Title>States Offer Financial Aid for Meeting 1998 Deadline</Title> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif>
<IMG SRC = "/tpg/enviro/ustt/ustthead.gif" alt="Underground Storage Tank Guide"></IMG><P>


<h2>States Offer Financial Aid for Meeting Upcoming 1998 Deadline</h2><P>
<body>

Underground storage tank (UST) owners in 14 states can rely on state programs for
financial assistance in meeting the 1998 tank upgrade or replacement deadline,
according to a recent U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) report (see
related story, p. 1).<P>

There are nine state direct loan programs, six of which are available only to
small businesses. The programs have interest rates ranging from 0 percent to as
high as 7.5 percent, the report stated. In two state interest subsidy programs,
the state contributes funds to reduce interest rates provided by private lenders.
At least 96 percent of eligible applicants who submit an application obtain a
subsidy, according to the report.<P>

In three state loan guarantee programs the state assumes a portion of the default
risk to encourage banks to loan money to tank owners, the report said. All three
programs are available only to small businesses and guarantee most of the loan
amount. Many loan program administrators reported that even with state loan
guarantees, some banks still are reluctant to loan money to tank owners for fear
of environmental liability.<P>

Of four state grant programs, only one is limited to small businesses, although
the other programs limit eligibility to financially needy businesses, the report
said. Oregon applicants must guarantee that they will remain in business for a
specified period. <P>

Information on the state financial assistance programs discussed below was
obtained from the EPA report.<P>

<h3>California</h3><P>

California's Replacement of Underground Storage Tank Loan Fund offers low
interest loans to small-business UST owners for tank upgrades, repairs, removals
or minor corrective actions. <P>

The state has made 114 loans totaling $16,665,723 since December 1994. Program
officials currently are reviewing 25 loan applications, which total $4,443,215.
Since the onset of the project, the state has declined 64 applications. Program
participants had no complaints about the program and found participation to be
relatively easy, according to the report.<P>

The minimum loan per borrower is $10,000, and the maximum loan is $350,000. Loans
with real estate as collateral must be repaid within 20 years, and loans with
other collateral must be repaid within 10 years. Each loan includes a 2 percent
loan fee. For more information, contact the California Trade and Commerce Agency,
Office of Small Business, Erik Watkins, loan officer; (916) 323-9879; or Jim La
Tanner, loan officer, (916) 327-3104.<P>

<h3>Delaware</h3><P>

Delaware's Small Retail Gasoline Station Assistance Program provides low interest
loans--at 2 percent above the Federal Reserve discount rate--to certain retail
service stations for installation of air quality protection devices, replacement
of existing UST systems, removal or abandonment and subsequent replacement of UST
systems, and installation of water quality protection devices. To be eligible for
the program, stations must:<P>

<UL>
<LI>have an average monthly throughput for gasoline and/or special fuels
(diesel) of less than 75,001 gallons for the previous 12 months; <P>

<LI>qualify as a small business under the definition used by the Small Business
Administration (SBA); and<P>

<LI>have a pre-construction inspection so that the Department of Natural
Resources and Environmental Control can inform the station of its upgrade
needs.<P>
</UL>

To date, four tank owners have applied for loans and been approved. Two
applications are under review. Program contacts indicated that tank owners and
operators have had difficulty using the 15-page application, because of its
length and the type of information requested.<P>

The maximum loan amount per borrower is $100,000 or 90 percent of the entire
project cost, whichever is less. Participants must pay a minimum of 10 percent of
the entire project cost. The loan must be repaid within seven years. For more
information, contact the Underground Storage Tank Branch at (302) 323-4588.<P>

<h3>Hawaii</h3><P>

The Hawaii Capital Loan Program-Underground Storage Tank Loan Account offers
direct, low interest loans--at 1 percent below the Prime Rate or 7.5 percent,
whichever is lower--and participates in loans from private lending institutions
for upgrades, replacements, closures and remedial actions. <P>

The state legislature has threatened to eliminate funding because of a perceived
lack of interest in the fund, the report said. According to program
administrators, few loan applications have been received  because UST owners do
not consider upgrades to be an urgent need. To date, the program has processed
one loan application and granted a $140,000 loan. <P>

The maximum direct loan is $1 million per borrower. The maximum state portion for
a participation loan  is $1 million or 90 percent of the total amount, whichever
is less, per borrower. For more information, contact the Hawaii Capital Loan
Program, Financial Assistance Branch, Department of Business, Economic
Development and Tourism, Grosvenor Center, Mauka Tower, 737 Bishop St., Suite
1900, Honolulu, Hawaii 96813; (808) 586-2576.<P>

<h3>Idaho</h3><P>

Idaho's Underground Storage Tank Financing Program is a loan guarantee and
interest subsidy program that provides assistance to gasoline station owners and
oil dealers for tank upgrades and replacements. To qualify for a program loan, a
business first must qualify for a loan through its commercial bank and through
the Small Business Administration (SBA).<P>

The only problem program administrators reported was a continuing hesitancy by
banks to loan money to UST owners for fear of incurring potential cleanup
liability, particularly when UST owners do not carry insurance policies, the
report said. To date, tank owners have submitted 14 applications to the program,
and seven loans totaling $496,000 have been approved. Six applications are
pending and one was either declined or withdrawn.<P>

The fixed interest rate to the borrower is 6 percent. SBA guarantees a maximum of
90 percent of the loan with the lending institution responsible for the 10
percent unguaranteed portion. For more information, contact the Idaho State
Treasurer's Office, Liza Carberry; (208) 334-3203.<P>

<h3>Iowa</h3><P>

The Iowa Comprehensive Petroleum Underground Storage Tank Fund-Guaranteed Loan
Program guarantees loans to tank owners or operators for capital improvements,
including tank upgrades, cleanups or capital purchases of property. To qualify
for a guarantee, the tank owner or operator must independently own and operate a
petroleum UST site; own less than 12 tanks at not more than two sites; have a net
worth of $400,000 or less; and demonstrate that he or she was unable to obtain
financing from at least two private lending institutions.<P>

To date, the program has approved 28 applications and reviewed 40 applications,
the report said. There is no maximum loan amount for the guarantee, but the
maximum guarantee is 90 percent of the loan. Interest rates may be either
variable or fixed and the maximum loan period is 20 years. Loan applicants must
pay an application fee of $150. For details, contact Williams and Company at
(712) 252-1455.<P>

<h3>Maine</h3><P>

Maine's Oil Storage Facility or Tank Replacement Program provides direct loans,
loan guarantees and grants to commercial underground and aboveground oil storage
tank or facility owners and local governments for tank upgrades, replacements,
removals, disposals and purchases of air quality equipment. <P>

To qualify, an applicant must demonstrate that its tank or facility is leaking,
or must be removed or replaced as required by law; it is financially needy; and
is a commercial entity that does not own more than a 50 percent stake in more
than one tank facility location. For a loan guarantee, the applicant also must
demonstrate that it qualifies for a bank loan. For a grant, the applicant also
must demonstrate non-profit status and hardship.<P>

To date, the program has approved 143 of 249 applications submitted. Of the
remaining 106 applications, fewer than 50 percent were denied and the rest were
withdrawn, according to program officials. For details, contact the Finance
Authority of Maine, 83 Western Ave., P.O. Box 949, Augusta, Maine 04332-0949;
(207) 623-3263; fax (207) 623-0095.<P>

Maine has another financial assistance program, called the Residential
Underground Oil Storage Tank Removal Program, that provides interest free loans
and grants to residential tank owners and operators for replacements, removals
and disposal of tanks. For more information, contact the Maine State Housing
Authority, 353 Water St., Augusta, Maine 04338-2669; (207) 626-HOME; (800)
452-4668.<P>

<h3>Maryland</h3><P>

The Maryland Underground Storage Tank Upgrade and Replacement Fund Loan Program
provides low interest loans to private tank owners for UST removals, replacements
and upgrades. To qualify, a tank owner must: <P>

<UL>
<LI>be in compliance with all federal and state laws and regulations; <P>

<LI>have registered its tanks before July 1, 1991; <P>

<LI>demonstrate the legal capacity to incur the obligations of a loan; <P>

<LI>demonstrate creditworthiness, collateral and other security; and<P>

<LI>provide a letter of intent to apply for assistance.<P>
</UL>

To date, the program has approved 30 of the 200 applications submitted by tank
owners. No applications have been denied: 30 applications are being processed and
140 were withdrawn. Applicants report that the applications are difficult to use
and they found it difficult to meet collateral requirements because they are
reluctant to sign personal guarantees, according to the report.<P>

The interest rate is equal to the yield of the most recent sale on state general
obligation bonds, which currently is 6 percent. Loans must be repaid within 15
years. The maximum loan amount is $50,000 per site, or $150,000 per owner per
year. For more information, contact the Maryland Department of the Environment,
UST Upgrade and Replacement Fund Office, Cindy Bojokles; (410) 631-3095.<P>

<h3>Massachusetts</h3><P>

Massachusetts' Underground Storage Tank Petroleum Product Cleanup Fund is a grant
program available to cities, towns, districts and other political bodies for tank
replacement, removal and closure. The fund went into effect May 19. For more
information, contact the fund at (617) 727-3200, ext. 628.<P>

<h3>Michigan</h3><P>

The Michigan Underground Storage Tank Financial Assurance (MUSTFA) Act-Interest
Subsidy Program provides an interest subsidy on loans for replacement and upgrade
of petroleum UST systems. To qualify for assistance, a business must be in
compliance with MUSTFA registration requirements. Program administrators
indicated that approximately 99 percent of applicants who complete the
application process are approved for the subsidy.<P>

The subsidy is for the first $200,000 of a loan per owner or operator. The
maximum period of interest subsidization is 10 years. For more information,
contact the MUSTFA Fund Administrator, Department of Natural Resources, 333 South
Capitol Ave., Town Center, 2nd Floor, Lansing, Mich. 48933; (517) 373-6247; and
the Department of Treasury, Cash/Debt Management Section, P.O. Box 15128,
Lansing, Mich. 48901; (517) 373-8404. <P>

<h3>Ohio</h3><P>

Ohio's Petroleum UST Linked Deposit Program offers an interest subsidy on loans
for replacement and upgrade of petroleum UST systems. Since the start of the
program in 1989, $1.6 million has been invested for subsidization, of which
$600,000 is outstanding investments. <P>

The $500,000 budget has not been expended, but program administrators expect to
receive more applications and grant more interest subsidies as the Dec. 22, 1998,
deadline approaches and awareness of the program increases. Of 23 applications
submitted to the program to date, 22 have been approved and one has been
denied.<P>

The interest rate subsidy for the first $100,000 of a loan per owner or operator
reduces the fixed borrowing rate by 3 percent. The maximum period of interest
subsidization is four years. For details, contact the Ohio Underground Storage
Tank Release Compensation Board at (614) 752-8963.<P>

<h3>Oregon</h3><P>

The Oregon Underground Storage Tank Financial Assistance Program-Tier IV
Essential Services Grant is available to UST motor fuel station owners and
operators and certain property owners in the state. The grant, which is the
lesser of $75,000 or 75 percent of the entire project cost, is for tank upgrades,
replacements, corrective action associated with upgrade or replacement, and
installation of pollution control equipment.<P>

Although the program works well, the grant is inadequate when severe soil and
groundwater contamination are present, and there are no provisions for tank
closure only, according to program administrators. For more information, contact
the Department of Environmental Quality, UST Financial Assistance Coordinator,
811 S.W. 6th Ave., Portland, Ore. 97204; (503) 229-5870; (800) 452-4011.<P>

Oregon also has another general assistance program, the UST Pollution Control Tax
Credit, that offers a 50 percent Oregon business income tax credit based on the
total costs of eligible project improvements. The credit can be used to cover UST
upgrades and replacements, and is available to tank owners and operators
regardless of whether they qualify for the Tier IV grants. For details, contact
the financial assistance coordinator at the phone numbers and address listed
above.<P>

<h3>Pennsylvania</h3><P>

Pennsylvania's Storage Tank Loan Fund provides loans at a 2 percent interest rate
to small, for-profit storage tank facility owners and operators for replacement
of leaking tanks, tank removals (if the business will continue to operate on the
site) and removals of a release or material affected by a release. Since April
1992, tank owners have submitted 74 loan applications. Fifty-seven have been
approved; 12 have been withdrawn or denied; and five are under review.<P>

The maximum loan provided by the fund is $50,000 or 75 percent of the entire
project cost, whichever is less. Loans must be repaid within 10 years. For
details, contact the Pennsylvania Department of Commerce, Division of Loans and
Technical Assistance, 490 Forum Building, Harrisburg, Pa. 17120; (717) 783-5046;
fax (717) 234-4560.<P>

<h3>Utah</h3><P>

The Utah Petroleum Storage Tank Loan Fund offers 3-percent fixed-rate loans for
upgrades, replacements and closures to tank owners who demonstrate compliance
with all state and federal UST laws, rules and regulations; have a certificate of
compliance; and have paid all fees, interest and penalties. No loans have been
made because the program is new.<P>

The maximum loan amount is 80 percent of approved project costs, $15,000 per tank
or $45,000, whichever is least. For more information, contact the Division of
Environmental Response and Remediation, UST Section, 168 North 1950 West, Salt
Lake City, Utah 84116; (801) 536-4100.<P>

<h3>Vermont</h3><P>

Vermont's Underground Storage Tank Loan Assistance Program gives zero interest
loans of as much as $40,000 to retail gasoline outlets that sell less than an
average of 20,000 gallons of gasoline per month and municipal facilities that
store petroleum products and have populations of less than 2,500. The program
covers replacement of motor fuel tanks that were in existence on or before Jan.
1, 1987.<P>

The state requires that all loans be guaranteed by a mortgage on real property or
equipment, and that they be repaid within 10 years. For details, contact the UST
Loan Program, Waste Management Division, Department of Environmental
Conservation, 103 South Main St., Waterbury, Vt.  05617-0404; (802) 241-3888.<P>


</body>

