<html> 
<head>
<title>IRS Issues Model Amendment For Veteran's Benefits Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/planhead.gif" alt="The 401(k) Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>IRS Issues Model Amendment For Veteran's Benefits Rules</h2>
<P>
The Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 (P.L. 104-188)  has corrected the tax code and ERISA so that employers may comply with the rules governing makeup contributions to the defined contribution plans of returning military veterans without violating qualified plan requirements.
</P>

<P>
Given these corrections, the IRS issued a revenue procedure on Oct. 7, 1996, which provides model language for amending plans to comply with the veteran's benefits rules in the Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act of 1994 (USERRA). 
</P>

<P>
Under USERRA, employees on leave for military service are entitled to receive defined contribution plan benefits -- and make up missed contributions -- for the length of the absence.  
</P>

<P>
But when USERRA took effect in October 1994, it was unclear how rules on contribution limits would apply to makeup contributions for veterans. For example, what if the makeup contributions, combined with the regular contributions the veteran is making to the plan, brings the employee over the annual contribution limit?
</P>

<P>
The Small Business Job Protection Act created a new section to the code, Section 414(u), to deal with these problems. The new section mandates that, when determining contribution limits, makeup contributions apply to the plan year(s) of absence, not the year(s) in which the contribution is actually made. 
</P>

<P>
The new revenue procedure (Rev. Proc. 96-49) provides model amendments for administrators who are modifying their plans to comply with the new section. These amendments may be completed without applying to the IRS or paying a user fee.
</P>

<P>
In general, plans are required to make such an amendment for plan years that begin on or after Jan. 1, 1998. However, plans are immediately required to comply with the USERRA rules. There rules went into effect in October 1994, and the two-year grace period bringing plans into compliance with them ended Oct. 13, 1996. 
</P>

<P>
The model language in the revenue procedure may be used by the following plans: master or prototype, regional prototype, volume submitter specimen, individually designed, and simplified employee pension plans (SEPs). 
</P>

<P>
In addition, plans must have received a favorable opinion, notification, advisory, ruling or determination letter that takes into account the requirements of the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
</P>

<P>
Plan administrators who use the model language must also file Form 8837, "Notice of Adoption of Revenue Procedure Model Amendments (Rev. Proc. 96-49)."
</P>

<P>
Here is the model language: 
</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<P>
	<LI><B>Amendment 1:</B> "Notwithstanding any provision of this plan to the contrary, contributions, benefits and service credit with respect to qualified military service will be provided in accordance with section 414(u) of the Internal Revenue Code." (This model amendment may be used to amend plans to provide for the requirements of USERRA and Code Section 414(u).)
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI><B>Amendment 2:</B> "Loan repayments will be suspended under this plan as permitted under section 414(u)(4) of the Internal Revenue Code." (This model amendment may be used to amend plans that provide for loans to participants, if the sponsor chooses to suspend loan repayments during a participant's military service.)
	</P>
</UL>

<P>
For an explanation of the new law affecting makeup contributions for veterans, see the "Special Report" in the October issue of <I>Current Developments</I>.
</P>




