<html> 
<head>
<title> Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/wage/wagehead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor
Standards Act">
<P>
<h2>DOL Announces Schedule for Future FLSA Regulatory Action </h2>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) Nov. 29, 1996, announced its 12-month agenda for proposing and
finalizing changes to federal regulations. Among the projects that would most affect the Fair Labor
Standards Act (FLSA) and its application to the American work force are those targeting DOL rules
governing child labor and overtime and minimum wage exemptions for executive, administrative,
professional and outside sales employees.<P>

The Regulatory Flexibility Act requires federal entities to summarize their regulatory priorities for each
coming year and establish a timetable for acting on those plans. However, the priorities, which are
published twice a year in the <I>Federal Register</I>, do not provide specific details on proposed or final changes
to the rules.<P>

Moreover, federal agency target dates for completing the projects historically have been unreliable.
Frequently, a federal department or agency delays issuing a proposed or final rule for several months, and
sometimes even years.<P>

<H3>High Priority</H3><P>

Due to changes in technology in the work place and job content over the years, DOL plans to review its child
labor regulations. The department in its announcement notes that changes in the places children are
working, differing federal and state standards, and different views on how to best coordinate school and
work necessitate a re-examination of the regulatory matter.<P>

DOL invited comment on its child labor regulations in 1994 and stated it would base its proposed regulatory
alternatives on those comments. Possible changes to be considered include specific modifications or changes
to hazardous occupations orders and changes to the hours 14- and 15-year-olds are allowed to work.<P>

The department says it also will move forward with plans to "define and delimit the term 'any employee
employed in a bona fide executive, administrative, or professional capacity.'" This term applies to minimum
wage and overtime exemptions established under the FLSA regulations. In its notice, DOL explained the
complex history of these exemptions and the fact that salary levels used in applying the exemption tests
are outdated and offer little guidance to employers.<P>

The salary tests have not been updated since 1975 and recent lawsuits have created confusion as to what
constitutes compliance with the regulations' "salary basis" criteria. "Numerous comments and petitions
have been received in recent years from industry groups regarding the duties and responsibilities tests in
the regulations," DOL said.<P>

Though the regulations have been revised to deal with specific issues, they "are still in need of updating and
clarification," according to the department. DOL says that it plans to issue a notice of proposed rulemaking
on the provisions in September 1997, and will involve affected interest groups to develop alternatives to
the current regulations. It further says that "although legislative proposals have been introduced in the
Congress to address certain aspects of these regulations, the department will continue to pursue revisions
to the regulations as the appropriate response to the concerns raised."<P>

<H3>Other Issues Before DOL</H3><P>

DOL's semiannual agenda indicates that several other federal requirements related to the FLSA will likely be
reviewed in the coming 12 months. Among them are the following:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI><I>Records to Be Kept by Employers Under the FLSA</I>. This proposal would simplify regulatory language and
streamline regulatory requirements to make them more easily understandable and reasonable. A notice of
proposed rulemaking should be issued by June, according to DOL.<P>

<LI><I>Minimum Wages in American Samoa</I>. Because the FLSA's minimum wage standards in American Samoa are
determined industry-by-industry and are delineated in separate portions of the regulations, the department
plans to combine and consolidate regulatory text as part of the Clinton administration's "Reinventing
Government" initiative. DOL planned to issue a notice of proposed rulemaking on the issue in November
1996, however, the department has yet to issue the proposal.<P>

<LI><I>Employment of Student-Learners, Apprentices, Learners, Messengers and Student Workers Under Section
14 of the FLSA</I>. This proposal falls under the Reinventing Government initiative as well, and would
consolidate and streamline the five separate parts of the <I>Code of Federal Regulations</I> that deal with this
topic to reduce duplication. A proposed rulemaking concerning the rule was due from the department in
November 1996, but no proposal has been issued.<P>

<LI><I>Miscellaneous Exemptions Under the FLSA.</I> This proposal would consolidate and streamline various FLSA
exemptions into a single set of regulations, including the provisions governing local delivery drivers and
helpers, FLSA applications to seamen, and radio and television personality overtime exemptions, among
others. A notice of proposed rulemaking is scheduled for September.<P>

<LI><I>Implementation of the 1996 Amendments to the FLSA</I>. This proposal would bring DOL's current regulations
into line with the amendments made by the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996. These include
changes to provisions governing minimum wages, computer professionals and the youth "opportunity"
wage, among others. DOL scheduled a notice for proposed rulemaking for November 1996, however, the
department has yet to issue the proposal.<P>

<LI><I>Application of the FLSA to Domestic Service</I>. This proposal includes technical amendments to the
regulations regarding domestic service employees. The department planned a final action on this matter by
December 1996, but no action has been taken on the matter.<P>
</UL>

A complete copy of the proposed regulatory changes for the 12-month period for each governmental
department may be found in the Nov. 29, 1996, issue of the <I>Federal Register</I>. <P>


<hr>
