<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Physician-Hospital Relationships: Managing the Delivery of Care</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN=
bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<hr>
<center><H1>Developing and Managing Physician Networks: Business and Legal Strategies</H1></center>
<hr>

<H2>Physician-Hospital Relationships: <BR>
Managing the Delivery of Care </H2>
The theme at the recent Catholic Health Association's executive conference
in San Antonio, Texas, was clear: The predominant concern of both physicians
and hospitals should be how to manage patient care effectively across the
continuum of services. Speaker Bernadette Broccolo, a partner at Gardner,
Carton &amp; Douglas in Chicago, explained, &quot;As health care systems
move into the second and third generations of physician-hospital integration
models, they must move away from focusing only on structure to looking at
the operational aspects and how the relationships and finance will really
work.&quot; 
<H3>IPAs-an Attractive Model</H3>
Present-day barriers to viable integration efforts include an overemphasis
on autonomy and financial gain, a reluctance of the parties to realign economic
and financial aspects (such as compensation, contribution of resources,
and allocation of risks and return), and a lack of leadership or trust.
To attract physicians to integrated delivery systems, Dr. Henry Golembsky,
a senior consultant with APM Management in San Francisco, recommended several
practical services that these networks should consider offering: continued
access to patients and practice growth; practice autonomy, especially in
clinical decision making; help with managed care contracting and cost control;
participation in plans with high-quality panels and reasonable payment levels;
a fair means of dividing capitated revenues; and a collegial, professional
atmosphere (see Box #1). <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The most successful form of physician integration is really not a
form of hospital physician integration, including equity models, but independent
practice associations [IPAs],&quot; Ms. Broccolo pointed out. &quot;And
the reason physicians have moved toward IPAs is because they have focused
on managing the delivery of care-agreeing to unify case management protocols,
unify utilization review, [unify] patient satisfaction measures, [unify]
outcomes measures-focusing on their success as providers as opposed to investors.&quot;
<H3>Incentives Point to Quality</H3>
Dr. Golembsky expanded on Ms. Broccolo's comments. &quot;Financial incentives
must be designed to motivate the management and delivery of high-quality
patient care.&quot; It is also important for integrated systems to ensure
that the rewards and risks are significant enough to actually influence
behavior. Incentives must be aligned among all parties-primary care physicians,
specialists, hospitals, and other providers. &quot;If one makes money by
taking advantage of a partner, over the long term that relationship won't
be stable,&quot; he cautioned.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H4>Box #1: Community Characteristics That Influence Network Growth</H4>
<FONT SIZE="2">What factors influence the growth of the health care industry in specific
communities? The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, based in Princeton, New
Jersey, analyzed a number of sample U.S. communities in search of an answer.
The foundation's report noted differences in the nature of change and the
speed at which it traveled across these selected areas, with several key
factors affecting the movement toward managed care: 
<UL>
<LI>If large, well-managed, and well-capitalized organizations exist in
a segment of the market, that segment is likely to play an important role
in change. 
<LI>Hospital sectors may be relatively concentrated with large institutions
and strong management, which often integrate vertically into insurance endeavors
(e.g., starting their own health plan or negotiating an exclusive arrangement
with an insurer) and take the lead in integrating physicians into the network.
<LI>Organizational strength, as in large physician group practices, allows
the entity to contract with health plans on the basis of capitation and
lead the coordination of the delivery of care. 
<LI>Experience with managed care affects change and rapid growth: familiarity
with health maintenance organizations (HMOs) leads to the formation of network
and independent practice association (IPA)-model HMOs; lack of experience
leads to the establishment of preferred provider organizations (PPOs) and
less structured forms of managed care. 
<LI>The degree of state and local political commitment affects the ability
of safety net providers to offer access; other factors include a preference
or aversion of providers to profit entities, not-for-profit entities, or
organizations from outside the community, as well as how private employers
act within the market. </FONT>
</UL>
<HR><I>Source: Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, Health Affairs, Summer 1996,
pp. 15-17.</I><BR>
<HR><BR>
<P><A HREF="/tpg/health/doks/doks.html">Return to Developing and Managing Physician Networks: Business and Legal Strategies Home Page</A><P>

