<html> 
<head>
<title> Court Rules on Double Recovery from Coordinated and Uncoordinated
 Insurance Policies</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/cobshead.gif" alt="Coordination of Benefits
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2> Court Rules on Double Recovery from Coordinated and Uncoordinated Insurance
Policies</h2><P>

An insured may be compensated by both an uncoordinated no-fault automobile
insurance policy and a coordinated health insurance policy when the insured's
injuries result from a motor vehicle accident, a Michigan appellate court
ruled.<P>

In <i>Shanafelt v. Allstate Insurance Co.</i> 1996 Mich. App. LEXIS 214 (App. Ct.
Mich. 1996), Joyce Shanafelt severely injured her leg when she slipped and fell
on icy ground while getting into her car. Shanafelt had a health insurance policy
that contained a coordination of benefits provision and a no-fault automobile
insurance policy with Allstate that did not coordinate benefits with other
insurance.  <P>

Shanafelt sought no-fault benefits from Allstate. Michigan's no-fault automobile
insurance act provides that coverage is provided where "the injury was sustained
by a person while occupying, entering into or alighting from the [parked]
vehicle." The district ruled, and the appeals court agreed, that Shanafelt's
injury fit within the "entering into" a parked vehicle provision.<P>

Shanafelt's medical expenses were paid by her health insurer under the
coordinated insurance contract then in effect. In disputing the district court's
decision that it pay damages, Allstate argued that Shanafelt's expenses had
already been paid by the health insurer. <P>

Double recovery is prohibited under Michigan law. The coordinated benefits
provision of the health insurer, however, provided that "the coverage under those
plans will be coordinated so that up to, but no more than, 100 percent of any
eligible expenses will be paid for or provided by all such plans combined." The
Allstate policy, being uncoordinated, did not have language stating that 100
percent of an insured's expenses would be compensated by all the insurers.
However, the policy did not limit a plaintiff's right of recovery under multiple
insurance policies.<P>

Accordingly, the appeals court concluded that when an insured has an
uncoordinated no-fault insurance contract with an insurer that does not limit the
right to recover duplicate insurance coverage, the insured may be compensated
twice by uncoordinated and coordinated policies. <P>
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/cobs.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/smallcobs.gif"  alt="Return to Coordination of Benefits
Handbook 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
