<html><title>Teaching Award Is Taxable, Tax Court Rules</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/perk/perkhead.gif" alt=" Employer's Guide to 
Fringe Benefit Rules"></center>
<P>
<h2>Teaching Award Is Taxable, Tax Court Rules</h2>
<body>
In a recent decision, the U.S. Tax Court has confirmed the IRS' long-standing
position that employees may not exclude from income awards they receive for
outstanding performance. The case, <i>Gloria Ann House v. Commissioner</i> (T. C. Memo.
1996-311), involved an award for "religious, charitable, scientific, educational,
artistic, literary, or civic achievement." <P>

Gloria Ann House, a professor at Michigan's Wayne State University, received a
$3,000 cash award from the university for teaching excellence. The university
issued House a Form 1099-MISC for the $3,000, but it did not withhold taxes.
Although House reported the award on her federal income tax return, she
identified and treated it as nontaxable income.<P>

The court concluded that House's teaching award was taxable income because it did
not meet the Code Section 74(b)(3) requirement for exclusion. To exclude an
educational award under Section 74(b), the recipient must transfer it to a
government agency, charitable organization or other Code Section 170(c)(1)
entity. Because House did not transfer her award, the IRS determined that she
owed income tax and an accuracy-related penalty. The tax court agreed.<P>

House did not dispute the IRS' contention that her award did not fulfill the
Section 74(b)(3) requirement for exclusion. Instead, she argued that because the
university did not withhold employment taxes on the award, the award did not
constitute income and did not need to be reported as income. The tax court
rejected these arguments.<P>

Very few employee awards are excludable from income, and those that are must
satisfy strict requirements. Code Section 274(j) provides an exclusion for only
two kinds of employee achievement awards -- length-of-service and safety
achievements. (See &#182;530 through &#182;539 of the <i>Guide</i> for a discussion of
employee award programs.) <P>

</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
