<html> <title> Flex Plans and the Family and Medical Leave Act</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/flexhead.gif" alt="Flex Plan 
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2> Flex Plans and the Family and Medical Leave Act: Proposed Regulations
Eliminate Some Confusion</h2>
<body>

Administering Section 125 cafeteria plans can be complicated enough. But the
enactment of the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 (FMLA), which requires the
maintenance and restoration of certain benefits for employees who take up to 12
weeks of FMLA leave, muddled it even further. To clarify the interaction between
the FMLA and Section 125, the Internal Revenue Service published proposed
regulations in the Dec. 21, 1995, <i>Federal Register</i> (60 FR 66229). <P>

The FMLA is enforced by the Department of Labor, which promulgated regulations in
January 1995 that, among other things, discussed employees' entitlement to
health-related benefits while on FMLA leave. (The FMLA is described in &#182;566
of the <i>Handbook</i>.) However, certain health benefits--such as health coverage and
medical flexible spending accounts (FSAs) under cafeteria plans, as well as COBRA
continuation coverage--are partially or solely under the IRS's purview. Since the
FMLA was enacted in 1993, the IRS has been wrestling with guidance on its side of
the equation. In 1994, the IRS released guidance on COBRA/FMLA issues; the new
proposed regulations address the impact of the FMLA on cafeteria plans. <P>

In general, the FMLA affects three broad areas of cafeteria plan
administration:<P>

<UL>
<LI>changes in family status;<P>

<LI>payment and cessation of cafeteria plan premiums; and<P>

<LI>medical FSAs.</UL><P>

The IRS's proposed regulations use a question-and-answer format, with a total of
eight questions, to clarify the FMLA's impact on various issues in these
areas.<P>

<h3>Plan Elections, Rights and Benefits</h3><P>

The proposed regulations clarify that an employee requesting leave under the FMLA
may revoke his or her existing cafeteria plan group health coverage election for
the remaining coverage period. Furthermore, if an employee loses health insurance
coverage while on FMLA-protected leave--for example, for nonpayment of the
policy's premium--the employer must reinstate the employee's coverage upon his or
her request. In addition, the reinstated coverage must apply under the same
conditions (including family and dependent coverage), with the same rights,
including the right to revoke or change elections, that applied prior to the
leave. However, the employee has no greater right to benefits for the remainder
of the plan year than an employee who has worked continuously during the plan
year, the IRS stated.<P>

If an employee elects to continue his or her cafeteria plan group health
coverage--including a medical FSA--during the FMLA-protected leave period, the
payment of premiums must continue without regard to the leave. Thus, the employee
would remain responsible for his or her premium contribution, if any, including
any amounts made pursuant to a salary reduction agreement. Similarly, an employer
would continue to contribute its share of the premiums during the leave
period.<P>

The proposed regulations also clarify that the FMLA requirements for cafeteria
plans do not apply to any non-health benefits, such as life insurance, provided
through the plan. Instead, an employer should rely on established policies for
provision of benefits during an employee's non-FMLA-protected leave period.<P>

Thus, an employee who takes FMLA leave presumably could revoke a flex plan
election regarding a non-health benefit to the same extent as employees on
non-FMLA leave--such as upon experiencing a change in family status, for example.
However, an employer may have to continue coverage of non-health benefits under a
flex plan during the FMLA leave to ensure that the employee can receive those
same benefits upon returning from leave. In that case, the employer may recover
the employee's share of the cost after the employee has returned from leave.<P>

<h3>Collecting Health Premiums</h3><P>

An employer can waive--on a nondiscriminatory basis--the requirement that
employees pay their share of premiums for health coverage during FMLA leave.
However, in cases where employees are required to pay for all or part of their
premiums, the IRS provides three payment options for employees who continue
health coverage--including medical FSAs--while on unpaid FMLA leave.<P>

<OL>
<LI>A pre-pay option, in which a cafeteria plan may <i>permit</i>--but not <i>require</i>--an
employee to pay, prior to FMLA leave, the amounts due for the leave period.
Contributions can be on a pre-tax salary reduction basis or an after-tax
basis.<P>

<LI>A pay-as-you-go option, in which employees may pay their share of premiums on
the same schedule as payments were made prior to FMLA leave, or under any other
payment schedule set forth in future FMLA regulations issued by the DOL.
Contributions generally can be made by the employee on an after-tax basis, but
they also can be made on a pre-tax basis from compensation due the employee
during the leave period (assuming that the Section 125 rules have been
satisfied). If an employee fails to make a scheduled payment, the employer may
make the payment and recoup it from the employee later. <P>

<LI>A catch-up option, where an employer recoups an employee's share of premiums
if the employee does not pay premiums during FMLA leave. However, the catch-up
option must be agreed upon in advance. Contributions can be made on a pre-tax
basis from any available compensation when the employee returns from FMLA leave,
but they can also be made on an after-tax basis.</UL><P>

However, the IRS noted three exceptions to these options: (1) the pre-pay option
cannot be the sole option offered (although it may be limited to employees on
FMLA leave); (2) the catch-up option can only be the sole option if it is also
offered to employees on unpaid non-FMLA leave as the sole payment option; and (3)
a cafeteria plan cannot offer a choice between the pre-pay or catch-up options
without also offering the pay-as-you-go option, if that option is also offered to
employees on unpaid non-FMLA leave.<P>

All three options include guidance on the collection of premiums on a pre- and
post-tax basis. Premium payments made on a pre-tax basis typically would arise if
an employee cashes out unused sick or vacation days. An employer should not
include such pre-tax payments in the employee's gross income if the employee
satisfies all other cafeteria plan requirements.<P>

The proposed regulations also outline procedures for payment of group health
premiums when an FMLA-protected leave period spans two cafeteria plan years. In
general, the regulations stress that any payment solution in this situation must
not enable the employee to defer compensation from one cafeteria plan year to the
next. Rather, the example provided in the regulations suggests that, to avoid
deferral of compensation, an employee should use some combination of the three
payment methods.<P>

<h3>Medical FSAs and the FMLA</h3><P>

Under the FMLA, employees who take FMLA leave must be permitted to continue
coverage under a medical FSA or revoke an existing FSA election for the remainder
of the coverage period. Furthermore, employees must be allowed to reinstate
their health FSAs once they return from FMLA leave on the same terms as prior to
taking the leave. However, the IRS noted that an employer cannot <i>force</i> a
returning employee whose coverage was terminated while on FMLA leave to reinstate
coverage.<P>

According to the IRS, as long as coverage is continued under FMLA leave, the full
amount of the elected coverage, minus any prior reimbursements, must be available
to the employee at all times, including the FMLA leave period. However, if an
employee's FSA terminates while the employee is on FMLA leave, he or she is not
entitled to receive reimbursements during that period. Furthermore, if that
employee is eventually reinstated, he or she cannot retroactively elect FSA
coverage.<P>

The IRS also noted that if a return from leave without pay constitutes a change
in family status under a cafeteria plan, an employee who returns from FMLA leave
can make a new medical FSA election for the remainder of the plan year.<P>

<h3>March 20 Comment Deadline</h3><P>

Written comments and requests for a public hearing are being received by the IRS
until March 20, 1996. Submissions should be sent to CC:DOM:CORP:R (EE-20-95),
Room 5228, Internal Revenue Service, P.O.B. 7604, Ben Franklin Station,
Washington, D.C. 20044. For more details about the regulations, call Catherine
Fuller at 202/622-6080. For information about written comments and the public
hearing, call Mike Slaughter at 202/622-8452.<P>

Employers may rely on the proposed FMLA regulations until the IRS issues final
regulations. The regulations are provided in this month's supplement to the
<i>Handbook</i>, in Appendix B.  <P>

</body> 

