<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Data Bank Finally Repealed</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/benehead.gif" alt="Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin"></center>
<P>
<P>
<h2>Data Bank Finally Repealed</h2>
</P>

<P>
Legislation formally repealing a controversial federal rule that required employers to report health coverage data to the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) was signed into law (Public Law No. 104-226) by President Clinton on Oct. 2.
</P>

<P>
Under the original requirement, which appeared in the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993, employers were required to report data to HCFA for calendar years beginning Jan. 1, 1994, and before Jan. 1, 1998. The first report was required to be filed no later than Feb. 28, 1995. The information was to have been used in a Medicare/Medicaid Data Bank to improve the identification of Medicare secondary payer cases and the ability to determine when employer plans should be the primary payer.  
</P>

<P>
Employers opposed the requirement from the outset, contending that it was administratively burdensome and expensive. A May 6, 1994, report by the U.S. General Accounting Office found that the data bank would have added significantly to employer recordkeeping, with no assurance that existing data on Medicare and Medicaid beneficiaries would improve. When that report was published, HCFA recommended that Congress enact legislation delaying implementation of the data bank for 18 months.
</P>

<P>
In response to employer concerns, a conference agreement accompanying an FY 1995 appropriations bill funding the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)--HCFA's parent agency--stated that no funds were to be used to implement the data bank. In October 1994, HCFA announced that employers would not have to comply with the rule.
</P>

<P>
However, the requirement was technically still on the books, and several legislative efforts to repeal the rules were unsuccessful. As the 1996 reporting date drew closer, an HHS appropriations bill again did not include funding for the data bank, and HCFA informally stated that it would not enforce the rule.
</P>

<P>
The law's path to enactment was almost a year long. It was introduced in November 1995 as H.R. 2685 by Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., and passed the House in March. The Senate did not approve the measure until Sept. 25, 1996. Clinton signed the bill a week later, officially consigning the data bank to history.
</P>



<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/bene.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/smallbene.gif"  alt="Return to Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
<center><h6>&#169; 1996 Thompson Publishing Group / <a 
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

</body> 
