<html> <title> How DOL's Wage &amp; Hour Division Conducts an Investigation</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/file/filehead.gif" alt="FLSA Employee Exemption Handbook">
<P>
<h2> How DOL's Wage &amp; Hour Division Conducts an Investigation</h2>
<body>
<P>

The Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) authorizes the U.S. Department of Labor (DOL)
to investigate and gather data concerning wages, hours and other employment
practices; to enter and inspect an employer's premises and records without a
subpoena; and to question employees to determine whether any person has violated
the provisions of the act.<P>

Investigations may occur if DOL receives a complaint from an employee or some
other individual, an improper practice is found in a particular industry, or as
part of a general plan to review as many contractors' practices as possible.
Frequently, because DOL investigators are required to treat complaints
confidentially, an employer may not know the reason for an investigation.<P>

Generally, investigations will extend back two years. However, an investigation
may extend back three years if the DOL investigator has received prior approval
from a DOL area director and regional solicitor. In general, DOL investigations
will go back three years if the agency anticipates the examination will result in
litigation.<P>

Usually, DOL investigators will inform an employer of the time and date of an
investigation. In addition, an investigator will tell the employer what records
will be reviewed.<P>

<h3>Interviews With Employers, Employees</h3><P>

During the first interview with an employer, an investigator will outline for the
employer the scope of the investigation, including documents to be reviewed and
employees to be interviewed. Typically, an investigator reviews documents to
determine coverage of individual employees under the FLSA (e.g., whether they are
exempt from the laws' minimum wage and overtime provisions). Subsequently, the
investigator will usually interview employees to test the adequacy and accuracy
of records and help determine the validity of alleged violations. The interview
also gives employees the opportunity to point out other suspected violations.<P>

Interviews are conducted without the employer or its representative present, and
all information given by employees during the interview is kept confidential.
Conversely, the investigator will not give the employee any information obtained
from the investigator's review of the employer's records.<P>

When the fact-finding portion of the investigation is completed, the investigator
will hold a conference with the employer and inform the employer of the
investigation results. In cases where an employee has corrected past monetary
violations by full payment of back wages prior to an investigation, the
investigator will not treat these as violations. Nor will the investigator treat
minor bookkeeping errors as violations. However, if the investigator has found
FLSA violations, he or she will inform the employer of the steps needed to
correct the violations.<P>

During the conference with the employer, the investigator may initiate
negotiation of payment of back wages to employees, or attempt to encourage the
employer to comply with the FLSA. However, the conference will not be the
employer's last opportunity to negotiate with DOL should the employer choose not
to agree to back-wage payments at that time. In deciding whether to challenge
DOL's findings regarding back wages due, the employer should take into account
the strength of its legal position and the possibility of protracted and
expensive litigation should DOL decide to file a complaint against the
employer.<P>

<h3>Minimizing FLSA Liability</h3><P>

There are several ways an employer can minimize interruption caused by a DOL
investigation as well as reduce its FLSA liability.  The employer should
cooperate with the DOL investigator and provide the requested information and
employees for interviews. A cooperative attitude is likely to expedite the
investigation and produce a minimal amount of disturbance in the workplace. In
addition, the employer should not attempt to pressure or intimidate employees who
are to be interviewed by the DOL investigator, as the investigator is sure to ask
the employees if they have been pressured by their employer to give certain
answers.<P>

Also, the employer should ensure that it is in compliance with the FLSA before
being investigated by the DOL. Although almost every large employer makes some
inadvertent errors in overtime calculations or employee classifications, the
employer's liability will be greatly diminished if it is substantially in
compliance with the FLSA.<P>

Employers' payroll departments should understand how to compute overtime
calculations, and human resources departments should understand how to classify
employees under the FLSA and treat exempt employees to maintain their exempt
status. Further, employers should determine and review the exempt status of
employees on a regular basis in accordance with FLSA regulations. Hiring an
outside consultant to conduct classification studies and examine overtime and
leave policies can be beneficial. In addition, employers should listen carefully
to their employees' complaints and be sensitive to their dissatisfactions.
Resolving potential FLSA problems before an employee complains to DOL is an
employer's best solution to potential investigations. 


</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
