<HTML>
<head>
<title> VCR Program Changes Expected; IRS Inundated With Submissions</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/mend/mendhead.gif" alt="Pension Plan Fix-It
 Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>VCR Program Changes Expected; IRS Inundated With Submissions</h2>

<P>
<i>By Paul M. Hamburger</i><P>

We have been hearing a great deal lately about the IRS Voluntary Compliance
Resolution (VCR) Program. Now, with the IRS stepping up its plan audit activity,
plan sponsors will be giving more thought to finding their compliance errors
ahead of time and submitting them to the IRS for approval. This has proven to be
so true that the VCR Program is overwhelmed with submissions. <P>

The number of IRS submissions under the VCR Program has increased so dramatically
that the IRS has taken steps to speed up processing. Many of these steps are not
published in any formal guidance and will not be published soon -- they are known
to those who have made a number of current VCR submissions. Others will be
announced through changes in the IRS employee plans manual.<P>

<h3>Key Administrative Rules</h3><P>

Here are some of the key administrative rules that the IRS reviewers have
followed to expedite the VCR submission process:<P>
<UL>

<LI>The actual plan language related to the qualification defect does not always
have to be submitted. If it is a fairly common plan provision (like
nondiscrimination testing in a 401(k) plan or required minimum distribution
language), the IRS will accept the word of the party making the submission that
plan operation did not conform to the plan document.<P>

<LI>Detailed schedules and data concerning the dollar amounts of correction for
each affected individual are not necessary. Instead, the submission need only
describe the overall amount necessary to correct, the manner in which the
correction will be accomplished, and the number of employees affected.<P>

<LI>Some of the correction rules are being relaxed. For example, if an
overpayment of plan benefits has been made and the amounts are relatively small,
the IRS will not likely require that the plan pursue the overpaid participants.
<P>

<LI>In a defined benefit plan that has overpaid annuity payments, for example, if
a participant has been overpaid less than $20 per month, the IRS may consider
allowing the plan to continue making the overpayment rather than cause concern
among affected plan participants by reducing pension payments to the amount
required by the plan. This is particularly likely if the overpaid participants
are not highly compensated employees (HCEs).</UL><P>

In another important change, the IRS will not always require that plan sponsors
who have violated the Section 401(k) nondiscrimination tests in past years
contribute amounts to nonhighly compensated employees (NHCEs). According to VCR
published procedures (those in the standardized VCR Program), the IRS typically
requires that corrections for nondiscrimination testing require that
contributions be made for all NHCEs. That way, the HCEs will be allowed to keep
the otherwise discriminatory excess contributions that should have been refunded
in previous years.<P>

Sometimes, however, making contributions for all NHCEs can be very costly.
However, if the plan were allowed merely to refund, with interest, excess amounts
to HCEs, the funds could come from the plan and the cost of correction would be
significantly less to the employer. <P>

Current (but unpublished) VCR procedures allow for a return of excess
contributions to HCEs to solve the nondiscrimination testing problem only if the
cost of the corrective contribution exceeds five times the cost of distributions
to HCEs. <P>

Under a change that the IRS is considering for submissions made after Dec. 31,
1996, the employer could correct a nondiscrimination testing failure by
distributing $1 for every $1 contributed to the plan by the employer. In some
cases, this could be a significant savings in terms of corrective contributions.
But because the IRS does not intend to publish this rule soon, sponsors wishing
to submit their 401(k) plans to the VCR Program for correction of
nondiscrimination testing should check with the VCR Program reviewers before
filing to verify that a proposed method of correction is acceptable.<P>

<h3>Changes to the APRS</h3><P>

In addition to the VCR Program changes, the IRS is considering changing its
"administrative policy regarding sanctions" (APRS).<P>

The APRS is not a formal program. Rather, IRS auditors looking at plan
qualification errors will consider the severity of any problems they find. If the
qualification defect is <i>de minimis</i>, the IRS reviewer may choose to apply
the APRS and indicate that the problem will be overlooked.<P>

Plan sponsors who are under audit can ask the IRS to consider a defect (or
defects) for APRS treatment; however, the IRS has the final say. <P>

The biggest limitation of the APRS has been its restrictive eligibility
requirements. For example, if a plan has more than one type of defect in a single
year, it is technically not eligible for APRS treatment.<P>

The IRS has been considering changes for late 1996 or early 1997 to the APRS
program that will allow plan sponsors to self-correct a broad range of
qualification errors without having to obtain IRS approval. In this way, a
sponsor could correct errors for one plan year by the end of the next plan year
and retain its qualification without having to file with the IRS.<P>

For more information on the VCR Program, see &#182;1113 of the <i>Handbook</i>.
For more information on the APRS, see &#182;1111. <P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/mend/mend.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/mend/smallmend.gif" 
alt="Return to Pension Plan Fix-It Handbook Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
