<html> <title>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear QDRO Case</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/signhead.gif" alt="Guide to Assigning &amp; 
 Loaning Benefit Plan Money"></center>
<P>
<h3><i>QDROs</i></h3><P>
<h2>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear QDRO Case</h2>
On Nov. 1, 1996, the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to review an important QDRO
decision, <i>Boggs v. Boggs.</i> In the <i>Boggs </i>decision, the Fifth U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals held that ERISA did not preempt Louisiana's community
property law. <P>

As reported in the June 1996 issue of <i>Current Developments,</i> the Fifth
Circuit's decision created a split between its views and those expressed by the
Ninth Circuit in <i>Ablamis v. Roper </i>(937 F.2d 1450) as well as the
Department of Labor (see DOL Adv. Op. 90-46A, Dec. 4, 1990).<P>

In the case, the participant, Isaac Boggs, was married for 34 years to Dorothy
Boggs. Dorothy died and Isaac married Sandra Boggs, who survived Isaac when he
died. Isaac named Sandra as his surviving spouse for his pension benefits and she
was the named beneficiary of his life insurance benefits. Isaac and Dorothy's
children sought a portion of these benefits based on Louisiana's community
property law. Sandra argued that ERISA's anti-assignment rule preempted
application of state community property laws. <P>

The Fifth Circuit rejected this argument. The court also rejected the arguments
for ERISA preemption that were raised by the Department of Labor. <P>

Because of the clear split between the Fifth and Ninth Circuits on this point,
the U.S. Supreme Court decided to hear the case. Assuming that the Court follows
what seems to be the clear intent of Congress in passing the QDRO rules in the
first place, it is likely that it will find that ERISA does, in fact, preempt the
application of community property rules insofar as those rules affect the
disposition of qualified pension or profit sharing funds in the absence of a
QDRO.<P>

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/sign.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/smallsign.gif"  alt="Return to Guide to Assigning &amp; 
Loaning Benefit Plan Money Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
<center><h6>(c) 1996 Thompson Publishing Group / <a 
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

