<html> 
<head>
<title> Public Employer's Guide to FLSA Employee Classification </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/self/selfhead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to Self-Insuring Health Benefits"></center>
<P>
<h2>Supreme Court to Hear ERISA Preemption Case Next Year</h2>

The Supreme Court is scheduled to hear an ERISA preemption case early next year
regarding a New York tax on health care services. The case will be heard between
January and April, said a court spokeswoman.<P>

In the case, <i>DeBuono v. NYSA-ILA Medical and Clinical Services Fund,</i> U.S.
Sup.Ct, No. 95-1594, (dated Oct. 15, 1996), the Court will decide whether a
state tax affecting two New York health care facilities operated by ERISA funds
is preempted by ERISA.<P>

The NYSA-ILA Fund is an ERISA-regulated multiemployer, labor management trust
fund established through collective bargaining agreements. It administers an
employee welfare benefit plan that provides medical, dental and other health
care services to ERISA plan participants. These benefits are provided through
three medical centers the fund operates--two in New York and one in New
Jersey.<P>

In 1991, New York enacted a health facility assessment (HFA) law, which imposed
a tax on gross receipts from patient care services and general operations of
in-state hospitals. The law, which was due to expire on April 1, 1992, was
amended to remain in force after that date.<P>

The fund filed suit in April 1992, claiming that ERISA preempted the tax as it
related to payments and contributions on health benefits. The suit also sought
restitution of the assessment taxes it had already paid.<P>

The state argued, however, that the HFA should not be preempted because it
covered ERISA plans by virtue of the plans' inclusion in a broader class of
entities subject to regulations. A federal district court in New York agreed,
saying the HFA was not preempted by ERISA because it has an "incidental impact
on ERISA plans."<P>

"The minimal tax imposed by the HFA is not great enough to pose a serious
economic threat to the plan, which might trigger preemption," the court said.
The amount of the assessment was six-tenths of one percent for the fund's
medical facilities.<P>

The Second Circuit, however, reversed the district court's decision, saying that
the HFA "depletes those assets earmarked for the provision of health care
benefits and, as a result, will cause the fund to reduce benefits provided
and/or charge beneficiaries more in the future for benefits received." (See
<i>NYSA-ILA Medical and Clinical Services Fund v. Axelrod,</i> 27 F.3d 823 (2nd
Cir. 1994).) That decision was ultimately vacated and remanded by the U.S.
Supreme Court because of the Court's ruling in <i>New York Conference of Blue
Cross vs. Travelers Ins.,</i> 131 L. Ed. 2d 695, (1995), which found that ERISA
does not preempt state laws which only have an indirect economic impact on ERISA
plans. However, the Second Circuit reaffirmed its original decision, saying it
was distinguished from <i>Travelers,</i> which involved a tax imposed on a third
party--insurance carriers--that provided health coverage. According to the
Second Circuit, the NYSA case involved no third party. Rather, the New York law
directly depleted the fund's assets and therefore has a direct affect on ERISA
plans. New York then requested the Supreme Court to review the case to determine
if the Second Circuit's opinion conflicts with the <i>Traveler's</i>
decision.<P>

<h3>Court Rejects AWP Case</h3>

The Supreme Court declined to review <i>CIGNA Healthplan of Louisiana v. State
of Louisiana,</i> 82 F. 3d 642 (5th Cir. 1996), in which the 5th Circuit Court
of Appeals ruled that Louisiana's any-willing-provider (AWP) law is preempted by
ERISA because it refers to and relates to ERISA plans.<P>

As a result of the court's ruling, the AWP law and other similar statutes cannot
require managed care groups to include any physician in their network who is
willing to abide by network terms and conditions.<P>

CIGNA Healthplan of Louisiana is a licensed HMO that provides prepaid coverage
for enrolled subscribers, including sponsors of ERISA plans. After excluding two
physicians from its network, CIGNA was notified by the attorney general's office
that a formal complaint had been filed charging them with violating the AWP law.
CIGNA, along with Connecticut General Life Insurance Co. (CGLIC), a licensed
health insurer that marketed CIGNA's network and used it in conjunction with
self-funded plans, sought a court judgment that the AWP statute was preempted by
ERISA.<P>

A lower court ruled in favor of CIGNA and CGLIC. The 5th Circuit affirmed that
decision. Before the 5th Circuit ruled in favor of CIGNA, the Supreme Court had
narrowed the scope of ERISA preemption in the <i>Travelers</i> case. The 5th
Circuit said the Supreme Court emphasized the appropriateness of preemption when
state statutes "mandate employee benefit structures or their administration." In
CIGNA's case, the appeals court said Louisiana's AWP law prohibits ERISA plans
from selecting a PPO that does not include any willing, licensed provider,
effectively requiring ERISA plans to buy benefits of a particular structure when
they contract with organizations like CIGNA and CGLIC.<P>

<h3>Court Rejects Two Other Cases</h3>

The Supreme Court declined to hear <i>Joseph Golden v. Kelsey-Hayes Co.,</i>
1996 U.S. App. LEXIS 539 (6th Cir. 1996), in which the 6th Circuit Court of
Appeals upheld a lower court's preliminary injunction against an employer,
reaffirming that, through rules of contract interpretation, courts will find
that rights accrue or vest under an agreement even if they are not explicitly
explained.<P>

The claim for vested benefits arose when a group of Kelsey-Hayes companies
reorganized and cut back on retiree benefits. There was a $500,000 per
beneficiary lifetime benefit cap, and increases to co-payments and annual
deductibles. In addition, a monthly payment that reimbursed Medicare premiums
for beneficiaries age 65 and older was eliminated. When plan participants and
beneficiaries challenged the cutbacks, the court said they would have to show
that both the employer and union intended to include a right to lifetime
benefits when they negotiated the collective bargaining agreements.<P>

The appeals court had ruled that evidence existed showing the plan sponsor's
intent to create vested rights to lifetime benefits through the collective
bargaining agreement and summary plan description.<P>

The Supreme Court also declined to hear <i>James E. Stiltner v. Beretta U.S.A.
Corp.,</i> 1996 U.S. App. LEXIS 1562 (4th Cir. 1996) in which the 4th Circuit
ruled that an employer's threat to stop providing "gratuitous" health benefits
to persuade a plan participant to drop his disability benefits claims does not
discriminate under ERISA because the employer was not obligated to provide the
benefits.<P>

James Stiltner began working for Beretta U.S.A. in November 1988 as an
independent contractor. He was hired full-time in February 1989, at which time
he received a letter describing his medical and long-term disability benefits,
which excluded coverage for pre-existing conditions. Beretta changed disability
insurers in 1990, and the new insurers also had exclusions for pre-existing
conditions.<P>

Stiltner suffered a heart attack--he had a heart condition when he began working
for Beretta--and stopped working in June 1990. He applied for disability
benefits but was denied. In 1992, he demanded that Beretta pay him more than
$330,000 in long-term disability benefits, claiming entitlement under the
employment contract. Beretta refused, but offered to pay him $3,000 and continue
to pay his health premiums if he agreed to release the company from all
liability on his disability claim.<P>

Stiltner sued, claiming that the SPD failed to mention the preexisting condition
exclusion and that the employment letter listed disability benefits as an
employment contract, obligating Beretta to provide the benefits. He also
asserted discrimination under ERISA Section 510.<P>

The lower court ruled in Beretta's favor. An appeals court panel initially
reversed the lower court's decision, but the full appeals court heard the case
and ruled in favor of Beretta. Citing the National Labor Relations Act, the
court defined discrimination under ERISA Section 510 as "actions affecting the
employer-employee relationship" and ruled that revoking a gratuitous benefit
does not interfere with the employer-employee relationship. "A benefit is merely
gratuitous when there is a lack of consistency or regularity in providing the
benefit and when there is no official program under which the benefits are
provided," the court said, adding that, conversely, nongratuitous benefits are
provided regularly and consistently and are protected under ERISA Section 510.
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/self/self.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/self/smallself.gif"  alt=" Employer's Guide to Self-Insuring Health Benefits Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
