<html> 
<head>
<title>Health Benefits May Vest With Termination of LTD Plan Based on Employer
Promises, Appeals Court Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/self/selfhead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to Self-Insuring Health Benefits"></center>
<P>
<h2>Health Benefits May Vest With Termination of LTD Plan Based on Employer
Promises, Appeals Court Rules</h2>

Although a reservation of rights provision prevented vesting of health benefits,
an ambiguously worded exception to the nonvesting provision exposed an employer
to providing lifetime medical benefits for participants on long-term disability
(LTD), a federal appeals court ruled in <i>Leo W. Chiles v. Ceridian Corp.,</i> 1996
U.S. App. LEXIS 24450 (10th Cir. Sept. 19, 1996).<P>

An LTD plan's ambiguous summary plan description (SPD) prevails over clear
language in the master plan documents and reasonably could be read to provide
employer-paid medical benefits as long as participants are disabled, the court
said.<P>

The court said welfare benefits generally do not vest, but a contractual right
to lifetime health benefits may be created. Here, the SPD appeared to have made
an exception to the reservation of rights if the LTD plan was terminated. Plan
termination issues typically arise under retirement plans, not with group
welfare plans where there is scant legal guidance, the court noted.<P>

Nonetheless, the court found that the LTD plan had been terminated upon sale of
the employer and transfer of the LTD obligations to the buyer; however, the SPD
was unclear whether it meant to automatically vest health benefits upon the LTD
plan's termination. The appeals court sent the case back to the lower court for
a finding on that issue, and on whether the participants must show reliance on
the apparent promise of health benefits.<P>

<h3>Facts of the Case</h3>
Control Data provided an LTD plan through its subsidiary, Imprimis. Control Data
provided a range of ERISA benefits through a master plan document. The LTD
plan's SPD stated the company would pay premiums for all benefits until plan
participants were no longer eligible for disability coverage.<P>

Control Data sold Imprimis to Seagate Technology. As part of the sale, Seagate
agreed to administer the disabled participants' rights according to Control Data
plan terms. Control Data transferred assets to Seagate to cover projected
liabilities under the plan. Seagate then created a new LTD plan for the Control
Data plan participants. When the sale was pending, Control Data informed
employees that it would continue to pay for health coverage for those in the LTD
plan; however, three years later employees were required to pay part of the
premiums.<P>

Control Data's ERISA plans contained amendment and termination provisions, with
the SPD of each plan stating that Control Data reserved that the right to change
or discontinue the plan. The SPDs retained the employer's right to terminate the
plan "at any time." The LTD master plan's reservation of rights provided that
notwithstanding the termination of the LTD plan, a participant who is totally
disabled on the effective date of termination "shall continue to receive
benefits in accordance with" the plan terms. The SPD similarly stated that plan
participants who were totally disabled on the termination date will have
continued disability coverage as long as they remain totally disabled.<P>

Upon being told they would have to pay part of the health premiums, the former
employees claimed that: (1) the benefits had vested by plan terms; (2) even if
the health benefits had not vested upon qualification for LTD, the LTD plan
guaranteed the benefits would vest for all those disabled at the time the LTD
plan was terminated; and (3) the LTD plan did terminate when Control Data sold
Imprimis to Seagate.<P>

The appeals court noted that courts consistently have ruled that group welfare
benefits--unlike pension benefits--do not vest under ERISA unless the employer
contractually agrees to grant vested benefits.<P>

The 10th Circuit noted that courts have not ruled so consistently, though, when
there is an alleged promise of retiree lifetime medical benefits and a general
reservation of rights provision. But, the court continued, the weight of case
authority supports the approach that a general reservation of rights clause
allows the employer to retroactively change the medical benefits even in the
face of clear language promising company-paid lifetime benefits.<P>

Here, the court said, it was not faced with the problem of a general reservation
of rights clause. Rather, the reservation of rights provision explicitly related
to the LTD benefits and clearly retained Control Data's right to change the
benefits of all LTD plan participants. Thus, there was no general contractual
vesting of health benefits.<P>

However, the SPD did seem to create an exception to that reservation of rights
for when the plan terminated. Thus, the court had to determine whether the
Control Data LTD plan terminated when Imprimis was sold to Seagate, or was just
modified as Control Data and Seagate contended.<P>

<h3>Plan Had Terminated</h3>
After noting the lack of legal precedent regarding welfare plan termination, the
court found the Control Data LTD plan was terminated based on four factors: <P>
<OL>
<LI>new trustees were appointed to a replacement plan instituted by Seagate;<P>
<LI>Seagate became the administrator of the new plan;<P>
<LI>Control Data transferred money to fund the new plan; and<P>
<LI>after the transfer Seagate assumed all of Control Data's obligations for
disability plan participants.<P>
</OL>

The court further pointed out that essential features of an ERISA plan include a
procedure for establishing and carrying out a funding policy for the plan and
procedures for plan operation and administration. After Imprimis was sold, the
responsibilities for funding and administering disability benefits shifted to
the Seagate LTD Plan.<P>
<h3>SPD Prevails</h3>
Control Data and Seagate contended the LTD plan's documents could not support a
conclusion that the term "benefits" included payment of health premiums. But the
court said when plan documents and SPD conflict, the SPD prevails. The SPD
stated that the company would pay the premiums for all benefits for those on
LTD. Another part of the SPD clearly states that the company pays the health
care premiums for employees on short-term or long-term disability.<P>

The court concluded the former employees had successfully argued that a
reasonable person could find the SPD to include payment of health premiums as a
benefit to which persons on LTD status are entitled.<P>

This did not mean the former employees automatically became entitled to health
coverage, however. The court said the benefits are available only where
employees rely on an ambiguous or faulty SPD, or otherwise show prejudice from
the inconsistency between the SPD and the master plan document. The court left
the issue of reliance to the lower court.<P>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>
In addition to underscoring the importance of clear and consistent document
drafting, the ruling applies law developed for retiree medical benefits to LTD
plans. In doing so, the court follows a line of reasoning that welfare benefits
do not vest statutorily upon retirement or upon LTD status, but may vest
contractually by virtue of employer and plan sponsor promises. In addition, the
court helps to fill a void of guidance on group welfare benefits terminations.
When a welfare benefits plan terminates, particularly a group health plan, after
the sale of a subsidiary can have implications for COBRA continuation of health
benefits, and who is obligated to provide the continued health coverage. There
also can be implications under Medicare Secondary Payer (MSP) rules, such as
whether the disabled still have employee status, and which coverage is primary
and secondary.
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/self/self.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/self/smallself.gif"  alt=" Employer's Guide to Self-Insuring Health Benefits Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
