<html>
<head>
<title> Adoption Assistance Finds Its Place in the Employee Benefits Spectrum</title>
</head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/dischead.gif" alt="Employer's Handbook: Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules"></center>

<h2>Adoption Assistance Finds Its Place in the Employee Benefits Spectrum</h2>

<P>
Benefits costs, especially for group health insurance, are continuing to rise, forcing many employers to transfer some premium expenses to employees. To soften this blow and preserve employee morale, employers are looking for low-cost, highly visible additions to their basic benefits packages. What they are frequently hitting upon to answer some of their needs is the adoption assistance plan.
</P>

<P>
And Congress has recently lent its legislative power to strengthening this benefit. Under a provision in the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996, employers can provide their employees with up to $5,000 per adoption, tax-free ($6,000 for special needs adoptions), beginning in January. (See the September 1996 issue of <I>Current Developments</I>, p. 3, for more information on the exclusion.)
</P>

<P>
The new exclusion has sparked employers' interest. But will it encourage more of them to launch adoption plans?
</P>

<P>
According to the National Adoption Center, approximately 100,000 families in the U.S. adopt each year. That number, when distributed across the nation's workforce, means a single employer will spend few of its total benefits dollars on adoption assistance.
</P>

<P>
But those few dollars can advance an employer's larger goals -- achieving benefits equity, improving industry competitiveness and strengthening employee loyalty and productivity. Employers that offer adoption assistance have discovered that, for a small investment, it delivers a high rate of return.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Adopting the Adoption Benefit</H3>
</P>

<P>
Steve Humerickhouse, founder of the Minneapolis-based Adoption Advocates, believes the number of plans will increase as employer awareness of the exclusion for adoption assistance spreads. "We're finding an immense number of employers looking at adoption assistance. The [recently enacted] exclusion could push them to actually implement the benefit," he says.
</P>

<P>
Helen Berry, senior benefits specialist at Lotus Development Corp., in Cambridge, Mass., also sees the benefit from this benefit. "If you're looking for a low-cost benefit that doesn't involve a lot of additional work, adoption assistance is a great way to go. Our employees really appreciate it and the price tag is right."
</P>

<P>
Adoption assistance programs are not new to the workplace; some employers have offered the benefit for many years. For example, Hallmark Cards Inc., in Kansas City, Mo., instituted adoption assistance benefits more than 15 years ago, according to Tresia Franklin, manager of benefits administration. "We're a very family-oriented company," she says.
</P>

<P>
Other companies have only recently introduced adoption benefits. Bell Atlantic Corp., a mid-Atlantic telecommunications provider, implemented its adoption assistance program as part of a union contract last July. "It's very new, but so far we've had about 60 inquiries and have helped about 5 employees to locate adoption agencies," says Joan Rasmussen, company spokesperson for Bell Atlantic.
</P>

<P>
As of 1995, only 23 percent of major U.S. employers offered adoption assistance benefits, according to a survey by Hewitt Associates. But, as employers search for cost-effective benefits, this percentage is likely to grow.
</P>

<P>
Adoption assistance benefits can include any combination of three major components -- financial assistance, paid or unpaid leave and resource and referral services. The most successful packages include each component in some form.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Achieving Benefits Equity For All Parents</H3>
</P>

<P>
Both employers and adoption assistance advocates usually cite benefits equity as the most important reason why employers should offer adoption benefits. "Most employers offer benefits for employees that have children born to them. The same rationale should apply to adoptive families because they're doing the same thing -- building stable families," says Patrick Purtill, director of government relations for the National Council for Adoption, in Washington, D.C.
</P>

<P>
When Suzanne Camp, adoption benefits coordinator at the National Adoption Center, in Philadelphia, speaks with employer groups, she asks them to "think about the maternity benefits you offer -- what is the relative cost of the insurance providing those benefits." She then explains to employers that adoptive parents should receive similar benefits.
</P>

<P>
Companies are beginning to consider this perspective that benefits equity matters to all employees. Employers that offer maternity benefits under the umbrella of their group health plans are now recognizing that some of their employees build families through adoption and should receive comparable benefits to ease the transition.
</P>

<P>
"We realize there are costs involved with adoptions. We wanted to make this benefit available to help employees," says Mary Lou Simmermacher,  a press relations representative with Hewlett-Packard Co., in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>

<P>
For employees at Eastman Kodak Co., in Rochester, N.Y., adoption assistance is "a reasonable benefit," says Paul Allen, manager of corporate media relations. "Parents that have to go the adoption route to form a family are not able to take advantage of the medical coverage available through maternity benefits. Adoption assistance rounds out our benefits program."
</P>

<P>
Lotus instituted adoption assistance benefits more than five years ago to "even the score" between birth and adopting parents. "We saw that our female employees received medical coverage and maternity leave," says Berry. "But we couldn't offer that to adopting parents under the existing benefits program. Adoption assistance gives those parents time to be with their child."
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>A Low-Cost Benefit</H3>
</P>

<P>
The low cost of adoption assistance benefits appeals to many employers. Because utilization rates hover between 1/2 percent and 2 percent of the employee population, even employers that provide the maximum $5,000 excludable benefit will spend relatively little for adoption assistance, accounting for a small percentage of total benefits dollars. For that minimal investment, Camp says, many employers feel "they're doing something good for their community."
</P>

<P>
Employers can reimburse many types of expenses -- adoption agency fees, legal fees and court costs, medical expenses of the child prior to adoption, temporary foster care expenses, travel and lodging expenses, and in cases of international adoption, immigration and naturalization fees, and immunization and translation fees.
</P>

<P>
Adoptions, even when arranged through nonprofit agencies, are expensive. According to Purtill, domestic adoption costs can average between $14,000 and $22,000. International adoptions, because they "involve more work and travel to extremely expensive areas like Moscow and Beijing," will cost even more, he adds.
</P>

<P>
Adoptive families finance these expenses just about any way they can. Families will tap personal savings, credit cards and family loans. "A lot of people are forced to take out second mortgages," Purtill says.
</P>

<P>
The reimbursement caps used by companies interviewed for this article range from $2,000 to $5,000. According to the 1995 Hewitt report, the reimbursement caps of about 79 percent of employers surveyed fell within this same range.
</P>

<P>
For example, Lotus reimburses up to $2,500 per finalized adoption for eligible expenses, including agency, placement and legal fees, medical examinations and temporary foster care.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Parental Leave Includes Parents Who Adopt</H3>
</P>

<P>
Many employers also have applied the concept of benefits equity to their leave policies for adopting parents. Adopting parents often need leave time for reasons beyond welcoming a child into the home. Adoption agency home studies, visits with their children while in temporary foster care, or travel to another region or country all require leave. A flexible adoption or parental leave policy that accommodates a wide range of needs can help adopting parents.
</P>

<P>
Hewlett-Packard employees can request up to one year of unpaid leave, even though most do not use the full year.
</P>

<P>
At Lotus, adopting parents receive up to 20 days of paid parental leave after their first year with the company, accrued at 2.5 days per month. They can use this paid leave as part of their leave under the federal Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Resource and Referral Services Give Employees A Head Start</H3>
</P>

<P>
Resource and referral services are a critical -- and relatively inexpensive -- benefit. For employees exploring the adoption option, the information gathering process can require many time-consuming telephone calls -- often only possible during working hours. Resource and referral services can streamline this process, benefiting both employers and employees. And adoption services can be incorporated into an employer's existing "work/life" program.
</P>

<P>
Bell Atlantic, Hewlett-Packard and Lotus use outside service providers. Hewlett-Packard's range of services includes practical information on the financing of adoptions, adoption options, local resources, referrals to reputable adoption agencies, and help coordinating it all.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Getting the Word Out</H3>
</P>

<P>
An adoption assistance program's success -- from achieving an almost hassle-free administration to using the benefit to communicate company culture and values -- depends on how an employer communicates the benefit's availability to its workforce.
</P>

<P>
Some common ways to communicate include paycheck stuffers, information brochures, work site seminars and benefits fairs. Almost all employers include information in their benefits handbooks. Many also publish announcements or news stories in their company newsletters.
</P>

<P>
At Amgen Inc., a biotechnology company in Thousand Oaks, Calif., every new employee is given this information as part of the new hire orientation, says Lynne Connell, senior corporate communications specialist. Amgen also uses emerging technology -- its company "Intranet" (a sort of internal Internet accessible only to employees) -- to make benefits information available at all times.
</P>

<P>
Lotus uses its computing and software expertise to inform employees of their benefits options. All benefits materials, including adoption assistance information, are available online, using the company's own Notes program.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Interested, But Wondering How to Start?</H3>
</P>

<P>
Introducing a new employee benefit takes planning. One resource that can get you started is the National Adoption Center's Adoption and the Workplace initiative. The center, along with the Dave Thomas Foundation for Adoption, a public charity established by Dave Thomas, founder of the Wendy's chain of restaurants, has developed a guide to help employers set up adoption assistance plans.
</P>

<P>
The <I>Employer's Guide to Adoption Benefits</I> provides answers to many questions, as well as a model implementation plan that employers can adapt to their needs.
</P>

<P>
In addition, the National Adoption Center, with funding from the W. K. Kellogg Foundation, has established a national database of employers offering adoption assistance benefits. The database collects information on benefit eligibility rules, financial reimbursement caps, paid and unpaid leave policies and resource and referral services. Employers also can request adoption assistance benchmarking studies to help them develop industry-competitive programs.
</P>

<P>
To request these publications, or for more information on adoption assistance in the workplace, contact: Adoption Benefits Coordinator, National Adoption Center, 1500 Walnut St., Suite 701, Philadelphia, PA 19102; 215/735-9988; 1-800-TO-ADOPT; <A HREF="http://www.adopt.org/adopt">http://www.adopt.org/adopt</A>. 
</P>

<HR>
<P>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT><CENTER>Adoption Assistance Benefits Promote Industry Competitiveness</CENTER></H4>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
Using employee benefits to maintain and strengthen industry competitiveness has become an increasingly necessary strategy for employers. As more and more employees change jobs more frequently, the quality of an employer's benefits package has become crucial to recruiting and retaining employees.
</P>

<P>
In the 1990s, employers are developing "work/life" benefit programs to improve their ability to compete for skilled employees. And many are learning that adoption assistance can play an integral role in that recruitment process.
</P>

<P>
The availability of adoption assistance enhances an employer's image as an industry leader, setting the pace for benefits innovation. According to Suzanne Camp, adoption benefits coordinator at the National Adoption Center, many employers seek information about the benefits programs provided by others in their industries. "These employers want the best benefits programs out there," Camp says. "And more and more, that means offering adoption benefits."
Bell Atlantic analyzes what benefits other employers offer as a routine practice. "We review benefits trends to learn what we need to do to remain competitive in the marketplace," says company spokesperson Joan Rasmussen. "It's a very competitive industry for us. Employees are no longer spending as much time with one company. Benefits are one factor that help us attract a qualified workforce."
</P>

<P>
The high visibility of adoption assistance benefits also demonstrates an employer's commitment to supporting families and the larger communities in which they do business. That commitment to integrating work and family more smoothly draws skilled workers to an employer -- and can keep them there.
</P>

<P>
Paul Allen, manager of corporate media relations at Eastman Kodak, says that, although adoption benefits represent only one component of the company's benefits program, it's one that "helps attract good employees. It fills a benefits niche and keeps us competitive."
</P>

<P>
A cutting-edge benefits program also can promote a company's competitiveness by improving its productivity. When an employer communicates through its benefits program that what's good for its workers is good for business, employee loyalty thrives, boosting productivity. And the heightened morale doesn't just come from employees who use a particular benefit, such as adoption assistance. It permeates the company's culture. Tresia Franklin, manager of benefits administration at Hallmark Cards, says, "Adoption benefits are a good morale booster even for people who don't use it."
</P>

<P>
"Really trying to manage work-life. That's what it's all about," explains Helen Berry, senior benefits specialist at Lotus. "It's fast-paced and stressful here; we work hard. But people know it's a caring environment because of our benefits -- adoption assistance, spousal equivalent benefits, wellness programs, paid parenting leave. People appreciate it and it shows."
</P>

</FONT>
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/disc.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/smalldisc.gif"
alt="Return to Employer's Handbook: Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
