<html> <title>New HCE Definition Eases Nondiscrimination Testing -- But Not for Flex
Plans</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/flexhead.gif" alt="Flex Plan
 Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>New HCE Definition Eases Nondiscrimination Testing -- But Not for Flex
Plans</h2>
The Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996, enacted in August, includes a host
of long-awaited measures that will simplify the complex nondiscrimination tests
that apply to retirement plans and certain types of welfare plans. That's good
news for sponsors of retirement plans, including defined benefit pension plans
and various forms of defined contribution plans, such as 401(k) plans.<P>

There's bad news for flex plan sponsors, however: The new, simplified rules do
not apply to Section 125 plans. <P>

Among the new rules is a simplified definition of a highly compensated employee
(HCE) as specified by Code Section 414(q). This HCE definition is a critical
element of many of the different nondiscrimination tests that must be applied to
various types of employee benefit plans.<P>

Unfortunately, the new HCE definition will not affect benefits that use
definitions of highly paid employees other than the one spelled out in Code
Section 414(q). This category of benefits includes Section 125 plans. Under
Section 125, cafeteria plans -- but not the benefits provided through these plans
-- must use an imprecise definition of a "highly compensated participant" for
purposes of the benefits/eligibility test (see &#182;710) and a "key
employee" standard for purposes of the concentration test (see &#182;720).
<P>

Section 125 plans are not the only plans that are unable to take advantage of the
new, simplified HCE definition:<P>
<UL><P>
<LI>self-insured health plans use a "highly compensated individual" definition
under Section 105 (see &#182;741); and <P>
<LI>under Code Section 79, group term life insurance plans use the same "key
employee" definition used in the Section 125 concentration test (see
&#182;742). </UL><P>
Of the benefits discussed in the <i>Handbook, </i>in fact, the new, simplified
definition of an HCE under Section 414(q) will affect only Section 129 dependent
care assistance plans (see &#182;743).<P>
<P>
<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/flex.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/smallflex.gif"  alt="Return to Flex Plan Handbook 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
