<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Allocating Medicare Revenues Among Providers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/pattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif"><BR>
<HR>
<H1><CENTER>Medicare Managed Care Manual</CENTER></H1>
<HR>
<H2>Allocating Medicare Revenues Among Providers</H3>
<H3>by C. Keith Powell, Esq.</H3>
One of the crucial questions a managed care organization (MCO) with a Medicare
risk contract must answer is how to allocate its revenues across provider
categories. Many MCOs try to start the allocation process by finding out
what the national distributions of provider payments are and fitting them
into their particular risk contract.<BR>
<BR>
MCOs should be aware that cost-based distributions across different providers
are extremely difficult to construct with great accuracy for a local area,
and even if such a distribution can be built it is generally of little use
in structuring revenue flows under the Medicare risk contract.<BR>
<BR>
The following are practical guidelines that apply to national provider cost
distributions as well as the limitations inherent in any attempt to use
national distributions to structure revenue flows under the MCO's individual,
geographically specific risk contract.<BR>
<BR>
<B>National Versus Local Costs</B><BR>
<BR>
For any provider category, certain parts of the country will have high costs
and other parts low costs. Unfortunately, areas of the country that have
high costs for one provider class (such as hospitals) do not necessarily
have high costs for other providers. For example, in a given area, hospital
costs may be 50 percent higher than the national average while physician
costs may be 20 percent lower than average. In such a case, there is no
way that an MCO could safely assume that its percentage distribution of
costs could be based on the national average. While the disparity between
national and local costs is most evident in extreme cases, it is present
in all cases. <BR>
<BR>
<B>All Providers Are Not Equal</B><BR>
<BR>
Even if an MCO can learn the average cost level in an area for a particular
class of providers, it should be aware that costs can vary considerably
within that class. For instance, one large surgical group can have much
higher costs than another in the same area.<BR>
<BR>
Estimating costs among various local providers of the same class can grow
even more complex when the fact that one provider will generally be much
more willing than another to offer a large discount to the MCO to get its
business is taken into consideration.<BR>
<BR>
Because of these two factors, even if the cost level of a given provider
group can be determined, such information does not predict the &quot;proper&quot;
amount of revenue to pay to that provider because it may be possible to
negotiate an excellent discount.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Statutory and Market Issues</B><BR>
<BR>
Under a typical Medicare risk contract there is much less money available
to providers in the aggregate than provider cost data would indicate, and
some classes of providers are more willing than others to absorb these shortfalls.
This makes cost distributions less reliable for allocating Medicare risk
contract revenues.<BR>
<BR>
MCOs should keep in mind that they receive only 95 percent of the average
cost under a risk contract, and the MCO typically takes 7.5 percent to 10
percent out of that reimbursement for administrative costs. However, the
Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) includes only about 0.25 percent
for Part A and 2.0 percent for Part B administration (the government's actual
cost for the administrative work that will be passed on to the MCO). <BR>
<BR>
According to recently published statistics, most MCO risk contracts offer
additional health benefits without charging enrollees for these benefits.
For instance, nearly half the MCOs offering prescription drug benefits do
not charge enrollee premiums. Offering these additional benefits at no charge
to the enrollee results in an addition of $100 per member per month in health
benefits for which no revenue is received. Thus, overall, the amount of
money available to providers, after the MCO deducts its administrative overhead,
is often only about 70 percent or less of the cost of those services.<BR>
<BR>
In a setting in which only 70 percent of the cost equivalent money is available,
some providers are much more able to control costs than others. Also some
providers will want the additional business more than others - a decision
that relates to such issues as marginal cost, supply of those providers,
and acceptance of managed care concepts. However, other providers will not
be open to discounting. For instance, many hospitals and certain physicians
may take 50 percent cuts to become exclusive providers, vendors of prescription
drugs will not. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Revenue Distribution Examples</B><BR>
<BR>
While MCOs should keep in mind the caveats outlined above, they may find
it useful to see estimates of provider costs for the aged in 1996 based
on HCFA data.<BR>
<P>

<B>Table 1: Revenue Allocation Among Providers</B>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="5" CELLSPACING="1">

<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD><B>Provider</B></TD>	<TD><B>GPPP Costs</B></TD>	<TD><B>Remaining Costs</B></TD>	<TD><B>Percent</B></TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD><B>Part A</B></TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Inpatient Hospital </TD>	<TD>$2,523.26</TD>	<TD>$2,523.26</TD>	<TD>46.05%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Skilled Nurse Fac.</TD>	<TD>$347.17</TD>	<TD>$347.17</TD>	<TD>6.34%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>HHA</TD>	<TD>$472.48</TD>	<TD>$472.48</TD>	<TD>8.62%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Hospice</TD>	<TD>$92.68</TD>	<TD>$92.68</TD>	<TD>1.69%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD><B>Part B</B></TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Physician</TD>	<TD>$1,265.17</TD>	<TD>$1,493.95</TD>	<TD>26.70%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Outpatient Hospital</TD>	<TD>$432.47</TD>	<TD>$500.08</TD>	<TD>9.13%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>HHA</TD>	<TD>$5.14</TD>	<TD>$5.94</TD>	<TD>0.11%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Independent Lab</TD>	<TD>$64.30</TD>	<TD>$74.35</TD>	<TD>1.36%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>GPPP</TD>	<TD>$276.24</TD>	<TD>$0.00</TD>	<TD>0.00%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
<TD><B>Total</B></TD>	<TD><B>$5,478.91</B></TD>	<TD><B>5,478.91</B></TD>	<TD><B>100.00%</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

<HR SIZE="4">With regard to Table 1, MCOs should note that the HCFA database
cannot easily break out the costs of group practice prepayment plans (GPPPs)
across provider categories. The calculation in column two simply allocates
GPPP costs over the remaining provider calculation in proportion to the
given costs of the other categories. For instance, if hospitals constitute
50 percent of all of column one costs except for GPPPs, the 50 percent of
the total GPPP cost is allocated to hospitals. Column three shows the percent
of total costs for each of the indicated provider categories.<BR>
<BR>
While Table 1 treats Part A and Part B separately, Table 2 combines all
provider costs by merging Parts A and B and recalculates the total costs
and respective percentages for each provider classification.<BR>
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>Table 2: Merged Part A and Part B Costs</B>
<P>


<TABLE BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="5" CELLSPACING="1">


<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD><B>Provider</B></TD>	<TD><B>Total Costs</B></TD>	<TD><B>Percent of Total Costs</B></TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Hospital</TD>	<TD>$3,023.34</TD>	<TD>55.18%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Skilled Nurse Fac</TD>	<TD>$347.17</TD>	<TD>6.34%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>HHA</TD>	<TD>$478.43</TD>	<TD>8.73%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Hospice</TD>	<TD>$92.68</TD>	<TD>1.69%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Physician</TD>	<TD>$1,462.95</TD>	<TD>26.70%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD>Independent Lab</TD>	<TD>$74.35</TD>	<TD>1.36%</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT>
	<TD><B>Total</B></TD>	<TD><B>$5,478.91</B></TD>	<TD><B>100.00%</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE><P>


<HR SIZE="4">Note that Tables 1 and 2 show only the costs for the Medicare
program benefits, and do not include the cost of supplemental benefits added
to almost all Medicare risk contract packages. The HCFA numbers given for
the cost of Part A and Part B deductibles, and copayments are, at best,
national numbers, and do not reflect area cost differences - a grave problem
for the value of Part B coinsurance and a serious concern for Part A values.
<BR>

<B>Trends Over Time</B><BR>
<BR>
HCFA data, over time, offers MCOs insight into patterns of change in cost
distribution, although there is no guarantee that such trends will continue
or apply to a given set of providers.<BR>
<BR>
The overall portion of money going to hospitals since the Medicare program
began has not changed much, however, there has been a strong shift from
the inpatient hospital setting to outpatient care. In contrast, the portion
of money going to home health agencies has soared in the past decade. Recently,
skilled nursing facility costs have reversed historic declines, and appear
to be rising.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><I>C. Keith Powell is an attorney and an actuary specializing in health
care issues. He also is co-author of the </I>Medicare Managed Care Manual<I>.<BR>
</I><HR>
