<html> <title> ADA Compliance Guide Specialty Chapters--Tips</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/able/ablehead.gif" alt="ADA Compliance
Guide"></center>
<P>
<h2> ADA Compliance Guide Specialty Chapters--Tips</h2>
<body>
Throughout the "specialty" chapters, practical tips present different options for
achieving ADA compliance.<P>

For example, in the colleges and universities chapter, when reviewing ongoing
compliance in academic programs, tips for making academic modifications
include:<P>

<UL>
<LI>having copies of general information on academic policies and procedures
available in large print, braille or on tape to ensure that the information is
accessible to persons with a wide range of disabilities; and<P>

<LI>considering whether extending time limits for completing courses for graduation
might be a reasonable modification for a student with a disability.</UL><P>

In the courts and correctional facilities chapter, tips concerning a review of
policies and procedures include:<P>

<UL>
<LI>considering whether reasonable modifications need to be made to requirements
for filing certain documents or recording proceeds of inmate conferences, such as
permitting a non-cursive or alternative signature if an individual cannot write
his or her name; and<P>

<LI>ensuring that facilities used to house a sequestered jury are accessible.</UL><P>

There are many tips in the hotel chapter's discussion of existing facilities,
such as:<P>

<UL>
<LI>ensuring that an employee, such as a door attendant or bellhop, is always
available to open front doors that are too heavy for individuals with certain
disabilities to open unassisted, if a hotel does not install automatic doors or
levers that make opening the doors easier; and<P>

<LI>reducing "white" or background noise in lobbies and elevators (for example by
turning down or turning off piped-in music) as a readily achievable barrier
removal for people with hearing impairments.</UL><P>

</body> 

