<html> 
<head>
<title>Employee Relocation Programs Offer Benefits For Children, Parents and Spouses</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/perk/perkhead.gif" alt=" Employer's Guide to Fringe Benefit Rules"></center>
<P>
<h2>Employee Relocation Programs Offer Benefits For Children, Parents and Spouses</h2>

<P>
Two economic trends are having a profound influence on employer relocation policies today: the widespread belt-tightening corporate America has undertaken in recent years and the growing number of women in the workforce. 
</P>

<P>
Together, these trends have changed relocation policies to reflect employers' more solid commitment to work/life programs.
</P>

<P>
A survey of 191 organizations released last month by the Employer Relocation Council (ERC) shows how powerful these trends have become. Cris Collie, executive vice president of ERC in Washington, D.C., sees the industry "focusing increasingly on work-family issues, on how we should address everything that comes into play" when employees relocate.
</P>

<P>
Through the 1960s, 1970s and even the 1980s, Collie says, most transfers were connected either to employee promotion or development. Dad, the typical transferred employee, would announce the transfer and Mom and the kids would pack up and head toward upward mobility. But that scenario, he says, has "gone the way of the black and white television." 
</P>

<P>
In the 1990s, most transfers represent lateral career moves for employees, springing from company mergers, cost-cutting strategies and corporate reengineering. An employer reorganizes and needs an employee's specialized skills in another division. A company downsizes and can offer a valued employee continuing employment only at another branch across the country. In recent years, an employer's invitation to an employee to relocate has more frequently become an alternative to the pink slip.
</P>

<P>
Despite the tight job market for many middle managers -- the group most frequently relocated, according to the ERC survey -- employees rarely just accept a transfer. Instead, they more frequently ask employers, "What about my family? My spouse? My kids? My parents?" Employers are answering with comprehensive relocation policies, Collie explains, that "serve as tools to persuade the employee to accept the transfer and then to make that transfer work."
</P>

<P>
Today, a transfer's success or a failure closely correlates with the effort an employer expends involving and assisting the employee's family -- especially the "trailing" spouse. And more and more relocation policy-makers recognize that employees worrying about their unemployed and unhappy spouses, their unreliable child care and their aging parents cannot be focused and productive in their new jobs. So many companies have added a myriad of family assistance components to their relocation programs, including child care, elder care and career assistance for spouses.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Child Care and Schooling</H3>
</P>

<P>
The ERC survey reports that 25 percent of responding companies have established child care and schooling assistance policies for relocating employees. Another 10 percent provide similar services according to employee demand.
</P>

<P>
Almost every employer responding to ERC's survey indicated that the location and quality of schools in the new work area concern their relocating employees. Fifty percent of employers also report employee worries about the availability of reliable and affordable child care services in the new location.
</P>

<P>
Some employers provide employees with a simple list of child care facilities and schools convenient to the new home. Others conduct workshops, counsel parents on children's needs and fears during the move, and even reimburse babysitting costs to allow the trailing spouse to seek employment.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Elder Care</H3>
</P>

<P>
Collie also says that the importance of elder care assistance has increased recently and will probably be more in demand in the coming years. "Most relocating employees are between 25 and 40 and a growing number of them are members of the 'sandwich generation' with responsibilities for both their children and their parents," he notes. According to an earlier ERC survey in 1993, 17 percent of employers maintained a formal policy on elder care benefits. An additional 7 percent provided some form of benefits on a case-by-case basis.
</P>

<P>
But, Collie says, as the elderly population rapidly increases over the next 10 years, employers will need to develop relocation policies even more sensitive to employee concerns about their aging parents.
</P>

<P>
Employees want benefits that will allow them to continue caring for their parents as they did before the transfer. For those employees simply seeking reputable elder care facilities that won't decimate their budgets, about 59 percent of employers provide directories of services available in the new location. Slightly more than half of the companies in the ERC survey will treat elderly relatives as equally important members of their employees' households and will pay for their relocation if they already lived with the employees. And a few will move elderly relatives even if they are not living with the relocating family.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Assistance for Spouses</H3>
</P>

<P>
Transfers also are much more likely to involve dual-career couples than they did even 10 years ago. And although the typical relocating employee, according to the ERC survey, is still male, 35, in middle management and earning $55,000, his spouse is just as likely to be pursuing a career as important to the financial well-being of their family as his.
</P>

<P>
Assisting a spouse in securing new employment has become a highly requested relocation benefit. "While employers can't guarantee jobs for trailing spouses, they can do a lot of things to make the search easier," Collie says. And, according to the ERC survey, more employers now extend spousal assistance to the partners of unmarried employees. One-third of employers surveyed now reimburse at least some relocation expenses for the partner accompanying the relocating employee. And about 23 percent of employers provide employment assistance to domestic partners.
</P>

<P>
Employer willingness to help unmarried partners as well as married spouses during the relocation process suggests a greater awareness that each employee's situation is unique. Collie says that even the advances made in recent years to address employees' family concerns don't help other segments of the employee population, such as unmarried individuals and single parents, as substantially. "Relocation policies and benefits can't be one for all," he says. "Transfers must be handled on a case-by-case basis."
</P>

<P>
The search for new solutions, he predicts, will become one of the most important challenges confronting the relocation industry today.
</P>



<hr>
<center>
