<html> 
<head>
<title> ERISA Does Not Preempt State HMO Law, Magistrate Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/healhead.gif" alt="Mandated Health Benefits&#151;The COBRA Guide"></center>

<h2>ERISA Does Not Preempt State HMO Law, Magistrate Rules</h2>

An HMO must treat a divorced spouse as if she is still a plan participant--and
not charge her the full COBRA premium--because ERISA does not preempt a
Massachusetts HMO law mandating such coverage, according to a U.S. magistrate in
Massachusetts. The case is <I>Cellilli v. Cellilli</I>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 12667
(W.D. Mass. 1996).<P>

<H3>Facts of the Case</H3><P>

Mary Ellen Cellilli was covered as a dependent spouse under the group health plan
of her husband's employer, Northeast Utilities Service Co. CIGNA Healthcare of
Massachusetts--an HMO--administered the plan. In May 1994, Cellilli and her
husband divorced. Their divorce decree required Ms. Cellilli's ex-husband to
maintain her health coverage.<P>

Apparently, Cellilli believed that her coverage would continue as if she were
still a dependent spouse--without any additional premium. However, Northeast
terminated her from the plan and sent her a COBRA election notice (COBRA provides
that a divorce or legal separation is a qualifying event that entitles a
qualified beneficiary to up to 36 months of COBRA coverage. See &#182;1123 of the
<I>Handbook</I>.) The notice indicated that she would be entitled to elect COBRA
coverage at her own expense.<P>

In March 1995, Cellilli, apparently dissatisfied with her COBRA coverage, filed a
complaint in family court. She requested that the divorce decree be modified so
that Northeast and CIGNA continue to cover her like a dependent spouse. She
supported her argument with a Massachusetts law regarding the continuation of HMO
coverage.<P>

Under that law (Chapter 176G, Section 5A), a divorce judgment could order that a
spouse who was enrolled in an HMO prior to a divorce "shall be and remain
eligible for benefits under said contract . . .without additional premium . . .
until the remarriage of either the member or such spouse, or until such time as
provided by said judgment, whichever is earlier."<P>

Northeast and CIGNA removed the case to federal court. They then filed a motion
for summary judgment, alleging that the state law claim was preempted by ERISA.
In response, Cellilli argued that although ERISA generally preempts all state
laws affecting ERISA plans, the insurance "savings clause" barred preemption in
this case.<P>

<H3>Did ERISA Preempt the State Law?</H3><P>

The U.S. magistrate first noted that under the state law's "plain language,"
Cellilli was entitled to continue the HMO coverage "without additional premium,"
because she was the spouse of an HMO member prior to the divorce. Thus, unless
the law is preempted by ERISA, the magistrate indicated that the defendants'
refusal to continue Cellilli's coverage in that manner was probably an error. <P>

The magistrate then gave an overview of ERISA's preemption clause, which provides
that ERISA's provisions "shall supersede any and all State laws . . .[that]
relate to any employee benefit plan." The magistrate then noted that ERISA's
"savings clause" rescues from preemption any state law "which regulates
insurance." In turn, the savings clause is limited by the "deemer clause" which
states that an employee benefit plan is not considered to be an insurer or to be
engaged in the business of insurance under any state law that regulates insurance
companies or contracts. <P>

The magistrate determined that the HMO plan was an "employee benefit plan" under
ERISA, and the state law "relates to" such a plan. Therefore, the magistrate
analyzed the "crux" of the dispute--whether the state law regulates insurance
within the scope of ERISA's savings clause and, if so, whether it may still be
preempted under ERISA's deemer clause.<P>

<H3>The Savings Clause</H3><P>

According to the magistrate, whether a state law regulates the business of
insurance depends on whether the law: (1) spreads risk, (2) integrally affects
the relationship between the insurer and the insured, and (3) is limited to the
risk-spreading parties.<P>

The magistrate noted that "on its face," the state law did all three: (1) it
spoke of "additional insuring risks," "premiums" and "health insurance coverage";
(2) it referred to "the commissioner of insurance"; and (3) it integrally
affected the relationship between the risk- spreading parties--the HMO, its
doctors and the insured.<P>

Therefore, the magistrate concluded that the state law directly controlled the
terms of insurance contracts and was saved from ERISA preemption unless it was
excluded based on the deemer clause.<P>

<H3>The Deemer Clause</H3><P>

In applying the deemer clause, the magistrate noted a distinction between insured
plans and self-funded plans--which could not be deemed an insurance contract
regulated by the state.<P>

The HMO plan was "clearly" not self-funded, according to the judge. Specifically,
the judge indicated that Northeast: (1) offered 17 different options through
CIGNA--including 11 HMOs, and five self-funded plans; (2) stated in a publication
that it "self-funds [its] group insurance plan, except for HMO coverage;" and (3)
defined its self-funded plans as ones in which claims were paid from general
assets" and costs were based on claims experience, while Northeast paid fixed
rates for HMO enrollees.<P>

The magistrate then noted that HMOs and insurance companies share the "indicia of
the business of insurance"--for a fixed fee, the risk and responsibility of
providing benefits is shifted from a beneficiary to a third party insurer.
Accordingly, the magistrate ruled that the HMO was an insured plan unaffected by
the deemer clause and therefore subject to the state law. The magistrate remanded
the case to state court for further proceedings.<P>

In reaching its decision, the magistrate rejected several contentions by the
defendants that the state law was preempted by ERISA. For example, the defendants
argued that it would be too costly, and contrary to ERISA's goal of uniformity,
to comply with the state law. However, the magistrate was "not persuaded" by this
argument, concluding that: (1) no concrete evidence was offered to show that 
compliance with the state law would be unduly burdensome; and (2) it was not the
judge's concern if the ruling resulted in "some disuniformities."<P>

"As the Supreme Court has stated, 'disuniformities . . . are the inevitable
result of the congressional decision to 'save' local insurance regulation.
Arguments as to the wisdom of these policy choices must be directed at
Congress,'" the magistrate indicated. <P><HR>

<CENTER><H4>Practice Pointer</H4></CENTER>

<FONT SIZE="2">This case serves as a reminder for insured group health plans subject to COBRA.
As explained at &#182;2000, these plans must comply with <I>both</I> the federal COBRA
requirements and any state insurance laws governing continuation coverage rights.
Typically, insurers are familiar with these requirements and will be able to
provide employers with information on any administrative differences from COBRA.</FONT>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/heal.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/smallheal.gif" 
alt="Return to Mandated Health Benefits&#151;The COBRA Guide Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
