<HTML>
<TITLE>
EPA's Self-Policing and Self-Disclosure Interim Policy </TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/fixx/fixxhead.gif" ALIGN=top></center>

<h2>EPA's Voluntary Environmental Self-Policing and Self-Disclosure Interim Policy</h2>
<BODY>


<P>
On April 19, 1995, EPA released a set of 14 questions 
and answers relating to the Agency's new environmental 
audit policy. According to EPA, the policy is designed 
to encourage regulated entities to conduct compliance 
audits and correct violations they find. The following 
six questions are part two of a two-part series presenting 
this EPA document. Part one of this document appeared 
in the May issue of the <I>Monthly Bulletin</I>.<B><BR>

<P>Q: How will EPA determine whether a company has done 
an environmental audit or self-evaluation that is &quot;appropriate 
to the size and nature of the facility?&quot;</B><BR>
A: In general, the larger and more complex the operations 
at a facility, the greater will be EPA's expectation 
that the facility conduct routine and periodic compliance 
audits that are comprehensive, objective, systematic, 
and documented. However, EPA does not want to preclude 
application of this policy to companies with limited 
resources that conduct less thorough or less formal 
compliance evaluations.<B><BR>
<P>
Q: What if a company self-polices and self-corrects violations 
but does not voluntarily disclose the violations?</B><BR>
A: A company that does not voluntarily disclose a violation 
will not have met one of the conditions for full gravity 
mitigation.  Therefore, EPA  could eliminate up to 
75% of the gravity portion of any civil penalty in 
such a case, depending on the circumstances.  However, 
where criminal conduct is involved, and depending on 
the circumstances, EPA might decide to recommend that 
criminal charges be brought against the entity, since 
failure to disclose could indicate an intent to conceal 
the criminal conduct.<B><BR>
<P>
Q: What kind of cooperation normally would be required 
by EPA in order to meet condition 7 in Section II.A 
of the policy?</B><BR>
A: In addition to providing information that is reasonably 
necessary  for EPA to determine the applicability of 
the policy, the regulated entity may be required to 
provide relevant documents and access to employees 
and others having knowledge of the violation. The regulated 
entity may also  be required to assist and cooperate 
in any ensuing investigations or proceedings against 
individuals and other entities regarding the violation.<B><BR>
<P>
Q: What amount of economic benefit will EPA consider 
&quot;insignificant?&quot;</B><BR>
A: EPA will be guided by existing penalty policy provisions 
relating to when EPA will not seek or proceed with 
calculation of economic benefit. For example, the RCRA 
penalty policy provides that &quot;enforcement personnel 
may forego calculating the economic benefit component 
where it appears that the amount of the calculation 
is likely to be less than $2,500 for all violations 
alleged in the complaint.&quot; RCRA Civil Penalty 
Policy, at 26 (1990).<B><BR>
<P>
Q: What is the status of the expansion of other media 
of EPA's enforcement response policy  under Section 
507 of the Clean Air Act?</B><BR>
A: Under Section 507 of the Clean Air Act, EPA gives 
small businesses that are not major sources of air 
pollution up to 90 days, or in some circumstances up 
to 180 days,  to correct violations identified through 
voluntary participation in a state compliance assistance 
program. The Section 507 policy does not apply to criminal 
acts, violations involving  imminent and substantial 
endangerment, or repeat violations. An Agency-wide 
workgroup has been working on expanding the Section 
507 to media other than air for several months. An 
expansion of this policy is expected to be completed 
this spring.<B><BR>
<P>
Q: How does the interim policy reward entities that have 
implemented state-of-the-art comprehensive environmental 
management systems that include periodic and objective 
compliance auditing as just one of several elements?</B><BR>
A: An entity with such a system is much more likely to 
meet the requirements for full gravity mitigation on 
a consistent basis than an entity that does not. In 
addition, an entity with such a system is in a much 
better position to prevent noncompliance, and avoid 
any penalties, in the first place. EPA will be looking 
into additional incentives that we can offer for state-of-the-art 
environmental management systems as we implement our 
Environmental Leadership Project.<P>

</BODY>

