<head>
<title>IRS Provides Model Amendment for Re-employed Veterans</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/planhead.gif" alt="The 401(k)
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>IRS Provides Model Amendment for Re-employed Veterans</h2>
<P>
In its final days, the 104th Congress passed a law requiring that plans reinstate
benefits for re-employed veterans (see the November issue of <I>Current
Developments</i>, p. 1). <P>

Does this new law require you to amend your plan?<P>

Yes, but you do not have to amend the plan sooner than the first day of the first
plan year beginning on or after Jan. 1, 1998.<P>

This amendment requirement is the result of a recent change to the Uniformed
Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act of 1994 (USERRA), enacted Oct.
13, 1994. <P>

Congress passed USERRA to clarify many requirements for employer-sponsored
pension and other benefits programs when employees are re-employed after military
service. The USERRA requirements were effective for re-employments initiated 60
days or more after Oct. 13, 1994. <P>

Originally, USERRA required that plan amendments had to be adopted by Oct. 13,
1996. But many (if not most) qualified plans were not amended for any of the
USERRA requirements by Oct. 13, because many of the original USERRA rules were
not clear or complete. Also, makeup contributions for returning veterans could
have violated statutory nondiscrimination and other limitations on
contributions.<P>

Congress has now amended the USERRA rules through a new Code Section 414(u), as
added by the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996. Now that the
qualification glitches of the original USERRA are corrected, plans must be
amended to incorporate the USERRA requirements.<P>

To help employers, the IRS issued a model amendment (Revenue Procedure 96-49).
The IRS has also delayed the effective date for adopting the amendment until
1998.<P>

The IRS revenue procedure includes two model amendments: all contributions,
benefits and service credit will be provided in accordance with Section 414(u);
and loan repayments will be suspended for employees who enter qualifying military
service, in accordance with Section 414(u). The latter amendment is optional for
those plans with plan loan features.<P>

Here is the procedure for adopting the amendment:<P>
<OL><P>
<LI>The model language is available only to sponsors of master and prototype
(M&amp;P), regional prototype, volume submitter specimen, and individually
designed plans that have received favorable IRS approval for all requirements of
the Tax Reform Act of 1986.<P>

<LI>A sponsor should adopt the model amendment in a timely fashion. No further
IRS filings are necessary and no additional IRS user fees are owed.<P>

<LI>M&amp;P, regional prototype, and volume submitter plans that use the model
language must file Form 8837 with the IRS. The IRS will not respond to this form
and no user fee is required.<P>
</OL><P>
<P>
</P>




<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/plan.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/smallplan.gif"
alt="Return to The 401(k) Handbook Home
Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif"
alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre>
</center>
