<HTML>
<HEAD> 
<TITLE>Health Plans Not Subject to DOL Plan Asset Regulations </TITLE> 
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/benehead.gif" alt="Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin"></center> 
<P>
<h2>Health Plans Not Subject to DOL Plan Asset Regulations</h2> 

<P>
In a change from an earlier proposed rule, the Department of Labor (DOL) has excluded health plans from a requirement that shortens the period of time in which plan assets must be turned over to a trust or insurer.
</P>

<P>
Under ERISA, employee contributions are plan assets that must be placed in trust (or turned over to an insurance company) as soon as possible after they are paid to the employer but not more than 90 days after they are paid. In December 1995, the DOL proposed regulations that would have moved up this deadline so that an employer would have place employee contributions in trust by the 15th day of the month in which wages subject to withholding were paid.
</P>

<P>
The DOL proposed a shorter deadline as part of its effort to tighten the ERISA standards that apply to employees' 401(k) plan contributions. According to the DOL, a shorter deadline for placing 401(k) participants' money in trust would prevent employers from "abusing" that money. The proposed regulations, however, included health plans in their scope in addition to 401(k) (and other retirement) plans.
</P>

<P>
However, the final DOL regulations, which were published in the Aug. 7 <I>Federal Register</I> and become effective Feb. 3, 1997, provide that employee contributions to health plans are not subject to this rule. Therefore, the 90-day rule is still in effect for health plans.
</P>

<P>
The final regulations also specify that cafeteria plan administrators may continue to rely on a 1992 ERISA "technical release" from the DOL (ERISA Tech. Rel. 92-01) stating that the DOL would not take action against cafeteria plan sponsors that do not place employee contributions in trust. 
</P>







<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/bene.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/smallbene.gif"  alt="Return to Employer's
Health Benefits Bulletin Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a> </pre> </center> <hr> <center><h6>&#169; 1996 Thompson Publishing Group / <a
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

</body> </HTML>
</DOC>
