<html> <title>Congress Learns to Live With FLSA Overtime Requirements</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/jobs/jobshead.gif" alt="Public Employer's Guide to FLSA Employee Classification"></center>
<P>
<h2>Congress Learns to Live With FLSA Overtime Requirements</h2>
<body>
<h3><i>On Capitol Hill, the Overtime Pinch Continues. But Will Congress Consider
Amending the Act This Year?</i></h3><P>

Employers on Capitol Hill are continuing to feel the pinch of complying with the
Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA). Federal minimum wage and overtime provisions of
the FLSA took effect for congressional employees Jan. 23 and since then, support
for overhauling the Depression-era statute has been increasing in the House and
Senate.<P>

House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., told a group of human resources professionals
in March that many House members are complaining that the FLSA is unworkable --
particularly those provisions of the act concerning FLSA-exempt administrators,
professionals and executives. Gingrich's comments follow closely a report
released by the non-profit Congressional Management Foundation that found that in
12 percent of House members' offices, either one staffer or none was designated
as non-exempt from the FLSA and therefore eligible for overtime pay.<P>

Earlier this year, the Flexible Employment Compensation and Scheduling Coalition,
a group advocating fundamental FLSA reform, conducted an "audit" of a fictional
congressional office in conjunction with its study of the Congressional
Accountability Act (CAA). Adopted as part of the Republican "Contract With
America" in January 1995, the CAA for the first time applied to Congress
substantial portions of the FLSA and 10 other federal workplace and civil rights
laws (see January 1996 <i>Current Developments,</i> page 1).<P>

The coalition's audit predicted that Congress would experience significant
problems determining which of its staff members are non-exempt for FLSA purposes.
This finding was far from surprising to the rest of the nation's employers, who
have for years experienced first-hand the confusion and expense that can result
from incorrectly classifying employees under the FLSA.<P>

Since early January representatives of public and private sector employers have
been closely monitoring Congress' attempts to comply with the act. Advocates for
reforming the FLSA strongly believe that congressional experience with the act
will convince lawmakers to overhaul the statute in the near future.<P>

In practice, the reaction of House and Senate members to the federal minimum wage
and overtime provisions for the most part has been as predicted. Many members
have complained that guidance for applying the FLSA's executive, administrative
and professional exemptions is inadequate, and that the statute unduly restricts
workplace flexibility. In fact, the House recently passed a resolution requiring
Congress' Office of Compliance -- an independent office charged with implementing
the CAA -- to issue additional clarification on applying the FLSA to Capitol Hill
workers. The Compliance Office is reluctant to issue guidelines on FLSA
exemptions, and the Senate has more readily accepted this position.<P>

<h3>The Congressional Management Foundation Study</h3>

So Congress has been left to find its own way. The Congressional Management
Foundation (CMF) study illustrates Congress' compliance efforts so far; CMF
surveyed 440 House members' offices regarding the FLSA and received 167
responses. In the Senate, all 100 senators' offices were surveyed and 55
submitted information.<P>

With respect to determining exempt/non-exempt status, CMF found that in the
House, 59 percent of positions are being classified as exempt (see chart below).
Moreover, House offices are in strong agreement on the classification of the
most senior and the most junior positions, the study found, and the most complex
classification issue so far has centered around the employment position
"legislative assistant."<P>
<img src="/tpg/person/jobs/jobsmay1a.gif" alt="This table is titled FLSA Classification of Job Positions by House Offices"><P>

In the Senate, the study found that 53 percent of positions are being classified
as exempt (see last chart).<P>

Meanwhile, the study also reviewed how House members and senators are altering
their business operations to comply with the FLSA. In the House, seven of every
eight offices responding to the survey said they had budgeted $5,000 or less to
pay overtime costs in 1996. In the Senate, 74 percent of offices budgeted $10,000
or less.<P>

From these and other figures, the study concluded that most offices are looking
for the least expensive options in adapting to the new overtime requirements. In
general, this has meant offices are eliminating the need to pay overtime whenever
possible.<P>

For example, in the House, the survey indicated that offices intend to enforce
shorter work hours, more carefully monitor work schedules, trim office workloads,
increase operational efficiency and allow for less staff "down time." In the
Senate, most offices also are working to better manage their operations; however,
unlike their House counterparts, Senate offices are more openly embracing the use
of "Belo plans," a method of compensation used by employers to stabilize pay for
non-exempt employees who work fluctuating work weeks.<P>

Overall, the study concluded that House and Senate offices "are making good faith
efforts to comply with the FLSA." But, predicted CMF, "It could be difficult for
many offices to actually maintain their current workload with such low overtime
budgets. As the year goes on, some offices may be forced to confront the painful
choice of either lowering the quality of their work, reducing the quantity of
work they produce, or paying more in overtime than they have currently
budgeted."<P>

<h3>The Prospect for FLSA Changes</h3>

Advocates of FLSA reform have long lobbied Congress for both major and minor
revisions to the act. In the last two years, key House and Senate committees have
staged hearings on various aspects of FLSA reform, and pressure to update the
statute to address the needs of the 1990s workforce is growing.<P>

Prior to enactment of the CAA, several lawmakers, particularly members of the
House Economic and Educational Opportunities Committee, openly sympathized with
the concerns of employers that are confused or overly burdened by FLSA
compliance. Now that all House members and senators have been forced to interpret
and comply with the statute on their own, their gripes are expected to fuel
additional calls for FLSA reform.<P>

Already, several bills targeting issues such as compensatory time off (in lieu of
overtime pay) and alteration of the 40-hour work week are being debated. But
despite this heightened interest in the act and the growing willingness of
lawmakers to consider amendments, time is growing short. Citing Congress'
burgeoning legislative calendar as well as upcoming elections in the fall , many
interested parties now doubt whether significant amendments to the FLSA could be
enacted before the end of the 104th Congress. If attempts at  amendment fail now,
supporters of FLSA reform will likely have to wait until at least next year to
achieve their goal.<P>
<img src="/tpg/person/jobs/jobsmay1b.gif" alt="This table is titled FLSA Classification of Job Positions by Senate Offices"><P>
</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
