<html> 
<head>
<title>New CBO Report Offers Options for Taxing Employee Fringe Benefits</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/perk/perkhead.gif" alt=" Employer's Guide to Fringe Benefit Rules"></center>
<P>
<h2>New CBO Report Offers Options for Taxing Employee Fringe Benefits</h2>

<P>
Although the federal budget deficit has decreased significantly in recent years -- from $290 billion in 1992 to $144 billion in 1996 -- it continues to concern both Democrat and Republican policy-makers. While still too early for speculation about how this month's elections will affect fiscal policy, a recent Congressional Budget Office (CBO) report predicts that an <I>increase</I> in the deficit could spur a flurry of legislative action in the new 105th Congress.
</P>

<P>
And that action could dramatically affect fringe benefits. One of the strategies proposed by the CBO for managing the deficit calls for revamping the tax treatment of fringe benefits.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Why the Concern Now?</H3>
</P>

<P>
Although budget policies have nearly halved the deficit since 1992, the CBO estimates that, beginning in 1997, the deficit will increase again, first creeping and then rapidly climbing toward $285 billion in 2002 -- the year Congress and the president have set for balancing the budget. By 2006, the deficit could top $400 billion.
</P>

<P>
Congress must implement measures now to curb this trend and meet the 2002 date targeted for balancing the budget, the CBO cautions. Its report, in effect, maps out the next four years and beyond, giving Congress some options for cutting federal spending and increasing taxes to achieve a balanced budget.
</P>

<P>
The CBO prepares information reports for Congress to use when grappling with the budget impact of proposed legislation. The reports, however, <I>are not</I> legislative proposals. 
</P>

<P>
<H3>The Rationale for Change</H3>
</P>

<P>
One area the CBO examined as a potential revenue source was the tax treatment of employee fringe benefits, including employee discounts, parking subsidies and on-premises athletic facilities.
</P>

<P>
CBO offered four economic policy reasons why Congress should consider changing the tax treatment of fringe benefits. 
</P>

<P>
First, employees who receive only cash compensation pay more income and payroll taxes than employees who receive the same compensation in both cash and nontaxable fringe benefits. For example, an employee earning $40,000 in cash only will pay more taxes than an employee earning $37,000 in cash, $1,800 in qualified transportation benefits and $1,200 in other excludable fringe benefits.
</P>

<P>
Second, the tax-favored status of a fringe benefit can increase employee demand for it because being able to exclude a benefit encourages employees to use it more than if it were taxable. Increased demand, in turn, can drive up a benefit's price for those who must pay for it with after-tax dollars.
</P>

<P>
Take parking, for example. Parking subsidies encourage more employees to drive to work rather than use van pools or mass transit. When more employees drive, available parking decreases. In response to increased demand and reduced supply (so the marketplace goes), parking prices will rise. As a result, employees not eligible for subsidies will pay more for their parking.
</P>

<P>
The exclusion for employer-paid mass transportation passes can partially reverse this effect by giving employees an offsetting incentive to use mass transit.
</P>

<P>
Third, a fringe benefit exclusion is worth more to higher-income employees because it allows them to receive greater total compensation but avoid moving into a higher tax bracket. Some employees may actually fall into a lower tax bracket if some of their compensation is in the form of excludable fringe benefits.
</P>

<P>
Finally, higher-income employees generally receive more fringe benefits than lower-income employees, and their benefits tend to be more valuable. For example, some servers at fast-food restaurants may receive free hamburgers during their shifts while top executives do business over lobster.
</P>

<P>
<H3>A Tax, One Way or the Other</H3>
</P>

<P>
The report outlined two ways to tap the revenues the federal government currently loses by allowing employees to exclude fringe benefits:
</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
<P>
	<LI>make all fringe benefits taxable to employees; or
</P>
	<LI>impose an employer-paid excise tax on them.
</UL>

<P>
Taxing all fringe benefits, the CBO noted, would create administrative problems, such as how to value a benefit. In most cases, valuing a benefit would be difficult for anything other than goods and services with fixed dollar costs.
</P>

<P>
For example, determining the value of a monthly bus pass is easy. A $57 pass is $57. But, how should an employer value a benefit, such as an on-premises athletic facility, offered to many employees who use it more or less frequently?
</P>

<P>
Allocating a fringe benefit's value also is a problem. After determining the total value of a fringe benefit, an employer would have to assign portions of that value to individual employees so that specific dollar amounts could be included in their incomes.
</P>

<P>
For example, suppose a clothing retailer gives its employees a 10-percent discount on merchandise from its stores. The retailer could tally all sales to employees during the year, calculate the difference between what the employees paid for the clothing and what they would have paid if they did not use their 10-percent discount, and then allocate that difference equally among its employees.
</P>

<P>
But some employees may have used the discount more frequently than others. For example, Bob buys $2,000 worth of clothing and receives $200 off his total purchases, while Mary buys $200 worth of clothing and gets only $20 off. Bob and Mary should not be allocated the same dollar value for their discount.
</P>

<P>
Recording each employee's use of a fringe benefit and assigning a value to that use is probably too complex for most employers. And, the CBO noted, even if employers implemented procedures for tracking fringe benefits and equitably assigning value to employees, the costs to the IRS to collect fringe benefits taxes could exceed any revenues collected.
</P>

<P>
<H3>An Administratively Simple Excise Tax</H3>
</P>

<P>
Instead of eliminating the fringe benefit exclusions and making the benefits taxable to employees, the CBO proposed that employers pay a 3-percent excise tax on the total costs of their fringe benefits, but only for benefits with easily determined total costs, such as subsidized parking or on-premises athletic facilities.
</P>

<P>
CBO noted several advantages to this approach.
</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
<P>
	<LI>To calculate the excise tax, employers would only need to total their fringe benefit costs. They would not have to calculate each employee's individual benefit. For example, the clothing retailer would only need to tally the costs of employee discounts used.
</P>
	<LI>The proposed 3-percent excise tax would be much lower than the current 7.65-percent Social Security and Medicare tax rate employers pay on wages. The lower rate would maintain an employer's financial incentive to provide fringe benefits.
</UL>

<P>
The CBO pointed out, however, that even with this excise tax, higher-income employees would still receive and exclude a disproportionate percentage of fringe benefits.
</P>

<P>
But the report also suggested that an employer could pass on its excise tax expenses to employees more or less progressively. Through their own policies, for example, employers could more equitably provide fringe benefits by reducing compensation paid in cash in proportion to fringe benefits received.
</P>

<P>
<H3>Let the Debate Begin</H3>
</P>

<P>
The likelihood of Congress enacting an excise tax remains uncertain. Moreover, any statutory change to the tax treatment of fringe benefits probably would develop in conjunction with other, large-scale benefits changes, like curbing the exclusion for employer-paid health insurance premiums.
</P>

<P>
But when and if the debate begins, the CBO report could be a valuable prep course for both sides. 
</P>


