<html> 
<head>
<title> Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/wage/wagehead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor
Standards Act">
<P>
<h2>Insurance Company Representatives Were Exempt Administrators, Court Finds </h2>
<H3><I>Case Is One of Few Involving Insurance Company Employees</I></H3>
<P>
In one of the relatively few cases to address the exempt status of insurance industry employees under the
Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), the U.S. District Court for Massachusetts recently ruled that marketing
representatives and specialists whose primary duty was to contact and deal with insurance agents and
recommend insurance products were exempt administrators. <P>

Though the insurance industry is one of the largest in the country, it has spawned few controversies under
the FLSA. Those lawsuits that have come before the courts have centered on the application of the wage and
hour law's administrative exemption.<P>

In the immediate case, Secretary of Labor Robert Reich brought suit against the John Alden Life Insurance
Company, claiming that it had failed to pay overtime to its marketing representatives and marketing
specialists working at the company's Westborough, Mass., office. In response, John Alden argued that the
employees were exempt as administrators under Section 213(a)(1) of the FLSA (see Appendix I of the
<I>Guide</I>).<P>

<H3>Marketing Responsibilities</H3><P>

Marketing representatives for John Alden were primarily responsible for contacting and dealing with
licensed independent insurance agents, recommending the company's various insurance products for
end-purchasers. The employees decided which agents to contact, when to contact them and which products
to emphasize.<P>

The representatives also were the main contact for the insurance company, informing agents of new
products or combinations of new products, price changes and analysis of new or renewal business. They
often passed on information about competitors and recommendations for the company that were relayed by
their supervisors and resulted in changes in John Alden products.<P>

The insurance employees were usually college graduates with two to six years of experience whose
salaries ranged from $50,000 to $75,000. Marketing representatives typically spent seven hours per day
talking with insurance agents and two hours each day on paperwork related to their contacts.<P>

Because of the amount of the employees' salaries, the district court applied the "short test" for the
administrative exemption (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.2(e)(2), see Appendix II). Under this test, employees who
earn more than $250 per week qualify as exempt if (1) their primary duty entails "the performance of
office or nonmanual work directly related to management policies or general business operations of [the]
employer or [the] employer's customers" (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.2(a)), and (2) these duties require the
employee to exercise discretion and independent judgment (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.2(e)(2)).<P>

<H3>Administration or Production?</H3><P>

The U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) argued that the marketing representatives were merely salespeople
performing production work, not administrators. Citing the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' decision in
<I>Martin v. Cooper Electric Supply Co.</I>, 940 F.2d 986 (1991), DOL pointed out that, in that case, the
salespeople were ruled production workers "because they actually produced . . . sales." DOL stated that the
marketing representatives were similarly situated because their main duty was the "day-to-day sales
operations of the company."<P>

The court rejected this argument, stating that <I>Martin</I> was distinguishable from the immediate case because
the John Alden employees did not set the prices or terms of the insurance policies; they promoted sales,
the court said, which was not a "production" duty. The court held that the product of the company was its
insurance policies.<P>

John Alden relied on DOL's regulations, which state:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The administrative operations of the business include the work performed by so-called white-collar
employees engaged in 'servicing' a business as, for example, advising the management, planning,
negotiating, representing the company, purchasing, promoting sales, and business research and control (29
C.F.R. &#167;541.205(b)).<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The employer contended that because the marketing representatives were "promoting sales" and
"representing the company," they should be exempted as administrators. The company also maintained that
the insurance agents were actually the sales force for its products and the marketing employees cultivated
relationships with those agents as representatives of John Alden. Though the marketing representatives did
not design the company's insurance products, the company stated, "they describe those products to agents,
thereby promoting company sales."<P>

The court found in favor of John Alden and ruled that the employees were primarily engaged in
administrative duties.<P>

<H3>Substantially Important Work</H3><P>

Under the regulations, administratively exempt employees do not necessarily have to "participate in the
formulation of management policies or in the operation of the business as a whole" (29 C.F.R.
&#167;541.205(c)). Although the exemption does apply to those employees who have a direct hand in
business policies and operations, it also encompasses those employees who affect business operations or
"carry out major business assignments" (29 C.F.R. &#167;541.205(c)).<P>

DOL argued that the marketing representatives "have no policy responsibilities and do not carry out major
assignments." However, John Alden maintained that the representatives had "considerable impact" on the
company as the only information source to agents about the company's products. The firm also claimed that
the success of the company depended on the representatives' ability to sell the insurance products.<P>

The district court ruled that the marketing representatives' work was "critically important" and affected
the company to a considerable degree. Therefore, the court found that John Alden had met the first prong of
the short test, and proven before the court that the representatives performed nonmanual work related to
business operations and management.<P>

<H3>Discretion and Independent Judgment</H3><P>

DOL also contended that the marketing representatives did not employ "real and substantial" discretion or
independent judgment in the key areas of their positions because they had no part in setting or negotiating
the prices or terms of the insurance products they were selling, and they did not make the approval
decisions on submitted applications. DOL also noted that the representatives' decisions about which agents
to call, when to call them and what sales pitch to use did not require discretion "with respect to matters of
consequence." DOL then added that making product suggestions or proposals did not denote sufficient
discretion because such action only entailed collecting information and entering it into a computer.<P>

John Alden maintained, however, that the representatives "clearly exercise discretion and independent
judgment in significant matters." The firm stated that the employees determined when to promote certain
insurance products in five New England states, maintained communications with insurance agents, identified
the interests and needs of these agents, kept files on competitors and analyzed product trends in the
industry to determine which company products best met market needs. The insurance company also stated
that the marketing representatives often made suggestions on which new products and new features to
adopt based on information gathered from the independent insurance agents.<P>

Considering this evidence, the district court ruled that the marketing representatives "exercise significant
discretion and independent judgment in carrying out their duties" and were not merely skilled laborers
operating within a strict set of guidelines. The court held that the John Alden employees met both prongs of
the short test and were therefore administratively exempt under the FLSA. (<I>Reich v. John Alden Life
Insurance Co.</I>, D. Mass., Civil Action No. 95-40086-NMG, Oct. 8, 1996) <P>

<hr>
