<html>
<head>
<title>Employees Who Quit Their Jobs Are Eligible for Educational Assistance, IRS
 Rules<P></title>
</head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/dischead.gif" alt="Employer's Handbook:
Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules"></center>

<h2>Employees Who Quit Their Jobs Are Eligible for Educational Assistance, IRS
Rules<P></h2>
<P>
Employers can provide educational assistance benefits to former employees who
have voluntarily separated from service, the IRS has clarified. In a recent
revenue ruling, the IRS concluded that the educational assistance exclusion under
Code Section 127 extends to employees who quit, as well as to active, retired,
disabled and laid-off employees.<P>

Revenue Ruling 96-41 represents the first guidance on this issue that employers
and the IRS can use as precedent.<P>

<h3>Different Circumstances, But Same Conclusion,</h3><P>

The revenue ruling considered two employers' educational assistance plans. One
plan offered educational assistance benefits to both current and former
employees, including former employees who had voluntarily left the company. The
other plan offered educational assistance benefits to former employees who were
involuntarily terminated because the company had downsized.<P>

The IRS ruled that in both situations, extending educational assistance benefits
to employees who had quit or were laid off did not risk the plans' qualified
status.<P>

<h3>What Changed?</h3><P>

An IRS official has informally stated that the ruling does not represent any
change in IRS policy on eligibility for educational benefits. Rather, the revenue
ruling confirms a 1986 private letter ruling (P.L.R. 8644078), which determined
that educational assistance benefits provided to employees up to two years after
they voluntarily left their employer were excludable. (The private letter ruling,
however, cannot be used as precedent.)<P>

Despite the IRS' position that it has not substantively changed its policy, some
employers might think otherwise for two reasons. First, although the existing
regulations under Section 127 allow employers to provide educational assistance
benefits to "retired, disabled, or laid-off" employees, the regulations do not
suggest that they also can provide benefits to employees who voluntarily quit.<P>

Second, the ruling conflicts with Section 127's legislative history. According to
a 1984 U.S. House of Representatives report on the exclusion, Congress intended
for employers to tax employees on educational assistance received not only after
voluntary separation from service, but also within the entire taxable year of the
separation.<P>

<h3>Possible Impact on Recruitment and Retention</h3><P>

Few employers want to allocate their limited benefits dollars toward educating
employees who have voluntarily quit. But a closer look at the earlier private
letter ruling suggests that this assistance can make good business sense.<P>

The letter ruling considered an educational assistance plan maintained for food
handlers in a company's restaurants. Most crew members were high school students
working on an hourly, part-time basis. They earned credits toward educational
assistance benefits based on hours of service and a schedule of benefits and
could receive educational reimbursements for up to two years after leaving the
company.<P>

The company developed the plan to help employees continue their education beyond
high school. That financial assistance probably boosted the company's ability to
recruit and retain students.<P>

Furthermore, by offering educational assistance benefits, the company was able to
supplement the handlers' low wages -- about $3,000 per year -- on a tax-favored
basis. 
<P>
</P>

</FONT>
