<html> 
<head>
<title> Retirement Plans May Limit Coverage to Employee Groups, But Exclusion
Rules Must
Be Specific</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/planhead.gif" alt="The 401(k)
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2> Retirement Plans May Limit Coverage to Employee Groups, But Exclusion Rules
Must
Be Specific</h2>
<h2><i>Microsoft Loses Lawsuit From Misclassified Common Law
Employees</i></h2><P>
Many employers limit coverage under their qualified pension and 401(k) plans to
certain groups of employees. Sometimes, the covered groups are clearly
distinguishable from noncovered groups: Plans may be limited to union or nonunion
employees or employees of certain company divisions or subsidiaries, for example.
In other cases, the distinctions are not entirely clear: The plan may cover all
"regular" employees or employees "on payroll," for example.<P>
The dangers of excluding individuals otherwise entitled to benefits can be
significant. A qualified plan could be subject to tax penalties for
disqualification for this error and the employer may be required to retroactively
fund the benefits for improperly excluded individuals (see &#182;321 of the
Handbook).<P>
Two recent cases highlight the significant financial risk employers take when
trying to limit coverage under certain benefit plans through exclusion rules that
are not specific.<P>
<h3>Playing Hardball With Microsoft</h3><P>
In <i>Vizcaino v. Microsoft Corp. </i>(97 F.3d 1197, 9th Cir. 1996), the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals held that workers originally classified by the Microsoft
Corp. as independent contractors, but classified by the IRS as common law
employees, must be allowed to participate retroactively in the company's 401(k)
and employee stock purchase plans as though they were common law employees. By
allowing for retroactive reinstatement in stock-based plans of one of the fastest
growing companies in the country, the court, in effect, awarded millions of
dollars in lost benefits to these individuals.<P>
Microsoft hired the workers as freelance independent contractors and told them
they would not receive benefits. The employees also signed agreements confirming
that they would be working as independent contractors. These workers, although
fully integrated into the Microsoft work force (working on teams with regular
employees, sharing supervisors, performing identical functions and working the
same core hours), were paid through the accounts receivable department and not
through Microsoft's payroll department. They were paid higher salaries than
comparable common law employees apparently because they didn't receive
benefits.<P>
In 1989 and 1990, the IRS examined Microsoft's employment records and
subsequently ruled that these workers were employees for withholding and
employment tax purposes. After learning of the IRS decision, the workers sued for
the right to participate in Microsoft's qualified 401(k) plan and employee stock
purchase plan.<P>
The 9th Circuit ruled that these workers were eligible to participate in both
plans. The court indicated that although Microsoft could have excluded them, the
eligibility criteria of the plan did not do so. The plan's eligibility terms
included employees "on the United States payroll of the employer." The court
found no distinction in how the employees were paid -- through payroll or through
accounts receivable -- so the workers, classified by the IRS as employees, should
have been eligible to participate.<P>
The 9th Circuit also found that the workers were eligible to participate in the
employee stock purchase plan. A worker's eligibility to participate in an
employee stock purchase plan is spelled out in Code Section 423. This type of
plan, in contrast to qualified retirement plans, must cover all employees of an
employer, with only certain limited exclusions. Microsoft argued that the workers
were ineligible to participate because they had previously signed agreements
acknowledging that they would not get benefits. <P>
The court declared this argument immaterial because the label used to describe
the workers' employment status in the documents was incorrect and Microsoft could
not legally exclude common law employees from the plan without sacrificing the
plan's tax status.<P>
(The 9th Circuit includes Alaska, Arizona, California, Hawaii, Idaho, Montana,
Nevada, Oregon, Washington and Guam.)<P>
<h3>Leased Employees Can Be Common Law Employees</h3><P>
The second case, <i>Bronk v. Mountain States Telephone &amp; Telegraph, Inc.</i>
(1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 16155), involved a group of workers who provided services
to U.S. West and Mountain States Telephone &amp; Telegraph, and who were paid
through temporary service agencies or leasing agencies. Allegedly, these
individuals were really working as common law employees of the employers and not
as leased employees. (Common law employee status is determined based on the facts
and circumstances and a 20-factor test established by the IRS. Essentially, this
test determines whether the recipient of the services primarily directs the
individual's employment and how the work is done.) Thus, the issue was whether
the plans excluded employees who were hired as leased employees but who really
met the status of common law employees of the employer. <P>
The companies' pension plans limited coverage to "regular employees" as
determined by the records of the company. This language, according to the
plaintiffs, gave them the right to be covered by the plans because they were
regular employees. The district court found that the ERISA and tax code minimum
participation standards require the inclusion in this particular case of those
leased employees who met the definition of common law employees. The district
court ordered the parties to conduct further proceedings.<P>
<h3>Plans Can Limit Coverage</h3><P>
Both of these opinions appear to rely on the belief that if an employer
establishes a qualified retirement plan, the plan must cover all of the
employer's common law employees. This is not true. Plans of most large companies
are limited in coverage. Many other plans cover either union or nonunion
employees. Similarly, plans may limit coverage to the employees in a certain
division, location, subsidiary or facility of the employer. The tax qualification
rules permit all these exclusions; they have never been seriously challenged.<P>
Challenges may become more common, however, if courts adopt expansive readings of
the Microsoft and Bronk opinions. Plans with imprecise exclusions may find that
excluded individuals (whether they are leased employees, independent contractors,
temporary employees or otherwise excluded) will try to challenge the imprecise
exclusions to obtain some additional benefits.<P>
Aside from the tax qualification concerns, significant amounts of money are at
stake. If an employer inappropriately excludes otherwise includable employees
from an ERISA plan, the employer will have to make up lost benefits, including
possibly lost earnings, to those employees. If the lost funds would have been
invested in investments that grew substantially during the years in question 
(like Microsoft stock), the amounts could add up to millions of dollars.<P>
Is there anything that employers can do to avoid a claim similar to that faced by
Microsoft? Yes. Plans should specify in detail all groups of excluded employees.
Eligibility provisions that simply indicate that "regular" or "permanent"
employees are covered are imprecise and generally unacceptable. So-called
"leased" employees may be just as regular or permanent as the traditional common
law employees.<P>
Instead, exclusions could be drafted for individuals (whether or not they are
employees) who are paid through unrelated third-party payrolls or hired through
agreements with unrelated third-party employment agencies. The precise language
depends on the employer's particular situation and should be drafted only after
consulting with a benefits attorney. Also, sometimes it's not possible to amend
the plan to correct imprecise language. Therefore, plan amendments should be
planned and implemented carefully.<P>
A final word of caution: Qualified plans are subject to precise coverage and
nondiscrimination rules. Employers should not exclude certain categories of
employees without considering the ramifications of these exclusions on the strict
qualification tests.<P>
</P>




