<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
'Environmental Justice' Claims Cannot Strike Down Permit</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/fixx/fixxhead.gif" ALIGN=top></center>

</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H2>'Environmental Justice' Claims Cannot Strike Down Permit, Says EAB</H2>

<P>
Issues of environmental justice -- the disproportionate 
impact of a hazardous waste facility may have on minority 
and low-income populations -- can be addressed in a 
permitting decision under the &quot;omnibus power&quot; 
clause of RCRA, ruled the Environmental Appeals Board 
(EAB) on June 29, 1995.<P>

Writing for a three-member panel, EAB judge Edward E. 
Reich held in <I>In Re Chemical Waste Management of Indiana,</I> 
RCRA Appeal Nos. 95-2 and 95-3 (June 29, 1995) that 
EPA has the power under RCRA $3005(c)(3)(A) to consider 
issues of &quot;environmental justice&quot; when considering 
an application for a permit to store, treat, or dispose 
of hazardous waste.<P>

&quot;Under the omnibus clause, if the operation of 
a facility truly poses a threat to the health or environment 
of a low-income or minority community, the omnibus 
clause would require the [EPA] region to include whatever 
terms and conditions are necessary to prevent such 
impacts,&quot; noted Reich.<P>

<h3>Congressman, ACLU Intervene</h3><P>

The case arose in March 1995, when EPA Region V, based 
in Chicago, issued a final permit decision approving 
renewal of the federal portion of the permit for the 
Adams Center Landfill Facility in Ft. Wayne, Ind., 
and allowing the landfill to expand its capacity. Indiana 
was authorized to run the base RCRA program in 1986, 
but oversight of corrective action and other requirements 
under the Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments were 
carried out by EPA [see <I>Manual</I>, &#182;1345].<P>

The EAB received three petitions challenging Region 
V's action, filed by the city of New Haven, to the 
east of Fort Wayne, and two residents of the city. 
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored 
People and Mark Souder, the congressman from Indiana's 
Fourth District, filed friend-of-the-court briefs. 
<P>

The plaintiffs and intervenors alleged that Region V's 
permit decision was not consistent with Executive Order 
12898, issued by President Clinton on Feb. 16, 1994. 
In the Executive Order, Clinton directed all federal 
agencies to identify and address &quot;disproportionately 
high and adverse human health or environmental effects 
of programs, policies or activities on minority and 
low-income populations.&quot;<P>

Region V erred by attempting to implement the Executive 
Order without guidance or criteria issued by EPA headquarters, 
said the petitioners. In addition, Region V's demographic 
study of the population within one mile of the landfill 
facility was flawed. They alleged that the 40 to 80 
percent of population within two miles of the facility 
is comprised of minorities, and the population is 80 
to 100 percent made up of minorities within three miles 
of the landfill.<P>

<h3>Board Rejects Claims</h3><P>

The parties opposed to the permit decision &quot;do 
not believe that the threats posed by the facility 
can be addressed through revision of the permit,&quot; 
noted Reich. &quot;Rather, it is apparent that the 
petitioners believe that their concerns can be addressed 
only by permanently halting operation of the facility 
at its present location, or at a minimum, preventing 
the phased expansion of the facility. Thus, the petitioners 
challenge the permit decision, including the modification, 
in its entirety, rather than any specific permit conditions.<P>

The Executive Order &quot;does not purport to, and does 
not have the effect of, changing the substantive requirements 
for issuance of a permit under RCRA and its implementing 
regulations,&quot; noted the Appeals Board. Under RCRA 
$3005(c)(1), EPA or an authorized state is <I>required</I> 
to issue a permit to any applicant meeting all of the 
requirements of RCRA and its implementing regulations.&quot; 
<P>

Thus, &quot;there is no legal basis for rejecting a 
RCRA permit application based solely upon alleged social 
or economic impacts upon the community,&quot; said 
Reich.<P>

&quot;If a permit application meets the requirements 
of RCRA and its implementing regulations, EPA <I>must 
</I>issue the permit, regardless of the racial or socioeconomic 
composition of the surrounding community and regardless 
of the economic effect of the facility on the surrounding 
community,&quot; Reich noted.  <P>

<h3>Omnibus Power Eyed</h3><P>

Nonetheless, the omnibus power granted to EPA by RCRA 
$3005(c)(3) allows the agency to include &quot;such 
terms as the Administrator (or state) determines necessary 
to protect human health or the environment&quot; in 
a permit, wrote Reich.<P>

&quot;If the nature of a facility and its proximity 
to neighboring populations would make it impossible 
to craft a set of permit terms and conditions that 
would protect the health and environment of such populations, 
the agency would have the authority to deny a permit,&quot; 
he noted. Similarly, EPA can include terms and conditions 
in a permit to address actual or potential impacts.<P>

Reich added, &quot;There is nothing in RCRA $3005(c)(3) 
to prevent Region V from taking a more refined look 
at its health and environmental impacts assessment, 
in light of allegations that operation of the facility 
would have a disproportionately adverse impact on the 
health or environment of low-income or minority populations.&quot;<P>

In this case, the petitioners have not demonstrated 
that the region erred in granting the permit, noted 
Reich. It held a series of information meetings and 
solicited comments from the community before issuing 
the permit.<P>

Moreover, Reich added, &quot;The petitioners have not 
demonstrated how the absence of a national environmental 
justice strategy or the absence of some other kind 
of nationwide criteria and guidance has led to an erroneous 
permit decision.&quot;<P>


</BODY>
