<html> 
<head>
<title> Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act </title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/wage/wagehead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to the Fair Labor
Standards Act">
<P>
<h2>FLSA 'Retaliatory Discharge' Relief Unavailable to Personnel Director </h2>
<P>
A personnel director who expressed concerns to her superiors about her
company's Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) compliance was not protected under the
law because performing one's job duties is not a protected activity as defined by
the statute's retaliatory discharge provisions, the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled recently.<P>

Lori McKenzie brought suit against her employer, Renberg's Inc., and its owner,
Robert Renberg, claiming that she was discharged in retaliation for informing her
employer of possible company violations of the FLSA. She claimed her actions were
covered by the labor law, and Renberg had unlawfully terminated her. Renberg
argued that McKenzie's activities were not protected under the FLSA, and that she
was released from employment for other work-related reasons.<P>

McKenzie served as personnel director for Renberg's and was responsible for
monitoring company compliance with state and federal wage and hour laws, equal
employment opportunity laws and other statutes that regulated the workplace. In
August 1991, a co-worker attended a wage and hour law seminar and shared with
McKenzie the materials and information she acquired. Upon reviewing this
material, McKenzie became concerned that certain employees of the company were
not being properly compensated for overtime worked.<P>

McKenzie approached the company attorney and expressed her concerns. She also
later discussed the problem with Renberg. Renberg fired McKenzie 16 days
later.<P>

At the district court level, a jury returned a verdict in favor of McKenzie on
her retaliation claim. However, the court entered judgment as a matter of law in
favor of Renberg, stating that McKenzie would have been terminated for reasons
outside those related to her employer's alleged retaliation. McKenzie appealed
the district court's decision, challenging the lower court's decision to grant
Renberg judgment as a matter of law.<P>

<H3>The Appeals Court Decision</H3><P>

The 10th Circuit rejected the lower court's reasoning, stating that "the mere
existence of a non-retaliatory motive that would justify an employee's discharge
does not absolve an employer of liability for a retaliatory employment decision."
Instead, the appellate court noted that the employer's non-retaliatory reason for
termination must be the motivating factor behind its employment decision, citing
the U.S. Supreme Court decision in <I>McKennon v. Nashville Banner Pub. Co.</I> (115 S.
Ct. 879, 885 (1995)).<P>

Before the appellate court, Renberg argued that McKenzie's actions were not
protected by the FLSA and that she did not produce sufficient evidence to support
the district court jury's retaliation finding. The 10th Circuit agreed with the
first of these arguments, and therefore did not review the second.<P>

Renberg maintained that McKenzie did not assert any rights protected under the
FLSA, but was merely performing her job's duties when she reported to the
company's officers. Section 215(a)(3) of the act states that it is unlawful for
an employer:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>to discharge or in any other manner discriminate against any employee because
such employee has filed any complaint or instituted or caused to be instituted
any proceeding under or related to the act, or has testified or is about to
testify in any such proceeding, or has served or is about to serve on an industry
committee.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

The 10th Circuit also has extended this protection to employees who presented a
good faith, but unproven, conviction that their FLSA rights had been violated
(<I>Love v. RE/MAX of Am. Inc.,</I> 738 F.2d 383, 387 (1984)). Otherwise, the types of
activities covered under this portion of the law are fairly explicit, the appeals
court said.<P>

However, "we have never held that an employee is insulated from retaliation for
participating in activities which are neither adverse to the company nor
supportive of adverse rights under the statute which are asserted against the
company," the court stated. Instead, the court presented examples of protected
activities that would invoke the retaliatory discharge protections of &#167;215(a)(3)
of the law, including:<P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>filing a formal complaint;<P>

	<LI>providing testimony in a FLSA proceeding; or<P>

	<LI>complaining to a superior about inadequate pay.<P>
</UL>

"McKenzie never crossed the line from being an employee merely performing her job
as personnel director to an employee lodging a personal complaint about the wage
and hour practices of her employer and asserting a right adverse to the company,"
the court noted. She never initiated any actions against Renberg on her own
behalf or for another employee, the court said. She only performed the duties of
her position, informing the company officials of the risk of claims under the
FLSA from employees. <P>

The court stated that McKenzie presented no evidence that she stepped outside of
her position as a company representative, asserted any rights under the FLSA or
took any action against the company. "McKenzie . . . lacks an essential
ingredient of a retaliation claim; that is she did not take a position adverse to
her employer or assert any rights under the FLSA," the court noted.<P>

The appellate court upheld the lower court's decision, but on the basis of this
rationale, stating that "McKenzie did not engage in activity protected under
&#167;215(a)(3)." (<I>McKenzie v. Renberg's Inc.,</I> 10th Cir., No. 94-5197, Sept. 4, 1996)
<P>




<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/wage/wage.html"><img src="smallwage.gif"  alt="Back to
Employer's Guide to Fair Labor Standards Act Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [
