<HEAD>
<TITLE>Equipment in the Physician Network: Refurbish, Lease, or Purchase?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC="/tpg/gif/logobar.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN=
bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<hr>
<center><H1>Developing and Managing Physician Networks: Business and Legal Strategies</H1></center>
<hr>

<H2>Equipment in the Physician Network: <BR>
Refurbish, Lease, or Purchase?</H2>
Provider networks that have just survived a merger, acquisition, or other
transitional step typically keep a sharp eye on their expenses. One high-cost
area is that of medical equipment used for special procedures such as cardiac
catheterization, computed tomography, and magnetic resonance imaging, as
well as chemistry analyzers and laboratory equipment. Purchasing this equipment
brand-new is far more expensive than installing refurbished equipment (see
chart). <BR>
<BR>
If the equipment needs of a physician practice or network do not demand
cutting-edge technology, one alternative to keep costs down is to use quality
reconditioned equipment-either bought or leased. This strategy is useful,
particularly if the network notices a decrease in utilization as a result
of managed care or if the organization has other plans for the capital.
In making equipment decisions, however, purchasers need to consider carefully
what will best serve the network and whether the advantages of buying used
equipment or leasing equipment outweigh the potential problems. 
<H3>How Leasing Can Help</H3>
Companies like Comdisco, Inc., of Rosemont, Illinois, offer equipment leasing
arrangements for health care providers. From the company's perspective,
providers that lease equipment receive the following benefits: 
<UL>
<LI>Available cash for other investments and acquisitions that have higher
potential returns; 
<LI>Maximum flexibility in the face of uncertain utilization; 
<LI>Shift in financial risk and protection against technological obsolescence;
<LI>Accurate projection of equipment costs over the life of the lease; 
<LI>Flexibility to easily acquire advanced technological upgrades as they
become available or trade up or out as needs change; 
<LI>Direct link of the costs of equipment-based services to the revenues
those services generate; 
<LI>A cost-effective and flexible financing solution that makes the network
more competitive; and 
<LI>Access to needed technology without the restrictive covenants that come
with tax-exempt financing. 
</UL>
<H3>Agreement Details Need Watching</H3>
Leasing arrangements, however, are not risk-free. Recently, the financial
details of the equipment leasing contract brought one provider to court:
Under a ruling by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit, the
court affirmed a finding by the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA)
that a hospital was not entitled to Medicare reimbursement for certain &quot;capital-related
costs.&quot; The costs in question involved the hospital's use of a computerized
tomography (CT) scanner owned by an outside company. [Public Hospital of
Salem v. Shalala, No. 95-3511 (7th Cir. May 7, 1996).]<BR>
<BR>
United States Medical Management, Inc., installed a CT scanner at the hospital
and serviced the equipment under the terms of the contract. The company
owned and insured the scanner, kept the software updated, and trained technicians
to use it. The hospital's responsibility included providing the space, electricity,
and staff, as well as paying a per-scan fee to the company. The contract
did not call for a monthly rental fee or a minimum number of patient scans.<BR>
<BR>
The problem leading to the court confrontation surfaced when the hospital
wanted to treat the scanner as a capital asset for purposes of Medicare
reimbursement. The Provider Reimbursement Review Board decided that the
hospital was entitled to treat the capital-related portion of its lease
payments as capital-related pass-through costs, concluding that the contract
was a lease. HCFA disagreed, finding that the costs should be classified
as operating expenses because the scanner services failed to meet the criteria
of a lease, rental, or license. HCFA found the agreement to be a contractual
relationship-a purchase service agreement for which the hospital was required
to pay based on usage (see sidebar). When the case reached the district
court level, the southern district of Illinois affirmed HCFA's finding,
and the appeals court agreed. 
<H3>Avoiding Problems Through Common Sense</H3>
Whether a physician network decides to purchase new equipment, refurbish
used equipment, or lease equipment from an outside company, it must consider
a number of issues. Comdisco recommends, for example, analyzing the network's
equipment portfolio and inventory to determine whether productivity and
utilization can be improved through an upgrade of the equipment to a more
efficient system. From a cost standpoint, it is also beneficial to avoid
duplicating equipment throughout the network. Long-term strategic plans
often help analysts determine what equipment is necessary now and in the
future.<BR>
<BR>
From a common sense standpoint, if the equipment is going to be refurbished
or reconditioned, it is imperative to ensure that the work is done properly
and that the equipment undergo preventive maintenance procedures as needed.
Time spent ensuring the quality of the equipment is just another component
of health care for which physician network administrators are responsible.
Poor equipment might lead to such problems as incorrect or inaccurate diagnoses,
wasted time, and repetitive testing. From the patient's point of view, anything
that happens at a provider facility is an integral part of the quality of
care received. <BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H2>Chart: The Cost of New vs. Refurbished Equipment</H2>
<B>Cardiac catheterization laboratory:</B> <BR>
new equipment price: $750,000 to $1 million <BR>
refurbished equipment price: $265,000 to$550,000<BR>
<BR>
<B>Angiography system:<BR>
</B>new equipment price: $800,000 to $1 million <BR>
refurbished equipment price: $280,000 to $550,000<BR>
<BR>
<B>Computed tomography scanner:</B> <BR>
new equipment price: $690,000 to $850,000 <BR>
refurbished equipment price: $245,000 to $470,000<BR>
<HR><I>Source: Comdisco, Inc., Rosemont, Illinois</I><BR>
<HR>
<H2>Sidebar: Common Leasing Provisions</H2>
A leasing agreement is one of many legal documents that physician administrators
might face in the increasingly complex tangle of health care. When deciding
on the language to be used in such an agreement, it is advisable to consult
legal counsel to ensure that the agreement complies with all applicable
federal and state laws. The following sample provisions offer a few ideas
for contract language. 
<H3>Ownership of Equipment </H3>
<UL>
<LI>The equipment shall at all times be the sole and exclusive property
of Lessor. Lessee [the provider] shall have no rights or property interest
therein, except for the right to use the equipment in the normal operation
of a medical practice consistent with the terms of this lease. 
<LI>Consider offering Lessee option to purchase the equipment at expiration
of the term. 
</UL>
<H3>Operation and Maintenance </H3>
<UL>
<LI>Lessee will use the equipment in a careful and proper manner in accordance
with all applicable manufacturer and vendor specifications, solely in the
conduct of a medical practice, and will comply with and conform to all federal,
state, county, municipal, and other laws, ordinances, and regulations relating
to the possession, use, and maintenance of the equipment. 
<LI>Lessee shall maintain the equipment in good repair and proper working
order and shall be solely responsible for the costs of maintenance of the
equipment during the term of this lease. Such maintenance shall be performed
in accordance with all requirements necessary to enforce all product warranty
rights, if any, and manufacturer specifications. 
</UL>
<H3>Risk of Loss and Damage or Destruction to the Equipment</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Lessee shall bear all risk of loss, damage, theft, or destruction, partial
or complete, to any or all of the equipment, from and after delivery of
the equipment to Lessee. The operation and use of the equipment will be
at lessee's sole risk. 
<LI>Any loss, damage, theft, or destruction, partial or complete, to any
or all parts of the equipment incurred or occasioned by any cause, circumstance,
or event of whatever nature, and any total or partial loss of use or possession
thereof to Lessee, should not in any way release, abate, affect, reduce,
or impair any of Lessee's obligations, including without limitation, Lessee's
obligation to pay rent for the equipment. 
</UL>
<H3>Rental</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Lessee agrees to pay Lessor during the term, annual rental payments
of $________, payable in monthly installments of $_________ on the ____
day of each month, beginning on the ____ day of _________, _______, for
the right to lease the equipment, without demand or set-off. 
</UL>
<HR><I>Source: Modified from Susan K. Daniel, Esq., and Susan J. Jacobson,
Esq., &quot;Equipment Lease,&quot; Integrated Health Care Delivery Systems:
Business and Legal Forms (Thompson Publishing Group, Inc. New York).</I><BR>
<HR><BR>
