<html>
<head>
<Title>Punitive damages not available under section 504, court rules<P></Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/handhead.gif" alt="Section 504 Compliance
  Handbook"></center><P>

<h2>Punitive damages not available under section 504, court rules<P></h2>
A jury's award of $1.3 million in punitive damages against an employer that
violated section 504 is invalid because punitive damages cannot be recovered
under section 504, the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals determined.<P>

Charles Moreno, a car inspector foreman with diabetes, proved that Consolidated
Rail Corp. (Conrail) violated section 504 by dismissing him because of his
disability. A jury found that Conrail owed Moreno $62,536 for lost wages and
benefits (which later was reduced by $24,388), $125,000 for emotional distress
and $1,312,752 in punitive damages. The district court entered the jury's
compensatory damages verdict, but not its punitive damages award. <P>

In its original opinion, the 6th Circuit decided that punitive damages were
available under section 504 (see October 1995 <i>Monthly Bulletin,</i> p. 1).
However, it later vacated this decision and affirmed, ruling that punitive
damages are not a section 504 remedy and remarking that no court held otherwise
until 1994.<P>

The appellate court decided that Congress did not authorize punitive damages
under section 504. A 1991 amendment capping at $300,000 punitive damages awards
under Section 501 of the Rehabilitation Act (concerning discrimination by the
federal government) showed Congress' intent to keep punitive damages unavailable
under section 504, the 6th Circuit ruled.<P>

It further held that punitive damages would be inappropriate under section 504.
"It would be highly anomalous to let a plaintiff asserting an implied right of
action under section 504 recover more in punitive damages than could be recovered
by a plaintiff asserting the statutory remedy created for section 501," the
appellate court stated.<P>

In a dissent, Judge Martha Daughtrey criticized the majority for relying on case
law that developed before <i>Franklin v. Gwinnett County Public Schools (Appendix
IV:907). (In Franklin,</i> the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that "absent clear
direction to the contrary by Congress, the federal courts have the power to award
any appropriate relief in a cognizable cause of action brought pursuant to a
federal statute.")<P>

The 6th Circuit also affirmed the district court's finding that Conrail was a
federal fund recipient covered by section 504. <P>

The state of Michigan used funds received through federal transportation programs
to pay Conrail to reconstruct railroad crossings that the company was responsible
to maintain. Rejecting Conrail's characterization of the funds as compensation
rather than a subsidy, the appellate court concluded that Conrail was covered by
the law.<P>

This case is <i>Moreno v. Consolidated Rail Corp.,</i> Appendix IV:588. 
<P>
<hr> <center> <pre> 
<a href="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/hand.html"><img
src="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/smallhand.gif" alt="Return to Section 504 Compliance
 Handbook Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/grantprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt="
[ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr> <center><h6>(c) 1996 Thompson Publishing
 Group / <a
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

