<head>
<title> ERISA Cannot Be Used in PHSA Case to Gain Greater COBRA Damages, Court
Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/healhead.gif" alt="Mandated Health Benefits --
The COBRA Guide"></center>

<h2>ERISA Cannot Be Used in PHSA Case to Gain Greater COBRA Damages, Court
Rules</h2>

An argument from a state government retiree that he can sue for COBRA notice
violations under ERISA because it provides more generous legal remedies than the
Public Health Service Act (PHSA) was rejected by an Illinois federal district
court. In <I>Mansfield v. The Chicago Park District Group Plan</I>, 1996 U.S. Dist.
LEXIS 17251 (N.D. Ill. 1996), the court held that, although the different
remedies in ERISA and the PHSA might seem unfair to public sector employees,
Congress clearly meant for those differences to exist.<P>

<H3>Facts of the Case</H3><P>

Robert Mansfield, an employee of the Chicago Park District, was covered under the
District's group health plan. Before his retirement in May 1993, Mansfield met
with a plan representative who did not explain that Mansfield could elect COBRA
coverage once he retired. (COBRA provides that a termination or reduction in
hours of employment is a qualifying event that entitles qualified beneficiaries
to up to 18 months of COBRA coverage. See &#182;1122 of the <I>Guide</I>.) Instead, the
representative said that Mansfield's coverage would expire June 30, 1993. <P>

After Mansfield retired, the District again failed to notify him of his COBRA
rights. In October 1993, Mansfield suffered a heart attack, and began regularly
receiving treatment related to that condition. However, because he was uninsured,
Mansfield had to pay all of his medical expenses.<P>

Mansfield sued the District alleging that, among other things, it violated
COBRA's rules under ERISA and the PHSA. He sought monetary damages (including
penalties for a lack of a COBRA notice), attorney's fees and a jury trial.<P>

The employer sought to dismiss Mansfield's claims, contending that: (1) only the
PHSA--not ERISA--applied to the case because Mansfield's claims were based on
coverage under a "governmental plan" that is exempt from ERISA; (2) the request
for a jury trial and attorney's fees under the PHSA should be denied; and (3) the
PHSA claim was timed barred based on the statute of limitations period under
state tort law.<P>

<H3>ERISA Claim Dismissed</H3><P>

The court agreed that Mansfield's ERISA claim should be dismissed, noting that
although the COBRA rules under ERISA and the PHSA are "essentially identical,"
ERISA specifically exempts governmental plans. Instead, Congress limited the
COBRA claims for state and local government employees to the PHSA's provisions. 
<P>

Mansfield maintained that, even though the employer was a governmental plan,
ERISA should still apply. He argued because the COBRA rules in ERISA and the PHSA
are "the same," the remedies and protections should also be the same, regardless
of whether a covered employee works in the public or private sector.<P>

The court noted that Mansfield "adamantly" argued this point because ERISA
provides for more remedies than the PHSA. For example, under ERISA, a plaintiff
may obtain attorney's fees, "money damages" and notice penalties of up to $100
per day. (These penalties are described at &#182;1520 of the <I>Guide</I>.) In contrast,
PHSA remedies are limited to "appropriate equitable relief." Mansfield called
this difference unfair to public sector employees and contrary to congressional
intent. <P>

The court disagreed, finding that Congress clearly exempted government plans from
ERISA and clearly set the remedies for COBRA violations under the PHSA.<P>

Although Congress' decision to provide more extensive remedies to private sector
employees under ERISA may seem "unfair" to public sector employees, Congress had
legitimate reasons for doing so, the court reasoned.<P>

Furthermore, the court determined that equitable relief under the PHSA typically
does not include money damages, such as notice or other monetary penalties.
However, it may include an award of money as restitution for losses caused by a
defendant to make a plaintiff whole. Accordingly, the court ruled that Mansfield
may recover restitution for out-of-pocket medical expenses due to the District's
alleged COBRA notice failure. On the other hand, it dismissed portions of his
complaint that sought monetary damages beyond those expenses.<P>

<H3>Jury Trial and Attorney's Fees Denied</H3><P>

The court also agreed to dismiss the parts of Mansfield's complaint that sought a
jury trial and attorney's fees under the PHSA. The court made the following
points: <P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>No case law exists regarding whether PHSA plaintiffs may obtain a jury
	trial. However, ERISA does not provide jury trials for plaintiffs. Following this
	logic, the court concluded that the PHSA does not allow jury trials.

	<LI>ERISA provides that prevailing plaintiffs can be awarded attorney's fees,
	but the PHSA does not. Therefore, the court said that it "will not read an
	attorney's fees provision into the PHSA where none exists," noting that in the
	PHSA/COBRA case <I>Brett v. Jefferson County</I> (see &#182;1900), a court declined to
	allow attorney's fees.
</UL>

<H3>Claim Filed Within Statute of Limitations</H3><P>

The District argued that Mansfield's claim should also be dismissed because it
was filed too late. According to the District, because the PHSA does not have a
statute of limitations for COBRA claims, the most analogous limitation period
should be one-year state tort law statute of limitations. Under this rule,
Mansfield's complaint was filed too late.  <P>

In trying to decide on an appropriate statute of limitations, the court looked to
the case law under ERISA because ERISA's COBRA rules are substantially similar to
those in the PHSA. In ERISA cases, courts have typically characterized ERISA
lawsuits as contract actions and looked to the state statute of limitations for
breach of written contracts. <P>

Under Illinois law, a 10-year statute of limitations applies to lawsuits over
breaches of written contracts. Because Mansfield's complaint--filed two years
after his lawsuit--fell within this period, the court found it was not
time-barred. <P>


 

