<head>
<Title>Copyright changes to benefit blind individuals</Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/handhead.gif" alt="Section 504 Compliance
  Handbook"></center><P>

<h2>Copyright changes to benefit blind individuals</h2>


Blind people will be able to get books in accessible formats much quicker because
of an amendment to U.S. copyright law. <P>

President Clinton signed H.R. 3754, the legislative branch appropriations bill
for fiscal year 1997, into law (P. L. 104-197) on Sept. 16. An amendment
sponsored by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., provides "it is not an infringement of
copyright for an authorized entity to reproduce or to distribute copies or
phonorecords of a previously published, nondramatic literary work if such copies
or phonorecords are reproduced or distributed in specialized formats exclusively
for use by blind or other persons with disabilities."<P>

The National Federation of the Blind (NFB), which played a key role in
negotiating the amendment, praised it as removing the time-consuming process of
getting copyright clearance before books are made available in an accessible
format for blind individuals.<P>

However, it is unclear what effect the amendment will have  for dyslexic or
learning disabled individuals and whether its exemption applies to college
service providers. How two of the amendment's terms -- "authorized entity" and
"other persons with disabilities" -- are interpreted will be crucial in answering
both questions.<P>

<h3>Authorized entity</h3><P>

The amendment defines authorized entity as "a nonprofit organization or a
governmental agency that has a primary mission to provide specialized services
relating to training, education or adaptive reading or information access needs
of blind or other persons with disabilities." <P>

Alan Adler, vice president for legal and governmental affairs at the Association
of American Publishers (which helped draft the amendment), claimed that
university service providers are not automatically authorized entities under the
amendment. Instead, he said their coverage will depend on such factors as whether
the university is nonprofit or has the primary mission of providing specialized
services for educating the blind. "Most universities will not fall within this
exemption," he said, although he added, "it's possible they would be exempt. A
state university might fall within the exemption or a nonprofit university."<P>

When asked if service providers would be authorized entities, James Gashel, NFB's
director of governmental affairs, said, "I don't see why they shouldn't be. The
only question is if the university is primarily involved in serving blind people.
I suppose it might be said that the population is a lot broader in a university.
But I don't know why they couldn't set up a nonprofit organization just for the
purpose" of putting books in an accessible format.<P>

Rather than set up a nonprofit, John Kelly, vice-president for consumer services
and marketing at Recording for the Blind and Dyslexic (RFB&amp;D -- also involved
in the amendment's wording), suggested that service providers instead coordinate
local production of texts in accessible formats with RFB&amp;D, since the
organization clearly is an authorized entity. <P>

<h3>'Other persons with disabilities'</h3><P>

There also is disagreement over whether students with learning disabilities are
covered by the proposed exemption. "Blind or other persons with disabilities" is
defined as "individuals who are eligible or who may qualify in accordance with
the act entitled 'an act to provide books for the adult blind,' approved March 3,
1931 (2 U.S.C. &#167;135a; 46 Stat. 1487) to receive books and other publications
produced in specialized format." <P>

Adler said that the exemption did not include students who have dyslexia or other
learning disabilities, emphasizing that the exemption is "fairly narrow" and
maintaining that "dyslexia is not defined as well as blindness."<P>

<h3>Library of Congress definition</h3><P>

However, Kelly disagreed, noting that many students with learning disabilities
are covered under the Library of Congress' Books for Blind and Physically
Handicapped Individuals program. <P>

In addition to blind people, this program makes books available to disabled
people who are "certified by competent authority as unable to read or unable to
use standard printed material as a result of physical limitations" and those
certified as "having a reading disability resulting from organic dysfunction and
of sufficient severity to prevent their reading printed material in a normal
manner."<P>

Competent authority for certifying reading disabilities is defined as "doctors of
medicine and doctors of osteopathy who may consult with colleagues in associated
disciplines."<P>

<h3>Specialized format</h3><P>

Adler and Kelly agree that the amendment's definition of specialized format does
not include large print to protect large print publishers' established markets.
Instead, it encompasses "braille, audio or digital text which is exclusively for
use by blind or other persons with disabilities."<P>

Digital text, or e-text, cannot describe graphs, algebraic equations or
geographical diagrams, Kelly said, but new technology is on the horizon that will
combine audio with e-text to provide audio descriptions of such elements and
thereby "give the blind consumer the ability to move around text in the same way
a sighted person could."<P>

Kelly also emphasized that, in spite of its ambiguities, the Chafee amendment is
a major step forward. "This has been truly a hallmark effort on publishing
companies to do the right thing," he said. <P>
<P>
<P>
 
