<head>
<title>With One Caveat, Retiree Health Coverage May Vest Under Document Terms Without Explicit Language, Court Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/self/selfhead.gif" alt="Employer's Guide to Self-Insuring Health Benefits"></center>
<P>
<h2>With One Caveat, Retiree Health Coverage May Vest Under Document Terms Without Explicit Language, Court Rules</h2>
<P>

</P>

<P>
While lifetime health benefits do not vest under ERISA, they may vest under contract terms even without explicit vesting language, two federal appeals courts stated. 
</P>

<P>
The rulings add impetus to a growing body of case law upholding retirees' rights to lifetime benefits based on promises by their former employers.
</P>

<P>
In upholding a lower court's preliminary injunction against an employer, the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in <I>Joseph Golden v. Kelsey-Hayes Co</I>., 1996 LEXIS 539 (6th Cir. 1996), reaffirmed that through rules of contract interpretation, courts will find that rights accrue or vest under an agreement even if they are not explicitly explained. 
</P>

<P>
According to the court, the evidence that expressed the plan sponsor's intent to create vested rights to lifetime health benefits included:
</P>

<P>
(1) collective bargaining agreement (CBA) language that tied retiree and surviving spouse eligibility for health coverage to eligibility for vested pension benefits; and
</P>

<P>
(2) summary plan description (SPD) language which indicated that the company guaranteed health benefits.
</P>

<P>
The claim for vested health benefits arose when a group of Kelsey-Hayes companies reorganized and cut back on retiree health benefits. Among the benefit modifications were a monthly premium contribution, increased co-payments and annual deductibles, a lifetime benefit cap of $500,000 per beneficiary and elimination of a special age-65 benefit--a monthly payment to pensioners 65 and older that reimbursed the cost of Medicare Part B premiums.
</P>

<P>
Participants and beneficiaries whose coverage stemmed from retirement before the restructuring challenged the cutback. To prevail, the court said they had to show that, under its ruling in <I>United Automobile Workers v. Yard-Man, Inc.</I> (716 F.2d 1476 (6th Cir. 1983), the employer and union intended to include a right to lifetime benefits when they negotiated the CBAs. 
</P>

<P>
The court, rejecting the company's argument that the Supreme Court implicitly had overruled <I>Yard-Man</I>, said that the Court, in <I>Litton Financial Printing Division v. NLRB</I> (501 U.S. 190, 111 S.Ct. 2215 (1991)), recognized that through rules of contract interpretation, benefits rights can be found to vest "even if they are not explicitly set out in the agreement."
</P>

<P>
Since eligibility for health benefits was tied to eligibility to vested pension benefits, which are intended to be for life, the court found that the parties also intended for the company to provide lifetime health benefits.
</P>

<P>
The court also noted that the SPD indicated the company guaranteed health benefits. One provision in the SPD stated that employees who retire without pension eligibility because they were ineligible for the pension plan would still have free, lifetime health coverage. The court agreed with the retirees that this language showed an intent to provide lifetime benefits.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Contract Terms May Create Lifetime Coverage Rights</H3>
</P>

<P>
In the second ruling, the 9th Circuit held that contract terms may create rights to lifetime health coverage, but rejected retirees' claims because they were based on language in a booklet which failed to meet all the requirements of an SPD. The case is <I>Jimmy Pisciotta v. Teledyne Industries, Inc.</I>, 1996 LEXIS 19188 (9th Cir. 1996).
</P>

<P>
An insurance contract referenced in the insurance booklet stated that the contract was the controlling document. The booklet gave Teledyne the right to modify or terminate employee welfare benefits. Therefore, Teledyne had the right to limit the retirees' health benefits, the court said. (While the case involved insured health benefits, the ruling still is relevant to self-funded plans on several points, including what documents are controlling in defining employee benefits, what claims are valid under the estoppel theory and the effect of promises of lifetime benefits.)
</P>

<P>
The appeals court also rejected the retirees' claims that Teledyne should be estopped from denying coverage because of promises made, holding that the estoppel claim is available only when plan documents are ambiguous. That was not the case here, the court said. 
</P>

<P>
Approximately 400 current and former employees claimed that Teledyne violated ERISA when it imposed a monetary cap on what it would pay for retiree health coverage. Teledyne said it would pay the entire premium for the rest of employees' and spouses' lives. A booklet issued to employees stated coverage would be continued, "during the lifetime of you and your spouse." The employees contended that the booklet should be deemed the SPD, and Teledyne's subsequent modification of benefits violated that promise of lifetime benefits.
</P>

<P>
In rejecting their claim, the appeals court stated, "The SPD is the statutorily established means of informing participants of the terms of the plan and its benefits."
</P>

<P>
Of 12 elements required to be in a SPD, the booklet contained only two, according to the court. No other plan document has such a promise of lifetime benefits, it said.
</P>

<P>
Teledyne's failure to produce a proper SPD did not create a right to lifetime benefits, the court found. A plaintiff was not entitled to a substantive benefit for such a violation, it said.
</P>

<P>
The court further stated that even if the booklet did amount to a SPD, the benefits did not vest. The booklet disclaimer stated that the insurance contract was controlling. Therefore, the contract gave Teledyne the right to modify or terminate employee welfare benefits.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Implications</H3>
</P>

<P>
Lifetime health and other welfare benefits have been litigated extensively, with courts consistently rejecting retirees' claims of vesting health benefits. Only more recently, through plan sponsor promises, have retirees found a way to successfully argue lifetime benefits.
</P>

<P>
Even that approach was limited by the Supreme Court, however, when it ruled that plan sponsors may modify plans to limit benefits if they retained that right in plan documents. That was not an issue in the 6th Circuit case. But the 6th Circuit's ruling does reaffirm that employers still can be held liable for lifetime benefits without an explicit grant of such rights. 
</P>

<P>
The case should put employers and other plan sponsors on notice that if they do not intend to grant lifetime health or other benefits, they should clearly say so in plan documents and SPDs.
</P>

<P>
The 9th Circuit's ruling implicitly states that lifetime benefits can be created through plan documents or SPDs. A troubling aspect of the ruling is that in the absence of an SPD, there apparently was no other communication to employees indicating their ERISA rights. 
</P>

<P>
Courts normally look to the SPD as the controlling document because it is typically given to employees. (See &#182;711 for a more detailed discussion.) The SPD usually controls when it contradicts the plan documents because what employees see and rely on determines what their rights are. But when no SPD exists, and the only communication of benefits rights is a booklet, under the prior reasoning it seems appropriate that the employer be bound by the booklet's terms.
</P>

<P>
Employers should ensure that they do provide SPDs rather than rely on booklets. Not all courts would agree with the 9th Circuit. Also, ERISA requires that participants be given SPDs. Without going through all the expense of a new and separate SPD, plan sponsors may use a wrap-around document with a booklet to include all the elements required to be in an SPD. 
</P>


<hr>
<center>
