<html> 
<head><title>President Clinton Expected to Apply FMLA and Other Laws to the Executive Branch</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/time/timehead.gif" alt="Family and Medical Leave Handbook">
<P>
<h2>President Clinton Expected to Apply FMLA and Other Laws to the Executive Branch </h2>

The Presidential and Executive Office Accountability Act (H.R. 3452), which applies a number of federal
laws, including the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA), to the executive offices and residences of the
president and vice president, is expected to be signed into law by President Bill Clinton, according to a
White House source. He has until Oct. 30 to either sign or veto the legislation.<P>

The bill, introduced by Rep. John Mica, R-Fla., and paralleling the Congressional Accountability Act enacted
in early 1995, was passed by the House of Representatives Sept. 24 by a vote of 410-5. It then passed the
Senate with an amendment by Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind. The House agreed to the Coats amendment without
objection and the bill was cleared for the president's signature on Oct. 18.<P>

"This Congress took unprecedented action by making itself subject to the same laws that govern private
citizens and businesses. My legislation will make the White House obey those laws, too," Mica said in an
Oct. 4 press release.<P>

Under the act, the executive branch of the federal government would be subject to 11 federal laws,
including the Fair Labor Standards Act and the Americans with Disabilities Act, as of Oct. 1, 1997.
However, the executive branch would not be required to comply with the FMLA until Oct. 1, 1998.<P>

Under this new law, the FMLA's provisions would apply to all eligible employees, defined as any employee
"who has been employed in any employing office for 12 months and for at least 1,250 hours of employment
during the previous 12 months." This definition is nearly identical to that contained in the FMLA.<P>

The executive office accountability law also would call on the president or a designee of the president to
issue regulations to implement the act that "shall be the same as substantive regulations promulgated by the
Secretary of Labor to implement the statutory provisions." The law would also allow the same remedies for
employees whose employers violate the statute's provisions, including punitive damages.<P>

