<head>
<title> Newborn Case Raises Interesting Issues Under New Law</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/healhead.gif" alt="Mandated Health Benefits&#151;The COBRA Guide"></center>

<h2>Newborn Case Raises Interesting Issues Under New Law</h2>

A federal district court case involving a former employee's failure to follow
written plan procedures in enrolling a newborn with health problems under COBRA
coverage provides a good example of how the Health Insurance Portability and
Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA) could affect such situations. The case is
<I>Variety Children's Hospital, Inc. v. Blue Cross/Blue Shield of Florida</I>, 1996 U.S.
Dist. LEXIS 14199 (S.D. Fla. 1996).  <P>

<H3>Facts of the Case</H3><P>

Lynda Yoder was an employee at Lil' Champ/Jiffy Stores until October 1992, when
her employment terminated. Yoder, who had employee-only coverage under the
company's plan, elected COBRA coverage. The insurer, Blue Cross and Blue Shield
of Florida, Inc., contracted with CobraServ to administer COBRA coverage. Yoder
was pregnant at the time of her qualifying event, and allegedly telephoned
CobraServ regarding her coverage. She contended that a CobraServ employee told
her that her unborn baby was covered under the plan and that she should call
again after the baby's birth.<P>

In December 1992, Yoder was in an automobile accident which she claimed caused
her to go into premature labor in January 1993. Yoder maintained that she
telephoned CobraServ after her son Todd's birth and again confirmed coverage.
Todd, who required extensive medical treatment, was treated at Variety Children's
Hospital but died in February 1993.<P>

Apparently, medical claims relating to Yoder's childbirth and Todd's treatment
were denied. She then sued Lil' Champ, CobraServ and Blue Cross in state court,
alleging, among other things, breach of insurance contract, breach of contract,
promissory estoppel, bad faith refusal to pay and fraud.<P>

The case was removed to federal court because the claims were governed by ERISA.
Upon removal, Yoder conceded that her state law claims were preempted by ERISA
and filed an amended complaint alleging, among other things: (1) breach of
insurance contract against Lil' Champ and Blue Cross; (2) breach of contract
against CobraServ; (3) promissory estoppel against Blue Cross and CobraServ; and
(4) waiver against Blue Cross and CobraServ.<P>

Yoder contended that: (1) she timely filed medical claims which were wrongfully
denied; (2) even as she disputed the denial of her claim, she continued to pay
COBRA premiums, which CobraServ accepted and acknowledged; and (3) Lil' Champ and
Blue Cross wrongfully canceled her COBRA coverage in May 1993 and returned her
premiums.<P>

<H3>Breach of Insurance Contract Claim/Exhaustion of Remedies</H3><P>

As a preliminary matter, the defendants argued that Yoder's claim should be
dismissed because she failed to exhaust her administrative remedies under the
plan. The court reviewed the law in the 11th Circuit and determined that Yoder
was required to exhaust her plan administrative remedies before bringing suit in
federal court, unless she could demonstrate that it would have been futile to
exhaust her administrative remedies. (See &#182;1913 of the <I>Handbook</I> for a
discussion of the exhaustion doctrine.)  <P>

Yoder argued that her court papers alleged sufficient facts to prove that she
exhausted her administrative remedies. However, the court disagreed. It dismissed
Yoder's "breach of insurance contract" claim, but allowed her to re-state her
allegations to raise the exhaustion argument.<P>

<H3>Breach of Insurance Contract Claim/Substantive Merits of Claim</H3><P>

Although the court dismissed the part of Yoder's complaint alleging a breach of
insurance contract, it reviewed the merits of Yoder's substantive arguments.<P>

Among other things, Lil' Champ and Blue Cross both contended the Yoder's breach
of insurance contract claim should be dismissed as a state law claim which is
preempted by ERISA. However, the court noted that Yoder abandoned her state law
claim after the case was removed to federal court; therefore, her claim was
essentially a claim under ERISA seeking to recover plan benefits, enforce her
plan rights or clarify her rights to future benefits. Thus, assuming she could
overcome the exhaustion-of-administrative-remedies defense, the court found that
Yoder's claim would be viewed as a claim under ERISA.  <P>

<H3>Breach of Contract Claim</H3><P>

The court also denied CobraServ's motion to dismiss Yoder's breach-of-contract
claim, essentially relying on its view that Yoder really raised her claim as an
ERISA-based claim. <P>

Next, the court separately addressed CobraServ's argument that Yoder could not
bring an ERISA claim against CobraServ as a third-party non-fiduciary
administrator. The court indicated that several courts have held that a "plan
administrator who merely performs claims processing, investigatory and
recordkeeping duties is not a fiduciary" and, therefore, not a proper defendant
in an ERISA case. However, the court determined that this was not the situation
with CobraServ. <P>

According to the court, Yoder alleged that CobraServ had discretionary authority
or control over plan management. Specifically, Yoder alleged that CobraServ was
responsible for paying benefits and/or determining eligibility for benefits.
Therefore, the court determined that the breach-of-contract claim (in the guise
of an ERISA claim) could not be dismissed. <P>

<H3>Waiver Claim</H3><P>

Yoder argued that Blue Cross and CobraServ waived their rights to terminate her
COBRA coverage when the defendants accepted her COBRA premiums. The court noted
that waiver is "the voluntary, intentional relinquishment of a known right."
Furthermore, the court indicated that because waiver generally is a state law
claim, it is preempted by ERISA unless waiver is recognized under ERISA. <P>

The court then noted that the 11th Circuit has kept the waiver issue unresolved.
Nevertheless, even if it were to allow for a waiver claim, the court noted that
the elements for a waiver argument were not present in Yoder's case. Essentially,
Yoder's claim was based on the defendant's acceptance of premiums, which were
returned when it was discovered that they were wrongfully accepted. Thus, the
court determined that there was insufficient evidence showing the defendants
intentionally relinquished a known right or benefitted unjustly from the receipt
of Yoder's premiums. <P>

"A 'something for nothing' waiver claim cannot stand," the court held.<P>

<H3>Promissory Estoppel Claim</H3><P>

In considering Yoder's promissory estoppel arguments, the court first noted that
Yoder was actually alleging an equitable estoppel, rather than a promissory
estoppel, claim. To that end, the court indicated that equitable estoppel is not
available for unambiguous written plans or oral modifications of the plan. <P>

The court then noted that plan documents provided that individuals with
employee-only coverage must apply in writing for family coverage before the birth
of a baby to ensure coverage for the newborn child(ren).<P>

Yoder contended that she contacted CobraServ prior to Todd's birth because she
perceived an ambiguity in the plan regarding coverage for newborns and
dependents, and she relied on CobraServ's representations that Todd would be
covered under the plan. However, the court concluded that the plan terms were
unambiguous about the procedure to enroll newborns. Because Yoder did not allege
that she applied for such coverage or followed the plan procedures, the court
dismissed Yoder's claim.<P>

<H3>Implications Under New Law</H3><P>

This case raises several interesting issues based on the recent COBRA changes
enacted under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996
(HIPAA). Under HIPAA, children who are born to or adopted by a covered employee
during a period of COBRA coverage become qualified beneficiaries with statutorily
protected rights. One of the issues left open by the new law is how these
children acquire those rights.  <P>

Before using the <I>Variety</I> decision to explore this issue, it is important to note
that the facts in <I>Variety</I> occurred long before the HIPAA effective date.
Therefore, the facts alleged in that case are being used for illustration
only.<P>

<H3>Question No. 1: Does HIPAA Override Plan Terms?</H3> <P>

According to the Lil' Champ plan, apparently, individuals with employee-only
coverage had to apply in writing for family coverage before a baby's birth to
ensure coverage for the newborn child(ren). On the other hand, HIPAA
automatically provides COBRA rights to children born to covered employees during
COBRA coverage.<P>

Thus, the first question under HIPAA is whether the law overrides the plan
provisions. Stated differently, if the plan requires prenatal written
certification before a child may be covered, can the failure to provide that
certification override statutory rights that do not arise until the child is
born?  <P>

This question affects a large number of plans with similar provisions and that
require a notification of birth within a certain time period for the child to be
entitled to health coverage.<P>

Although it is not clear at this point, it would not be surprising to find that
the HIPAA rules will require that COBRA coverage be offered to a newborn child
notwithstanding a participant's failure to provide a prenatal written
certification. On the other hand, it is possible that plan provisions might
survive the HIPAA change because these provisions relate more to eligibility for
dependent coverage as a precondition for acquiring COBRA rights.  <P>

Another way could reconcile the plan's rule with the HIPAA statutory rule.
Basically, the plan's rule would be followed if the child wishes simply to retain
the status of a non-qualified beneficiary dependent child under the plan terms.
Why would that be the case? Because as a non-qualified beneficiary dependent
child, there may be no additional premium (or a small dependent rate premium). On
the other hand, if the child wants the qualified beneficiary protections and
rights, the qualified beneficiary would arguably have to pay a  COBRA premium
separate from the covered employee. Whether this distinction is a valid one may
be clarified in future guidance from the IRS.<P>

<H3>Question No. 2: Within What Time Period Must a Newborn Elect COBRA Coverage?</H3> <P>

Assume that the future HIPAA guidance from the IRS provides that a covered
employee's newborn (or adopted) child retains COBRA rights automatically from
birth (or adoption), regardless of any plan provisions that would require some
prenatal (or pre-adoption) action to preserve coverage options. The next question
is how this right is to be effectuated.  <P>

Based on the statutory language, it appears that the statutory protections of a
newborn or adopted qualified beneficiary are not premised on an actual election.
Thus, Yoder's child under the new law might have had to have been automatically
treated as a qualified beneficiary entitled to elect COBRA coverage from the date
of birth forward. But if the child does not follow the plan enrollment terms,
does COBRA provide the child with a special period within which to elect COBRA
coverage, regardless of plan terms? Again, further guidance is needed.  <P>

<H3>Question No. 3: When Must a Newborn (or Adopted) Qualified Beneficiary's COBRA
Premium Be Paid?</H3> <P>

Assuming that a newborn (or adopted) child acquires the status of a qualified
beneficiary, what premium may be charged and when must that premium be paid?
According to IRS Revenue Ruling 96-8 (see &#182;1810), if a qualified beneficiary
group was treated as a family before a qualifying event, the plan is allowed to
charge that post-qualifying event "family" of qualified beneficiaries the same
total premium. Nevertheless, this is not necessarily required in every case. <P>

Thus, when a child is born to a covered employee during a period of COBRA
coverage and becomes a qualified beneficiary, the plan must determine whether the
child is to pay a separate COBRA premium (as a single qualified beneficiary) or
merely the rate charged for additional dependent children. This is not entirely
clear.<P>

Next, regardless of the amount of the COBRA premium, it is important to know when
that premium must be paid. Assume that, as in Yoder's case, a child is born well
into a qualified beneficiary's period of COBRA coverage. Also assume that the
child is born in the middle of a month.  <P>

Before HIPAA was enacted, the covered employee/qualified beneficiary had to
comply with the plan terms for adding a newborn child. As explained at
&#182;1114, this newborn child would not be a qualified beneficiary. Assuming the
plan terms for adding such a newly acquired dependent were met, the covered
employee/qualified beneficiary would have to pay the premium for this newborn
non-qualified beneficiary within the time frame required by the plan.<P>

Under HIPAA, however, the newborn child is becoming something much more than a
newly acquired non-qualified beneficiary dependent. Instead, the child is an
actual qualified beneficiary electing COBRA coverage. Therefore, one could argue
that the child has a statutory grace period for the payment of COBRA coverage. 
<P>

Ordinarily, COBRA requires that premium payments be made within a strict time
frame. (See &#182;1440 for a discussion of the timeliness of premium payments.)
Generally, the initial COBRA premium for the period between the qualifying event
and the COBRA election must be paid within 45 days of the COBRA election.
Subsequent premiums are generally due within 30 days. However, if a newborn
child's COBRA "election" occurs on the date of birth, it is not clear how these
strict time periods are supposed to apply.<P>

For example, if a child is born on March 15, 1997, when is the premium from the
date of birth due? Within 45 days? Within 15 days (that is, by the due date for
the March COBRA premium)? Within 30 days? Again, in the absence of guidance, it
is hard for administrators to know what the right answer is.<P>

One suggested approach would be the following: The child would have within 45
days from birth to pay the initial premium through the end of the month in which
the birth occurred. All subsequent premiums would be due within the regular
30-day grace period.<P>

Until the IRS issues guidance on these  issues, administrators will have to
implement a reasonable, good-faith approach to these questions. <P>


