<head>
<TITLE>Experts on RMP Rule Outline Road Ahead, Answer Questions</TITLE> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/blst/blsthead.gif" alt="Risk Management Program
Handbook"><h4> <i>Accidental Release Prevention Under the 1990 Clean Air Act
</i></h4></center><hr> 
<h2>Experts on RMP Rule Outline Road Ahead, Answer Questions</h2>

<P>
Questions about the breadth of the risk management program (RMP) rule and its application highlighted a recent nationwide video conference on the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) recently finalized regulation. Throughout the day-long presentation, viewed by more than 2,000, a panel of experts from industry and EPA summarized key aspects of the new rule and answered questions phoned or faxed in by viewers.
</P>

<P>
In his opening remarks, Jim Makris, director of EPA's Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office (CEPPO), said, "If you take the RMP plan information submitted by facilities and you combine that with EPCRA submissions [data reported under various sections of the Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act], you have a powerful tool for shaping prevention in our communities."
</P>

<P>
Many questions presented to the panel related to threshold quantity (TQ) determinations, application of the rule to temporary operations like railcar delivery, and identification of worst-case scenarios to analyze as part of the hazard assessment requirements of the RMP rule.
</P>

<P>
How to account for, in TQ determinations, quantities of regulated substances delivered to facilities by railcar and tank truck is a "big issue that will be evolving," Makris said. A rough rule of thumb for rail cars is "if you have received it and it has been delivered, it [the quantity inside the car] must be considered in a TQ determination," said R. Craig Matthiessen, director of EPA's chemical accident prevention staff. 
</P>

<P>
EPA's perspective, however, should be coupled with how the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has interpreted temporary operations under the process safety management (PSM) standard (29 CFR 1910.119), said panelist J. Steve Arendt, president of JBF Associates Inc., a process safety consulting firm. In effect, OSHA has said that facilities are not covered by the PSM standard simply because a railcar comes onsite and connects to a process without depositing an amount in excess of the TQ for the substance, Arendt said.
</P>

<P>
On this and other compliance issues, EPA is working with OSHA to establish consistency. The two agencies so far have developed a "coordination letter" that addresses compliance assistance to facilities and they eventually will negotiate a memorandum of understanding to cover all RMP compliance and enforcement issues, Matthiessen said.
</P>

<P>
One of the starting points for any facility potentially subject to the RMP rule will be the identification of "processes" that contain regulated substances and the determination of whether the TQ for each substance is met within the boundaries of the process. Matthiessen said EPA has decided to use the same definition of "process" that OSHA utilizes with the PSM standard. "Thus, you go process-by-process ... you determine the TQ by adding up the total quantity of a listed substance in each process," he said.
</P>

<P>
Related to the TQ determination is the analysis to define what parts of a process must be considered in identifying worst-case release scenarios under the hazard assessment requirements of the rule. The expert panel was asked, "How far back in the process do you need to go in identifying worst-case scenarios? Do facilities need to assume, for example, that a fire progresses back through process piping to impact various connected vessels in the process?" Arendt said that the RMP rule only requires you to look at the largest vessel or piping in a process that would create the greatest impact if the contents were released. "You don't need to go way back through a process," he said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>OCA guidance as screening tool</H3>
</P>

<P>
To help with the task of identifying worst-case scenarios, EPA's Offsite Consequence Assessment (OCA) guidance can be a useful screening tool, Matthiessen said. Facilities can use it to analyze covered processes and identify hazard zones for a number of potential release scenarios, then choose only a few to analyze with more sophisticated modeling techniques, he said. An interim final version of the OCA guidance was released by EPA at the time the final RMP rule was signed. EPA plans to have the guidance peer reviewed over the next few months and intends to keep it up-to-date, Matthiessen said.
</P>

<P>
Several questions were raised regarding the criteria for classifying processes into Programs 1, 2 or 3, each of which entails different regulatory requirements under the RMP rule. Program 3, the most stringent tier, would apply to processes that fall within one of nine Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) codes and to processes already covered by the PSM standard. However, Arendt pointed out that if a process meets the criteria for Program 1, the least stringent tier, it would be eligible for Program 1 even though the process already is subject to the PSM standard or falls within one of the listed SIC codes.
</P>

<P>
One of the criteria for Program 1 eligibility is that there can be no public receptors within the hazard zone of a worst-case release scenario involving a covered process. A number of questions were presented to the expert panel concerning the definition of "public." Basically, anyone that is not a facility employee or an onsite contractor is considered to be the public, Arendt said. Thus, employees of neighboring plants are part of the public, he said. However, service contractors that periodically come onsite would not be considered part of the public because they are covered by OSHA requirements and are not ordinary visitors, Matthiessen said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Hypotheticals described</H3>
</P>

<P>
Several people addressed the expert panel with hypothetical situations and asked the panel to interpret how the RMP rule would apply. For example, one hypothetical involved a fertilizer manufacturer delivering to customer cooperatives an amount of product containing greater than the TQ for ammonia. Would the customers then be covered by the RMP rule? Arendt responded that yes, they would be covered and added that this type of situation may be ripe for development of a model RMP for co-op customers.
</P>

<P>
Another hypothetical involved a co-op with an ammonia retail operation that qualifies for Program 2. At this site, farmers come to the co-op and hook up their own equipment to the storage tank to transfer ammonia into their containers. Must the co-op consider the farmer's connecting equipment within its hazard review, which the co-op is required to conduct under the prevention section of the RMP rule? According to EPA's Matthiessen, it is up to the co-op to work it out with the farmer to ensure that faulty or inappropriate equipment is not used, and perhaps communicate this issue with the local emergency planning committee (LEPC) and the community.
</P>

<P>
With regard to revising an RMP plan once it is submitted, the question was posed whether periodic changes to a process hazard analysis (PHA) for a covered process would require a facility to submit a revised plan. One of the major requirements of the RMP rule is that facilities with covered processes must submit to a central location (to be determined at a later date by EPA) an RMP plan summarizing the facility's hazard assessment, prevention and emergency response programs. "For major modifications to a process that require PHA revalidation, a revised RMP plan must be submitted," Matthiessen said. "But not the entire plan, you may need to just submit revisions," he said. JBF's Arendt said he doesn't believe a revised RMP plan will be necessary each time some change is made to a PHA--just when a PHA is revalidated, he said.
</P>

<P>
Since the RMP rule was finalized, EPA has been emphasizing that one of the primary purposes of the risk management program is to provide state agencies, the public and local emergency response agencies with information that is useful for chemical accident prevention and emergency response planning. 
</P>

<P>
In relation to this goal, an important point was raised by a hazardous materials specialist employed by a small fire department in the northeast. He said that Tier II chemical inventory data submitted under sections 311 and 312 of EPCRA created paperwork burdens that his department has had difficulty transforming into useful information. Will EPA help local responders use the new RMP plan information? he asked. 
</P>

<P>
EPA's Makris responded by noting that the new version of CAMEO emergency planning software should be helpful. He added that EPA is planning to make it easier to access and use RMP plan information electronically. Also, the agency has plans to add an RMP question and answer database to CEPPO's Internet site (the address is <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/swercepp">http://www.epa.gov/swercepp</A>).
</P>

<P>
With respect to LEPCs, Makris said they will play an important role in the flow of RMP information to the communities, although they will not be involved in enforcement unless state law grants them authority. However, EPA plans to develop formal guidance to help LEPCs perform their role, he said.
</P>

<P>
Addressing the costs to implement a risk management program at a facility, the expert panel was asked to estimate a ballpark figure for a generic, small plant with two covered processes onsite. Assuming that the facility already was complying with the PSM standard, Arendt estimated the total cost to implement a risk management program could be as little as several thousand dollars, or up to about $10,000. "The greatest cost will be the hazard assessment, but the OCA guidance will help," he said.
</P>

<P>
The video conference, which occurred the same day (June 20) the final RMP rule was published in the <I>Federal Register</I>, was produced by Coastal Video Communications Corp. and co-sponsored by EPA and the American Institute of Chemical Engineers' Center for Chemical Process Safety.
</P>




